<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BRYANTAWARD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DEAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Fourteen months ago, Virginia Tech lost to Temple at home in what
the Hokies now call ``Black Saturday.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   But that loss was an aberration. Virginia Tech football is among
the top programs in the nation, thanks in part to defensive end
Corey Moore, freshman quarterback Michael Vick and coach Frank
Beamer. All contributed heavily to the Hokies' 11-0 1999 regular
season with Moore earning the Lombardi Award and Vick being the
youngest-ever Heisman Trophy finalist.
</P>
<P>
   The postseason honors kept rolling in for Virginia Tech on
Thursday night at the Westin Galleria Hotel as Beamer won the Bear
Bryant Award, which goes to the nation's top college football
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can win an honor in his name, with his name on it,
that's special,'' said Beamer, 53, who guided the Hokies to their
best season. ``Growing up, coach Bryant was the guy. If you said
`college football coach,' Bear Bryant would be the guy you said.''
</P>
<P>
   A few more seasons like 1999, and someone might one day have an
award bearing Beamer's name.
</P>
<P>
   A Nokia Sugar Bowl loss in the national championship game
Tuesday night aside, the Hokies probably were college football's
biggest story this season.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech finished the season ranked No. 2, which set up
Tuesday's showdown with Florida State in New Orleans in which the
Seminoles erased a 29-28 third-quarter deficit to win 46-29.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great year, and you can't let the fact you had a
disappointing finish erase all the great moments and great wins
that we had throughout the year,'' said Beamer, who last month was
named the Walter Camp Coach of the Year, the Associated Press Coach
of the Year and the Big East Coach of the Year. ``We played hard in
the bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just that Florida State made more big plays than we did
and they did the things to win a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Beamer was all smiles Thursday. As one of seven finalists, he
beat out a quality field of coaches honoring the late Paul ``Bear''
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like the less I coach, the more awards we win,'' said
Beamer. ``I'm so thankful. It says something. It says we have a
great staff and great players. You don't see too many people
nominated for Coach of the Year honors that don't have great
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, there's a thin line between being OK and not
being OK. Tonight I feel like we're OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists were Bobby Bowden, Florida State; Bob
Pruett, Marshall; Glen Mason, Minnesota; June Jones, Hawaii; Mike
DuBose, Alabama; and Barry Alvarez, Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   All were in attendance except Bowden and Alvarez. Bowden's wife
fell and fractured her arm Wednesday at an airport and is in a New
Orleans hospital. Alvarez has had surgery on his knee twice this
season and aggravated the joint while walking the sidelines with
the aid of a cane in Saturday's Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer wasn't the only one honored Thursday. Former University
of Texas football coach Darrell K Royal was presented the lifetime
achievement award. Former President George Bush was the keynote
speaker at the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer said he was proud that Virginia Tech is one of only eight
teams in the nation to have gone to a bowl the last seven years and
wants to keep the program at the top level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be a consistent program,'' Beamer said. ``We feel
real fortunate that we've gone to seven straight bowl games, and
hopefully we can go to seven straight in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``And get to the point when you ask anyone in any part of the
country, `Name the top 10 programs in the country,' maybe Virginia
Tech will be in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over at Virginia Tech in January 1987 from Bill
Dooley, Beamer has compiled an 88-59-2 record after inheriting NCAA
sanctions with reduced scholarship numbers. The Hokies have
averaged nine wins per year since '93.
</P>
<P>
   The Bryant Award and dinner benefits the American Heart
Association, the nation's largest voluntary health organization
dedicated to the reduction of disability and death from
cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``This event is a great time for old friends to get together and
support a worthy cause,'' Beamer said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
