<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9104 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-GOODEN-HNS     01-07 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-GOODEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros are moving to what figures to be a hitter-friendly
ballpark, they traded their best pitcher from a year ago, and their
most promising young starter is rehabilitating from surgery and has
yet to begin throwing with spring training less than six weeks
away.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who are betting against the Astros' four-peating as
champions of the National League Central understandably believe
pitching will be what ails them.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a doctor in the house? Maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros signed veteran righthander Dwight ``Doc'' Gooden to a
minor-league contract Thursday and invited him to spring training
as a non-roster player. For all intents and purposes, Gooden
represents an insurance policy in the event Scott Elarton is unable
to start the season on time, not to mention potential depth in an
unsettled starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Quite frankly, if Gooden proves during spring training that
there still is some magic left in his once-golden right arm, the
Astros will find a place for him on their pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hold any illusions of grandeur that at 35 years old we
are going to see the Doc Gooden of 27 or 28 years old. But knowing
Doc, I'll take my chances when he's on the mound,'' said Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker, who was in the Mets organization
during Gooden's heyday in New York. ``He still has that competitive
fire, and you know you're going to get an honest effort from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps himself in incredible physical condition. The arm
strength is still there, and he still has good breaking stuff. He
has a lot of confidence in his ability, and that all adds up to a
pitcher who I believe can come into camp and really make a
significant contribution to our ballclub this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros aren't so sure with regard to Elarton, who pitched
through pain throughout the second half of the 1999 season and
required rotator-cuff surgery this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elarton has not picked up a ball yet,'' Hunsicker said. ``He's
coming back to see our doctors here in Houston next week, and at
that point he'll hopefully get the go-ahead to start playing catch.
This is going to be a situation very similar to Chris Holt of two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really not going to know what we have until halfway
through spring training _ until he gets on the mound, starts
throwing and starts putting his arm through the rigors of pitching
day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the main reason Hunsicker has been searching for an
experienced starter, but in Gooden he signed a pitcher capable of
making the team on his own merit and not just as the beneficiary of
an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doc Gooden is going to get every opportunity to make this
ballclub, first and foremost as a starter because that is where he
is most effective,'' Hunsicker said. ``As far as I'm concerned,
(Shane) Reynolds and (Jose) Lima are the only two names that I'm
willing to pencil in that rotation right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Elarton is healthy, that means we've got four guys for
three spots. The odd man out probably will go to the bullpen, but
we haven't talked much about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Elarton is healthy, the four pitchers competing for the
final three spots in the rotation are Elarton, Gooden, Holt and
Octavio Dotel _ one of the players the Astros acquired in the trade
that sent 22-game winner Mike Hampton to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden made a name for himself with the Mets, compiling a .649
winning percentage in 11 seasons with them. He also appeared in
four All-Star Games, was named NL Rookie of the Year in 1984 and
won the NL Cy Young Award in 1985 when he was 24-4 with a 1.53
earned run average. At 20 years old, he became the youngest pitcher
to win the coveted award for pitching excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden missed the 1995 season while serving a drug suspension
and resurfaced with the Yankees, pitching two seasons in the Bronx
and throwing the only no-hitter of his career in 1996. He spent the
past two seasons in Cleveland, where he pitched respectably despite
injuries _ most notably a shoulder strain that limited him to 22
starts in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm healthy, and I'm looking forward to trying to win a spot
in the rotation and help this team get to the next level,'' said
Gooden, whose 188 career victories rank fourth among active
pitchers behind Roger Clemens (247), Greg Maddux (221) and Orel
Hershiser (203). ``There's no doubt in my mind that I can do that.
I'm looking forward to coming back to the National League and
joining a team that already is put together well. Hopefully, I can
be the missing piece to the puzzle. When my agent told me the
Astros were interested, right away my mind was set. This situation
fits me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference between now and my early days when I had
an overpowering fastball is that when I got behind in the count,
everyone knew what was coming. Now, I'm more of a complete pitcher,
a smarter pitcher. I just don't have the velocity I had at one
time. I rely more on setting hitters up, moving the ball around and
maybe throwing a breaking ball every now and then when I'm behind
in the count.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Gooden's first career start was at the Astrodome
in 1984. He recalled being so nervous that he walked about four
miles from the team's hotel headquarters to the ballpark and jumped
the fence to get onto the grounds. He got the third degree from a
security guard who had no idea who he was.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years later, his name is among the most recognizable in
the game. Whether Gooden can approach his success of the 1980s
remains to be seen, but the Astros believe he is worth the gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty excited about this,'' manager Larry Dierker said.
``Obviously, when we lost Mike Hampton, it created a void in our
rotation, and to be able to fill that void with a pitcher of this
caliber is a very good opportunity for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had pretty good success with our pitchers over the last
few years, and I think we have a pretty good program for them. I
have no reason to think that he can't fit right into that program
and be a productive pitcher for us.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
