<HEADER>
A9105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     01-07 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THERE is always something poignant, a little sad, a little hopeful,
about a once-great pitcher trying to recapture the flame of his
youth. The Astros hope Doc Gooden can do it, for at least one year,
which is why they signed him Thursday to a minor-league contract.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't really old at 35, but he has 15 seasons behind him. He
needs 12 wins to reach 200 for his career. It is the stuff of
summer wishes, winter dreams. At a social gathering in Houston, a
night or two before the New York Mets opened the 1984 season, a
writer mentioned to Davey Johnson that he had covered Nolan Ryan's
first big-league start.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who had played college ball at Texas A&AMP;M and feels at
home among Texans, became animated. ``Are you working Saturday
night?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The scribe said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you ought to come out to the stadium anyway,'' urged
Davey. ``We're starting a kid named Dwight Gooden. Someday you may
want to be able to tell your grandkids that you saw both Nolan Ryan
and Dwight Gooden in their major-league debuts.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the kind of advice reporters normally get from
managers or coaches, and the friendly tip was appreciated. Gooden,
in five innings of work, beat the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The season turned out to be a spectacular one for the teen-ager
from Tampa. He won 17 games and finished with 276 strikeouts and an
earned run average of 2.60. At 19, he was the National League
Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the media and fans quickly anointed him ``Dr. K,''
a partial tribute to Julius Erving (``Dr. J'') and a play on the
symbol for a strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be no limit to what Gooden would accomplish.
In 1985, he posted a 24-4 record, 268 strikeouts and a 1.53 ERA. At
20, he won the Cy Young Award. He was a specimen not exactly common
among pitchers, a splendid athlete, quick with his glove and his
bat.
</P>
<P>
   A month into the 1986 season, he had beaten the Astros on two
hits for his 13th career shutout, driving in two runs with a
triple. He was not yet 22.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden was what baseball always promises but seldom delivers:
baby love. It wasn't simply the way he overpowered the league. Tom
Seaver, Vida Blue, Fernando Valenzuela and others captured the fans
in their impressive freshman seasons. What made you marvel at
Gooden was the fact he made the jump virtually out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   The Shea Stadium fans began bringing placards with the letter K
imprinted on them to tabulate his strikeouts. A section of the
bleachers began to be identified as the ``K Korner.''
</P>
<P>
   When a creature of this caliber arrives, you check for possible
weak spots. Gooden was 6-3, 198 pounds and still growing. If you
questioned anything, it was whether he could maintain the pace,
especially in New York, where the fans are often so eager to devour
their young. Would he fall victim to the too-much-too-soon
syndrome? Would the big city, bright lights snare him?
</P>
<P>
   He was in awe of nothing. He had been around major-leaguers all
his life, going to spring-training games in Tampa with his father.
He was quiet and modest, with a solid family base.
</P>
<P>
   Wise observers held their breath. ``We don't have pitching stars
anymore,'' said Frank Cashen, the Mets' general manager. ``They're
more like meteors.''
</P>
<P>
   No, he was not immune to the kind of cosmic explosion that too
often awaited the golden children. The signs began to creep in. He
began to show up late for appointments or miss them altogether. He
missed the Man of the Year banquet in his honor in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Now his whole private life was front-page news. There was a
nasty scrape with the police in his hometown. The police report
said they spotted a new Mercedes weaving through traffic. Gooden,
the driver, and a friend were described as ``combative.'' Witnesses
said they saw the officers beating two men on the ground without
resistance. Rumors began to float. But his teammates were shocked,
even those with drug problems of their own, when Doc Gooden checked
himself into a clinic in New York for treatment of cocaine abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The fans felt betrayed. The famed Stage Delicatessen scratched
the young pitcher's pocket sandwich from its menu. As one social
critic noted, it was just another town without pita.
</P>
<P>
   But in Gooden's first start after finishing his rehab, the crowd
gave him a standing ovation. He struggled with drugs, missed the
1995 season, pitched his first no-hitter in 1996 for the Yankees,
and was lightly used the past two seasons in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Now Doc is reaching for one more chance, perhaps a last chance.
Having lost Mike Hampton, the Astros are in a position to give him
one. May he make the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
