<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CLINTON PRESENT, PACE OF ISRAEL-SYRIA TALKS IS SAID TO PICK
UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs 1st and 4th grafs for updating) 
(bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ President Clinton on Thursday spent a
third day coaxing Israel and Syria toward the framework of a peace
accord. U.S. officials reported Thursday evening that the pace of
talks had begun to pick up, with Clinton promising to cancel
commitments in Washington and return early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving here late Thursday afternoon, Clinton and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and, in a separate meeting Thursday evening,
with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa. Under the terms of a
news blackout surrounding the talks, administration officials
declined to discuss the specific state of talks over the return of
the Golan Heights, which Israel seized in the Arab-Israeli war in
1967.
</P>
<P>
   But James Rubin, the State Department spokesman who had
complained Wednesday of the dead-slow pace of the talks, said
Thursday night, ``Maybe we've moved from chugging to trotting.''
</P>
<P>
   While it was unclear what, if anything, Clinton accomplished in
his six-hour visit here on Thursday, which ended at 10 p.m., it
seemed likely that he cut through procedural disputes over how the
talks would proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two sides have been portrayed by the U.S. mediators
as moving at a glacial pace, that may partly be posturing for their
domestic constituencies. The rough outline of a deal for the return
of the Golan Heights, the buffer zone that Israelis have long
contended is vital for their security, has been fairly well
understood since talks between Israel and Syria that date from the
summer of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The big questions have centered on where exactly the new borders
would be drawn, how Syria and Israel would share access to water
and what other security measures _ from early-warning stations to a
reduction of military forces on both sides of the border _ would
complete the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the talks sputtered on and off and were suspended in 1996.
This week has marked the first substantive discussions in nearly
four years, with Israel, Syria and the United States agreeing here
to set up four committees to negotiate the most contentious issues.
The two committees dealing with the most sensitive issues, borders
and access to water, have yet to meet.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin said Thursday that those meetings were superseded by
the sessions the president was holding, ``where many of the same
substantive issues are being addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's clear hope is to emerge from this set of talks with
what the State Department is calling a ``framework agreement'' _
something more concrete than a set of objectives but far less
complete than a treaty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rubin said that document, already being drafted, is partly based
on the 1995 and 1996 discussions of Israelis and Syrians in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that the working document will be published at
the end of this round of talks, which could easily extend into the
weekend and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The slowness of both sides to engage on the hardest issues
suggests that the negotiations may take far longer than Clinton and
Albright hoped. Israel may be carefully gauging the chances that
any final deal would win approval in a national referendum, in
which the conservative opposition is bound to fight any effort to
return the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Americans, it is standard operating procedure to
underplay the prospects of success, in an effort to portray any
agreement, no matter how vague, as a momentum-building step toward
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in several years, the parties _ Israel,
Syria and the Palestinians _ have a common goal in sight, and the
common sense to see that they have a historic opportunity to
achieve it now,'' said National Security Adviser Sandy Berger in a
speech Thursday to the National Press Club.
</P>
</TEXT>
