<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
 TEXAS DEFENSE PUTS CLAMPS ON BAYLOR (For
use by NYTimes News Service clients) By MIKE JONES c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The question was whether] Baylor was trying to shorten
the game, or was Texas' defense just too tall?
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in trying to push the ball and get the quickest shot
we could,'' said Bears guard Tevis Stukes, who frequently was
looking for an open man with 10 seconds left on the shot clock.
``But they kept moving our offense out to the half-court line. And
that gave us problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Big time.
</P>
<P>
   The 17th-ranked Longhorns (9-3) dominated Baylor defensively on
the way to a convincing 71-43 victory last night before an
announced Erwin Center crowd of 10,495.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it better when we were playing against cheerleaders,''
Baylor coach Dave Bliss joked, referring to a games he coached in
the Southwest Conference at SMU when former Texas coach Bob
Weltlich recruited a cheerleader when players were bailing out of
his program in his first season (1982-83).
</P>
<P>
   Texas held Baylor to a 34.9 shooting percentage last night in
handing the Bears (9-3) their 19th consecutive Big 12 loss. The
Longhorns forced 23 turnovers while holding the Bears to 22
rebounds and limited the visitors to four points in the last 13
minutes of the first half. Baylor twice was whistled for 35-second
violations and once could not get the ball over half-court in the
required 10. And Texas held Baylor's top two scorers _ Stukes and
Terry Black _ to a combined 27 points, nine below their combined
averages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Barnes has been talking to us about what is going to be
our identity,'' Texas point guard Ivan Wagner said. ``We've decided
to make defense our identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Longhorns perhaps were trying to make a statement
to No. 2 Connecticut, where Texas plays on Monday, Wagner said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was out to make a statement to UConn,'' he said.
``Maybe to the rest of the Big 12 as to what they can expect night
in and out. Hopefully, we got our point across.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas held an opponent to less than 40 percent shooting for the
sixth time this season and the 20th time in 44 games under Rick
Barnes. Texas is 15-5 in those games, 6-0 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm not a good offensive coach,'' Barnes said. ``But I
believe in defense. I believe you can create offense with defense.
Defense can be there every night and, if it is, you've got a
chance. Defense can overcome turnovers, poor free throw shooting _
a multitude of sins.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas broke from a 13-all tie to outscore the Bears 17-4 and
take a 30-17 halftime lead, the lowest point total in a half for an
opponent this season.
</P>
<P>
   Center Chris Mihm led a balanced attack with 15 points and eight
rebounds in 27 minutes. Nine Longhorns played at least 12 minutes
and no one played more than Wagner's 28. That is in stark contrast
to last season, when four members of the eight-player rotation on
the Big 12 regular-season champions averaged more than 31 minutes
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bench was the difference in this game,'' Barnes said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
