<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9116 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-MERCEDES-HNS &LR;      01-07 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MERCEDES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KAPALUA, Hawaii _ A year ago, David Duval blew through a
defenseless Plantation Course at Kapalua for a nine-stroke victory,
finishing with a remarkable 26-under-par total at the Mercedes
Championships.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, Kapalua blew back.
</P>
<P>
   In '99, the trademark trade winds were absent and the palm trees
were barely ruffled. But in the first round of the 2000 PGA Tour
season, gusts over 30 mph ensured nobody would embarrass this long,
hilly, lush resort.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik tried. He was 6 under par after 11 holes. But
the course got even soon enough, extracting a couple of double
bogeys before Parnevik steadied himself for a 4-under-par 69 that
left him one stroke ahead in the PGA Tour's season-opening event
for 1999's winners. Duffy Waldorf was a stroke behind at 70, but
guess who was breathing down their necks.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, it's the same guy who won everything in sight in the second
half of '99. Tiger Woods, who is shooting for a fifth consecutive
PGA Tour win, shot 2-under on the back nine and was tied with Ernie
Els for third at 2-under 71.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the torrid pace set in '99. But considering
the windblown conditions, the scores Thursday were impressive in
their own right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody keeps telling me that this is normal,'' said Hal
Sutton, who struggled to a 4-over 77. ``But if this is normal and I
had to play in this every day, I'd quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was blowing me all over the place. And I don't know what
all the skinny people were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter whether you were tall or short, porky or trim.
Everybody had to battle the breeze. Only eight players broke
par-73. Parnevik was alone in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blew a little,'' understated Woods. ``For example, on the
first hole, I had 242 yards and hit a soft 7-iron. Then on the 10th
hole, I had 136 yards and hit a soft 7-iron. Over 100 yards'
discrepancy in those holes, but I hit the same club (on his second
shots).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way this course is supposed to play. Under these
conditions, you've just got to keep plugging along. Six under par
obviously is wonderful playing. But you just have to remember that
there's so many holes left to be played. When it's blowing that
hard, marginal shots won't get it done. You just need to keep
making pars and plodding along, make a few birdies, and you'll be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Woods isn't panicking in the face of a two-shot
deficit after only one round.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parnevik ruled the day with his shotmaking _ which was
mostly good, but some weren't so good.
</P>
<P>
   He was a master on the grainy, sloping Kapalua greens, making
four birdie putts of 15 feet or longer. His 25-footer at the par-3
11th got him to 6 under par. At that point, he was six strokes
ahead of Woods and four ahead of his closest pursuer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the fun started,'' Parnevik said.
</P>
<P>
   The downwind 12th was his first problem. His wedge came up short
of the green, and then he three-putted after chipping up past the
hole. On the 13th, which was a head-butt into the wind, Parnevik
had 150 yards to the hole and ``absolutely killed a 3-iron that
came up 20 yards short of the green.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, I got too cute with the chip shot and left it short in
the bunker, blasted out and two-putted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik's recovery was just as spectacular as his collapse. He
birdied the 14th and 15th holes from short range and offset a bogey
at the 17th with a tap-in birdie at the 663-yard finishing par-5.
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the wind and the elevation changes at Kapalua proved
troublesome for all the players.
</P>
<P>
   As Notah Begay III said: ``You've got all these variables to
factor in within 45 seconds. It's like being on a game show.''
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, somebody will win $522,000 at the end of this show.
But they will earn it, judging from Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse is the grain on the greens. It's so strong,
it will push balls uphill, particularly if the wind is blowing with
the grain, as it often is. All of which combine to make last year's
tournament record by Duval a distant memory that is undoubtedly out
of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's real safe,'' said Jim Furyk, who shot 1-under
72. ``And I've seen it blow worse than this here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at least all the long holes are downwind, downhill and
down-grain. This is the way the course is supposed to play. But at
the top of the hill on the 16th and 17th greens, the ball didn't
want to stay stationary.''
</P>
<P>
   Furyk and playing partner Brian Henninger had to get rulings on
the 17th green, which is near the highest point on the course, as
their balls began to roll after they had been respotted on the
green.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Faxon, one of the few under par at 1-under, said he hit a
9-iron 65 yards into the wind on the par-5 ninth. He later hit the
same 9-iron 190 yards downwind on the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   For one day, Parnevik got it around the course better than
anybody else. He even managed to steal a little of the fans'
spotlight from Woods by wearing some fire-engine red slacks. As he
reached the 18th green, Parnevik knew he had made an impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announcer, he announces what clothes you're wearing,''
Parnevik said. ``He goes, `In the wild red pants from Sweden ' So
one guy in the crowd screams, `Hey, if you knock it in the hole, we
don't care what color pants you have.' It was a fun day,
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
