r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-07 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS' NEW LIFE FAR FROM UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTCHESTER, Calif. _ Last year Baron Davis carried the UCLA
basketball team. This year he's lugging the Charlotte trainer's
black medical kit. The Bruins? They weren't heavy, they were his
brothers. But Terry Kofler's black bag is !ital!a load!off!.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was almost out the gym door after the Hornets' practice
Thursday at Loyola Marymount when Kofler corralled him. ``Hey,
Baron, you take this one,'' he said, pushing in Davis's path a bag
big and bulky enough to be holding a corpse.
</P>
<P>
   Davis picked the bag up without complaint, the way it says to in
the unofficial NBA rookie handbook, and dragged it toward the bus.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a sight, Davis coolly trying to carry the bag and
carry on a conversation and keep his sweat pants _ the ones with
the dead elastic waistline _ from gathering in a pool around his
ankles while a few Hornets who weren't already on the bus tried
hard not to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that what rookies are for, comic relief?
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Los Angeles native has adapted better than many
people thought he would to the highs, lows and hazing of NBA life.
Davis, 20, is enjoying a hearty laugh at the expense of, as he put
it, ``a lot of doubters who thought I'd be a big disappointment in
the NBA because of my (surgically repaired left) knee and because
I'm so young.''
</P>
<P>
   He is averaging 20 minutes and 6.2 points off the bench for a
Hornets team that's flexing its muscle and arm-wrestling Indiana
for control of the Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   Davis knows his place among a veteran group that includes Eddie
Jones, Anthony Mason and Derrick Coleman, though he's not above
stealing the spotlight occasionally with one of his space jams.
Everyone from David Wesley to David Stern was agog last month when
the 6-foot-3 Davis dunked over 6-foot-11 Kevin Garnett during a win
at Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the soundness of his left knee. It obviously had
recovered by then from a bone bruise Davis suffered in November.
</P>
<P>
   The dunk led the weekly NBA highlight reel and nearly a month
later, players continue to sidle up to Davis and say, ``Whassup
with that dunk on Kevin Garnett?''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins fans have seen it all before. Indeed, he often gave them
reason to feel like they had shown up for a personal screening of
Davis' highlight film and a game broke out. Davis played as if he
was updating his resume on every possession. He was in such a hurry
to get to the NBA, he cut short his collegiate career by two years.
</P>
<P>
   The restlessness he wore like baggy shorts at UCLA is gone,
Davis said, discarded along with that goofy white headband he
favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm very patient,'' he said and why not? ``I'm on a
good team and I'm around great guys who are teaching me the little
tricks of the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   People can criticize Davis for not staying at UCLA, but the way
he looks at it he never left school. He's simply accruing advanced
credits in his chosen career field _ basketball _ while serving one
heck of an internship.
</P>
<P>
   ``College was fun,'' Davis said, ``but as far as learning about
being a better basketball player the NBA is a great place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Hornets practice on this day, we could see what he
means. Davis was paired with Jones on a shooting drill and later
got a few technical tips from a braying Bobby Phills.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Davis hasn't at times second-guessed himself.
Every now and then, he gets a pang in his side. It's a nostalgia
cramp and sometimes it takes a lot of deep breaths to make it go
away.
</P>
<P>
   Said Davis, ``There are days when I think, `Oh, man, I should
have come back, we would have had a great team.'''
</P>
<P>
   Davis averaged 30.7 minutes, 15.9 points, 3.6 rebounds and 5.1
assists as a sophomore. For better or worse, he was the Bruins'
go-to guy. Because he also played the point, there were people who
complained his presence was overpowering. They are the same people
who projected a better season this year for the Bruins without him.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   It's highly unlikely UCLA, which opened Pacific-10 play Thursday
at Washington, would have lost to Colorado State, been blown out by
Gonzaga and barely escaped from South Florida's clutches with Davis
in the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been nice to have been the Man for another year or
two. But Davis likes what he is in Charlotte just fine: the porter
in charge of delivering the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
