<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9118 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-Doctor-Killings-KAN &LR;      01-07 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Doctor-Killings-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Former physician asks to withdraw pleas in killing two of her
children  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Claiming that her thinking was clouded by medication and mental
problems, former physician Debora Green asked Thursday to withdraw
pleas of no contest to killing two of her children.
</P>
<P>
   Green was sentenced in May 1996 to life in prison for setting a
fire that raced through her family's suburban Kansas City, Mo.,
home in Prairie Village, Kan., in 1995, trapping the children
upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   She also was sentenced for the attempted murder of a third
child, who climbed out a window to escape, and for trying to kill
her then-husband by poisoning his food.
</P>
<P>
   By pleading no contest to the charges, she avoided a trial and
possible death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But in documents filed Thursday in Johnson County (Kan.)
District Court, Green said that she was ``unduly influenced'' by
the advice of her attorneys to take the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   She now seeks that trial and a chance to post bond while the
case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Wichita, Kan., attorney Kurt Kerns, who filed the action on
Green's behalf, did not respond to an interview request Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Morrison, who prosecuted Green, said her
motion was ``without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those actions are very common,'' he said. ``It comes as no
surprise. We'll oppose it obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Such requests rarely result in new trials.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who is now 48, is being held in maximum security at the
Topeka Correctional Facility in Kansas. She will be eligible for
parole consideration in 2035.
</P>
<P>
   Green's case drew national media attention and was the subject
of a book by Seattle author Ann Rule.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after Green was sent to the penitentiary and taken
off the medication that she recognized the effect of her medical
conditions and the drugs on her ability to make decisions,
according to her motion.
</P>
<P>
   The petition stated that she suffered from severe depression,
severe anxiety, psychosis and bipolar disorder with manic episodes.
She was being treated with antidepressants, antipsychotics and
anticonvulsants, the petition said.
</P>
<P>
   The mixture of mental illness and drugs made her unable to
understand what was happening and unable to communicate with her
attorneys ``in a rational and meaningful sense,'' according to her
claim.
</P>
<P>
   Because she was incompetent to make those decisions, her
petition said, she was denied her right to a fair trial and due
process of law.
</P>
<P>
   She was represented at the time by Dennis Moore, now a U.S.
congressman, and Kevin Moriarty.
</P>
<P>
   Both said Thursday that they had not seen the motion yet and
could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   At Green's plea hearing in April 1996, District Judge Peter
Ruddick questioned her about the drugs she was taking and whether
she was able to understand what was happening in court.
</P>
<P>
   She said she knew what she was doing and didn't want to compound
the suffering of her family and surviving daughter by taking the
case to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that it is best to end this now so that we can begin
to heal from this horrible loss,'' she said in court that day.
</P>
<P>
   At her sentencing in May of that year, she read a statement that
cautioned against ignoring the signs of alcohol abuse and mental
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcohol, psychiatric illness and even more basic communication
failures within our family set the stage for this tragedy,'' she
said in court. ``I do not seek to use that fact to escape my
personal responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's former husband, Mike Farrar, nearly died from the
complications of the poisoning attempts that occurred in the months
before the fatal fire, and had to undergo surgery a number of
times.
</P>
<P>
   He has since remarried, and he and his surviving daughter, now
15, are doing well, he said Thursday. He said he spoke to Morrison
about the motion and was ``not particularly concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a tremendous amount of faith in Paul Morrison and his
office,'' Farrar said.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing date on the motion has not been set yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
