<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALFFY'S BACK, AND LOOKS GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ziggy Palffy played Thursday night against the
Florida Panthers, even had an assist. But the Los Angeles Kings
know his sore lower back isn't going to be healed any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, who missed Tuesday's game in St. Louis after his back
flared up in pregame warmups, worked out Thursday morning but was
not cleared to play until minutes before game time.
</P>
<P>
   One day after seeing a soft-tissue specialist and a doctor for
the discs in his lower back, Palffy appeared to have the form that
has made him the club's leading scorer (35 points).
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, he broke in on Panthers goaltender
Mike Vernon. Palffy's wrist shot hit Vernon's pads and popped out.
Luc Robitaille took a whack in front, but Len Barrie poked it in
for his second goal of the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was Palffy's 21st assist of the season. It also was a much
better situation than the Kings had two days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, his back stiffened up just before the game and the
Kings had to go scrambling for a body to fill his roster spot.
Enforcer Steve McKenna already was in street clothes in the press
box when he received word that Palffy was out and he was in.
</P>
<P>
   There is quite a difference between McKenna, who has no goals
and just four points, to Palffy's 14 goals. Tuesday night, the
Kings' first line consisted of Barrie and wingers Marko Tuomainen
and Vladimir Tsyplakov.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors say there can't be further damage,'' said Kings
coach Andy Murray, who thought of holding Palffy out until Tuesday
night against Ottawa. ``Three days isn't going to make a lot of
difference. He could use three months. We're preparing like he's
not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vote of confidence: Murray met with the Kings before the morning
practice and singled out defenseman Jaroslav Modry as a key
contributor in Tuesday's 1-1 tie against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Modry, who scored late in the second period Thursday to give the
Kings a 3-1 lead, was coming off a terrible game Monday night in
Dallas. His failure to control the puck early in the game resulted
in a short-handed goal for the Stars. But Tuesday, he set up
newcomer Bob Corkum on the Kings' first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Modry was not a favorite of former coach Larry Robinson, and
despite an impressive training camp he was benched after Mattias
Norstrom returned from a contract holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Modry has played sparingly this season, but scored a goal Dec.
30 in the Kings' 8-2 rout of Edmonton. Thursday, he played in place
of defenseman Frantisek Kaberle, who also has played on the power
play with Garry Galley (concussion), but has been scratched the
past few games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the skate, I took Modry as an example of what we
want,'' Murray said. ``He recovered from a very bad game in Dallas
to have a very good game in St. Louis. We want Kaberle to have a
rest and Modry to have a vote of confidence.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff Writer Brian Dohn contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
