<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Grace-Retirement-KAN </SLUG>
  
 `Amazing Grace' retires from fast-food job at 90  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARA ROSE WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Nearly a dozen years ago, when she was 79,
Grace Staab walked into an Independence Taco Bell for lunch. In a
sweet, grandmotherly way she scolded a manager for having an untidy
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Before she knew it, she had left with a full stomach and a
part-time job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was after the noon hour the day I walked in there,''
recalled Staab, of Raytown. ``The place was a bit trashed. The
shift manager came out and said to me, `How's everything?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said everything is fine, but this would be an easy job to
keep these tables wiped up. Then they just talked me into that job.
I just went in there for a taco.''
</P>
<P>
   She thought she would try the hostess job for a week or two, but
weeks turned into years.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Staab _ now 90 _ threw herself a retirement party
at the Taco Bell in Raytown, where she has worked since leaving the
Independence Taco Bell about five years ago. More than 80 persons
showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace has been saying for a long time that if she makes it to
the year 2000, she would finally retire,'' said Glen Pitts, who
hired Staab at the Raytown restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a great work ethic. It's not so much her keeping the
lobby clean, but she's great for public relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Staab has greeted every customer who came through the door.
She's carried trays, helped mothers with cranky babies, decorated
the restaurant with flowers from her garden, and bounced from table
to table chatting with customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when they have to wait too long in line, I help them pass
the time by telling jokes,'' Staab said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder her regular customers call her ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy and Pat Voyles have eaten at the Taco Bell once a week since
Staab started there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves this lady,'' Roy Voyles said. ``She is the
life of the party. She always has time for you. She could be
feeling bad, and she'll make you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Staab has worked since she was 8 years old, when she washed
dishes for 25 cents a load. In the 1930s and '40s, she checked
coats.
</P>
<P>
   When she accepted the Taco Bell job in September 1988, she
already had two others. She worked from 6 to 10 a.m. at her
grandson's bakery in Independence, and from 4 to 8 p.m. at another
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Taco Bell filled the empty hours between 11 a.m and 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Staab can still drive her 1975 Buick Park Avenue during the day,
but she gave up the other jobs when she could no longer see well at
night. Emphysema, she said, has now slowed her down.
</P>
<P>
   Since meeting Staab five years ago, Mildred Wash has driven once
a week to the Taco Bell from her home near Swope Park. She's amused
by the notion that Staab might be losing her energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humph!'' Wash said. ``At her age, she really moves like a
young person. She can work circles around most people. She really
keeps this place clean, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Staab loves to work, she still finds time to do a lot
more.
</P>
<P>
   She's traveled to China, Korea, Mexico and Alaska. And she has a
large family: three children, 24 grandchildren (including spouses
of her grandchildren), and 26 great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Staab said she will miss the people at Taco Bell, but will find
plenty to keep her busy at home. Great-grandson Ben Premoe said
he's not worried about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're at her house, she never sits down,'' he said.
``I'm surprised she stops long enough to go to bed at night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
