<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9121 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN     01-07 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FORAY FAR FROM HORSEPLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Solomon Feingold describes himself as a longshot
bettor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely hate favorites,'' says the 59-year-old
grandfather from West Hills. ``I'm not interested in putting down
$2 to win $3.40.''
</P>
<P>
   But based on past performances, he should be considered one of
the favorites in the first-ever national horse-race handicapping
tournament today and Saturday at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said he has won more than $250,000 in handicapping
tournaments over the past 15 years. That includes the $125,000 he
received in October for outwitting 700 other players at the Orleans
Casino in Las Vegas to qualify for this weekend's event.
</P>
<P>
   He's one of 160 qualifiers from among 45,000 competing at 40
racetracks, simulcast facilities and casinos around the country for
what could be called the horseplayers' U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The contestants run the gamut from professional handicappers
like John Conte of New York, turf writer Bob Randazzo of the
Cleveland Plain Dealer and trainer-statistics analyst Frank Tate of
Oceanside, to a blind man from Minnesota and a 68-year-old retired
preschool teacher who qualified at New Hampshire's Rockingham Park
by winning the first tournament she ever entered.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, who runs an advertising agency in Agoura, lands
somewhere in between those extremes. He's not a professional or a
full-time horseplayer, but a dedicated racetracker who's been
playing the races since he was a teen-ager in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling was part of the upbringing,'' said Feingold, although
he notes that his parents didn't gamble. ``We bet with bookies on
the games and the horse racing. We had the illegal numbers, which I
played maybe a couple times in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Feingold didn't become a cards player, he noted wryly, because
``I don't like smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   He gravitated toward the racetrack because there a gambler can
put up a small amount of money to win a lot, and because the
parimutuel system makes winning and losing a matter of skill in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a thrill,'' Feingold said. ``It's not the money as
much as(the chance to say), `Wow, I beat everybody.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon at the track, he said, he's content to take a
table for one in the dining room and watch the races on the
television screens. He'll risk about $2,000 a day on a mixture of
win, place, exacta, trifecta, pick-three and pick-six bets.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to check horses' recent efforts with the help of the
tracks' video replay machines. Mostly, though, he looks for clues
in the Daily Racing Form past-performance charts that he believes
other bettors will miss.
</P>
<P>
   He looks for big fields in cheap races on the theory that
they'll produce more longshot winners.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers horses stepping up to tougher competition to horses
diving in class, because the ``public'' is a sucker for droppers.
</P>
<P>
   He likes horses trying a distance after fading in sprints,
because the slower pace of the longer races might keep them going.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't play hunches or listen to tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make money by betting favorites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold believes his natural preference for longshots gives him
an advantage in handicapping tournaments, in which the winner is
the player whose horses produce the highest total payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   At the Orleans tournament last fall, Feingold played 36 races
beamed in from Santa Anita, Bay Meadows, Louisiana Downs, Belmont
Park and Calder and picked six winners returning between $18 to $45
on $2 bets.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1990s, Feingold stopped competing in tournaments
because, increasingly, they required players to bet on races from
places other than the California tracks with which he's familiar.
</P>
<P>
   When he decided to play the Orleans qualifier last fall,
Feingold called on a pair of ``consultants,'' friends from Las
Vegas and El Paso who follow racing nationwide. They led him to
half his winners. He cut them in for a share of the prize.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants will be available to Feingold again this weekend
on sort of a ``Phone a Friend'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, sponsored by the Daily Racing Form, promises a
$200,000 purse. The champion will receive $100,000 plus a
``Handicapper of the Year'' award that will be presented at the
Eclipse Awards dinner at the Beverly Hilton on Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The rules require each player to take stabs at 20 races each day
10``mandatory'' races selected by tournament organizers, and 10 of
the player's choosing. The player with the highest total payoffs on
$2 win bets will be the champion.
</P>
<P>
   For contest purposes, payoffs will be capped at 20-1, so one
fluke longshot won't decide the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold limbered up for the tournament with a trip to Santa
Anita one day last week. He played a $148 pick-six ticket and hit
for $7,800.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready,'' he declared. ``I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   At Santa Anita: The weekend features the first local 3-year-old
stakes of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's San Miguel Stakes has drawn Del Mar Futurity winner
Forest Camp, switching from David Flores to Chris McCarron for his
first start since finishing sixth as the Breeders' Cup Juvenile
favorite at Gulfstream Park. The Bob Baffert-trained colt will
break from post 1 which hasn't produced a 6-furlong winner at the
Santa Anita meet against five opponents who include impressive
maiden-breaker Swept Overboard.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Santa Ysabel finds D. Wayne Lukas-trained Surfside, the
3-year-old filly with the best chance of taking on colts in the
Triple Crown preps, returning in just 20 days from her seven-length
victory under PatDay in the Hollywood Starlet. The field for the 1
1/16-mile race will be set today. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Santa Anita leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Kent Desormeaux,
10 wins; Corey Nakatani, 9; David Flores, 7; Chris McCarron and Pat
Valenzuela, 6. Trainers: Bob Baffert and Ron McAnally, 5; Bobby
Frankel, 4; John Dolan, Neil Drysdale and Bill Spawr, 3. &QL; 
Handicapper helper: Since front-runners went winless in 14
main-track sprints in the first three days of the Santa Anita meet,
they held on to win a strong 7 of 17 of those races in the
following four days. &QL; 
On the stakes schedule: At Santa Anita: today, $100,000 Survive
Stakes, California-bred fillies and mares age 4 and up, 5 furlongs;
Saturday, $100,000 San Miguel, 3-year-olds, 6 furlongs; Sunday,
$100,000 Santa Ysabel, 3-year-old fillies, 1 1/16 miles. At
Gulfstream Park: Saturday, $100,000 Broward Handicap, 3-year-olds
and up, 1 1/16 miles; Sunday, $100,000 Mac Diarmida Handicap,
3-year-olds and up, 1 3/8 miles. &QL; 
Mileposts: Frank Stronach, whose company owns Santa Anita, Golden
Gate Fields and Gulfstream Park, has dropped his threat to pull his
five U.S. tracks out of the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association at least until next January. NTRA officials have
promised to think about Stronach's recent demands a clearer mandate
for the organization, a democratically selected board and a
commitment to ``free enterprise'' in the industry. It's thought
that the two-year-old NTRA would have been crippled without
Stronach.... Laffit Pincay will receive a ``Special Eclipse Award''
at the Eclipse dinner Jan. 17 at the Beverly Hilton, recognizing
his achievement in breaking Bill Shoemaker's career-wins record
Dec. 10 at Hollywood Park.... Pincay returns Saturday from a
three-day suspension.... Pat Day wound up leading the national
jockey standings for 1999 with $18.1 million in purses, about
$800,000 more than Jerry Bailey. Bob Baffert led the trainers with
$16.8 million, about $4.7 million ahead of D. Wayne Lukas. Dubai
World Cup winner Almutawakel ($3.29 million) was the richest horse
who raced at least once in North America. Storm Cat, whose
offspring earned $9.6 million, was the top sire.... Karl Korte, 65,
a jockey on and off since 1953, stretched his career into a sixth
decade when he rode in a race at Gulfstream Park on Monday. If
that's a record, it may not last long: Ray York, 67, who won the
1954 Kentucky Derby with Determine, is preparing to make a brief
comeback at Santa Anita in February and notch his seventh decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
