<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-1STLD-W     01-07 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-YT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS TO CUT TAXES AS HE AND OTHER CANDIDATES TRADE BARBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ Eight years after his father learned the hard way
about making promises on taxes, Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday
night offered an unequivocal pledge never to raise taxes and _
going even further than the former president _ promised to cut
them.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a fierce competition with Sen. John McCain less than a
month before the presidential primary in New Hampshire, Bush, of
Texas, sought to overcome his father's famous reversal of a ``no
new taxes'' pledge. Conservatives never forgave then-President
George Bush for that move, which cost him critical support in the
1992 primary here and haunted his campaign against Bill Clinton
that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only no new taxes,'' Bush said in a debate with
his five rivals for the Republican presidential nomination at the
University of New Hampshire. ``This is tax cuts, so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Rather than create more government, I think we ought
to pass money back to the working in people in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's promise was a dramatic point of an hourlong debate in
which he and McCain, of Arizona, abandoned their months of
cordiality and sparred aggressively over their prescriptions for
campaign finance and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain clung to portraying himself as the reform candidate, even
as he was alled upon to defend his recent intervention with the
Federal Communications Commission in a matter that ultimately
benefited a major campaign contributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why I've worked so hard for campaign finance reform
because all this money washing around Washington and all those
uncontrolled contributions taint all of us,'' he said, smiling
broadly, as he did throughout the questions about his conduct. ``No
matter what we do we are under a cloud of suspicion, and I am one
of those as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate, the fourth featuring all six Republican candidates,
was the most spirited, and at times the most entertaining, of the
party's campaign. McCain suggested that Bush was behind an
independent group's advertising campaign attacking him. Bush, in
turn, scolded McCain for backing a campaign finance bill that ``Al
Gore is applauding.''
</P>
<P>
   The tense moments between Bush and McCain set the tone for an
increasingly strained competition between the two politicians, who
are neck and neck in the polls here, in the run-up to the New
Hampshire primary on Feb. 1. The competitors will meet three more
times in the next four days _ at a debate on Friday in South
Carolina, a dinner on Sunday in New Hampshire and another debate on
Monday in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and McCain battled each other, their four opponents,
struggling for attention, sought to portray them as not
sufficiently conservative for Republican primary voters. They
seized on the issue of homosexuals in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Every candidate took issue with comments on Wednesday night by
Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley _ standing on
the same stage at the University of New Hampshire _ that strongly
endorsed the right of homosexuals to serve openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
   But some contenders argued that McCain and Bush did not go far
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we accept the radical homosexual agenda,'' said Alan Keyes,
a former State Department official, ``be it in the military or in
marriage or in other areas of our lives, we are utterly destroying
the concepts of family.'' He added, ``those candidates up here
unwilling to face that fact and playing games with this issue are
doing so irresponsibly at the price of America's moral
foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes said he objected to comments by Bush, who did not rule out
appointing openly gay people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends what their policies are,'' Bush said. ``Depends on
what their views are.'' Referring the the administration's current
policy on gays, he said, ``I'm a don't ask, don't tell man.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also voiced support for the current policy, saying, ``I
would make sure that a policy that's working and is working and
should work was continued.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 60 minutes to share among the six of them, the
candidates often interrupted one another and often ignored the
questions posed by the moderator, Tim Russert of NBC News, and
three local journalists. Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah replied to a
question about Internet taxation by talking about the U.S. policy
toward Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic between McCain and Bush was notable because for
months, the two had hardly seemed like rivals. They were even
praising each other in debates. But on Thursday night, McCain
turned to Bush and suggested that he was behind an advertising
campaign by a conservative antitax group that has broadcast
commercials attacking McCain.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, a supporter of yours is running ads morphing Bill
Clinton's face into mine,'' McCain said. Then, seeking to inject
some levity into his accusation, he added, ``And by the way, ask
him to get a better picture, will you?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said, ``I don't think you have an idea of how
important campaign finance reform could restore the confidence of
young Americans in their government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush shot back: ``What you don't need to do is tell me what I
have an idea about or not.''
</P>
<P>
   This state has a tradition of opposing taxes, and Bush has made
his $483 billion, five-year tax cut plan a centerpiece of his
campaign here. In the first major policy dispute with McCain, Bush
this week accused McCain of shortchanging the middle class on tax
cuts. But McCain argued that the governor's proposal would go to
tax breaks for the upper class _ at the expense of money for Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, McCain said, ``Governor Bush said the other
day we're awash in cash. We've got a $5.6 trillion debt that we're
saddling young Americans with. We ought to pay down the debt. But
we also ought to make Social Security solvent.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the wealthy publisher who advocates the abolition
of the current tax code, took issue with Bush's drive to come
across as a tax cut crusader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He signed a pledge in 1994 promising not to put in a business
tax or to raise the state sales tax,'' he said of Bush's record in
Texas. ``Two years later he violated that pledge.'' He added, ``We
know what happens in the Republican Party when we violate no-tax
pledges.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes repeats that attack in his first _ and long anticipated _
caustic commercial of the campaign. In the commercial, Mary C.
Williams, who runs an organization in Texas called Taxpayers for
Accountability, said Bush's ``record as far as taxes are concerned
is a record of broken promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their sharp exchanges, Bush refused to be drawn into
questions about McCain's dealings with the FCC on behalf of a major
contributor, Paxson Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objection with John is not how he conducted himself as
chairman of the Commerce Committee,`` Bush said. His concern, he
explained was that the senator's campaign reform plan would, ``hurt
the Republican cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Often on Thursday night, the other contenders were eclipsed by
Bush and McCain. Forbes was asked why, after spending millions of
his fortune on his campaign, he had not made inroads in the polls.
Asked by one reporter if he was too aloof, Forbes drew laughs when
glanced at McCain and replied, ``Maybe you want me to give a hug to
John.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be glad to, Steve,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary L. Bauer, who is also battling for the conservative vote,
cast himself as more responsive to those voters than Bush. He
accused President Bush of making ``a colossal mistake'' by
appointing David Souter to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Governor Bush would defend his father, Bush said,
``Listen, I'm the only one on stage who's appointed judges.'' He
added, ``My dad can defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the debate the candidates spent time joking,
interrupting one another, swapping put-downs and complaining that
they were not drawing adequate attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush flashed his quick humor when he was asked, based on his
past comments about his belief in Christ, whether as president he
would think to himself ``What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take an expression into the Oval Office of, `Dear God
_ help me!''' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   To that, Keyes deadpanned, ``So would we, governor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't very Christian of you,'' Bush complained.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, it was Bush and McCain needling each other.
McCain said that Bush's plan for a tax cut dissipated the federal
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it doesn't,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it does,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No it doesn't, yes it does,'' Bush mimicked.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Keyes and Russert engaged in a semitense
standoff as Russert implored the candidate to stop talking, while
Keyes refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes ultimately sniped, ``The format of this debate is a little
strange. I begin to wonder when Mr. Russert will declare his
candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, too, seemed to feel overlooked. ``I'm going to stay here
and take some time myself,'' he insisted when one of his efforts to
make a comment bucked up against a time limit. ``I'm taking this
microphone, I tell you right now.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
