r a BC-Pheng-Holdup-KAN &LR;      01-07 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pheng-Holdup-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Woman accused in robbery attempt is ordered held without bond  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN T. DAUNER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pheng Siriboury's botched attempt Friday to hold up an suburban
Kansas City, Mo., bank was an ``act of desperation'' after she ran
up more than $100,000 in debts, her attorney told a federal
magistrate Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Johnson County, Kan., woman was ordered held
without bond on charges of attempting to rob the Bank of America in
Olathe, Kan., brandishing a firearm in a crime of violence and
taking hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Some bank employees who were taken hostage were held for eight
hours until a hostage disarmed Siriboury about 1 a.m. Saturday. No
one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Siriboury's attorney, Michael Harris, a federal public defender,
said that she should be released on bond to her parents. Saying she
was unlikely to commit another crime, Harris asked for electronic
monitoring, psychiatric counseling and a curfew. He said he would
seek a private psychiatric analysis to back up his request.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said Siriboury, a native of Laos, suffers from bipolar
disorder and a chemical imbalance. She needs treatment she can't
get in jail, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Streepy opposed release, saying
she was a danger to the community and a risk to flee.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate David J. Waxse said he would revisit the bond
matter if Harris could bring in sufficient evidence that Siriboury
was not likely to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Harris told Waxse that Siriboury's parents brought her to the
Kansas City area from Laos when she was 2 years old. She dropped
out of Olathe North High School as a sophomore, he said, and ran
away from home after arguments with her parents. She spent about a
month in a juvenile psychiatric facility in early 1993 and dropped
out of high school for good in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   She was married in 1997, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said Siriboury was ``addicted to gambling'' and had run
up debts _ ``maybe as high as $150,000'' _ part of it on credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her gambling addiction ruined her and her husband
financially,'' Harris said, adding that she was living with her
``estranged husband'' in Leawood, Kan., at the time of the bank
robbery. It was that situation that led to her ``act of
desperation,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Siriboury said nothing during the detention hearing, which
lasted about 30 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
