<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9127 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-OSHA-Home-KAN &LR;      01-07 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSHA-Home-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Employers relieved after Labor Department rescinds at-home work
policy  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Chris Long, president of Associated
Industries of Missouri, looked forward Wednesday afternoon to a
nice, relaxing airline flight to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Cheri Stubblefield, vice president of Creative Courseware Inc.,
celebrated an escape from what could have been the death of her
company as she knew it.
</P>
<P>
   Both were relieved that the U.S. Department of Labor _ in an
unusually quick turnaround _ rescinded a policy letter that only a
day earlier had been causing coast-to-coast panic among employers
who had employees working at home.
</P>
<P>
   Relief came when Labor Secretary Alexis Herman withdrew a
7-week-old ``guidance letter'' that had said employers were
responsible for meeting the same Occupational Safety and Health
Administration standards for at-home workers as for employees
working in the employers' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``An unfortunate letter,'' Long said of the initial opinion,
which was dated Nov. 15 but received national attention only this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telling employers that their liability would have extended to
situations where employees worked at home would have finished any
at-home opportunities,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Long said his association, which represents about 1,500 of the
largest employers in Missouri, sent one of many negative responses
about the guidance letter to the federal agency. He said it
``speaks well of the department that they listened to public
reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Creative Courseware officers did not formally respond to the
guidance letter, but it caused trepidation, Stubblefield said.
</P>
<P>
   The company specializes in performance consulting for businesses
and develops training materials, computer software support
materials, online help systems and computer manuals. This type of
work allows several employees to work from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have drastically altered the way we do business if we
would have suddenly had to provide office space for whatever
contractors happened to be working for us on the project of the
moment,'' Stubblefield said.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect could have been cost-prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have had to go out and rent one of those buildings
Sprint is vacating,'' she joked.
</P>
<P>
   Or, she added, ``we would have had to put contract stipulations
in each contract as to the conditions in home offices. The
oversight would have been a nightmare. We would have had to have
some right of access and inspection. It would have opened the door
to all kinds of legal problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubblefield said a pall placed on employers' willingness to
allow at-home workers would have harmed working mothers especially.
Many of them are in the labor force only because of the opportunity
to work at home, she said, and they might not be employed if they
didn't have that option.
</P>
<P>
   Herman's announcement Wednesday emphasized that the advisory
letter (which responded to questions asked in August by a company
in Texas) never had been intended as a statement of policy for all
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, though, many such guidance letters have been made
public and served to alert other companies as to the prevailing
regulatory winds.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 million Americans are thought to work regularly in
their homes, which means many employers would have been affected if
they were given responsibility for ensuring OSHA safety standards
in home offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Economic Policy Foundation, a research organization in
Washington, estimated that applying OSHA regulations to home
offices would have cost $22.5 billion in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   That's what it would have cost employers to remove hazards,
install safety equipment and signs, and do other things necessary
to bring home offices in compliance. Subsequently, an additional
$8.8 billion a year would have been spent on inspections and
upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   In rescinding the guidance letter, Herman noted that
``family-friendly, flexible and fair work arrangements, including
telecommuting, can benefit individual employees and their families,
employers and society as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the safety of at-home workers is a concern, the labor
secretary said she would convene a task force that includes
representatives of the Commerce Department, the Small Business
Administration, Labor Department and others to examine ``the broad
social and economic effects of telecommuting.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial query about employer liability for at-home workers
came from CSC Credit Services in Houston. The company asked OSHA to
respond to five principal questions:
</P>
<P>
   - What is the employer's obligation within the home work
environment?
</P>
<P>
   - Is the employer responsible for compliance with the home
itself?
</P>
<P>
   - Is the employer required to do periodic compliance inspections
in the home, which may include safety, health, fire and
environmental issues?
</P>
<P>
   - What would be OSHA's inspection procedures in a private home?
</P>
<P>
   - Does the employer have to include these home locations in its
file regarding record-keeping (for OSHA)?
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the responses from OSHA's compliance office said that
OSHA regulations applied to anywhere an employee worked and that
employers had responsibility for inspecting and ensuring safe
working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Sentences such as this raised public ire: ``For example, if work
is performed in the basement space of a residence and the stairs
leading to the space are unsafe, the employer could be liable if
the employer knows or reasonably should have known of the dangerous
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman's subsequent retraction of the letter did not get into
details about what parts of the advisory may or may not survive.
Those decisions may evolve from the work of the task force she
convened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HEAT-HNS &LR;      01-07 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ If need be _ and a few moments of fantasy are beginning to
seem necessary _ Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich can always imagine
his summer reward for the dues paid in a sinking season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Had he blurred his vision just a little Thursday night and
looked closely at Heat center Alonzo Mourning demolishing an
outmanned frontcourt, Tomjanovich could have easily pictured
himself coaching the United States Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   He could have watched the Miami Heat overpower what is left of
his Rockets and imagined the Dream Team routs to come. It wouldn't
even have been hard to imagine Rockets guard Steve Francis' flights
into the teeth of the Heat defense as one of those underdog
challenges against the Dream Team that becomes the highlight of
mundane routs.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton one night. Mourning another. And the Rockets were
left Thursday looking much like the sort of undermanned teams to be
whipped in Sydney. But after the Heat settled for a 111-99 win not
nearly that close, Tomjanovich at least knew where and when he
could reverse his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he knows what he has to work with this summer,''
Mourning said. ``I expect to have a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning seemed to be having about as much fun Thursday as he
ever shows. So caught up in his current problems after a loss to
the Grizzlies on Tuesday, the day he was named to the Olympic team,
Mourning had forgotten who would be his Olympic coach. That changed
when Tomjanovich offered his congratulations Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning then scored 28 points _ one shy of the 29 his future
Dream Teammate Payton hit the Rockets with Tuesday _ on 12-of-15
shooting. He needed just three quarters to block a season-high nine
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason (Payton and Mourning) are on the (Olympic) team is
they're good,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He's damn good. There was
nothing we could do. We had nobody to stop Mourning. He was
phenomenal at both ends of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   With center Kelvin Cato joining Hakeem Olajuwon, Charles Barkley
and Tony Massenburg as unavailable Rockets big men, the Heat met
little resistance inside. Carlos Rogers, still badly weakened by a
respiratory infection, fell into quick foul trouble and played just
19 minutes. Thomas Hamilton was not nearly quick enough to slow
Mourning defensively. Kenny Thomas, a 6-7 rookie, switched to him
but was not nearly strong or tall enough inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about P.J. (Brown) and (Tim) Weatherspoon,''
Thomas said. ``I think I can guard guys in the post. But he
(Mourning) is big, and he's strong. He's taller than me, of course.
I was just trying to play him straight up, and the coaches told me
to give him jump shots. That's all I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat was so dominant inside that it outscored the Rockets
60-30 in the paint. And having lamented its mediocre board work of
late, Miami outrebounded the Rockets enough to outscore them 16-10
on second-chance points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough with all our injuries to our big men,'' said
Rockets forward Walt Williams, who had 17 points off the bench.
``It's tough inside all the time. Olajuwon, Barkley, Tony
Massenburg, Kelvin Cato. That's a big part of this team.
Establishing ourselves down low right now is hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the benches were emptied, the Heat had taken a
27-point lead in the third quarter. Mourning played just three
minutes in the fourth, watching as the Rockets cut a 24-point lead
in half in the final seven minutes with every Heat starter on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not feeling (undermanned),'' Tomjanovich said. ``I know we
are. We're sort of in a rebuilding deal. Cato is a big part of
that. Not having the guy in a game like this is devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Rockets hope was to penetrate enough to draw Mourning
and either finish over him or pass outside to shooters left open.
Francis pulled off one example of beating Mourning, soaring to
score over him for a three-point play early in the second half.
Francis finished with 22 points and six assists, easily leading the
Rockets in both categories. And he might have been the only person
in the building unimpressed by Mourning's dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was fouling me every time,'' Francis said. ``He fouled me
every single time. I was over the rim and just lost the ball. I'm
definitely going to lift tomorrow, so I'll get my legs stronger and
put it on his head five times instead of one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets did act for much of the night as if they expected to
come up with such an inexplicable result. Though within two points
six minutes into the second quarter, they were outscored 14-5 to
end the half, making just two of 12 shots in six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, they could barely get shots, and when they
did they made few. The Rockets made five of 15 shots as their most
consistent offense became drawing illegal defenses, and the Heat
pulled away easily.
</P>
<P>
   Miami attacked the basket, making 14 of 22 shots in the decisive
third quarter and rarely shooting outside unless via penetration
and a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game plan was to go straight to the basket and make
plays,'' Mourning said. ``When you take the ball aggressively to
the basket, it forces the defense to help. If they don't help, you
get high-percentage shots. We got it on the floor and took it to
the basket. We need to continue to pound the ball inside and use
our size.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning didn't say it, but he might just memorize that little
speech. It sounded just about right for Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Tomjanovich) said it was going to be fun,'' Mourning said.
``I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   His summer coach must surely know how he feels.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
