<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9129 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-Heaster-Column-KAN &LR;      01-07 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Heaster-Column-KAN </SLUG>
  
 KCP&AMP;L merits kudos, not carping  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Speaking as a Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co.
customer and interested observer of the local business scene,
KCP&AMP;L's decision to scrap its planned merger with Western Resources
was as welcome as the flowers in spring.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the leading local power company in a deal playing
second banana to a Topeka, Kan., company never did seem fitting.
Nobody would say as much, but it downgraded Kansas City's image as
the dominant regional economic force.
</P>
<P>
   Most area residents probably don't think of KCP&AMP;L as the city's
most dynamic enterprise _ when they think of it at all, that is.
When locals think of KCP&AMP;L, it's mostly when their lights go out.
When the lights come back on in relatively short order, as is
usually the case, the company's promptness is taken for granted.
Meantime, this efficiency doesn't predispose the community to cut
KCP&AMP;L much slack when Mother Nature contrives to make service
restoration a long and difficult process.
</P>
<P>
   Although KCP&AMP;L is one of the area's most important companies, it
is also the most underappreciated. Nobody gives it bouquets for its
highly dependable service, but when things go extraordinarily wrong
the media and most customers are always quick to carp.
</P>
<P>
   This is too bad because KCP&AMP;L's record for filling the local
economy's electricity needs has been nothing short of spectacular.
While it has taken its public relations lumps for doing what's
necessary to keep up with rising power demand, it never gets the
thanks it deserves when the added capacity saves the day.
</P>
<P>
   As those blistering summer peak-demand periods pass without any
need for rolling brownouts, credit is never given where it's due.
Nobody ever says, for instance, ``It's a good thing KCP&AMP;L pushed
successfully for the Wolf Creek nuclear power plant years ago,
despite much protest, because otherwise we'd be in real deep
trouble about now.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, most people never stop to think about the symbolism of
the name: Kansas City Power &AMP; Light. It's a metaphor for what
inspires local pride and progress. To imagine Kansas City without
an eponymous power company is a depressing prospect. This symbolism
wasn't lost on those seeking to revitalize downtown when they
decided to call their project the Power &AMP; Light District.
</P>
<P>
   Even the company's erstwhile art deco headquarters remains to
this day the most distinctive edifice downtown. They don't build
'em like that anymore, and it would be a sad day if this beautiful
monument to Kansas City's 20th century vigor became known as
anything other than the Power &AMP; Light Building.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to tell where KCP&AMP;L will go from here, or what shape
it will take. Deregulation is changing the face of the electric
power industry, although not as rapidly hereabouts as some other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the future brings, though, those served so reliably by
KCP&AMP;L should never lose sight of the fact that their quality of
life has benefited immensely from the efficiency of this company
and the dedication of its employees.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever happens, it would be gratifying to see the name
survive in perpetuity as the symbol of a city so exciting it was
once celebrated in songs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
