<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9133 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBA-BOY-2NDLD-WRITET     01-07 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS IN MIAMI PROTEST INS DECISION TO RETURN BOY TO CUBA
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs 2nd and 4th grafs for updating) 
 (sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hundreds of Cuban-Americans, energized by a new cause,
shut down much of Miami on Thursday with waves of civil
disobedience, blocking access to the Port of Miami and choking
traffic on dozens of busy streets, to protest the Clinton
administration's decision to return 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to
his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   About 135 protesters were arrested by riot police officers, who
led them away peacefully in plastic handcuffs as the crowd chanted,
``Libertad Elian, libertad Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are asking for is that this boy have his day in court,
and that the boy's father come here to ask for his son without
pressure from the Cuban government,'' said Jose Basulto, the
founder of the Cuban exile group Brothers to the Rescue, before
being taken into a police van.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening, the disturbance spread from downtown Miami to
other pockets, bringing many cars to a standstill at rush hour and
leading Gov. Jeb Bush to suspend tolls on several major highways.
Later, riot police fired tear gas to disperse hundreds of
protesters from one intersection.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident, a commuter rammed a car through lines of
demonstrators who were linking arms to block an intersection,
knocking down two protesters. They were taken to a hospital. In
another incident, a police officer who was hit by another motorist
suffered broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Immigration and Naturalization Service ruled
that the boy should be returned to his father in Cuba by Jan. 14.
The decision came more than a month after the unseaworthy boat
Elian, his mother, his stepfather and 11 other people took capsized
en route to Miami. Eleven of them died, including his mother and
stepfather. Elian's father, Juan Gonzalez, said he did not know the
boy was leaving the country and wants the boy sent back.
</P>
<P>
   Elian soon found himself in the middle of a sensitive diplomatic
tug-of-war between Cuba and Miami, between his father on the island
and his relatives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And in a sign that the boy's return to Cuba by Jan. 14 may not
proceed as smoothly as the administration would like, lawyers for
the boy said that immigration officials had not asked his Miami
relatives to turn Elian over and that the relatives may not do so
without a deportation order from the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS doesn't want to do the dirty work of deporting the
boy, and after not even being heard, we may not be inclined to help
them,'' said Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, one of a phalanx of lawyers
representing the family. ``There is no order to turn the boy over.
We think they have to initiate deportation.''
</P>
<P>
   An INS spokesman, Russ Bergeron, said the agency would not
forcibly remove the boy, and added: ``This is not a deportation.
This is an attempt to honor the wishes of the father.''
</P>
<P>
   Along block after block, in cafeterias and storefronts, Elian's
case has served as a clarion call for Cuban exiles here, a group
that over the last decade has grown considerably older, wearier and
more fractured since the death two years ago of one of its most
vocal leaders, Jorge Mas Canosa.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing unites Cuban-Americans like a good brawl with Fidel
Castro, and this one _ the story of a boy who watched his mother
die at sea as they fled Cuba by boat _ carries just the right mix
of politics and drama to embolden the community.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true in Cuba, where Castro has used the case as a
patriotic rallying cry to re-energize the Cuban people against
Americans who have ``kidnapped'' the boy. The father said he did
not know his former wife and his son were leaving the country for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Garcia, security director for Alpha 66, a paramilitary
group that has sought for decades to overthrow Castro, said: ``This
has unified the community in the last few days. It has unified the
community in Miami in an incredible way. People had grown distant
from the cause. Time has passed. People had lost their will, their
enthusiasm. Now people are fighting shoulder to shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Attorney General Janet Reno said on Thursday that
she saw no basis for reversing the decision by the immigration
service to return the boy to his father in Cuba. But Reno said she
could not absolutely rule out a change of mind ``if any information
we are not privy to'' comes to light.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials interviewed Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, on two separate occasions, the first to listen to his
plea that his son be returned, and the second to ensure that he
truly wanted his son back in Cuba without pressure from Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are satisfied he is speaking for himself,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has declined a American offer to let him pick up his
son in Florida and has asked the INS to have the National Council
of Churches, a group that met with Gonzalez in Cuba, act as
intermediary in the boy's return, Bergeron said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Immigration experts and INS officials maintain that Elian's
Miami relatives have no legal standing to overturn the decision
since Elian's father is the one who speaks for him.
</P>
<P>
   But many Miami exiles disagree. They point to the fact that the
immigration service initially agreed that the case should be
handled as a custody matter by state courts. And they point an
accusing finger at President Clinton, saying he caved into
political pressure from Castro, who threatened to turn the incident
into a migraine headache for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton said politics did not enter into the
administration's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Clinton doesn't mind breaking the law, but there
are laws in this country,'' said Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, a
Republican who represents Miami in Congress. ``This is illegal.
Only a court of law can decide this.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian, who has been living with his paternal great-aunt and
great-uncle, was sheltered for the most part from the commotion.
When he returned home from school, which he began attending this
week, he flashed a smile and waved to cheering fans from atop his
great uncle's shoulders. Relatives said they were heartbroken about
having to tell him of the INS decision. They said they would try to
broach the subject on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he doesn't want to go,'' said Alfredo Martell, one of
Elian's many cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the family said on Thursday they want immigration
officials to issue a deportation order for Elian in the hopes that
the case would then go before an immigration judge. ``We would be
perfectly willing to go along with that,'' said Spencer Eig,
another lawyer for the family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
