<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9136 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-TRANSPORT-FUNDS-LADN     01-07 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPORT-FUNDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR'S THREAT HAS MTA SWEATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Terri Hardy  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO -- Under Gov. Gray Davis' ``use it or lose it''
crackdown on highway funds, the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority could forfeit up to $447 &UR;  &LR; million in unspent federal
funds intended for buses, street and freeway improvements,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In an unexpected bombshell dropped during his State of the State
address Wednesday night, Davis warned that if local transit
agencies throughout California do not spend $1.7 billion
``languishing'' in their accounts by July 31, the state would
``reprogram'' the money for them.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' remarks set off a firestorm of concern Thursday among Los
Angeles area transportation officials, but his staff was unable to
provide details on the money at risk or on how the governor intends
to carry out his ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   David Yale, the MTA's director of capital planning and
programming, said the agency already is hard-pressed to meet new
state deadlines that went into effect this year. The MTA had mapped
out a three-year plan of action that now must be completed in the
next seven months -- a task that could prove impossible if Davis
carries out his threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we sit on our hands we could lose this money,'' Yale said.
``L.A. County agencies will have to respond by expediting
transportation improvements even more quickly than we
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   In that time, the MTA would have to buy 370 critically needed
buses and carry out a host of improvements to major streets,
creating of diamond lanes, installation of freeway ramp meters and
freeway improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Yale said he believes Davis eventually will ease the deadline to
something more realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is using a bully pulpit to get transportation
agencies to focus on getting projects done faster,'' Yale said.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor's get-tough message -- a key provision in his
overall transportation plan -- was clouded Thursday by conflicting
and vague information when his office was pressed for details.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary McLean, a spokeswoman for the governor, could not provide
a breakdown by region showing how much money was unspent, and
little information was available on the types of transportation
funds under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   And in a hastily convened meeting with members of the governor's
administration, frustrated representatives from city and county
associations said no verification of the ``languishing'' funds was
provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out of that meeting more confused than when we went
in,'' said DeAnn Baker, a legislative representative for the
California State Association of Counties. ``There is no way that we
are sitting on $1.7 billion. We asked them to show us the money and
they couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker acknowledges that a significant amount of money is
unspent, sometimes because of poor communication or planning. But
in many other instances the reasons are good, or out of the local
agencies' control, including putting aside money for potential cost
overruns or receiving money late from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Davis administration officials told the group -- but provided no
written documentation -- that cities and counties were holding on
to $500million in capital project money known as ``STIP'' funds;
$800 million in federal Regional Surface Transportation Program and
Congestion Management Air Quality funds; and an additional $300
million that could not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Harrison, a spokesman for the state Department of Finance,
said late Thursday that the $1.7 billion figure was taken from a
document produced 18 months ago by the state controller, but the
breakdown of types of funds was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   A regional chart showing unspent money was included, showing Los
Angeles County holding $113 million and Los Angeles City holding
$17.8 million far below the MTA's own figure.
</P>
<P>
   Also unclear to the cities and counties was the governor's
ability to somehow take away federal transportation funds.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said the governor at this time is not empowered to
``reprogram'' those funds, and legislation changing the law would
be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   During the Wilson administration, legislation was drafted to
give cities and counties more control and planning over how their
transportation funding was spent. But Baker said there is a sense
that the Davis administration would like to see more control.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, AB 1012, a bill that required speedier deadlines and
added the threat of losing transportation money, was signed into
law.
</P>
<P>
   During a day of uncertainty Thursday, the only thing that could
readily be agreed upon was that transportation financing, with its
host of funding sources, rules and new deadlines, is almost
impossible to comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   MTA's Yale said his agency is operating under strict deadlines
imposed under AB 1012 that would set amounts of the $447 million to
be spent by Sept. 30, 2002. But an official in the office of
Assemblyman Tom Torlakson, D-Martinez, the author of AB 1012, said
no such restrictions apply to those MTA funds.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0025 </DOCNO>
