<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-INCENTIVES (Undated) _ On Wednesday, only hours after
New York's Gov. George Pataki asked lawmakers in Albany to
subsidize tuition for anyone who commits to teach in a New York
public school, Gov. Gray Davis of California addressed the
legislature in Sacramento with what, in effect, amounted to a
counteroffer. California, Davis proposed, should offer candidates
for its teaching jobs $10,000 home loans, $30,000 bonuses if they
attain advanced certification and $11,000 to repay college loans if
they agree to work in low-performing schools. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-OBRIAN (Undated) _ Patrick O'Brian, the Anglo-Irish
novelist whose stirring tales of the British navy in the Napoleonic
Wars made him a literary celebrity at an age when most writers have
long ceased to ply their trade, died in Dublin on Sunday. He was
84. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEATH-PENALTY (Houston) _ In his five years as governor of
Texas, George W. Bush has presided over the executions of 111 men
and one woman, nearly one of every five carried out in the United
States since the Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty in
1976. By any measure, Bush's commitment to capital punishment is
unquestioned. But as he runs for president as a more compassionate
kind of Republican, his death penalty record also offers insights
into his distinct views of mercy and justice. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY _ When Clinton administration officials
interviewed Gen. Charles Krulak for the job of commandant of the
Marine Corps in 1995, he recalls, no one asked him for his views on
any social issue facing the military. And so he said he was
dismayed when he read that the two Democratic candidates for
president, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley,
would require their appointees to the Joint Chiefs of Staff to
support allowing homosexuals to serve openly in the military. Gore
went even further than Bradley to say it would be a litmus test for
any nominee he selected. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DVD-BOOM (Undated) _ Analysts and retailers predict that the
growing popularity of DVDs, which resemble compact discs that play
music but are capable of storing enough additional digital
information to provide moving images, will reinvigorate the video
retail business by giving customers a new reason to visit video
stores. By Terry Pristin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic have been sent to NYT photo/graphic
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Relatively little is known about Vladimir
Putin's views on what kind of economic system should evolve in
Russia. The acting president has said little about the country's
enormous debts, or the cronyism and favoritism that have alienated
many foreign investors. On Thursday, though, Putin took a few steps
that suggested he was beginning to deal with Russia's economic
problems. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ When a show is providing a thrill
a minute, there is a risk that the competing act down the block
will be ignored. Given the recent stock market, that is what has
happened to the least risky _ and therefore least exciting _
investment around: inflation-indexed bonds. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   UAL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ United Airlines decides to switch its
advertising strategy. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Gail Collins on the primary
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Thomas L. Friedman on the lack fo
Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
backup American women soccer players, who will be filling in a
tournament in Australia because the front-line players _ the World
Cup heros of 1999 _ are sitting out in protest over their
contracts. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MATCHUPS (Undated) _ NFL playoff matchups: four first-round
games this weekend. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIORAMAS (New York) _ The painted backgrounds of the dioramas
at the American Museum of Natural History have a curious place in
the hearts of almost everyone who has grown up in New York City
during the last century. They are some of the most elaborate
landscape paintings in the city and some of the most frequently
viewed pictures anywhere, but almost nobody knows who did them or,
in a sense, even seems to notice them when they're staring straight
at them. Are they art? Of course. Moreover, diorama painting is a
dying art, dioramas being relics from the days when verisimilitude
was a necessary skill among painters, and artists were the ones who
provided the world with pictures from abroad. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY-DANCE (New York) _ Dance is upfront on Broadway this
season, very possibly because dance expresses what words cannot. Or
as Isadora Duncan put it, ``If I could write it, I wouldn't need to
dance it.'' More than ever, the all-dance show has virtually become
reality. From ``Swing!'' to ``Tango Argentino,'' by way of
``Fosse'' and ``Contact,'' so-called dance-driven shows are posing
a challenge to the conventional musical. Current revivals that
integrate song, dance and plot (``Kiss Me, Kate'' and ``Annie Get
Your Gun'') and their not-so-integrated new counterparts
(``Footloose'' and ``Saturday Night Fever'') also make room for
dance. Add the naturalness with which dancing weaves through the
parlor setting of ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' and the dance
aficionado can count the ways in which show business acquired new
meaning in 1999. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NH-MEETING-CANDIDATES (Dover, N.H.) _ There are many idealized
notions about American presidential politics, and they start in the
state of New Hampshire. Here, by popular conception, is where the
race for president begins, the place with the first-in-the-nation
primary, where the candidates are methodically questioned by
informed citizens whose decisions guide a nation. And here, most of
all, is the last remaining spot in the nation where a regular
citizen can shake hands and converse with someone who might very
well be the next president of the United States. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CRITICS-AWARDS (New York) _ Which turn-of-the-year movie
horse race do you follow? The one at the box office? Or the
stampede of critical 10-best lists that nudges prestigious films
toward Academy Award consideration? A year ago when ``Saving
Private Ryan'' won many critics' polls and did slam-dunk business,
it looked as if Hollywood was gearing up to steal back some of the
critical thunder that has increasingly accrued to independent
films. But this year, the tables have turned again. On Sunday
evening when the New York Film Critics Circle distributes its
annual awards, mainstream Hollywood will be given a mostly frigid
shoulder. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERSTOOD-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``If You Only Understood'':
Rolando Diaz, director; a musical documentary. In Spanish, with
subtitles. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   WHISTLE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Life Is to Whistle'': Fernando
