<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCLA-WASHINGTON-L     01-07 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WASHINGTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA FALLS TO WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Neither of UCLA's games this weekend is on TV, and
based on its performance Thursday night against Washington, the
blackout is a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of ineptitude is not meant to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   There are good losses, there are bad losses, and then there is
Washington 63, UCLA 62, in front of 9,012 at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Bruins hurt as badly as they played.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable. I can't put it into words,'' said
teary-eyed freshman Jason Kapono, whose last-second jumper was
ruled a 2-pointer, not a 3-pointer, thus sealing UCLA's defeat.
``We should have never been in that position. We should have never
been in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a game the Bruins (8-3, 0-1) seemingly had to win to
compete for the Pacific-10 title. And it was a game they should
have won given Washington's inferior talent, inferior record (6-7,
1-0) and injury-riddled roster.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, UCLA had victory within its grasp when it took a 60-56
lead with 1:20 remaining. Then, collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the stretch, once we got a four-point lead, we didn't
execute our offense and we weren't able to get stops defensively,''
Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``In a possession-by-possession
game, that's going to be the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's demise was filled with errors in judgment. First, Ray
Young committed a bad foul on Washington's Will Perkins, a mediocre
player who was attempting a difficult shot. Perkins had no trouble
with the free throws, however, which trimmed UCLA's lead to 60-58.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the game's biggest mistake. Defended closely by Senque
Carey, UCLA guard Earl Watson committed an inexcusable five-second
violation near midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he was that close,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's Deon Luton, who had a game-high 26 points and
baffled UCLA's defense all night, drained a 3-pointer from the left
corner with 39 seconds remaining to give the Huskies a 61-60 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Jerome Moiso made UCLA's next mistake _ an ill-advised
3-pointer that he attempted !ital!after hesitating for a
second.!off! He knew it was a bad shot, and he took it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 seconds left, the Bruins frantically fouled Luton, who
hit both free throws for a 63-60 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Watson raced downcourt and missed a 3-pointer. UCLA grabbed the
rebound, and it was Kapono's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to hop back to get the 3-pointer,'' said Kapono, who
led the Bruins with 19 points. ``I thought I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Referee Bill Kennedy didn't hesitate in calling Kapono's shot a
2-pointer, and Lavin did not complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a 3, I was standing right next to him,'' Watson said.
``But that's how Pepperdine felt (after a blown call in Pauley
Pavilion). What goes around comes around.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Washington played well, and that's the most
ominous sign for the Bruins. They faced a bad team on a bad night
and still couldn't get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies shot 39 percent from the field; they shot 52 percent
from the foul line; and they had no scoring threats except Luton.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins were so sloppy they couldn't take advantage. At
times, they acted like they'd never seen a zone defense before.
They committed 19 turnovers. They shot 42 percent from the field.
They shot 47 percent from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they lost in Seattle for the third consecutive
season, and Saturday's game at Washington State suddenly becomes
critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough one to take,'' Watson said in a quiet locker
room. ``This was a win we definitely needed. We're starting behind
(Stanford and Arizona).''
</P>
<P>
   After Luton's dunk gave Washington a 55-54 lead, Moiso and Dan
Gadzuric teamed up for UCLA's best play of the night. Moiso,
standing at the foul line, passed to Gadzuric, who had sealed his
man in the low post, for a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds later, Gadzuric deflected a pass, sprinted
downcourt, then found Young for a dunk. Washington closed to 58-56
on Luton's free throw, then Gadzuric gave UCLA a four-point lead
with a layup. At that point, the Bruins unraveled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
