<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9159 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-PANTHERS-LA     01-07 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-PANTHERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRIE LIFTS KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Len Barrie wasn't around the last time the Los
Angeles Kings played the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most painful game of the young season when the Kings
lost after blowing a two-goal lead in the final three minutes. But
with just one victory in the last nine games, times seem far more
desperate now.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie, who opened the season with minor-league Long Beach,
recorded the first two-goal game of his career in a 4-2 victory
Thursday over the Panthers, the runaway leaders in the NHL's
Southeast Division.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie's second goal matched his season total. It came in the
second period when the Kings fired 26 shots on Panthers goaltender
Mike Vernon, tying a club record. It also was the most ever in one
period against the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   When Jaroslav Modry added a power-play goal late in the period,
the Kings appeared to carry over the solid effort from Tuesday's
2-2 tie against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's victory opened a three-game homestand for the Kings.
It also marked the start of a three-week stretch where the Kings
will play six of seven games at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike three months ago, when the Kings got out to a solid start
that included a strong power play, the offense has been sputtering.
They ended a six-game losing streak last Thursday with an 8-2
victory over Edmonton, but in the two road games that followed, the
Kings went 0 for 7 on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers came in after a 5-1 victory Wednesday against the
Mighty Ducks and looked ready to sweep Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   With 6:06 gone in the game and Modry off for tripping, Ray
Sheppard rebounded a Robert Svehla shot past Kings goaltender
Stephane Fiset for the game's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie tied it less than three minutes later, but the Kings
already were setting a tone. The Panthers had just two shots on
Fiset in the period.
</P>
<P>
   They added only five more in the second, but that wasn't the
story. The Kings peppered Vernon at a record pace in the period.
That tied a club record set just two days apart, Oct. 12 vs. the
New York Islanders and Oct. 14 against Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Ziggy Palffy, who missed Tuesday's game in St. Louis with
continued lower back problems, had three shots, including a wrist
shot that rebounded off Vernon and was converted into a goal by
Barrie with three minutes gone in the period.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear right then that the Panthers might not come back
in this game. Even when Svehla made it a one-goal game with 8:46
left in the third period and Kings coach Andy Murray called a
timeout, it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers haven't done well in California the past two years
and it was tough to come back after playing the night before. After
getting just seven shots in the first two periods, Florida's
frustration bubbled over in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Whitney, the club's second-leading scorer with 38 points,
butted Marko Tuomainen early in the third period and drew a
five-minute major penalty and a game misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   None of that mattered to Barrie, who played two games with the
Panthers during the 1993-94 season.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of his career Barrie has floundered in the NHL
after being a prolific scorer in the minors. Previous stops in
Philadelphia, Florida and Pittsburgh netted five career goals and
talk that he couldn't play at this level.
</P>
<P>
   But when Jozef Stumpel was sidelined for five weeks after
abdominal surgery, Andy Murray had another idea.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Barrie's NHL experience came on the third line, better
know for defense than scoring. Murray thought Barrie was playing
out of position and put him on the Kings first line with Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   The results were disappointing. Until Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
