<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CSUN-NORTHERNARIZ     01-07 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-NORTHERNARIZONA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE BEATS NORTHERN ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He was deft in the final minute. But after the
game, that's when Markus Carr came up just as big.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that saying?,'' Carr asked himself. Then, in a moment,
it came to Cal State Northridge's hero of the night: ``Admit it,
learn from it, forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr admitted the CSUN men's basketball team had an off night.
He suggested a solution. And no one will forget the way he played
in the final 20 seconds of the Matadors' 69-66 victory over
Northern Arizona Thursday night at Matador Gym.
</P>
<P>
   Carr made the winning basket, a turnaround jumper from 10 feet,
with 19.4 seconds left, then blocked Ross Land's 3-point attempt
with one second left, preserving a thrilling win in front of a
season-high crowd of 1,369 in CSUN's Big Sky Conference opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markus showed a lot of poise and executed the (winning) play
perfectly,'' CSUN coach Bobby Braswell said.
</P>
<P>
   But Braswell was just as impressied with Carr's blocked shot on
Land, the Lumberjacks' best shooter. Land is 6-foot-5. Carr is 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the game, to make that play,'' Braswell said.
``He made a good play.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (9-3) has won seven of its last eight games. The Matadors
opened conference last year with a 96-79 overtime loss at NAU in
which they were outscored 21-4 in the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, CSUN went on a 9-0 run with less than eight
minutes to play in the second half, and tied NAU (6-7, 0-2) at 61
with 5:19 left. Neither team led by more than two the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between this year and last year _ we lost that
(game),'' Braswell said.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN looked well on the way to a loss after the first 10
minutes. Starting center Dan Read was already on the bench with two
fouls and the Matadors were shooting horribly (4 of 15 at one
point).
</P>
<P>
   CSUN hadn't played since a 94-86 win over Cal Poly San Luis
Obispo on Sunday, and Braswell also said a change in practice time,
from 2 p.m. to 11 a.m., may have upset the players' rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably had the worst two days of practice of the year
this week,'' Braswell said. ``(Then) we played lethargically in the
first half.''
</P>
<P>
   After a late first-half run by CSUN cut NAU's double-digit lead
to just three _ 44-41 _ at halftime, the Matadors let down again
and let the Lumberjacks build 57-47 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired play by three reserve guards _ Marco McCain, Craig
Calloway and, most notably, Carl Holmes _ helped propel CSUN to its
final charge.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes had nine points and four steals in the second half.
McCain clamped down defensively on Cory Schwab, who made all five
of his shots in the first half but was only 2 of 5 in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, our bench played well,'' Braswell said. ``Carl
and Marco were phenomenal tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN travels to Idaho State Saturday for its first Big Sky road
game, and the first game away from home for the Matadors since they
lost to Texas-El Paso on Dec. 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
