<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SHOW-LADN </SLUG>
 
SPORTY MODELS, SUVs RULE AT L.A. AUTO SHOW 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Chris Sieroty 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES-- The buzz as the 96th Greater Los Angeles Auto Show
opens Saturday, Jan. 8, is all about style.
</P>
<P>
   The styling of several new roadsters making their world or North
American debut at the auto show. The European styling of some
American and Japanese sedans making their premier appearance. And
the new, smaller sport-utility vehicles that will roll out this
spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   All told, in fact, nearly three dozen cars, trucks or SUVs will
make their debut in Los Angeles this weekend. The number of new
cars -- plus the hundreds of retooled cars also at the Convention
Center -- indicates the importance of the Southern California
market to the world's auto makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's show will give the North American Auto Show in
Detroit a run for its money,'' said George Peterson, president of
AutoPacific Inc., a Tustin-based automotive and marketing research
and product consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   ``With its climate and love for the automobile, Los Angeles is
establishing its position as one of the premier shows. It has moved
ahead of New York and Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why so many vehicles are making their world or North
American debut in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Sports cars premiering at this first major international auto
show of the new year include: the Audi TT Roadster, Acura's CL
sports coupe and the BMW Z8 roadster, featured in the recent James
Bond movie ``The World is Not Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a myriad of new SUVs on display at the Los Angeles
Convention Center, among them the Mazda Tribute and Pontiac's
five-door Aztek, the company's first-ever SUV. Daewoo also joins
the SUV market with its Korando, along with the Hyndai Santa Fe and
the Infiniti QX4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other cars, including BMW and Porsche, have sex appeal and
that draws them to the display but it's not what people want to
buy,'' Peterson said. ``People appreciate expensive automobiles but
will leave the auto show and buy a sport-utility vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the SUVs receiving the most hype at this year's auto show
is the 2001 Tribute from Mazda. After a five-year absence from the
market, Mazda hopes its new model will become the leader among
smaller SUVs with its V-6, 260-horsepower and sports sedan
handling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tribute cuts across several levels of the SUV market,''
said Richard Beattie, president and chief executive officer of
Mazda North American Operations, at a media preview held Thursday.
``With the Tribute, we've invented a whole new class of SUV,'' he
said. ``It's more functional and powerful than a mini-SUV and more
maneuverable and efficient than a truck-based, compact SUV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we have been at a disadvantage without a four-door
SUV.''
</P>
<P>
   Beattie wouldn't say what the Tribute's sticker price will be,
only that: ``I think consumers will be pleasantly surprised by its
value.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson says Mazda will find the SUV market a crowded one.
``Between now and 2005, the number of SUVs sold will double,'' he
said. Initially, the new sport-utility vehicle will be sold only in
North America.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the price scale, Porsche is introducing its
model-year 2001 911 Turbo at the L.A. show. With a 415-horsepower
twin engine and updated styling, the new 911 will take its place at
the top of the model line when it goes on sale in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 2001 911 Turbo is the next step in the evolution of this
legendary model,'' said Fred Schwab, president and chief executive
officer of Porsche Cars North American.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Carlson, spokesman for Porsche Cars North America Inc., said
Porsche decided to introduce the new 911 Turbo at the Los Angeles
Auto Show because 17 percent of all Porsches are sold in Southern
California. California also has the largest number of Porsches
registered in the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big consumer show,'' Carlson added, ``so it makes sense
to debut our top model in one of our top markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab said the 911 goes from zero to 62 miles per hour in 4.2
seconds and tops out at 189 miles per hour. He said it is the first
911 Turbo to be fitted with a liquid-cooled, rather than
air-cooled, engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Porsche, which makes it an icon, and it's a turbo,
which makes it a really fast icon,'' said Jim Hall, vice president
of AutoPacific's Detroit office. ``It's the fastest production
model Porsche has ever sold and one of the most expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The company hasn't announced its price plan for the new 911
Turbo, said Carlson. However, the sticker price should be slightly
higher than the $105,000 the German automaker charged for the 1998
model of the 911 Turbo.
</P>
<P>
   A little less expensive than a Porsche is the redesigned Saturn
SC, an updated three-door coupe for the 2001 model year. The only
three-door coupe in the world, the Saturn SC features a new
exterior along with a number of interior improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Trudell, chairwoman and president of Spring Hill,
Tenn.,-based Saturn Corp., said some of the interior changes
include an extensive update in the electronic systems, new security
features and reduced engine noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Saturn's mildly wedge-shaped body and smooth surfaces
continue to form the basis of the distinctive Saturn swoosh,''
Trudell says, ``all body panels below the beltline are new on the
2001 coupe, giving the car a fresh exterior appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said that smaller vehicles are usually part of what he
calls the ``fashion market,'' meaning they are hot sellers for 18
months and then their popularity diminishes. ``The Saturn SC has
broken that rule,'' he said. ``The new Saturn SC is really
important to the company in terms of volume. If it wasn't a
three-door sports coupe, it would fit into the category of a ho-hum
vehicle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
