<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS HE REALLY OFF HIS ROCKER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News    Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball commissioner Bud Selig Thursday ordered Atlanta Braves
pitcher John Rocker to undergo psy- chological testing. Selig may
yet dis- cipline Rocker for making idiotic re- marks about
minorities and homo- sexuals.
</P>
<P>
   This is a slippery slope. Rocker, in his recent Sports
Illustrated inter- view, managed to offend virtually ev- ery
minority group in this country, but Rocker does not make his living
on the basis of his opinions and it's not against the law to be an
ignorant pig.
</P>
<P>
   ``If saying stupid things was a crime, there would be no talk
radio,'' notes Globe radio-TV critic Howard Manly.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his home in Milwau- kee Thursday night, Selig said,
``Ob- viously, I've given this a lot of L thought. I'm sensitive
about the L ramifications and I understand the ramifications, and
I'll make my fu- ture decisions based on what I per- ceive those
ramifications to be.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, most of you have prob- ably read Rocker's stupid rant in
SI. Lowlights include: ``Imagine having to take the (No.) 7 train
to the ball-H park, looking like you're (riding L through) Beirut
next to some kid with purple hair next to some queer with AIDS
right next to some dude who just got out of jail for the fourth
time next to some 20-year-old mom with four kids. It's depressing .
. . The biggest thing I don't like about New York are the
foreigners. You can walk an entire block in Times Square and not
hear anybody speak- ing English. Asians and Koreans and Vietnamese
and Indians and Rus- sians and Spanish people and every- thing up
there. How the hell did they get in this country?''
</P>
<P>
   He also called a black teammate a ``fat monkey,'' and said,
``How bad are Asian women at driving?''
</P>
<P>
   The article appeared several L weeks ago and prompted public
out- cry and a limp apology from Rocker (who has since been ordered
to keep quiet by his agents, the Hendricks brothers). Rocker said
he was not a racist. Now he's going to have to prove to baseball
that's he's not crazy, either. Selig is a firm believer in social
responsibility and it appears he wants to punish the pitcher, but
only if Rocker is deemed mentally healthy.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare for a pro athlete _ one not under arrest _ to be
ordered to undergo psychological testing. In L 1986, the Red Sox
ordered Oil Can Boyd to be examined by a psychia- trist. Two years
later, when Wade Boggs went on television and told the world he was
addicted to sex, the Can asked, ``Who needs the psychia- trist
now?''
</P>
<P>
   There is some disagreement re- garding the Players Association's
L role in the Rocker edict. The com- missioner's release said the
order was issued ``following consultation with the Major League
Baseball L Players Association,'' but PA execu- tive Gene Orza said
the organization did not authorize the release.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night Selig said, L ``There's no question about that
(con- sultation with the Players Associ- ation) and I don't think
you'll see any more of that.''
</P>
<P>
   What now? It's one thing to L dump Wil Cordero when he beats his
wife. It's logical to dump Christian Peter when his record of
crimes against women is disclosed. An-L nouncers Jimmy the Greek
and Ben Wright lost their jobs because of comments that were deemed
racist or sexist. But Rocker is not an an- nouncer and he hasn't
committed any crime. Baseball found it difficult to dump Reds owner
Marge Schott for saying that Hitler was a swell guy.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear Rocker needs some L help. Sadly, he said things that
a lot of other people think and say in pri- vate, but few
individuals are stupid enough to go public with such trash.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have turned the case over to Major League Baseball.
At- lanta team president Stan Kasten said his first inclination was
to re- lease Rocker, but Braves executives met with the pitcher and
said he was extremely contrite. Rocker has re- portedly started
calling teammates to apologize. During his years in the minors, he
lived with at least three players who would qualify as ``for-
eigners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Players Association is also on thin ice. The PA normally
fights all fines and suspensions, but this is a case in which an
association mem- ber has offended just about everyone in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, Rocker will be shunned. He should at
least do some serious community service with the disenfranchised.
And may- be he should swallow a 100-mile-per- hour comebacker off
the bat of Sam- my Sosa (one of those ``Spanish peo- ple'').
</P>
<P>
   Kasten is the son of Nathan Kas-H ten, who was hauled out of his
native Poland in 1939 and ordered to build a concentration camp
called There-H sienstadt. He worked in the camps for six years and
carried bodies to the incinerator at Auschwitz. Of the 53 Kastens
taken to camps, Nathan Kasten was the only survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Nathan's son said this about John Rocker:
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time he goes to New York, he needs to take a trip to
the Statue of Liberty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
