NYT-01-07-00 0224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-OWNER-T     01-07 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-OWNER-TEX </SLUG>
 MAVERICKS OWNER-TO-BE KEEPS OPTIONS OPEN
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By DWAIN PRICE c.2000
Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ On paper Monday, Mark Cuban lost almost $600 million in
the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   How did he lament the loss? A few hours later he went out and
agreed to pay $280 million for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Now Cuban must take stock of a Mavericks franchise that has been
the laughingstock of the NBA for nearly a decade. And for starters,
he must determine who is going to coach this team next season.
</P>
<P>
   A list of the possible candidates likely will include Iowa's
Steve Alford, Duke's Mike Krzyzewski, Denver assistant coach John
Lucas, New York Knicks assistant coach Don Chaney, former NBA coach
Del Harris, and Isiah Thomas, who helped build the Toronto Raptors
and currently is the commissioner of the Continental Basketball
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, a graduate of Indiana University, said he's going to wait
until after the season to hire a new coach. Even though Alford,
Thomas and Krzyzewski all have IU connections, that doesn't
necessarily mean one of them will be the next Mavericks coach,
Cuban said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I've ever met Isiah is when he put a move on me
playing basketball at IU,'' Cuban said. ``And I'm still looking for
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isiah wouldn't know me if he saw me. The Raptors have a lot
better IU connections than anything I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Alford, a former Mavericks player, helped put Southwest Missouri
State on the map before moving on to Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met Steve, but I don't know him,'' Cuban said. ``It's not
even something I'd really consider at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said he also won't consider hiring another IU alumni,
Quinn Buckner, as the Mavericks coach. Buckner, a friend of
Cuban's, coached the Mavericks to a 13-69 record during the 1994-95
season.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said it's not a definite that Mavericks coach//general
manager Don Nelson will be back next season as the team's GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has to do with the conversations I have with
Nellie,'' Cuban said. ``We've got to feel each other's pulses.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no definites; there's no anything at this point
and time, because I don't know enough. I can't just walk in and
say, `OK, let's just change everything, or let's plan for next
season already,' because I haven't educated myself on enough stuff
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has two years left on his contract as the Mavericks'
general manager, with one year at the Mavericks' option.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban has already had a two-hour meeting with Nelson, and
likewise with Terdema Ussery, the Mavericks president and chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Terdema and I like Terdema; he's a great guy,'' Cuban
said. ``He's a quality guy, but I don't know anybody yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And because Cuban doesn't know anybody, he said he's not going
to make changes just for the sake of making changes.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, who has had Mavericks season tickets since 1994, said he
wants to make the game fun again for the fans. Minority owner Frank
Zaccanelli, who is trying to decide whether to sell his 3 percent
stake in the Mavericks, said he has no doubt Cuban will turn the
Mavericks into a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've seen and heard over the last three days leads
me to believe Mark is doing all of the right things,'' Zaccanelli
said. ``I know he's going to do everything in his powers to bring a
winner to Dallas, and he's going to make everyone who is a fan of
the Dallas Mavericks very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban is an owner with deep pockets, much like Portland owner
Paul Allen. He also will be a hands-on owner, much like the
Cowboys' Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess maybe from a geek perspective, yeah, I've got some
Paul Allen in me,'' Cuban said. ``From a money perspective, you can
make that comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from a Portland Trail Blazers perspective, and the way he
brought those players in, amen. If I can do the same things that he
did and bring in those type of players, I'll do it in a heartbeat.
Money is not the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Harper is also expected to have a position in the
Mavericks front office. However, Cuban said he has yet to decide
what that will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things are moving along at a turtle's pace as
everybody figures things out,'' Cuban said. ``I haven't had a
chance to talk to people to see exactly what his role is going to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Cuban is just tired of the jokes about the
Mavericks being the worst pro sports team of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 90s are gone,'' Cuban said. ``It might take a year to turn
it around, it might take two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't buy this team for the money. I did this to win.
Maybe I'll end up being a moron, and people will think I'm a fool.
But I'm going to give it everything I've got, and I'm going to
learn everything that I can.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
