<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9191 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-TULSA-TCU-TEXNO.2     01-07 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TULSA-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
 NO. 22 TULSA MAKES TCU OFFENSE DISAPPEAR (For
use by NYTimes News Service clients) By ARTHUR GARCIA c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Scoring 130 points against the likes of
North Texas and Grambling State is one thing. Playing against No.
22 Tulsa is something else.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs' scoring revival ended two games after it
started, as Tulsa came into Daniel-Meyer Coliseum and put on a
clinic at both ends of the court. The Golden Hurricane, deliberate
on offensive and tenaciously guarding the basket, humbled the
Frogs, 94-73, in the Western Athletic Conference opener for both
teams before a season-high 5,260 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricane (14-1, 1-0) players passed and passed and passed
until they found an open shot, which usually found the bottom of
the net. Brandon Kurtz, a 6-foot-10 Tulsa center, did the most
damage, dropping in nine of 11 shots for 21 points, but he wasn't
the only one knocking them down. Eric Coley was 9-of-13, David
Shelton 8-of-11 and Marcus Hill 6-of-10. As a team, Tulsa connected
on 39 of 63 (61.9 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``They have an excellent ballclub and they proved that
tonight,'' Frogs coach Billy Tubbs said. `'I'm disappointed with
the team. I didn't feel we really battled.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU (9-7, 0-1) never found the rhythm or the easy baskets that
were so plentiful in its past two outings. The Frogs, who have lost
three of their past five home games, needed an Estell Laster jumper
in the last minute of the first half to avoid their lowest-scoring
half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't prepared to run our offense the way it needs to be
run,'' said Tubbs, who has now lost four regular-season home games
for the first time at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs' full-court trap failed to produce timely turnovers,
as Tulsa's guards calmly broke the pressure. The Hurricane finished
with 20 turnovers, but had only five when the game was decided in
the first 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a team that for the most part gets off to a good
start,'' Tulsa coach Bill Self said. ``That was the case tonight,
and TCU was never able to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs fell behind 14-7 four minutes into the game as Tulsa
made six of its first seven shots. TCU got as close as 14-12, but
the visitors quickly got their advantage into double figures.
Tulsa's hot shooting eliminated the Frogs' fast break, their
offensive staple, and turned the game into TCU's Achilles' heel, a
halfcourt affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no fun when they're making shots and you're missing,''
said Laster, who topped TCU with 19 points. ``It alters tempo, and
it alters momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU did make some mini-runs at Tulsa in the first half, the last
to get the lead down to nine (35-26) on Myron Anthony's layup with
four minutes left in the half. Tulsa, however, scored the next 10,
effectively settling the outcome before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs didn't get much production from the frontcourt, with
Anthony and Marquise Gainous both falling prey to foul trouble.
Anthony looked frustrated after picking up two early charges and
wasn't the force he has been in recent games. He had a quiet 12
points and 13 rebounds _ his fifth consecutive double-double _ and
fouled out with 3:10 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs did point out that Anthony and Laster played hard, but
``we also had some no-shows.'' Tubbs also said: ``We had no signs
of guarding anybody in the paint.'' Tulsa made 20 layups.
</P>
<P>
   Gainous, the Frogs' leading scorer, was a total nonfactor,
having more fouls (four) than points (three) in 23 minutes. Bingo
Merriex, making his second consecutive start at forward, also had
just three points.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs came in on a high, running up two of the highest
scoring games in school history in the past eight days and suiting
up all 12 players for the first time this season. They left the
floor last night with a number of questions heading into Saturday's
nonconference game at Southwest Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can use this as a measuring stick on what we need to do,''
Laster said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
