<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-JAZZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEISTY MAVS CAN'T KEEP UP WITH JAZZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A scenario only the imaginative could envision unfolded
Thursday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Nelson, assistant coach and son of general manager/coach
Don Nelson, actually assumed the reins of the Mavericks under the
watchful eye of owner-to-be Mark Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the Mavericks' general manager/coach for creating the
improbable scene during Utah's 105-92 victory. The emotional,
48-minute contest included eight technical fouls, three ejections
(Don Nelson, Mavericks center Shawn Bradley and Jazz coach Jerry
Sloan) and an on-court confrontation between Don Nelson and Jazz
forward Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize he's an older fellow, but I'll tell you what,''
Malone said, ``he'd probably be overmatched with this one right
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson declined to comment on the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Malone chose otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're totally out of line to get into a player's face
like that,'' said Malone, who scored 14 of his team-high 24 points
in the third quarter. ``I think it's a fine line that you don't
cross, and I think he crossed that line. I have no respect for that
in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to apologize for, and I will not apologize to
anybody for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson went onto the court after being ejected by official
Scott Wall with 6:04 remaining in the third quarter. Nelson
objected to Malone putting a knee into the abdomen of center Shawn
Bradley while driving toward the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Malone defended his physical play by saying ``I know when a guy
is going to block my shot or when he's going to commit a hard
foul.''
</P>
<P>
   The collision forced Bradley to leave the game, but he returned
later. Nelson and Malone engaged in a verbal exchange before the
coach bumped the player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to have to jump on his back and hold him
down,'' Donnie Nelson said of his father. ``That's what he is. He's
a competitor, and he's feisty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, who trailed by only three points after three
periods, matched their coach's feistiness on the court before the
Jazz put the game away with a 34-point fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We executed,'' Sloan said. ``We kept our concentration. That's
been our biggest problem all year. We're not a very good team when
we lose our concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, who has agreed to purchase controlling interest in the
franchise for $280 million, watched the Mavericks extend their home
losing streak to six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance at the end, and we didn't come through,''
guard Erick Strickland said. ``That's the way it's been going.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Michael Finley led the Mavericks with 30 points, Dirk
Nowitzki added 24, and Cedric Ceballos scored 21. But the
injury-depleted Mavericks received only seven points from their
bench while playing with a seven-man rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just were not able to sustain it,'' Donnie Nelson said.
``The guys were dragging out there and just lost momentum toward
the end. I thought that we played hard for 45 minutes.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0311EST &QL; 
