<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-PANTHERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRIE GOOD WIN FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The game looked easy Thursday night when Len
Barrie was scoring goals and the Los Angeles Kings were taking
shots at a record pace. The important stuff happened later, when
they were challenged to fight. And maintain their focus.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' 4-2 victory over the Florida Panthers was much harder
than it appeared. It always is when a team has just one victory in
its past nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie had given the Kings the lead with his first two-goal game
of his journeyman career. The Kings tied a club record with 26
shots in the second period. But the game actually seemed to turn
when the Staples Center crowd of 14,114 shifted its attention to a
huge fight in the stands midway through the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was some yelling behind the Panthers' bench between
players and fans. Security guards were just breaking up the first
brawl when the second altercation took off.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings watched it all and then watched the Panthers, the
runaway leader in the Southeast Division, make it a one-goal game
when Robert Svehla scored midway through the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a position where we play six of our next seven at
home,'' captain Rob Blake said. ``Getting off on the right foot
means a lot. We've got a chance to get back on track and we needed
to stay strong at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   So what was Blake doing going off with a penalty after mixing it
up with Panthers' enforcer Peter Worrell with three minutes left
and the Kings leading by a goal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Worrell did what he is supposed to do, go after our best
player and try to get him out of the game,'' Kings coach Andy
Murray said. ``You don't see Peter Worrell on the ice in the final
3{ minutes in the game unless he is doing that. But we survived.
We'll see what it means down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray could breathe easier after Glen Murray added an empty-net
goal with 35 seconds remaining. But a critical stretch has just
begun. Five of their next six games are at home, but all are
against playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the Kings were playing a team that wiped out the
Mighty Ducks 5-1 the night before. They have a 13-point lead over
Carolina in their division, not to mention high-scoring Pavel Bure,
who was NHL Player of the Month for December.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't enough, the Panthers beat the Kings in the
season's opening week with perhaps the most painful game to date.
The Kings had a two-goal lead with three minutes left and lost 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie wasn't around for that one.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie tied the game in the first period and put them ahead
three minutes into the second. Entering the game, he had two goals
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie who played briefly for the Panthers during the 1993-94
season, had talked to Florida last summer, but a deal could not be
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there was little incentive when a team tells you they
don't want you,'' Barrie said. ``I'm just glad I could help out
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of his career Barrie has floundered in the NHL
after being a prolific scorer in the minors. Previous stops in
Philadelphia, Florida and Pittsburgh netted five career goals and
talk that he couldn't play at this level.
</P>
<P>
   But when Jozef Stumpel was sidelined for five weeks after
abdominal surgery, new Kings coach Andy Murray had another idea.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Barrie's NHL experience came on the third line, better
known for defense than scoring. Murray thought Barrie was playing
out of position and put him on the Kings' first line with Ziggy
Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   The results were disappointing. Until Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
