<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 03:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9195 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ELEPHANT-SEALS-SFCHRO     01-07 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELEPHANT-SEALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCIENTISTS REVEAL ELUSIVE ELEPHANT SEALS' SECRETS  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The elephant seals and sea lions that swim and
dive for food by the thousands in California's cold coastal waters
have long posed major mysteries for scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Now two groups of researchers have solved some of the puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   Using implanted radio transmitters, satellites and
microcomputers, one group has tracked dozens of the huge seals to
reveal the first details of their long migration patterns and
feeding behavior as they swim from their breeding grounds at A &LR; n &LR; o
Nuevo Island near Santa Cruz, Calif., to Alaska's icy Aleutians.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of scientists, using ultra-sensitive molecular
detective techniques, has identified a powerful nerve poison that
killed hundreds of California sea lions in spring 1998 and left
countless others with severe brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   The team that tracked the daily movements of 47 elephant seals
by satellite was led by marine biologists Burney LeBoeuf and Daniel
P. Costa at the University of California at Santa Cruz. They have
been reporting on their quest at several recent research meetings.
</P>
<P>
   In more than a year of tracking studies, the Santa Cruz team
found marked differences in the migration routes of the monster
male elephant seals and the smaller females.
</P>
<P>
   The males, some weighing more than three tons, swam directly
north offshore along the coast, where they risked deadly attacks
from voracious sharks and killer whales. And when they dived to the
ocean bottom _ sometimes as deep as 5,000 feet _ they probably
preyed largely on fish such as skates, rays, ratfish, small sharks
and hagfish, the scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   The much smaller females, by contrast, ranged across a far wider
area of the North Pacific during their annual migrations from the
A &LR; n &LR; o Nuevo rookery where they breed and nourish their young pups.
The primary food for the females appeared to be free-swimming prey
higher in the water column _ primarily squid, the Santa Cruz
researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Both males and females spend months at sea to feed and build fat
for their bodies. In general, they are at A &LR; n &LR; o Nuevo from December
to March. After that, they migrate north, return once in late
spring or summer and head north again until December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago,'' said LeBoeuf, ``we knew woefully little
about the diving and foraging behavior of marine mammals. We knew
the seals entered the sea to feed and returned at predictable
times, but we knew nothing about what they did and how they did it.
Technological advances in instrumentation, microcomputers and
satellite technology have changed all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   A very different and far more numerous species of marine mammal,
California sea lions, suffered a mysterious disaster in May and
June 1998 when more than 400 of them died and countless others
suffered severe brain disorders from a cause no one could
determine.
</P>
<P>
   The creatures, scientifically named Zlophus californianus,
suffered all the symptoms of severe brain disease _ repeated
seizures, weaving heads, muscle spasms, depression and abnormal
scratching. Seventy were treated at the Marine Mammal Center in the
Marin Headlands, but 48 died despite the best efforts of rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute led a
team of more than 25 researchers investigating the disaster, and
what they found is reported in this week's scientific journal
Nature by Christopher A. Scholin of the institute, Frances Gulland
of the Marine Mammal Center in Sausalito and colleagues at 14 other
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the disease among the sea lions was caused by
the sudden bloom of algae that produced a deadly neurotoxin called
domoic acid, capable of killing the large mammals but proving
harmless to anchovies and other small fish on which the sea lions
prey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a very tightly coupled food web to cause such
deaths,'' Scholin said in an interview Wednesday. ``You need the
particular toxin-producing algae blooming just at the right time
... _ in this case it was Pseudo-nitzchia australis _ and then you
need the plankton-eating fish to take up the toxin without harm,
and finally you need the predators coming in to eat the fish _
exactly what happened in the spring of 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   That spring was also marked by the appearance of El Ni &LR; n &LR; o, when
Monterey Bay's waters warmed to an unusual degree while freshwater
runoff from the land increased. The runoff and the warm ocean water
may have added to the problem, Scholin said, but so far a
connection between El Ni &LR; n &LR; o and the sea lion catastrophe cannot be
proven.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, some suggestive evidence from 1991, when the
warm water phenomenon also occurred and an unusual number of deaths
was reported throughout Monterey Bay among the pelicans and
cormorants that fed largely on anchovies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were also anecdotal reports of peculiar behavior among
some sea lions, and that alerted us that something was going on,
although there was precious little documentation,'' said Scholin, a
molecular biologist.
</P>
<P>
   To make the connections along the food chain this time, however,
Scholin called on the varied specialties of his colleagues to do
the most precise kind of toxicology, chemical analyses and DNA
probes to identify the algal bloom and to track the toxin levels
through varied fish and mussel species to the sea lions themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At the Marine Mammal Center, Gulland said volunteers brought
more than 200 sick and dying sea lions to the center during a
period around Memorial Day 1998. Most were starving and emaciated,
she said, because El Ni &LR; n &LR; o's warm waters had driven the fish on
which they normally feed to colder waters far from the animals'
feeding grounds close to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Analysis of their body fluids and the anchovies they had eaten
showed all the signs of poisoning by high levels of domoic acid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rapid and dramatic nature of the 1998 mortality event
suggests that even a short `pulse' of DA (domoic acid) in the food
web, lasting only days or weeks in a localized area, may be
sufficient to kill or sicken marine wildlife,'' the team's report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Web site for information on elephant seals at Ano Nuevo &LR; 
 &UR; is: www.anonuevo.org. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Web site for the Marine Mammal Center's continuing &LR; 
 &UR; research is: www.tmmc.org/science.htm. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 03:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-COLLEGES-BLACKS-SFCHR     01-07 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGES-BLACKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BLACKS NARROW THE EDUCATION GAP  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   African Americans have made striking gains in earning college
and graduate school degrees during the past decade, according to a
new report by the United Negro College Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the steady growth, they still have a long way to go
in closing the gap in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   The number of African Americans earning bachelor's degrees
increased 63 percent from 54,996 in 1987 to 89,412 in 1996,
representing a rise from 5.5 percent to 7.7 percent of all college
graduates, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   ``More progress needs to happen, but progress is happening,''
said Kimberley Edelin Freeman, executive director of the Frederick
D. Patterson Research Institute, which released the report
Thursday. The institute is the research arm of the United Negro
College Fund.
</P>
<P>
   African Americans have made even larger gains in graduate
degrees, with an 87 percent increase in master's degrees earned
from 13,144 in 1987 to 24,552 in 1996. The number of doctoral
degrees awarded to African Americans increased 54 percent during
the past decade, from 1,016 in 1987 to 1,569 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   African American women are making greater strides than their
male counterparts, with the number earning bachelor's degrees
rising 73 percent during the past decade, compared with 47 percent
for African American men. Similar strong gains by women exist at
the master's and doctoral levels.
</P>
<P>
   John Douglass, a research fellow at the University of California
at Berkeley's Center for Studies in Higher Education, said the new
figures were encouraging but that more progress is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A higher education degree is becoming more and more important
with every decade, and it is extremely important that the higher
education community continues to make efforts to increase these
rates'' among African Americans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edelin Freeman said the reasons behind the rise include an
expansion of outreach programs, increased access to financial aid
and affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their dramatic gains, African Americans continue to be
underrepresented at graduation time, receiving 7.7 percent of
bachelor's degrees although they are 14.3 percent of the
traditional college age population, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   They represent 6 percent of the master's degree recipients and
3.5 percent of the doctoral degree recipients, although they are 13
percent of the graduate school age populations.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that more attention needs to be directed toward
developing successful transition programs to increase transfer
rates from community colleges, where 45 percent of African
Americans start college work.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, educators should create programs to help minority
high school students do better on standardized admissions exams and
to ensure that they take the courses they need to earn a four-year
degree, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many students who have the ability and academic
potential for college work but who do not receive the critical
guidance to apply to college prior to their high school
graduation,'' the report says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
