<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN VISIT TO S.F. BAY AREA TOMORROW OPENS HIS CALIFORNIA 
 CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By PAMELA J. PODGER and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In his first California visit since joining the
Reform Party, conservative commentator and presidential candidate
Pat Buchanan will swoop into the Bay Area Saturday for a
fund-raising bash.
</P>
<P>
   The former Nixon White House aide will be feted at a
$150-per-person reception at 12:30 p.m. in a private home in
Pleasanton. He will remain in San Francisco over the weekend, but
is not scheduled to make any public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan will return to the Golden State on January 18 _ after
visits to Utah, Colorado and Iowa _ and is expected to give a
speech on immigration issues at the Nixon Library in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's appearances in California are expected to
energize his supporters in the Reform Party, who say his stance on
trade and economics are crucial to America's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I have noticed about Buchanan, and I've observed him
at several meetings, is that he has taken on more of the Reform
Party economic focus, and made it more central in his campaign,'' a
switch from his fiery social rhetoric, said Valli Sharpe-Geisler,
the former Reform Party chair of California.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Dattner, a leading California Reform Party activist, said
many newcomers to the party supported Buchanan in the recent
process of submitting names to an internal governing body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hopeful sign, and a very interesting opportunity
to build from the bottom up, and build something new for the
American people,'' Dattner said. ``We're going to see how it shapes
out. His statements on trade and lifting sanctions are very
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who has appeared at gun shows and galvanized the
militia with his ``Lock and Load'' campaign, is a thrice-failed GOP
candidate whose anti-abortion conservatism and anti-trade populism
could draw off votes from both the Republican and Democratic
candidates, political observers say.
</P>
<P>
   His campaigns in 1992 and 1996 hurt the Republican
front-runners, yet Buchanan failed to break out of second-tier
status.
</P>
<P>
   Now Buchanan hopes to win the Reform Party nomination and the
$12 million in federal money reserved for the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the Reform Party in late October, Buchanan denounced the
two-party system as a ``snare and delusion, a fraud upon the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   He specifically asked in early November that his name not be
included on the California ballot, with his spokesman Neil
Bernstein issuing a statement that the campaign wasn't going to
spend money on a ``beauty contest out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In his campaign for the Reform Party nomination, he is running
against potential rivals New York tycoon Donald Trump and former
1980 Independent candidate John Anderson. As of November 1, federal
campaign disclosures show Buchanan has raised about $3.88 million.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials are squabbling over where the party will hold
its August national convention. California is favored by party
founder and Buchanan-backer Ross Perot, and Minnesota is favored by
supporters of Gov. Jesse Ventura, who appears to be leaning toward
Trump and Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's task will be to woo votes from the Reform Party
followers who are disenchanted with mainstream politics. But their
wide-ranging views range from militia activists to the party's 1st
Congressional District candidate, Pam Elizondo of Laytonville in
Mendocino County, who describes herself as an ``environmental
healing advocate.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has railed against the World Trade Organization, unlike
Anderson, who dreams of a new world political order that lobbies
for global laws and universal human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Buchanan will appeal to voters who hold such divergent
views, Bernstein said, ``Pat has a number of stances that mesh with
the mainstream of the Reform Party, in fact the majority of the
Reform Party when you're dealing with the budget and trade
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   While some gun owners hold Buchanan in high esteem, he has
failed to win over others, including Rohnert Park resident Clayton
Cramer.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer, who heads the 500-member Sonoma County chapter of the
National Rifle Association, said he dislikes the ``nativist'' tone
to Buchanan's rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appeals to some gun owners,'' Cramer said. ``But his
position on gun control is about the only thing I have agreement
with him on, and he has real hostility toward free trade and fairly
irritating views on immigration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
