<HEADER>
A9263 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-MEDIOCRITY-COX     01-07 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEDIOCRITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mediocrity marks the wild-card round
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami coach Jimmy Johnson's team lost six of its past eight
games. But he prefers the Dolphins' position to that of the 19 NFL
teams that aren't playing in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've felt in a while,'' Johnson said. ``We're
in the playoffs. That's reaching one goal. It's not the ultimate
goal, but that's reaching one goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite winning only once since Nov. 21, the Dolphins (9-7) will
play Sunday in an AFC wild-card game at Seattle (9-7). The Seahawks
also used a back door into the postseason, losing five of their
past six games. Seattle is in the playoffs for the first time since
1988, ending the league's longest playoff drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited for the whole franchise and everybody to be
able to go to the playoffs,'' Seahawks running back Ricky Watters
said. ``But when you lose five of the last six, there's got to be a
bad taste in everybody's mouth. We have not been getting the job
done. I hope everybody feels the same way. If we keep playing the
way we've been playing, is it going to matter? We're going to get
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks and Dolphins aren't alone. In a postseason marked
by mediocrity, several teams will be looking to rebound from
late-season swoons. In the NFC, the Cowboys finished 8-8 after
losing three of their last five games. The Lions (8-8) lost four in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   But Seahawks linebacker Chad Brown insists that none of it
matters in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've been invited to the dance, you can take the prom
queen home,'' Brown said. ``You're in the dance. Everybody has a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not much of a chance. No team with a .500 record or
worse has ever won an NFL playoff game. And only five wild-card
teams have advanced to the Super Bowl. The 1980 Oakland Raiders and
1997 Denver Broncos were the only wild-card teams to win world
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see what happens in these
playoffs,'' Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman said. ``A lot of people
thought that we shouldn't get in and didn't deserve to get in, and
we weren't even the last team to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   The lowest NFC seed is Detroit, which plays Saturday at 10-6
Washington, where the Lions have lost 17 games in a row. Detroit
will have to do it without quarterback Charlie Batch, who won't
play because of a fractured thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, which plays Sunday at Minnesota (10-6), has lost seven
road games in a row. The Cowboys haven't won a non-divisional road
game since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Dallas carries some confidence into the postseason.
On Nov. 8, the Cowboys were beating the Vikings 17-0 in the first
half of a Monday night game. But after running back Emmitt Smith
broke his hand, and Aikman suffered a concussion, Minnesota rallied
for a 27-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game we go into, we feel like we can play well and win
games,'' Aikman said. ``We're not taking a psychology course this
week to tell ourselves that, 'We can do it, guys.' We know we can
do it. We've just got to go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
