<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9266 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-ROSTERS-COX     01-07 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROSTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Most playoff teams will make major roster changes in offseason
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a long, hard look at this year's NFL playoff teams. Chances
are their rosters won't be the same next season.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 teams competing in the march to Super Bowl XXXIV in
the Georgia Dome, all but three could undergo extensive makeovers
before the 2000 season. Only Indianapolis, with just one starter
eligible for free agency, St. Louis and Tennessee figure to have
many of the same players next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins must decide whether to bring back quarterback Dan
Marino, who is nearing the end of his Hall of Fame career.
Buffalo's veteran trio of receiver Andre Reed, defensive end Bruce
Smith and running back Thurman Thomas could be victims of the
salary cap next season. And Minnesota probably will have to cut
loose one of its top two quarterbacks _ free agent Jeff George or
former starter Randall Cunningham _ because the Vikings can't
afford both.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins could make the biggest splash in the offseason.
With one of the league's smaller payrolls this season, Washington
is projected to be $15.4 million under the salary cap next year.
The cap should increase $4.9 million to $62.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Washington also holds three first-round picks in April's draft,
including the No. 2 choice, obtained from New Orleans in last
year's Ricky Williams trade. The Redskins also own pick Nos. 12 and
24. Former Washington general manager Charley Casserly, who was
bumped into a consultant role last year by new owner Daniel Snyder,
deserves much of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charley put that team in contention this year and for years to
come,'' Colts general manager Bill Polian said. ``Not only did he
get a great quarterback (Brad Johnson) when most people were afraid
to pull the trigger, but then he leaves them with three No. 1
picks. That ain't luck. That's expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins must re-sign several key players, including running
back Stephen Davis, who led the NFC with 1,405 rushing yards and 17
touchdown runs. Fullback Larry Centers, defensive end Marco Coleman
and three starters on the offensive line _ center Corey Raymer,
guard Keith Sims and left tackle Andy Heck _ also become
unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Polian and the Colts aren't in bad shape, either. Indianapolis
is projected to be $13.82 million under the salary cap next year.
Tight end Ken Dilger is the only starter eligible for free agency,
and Indy might designate him its ``franchise player.'' A team then
would have to give the Colts two first-round picks to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, projected to be more than $5 million over the cap,
figure to endure a tumultuous offseason. Several key defensive
players _ linebacker Randall Godfrey, free safety George Teague and
defensive ends Alonzo Spellman and Kavika Pittman _ become
unrestricted free agents. Wide receiver Michael Irvin also becomes
a free agent, but he might retire because of a neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0939EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
