<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9268 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-SIERRALEONE09-COX     01-07 2314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRALEONE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A grim return to war-torn Sierra Leone
 &HT;    (Editor's note: Hap Cawood retired Dec. 31 after many years as
editorial page editor of the Dayton Daily News. His final project
was this report on his visit with a congressional delegation to the
African nation of Sierra Leone, which has been rocked by a very
uncivil civil war.)
 &HT;    (Photos are available by calling CoxNet at 404-526-5456.)
 &HT;    By Hap Cawood
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ The girl is maybe 2 years old. Her
smile sparkles against the backdrop of her more reserved
countrymen, about a hundred men and women, young and old, who stand
as willing displays of a barbarity hard to fathom. Each one has had
some limb cut off by machete.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl doesn't seem to miss her right arm, which was
slashed off a few inches below the shoulder by a rebel, probably a
teenager, one of the thousands of children kidnapped and
brainwashed to mutilate and kill.
</P>
<P>
   The girl is in the arms of a visitor, whose blue cap catches her
eye. Her left hand scoops away the hat and plops it on her head,
and the girl giggles triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   We all laugh; not long, but for a moment. Laughing was the last
thing we expected to do at the Murray Town Amputee Camp in
Freetown, Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   We turned to a grim, pregnant teenage girl, who looked straight
ahead at no one in particular. The fullness of the girl's midriff
was accented by her two arm stubs. The rebels had raped her, then
finished their work with the blade, cutting off her arms above the
elbows.
</P>
<P>
   The girl is one of thousands _ more than 10,000 by one count _
cut apart in a civil war whose killers are supplied, in part, by
the likes of Libya's Moammar Khadafy and Liberian President Charles
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   These victims are what brought me here as part of the entourage
of my congressman, U.S. Rep. Tony Hall (D-Ohio), and U.S. Rep.
Frank Wolf (R-Va.).
</P>
<P>
   I was a Peace Corps volunteer in Sierra Leone in 1962-64, during
that nation's years of early independence from Great Britain. I
knew these people as kind, loving and industrious; I never imagined
the nightmare that would eat the nation alive.
</P>
<P>
   If you could see face-to-face the darkness of human madness
wrought on these people, your heart would ache into your sleep.
</P>
<P>
   If you could see the courage with which the innocent people of
this country endure the nightmare wrought by countrymen who have
failed and betrayed them, if you could see the determination with
which Sierra Leoneans and others struggle to heal and restore, you
could not help but measure your life against theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The victims
</P>
<P>
   If luxury and leisure are your pleasure, forget going where
Congressmen Hall and Wolf go. A few times a year, they rumble
around ditch-deep ruts to places where suffering commands their
attention.
</P>
<P>
   On this three-day trip in early December they would meet
mutilated and starving victims, angry and hopeless citizens,
powerful and powerless lawmakers, and an architect of the killing
who blithely denied everything.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Lynch, Anglican bishop of the diocese of Freetown, gave
us a taste of what he had experienced during the rebels' January
assault on Freetown. The child-soldier rebels, conscripted,
kidnapped, brainwashed, given weapons to assuage any sense of
powerlessness, were further wired for savagery by wads of cocaine
stuffed beneath skin flaps cut on their foreheads and patched over
with a bandage.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch told us how rebels came to his house, where some of his
congregation had sought refuge. After one of them put an automatic
rifle to Lynch's head to restrain him as the rebels carted off
three boys (two were executed), the fear-shaken Lynch went upstairs
to pray.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling a spiritual wave of guidance and confidence that still
amazes him, and against the advice of his dumbfounded staff, Lynch
went down the hill to the rebels' headquarters, which was
rollicking with loud music, girls and drugs. He asked the startled
guards to take him to their commander. Lynch said he told the
commander that the people of his church were nonviolent and
innocent. The commander ordered his charges not to bother the
rectory. The bishop's refuge withstood the devastation all around.
</P>
<P>
   Others were less fortunate. In the hallway of the tiny Holy Mary
Clinic, run by a young Sierra Leon his Italian wife and
subsidized by friends, sat girls holding their babies. Some of the
mothers were maybe 13 or 14. Many had been among the 3,000 swept up
and kidnapped in the January attack. Girls over 12 had been used as
sex slaves. The boys had been used as spies, soldiers and
scavengers.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred abducted girls had returned to the community served
by the clinic. Now many were giving birth. Traumatized, they were
lucky by comparison: Some girls who bore their babies while on the
run with rebels escaping the ECOMOG forces had to see their babies
buried alive.
</P>
<P>
   At the next stop, the National Workshop Displaced Persons Camp,
a bubbling mass of scantily clad little children sang songs of
welcome and peace. Here the extremes of suffering and compassion
roiled in yet another setting.
</P>
<P>
   On the concrete floor of one warehouse-sized building, hundreds
of people sleep. They are fed in lines, given water through
makeshift outdoor pumps, accommodated by latrines a few minutes'
walk away. In another tentlike, dirt-floor building made of plastic
sheets, children are taught. Classes are held in different corners
_ with simple benches, a table for the teacher and a little
blackboard.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the pressing conditions, one must ask: What if this
camp were not here? What would happen to the hundreds of thousands
of people without food, water, health care, schools, vocational
training, safety, a place to sleep?
</P>
<P>
   This camp was built and run thanks to the International Rescue
Committee, an American nonsectarian volunteer agency serving
refugees worldwide in calamitous circumstances. About five other
American-aided agencies also helped.
</P>
<P>
   In Sierra Leone, the United Nations provides and coordinates a
lifesaving network of aid from Europe and elsewhere. Governmental
and nongovernmental agencies help rehabilitate child soldiers.
American agencies provide disaster relief and help for rape
victims. UNICEF rescues children. CARE delivers food _ the list
goes on and on, a countervailing force against the more visible and
dramatic evils of the world and calamities of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hall tried to broker compromises so his congressional
colleagues would approve U.S. payment of its U.N. dues. This is
why. He has seen the mammoth and difficult lifesaving work at the
end of the line, in places like this.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful yet powerless
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, led by a truckload of red-beret Nigerian peacekeeping
soldiers, the ambassador's bulletproof car ascended the hill
overlooking the bay of Freetown. We entered the residential
compound of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. Four of us followed Hall
and Wolf into a handsomely appointed parlor, then through smaller
rooms and a metal detector into President Kabbah's office.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, sturdy and easy in his manner, Kabbah greeted the group
with a soft voice. A retired U.N. diplomat, he had been elected
president, had been overthrown by a junta, then was brought back
after Nigerian soldiers from ECOMOG, or Economic Community of West
African States Monitoring Group, overthrew the junta and put Kabbah
back in place. He is, in short, Sierra Leone's hope.
</P>
<P>
   After welcoming remarks, Kabbah invited comments. As is the
norm, Hall talked and acted with a president or ambassador the same
as he would with a constituent in Dayton: straightforwardly,
simply, politely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago I brought a Dayton delegation of 20 people to
Sierra Leone seeking a special relationship,'' Hall said without
raising his voice. ``The delegation included people from the
university, businesses and nonprofits. We weren't just interested
in a visit. The people of Dayton wanted to help make a difference.
When I went back, I helped Sierra Leone get a World Bank loan and
food and medicine. We were received nicely here, but when we tried
to do things, corruption got in the way. And this was before all
the fighting. Frankly, I got so disgusted with Sierra Leone that I
washed my hands of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to appeal to you to change that position,'' Kabbah
said, offering thanks for the assistance. Kabbah agreed
emphatically, saying how ashamed he was at how corruption had
crippled the country before anarchy took it down for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   Hall asked Kabbah what help he needed. Kabbah told him.
</P>
<P>
   Winding down the hill from the president's compound, we headed
for the worn Parliament building. Seated at the edge of the head
table facing a cavernous committee room, Hall laid out his power
card.
</P>
<P>
   He described the ``conflict diamonds'' bill he and Wolf are
pushing. The bill would require the origin of diamonds to be
certified. It would ban the U.S. import and sale of diamonds from
Sierra Leone, Liberia, Angola and the Congo, where diamonds
proceeds are used by rebels to commit mayhem. The ban would stick
until the governments got control of their diamonds and declared
them _ by listing them and paying government royalties on them _ so
that income could be used to support schools, hospitals, roads,
services for the people. Some parliamentarians applauded. Others
sounded skeptical, questioning whether this approach could work.
Doubts had been raised in the United States when Hall announced the
measure, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a perfect bill,'' Hall replied. ``It's not a perfect
solution. But it has the attention of diamond miners and dealers.''
Hall then told them he had gone to the headquarters of the world's
largest legitimate diamond dealer, De Beers Corp., and De Beers
pledged not to buy undeclared diamonds from Sierra Leone or the
other conflict countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the hurt, the sickness, the killings,'' Hall said in
his closing comments to the mining ministry officials. ``I am sick
of it, and I know you are sick of it yourself. You had minerals and
didn't declare them. With its resources, this country has the
ability to be one of the richest in the world, yet it has made
itself one of the poorest. I hope that I can help. Please let me do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the members of parliament or the Ministry of Mineral
Resources saw Hall and Wolf's offer as naive and presumptuous or as
a hopeful tool for reform, I don't know. President Kabbah saw the
leverage it offered and said he supported it. One of Kabbah's
requests to Hall and Wolf was that they exert what pressure they
can to help the Commission for the Management of Strategic
Resources succeed. Success means getting control of the diamonds
that are smuggled through Liberia.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after hearing that conversation with Kabbah, I was back
in Dayton reading an international wire report. It detailed the
Dec. 15, 1999, letter by Wolf and Hall asking U.S. Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke to push U.N. sanctions on any diamond mined in
Sierra Leone that is not certified by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel leaders
</P>
<P>
   The two main rebel leaders who had been brought into the
government as part of the truce were invited to meet Hall and Wolf
at different times at the ambassador's residence.
</P>
<P>
   The youngish Johnny Paul Koroma, the former army major who
headed the coup that overthrew President Kabbah in May 1997, didn't
look like a rebel. Sitting in a small circle of chairs in the
hallway of the ambassador's residence, Koroma was smooth. Pressed
about the atrocities, he said research and history would prove that
the barbarity had been committed by the Revolutionary United Front,
headed by Foday Sankoh. It just so happened that, in the coup,
Koroma had joined up with Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Wolf pressed Koroma on how quickly and thoroughly he
would get his troops to disarm. Koroma said his soldiers were
coming in from the bush as we spoke. The congressmen said they
would look for the results of that.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Koroma, Sankoh _ whose RUF deliberately maimed civilians
to instill fear and frustrate elections _ didn't accept the
Hall-Wolf invitation to meet at the ambassador's residence at the
time given.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh had gotten a similar invitation from Secretary of State
Madeline Albright when she visited Sierra Leone in October,
offering $55 million in U.S. support for efforts to uphold the
shaky peace pact. Sankoh had agreed to meet her _ if she came to
his headquarters. She went.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh sent U.S. Ambassador Joseph Melrose Jr. the same response
to the Hall-Wolf invitation: Sankoh would meet with them if they
came to his headquarters. Hall told the ambassador, ``No. I'm not
here to play games. He knows my schedule. He knows where to find
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, as Hall and Wolf headed for the door to leave,
someone knocked. It was Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's chief of staff, Rick Carne, and others at the meeting
summarized it for me.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, leaning forward, aggressive in manner, eyes alert,
uneducated but street-wise, denied everything. When Hall and Wolf
asked about the atrocities, Sankoh said it was all a fabrication of
a propaganda machine. When pressed about the kidnappings, the use
of young girls as sex slaves, Sankoh said no rebel would do that,
that this would hurt the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh said he wanted peace. In essence, the parting words of
Hall and Wolf were: We'll see; prove it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dangerous and desolate thing to fabricate one world and
kill in another. But people like Sankoh are not the only such force
in the world. In this truth, and in the power of the spirit that
unites and uplifts mankind, Hall and Wolf are absolutely confident
and, if so called, will go to the ends of the earth in its service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 0951EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SIERRALEONE09-COX     01-07 2314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRALEONE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
