food and medicine. We were received nicely here, but when we tried
to do things, corruption got in the way. And this was before all
the fighting. Frankly, I got so disgusted with Sierra Leone that I
washed my hands of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to appeal to you to change that position,'' Kabbah
said, offering thanks for the assistance. Kabbah agreed
emphatically, saying how ashamed he was at how corruption had
crippled the country before anarchy took it down for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   Hall asked Kabbah what help he needed. Kabbah told him.
</P>
<P>
   Winding down the hill from the president's compound, we headed
for the worn Parliament building. Seated at the edge of the head
table facing a cavernous committee room, Hall laid out his power
card.
</P>
<P>
   He described the ``conflict diamonds'' bill he and Wolf are
pushing. The bill would require the origin of diamonds to be
certified. It would ban the U.S. import and sale of diamonds from
Sierra Leone, Liberia, Angola and the Congo, where diamonds
proceeds are used by rebels to commit mayhem. The ban would stick
until the governments got control of their diamonds and declared
them _ by listing them and paying government royalties on them _ so
that income could be used to support schools, hospitals, roads,
services for the people. Some parliamentarians applauded. Others
sounded skeptical, questioning whether this approach could work.
Doubts had been raised in the United States when Hall announced the
measure, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a perfect bill,'' Hall replied. ``It's not a perfect
solution. But it has the attention of diamond miners and dealers.''
Hall then told them he had gone to the headquarters of the world's
largest legitimate diamond dealer, De Beers Corp., and De Beers
pledged not to buy undeclared diamonds from Sierra Leone or the
other conflict countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the hurt, the sickness, the killings,'' Hall said in
his closing comments to the mining ministry officials. ``I am sick
of it, and I know you are sick of it yourself. You had minerals and
didn't declare them. With its resources, this country has the
ability to be one of the richest in the world, yet it has made
itself one of the poorest. I hope that I can help. Please let me do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the members of parliament or the Ministry of Mineral
Resources saw Hall and Wolf's offer as naive and presumptuous or as
a hopeful tool for reform, I don't know. President Kabbah saw the
leverage it offered and said he supported it. One of Kabbah's
requests to Hall and Wolf was that they exert what pressure they
can to help the Commission for the Management of Strategic
Resources succeed. Success means getting control ofamonds
that are smugglugh Liberia.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after hearing that conversation with Kabbah, I was back
in Dayton reading an international wire report. It detailed the
Dec. 15, 1999, letter by Wolf and Hall asking U.S. Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke to push U.N. sanctions on any diamond mined in
Sierra Leone that is not certified by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel leaders
</P>
<P>
   The two main rebel leaders who had been brought into the
government as part of the truce were invited to meet Hall and Wolf
at different times at the ambassador's residence.
</P>
<P>
   The youngish Johnny Paul Koroma, the former army major who
headed the coup that overthrew President Kabbah in May 1997, didn't
look like a rebel. Sitting in a small circle of chairs in the
hallway of the ambassador's residence, Koroma was smooth. Pressed
about the atrocities, he said research and history would prove that
the barbarity had been committed by the Revolutionary United Front,
headed by Foday Sankoh. It just so happened that, in the coup,
Koroma had joined up with Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Wolf pressed Koroma on how quickly and thoroughly he
would get his troops to disarm. Koroma said his soldiers were
coming in from the bush as we spoke. The congressmen said they
would look for the results of that.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Koroma, Sankoh _ whose RUF deliberately maimed civilians
to instill fear and frustrate elections _ didn't accept the
Hall-Wolf invitation to meet at the ambassador's residence at the
time given.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh had gotten a similar invitation from Secretary of State
Madeline Albright when she visited Sierra Leone in October,
offering $55 million in U.S. support for efforts to uphold the
shaky peace pact. Sankoh had agreed to meet her _ if she came to
his headquarters. She went.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh sent U.S. Ambassador Joseph Melrose Jr. the same response
to the Hall-Wolf invitation: Sankoh would meet with them if they
came to his headquarters. Hall told the ambassador, ``No. I'm not
here to play games. He knows my schedule. He knows where to find
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, as Hall and Wolf headed for the door to leave,
someone knocked. It was Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's chief of staff, Rick Carne, and others at the meeting
summarized it for me.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, leaning forward, aggressive in manner, eyes alert,
uneducated but street-wise, denied everything. When Hall and Wolf
asked about the atrocities, Sankoh said it was all a fabrication of
a propaganda machine. When pressed about the kidnappings, the use
of young girls as sex slaves, Sankoh said no rebel would do that,
that this would hurt the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh said he wanted peace. In essence, the parting words of
Hall and Wolf were: We'll see; prove it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dangerous and desolate thing to fabricate one world and
kill in another. But people like Sankoh are not the only such force
in the world. In this truth, and in the power of the spirit that
unites and uplifts mankind, Hall and Wolf are absolutely confident
and, if so called, will go to the ends of the earth in its service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
