<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD08-COX     01-07 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trying to get a grip on hammer of the future
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is only fitting that we venture into the new
century with what is presumably the world's first left-handed
hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Beside me as I write is a thing called the RIDGID RoboHammer.
RIDGID, the tool purveyor wedded to Home Depot, called it ``the
world's most ergonomically designed hammer.''
</P>
<P>
   It has to be noted that in fine woodworking there is little use
for a hammer. Mallets, rubber or composite deadblow hammers, yes,
but nails, the common target of a hammer, are not among our
preferred fasteners.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a hammer is one of the most basic tools in every
household, and since the folks at Home Depot sent me this thing, I
shall attempt to tell you about it.
</P>
<P>
   RoboHammer certainly looks like the hammer of the future,
although there is nothing Robo about it. You still have to grasp
the handle, lift it and strike manfully with it in order to achieve
any result.
</P>
<P>
   The shaft and the head are more or less one piece of steel. I
say more or less because the head is split and dovetailed for half
its thickness just in front of the shaft. This, presumably,
provides the ``shock-absorbing technology that minimizes recoil and
focuses more energy at impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The shaft is cranked, or bent, twice, putting the striking
surface a bit farther ahead of the handle than on my trusty old
all-steel True-Temper. The lower two-thirds of the shaft is covered
with material that provides a secure grip.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the shaft of the right-handed version, right
where you grip it, a large swelling appears on the left edge of the
back, with a corresponding concavity to its right. For lefties,
this arrangement is reversed.
</P>
<P>
   This arrangement is supposed to make gripping the hammer more
comfortable, although I find it no mfortable than a
traditional hammer.
</P>
<P>
   The RoboHammer is fairly heavy at 30 ounces. Its claw
arrangement seems perfectly standard to me. As with all things new,
a really good test of this hammer would require a lot of use,
because old habits and old comforts are hard to break. I can't just
pick the RoboHammer up and start whacking a nail like I can with my
old hammer because I need to fuss with my grip to get hold of it.
The leaden feel when it hits a nail doesn't make me happy, either.
</P>
<P>
   But then I'm nothing if not a dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   The RoboHammer, at ``under $30'' in either left or right hand
models, may be the wave of the future. Who knows _ the left-handed
monkey wrench may not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
