   These columns for release Saturday, January 8 and Sunday,
January 9, 2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ I'm essentially a mid-20th
century Southerner, spoiled by things like the old downtown Rich's
department store, where the customer was always right, where
salespersons communicated from behind a counter rather than reading
a spiel into a telephone, where reason rated above fine print and
when you called on a telephone, you actually got a human being.
Those are some of the things I think I will miss most as we
progress into the new millennium. (Jim Minter is a former editor of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Voter turnout even in presidential elections has
been dwindling for 20-plus years, and now polls find that although
the presidential primaries are all but upon us, a uniquely large
number of potential electors aren't paying the slightest attention.
The prospect thus reappears of another president elected by less
than half the electorate or even, if the Reform Party gets up a
plausible campaign, of a president chosen by only a plurality of a
minority, a la Bill Clinton. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent
for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Coca-Cola announced that the bottoms of their
new bottles will carry the names of 12 U.S. cities. This is a
return to the days when Coke's embossed city-named bottoms were the
source of playful workplace gambling, much as is the football pool
today. Office staffs can start gearing up. (Howard Kleinberg is a
columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ The recent flap over making firms
responsible for the safety and health of their at-home workers
spotlights how muddled the so-called ``work and family'' issues
have become at the turn of the new century. (Andy Glass is a
columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED
THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRALEONE _ FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ When her baby is born,
the teenage girl won't be able to hold it. That's because after the
rebels raped and impregnated her, they hacked off her arms at the
elbow with a machete. If you could see face to face the darkness of
human madness wrought on these people, your heart would ache into
your sleep. I was a Peace Corps volunteer in Sierra Leone from
1962-64, during that nation's heady years of early independence
from Great Britain. I knew these people as kind, loving and
industrious; I never imagined the nightmare that would eat the
nation alive. Nor did I ever expect to return there, especially
after the last decade of coups and fighting. But life has its pulls
and patterns. (Cawood, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: MOVEUNDAY in both (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.)
