<P>
   RELIGION-FEET _ ATLANTA _ At Central United Presbyterian Church
in Atlanta they wash feet. It's a program with spiritual links to
Christianity and physical ties to the church's homeless shelter.
Every Wednesday _ from November through March _ volunteers cleanse
and minister to the feet of homeless men. A look at the program and
its benefits. (Henry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
30.
</P>
<P>
   MLK-SUMMIT _ ATLANTA _ Hands on Atlanta hosts its 7th annual
Martin Luther King, Jr., Service Summit. The two-day event, Jan.
16-17, consists of a day of workshops and forums examining issues
regarding the life and work of Dr. King, followed by a day of
service in the greater Atlanta community. We talk to volunteers who
have participated in the summit, will be doing so again this year,
and what it means to them. (Henry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
20.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-GAYS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ As a gay man, it is no surprise
that the Rev. Mike Castle supported a recent failed effort to
extend the Dayton's anti-discrimination ordinance to include
homosexuals and poor people. Last Sunday(1/2), he invited the
author of that proposal, City Commissioner Mary Wiseman, to speak
to his congregation at Cross Creek Community Church. The
congregation, about half of whom are gay, gave Wiseman a warm
welcome. ``Jesus showed up at city hall, and all hell broke
loose!'' proclaimed Castle. Those who successfully opposed the
amendment would agree that, indeed, Jesus showed up at city hall.
But he was on their side. (Dayton Daily News). 27. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
