<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COPS-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ City police said they will ban
bullhorns among the thousands of demonstrators expected to come to
protest during the trial of four white police officers accused of
murdering a West African immigrant in the Bronx. Police are
revealing few details about the security plans, except to say they
expect up to 1,000 protesters a day. By MELISSA GRACE.
</P>
<P>
   STROKE-CELLS (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ Four days before
Christmas, occupational therapist Tara Van Buren gave stroke
patient Maribeth Cook the same command she had given numerous times
since Cook's experimental fetal pig brain cell transplant on Sept.
1. ``Open your left hand.'' The response of Cook, 39, to that
command had not changed since her stroke in 1994. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-NY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Republican presidential hopeful John
McCain has failed to qualify for the primary ballot in all of New
York's election districts and blamed the setback on his party
leadership's unilateral backing of GOP front-runner George W. Bush.
Barring a miraculous write-in campaign, McCain has therefore
already
</P>
<P>
   lost a third of the GOP delegates New York will send to the
Republican
</P>
<P>
   National Convention in August. By LARA JAKES
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWEST-AIRLINES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Three months after Southwest
Airlines began flying out of Bradley International Airport in
Hartford, passenger traffic has soared 30 percent and fares on
other airlines have dropped by as much as 75 percent. Now officials
at Albany International Airport hope to duplicate that success when
the airline begins service in early May. By KERI P. MATTOX.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   iMAC-MAN (San Francisco) _ When the designers of the Apple
Macintosh were hunting for that perfect color _ those lollipop
shades that highlight the translucent skins of the popular iMac
line _ they would drive to a small, fume-filled shop in an
industrial section of San Francisco. There, they would tap the
creativity of Bob Flores, a former auto body shop manager whose eye
for color is fueling a revolution in the consumer computer market.
By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MAGNOLIA (Undated) _ ``Magnolia,'' writer-director
Paul Thomas Anderson's follow-up to ``Boogie Nights,'' is as
maddening as it is impressive, a failure of such insanely grand
ambitions that it still comes closer to pure art (and giddy
revelation) than movies with more modest goals. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MALCOLM (Undated) _ Memo to Fox: Don't screw up ``Malcolm in
the Middle.'' This sitcom is too good. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (`s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-PHIL-JACKSON (Los Angeles) _ Before Phil Jackson ever
coached M.J., he taught Frankie J. Before Jackson worked in the
state-of-the art Staples Center in Los Angeles, he froze in the
drafty Washington Avenue Armory in Albany, N.Y. And before he
became the intellectual leader of the six-time NBA champion Chicago
Bulls, Jackson tasted a title with the 1984 Albany Patroons, who
reigned atop the Continental Basketball Association. Jackson said
he still harbors a special place in his heart for that CBA title,
which helped convince him that he made the right career choice. By
MARK SINGELAIS.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (`f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WATER-FILTERS (Undated) _ If you've been investing in bottled
water, you may be able to cut back on expenses by using a water
filter to make your water taste mountain fresh. Water filters can
be costly to install in your home and not an option if you rent an
apartment. But water filtration pitchers, such as those by Brita or
Pur, improve the
</P>
<P>
   taste and quality of household tap water. By FRANCES INGRAHAM
HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-COUNTERS (Undated) _ Today's kitchen reflects growth,
sociability, individuality and entertainment. So many new features
and functions call for various counter heights. Multi-level, solid
surface counter tops and islands provide the necessary heights to
accommodate various functions and family members. BY FRANCES
INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For the first time in about 40
years, the magic of television was again alive on the day of New
Year's Eve as I watched as much as I could of the 25-hour
``Millennium 2000`` on the Public Broadcasting System. The PBS
celebration repeatedly drove home the fact that television has
indeed made planet Earth a global village. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ New York Gov. George Pataki's
political hero, Teddy Roosevelt, was nothing if not a realist.
``The most successful politician,'' TR once said, ``is he who says
what
</P>
<P>
   everybody is thinking most often and in the loudest voice.''
That remark crossed my mind the other day as I heard Pataki, in his
latest State of the State address, pledge once more to cut taxes _
especially on business and especially upstate, where job creation
lags behind both the rest of the Empire State and the nation as a
whole. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
