</P>
<P>
   Putin will benefit from his incumbency, positive coverage on
Russia's state-controlled media and the financial backing of a
corps of business tycoons _ the so-called ``oligarchs'' _ that
aided Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Putin's much publicized firing last week of Yeltsin's
daughter, Tatyana Dyachenko, from the Kremlin staff, and the
re-assigning of other top aides, the changes were more cosmetic
than substantial, many Russia analysts believe. It served to
distance Putin from the unpopular and scandal-tainted crowd who
steered Yeltsin's presidency. But the Kremlin inner-circle
``created Putin from zero'' and he will need them to win the
election, noted Andrei Piontkovsky, director of the Center for
Strategic Studies in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Yavlinsky last week sounded like a man fully expecting to lose.
``Right now, it isn't serious to speak about anybody other than
Putin winning the election,'' Yavlinsky told a radio interviewer.
``But if we ever want to change things for the better in our
country, if we want to preserve openness and democracy, other
people also must run in the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is an unpredictable place. Over the next 11 weeks of the
campaign, Putin could fall as fast as he rose to prominence.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems unlikely. Putin and the Kremlin have fashioned a
winning combination of power, patriotism and the political
organization Yeltsin relied upon to win reelection in 1996 and
retain his office during the depths of unpopularity.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Putin offers something Russians have been yearning for:
a leader whom they can feel good about, and an articulated policy
that promises no great highs and risks no new lows. That may be the
kind of breather Russia's shaky democracy needs to survive in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers correspondent Charles W. Holmes recently
returned to Washington, D.C. from Moscow after covering Russia and
the former Soviet Union from 1997 to 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
