<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-MAGNOLIA-     01-07 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MAGNOLIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A BIG PICTURE IS BURIED SOMEWHERE IN LENGTHY `MAGNOLIA' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's in the humble opinion of this narrator that strange
things happen all the time,'' intones the stentorian male
voice-over to ``Magnolia,'' and if ``strange things'' include
three-hour movies with wacko Biblical climaxes, he's right. There
are stranger films, and there are better ones, but few take
strangeness to such tragic depths. And few involve airborne frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia'' is writer-director Paul Thomas Anderson's follow-up
to ``Boogie Nights,'' that breathless merry-go-round masquerading
as a movie about the porn industry. It's only his third feature _
his first was ``Hard Eight,'' a simple, gripping tale of gamblers _
and Anderson's gifts are already so well-formed that he's managed
to develop a few bad habits.
</P>
<P>
   One is the urge to stuff everything he thinks and feels, every
last Faulknerian twitch, into a single strand of celluloid. Among
other things, the film offers discourses on life, death, childhood,
parenthood, cancer, suicide, love, hate, infatuation, addiction,
celebrity, obscurity, intelligence, stupidity, prophecy, destiny,
Exodus, coincidence, regret and the past.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is fascinating, bits of it are flecked with genius
and some of it actually coheres. Much does not.
</P>
<P>
   The result is as maddening as it is impressive, a failure of
such insanely grand ambitions that it still comes closer to pure
art (and giddy revelation) than movies with more modest goals.
</P>
<P>
   It's a virtual hit parade of tragic characters. Not content to
focus on one or two protagonists, ``Magnolia'' gives us a young
woman (Melora Walters) addicted to coke; her lonely swain, an
earnest cop (John C. Reilly); her estranged father (Philip Baker
Hall), an iconic quiz-show host who's dying of cancer; a wan little
boy (Jeremy Blackman) who's an ace contestant on the icon's show; a
pathetic, lonely, has-been ``quiz kid'' from an earlier era
(William H. Macy); a snarly old man (Jason Robards), also dying of
cancer; his kind nurse (Philip Seymour Hoffman), desperate wife
(Julianne Moore) and estranged son (Tom Cruise). The latter is a
sleazeball sex guru who pitches a course for wannabe Don Juans
called ``Seduce and Destroy.''
</P>
<P>
   The film leap-frogs from storyline to storyline, finding points
of junction and threads of shared fate that unite at the end in a
loose knot. The many-petaled flower of the title refers to Magnolia
Boulevard in California's San Fernando Valley, where all of the
action takes place, and to the multifold fortunes of life. But in
cramming so many plots into one film, Anderson sacrifices meaning
he sacrifices the potency, intimacy and cohesion of a single human
tale. He uses too many bells and whistles. On too many occasions
his own, ripe virtuosity stands in the way of storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes are short (they're really mini-scenes, or scenelets),
the camerawork is splashy (lots of zoomy close-ups), the editing is
sharp and the acting is simply extraordinary _ particularly Cruise,
in a tour-de-force of inspired narcissism, and Robards as his
regret-plagued father.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments of undeniable brilliance. A sequence set to
Aimee Mann's ``Wise Up'' (one of nine Mann songs on the soundtrack)
is both hilarious and profoundly heartbreaking. As for the frogs _
you've heard of deus ex machina? Try Ranidae ex machina. Frogs from
a machine.
</P>
<P>
   Watching ``Magnolia'' is a bit like pressing your nose against
one of those ``Magic Eye'' pictures in the Sunday funnies: You keep
waiting for the big picture to pop out of the maelstrom. Somewhere
in the midst of this extraordinary, infuriating, indulgent
mishy-mash of a movie there may indeed be a big picture, but it
would take more than one sitting to find it. And your eyes might
cross in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
