<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9360 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-IMAC-MAN-HNS &LR;      01-07 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMAC-MAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     A FIGURE BEHIND iMAC's SUCCESS DEALS IN TINTS AND HUES  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT BEER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the designers of the Apple Macintosh were
hunting for that perfect color _ those lollipop shades that
highlight the translucent skins of the popular iMac line _ they
would drive to a small, fume-filled shop in an industrial section
of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   There, these hotshots of a new era of industrial design sought
the expertise of a former supermarket bagger and auto body shop
manager whose eye for color is fueling a revolution in the consumer
computer market.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Flores, Apple's color guru and the owner of R. Flores Color
Design, is an unlikely industrial design icon.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't take himself seriously, for one thing. His belly
shakes when he laughs, which is often. He corrals his long ponytail
with a rubber band to keep it from dipping into an array of paints,
tints and other chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, 35, is modest about his role in the growing trend of
converting the beige utilitarian computers of yesteryear into
vibrant, user-friendly fashion statements.
</P>
<P>
   Since its debut in 1998, the iMac and its bright cousins have
been topping the bestseller lists, based in part on their bright
cases. Other computer manufacturers, including Compaq and Gateway,
are now trying to play catch-up with their own high-style boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just do what I do,`` Flores said of his role in this design
movement. ``I love color, and I love bringing color alive in
products.``
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, designers with Cupertino-based Apple Computer
Inc. will stop by Flores' paint shop seeking his advice and his
color mixes.
</P>
<P>
   The process of how these colors are eventually melded into the
Apple product line is a zealously guarded secret.
</P>
<P>
   But Flores does hint at how he works with other designers to
arrive at just the right color. One industrial designer asked him
to see whether he could match the color of an early morning sun
hitting an office window.
</P>
<P>
   However it happens, the end result is apparently pleasing to
Apple's designers, who credit Flores with helping to make the new
Mac line a success.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Howaarth, one Mac designer, scribbled ``You're a bloody
genius`` on a product picture hanging on Flores' wall. Apple
executives, notoriously closed-mouthed about the company's
manufacturing processes, declined to comment about Flores' role in
their business.
</P>
<P>
   It is an unlikely success story for Flores, who would not
disclose how much he has been paid by Apple.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a keypunch operator, he remembers that he always
played with color, painting pictures of nude women on cigarette
lighters and customizing plastic models with wild hues.
</P>
<P>
   His lifelong love affair with color began during the summer of
1980.
</P>
<P>
   During his shift as a supermakert bagger, he spotted a candy
apple burgundy Camaro as a low-rider pulled into the parking lot.
The driver was a regular customer who owned a car paint shop. After
serving an unpaid apprenticeship and then graduating from a trade
school, Flores managed a body shop in San Francisco. But arguments
over insurance coverage and other administrative chores drove him
to start his own paint shop.
</P>
<P>
   His first solo work was designing and painting business signage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a Apple color consultant was referred to him to figure
out how to perfect the metallic sheen of the 20th anniversary
Macintosh, a futuristic machine with a then-unusual flat panel
display.
</P>
<P>
   According to Flores, Apple designers found his take on color
refreshing and unpretentious, and they began working with Flores
directly.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Apple co-founder Steve Jobs to the company in 1997
brought the iMac into being, and Flores' career as a premier
industrial colorist began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colors are a driving force in consumer choice, there's no
doubt about it,`` said Chris Smith, a San Francisco industrial
designer and Web consultant. ``Apple has staked their brand on
their industrial design, and the colors are a major part of that.``
</P>
<P>
   For Flores, color is everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really see the completed computers,`` Flores said.
``I'm too busy mixing for the next project.``
</P>
</TEXT>
