<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9361 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-07 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE WORLD THROUGH THE MAGIC OF PBS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the early 1950s, when television and I were
but kids, there was a popular phrase that had not yet become a
clichi or a joke. Usually it preceded a live broadcast from some
celebrity's living room _ Edward R. Murrow's ``Person to Person`` _
or from what was then considered an exotic locale _ like Miami
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase explained how it was possible to bring millions of
people into Grace Kelly's home or onto the sand in front of the
Fontainbleu Hotel. It was ``through the magic of television.``
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in about 40 years, the magic of television
was again alive on the day of New Year's Eve as I watched as much
as I could of the 25-hour ``Millennium 2000`` on the Public
Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the image was of loin-cloth-clad Maori warriors, wading
ashore from an ancient canoe in New Zealand, or of an all-girl, Big
Band quartet in Prague, singing a Czech-accented ``Beer Barrel
Polka,`` the PBS celebration repeatedly drove home the fact that
television has indeed made planet Earth a global village.
</P>
<P>
   And because the marathon broadcast was interrupted only by
commercials for PBS itself (unlike ABC's millennium presentation),
I was reminded that public broadcasting is truly one of our
country's most precious treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium 2000`` was the inspiration of Zvi Dor-Ner, the
executive producer at PBS' shining star, Boston station WGBH.
Unprecedented in the history of television in length and scope, the
live broadcast was coproduced by WGBH, the BBC and a consortium of
58 nations. According to PBS, more than 2,000 cameras, sending
images through 60 satellite paths and thousands of miles of
fiber-optic cable, were used to circle the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The result was an astounding journey, both visually and
emotionally. Everytime I sat down to take in another sunrise,
midnight celebration, interpretive dance or adolescent's poem,
tears welled up and rolled down my cheeks. During one segment, in
which cartoon-like dancers in white suits and fedoras hopped
merrily up and down on every level of the Leaning Tower of Pisa, I
darn-near suffocated from laughing AND crying.
</P>
<P>
   Since the broadcast, I have searched the half-century of my
over-stuffed memory bank for any other media presentation that made
so clear an oft-denied reality: Despite our diversity and habitual
miscommunication, humanity is really one big family, much more like
one another than we are any other species on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the bank comes close to ``Millennium 2000.``
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast also offered ample evidence of why all the
millennial doom-sayers were dead wrong in their predictions of
violence and disaster. Performer after performer, presenter after
presenter, each woman, man and child faced the PBS cameras and
delivered the same essential message:
</P>
<P>
   Here is my personal gift in honor of THE world. We're all in it
together.
</P>
<P>
   If I had to pick one image that best symbolized the magnificence
of ``Millennium 2000,`` it would be that of an older, gray-haired
Chinese man who performed a slow, graceful dance during the sunrise
of the first day of the new century in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a white silk martial arts-like robe and flowing
pants, the man was a striking contrast to the deep green grass on
which he danced. Then, in a move that took my breath away, the
segment's producers switched from a ground camera to one in a
helicopter for the proverbial bird's eye view: The man was dancing
alone at the edge of a mountain top.
</P>
<P>
   I have since learned that the venue was Mount Tai, the most
revered of the five Taoist mountains of China. According to the
``Lonely Planet`` travel guide, it is ``a place where most Chinese
come at least once in their lifetime.``
</P>
<P>
   About 500 years before the first Christian millennium began,
Confucius climbed the 6,600 steps that lead to Mount Tai's
1,400-meter summit. There, he is reported to have looked down and
declared, ``The world is small.``
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five hundred years later, PBS proved his simple but
profound observation still to be true _ proved it through the magic
of television.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
