<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-MALCOLM-HNS &LR;      01-07 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MALCOLM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A WILY FOX WOULD LEAVE `MALCOLM' ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memo to Fox:
</P>
<P>
   Don't screw up ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' This sitcom is too
good.
</P>
<P>
   You somewhat choked on ``Action,'' an achingly funny comedy that
got only a handful of viewers (all of whom loved it) before you
pulled the plug. You should have done something to keep it on life
support, if just a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   (That said, Fox must still get some credit for putting that
skewed Hollywood comedy on in the first place.)
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' The show was not
technically listed as a mid-season replacement _ it was always
slated to start after the football regular season _ but you network
folks must be harboring strong hopes for the show debuting Sunday.
That is why it was moved from its initial 7 p.m. listing to the
more coveted post-``Simpsons'' time slot of 8:30 p.m. (bumping
``Futurama'' to 7 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Hopes are well placed. We thought ``Malcolm in the Middle'' was
among the funniest new sitcoms in an extremely weak comedy year
when we first saw the pilot way back in July. After seeing the next
two episodes as well, there is nothing to discourage that first
impression.
</P>
<P>
   If Fox does anything well, it is presenting sitcoms with wildly
messed up families (the Simpson clan and the Bundys of ``Married
with Children''); functioning, if not well, then passably in
contravention to social norms. (Ironically, while the network wants
this family to become a touchstone like its Fox predecessors,
Malcolm's clan does not have a known last name, or a hometown,
though it appears to be California.)
</P>
<P>
   Mired in a nightmare season of low ratings and widespread
cancellations (``The Badland,'' ``Harsh Realm,'' the half-hour
version of ``Ally'' and the never-seen ``Manchester Prep'' are
among the others), Fox goes back to its strength once more, and
delivers.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm (Frankie Muniz) is an average kid, the third of four
brothers. He is a little coarse, of course, but what 9-year-old
isn't? His oldest brother is in military school, his next oldest is
always in fights, and his youngest is usually the subject of some
benign torture from his older siblings.
</P>
<P>
   To Malcolm's horror, and his parents' shock, the kid discovers
that he is no average kid, but rather the astounding brains of a
rather dim family. He possesses a photographic memory and an IQ of
165. When his mom is told he is going to be placed in a ``special''
class, she at first suspects it's because he is slow rather than
brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm balks, because he knows being placed with the nerdy
advanced kids _ the ``krelboynes'' (named after the departed
teacher who started the gifted program years ago) _ makes him a
marked man on the playground.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm at times tells the story-within-the-story through the
conceit of talking to the camera (not as obnoxious as you might
think). Jane Kaczmarek as mom Lois and Christopher Kennedy
Masterson (brother of Danny Masterson of ``That '70s Show'') as
older brother Francis stand out in a wonderfully bizarre cast of
characters. But it is Muniz who people will be talking about most.
</P>
<P>
   Provided that you, Fox, don't screw it up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-YAC-CONNER-BOS &LR;      01-07 1633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-CONNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNER READY TO RUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ ``I've got a pretty wife, 29 boats, I'm
sailing fast and having fun here. Life can't get much better than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   So quoth Dennis Conner, who on Tuesday afternoon gave four
blasts on the boat horn over his compound, startling his crew and
everyone within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   There was no particular reason for the blast. It was just that,
after nearly four months of being largely overlooked on this
waterfront, he wanted to say, ``We've arrived!''
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was Day 2 of a scheduled 10 rounds of racing to
determine who among the six challengers will ascend to the finals,
then to the America's Cup match in February.
</P>
<P>
   Stars &AMP; Stripes had just beaten Prada, the glamour team in this
regatta, by a convincing 1 1/2 minutes, and by midweek the Conner
team was on the move, 3-0, by Wednesday. Topping the points table
with seven races to go.
</P>
<P>
   It was a quarter century ago that the 32-year-old Olympic dinghy
sailor from San Diego was trimming main for Ted Turner on
Courageous in Newport. Sailing the critical starts that year, he
helped spark the US to a victory over Australia, his first of seven
America's Cups.
</P>
<P>
   So much water under the keel since then . . .
</P>
<P>
   But Conner blew his horn the other day to let this waterfront
know that _ far from being the gentrified elder statesman here to
sell a few souvenirs that some make him out to be _ he is still a
scrapper and here to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly more elder and more of a statesman now, Conner was
sounding the attack. Stars &AMP; Stripes, the midnight blue boat built
a bit wider and larger than most this year, had soundly thrashed
Prada _ the favorite of the 11 challengers that started trial
racing last October.
</P>
<P>
   While the extremely changeable weather here creates unexpected
upsets, Stars &AMP; Stripes beat Prada in a traditional race in which
picking the correct side of the course, then choosing tactics _
whether to play wind shifts or cover the moves of the boat behind _
is the match-racing tradeoff.
</P>
<P>
   As Stars &AMP; Stripes was towed slowly into the harbor with its
ecstatic sailing team aboard and well-wishers awaiting at the dock,
Conner stepped out of his second-story dockside office and blasted
the cannon four times across the harbor. Shades of Fremantle: Big
Bad Dennis had it rolling again!
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this America's Cup, Conner is not on the boat
to make the calls. With his $12 million budget _ a quarter that of
Young America's, for instance, and a fifth of Prada's _ he needs to
run the campaign from the office, mostly in the function of dialing
for dollars _ fund-raising calls back to the States.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm also the one who has to deal with the insurance
company when someone dents one of the cars,'' he says. ``Roger
Pensky doesn't drive his own car anymore, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a better analogy is with Red Auerbach. Long after he had
stopped riding the bench in the Celtics' halcyon years, Red was
still the team's driving force, as Conner is the force behind Stars
&AMP; Stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss him on the boat, really miss him,'' says Tom Whidden,
Conner's best friend of 20 years and still the tactician credited
with almost always having Stars &AMP; Stripes in the right place on the
race course. ``Dennis is still the key to the whole team. His will
is still there driving the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's skipper, Ken Read, describes his boss and mentor's
effect on the team. ``He's the kind of leader who is a real
leader,'' says Read, a J-24 Olympic champion who has won the
presigious Rolex Yachtsman of the Year award. ``He hires the best
professionals he can find, gives us anything we want and need, then
lets us make our own decisions. He never second-guesses us.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the trials, Conner was on the boat, largely because
Whidden had not signed on to the team as senior member of the
afterguard. But, says Whidden, who was busy running North Sails in
Connecticut, ``Dennis kept the pressure on. He called me every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   When Whidden did agree to team up with his old friend, Conner
got off the boat and let the team of Whidden, Read, Peter Isler,
and Peter Holmberg act as the afterguard _ one of the most
experienced in Auckland. And though all agree that the combination
of experience and enthusiastic youngsters in the front of the boat
works to a tee, Conner is not as happy riding a swivel chair. ``I
would obviously rather be sailing than doing anything else,'' he
says. ``But those guys are doing great. They don't need me there,
but up here paying the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars &AMP; Stripes is still a long shot in a regatta in which
budgets range from $20 million to $80 million, in which teams
having two boats and huge crews allows for development and
advancement between rounds. But New Zealand is different, says
Conner, who created the two-boat program as early as 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, a two-boat program doesn't work,'' he says. ``The wind
is so shifty and the speed varies so much that you'd sail 100 yards
and have to change sails. You can't test two boats in a straight
line for very long, which is what you have to do in a two-boat
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this could just be Conner blowing smoke, putting his
spin on matters. Stars &AMP; Stripes is a one-boat program, pure and
simple. It also was late in starting, and the boat had to be
all-purpose, in this case heavier fittings and less refinement than
so-called ``glamour'' programs such as Prada.
</P>
<P>
   Like many sports figures, Conner is somewhat superstitious and
believes in omens. Sail numbers are assigned to boats in order of
when they are commissioned, so when he was assigned No. 55 for
Stars &AMP; Stripes, he believed it was an omen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-five was the number of Stars &AMP; Stripes in '87,'' he
said. ``It's a very positive omen for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Conner's career has been, Fremantle will always be
the high water mark. Having lost the Cup in 1983 in Newport, Conner
asked for support from the New York Yacht Club to field a
challenger campaign to get it back. After New York turned him down,
he fielded his own campaign with the backing of his hometown San
Diego Yacht Club.
</P>
<P>
   At one point as the team worked on development in Hawaii, he
recalled, ``We didn't have enough money to pay the milk bill for
the crew. We had to keep saying, `We'll pay you next week.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But when he did show up in Fremantle with his gunsmoke-blue
12-meter, Stars &AMP; Stripes, the challenger trials quickly became a
struggle between Conner and New Zealand, which was sailing
America's Cup for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Conner came face to face with another brash newcomer to the Cup,
22-year-old Chris Dickson, who reminded him of himself.
</P>
<P>
   With the ESPN cameras whirring, Conner and Dickson became fierce
rivals and mutual admirers. They fought on the water with the
Australian winds and big seas, and in the press center where their
nightly sparring became as ferocious as the big winds.
</P>
<P>
   The largest issue came down to New Zealand's fiberglass
12-meter. All the other twelves were built from aluminum, which
became the preferred medium after wood. The theory developed that
fiberglass could be molded in such as way as to allow builders to
put more of the weight in the center with less in the ends.
</P>
<P>
   The added stability, especially in choppy water, allowed a
lighter (faster) boat to have the stability of a heavier one. New
Zealand naturally denied it, but Conner's line remains one of the
better known in Cup history: ``Why would you build a boat out of
fiberglass unless you wanted to cheat?''
</P>
<P>
   As the showdown between Dickson and Conner drew near, as each
side tried to rattle the other, Dickson made the following
characterization: ``If you got into a duel with Dennis Conner and
he had two bullets in his gun, he'd put the first one right between
your eyes. But if he had just one bullet, he'd be too rattled to
shoot straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Conner quickly cut through the hype by trouncing his
young meancer, 4-1, in the semifinals, Whidden conceded that there
was some truth to Dickson's observation and that it was Whidden's
job in part to ``keep Dennis in his comfort zone. When he's there,
there's no better sailor at the wheel of a boat.''
</P>
<P>
   After the semis with New Zealand that year, Stars &AMP; Stripes' 4-0
drubbing of Australia's Kookaburra was anticlimatic. And before a
huge international audience watching sailing on ESPN for the first
time, Dennis Conner became the best-known sailor in the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the day after Stars &AMP; Stripes went up, 3-0, in the
semis, the feeling was loose and casual at the compound. Because
the French had caused a collision, damaging the Stars &AMP; Stripes
stern, the midnight blue boat sits in the shed being fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Read wanders into the hospitality tent, grabs an espresso,
and joins Whidden for breakfast. Conner ambles in, making jokes
about the danger of talking to reporters. He is deply tanned, and
wears the red-white-and blue team gear, the same Canterbury gear he
sells in the Stars &AMP; Stripes retail shop adjoining the compound.
</P>
<P>
   When he wanders into the shop, several tourists crowd him for
autographs. Some get their picture taken with him. It's a natural
gesture for him to put his arm around people he poses with. A
typical hot morning around the Stars &AMP; Stripes dock _ summertime
and the livin' is easy. There's not even a security guard at the
gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am having the time of my life,'' says Conner, who is already
planning his next Whitbread (round-the-world) campaign, not to
mention some Etchells racing back in the States next summer. ``And
right now,'' he adds, speaking of Etchells, ``I'm going pretty damn
fast. Life is sweet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
