<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN IN ITS OWN CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With conference play getting under way this week, it seemed
appropriate to take a quick look at how some of the major
conferences should look in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East has no surprises. Despite the University of
Connecticut's loss to Notre Dame Wednesday night, the Huskies are
still the class of the league. The home loss to Notre Dame proved,
however, that the rest of the conference is starting to catch up
and is close to reaching the on-any-given-night stage where the
Huskies have to do more than just show up to be assured of victory.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's problem _ if it can be called that _ is that it knows
the important part of the season comes in March.
</P>
<P>
   As defending national champions, coach Jim Calhoun doesn't have
the trump card of casting his team into a unit that needs to work
harder to achieve the ultimate goal of winning a title.
</P>
<P>
   No team can play at its highest level every game. Like the
preseason NIT loss in November to Iowa, which served as the first
wake-up call of the season, UConn will find games in which less
talented teams will play above their heads and beat the Huskies _
even at home.
</P>
<P>
   The other Big East power is Syracuse. Again no surprise. Jim
Boeheim's teams always compete. What's unusual this season is that
the team is not only unbeaten, but has yet to play a game outside
the Carrier Dome. The Orangemen will get their first real test
Saturday when they visit Miami.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Big East becomes a free-for-all of teams with
St. John's the best of the rest. Providence might be a team to
watch; they visit Boston College Saturday at Conte Forum. Since
7-foot-2-inch Karim Shabazz became eligible last month, the Friars
have turned into a different team, beating Arkansas and the
University of Massachusetts. ``I hope we don't expect too much of
him,'' Friar coach Tim Welsh said when Shabazz transferred to PC
from Florida State. Too much? It's become not enough since Shabbaz
averaged 19 points and 11.3 rebounds and blocked 18 shots in his
first three games back.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the conferences:
</P>
<P>
   ACC _ Surprise, surprise. Duke has retooled and has not lost
since back-to-back opening losses in the preseason NIT. North
Carolina and Maryland are lurking.
</P>
<P>
   SEC _ Auburn was the preseason favorite and Florida was right
there with them. Nothing has changed. Both are in the Top 10 in
this week's polls. The surprise has been the shaky play of
Kentucky, which is only a marginal Top 25 team. Tennessee, which
won 13 of its first 14 games, needs to be watched.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten _ From bottom to top the toughest conference. How good
is this league? Consider: Michigan State has a 9-4 record and is
still in the Top 10. Indiana. Iowa. Purdue. Illinois. Ohio State.
Try to find an easy night in this conference.
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 _ Kansas, the perennial leader, might have company.
Oklahoma and Oklahoma State won 22 of the first 24 games between
them. And no one wants to play an Eddie Sutton-coached Oklahoma
State team in March. Texas, with center Chris Mihm coming to
Hartford for a showdown against the Huskies' Jake Voskuhl, has
drawn the attention of NBA scouts. The UConn sports information
office has requested 19 credentials from NBA scouts for Monday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA _ Cincinnati is head and shoulders above
everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 _ Unlike its brethren in football, the conference is
loaded with quality teams. Stanford. Arizona. UCLA. Washington.
Arizona State. Take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain West _ Utah struggled at first, but with Hanno Mottola
healthy, the Utes should be the class of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic 10 _ Temple and Xavier are the front-runners and
everyone else is chasing. Dayton bears watching.
</P>
<P>
   Ivy _ Penn and Princeton. Same as it ever was.
</P>
<P>
   America East _ Hofstra is the best team. But Delaware has the
home-court edge with the conference tournament being played there
each March. It's vital for Hofstra to win the regular season to get
a home-court edge over the Blue Hens in the America East title
game, which is always played at the home court of the highest
seeded remaining team.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University and Northeastern? Forget about it. It's been a
horrible year for both schools, who play each other Saturday. But
there is a difference. BU has been riddled with injuries, but has a
harmony on the squad that wasn't there a year ago. The Terriers are
in a rebuilding mode and coach Dennis Wolff doesn't have to worry
about internal problems. It's different at Northeastern, where
internal problems continue to smolder with the potential of tearing
the entire program apart. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coach Cal's next step? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye on ex-UMass coach John Calipari. Coach Cal has told
friends that he now is more likely to return to college coaching
than the NBA. Memphis has been courting him for months and that
remains a possibility while Cal spends the season as Larry Brown's
assistant with the Philadelphia 76ers. Money is not a problem _ at
least right now _ since Cal is still getting money from his
contract with the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Stability is. Cal has three childern and reportedly likes a
college environment where he and his wife can raise their family.
He also wants to be at a program where he can win. Memphis might be
a good starting point, but by waiting to the end of this season,
Cal can see what college job opens and pick the best offer. He
won't come cheap _ probably somewhere in the $500,000 to $800,000
range per year, but there will be programs out there willing to pay
the price . . . Only three unbeaten teams remain _ Stanford,
Syracuse, and LSU, while there are only three winless teams,
Arkansas-Pine Bluff, Howard, and Delaware State. Since Howard and
Delaware State are both in the MEAC, someone has to win . . .
Oklahoma's 12 wins in its first 13 games is the best for the
Sooners since 1989-90 . . . While the upset of Wright State over
Michigan State was amazing, so is the fact that two of Wright
State's starters were freshmen who each played 40 minutes . . .
Indiana is off to a quick start with 11 wins in its first 12 games,
which could be a sign the Hoosiers are back. But consider this: The
Hoosiers were 13-2 last season and finished with a 9-7 Big Ten
record. They were 13-1 in 1996-97 and finished with a 7-9 Big Ten
record . . . Nice scheduling award goes to FSU, which beat Wake
Forest, 66-64, Tuesday night, the same night the Seminoles beat
Virginia Tech for the national championship. It was a Seminole
night no matter how you looked at it because the FSU win was its
first at Wake Forest in seven seasons . . . Kansas is getting
people excited with its 11-2 start. But as most Jayhawk fans note,
March is the time coach Roy Williams's team is held most
accountable for its actions . . . Watch out for Seton Hall. Tommy
Amaker has things going for the Pirates, who have won nine of their
first 11 games; he has arguably the best recruiting class in the
country coming in next season and he has made peace with point
guard Shaheen Holloway, who was in and out of Amaker's doghouse
much of last season. Holloway's steady play has been a key reason
for the Pirates' early season success . . . Although it's a little
early to be talking about Ratings Percentage Index figures, which
are used as a strong guideline by the NCAA selection committee in
choosing the 64-team field, it is interesting to note that some
early RPI rankings have Kent and Ball State, a couple of mid-major
teams, ranked in the Top 10 . . . When you have a bad day, you have
a bad day, which is what happened to BU the other night after its
loss to Drexel in Philadelphia. The Terriers were three hours into
their return trip to Boston when their bus broke down _ in the
South Bronx, a very dangerous area. The driver took off to find
help _ which did come _ but only after a 3 1/2-hour wait. Instead
of getting home at 2 a.m, coach Dennis Wolff and his team arrived
back at BU for the morning commute at 6:30 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
