<SLUG> BC-TV-MALCOLM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX'S `MALCOLM' AN OFFBEAT TREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MALCOLM IN THE MIDDLE 
Starring: Frankie Muniz, Jane Kaczmarek, Bryan Cranston,
Christopher Kennedy Masterson, Justin Berfield, Erik Per Sullivan 
On: Fox 
Time: Sunday at 8:30 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a sitcom arrives without the ridiculous riot of
Frankenlaughter that we've learned to take for granted, you know
there's something funny going on. You know that the network _ in
this case Fox _ has enough confidence in its new comedy _ in this
case ``Malcolm in the Middle'' _ to think that viewers will give up
a few chuckles without the abrasive insistence of a tin-can laugh
track.
</P>
<P>
   And it turns out that Fox's faith in ``Malcolm in the Middle''
is very well founded indeed. The blessed absence of metallic mirth
is only one of the reasons to be happy about this twisted family
sitcom, which premieres Sunday night at 8:30 after weeks of
relentless Fox hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm'' is an instantly likable series, as it takes
conventional TV-family material and gives it a good old-fashioned
goose. It's a worthy descendent of sitcoms like ``The Wonder
Years'' and ``Roseanne,'' and it even nods to the neighborhood high
jinks of ``The Little Rascals'' (minus the racist overtones). But
``Malcolm'' is also refresingly surrealistic and irreverent. In a
TV season notably lacking in worthwhile comedies, ``Malcolm'' is a
nice treat _ a nice, gonzo treat.
</P>
<P>
   The show's territory is a messy suburban home swarming with
rough-and-tumble boys. In fact, creator Linwood Boomer has said
that his second choice for the show's title was ``Fighting in
Underpants,'' an activity these kids either do or are close to
doing at all hours. Malcolm appears to be the only sane one in his
family. A 9-year-old Everychild who just wants to be normal and fit
in, he often suffers from preteen social angst. But he is also a
certified genius, the owner of an IQ of 165. One minute he's
distraught because Mom is forcing him into a playdate with a
wheelchair-bound nerd, the next he's performing arithmetic wonders
at record speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Swirling recklessly around Malcolm are Reese, his scamp of a
next-oldest brother, and Dewey, a little tyke who is ``trapped
somewhere between toddler and hampster.'' Francis, the wily oldest
brother, was sent to military school for discipline, although he
appears regularly on the show _ often by telephone. And of course
Malcolm's parents are everpresent, particularly his chaotic, weary
mother, Lois, who has given up her dignity to get down in the
trenches with her boys. Beautifully played by Jane Kaczmarek, she
is a no-nonsense kook always focused on containing the insanity.
Dad, on the other hand, walks through his days like the most
contented of zombies. He's clueless.
</P>
<P>
   Fox sent three episodes to critics, and each is built around
standard plotlines _ the school bully, Mom's mysteriously burned
dress, the class picnic. But the perspective of the show is so
wonderfully inventive and stylized, it all feels quite original.
It's as if creator Boomer has taken ordinary suburban life and
turned up the exaggeration meter a few notchs, pushing all the
authenticity over into the realm of absurdity. Even the camerawork
is used to make wacky jokes, with well-placed close ups and wide
angle shots.
</P>
<P>
   One gimmick has Malcolm repeatedly addressing the camera,
breaking the fourth wall to comment on the action. It's a risky
technique, but it works remarkably well here, cementing our bond
with Malcolm, the show's anchor. After he complains about having to
join the gifted class to his mother, she tells him: ``Just
remember, any kid who makes fun of you is a creepy little loser
who'll end up working in a car wash.'' He then turns to the camera
_ and us _ and confesses, ``That shouldn't make me feel better. But
it does.'' It's a sweet, intimate moment, and it balances the
show's mostly frenetic tone. As Malcolm, Frankie Muniz is wonderful
and sympathetic, particularly as worry furrows his delicate brow.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday night's episode, there are a few racy bits. A frazzled
Lois answers the door without wearing a top, and Hal, almost
preternaturally hairy, stands naked in the kitchen while Lois
performs her monthly body shave. (All nudity is obscured.) Don't
let these trademark Fox scenes keep you from giving ``Malcolm'' a
chance, even if you are inclined to click away from ``edgy'' TV.
They aren't played for titillation so much as familial goofiness,
and the next two episodes are ``clean.'' ``Malcolm in the Middle''
may not be polite _ what family sitcom worth its salt could be in
this day and age? But it doesn't have a mean bone in its cheerfully
black-and-blue body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
