<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9412 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     01-07 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISGUISE THE OPEN WALLPAPER SEAMS BY PAINTING THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 09, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The wallpaper in one room of my house was installed three
years ago, with the seams butted rather than overlapped. Now I
notice the seams have opened up, not much, but enough to create a
white line where each strip of paper butts against the other. What
happened? And what can I do about it? The paper is predominately
beige in color.
</P>
<P>
   F. B., Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. What happened is a good question that the manufacturer of the
paper and the installer would like to have an answer to. So would
the handyman, who can at least give an educated guess. For
starters, modern paper is butted at the seams; in fact, it would
not work to overlap the seams because overlapped seams would
prevent a proper pattern match.
</P>
<P>
   OK, for more answers, the paper might have shrunk after
installation because it was defective. This could happen with
prepasted paper or with paper that is pasted. You may have a case
with the manufacturer; contact him and see what he says.
</P>
<P>
   The prepaste or added paste might have shrunk, pulling the
strips of paper away from each other. If the paper was prepasted,
again, you may have a case with the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure except to replace the paper, but you may not
have to if you disguise the seams by painting the gaps with a flat
latex paint the color of the paper. The handyman did this after he
botched a papering project many years ago, and you know, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you think of this idea: Wax the ceramic tile in my
shower and bath to protect it, or at least to protect the grout
against dirt?
</P>
<P>
   BOB McAULIFFE, Mansfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Frankly, not a lot. Your idea is good, especially to protect
the grout, but the material is not. First, glazed tile does not
need protection; the glazing on most tiles is glass, quite
resistant to dirt and easily cleaned. With wax, you would have to
cover everything, and buff with a power buffer as well. Too much of
a hassle for little effect. Wax tends to attract dirt, and dirty
wax is not cleanable except by removal, which would have to be done
once a year or so and more applied. Whoo, I don't want to think
about it!
</P>
<P>
   However, here is what you can use instead of wax: Tile sealer or
masonry sealer. Apply one coat once a year to the entire surface
(it's easier that way than dabbing sealer on the grout lines).
Polish with a dry cloth. The tiles will be unaffected, but the
grout will be as dirt-resistant as it will ever be.
</P>
<P>
   As for cleaner or sealer, try Tile Guard products: grout
cleaner, grout coating, and silicone grout sealer; call
800-445-0619. For a cleaner, try KRC-7, sold in plumbing supply
shops. For a tile colorer and sealer, try Grout Colorant, sold in
tile stores. For new grout, try Colorlastic by Tec, Gainsville,
Fla., 904-372-3931. The company claims it is stain resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping grout clean is not easy, and that is why the handyman
recommends black grout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. There is good storage space behind the eaves on the second
floor of my house, but is it ever cold in there. I was thinking of
insulating that space with polyisocyanurate, the one-inch-thick
foam insulation with foil on both sides. Some say I can do that,
others say not to. They don't say why I should not; is there a
reason not to use such insulation?
</P>
<P>
   MARK CHAPMAN, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no reason that I know of against using this type of
insulation in almost any application, except that it is quite
expensive. But because it is flammable, it must be covered with
plasterboard or other fire-resistant material, wherever it is
exposed, whether it is exposed in living space or in that storage
space.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to install, and if you obey the rules, you can
put it in to keep that space a little warmer; not a lot, if the
space is not heated, but a little. To keep it warmer, you'd have to
add heat, or better yet, open the doors to the space so a little
house heat can get in there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My no-wax kitchen floor is 18 years old, and I am having a
tough time with wax buildup. I used no-buildup wax, or thought I
did, and tried a lot of other things over the years, including wax
strippers and waxes. Still there is buildup, and the vinyl looks
terrible. What can I do to remove remaining wax and possibly rewax?
</P>
<P>
   ROGER ROWELL, Newburyport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the vinyl is beyond redemption because it is 18 years
old, a long time for sheet vinyl to last. It is so old that waxing
will not restore the shine. The older the vinyl, the more it will
absorb the wax, and the shine is gone. You could try stripping the
wax by applying llberal amounts of paint thinner or a strong
ammonia solution. Then rewax, but I doubt that will work. The wax
has penetrated the finish, making it that much harder to remove.
And, the new wax on an absorbent surface will not restore the
shine. Consider new floor covering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-BILLS-FLUTIE-ART-     01-07 1732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-FLUTIE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE: SACKED FROM THE BLIND SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. - Doug Flutie can't remember what he said
Monday when Wade Phillips, his coach, told him he was being sent to
the bench. It was too shocking. But Flutie clearly remembers what
he was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exactly what happened (11 years ago) with the
Patriots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The words came. Flutie is not over the hurt, and he'll stop
midway through a sentence and ask, ``Do you think this would have
happened if I was 6-1?'' and then go on to say his first words to
his replacement, Rob Johnson, were, ``Just win a damn (Super Bowl)
ring.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he'll go back 11 years when former Patriots coach
Raymond Berry shocked him and the team's fans by naming Tony Eason,
still hurt and still unable to throw well, as the starter in New
England's last game of the 1988 season, against a poor Denver team,
a game New England had to win to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me about this is that I felt the decision back
then was made because Tony was a first-rounder, Tony was making a
million-two and I was making a hundred grand, and if I went into
that offseason as a free agent and a starter, they were going to
have to pay me what Tony made,'' said Flutie. ``So they had to make
a decision then . . . and do it. And I feel like I got caught in
the middle of that.''
</P>
<P>
   And here in Buffalo, Johnson makes $5 million a year and Flutie
about $4.4 millon, an expensive scenario that clearly can't last
long. Flutie's mind searches for reasons why and he sees so many
similarities between New England and Buffalo, beyond both Berry and
Phillips telling him he doesn't throw the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, here's a situation where they've given up a
first-rounder plus for Rob, he signed for a lot of money, and he
hasn't done anything yet . . . it all had that same feeling,'' said
Flutie. ``Now . . . Rob is a much more talented quarterback than
(Eason) . . . Tony was still injured at that point . . . at least
here I can accept it because I know how talented a quarterback Rob
is. So I accept it a little easier . . . but it still doesn't
replace that hurt feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The hurt feeling ``knowing that I busted my ass for 15 weeks,
locked up a playoff spot, ready to take the team into the playoffs
. . . really, the whole reason I came down here from Canada was to
win a Super Bowl. We have a great defense, the best in the league,
and we have a real shot at the Super Bowl . . . and I helped put us
in position, and then you have to turn it over to somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   A Toronto newspaper reported Thursday that Flutie may want to
return to the Canadian Football League. Wide receiver Andre Reed
disclosed on his Web site this week that he and Flutie don't speak
to each other; sources say Reed despises Flutie. And Scott
Berchtold, the Bills' vice president/communications, captured this
week of conspiracy theories by saying, ``It's like how they used to
play Beatles' records backward to find some hidden meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as . . . did owner Ralph Wilson make a call?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The grass is still green in Buffalo and not a snowflake _ let
alone a snowbank _ is in sight. Eerie times for early January, for
the warmth just won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   And the heat is coming not only from the weather gods, but also
from the Bills, because Phillips has made a decision that is
red-hot in its riskiness and white-hot for its daring. Depending on
what happens Saturday in Nashville, there may never be another
icicle in Buffalo because the hot anger from perhaps the NFL's most
passionate fans may last for eons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell the difference (between Flutie and Johnson),''
said Phillips in words that may be his epitaph if Buffalo can't
more the ball in the AFC wild-card game against the Titans. ``Even
in practice last week, I thought we practiced as good as we
practiced all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as likely, if Buffalo wins and goes deep into the playoffs
under Johnson, the warmth of the praise for the Buffalo brain trust
might delay the onset of winter for another Ice Age or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough decision certainly,'' said Phillips. ``I studied
the film. It wasn't a haphazard thing. I talked to our coaches and
I think it gives us the best opportunity to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, who helped lead the Bills to the playoffs, has been
benched and Johnson, who has started all of eight NFL games in his
career, is in. The Bills already have a defense good enough to win
the Super Bowl but scoring has been the bane of the Bills for much
of the second half of the season. If the Bills can score, Phillips
believes, Buffalo is good enough to win the Super Bowl. And
Phillips is correct.
</P>
<P>
   Still in all, benching quarterbacks on the eve of the playoffs
just isn't done in the NFL. Not since Jets coach Joe Walton benched
Ken O'Brien for Pat Ryan heading into the 1986 playoffs and a game
against the Chiefs (which the Jets won), has a coach been this
daring.
</P>
<P>
   But those Jets had lost five in a row under the mediocrity of
all mediocrities, O'Brien; Flutie, for his part, had completed his
last 12 passes in a row in his last action against the Patriots two
weeks ago in Foxborough, a game the Bill won in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   As Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher put it, ``I never second-guess a
coach's decision, but from a standpoint of being surprised, yes,
I'm very surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   An understatement. ``Shocking'' is the only apt word as Flutie
is still shocked and his days in Buffalo possibly may be done.
Depending on what happens in Nashville, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how I do it,'' said Flutie, when asked to reply to the
criticism that he can't throw the long ball. ``Everybody has
different ways of getting it done. Rob may go downtown more often
and hit some big plays. It doesn't faze me that I hit somebody on a
slant and he goes 80 yards for a touchdown or I throw the long ball
and he outruns a guy for a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, said Flutie, he throws the ball as far as Johnson.
And the quarterback efficiency ratings (Flutie's is 75.1; Johnson's
is 119.5 after an exceptional game last Sunday against the Colts)
``are a joke,'' said Flutie. ``I've thrown three interceptions on
the last play of the game trying just to throw one up. I run for
first downs and that has nothing to do with quarterback efficiency
ratings. I avoid sacks and throw the ball away and all that does is
hurt my percentage. But they're the little things that help win
games.''
</P>
<P>
   As always with Flutie. He may not look the best but he usually
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wade came to me and said it was his decision and I have to
believe that,'' said Flutie, as another Beatles' record was played
backwards. ``Whether I do or not, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has fears and I'm sure I'll be nervous,'' said
Johnson, who was 24 of 32 for 287 yards and 2 TDs against the
Colts. ``but you just have to deal with it. You just have to
overcome it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Phillips told him Monday ``that he thought with me
that we had the best chance of winning, the team . . . better . . .
That was good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills' thinking is that NFL defensive coordinators have
caught up to Flutie. Defenses often bring eight men up close to the
line and dare Flutie to beat them with his passing. Teams now rush
Flutie from the outside, keeping him from performing his virtuoso
act of scrambling to the outside, while interior linemen rush with
their arms up, leading to deflections of Flutie's passes.
</P>
<P>
   Reed and Flutie are in a deep freeze, because Reed believes
Flutie does not throw him the ball enough and because Reed believed
that Flutie went to the coaches two weeks ago and had Reed removed
from the Patriots game. More than a few times, Reed has given up on
his routes while Flutie has scrambled, an unhappy symptom, some
believe, of what ailed the Bills offense; a key part of any
offense, the deep ball, was missing.
</P>
<P>
   And the domino effect builds, affecting the Bills' running as
well, because teams do not have to worry about the long pass.
</P>
<P>
   Still in all, Reed has sulked many times before in his career
and Flutie's third-down success has been outstanding, often making
plays few other quarterbacks can make. The Bills have converted
40.8 percent of their third downs this season, third in the league.
Most important, the Bills (11-5) have won under Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   No Ken O'Brien, Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flutie said he does not intend to return to play in Canada,
except one day ``When this is all over, it would be nice to play
with my brother (Darren who was on the Grey Cup-winning Hamilton
Tiger Cats last season),'' he said. As for Reed, Flutie insisted he
had nothing to do with Reed being removed from the Patriots game,
saying that it was his belief Reed had sore ribs going into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie was told by Phillips before the Colts game that he would
be rested to ensure that he would be at full speed for the
playoffs. Part of Flutie agreed, but in the back of his mind, there
was doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not hurt, I don't want to rest, I want to play,'' Flutie
recalled saying to a friend when Phillips told him he'd be sitting
the last regular-season game. `` `No matter what Rob does, you're
the guy.' Wade said that. But I've been there before. I've seen how
it works. I didn't really anticipate it happening, and I thought it
was my own paranoia. But obviously . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   And now, one of the gutsiest decisions ever made by an NFL coach
has been made, and in Nashville, Wade Phillips, Rob Johnson and
Doug Flutie will learn its consequences. For sure, football life
never will be the same for the three of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accepted the decision now,'' said Flutie. ``My way of
dealing with it is to know I'm going to get back out on the field
again. I believe in Rob and I believe in the team, and we're going
to win games. At some point, I'm still going to be a big part of
this, whether it's coming in with four minutes to go, down by 5,
whether it'll be one game to the next or whatever it may be. I
still deep down believe that I'm going to be a big part of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      01-07 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK GRIEVANCE GETS THE BALL SPINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The clock on when and if Bill Belichick will become the
new Patriots coach and general manager began ticking when his
agent, Neil Cornrich, filed an eight-page grievance with the NFL
over the validity of his current Jets contract, which Belichick
wants voided so he can pursue another job.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome affects the future leadership of the Patriots, who
Monday sought permission to speak to Belichick about coming to New
England.
</P>
<P>
   That triggered a series of wild events that have once again
stirred New York-New England tensions and virtually reenacted the
1997 scenario between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, despite stating that his decision Tuesday to resign
after one day as Jets coach was influenced by an uncertain
ownership situation in New York and not because of his desire to
take the job in New England, would like to be coach and GM of the
Patriots, according to a source close to him.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said the Jets have until the close of
business Monday to file a response on the grievance. At that point,
commissioner Paul Tagliabue will likely request a hearing, then
review the case before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   There are differing opinions on the likely outcome. One NFL
official said the league would be tough with Belichick and not
allow him out of the contract, forcing him to sit out or take a
college job, while a friend of Belichick said there was renewed
confidence that the league would allow Belichick to move to the
Patriots after the commissioner decided the proper compensation.
The Patriots continued to go forward with their contingency plans,
interviewing Chicago offensive coordinator Gary Crowton at Robert
Kraft's headquarters in Boston, and again at team headquarters in
Foxborough, where vice president and CEO Andy Wasynczuk and vice
president of player personnel Bobby Grier met with the 42-year-old
Crowton, considered one of the top offensive minds in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are also interviewing Baltimore defensive
coordinator Marvin Lewis. The team said there were no interviews
scheduled over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell will interview in
Foxborough, after the Patriots granted the Green Bay Packers
permission to interview him for their head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have contacted the Rams concerning offensive
coordinator Mike Martz, and a report that New England also was
interested in talking to the Rams' personnel man _ and former
Patriots college scouting director _ Charley Armey was premature.
</P>
<P>
   Given the turnaround in St. Louis this season, the Martz-Armey
combination would be intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Crowton, the first offensive coordinator interviewed by the
team, is an interesting candidate. Crowton is the former head coach
at Louisiana Tech University, where he directed a high-powered
offense. This was his first season in Chicago, and he brought
excitement to an offense that is quarterback-friendly _ designed so
the quarterback can audible and the receivers can make site reads.
Crowton also emphasizes downfield blocking by the receivers and
tries to set up mismatches against the defense that can exploit
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Crowton likes to run screens, which make linebackers have to
move laterally and which tends to wear them down.
</P>
<P>
   Crowton is the former quarterback coach at Boston College
(1991-93), where he coached former Jets and current Seahawks backup
Glenn Foley.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Crowton used three quarterbacks _ rookie Cade
McNown, Shane Matthews, and Jim Miller. They were the first three
quarterbacks on the same team to each throw for more than 1,000
yards. Crowton has also worked at the University of New Hampshire,
and was a graduate assistant to Mike Holmgren at Brigham Young
University.
</P>
<P>
   Crowton is also credited with turning NFL Europe receiver Marcus
Robinson into a star. He's considered quite popular among his
players and with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell will be on a few lists around the league as coaching
vacancies occur. But it seemed the Patriots only decided to talk to
him because the Packers felt he was worthy of an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots may feel they know Sidwell, but until he explains
his philosophies of how to run the show, how to deal with players
and their problems, and how he would get the offense jump-started,
they will never know completely what Sidwell can do. Because his
focus has been on defense, the Patriots have rarely asked him
questions about offense.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the filing of the grievance in New York, Bill Parcells
addressed the media in a telephone conference call and said he
would wait to see who emerges as the owner of the team before
making any commitments, but he did hint he could be talked back
into coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my watch,'' he said. ``I have a responsibility to the
organization and I'm in charge of finding a new coach now. I will
not abandon the franchise. What I said Monday is what is my
intention to follow through with. I am not trying to open any doors
or windows, but I won't let this franchise go down the tubes. I am
going to say this is on my watch and I am going to ensure something
good will happen from this.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been much speculation about Parcells since Belichick
suddenly resigned. There's little question New York fans would like
him to return as coach, and the new Jets owners may feel the same
way, especially after paying $600 million for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I said on Monday is the truth,'' said Parcells. ``When I
made that statement on Monday, that was completely my intention. I
am not leaving a ray of light to deviate from that, but I do not
know what is in the future. I do want to discuss with the new owner
what he wants done here. But my intention is to not coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is so popular and can sell his goods so well in New
York that he may be able to name either defensive coordinator Al
Groh or offensive coordinator Charlie Weis coach and sell Jets fans
on it.
</P>
<P>
   Groh would likely be Parcells's top choice, but Weis is very
interested in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland-based Cornrich said in a statement late Wednesday,
``It is unfortunate that the commissioner's office issued a
directive that precludes Bill Belichick from speaking to other
clubs about future NFL employment, thereby denying him the ability
to earn a livelihood for himself and his family. Likewise, it is
disappointing that this sanction was imposed without even having
heard Bill's position on the various reasons he is entitled to seek
other employment. We will be addressing the issue with the NFL
shortly and are hopeful that there will be a prompt resolution to
allow Bill to move forward with his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said in his teleconference that he had not spoken to
Belichick since learning of his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to talk, I am here to talk to him,'' Parcells
said. ``But I take everything he said at face value. He made his
decision and I respect that. We have had a good professional
relationship for a long time, and I appreciate what he did for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has refused to talk about anything concerning the
Patriots. There has also been speculation on which Jets coaches
would come with him to New England, but all of the coaches except
Dan Henning have at least another year on their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick would need to bring a personnel person with him, and
speculation is that Phil Savage, the 34-year-old director of
college scouting for the Baltimore Ravens, would be his top choice.
Belichick's also very close to Scott Pioli, the Jets' director of
pro personnel. One problem: Pioli is married to Parcells's
daughter, Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
