<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS CONFUSED BY MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several of TV's prominent NFL analysts remain baffled by Bill
Belichick's resignation Tuesday after one day as New York Jets head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden, for one, was shocked. ``I still don't understand
it,'' the Fox color man told reporters Wednesday. ``Belichick was
all set. Everything was in order and in place. It still shocks me.
I don't know how you walk away from that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Madden did not understand what Belichick was trying to say at
his news conference. ``Belichick was saying how the death of (Jets
owner) Leon Hess changed things for him,'' he said. ``He talked
about that as if it happened this weekend. The last I checked, Hess
died months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Cris Collinsworth, who works for both HBO and Fox, found his
attention shifting to Patriots owner Robert Kraft, who has had his
issues with Bill Parcells and the Jets in the recent past. ``I
can't help but think that Bob Kraft is smoking some 8-foot cigar
somewhere, blowing smoke rings and doodling the names of Parcells
and Belichick,'' Collinsworth said. ``I know he's got to be having
the time of his life, laughing hysterically.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowingly or unknowingly, Collinsworth said, Kraft helped cause
a disaster within a rival organization. ``As soon as he sent the
fax down asking for permission to talk with Bellichick, things went
haywire,'' Collinsworth said. ``Thanks to Kraft's shenanigans, he
got rid of both Parcells and Belichick.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS's Armen Keteyian also had an interesting spin on the week's
events, also involving Kraft. ``You can say a lot of things about
Kraft, but he is a very smart businessman,'' Keteyian said. ``The
Belichick thing boils down to two things: money and power. In this
case, how much power Belichick would have and how much money he
would need.''
</P>
<P>
   Keteyian recalls the Jets starting to position Belichick as head
coach during the middle of the season, making him available to
select media in an attempt to change his drab image. All of that
planning fell apart Tuesday when Belichick stood in front of a room
of reporters and rambled on in some weird stream of consciousness,
revealing how his wife clips coupons and has been pretty frugal
over the years, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's news conference generated a lot of speculation. One
theory is that Little Bill quit because he felt he'd never be able
to break away from the perception that the Jets are still
Parcells's team.
</P>
<P>
   But Keteyian believes that another factor may have been the
changing landscape among NFL coaches. In addition to the
resignation of Parcells, Ray Rhodes was fired by Green Bay on
Sunday, Pete Carroll got the ax on Monday, and Mike Ditka was let
go by New Orleans on Wednesday. Belichick supposedly is paid about
$750,000 a year, but with several jobs available and his name
appearing on everyone's short list, he could command at least
double and perhaps triple that amount.
</P>
<P>
   More intriguing to Keteyian is the debt that Kraft owes NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue. The NFL intervened in the Parcells
mess three years ago, then bailed out the Foxborough stadium plans.
Now the Belichick disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kraft is a powerful owner to have in your debt,'' Keteyian
said. ``The NFL is not uncomfortable keeping track of who owes what
and it will appear in things like NFL committee votes _ taking the
league position that he may not ordinarily agree with or keeping
silent when he should be shouting.''
</P>
<P>
   As for CBS's Greg Gumbel, he sees the firings as simply the
latest example of one of the weirder years in NFL history.
``Players and coaches don't have the luxury of sitting around and
waiting to build a franchise,'' Gumbel said. ``They have to produce
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A sweet number
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sugar Bowl earned a 17.5 national rating, a 2 percent
increase over last year's BCS finale. In Boston, the numbers were _
as usual _ well below average . . . ESPN.com has hired Andy Katz as
a senior writer. Katz was the NBA writer for the Fresno Bee . . .
Mitsubishi will be underwriting CBS's costs of producing the AFC
Championship Game in HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
