<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG LOSER IN FOOTBALL BOWLS: CORPORATE SPONSORSHIP OF EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the garrish shows of corporate carpetbagging in the
college football bowls, this one stung like chlorine in the cornea.
The burning started Saturday while watching the Rose Bowl. The
burning started again on Tuesday night when I turned on the game
between top-ranked Florida State and No. 2 Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Everytime a player was shown drinking fluids, the camera also
caught the massive blue letters on the white cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Schwab.''
</P>
<P>
   Everytime the coach was seen drinking, it was the same cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Schwab.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if you needed an eye chart, the camera would come
to a rack of cups during breaks in the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Schwab. Charles Schwab. Charles Schwab.''
</P>
<P>
   Now I am not naive. We all know that corporate sponsorships have
eviscerated whatever dignity there was out of the college bowls.
Some bowls are sponsored by ghastly icons of gastronomy seemingly
prepared in the bottom of a food disposal ( corn chips, fried
chicken and steaks).
</P>
<P>
   Other sponsors claim to be communications giants, but are
actually gnats driving people nuts with dumb directory assistance
or transforming attentive drivers into glazed zombies (telephone
companies, cell phones). Others sound as personal as Hal the
computer in ``2000, A Space Odyssey'' (anybowl.com).
</P>
<P>
   Now we as a society have not gotten very disturbed about this,
watching the bowls grow from basically four or so 30 years ago to
23 today. We have not questioned deeply the rise in corporate
sponsorships of even high school scoreboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Schwab'' hits me differently. While most corporate
logos are bad enough, being seen all over TV along the walls, on
the 50-yard-line or on the shoulders of player jerseys like the
overblown medals of tinhorn dictators, ``Charles Schwab'' is so
huge as to become the foreground. It blatantly turns college
athletes into billboards when, if they were to try and go out and
get paid to advertise the same product, they would lose their
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   I figure if corporations are getting to this level, doing
everything but plugging these teenagers and young men into a socket
so their helmets glow ``Eat at Joe's,'' then it makes you wonder
what is their commitment to actual education.
</P>
<P>
   According to the IEG Sponsorship Report, a Chicago-based
newsletter that tracks sponsorships, corporations spent an
estimated $5.1 billion on all sports sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   That is more than the $3.25 billion corporations gave to higher
education in 1998, according to the New York-based Council for Aid
to Education. In another light, the $5.1 billion spent on sports
dwarfs the $1.3 billion proposed this week by President Clinton to
rebuild the nation's dilapidated public schools. The $1.3 billion
merely matches the level of corporate sponsorships of auto racing
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the nation, according to the General Accounting
Office, would need to spend $112 billion to fix the schools. One
reason Clinton's proposal is so lame is because the Republicans
last year shot down a $3.7 billion proposal. This is despite the
plea about the schools from Dan Wilson, the American Institute of
Architects's senior director of federal affairs. Wilson said, ``If
we don't do something, it's a national disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also becoming a disgrace to see corporations and compliant
colleges and universities exploit their athletes as cash cows,
raking in dollars with mediocre graduation rates. Up until now,
society has allowed that a college scholarship was lavish
compensation for an athletes. If they all they were doing was
playing a game, that would still be true.
</P>
<P>
   But that ``Charles Schwab'' cup smells of a new level of
exploitation. When the big bowls bring in $13 million a team, when
corporations are advertising so close to the lips of athletes that
it is as if the athlete is indeed mouthing ``Charles Schwab'' on
every sip, athletes should get a cut.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have long said pay the athletes and reorganize them
into minor leagues like baseball. Or perhaps there can be some
detached club affiliation with a college, where the students who
want to go to down the street to school can and the ones who think
they can go pro can concentrate on bulking up.
</P>
<P>
   With neither of these in the immediate offing, I have another
thought. If these corporations think it is fine to exploit young
people for profit, then they should have no problem sharing those
profits, in a bowl-sponsors scholarship fund that benefits all
students.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know, every one of those .com, corn chip and Charles
Schwab-type companies will tell you how much they already give to
education. Sorry. Charles Schwab alone has over $460 billion in
assets, enough to fix the nation's schools, provide college
scholarships for all who need them and even start their own minor
league in football. Think about that and then your eyes really
start to burn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1336EST &QL; 
