<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-KNOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURVIVOR LUMBERS ON THE ROAD TO REDEMPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
EVERYTHING YOU KNOW 
By Zoe Heller 
Knopf, 205 pp., $22 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chewed-over subjects like bad marriage and the immorality of
Hollywood are risky business for a first novel. Add manslaughter,
suicide and hack celebrity and you've got the makings of real
bathos. Unless, as is the case with Zoe Heller, you've got the wit
and craft to carry it off.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Heller, a British journalist who has written for
Granta, Vanity Fair and the London Review of Books, is nothing like
her protagonist, the world-weary Willy Muller. But she slips into
his skin and gives us an absorbingly arch _ and male _ narration
full of sly pride and paralyzing doubt. Muller, recovering from a
heart attack, blocked in his attempts to turn his memoir into a
screenplay, has plenty of self-disgust to dispense with. But he's
so right-on when he skewers the silliness around him _ and so
clearly capable of discerning truths amid the wreckage of his life
_ that he draws us in as he lumbers toward some measure of
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   As the book opens, Willy is just out of the hospital, taking a
dissolute sort of inventory of his life. ``Women still want to have
sex with me, I thought this morning as I lay in bed. I have quite a
lot of hair left. I was born in the First World. I am still not
smoking. I have been making this rapid survey of Things To Be
Grateful For every morning since my heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   He has survived plenty, he reassures himself: imprisonment for
manslaughter after the death of his wife, years of hate mail from
readers of his dissembling memoir, ``To Have and To Hold.'' But the
afternoon mail brings a startling package _ the diary of his
daughter Sadie, who committed suicide months before. Balancing
guilt with curiosity, Willy turns to the first page. It is dated
Dec. 31, 1970, shortly after Willy's wife, Oona, died in a
mysterious fall in the kitchen. ``Mum who is called Oona died in
september and there is quite a controversy about that. Now we live
just with dad who is called William Muller. He used to be on
television. He reported current affairs for a program called 24/7
but he is not working at the moment because he has a lot on his
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   He still does, of course, and once he begins reading the diary,
he can't stop. Heller, who was born and educated in Britain, is
able to imbue her narrator with a kind of cultural
cold-bloodedness. She draws a bead on the details that make LA so
alluring and so unredeemably pastel. ``Nine years ago, when I first
came to Los Angeles, I really believed I had found my perfect city.
. . . (It) seemed to me a place of limitless erotic promise _
gleaming, hygienic days; mysterious, noirish nights. Everything
about it spoke of sex: the galloping freeways; the roaring Niagara
of my hotel shower; the odd, swimming-pool fragrance of the tap
water, the ticklish shiver and momentary blindness that occurred
whenever I passed from a sunny street into the dark cool of an
air-conditioned lobby. I'm not sure exactly when all these things
ceased, or when they ceased to excite me. I guess it's been a slow
ebb.''
</P>
<P>
   Willy's agent suggests he keep quiet about the heart attack and
repair to a villa in Puerto Vallerta, Mexico, to crank out the
screenplay. Brushing off a passing parade of girlfriends, drunken
pals and film industry types, Willy sinks more deeply into Sadie's
diary. While he skated free and clear on the revenue of his memoir,
she sank. There is the freezing apartment, the married lover, the
newborn named Pearl.
</P>
<P>
   His mother's death propels him back to England, and tempers his
cynicism. But the final reckoning comes from his accountant, a
70-year-old Yoda in Calabasas living in a house with an Astro-Turf
lawn. An LA numbers guy with old-world smarts, Meir Rosenblatt sits
under a lemon tree and talks about back taxes and cutbacks, courage
and cowardice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A coward isn't a bad man, necessarily,'' the accountant says.
``You can't know if you're a bad man until you die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to wait until you hear God's decision?'' Willy
asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yes, that's true. But I meant something else. Only when
you die do you run out of chances to be good. Until then, there is
always the possibility of turning yourself around.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end (without revealing too many plot twists), Willy is
able to muster some courage to go spelunking in the past. And to
emerge with, as he puts it, at least a ``plurality'' of truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0091 </DOCNO>
