<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MAGNOLIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAGNOLIA' SPUTTERS AND SIZZLES, WITH LIKABLE FLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MAGNOLIA 
Directed and written by: Paul Thomas Anderson 
Starring: Jeremy Blackman, Tom Cruise, Melinda Dillon, April Grace,
Luis Guzman, Philip Baker Hall, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Ricky Jay,
Orlando Jones, William H. Macy, Alfred Molina, Julianne Moore,
Michael Murphy, John C. Reilly, Jason Robards, Melora Walters 
Running time: 179 
Rated: R (strong language, drug use, sexuality and some violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot of sprawl and sputter in ``Magnolia.'' But there's
also a lot of sizzle in its charting of parents and children facing
off across emotional chasms that would dwarf the San Andreas Fault.
The faults of Paul Thomas Anderson's often ungainly but ultimately
winning and often powerful follow-up to ``Boogie Nights'' are ones
of ambition. In a culture and an art form where shortcomings
usually involve caving in to one form or other of political or
economic pressure, it's easy to like even this movie's faults,
which essentially can be thought of as overreach and underbite. As
for the parts that go right, they're like very little else that's
out there today.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Anderson's crisscrossing stories of Los Angelenos in
crisis seem as random as a drive-by shooting. If Anderson intends
to pull their strands together, you can't imagine how. Nor, I'm
willing to bet, will you even come close to guessing the climactic
stroke that comes out of the blue. What I think will happen, or at
least what happened to me, is that you're going to get increasingly
caught up in this or that playing out of this or that character's
story. Certainly there are enough of them, and they infectiously
proceed from what has to be Anderson's joy in writing meaty scenes
for actors.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cruise has his best role since ``Born on the Fourth of
July'' as a motivational motormouth of machismo manure. Cruise, at
his best playing tightly wound types, shows up here in the attack
mode wearing long hair, cowboy vest, and black leather pants. As he
restlessly paces the stage at a hotel meeting room and starts
unreeling his women-are-the-enemy rant, you don't know whether to
laugh, hose him down, phone for the bomb squad, or all of the
above. You can't imagine where Cruise can possibly go with this
character, given his initial high attack, but Anderson finds a few
places to lead him, including an interview with April Grace's
perceptive TV reporter who steers him into emotional territory he
didn't anticipate.
</P>
<P>
   The rich lineup includes Anderson regulars Julianne Moore and
Philip Seymour Hoffman, each in a way connected to a dying TV
executive played by Jason Robards. Not until she realizes that her
bedridden husband is dying does Moore's brittle beauty realize that
she married him for more than the money and comfort he brought her.
One scene, a drugstore encounter involving painkillers, is almost
worth the ticket price. Hoffman plays the ailing exec's in-home
nurse, bringing fresh spin and imaginative choices to what could in
other hands have collapsed into mundane bathos.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Bill Macy's washed-up ex-quiz kid, strapped for
cash, starved for love, about to make a big mistake. Philip Baker
Hall, another Anderson stalwart, turns up as a TV game-show host
and turns in a startlingly poignant performance as a man altogether
unlikable yet pitiable. John C. Reilly is perhaps the most
sympathetic as a lonely cop just bright enough to realize he isn't
bright enough, but trying to hang in there all the same, on all
fronts. He hopes he might get something going with Melora Walters's
damaged sparrow, who lives cooped up in her flat with the shades
drawn, trying to numb her rage and pain with cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of lovely stuff going on between the actors,
especially in one-on-one confrontations. Time after time, you can
feel the tension, you can feel the give-and-take, you can feel the
moment breathe. The larger picture doesn't always take on the
urgency of those peak moments when Anderson and his camera move in
close on these aching people. They're flailing about, trying to
figure out what they've got to do to make their lives whole while
the song ``It's Not Going to Stop (Until You Wise Up)'' throbs in
the background. ``Magnolia'' turns the generation gap into a San
Fernando Valley minefield, but it's made with just enough affection
for the characters to tantalize us with the possibility that at
least a few disasters can be averted. ``Magnolia'' is ``Short
Cuts'' with hope. It's my kind of mess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
