<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLAN-DRUZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON GOLAN, SOME DRUZE LONG FOR SYRIAN RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAJDAL SHAMS, Golan Heights _ In this Druze village on the
shoulders of Mount Hermon, at the northern end of the Israeli-held
Golan Heights, some 300 demonstrators gathered defiantly, singing
along as the Syrian national anthem blared over loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   A man climbed a 20-foot bronze statue of Sultan Pasha Al Atrash,
a Syrian nationalist who led the 1920s revolution against the
French, and tied the red-white-and-black Syrian flag to the
sultan's raised sword as it unfurled over the village square.
</P>
<P>
   Two Israeli military vehicles idled in the distance, out of view
of the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   But the gathering Monday offered a glimpse of the mounting
expectations and deep longings among some members of the Golan
Druze community, who sense their homes will soon return to Syria
after being under Israeli control since the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   The US-mediated Syrian-Israeli peace talks, which got underway
this week in Shepherdstown, W. Va., are proceeding slowly and
deliberately. The final details of a deal, which analysts expect to
include the return of the Golan Heights to Syria in return for
Israeli security guarantees, are far from being resolved.
</P>
<P>
   And the relationship between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and his negotiating partner, Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa,
seems less than warm.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, however, is stopping the 18,000 residents of the
Golan's community of Druze, a secretive sect of Shiite Islam formed
in the 11th Century, from celebrating what they believe is the
inevitable return of their community to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has it stopped the 18,000 Israeli settlers who live amid the
cattle ranches and wine vineyards of the Golan from stepping up
their own publicity campaign alerting Israelis to the military
risks and threat to vital water resources that would accompany
returning the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis have finally admitted that this is Syrian land,''
said Iman Abu Jabal, 33, the man who raised the flag over the town
square.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Jabal, a carpenter, was a leader of the demonstration, which
included a half-dozen people holding framed photographs of sons and
brothers held in Israeli prisons and chanting calls for their
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel was forced to admit the Golan is Syrian by those of us
who fought occupation,'' said Abu Jabal, who said he was released
from an Israeli prison two years ago after serving a 12-year
sentence for exploding an Israeli weapons depot on the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Like many young Druze, Abu Jabal, who was born just before Syria
lost the Golan to Israel in the June 1967 war, has heard his father
and the elders of other family clans tell stories of a happier
time, as they recall it, when this farming community was under
Syrian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the land around the town is still blanketed with
bountiful apple and pear orchards, and the warm smell of
woodburning stoves wafts from the houses that cling to the steep
hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents of Majdal Shams and other Druze communities have
relatives in Syria whom they have not seen for more than 30 years.
Their emotional attachment to their Syrian nationality is a
powerful one.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, the demonstration disbanded. The Israeli military
vehicles approached the center of town. And just then, Abu Jabal
climbed the statue and quickly took down the Syrian flag, stuffing
it in a plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   Such a defiant display of Syrian nationalism as raising a flag
could land a Majdal Shams resident in an Israeli jail.
</P>
<P>
   But in some homes in the notoriously insular community of the
Druze, people are less stridently pro-Syrian and more worried about
their future. Some privately express reservations about a peace
process that would place them once again under the authoritarian
rule of Syrian President Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sentiment not often expressed since many fear that
they could be labeled Israeli collaborators when and if the Syrian
government regains sovereignty in the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   This sentiment was expressed, however, in a letter sent to Barak
by Druze Sheikh Muafiq Tarif, an Israeli citizen who lives in the
Galilee. The Israeli Druze leader asked for a committee to be
established ``to discuss the issue of finding a solution to the
problem of those in the Golan who are loyal to Israel and hold
Israeli citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, which was cited in an article in the Dec. 14
issue of the Israeli newspaper Ha'aretz, Tarif said as many as
2,000 of the 18,000 Golan Druze wish to stay under Israeli
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   But Salman Fakhr El-Din, a leader of the Druze community and
director of the Golan Research Unit, which monitors Israeli
broadcasts and newspapers on the occupation of the Golan, says,
``If this feeling exists, I have not heard it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe for one minute we have more democracy in
Israel than in Syria,'' said Fakhr El-Din. ``It's true in Israel
you can shout against the government. But if you are Arab you can't
build a home where you want to, and you are not given the same
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that in Syria opposition to the government is
limited,'' said Fakhr El-Din. ``But at least you can build your
home where you wish and you are sure that when you do so you are
building in a nation that sees you as an equal citizen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
