<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATION WILL EAT UP RETIREMENT FUND FOR DAUGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 9, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My small business is doing well enough to allow me the
opportunity to plan for my two daughters, aged 11 and 6. Their
college costs are covered, due to the goodwill of their
grandparents. So I am attempting to plan not just for my
retirement, but for my daughters as well. My 11-year-old has been
on the business payroll for three years, earning approximately
$2,000 per year. This has been invested in a Roth IRA in Vanguard's
Index 500 fund, with a current value of $7,142. What do you think
of this strategy? What type of lifestyle would this allow when she
is 60 years old if I continue this for 20 or 30 years? I hope to do
the same with my younger child when she is eight years old. Should
her plan be similar?
</P>
<P>
   M.D., Sharon, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I based my calculation on a projection of 10 percent average
annual growth for 25 additional years, which took the account to
$283,122 by the time your older daughter is 36 years old. If the
funds were then left to grow without additional contributions for a
further 24 years, the pool would grow to $2,788,676. Alas, if you
adjust that figure for a presumed 3.5 percent inflation rate over
the course of 49 years, that money would have the buying power of
only a little more than $516,000 in today's money. Put another way,
she might then invest it in a fixed-income portfolio, which would
bring her an annual income stream with the buying power of $33,540
in today's dollars. For many people, that wouldnt represent a
handsome and comfortable retirement, but for almost anybody it
would represent a wonderful start.
</P>
<P>
   One warning: in order to face the taxman with a clean
conscience, I suggest you bend over backward to assure that the
amount of work which your daughters perform to earn that $2,000 a
year is truly worth $2,000, maintaining very careful records to
demonstrate that the work was done and that their remuneration is
in line with (or less than) that of other employees who do similar
work.
</P>
<P>
   I have no quarrel with your choice of investment, and strongly
recommend that you follow precisely the same approach with your
younger daughter. Since her investment time period will be
different, the chances are that the amount of the eventual
accumulation in the two accounts will me somewhat different. But if
you chose a different investment vehicle for each child, there's a
significant chance that it might end up being very different, which
could cause dissension and unhappiness in the ranks. When I was a
boy, my father converted some warrants that came to two of my
sisters and myself into cash, and then reinvested the proceeds. For
one sister and myself, he chose a couple of good old workhorse
industrials, which plodded along predictably and unspectacularly.
But for the other sister, he took a chance on an early mutual fund
that invested in that new fad called television. In a very few
years, one sister was seeing dividends that were twentyfold those
of her siblings. She reminded us about the discrepancy, often. So
for harmonys sake, I suggest absolutely identical investment
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 50-year-old self-employed person with an income of
$40,000 to $45,000, and the only debt I have is a $438-a-month auto
loan. I think I am a fairly typical reader who is starting late
with my retirement portfolio. Starting my IRA about three years ago
I have about $3,500 each in Janus Twenty, Janus Mercury, and Janus
Equity Income funds, contributing $2,000 a year. If I want to
retire between 65 and 70, what advice can you give me to maximize
my retirement savings? Please give me some hope.
</P>
<P>
   P.F., Sandwich, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Using a $42,500 midpoint for your estimated earnings, I
calculate that you are spending 4.7 percent of your earnings on
your retirement portfolio, and 12.4 percent on your wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Do you see something out of whack?
</P>
<P>
   At the rate you are going now, you would have $110,329 in the
IRA accounts by age 65, or $190,453 at age 70, based on a
presumption of average investment returns of 10 percent a year and
continued maximum contributions.
</P>
<P>
   I think that the only hope of a substantial retirement portfolio
which I can hold out is if you fairly dramatically increase your
savings rate -- even to the point of a crash savings program. For
example, if you were to save as much for retirement as you are
spending on your auto, you could accumulate $218,544 after 15
years, or $385,525 after 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Probably that's an unrealistic suggestion, but once you complete
the auto loan contract, perhaps you could resolve to try to make
that car go 200,000 miles, and to put the extra $438 a month into
retirement accounts. In the meantime, you could adopt other savings
disciplines. For one, you might set $42,500 as a base earnings
level and resolve to add any amount that you earn above that figure
to the retirement pool. Another slow-but-steady approach would be
to empty your pocket change into a jug every night, and monthly
empty the jug, roll the coins, and add the money to a retirement
account.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to save money, but all of them require the
will to save and the discipline to stick to whatever program you
establish.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with your choice of funds. The route to
success will be not to gamble on more aggressive investments, to
establish more aggressive savings patterns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I inherited $292,000 last year. My aim is to create a
portfolio that I'll tap for my retirement and the occasional (every
five to ten years) big-ticket item.
</P>
<P>
   The first of these items will probably be the down payment for a
home, which will happen within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   I am 35, single, childless (and don't plan on having children).
I havent set my heart -- or my investment objectives -- on early
retirement. I have two questions.
</P>
<P>
   The first concerns allocating money among several Vanguard
funds. I'm looking to create a portfolio that is about 80 percent
equity and 20 percent bonds. I'm willing to ride out the
vicissitudes of the market and don't plan to tap the interest this
money generates until I retire. I'm pretty thrifty and not very
materialistic, and I think I could live quite comfortably in
retirement on the equivalent of $35,000 a year in today's dollars.
I figure that would be $69,643 to $98,238, depending on whether I
retire at age 55 or 65.
</P>
<P>
   Provided I dont deplete my principal, a relatively conservative
8 percent annual return should supply this, no? To generate this I
plan to put 20 percent in Vanguard's GNMA fund, 50 percent in
Vanguard Index 500, and 10 percent each in its Mid-Cap, Small-Cap
and Total International Index funds.
</P>
<P>
   The second question involves the home down payment. Am I better
off putting, say, $40,000 in a money market fund so that I have
liquidity, or should I just pull the money out of one or more of
the stock funds when I need it? I'm leaning toward the second
option; even after paying the capital gains tax, I think I'd
probably earn more in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   P.T., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start with the second question, which is easier. I
strongly disagree with the idea of putting this money into stock
funds. If indeed there were a long run you might be better off
sticking with stock investments, but when it comes to investing,
two years is a short run, and your problem might just as well turn
out to be how to best take advantage of a trading loss than how to
pay the capital gains you so blithely presume would be in the
cards. If you're sure you'll be buying the home in two years
(rather than sooner), I suggest you put $36,280 in Vanguard's Prime
Money Market fund, counting on average 5 percent interest to get
you to $40,000 after 24 months. Whats the worst that can happen?
</P>
<P>
   Well, if you earned 4 percent instead of 5 percent, you'd have
to dig up about $750 to get to that $40,000 down payment, which
will probably be a can-do situation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I like your idea for investing the major part
of the bequest, especially since you dont seem to be too devoted to
the idea of retiring at age 55. If you were to adopt that target,
and did achieve your target 8 percent average total returns, you
would have $1,191,899. If a fixed-income portfolio yielded 6.5
percent at that time, you would need a little less than $1,075,000
to supply your desired $69,643 annual income stream, leaving you
with but $116,899 left as a capital pool to protect you against
inflation. Your calculations were based on a presumption of 3.5
percent average inflation, and that sum would not be enough to
provide sufficient protection. Remember, the earlier you retire,
the more you need to have on hand to deal with post-retirement
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   True, you would perhaps have the prospect of Social Security in
a decade or so to bail you out, but it doesnt strike me as a
comfortable situation.
</P>
<P>
   If you retired at age 65, on the other hand, the situation would
be quite rosy, with the pool growing to $2,573,266, and only about
$1.5 million of it needed to provide your $98,238 income stream.
The balance would represent plenty of protection, and even more if
you qualified for a Social Security check.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that could upset this rather tidy applecart is
that reference early in your letter to drawing upon the nestegg for
that occasional big ticket item. My suggestion would be that since
your fortunate bequest should allow you not only to buy your first
home, but als to provide a satisfactory retirement, you establish a
modest savings program based on your current earnings, with this
designed to meet the cost of those big ticket items.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
