<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SNOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SNOW FALLING ON CEDARS' IS JUST BEAUTIFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SNOW FALLING ON CEDARS 
Directed by: Scott Hicks 
Screenplay by: Ron Bass and Hicks, based on David Guterson's novel 
Starring: Ethan Hawke, Youki Kudoh, Rick Yune, Max Von Sydow, James
Cromwell, Richard Jenkins, James Rebhorn, Celia Weston, Sam
Shepard 
Running time: 127 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (disturbing war images, sensuality and brief strong
language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somber, velvety, haunting, ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' is a film
with the same gravitational pull as the novel on which it's based _
and the same moral weight, arising from its facing up to the US
internment of Japanese-Americans during World War II. It's a series
of interlocking mysteries that begins in fog with the death of a
fisherman in the Pacific Northwest in 1950. It ends with the
clearing away of actual and metaphorical fog and the unlocking of a
single chamber in a single human heart. In between, it transports
us to a magical world arising from novelist David Guterson's
longtime residence on Bainbridge Island in Puget Sound. The
fictionalized island and its environs, where life gets pretty
primal among the fishing and berry-picking locals, is a vivid
character, too, in a film populated by characters who all leave an
imprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' is the kind of richly layered film
that Hollywood seldom attempts, much less brings off. But it's more
than brought off here in grand, solid style and beautifully crafted
detail. Perhaps the most remarkable achievement of director Scott
Hicks (in his first film since ``Shine'') is his ability to make us
feel the things haunting the island and its Anglo and
Japanese-American populations. The man put on trial for the
fisherman's murder is an angry Japanese-American war veteran whose
return needles the consciences of the locals, who stood by and in
some cases even profited when the Japanese-Americans were rounded
up and shipped off to the internment camps. Although it's never
stated, we feel he's as much on trial for his race, and for the
guilt he triggers, as for the killing of which he's accused.
</P>
<P>
   Several kinds of guilt are held under the microscope here,
including the feelings arising from the thwarted love between the
Anglo son of the island's idealistic newspaper editor and a
Japanese girl who subsequently married the man now on trial. Will
Ethan Hawke's young reporter, coiled inside his own damaged soul,
pursue leads with full diligence, knowing they'll benefit a man he
views as a rival? The ideals of his late father (played warmly,
trenchantly, and with economy by Sam Shepard) are at war with his
unwillingness to let go of his memories and hopes attached to the
woman he loved (Youki Kudoh's Hatsue), but lost because post-Pearl
Harbor racism overwhelmed them. The courtroom issues, personal
issues, and larger social issues swirl transfixingly across the
screen, arising from internal and external sources, flitting
through several time periods.
</P>
<P>
   This resonant film, with its stygian blackness and grave
clarity, and its blanketing snow symbolizing the death of communal
reason and of a couple's love, will impel audiences to reflect as
well on our wartime racism. Even the film's most conventional
aspect, the courtroom drama, is both rock-solid and filled with
immediacy in its ambered way. Max Von Sydow, who plays the shrewd
and humane defense lawyer, and whose weathered face is a map of
human experience, seems the likeliest Oscar candidate in an
excellent cast that ranges from the tormented Hawke to Celia
Weston's aggrieved mother, an embodiment of racism at its most
homespun. There should be more than one nomination for ``Snow
Falling on Cedars.'' Even in this season, more bountiful than most
in films drawn from formidable literary sources, it's second to
none in its ability to specify a world and immerse us in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0096 </DOCNO>
