u i BC-AFRICA-VACCINE-BOS &LR;      01-07 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-VACCINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICA SEEKS ITS OWN AIDS VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ African governments, skeptical of fighting AIDS
with high-cost Western drugs like AZT, have embraced another
scientific strategy in the battle against the epidemic _ the
pursuit of a workable vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Several countries in southern and central Africa are eagerly
collaborating with foreign researchers to create or test
experimental vaccines. Some are even putting up modest amounts of
their own funding for the projects.
</P>
<P>
   The push for a vaccine appeals to government officials who are
bitter about the high cost of foreign drugs and the global
imbalances in AIDS-related research. Most vaccine work is focused
on subtypes of the human immunodeficiency virus that are prevalent
in the Northern Hemisphere, while more than 90 percent of HIV
infections occur in Africa, where different strains flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only practical, affordable means to control our AIDS
epidemic over the long term is by mass vaccination,'' said Walter
Prozesky, head of the South African AIDS Vaccine Initiative,
recently.
</P>
<P>
   But the search for a vaccine poses problems, AIDS experts
caution, both by raising false expectations that a cure will be
available soon and by providing African governments with an excuse
for not implementing proven measures to reduce HIV infections or
break down the stigmas and taboos surrounding AIDS and sexual
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tendency toward magic bullet solutions, and
vaccines are part of that,'' said Mark Lurie, a field scientist at
the African Center for Population Studies and Reproductive Heath in
Mtubatuba, South Africa. ``Vaccine research is a critical part of a
multiprong strategy against AIDS. But we haven't managed to
implement what we know works, so we rely on dreams about what might
be done in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers behind Africa's AIDS epidemic underscore the urgency
of finding more effective interventions. In Botswana, Zimbabwe,
Swaziland and Namibia, one in four adults carries the AIDS virus.
South Africa counts 1,700 new infections each day.
</P>
<P>
   Health ministers of the 14-member Southern African Development
Community, as well as Rwanda and Uganda in Central Africa, pledged
last November to make vaccine research their top scientific
priority in response to the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Most research undertaken by African countries is foreign-funded
and involves partnerships with international scientists. Uganda has
begun the first African trials of a French vaccine tested last year
in the United States. Malawi, Zimbabwe, and Tanzania have joined
hands with the National Institutes of Health in the United States.
South African researchers have teamed up with scientists in North
Carolina and hope to begin human tests next year.
</P>
<P>
   That contrasts with the hostility voiced by some African leaders
to other approaches already available. Most of the governments in
the region refuse to make AZT available, even to prevent
transmission of HIV from a pregnant woman to her fetus, much less
fund their own research to satisfy their doubts about such drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the foreign-made medications is a primary concern,
health officials say. Providing a month-long course of AZT to all
pregnant women _ even at reduced prices offered by the
manufacturer, Glaxo Wellcome _ would deplete government coffers at
a time when health budgets strain to cope with ailments like
tuberculosis, malaria, and malnutrition. Uganda has conducted tests
on an alternative drug called nevaripine, which costs about $4 for
a single-dose treatment for pregnant women, but regional health
ministers say even that is too high.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Bellamy, director of UNICEF, disagrees. ``It is true that
even a $4 drug treatment will challenge the health budgets of many
African countries _ but the cost of failing to introduce this
preventative regimen will be incalculably higher,'' she said
recently. ``If immediate steps are not taken to reduce the risk of
mother-to-child-transmission, already overburdened health systems
will simply be unable to cope with the needs of the huge numbers of
sick and dying young children.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa, the African country most able to afford and
conduct vaccine research, has vowed to have a locally produced
vaccine available by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   That's not much time, even if everything goes well. It took 40
years to develop the polio serum, noted Saladin Osmanov, a vaccine
specialist with the UN AIDS program. Less than a year old, the
South African effort has an annual budget of about $3.5 million _
tiny by international standards.
</P>
<P>
   South Africans are closely watching as a US-made vaccine,
VaxGen's ``Aidsvax,'' undergoes final human trials. But even if it
works, it is designed for HIV subtypes prevalent in the Northern
Hemisphere and would serve only as model for vaccines against
African strains.
</P>
<P>
   Just preparing a community for human testing of a vaccine is no
simple task. Field workers have spent more than a year working in
the South African village of Hlabisa, in the province of
Kwa-Zulu/Natal. The villagers elected a community advisory board to
steer the preparatory work. Local church leaders were brought on
board. Education programs were designed for the schools. The
village had to be mapped, which meant numbering each dwelling. New
health services were introduced, including HIV testing.
</P>
<P>
   All that, without any vaccine worth testing on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vaccine initiative is about more than the vaccine,'' said
Janet Frohlich, the community liaison officer. ``Part of the
process involves educating people about expectations. They have to
understand that they may be looking at a 10-year program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0097 </DOCNO>
