<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HURRICANE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S INTENSITY POWERS `HURRICANE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HURRICANE 
Directed by: Norman Jewison 
Screenplay by: Armyan Bernstein &AMP; Dan Gordon, based on Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter's book, ``The Sixteenth Round'' and Sam
Chatton's and Terry Swinton's book, ``Lazarus and the Hurricane'' 
Starring: Denzel Washington, John Hannah, Deborah Kara Unger, Liev
Schreiber, Vicellous Reon Shannon, David Paymer, Dan Hedaya, Harris
Yulin, Rod Steiger 
Running time: 146 minutes 
Rated: R (language and some violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former New Jersey boxer Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, now 62,
lives in Canada, a free man. How he got there, after being
imprisoned more than 19 years for a triple murder he didn't commit,
is the subject of ``The Hurricane.'' It's a big, old-fashioned
movie that could easily have collapsed under the foursquare weight
of its good intentions. That it doesn't is due largely to the
amazing concentration that Denzel Washington brings to the central
role of Carter. It's an astonishing performance, partly because
it's so devoid of histrionics, and it has Oscar nomination written
all over it.
</P>
<P>
   After a predictably kinetic beginning, in which we see ample
evidence of the knockout punch that made Carter such a formidable
middleweight, Carter himself is dealt a blow that few would have
bet he could survive. He and a fan, John Artis, are convicted of
murder in the 1966 shooting deaths of three people in a bar in
Paterson, N.J., after having first been cleared. Efficiently, the
script shows us what Carter goes in with _ toughness, and the
ability to temper his explosive urges with discipline, acquired in
the Army, where the former gang member learned to channel his fists
into boxing. It would be going too far to say that the real fight
takes place inside Carter, and that it's between rage and
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   What we see instead is something more subtle and more
interesting, thanks to Washington's intensity. Most of the film is
the opposite of an action picture. It's a portrait of stoicism and
self-renewal as Washington's Carter in effect migrates to his own
interior. Drawing upon inner resources isn't a subject to which a
movie camera naturally gravitates, but in Washington's case it
does. The most powerful scene comes when Carter refuses to wear a
prison uniform and insists on retaining his own clothes, even if it
means a stretch in solitary, because in doing so he retains some of
the dignity that has been so rudely stripped from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurricane'' needs the powerful performance it gets from
Washington because, while the other actors throw themselves into
their work with the invigorating knowledge that they are fighting
the good fight, their material is limited and on the simplistic
side. That is even the case with Vicellous Reon Shannon, who plays
the young lawyer-to-be, Lesra Martin, who became not only an
impassioned advocate but a surrogate son. It's Martin, as the
semi-literate protege of a trio of social workers, who gets the
ball rolling when he buys a copy of Carter's book, ``The Sixteenth
Round,'' at a rummage sale, is moved by Carter's story of his
railroading, contacts him, and causes the case to be reopened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurricane'' is the kind of movie that works in bold
strokes and primary colors and leaves little room for shadings. As
the trio of white Canadian activists who throw themselves into
working for Carter's release, Liev Schreiber, Deborah Kara Unger,
and John Hannah are pretty much angels of mercy and nothing but.
The dynamic of their ad hoc family is left unexplored, as is the
fact of Carter's subsequent marriage to Unger's character, Lisa
Peters. Dan Hedaya, a caricature of racism as the cop who makes the
persecution of Carter his life work, does his usual job of making
five o'clock shadow stand for vindictive meanness. Apart from
Washington, only Shannon has any real chance of seeming emotionally
dimensionalized, and he makes the most of it in this film that
clearly sorts out the good guys from the bad.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably the fact that Canada plays such a positive role in
the story of Rubin Carter (he has lived there since his release)
provided added motivation for filmmaker Norman Jewison, who was
born there, and who previously explored race-centric themes in ``In
the Heat of the Night'' and ``A Soldier's Story.'' Not that Jewison
is so xenophobic as to refrain from spotlighting Bob Dylan's song,
``Hurricane,'' on the soundtrack. There's a certain
over-earnestness in this film, and more than a few compromises and
generous helpings of dramatic license. But its celebration of a
spirit that refused to go down for the count is the important thing
here, and Washington gets it shiningly right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
