<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON OF GREAT EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is no time to miss your number.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate earnings season is upon us again and these quarterly
numbers will face particularly close scrutiny. Disappointments,
like a few announced in advance this week, may be dealt with
harshly.
</P>
<P>
   The action begins in earnest next week and will stretch into
early February. For a warm-up, watch how the market treats Lucent
Technologies Inc., following a late warning Thursday that quarterly
results would fail to meet forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The market's new worries over rising interest rates and the
ballooning valuation of some stocks, particularly technology
issues, during the final quarter of 1999 demand strong bottom-line
performance to continue to support share prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's really important to hit the numbers,'' said Stephen
Demirjian, who invests in small stocks at Westfield Capital
Management in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: Fourth-quarter earnings forecasts by brokerage
analysts for companies locally and across the nation are generally
upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind is at our backs right now,'' said Ned Riley, chief
investment officer of State Street Global Advisors. ``The
environment couldn't be any better for most industries.''
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Capital survey of forecasts for earnings among the 100
largest Massachusetts companies each tracked by at least one
analyst, conducted for us by First Call Corp. of Boston, is mostly
rosy. It forecasts profits exceeding those for the same period of
1998 or improvements over year-ago losses in three out of every
four cases.
</P>
<P>
   Among all stocks in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, earnings
will jump by about 17.5 percent for the year, according to Chuck
Hill, director of research at First Call. That's ahead of the 3.7
percent increase in 1998 and the S&AMP;P's historical annual
improvement of about 7 percent. The early forecast for 2000:
profits will rise about 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half the earnings are really pretty much in the
bag,'' said Hill. ``The expectations for the second half are good,
but that's certainly dependent on what the Fed does in the
spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks will remain in the spotlight not only because
of their high prices but also because of their track record
delivering on high hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies in the S&AMP;P 500 will generate annual profit
increases of at least 30 percent for 1999 and earnings will
probably rise about 24 percent in the year ahead, according to
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: There is so little room for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations have been elevated to almost a perfection-type
environment,'' said Riley. ``When there's something less than
perfection, the market is not very forgiving and takes its wrath
out on individual stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   So now those individual companies have to perform again. But
reading the significance of corporate earnings reports for any
single quarter or year-to-year changes can be tricky.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI Inc. of Andover, which owns interests in dozens of Internet
companies, reports wildly varying quarterly profits and losses
based on stock transactions, big investments, and other special
circumstances. Over the last quarter, CMGI spent huge sums on its
AltaVista unit, which it plans to take public this year.
</P>
<P>
   Very young companies, particularly the crop of Massachusetts
firms that launched initial public stock offerings in 1999, often
are expected to post quarterly losses as they build business. In
many cases, the amount of revenues they produce is at least as
important as the bottom line in evaluating progress.
</P>
<P>
   But for most companies, profit numbers speak for themselves and
investors know what they want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric Technology Corp. of Waltham waited until the market
closed on Monday to announce that revenues from an older line of
its engineering software would fall short of expectations and drag
earnings down below forecasts. The immediate reaction: Parametric
shares plunged 20 percent the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, earnings surprises can work both ways. PeopleSoft
Inc. told investors Thursday that its business-management software
products may have generated fourth-quarter results that beat Wall
Street expectations for sales and profits. The stock jumped
immediately and finished Thursday up 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Professional investors such as Demirjian who like smaller
companies said the weeks ahead may be unusually pleasant for some
stocks that exceed earnings forecasts. He said small high-tech
stocks have been clubbed almost across the board this week and
those companies that produce strong profits may look like better
buys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
