<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-0108-     01-07 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-0108-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S WAR BOGS DOWN IN CHECHNYA
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ While Russian leaders make bold predictions of imminent
victory in Chechnya, in reality the fight for control over the
rebellious republic is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military commanders temporary halted the intensive air
and artillery bombardment of the breakaway republic on Friday, but
kept up the ground offensive in the capital Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   An alleged use of chemical weapons by Islamic separatists, which
could harm civilians in the shattered city, led to the decision,
Lt. Gen. Gennady Troshev, deputy commander of Russian forces in the
region, said according to the news agency ITAR-Tass.
</P>
<P>
   But the same allegations have been leveled against the Russian
military by the rebel. Claims on neither side have been verified.
</P>
<P>
   In its three-month-old campaign to subdue rebel troops, the
Russian air force has bombed unrelentingly Chechnya's northern
lowlands, causing mass civilian evacuations, while the
50,000-strong army has romped across the territory of 5,000 square
miles (about half the size of Maryland).
</P>
<P>
   By Christmas, Russian commanders claimed they controlled
two-thirds of Chechnya, including its second-largest city,
Gudermes, and were closing in on Grozny. Generals said they had the
core of the rebel forces, estimated at between 10,000 to 15,000
men, running for mountain hideouts along Chechnya's southern
border, located between the Caspian and Black seas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of Grozny's liberation should take a matter of
days. The question of the liberation of the rest of the Chechen
territory is a matter of weeks,'' said Gen. Valery Manilov, the
first deputy chief of the Russian General Staff.
</P>
<P>
   But what was first painted to be a rout now resembles the same
disastrous war of attrition that killed at least 30,000 soldiers
and civilians during Russia's first Chechen conflict from 1994 to
1996. That ill-fated war which pitted mostly poorly trained and fed
Russian army recruits against hard-nosed Chechen guerrillas who
were fighting from independence from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, the army has run into fierce resistance from
the rebel forces, which appear to have halted the Russian advance
on the rebels' two largest strongholds, Grozny and the mountain
ranges. On Wednesday, the rebels beat the Russian army out of
Alkhan-Kala and another smaller village, which had been under
Russian control for about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the rebels say a ``turning point'' has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``The period of the Russian army's triumphant march through
Chechnya is over,'' said Chechen presidential administration chief
Apti Batalov on Wednesday. ``A turning point in the second war in
Chechnya is about to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   This could mean bad news for Russia's acting president, Vladimir
Putin. The Chechen campaign has brought him power and a wave of
popularity that right now looks strong enough to sweep the
country's presidential election scheduled for March 26.
</P>
<P>
   Putin obviously would like to declare victory in Chechnya before
the elections _ just as the outnumbered rebels would like to turn
the tide of the fighting in hopes ending the conflict before that
time, said Moscow military analyst Pavel Flegenhauer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our dejected and impoverished population wants something to
cheer about. They don't want to look at body bags,'' Flegenhauer
said. ``The longer this goes on, the bloodier it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Russian commanders have blamed their setbacks this week
on severe weather and heavy fog, which have grounded their planes,
the most efficient line of attack against Chechen targets. First
Deputy Interior Minister Valery Fyodorov, whose troops are
spearheading Russian attacks
</P>
<P>
   in Grozny and are bearing the brunt of losses in recent fighting
in the city, announced on Thursday that ``The anti-terrorist
operation is going according to plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even though former Russian president Boris Yeltsin
declared on the same day during a trip to Jerusalem that the
campaign would be over in one month, Fyodorov pointedly would not
give an estimate on the end of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Other Russian officials, meanwhile, shed the bravado and grimly
agree with the rebels' assessment of a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders at the military headquarters in Mozdok,
Russia, some 100 miles north of Grozny, have admitted that rebels
sneaked behind Russian lines and set fire Tuesday to a Russian
field hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have also been mining roads behind Russian lines, and
Russian platoons say ambushes are a ``direct threat.'' Russian
commanders have warned their troops that the rebels may try to send
small groups of saboteurs disguised as civilians into
Russian-controlled settlements, like Gudermes.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, the Associated Press quoted one Russian
paratrooper fighting rebels in the hills saying he expected ``tough
fighting ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be able to defeat the rebels with aircraft and armor.
We will have to go there (into the mountains) on foot. And it will
take a long time,'' said Lt. Col. Mikhail Sukhovskoy, commander of
a paratroop battalion.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' tactics are the same that they used to bring about
an end to the first Chechen War: inflict high casualties on Russian
troops and hope that doing so will bring about a stalemate on the
battlefield and a change of Russian public opinion against the war.
</P>
<P>
   The first war began when Moscow attempted to crush the Chechen
struggle for national independence. When the death toll for the
army reached unacceptable levels, the Kremlin decided to sign a
hastily constructed peace accord just before presidential elections
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim period, Russia did little to rebuild
infrastructure like factories, schools and hospitals destroyed in
Chechnya during the fighting. Unemployment has run high, as has
lawlessness, with a handful of rebel commanders setting up fiefdoms
within the state and ruling with the power of their weapons kept
from the first conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen forces now fighting the Russians are a minority of
the population, a group headed by two leaders, a Chechen named
Shamil Basayev and an Arabian called Khattab, who is a follower of
the Islamic sect called Wahabbism.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three months, the Russian side has refused to begin
peace talks with any Chechen commander or official, including the
elected president Aslan Maskhadov. How much control he wields with
the rebel forces and armed clans is unknown. Putin said this week
that he doesn't
</P>
<P>
   rule out talks, but refused to say whom he would deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Independent observers say the Russian side has no other viable
exit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've started a military campaign, but we haven't defined what
it means to win. Putting a flag in the ground in Grozny won't end
this,'' said Yuri Levada, the head of Moscow's Public Opinion
Institute. ``Putin can't count on this event to end the war. He
must start thinking about talks.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
