<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9448 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-07 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOGUS TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki's political hero, Teddy
Roosevelt, was nothing if not a realist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most successful politician,'' TR once said, ``is he who
says what everybody is thinking most often and in the loudest
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   That remark crossed my mind the other day in New York's Assembly
chamber as I heard Pataki, in his latest State of the State
address, pledge once more to cut taxes _ especially on business and
especially upstate, where job creation lags behind both the rest of
the Empire State and the nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   It was toasty inside the state Capitol's newly restored Assembly
chamber but bitterly cold outside. It'll be a far colder day,
though, before this governor misses a chance to extol the virtues
of tax cuts. And it's not as though New Yorkers can't use them. The
state ranks first in the country in combined per capita state and
local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that New York is well back in the national pack
on state taxes and at the top of the heap in local taxes. New
Yorkers pay two-thirds more than the national average in property
taxes, and cutting state business taxes probably has less to do
with stimulating job creation than a hefty cut in the top bracket
of the state income tax. After all, the people with the power to
make decisions on job creation and business location tend to be
people with high incomes.
</P>
<P>
   But pushing for a cut in income tax rates for the prosperous is
political suicide in a 5-3 Democratic state like New York. You want
tax cuts for the rich, Governor? Hey, here's the door; don't let it
smack you in the butt on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is right when he calls for an end to regressive taxes
like the gross receipts tax on energy use, which afflicts human
beings as well as businesses. This tax murders manufacturing. If
you operate a business in New York where you have to turn on big
machines every day, you know how outrageous electricity costs are.
Part of that is the result of decades of rotten regulation of the
electrical generation industry, but killing this tax won't hurt a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   However, the governor also wants to cut taxes for small
businesses, for farms and for railroads. To the extent that this
stimulates job growth, fine. But tax cuts like this need to be
assessed in context. And the relevant context is that business pays
a far smaller share of the total New York state tax dollar today
than it did a few decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the state budget of 1959-60, businesses directly supplied 25
cents of every state tax dollar while individuals directly paid 36
cents. The rest came from various taxes that affect businesses and
consumers in varying measure. Businesses, for example, pay about 25
percent of New York state's sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Rockefeller thought businesses were paying too much, so
he took action to reduce their share. That trend continued after he
left office, and _ for a variety of complex reasons _ has been
mirrored across the nation. By the New York state budget of
1991-92, the share paid by individuals had gone up 47 percent and
the share paid by businesses had dipped 17 percent. That ratio has
stayed pretty much the same since Pataki was elected in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   What's the point? Simply that cutting taxes to stimulate
economic growth is complicated and that New York's real tax crisis
resides at the local level, in a stunning overabundance of town
halls and school district offices. For historical reasons _ because
of political boundaries created centuries ago to conform to
economic boundaries that no longer exist _ New Yorkers suffer from
having way too much local government killing private sector
employment. In metro Albany alone, a region of not quite 1 million
people, the taxpayers support 770 separate local taxing units.
</P>
<P>
   What's really interesting is that the vast majority of the local
officials in these little, conspicuously redundant governments are
Republicans, members of the political party supposedly most
fervently devoted to tax-cutting. Not if cutting taxes means losing
their lip lock on the public teat, though.
</P>
<P>
   Mention consolidation of local governments or school districts,
and these local Republican politicians howl about the evils of
centralized government in Eastern Europe before communism failed.
They explode with dire warnings that the same horrible thing could
happen in New York if the vestigial local government that pays
their salaries should be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   The sad fact is that politicians never really cut taxes. They
just rearrange them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
