<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, Jan. 8 ,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ President Clinton brought
Israeli and Syrian negotiators together for face-to-face talks
Friday, and presented them with a detailed document as a starting
point for areas of agreement and disagreement between the two
Mideast foes. A week of sensitive talks were expected to pause for
religious observances by both groups on Saturday and resume
Saturday night. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ELIAN _ MIAMI _ The situation continues to be tense in the
wake of the INS decision to return 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to his
father in communist Cuba. Developing. (MWilliams, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA _ MOSCOW _ Two weeks ago, the Russian military
began an all-out aasault on the Chechen capital Grozny stating that
they would take control of the city in two to three weeks. That
didn't happen, and military leaders are coming dangerously close to
having egg on their faces. Worse, the longer the war goes on, the
more it resembles the 1994-96 fiasco. Developing. (Coker, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving spot Fri., Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-DANDO _ LONDON _ Last April, an unidentified killer shot
popular television personality Jill Dando in the face at nearly
point blank range. The shooting took place at the front door of her
apartment in a trendy London neighborhood. Some investigators
believe the 37-year-old star was killed by a stalker, while others
believe she was the victim of a professional hit. While they have
plenty of theories, police have few hard pieces of evidence.
Scotland Yard is sending a team of detectives to the United States
to seek the help of American ballistic and forensic experts.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (i)International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXAMS _ A federal judge in San Antonio is expected to rule
today on a two-year-old suit that alleges Texas' requirement to
pass TAAS to graduate discriminates against minority students. The
ruling could have broad implications, from the root of Texas'
accountability system to the presidential campaign trail. The exam
is a centerpiece of Gov. George W. Bush's education program.
(Kurtz/Harmon, Austin American-Statesman). 30-35.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-DEATH _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Republican lawmakers scrambled
Friday to round up the votes to pass a law that would allow the
state to kill its Death Row inmates quicker, even if it meant
taking a lawmaker away from his sister's funeral. Chartered planes
_ paid for by the state Republican Party _ were dispatched across
the state to bring GOP lawmakers to Tallahassee to vote. One was at
his sister's funeral. Another at the birth of his first child. Two
were ill. Supporters _ who need 2/3 majorities in both chambers to
approve laws that would change court appellate procedures _ say the
average of 14 years of appeals of Death Row inmates is an insult to
their victims and should be shortened to 5. On Thursday, lawmakers
in both chambers overwhelmingly approved
</P>
<P>
   lethal injection as the primary means of execution in Florida,
leaving only Georgia, Alabama and Nebraska as states that require
electrocution as the sole means of execution. (Date/Gelbart. Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FLAGFIGHT _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The South Carolina Heritage
Coalition is planning a big march in support of the Confederate
flag on Saturday, Jan. 8. An advancer on how the march is likely
only to make both sides in the debate dig in their heels. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLU-GEORGIA _ Flu, the last, uninvited guest of the holidays, is
moving into Georgia. In the past two weeks, Georgia was upgraded to
having a ``regional'' problem with the illness - causing almost 8
percent of hospital cases. (Lore, Atlanta journal-Constitution).
22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The CDC is expected to issue state-by-state flu figures
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   GA-TEENDRIVING _ Gov. Roy Barnes elevated the debate over
raising the teen driving age this week by asserting that he
supports the idea of making Georgia teenagers wait until they're 17
to get a driver's license. He says too many teenagers have been
involved in serious accidents at younger ages, and have proven that
there are problems with maturity and experience. Lt. Gov. Mark
Taylor also is receptive to the idea of increasing the driving age,
and a Cobb Republican has introduced a bill to do just that. If
Barnes weighs in to try to push the legislation through, it could
put him on a collision course with House Democratic leaders, who
don't want the change. (Pruitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   SC-GOPDEBATE _ Coverage of South Carolina GOP debate. (Heath,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GOPDEBATE-BAXTER _ Color and commentary from the South Carolina
GOP debate. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 18.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CYBERTERROR _ WASHINGTON _ Seeking to defend America's
cyberspace, President Clinton asked Congress on Friday for $2
billion to safeguard government computers against terrorist attacks
and to protect the nation's online infrastructure, such as power
plants, telecommunications, banking, transportation and emergency
services. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. PLEASE NOTE:
SPORTS STORIES will have an E.T.A. of 9:30 P.M. If news, business
or features stories will move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
