<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Jan. 8:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Shepherdstown, W.Va.) _ Developments: President
Clinton, Prime Minister Barak and Foreign Minister Shara meet. By
David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   ORTHODOX-LEADERS (Bethlehem) _ Patriarchs and politicians
(including Boris Yeltsin) from all the major Eastern Orthodox
churches and nations filed into the fourth-century Church of the
Nativity for a Christmas service that may have been the most
inclusive gathering of Orthodox Christian leaders in modern times.
By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Dateline to kum) _ Deputy Russian commander in
Chechnya tells of command shakeup there; he says Grozny is an
ecological disaster zone because tanks of chlorine have exploded,
and also says that Russian air and artillery attacks have stopped
because of fog. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PRINCE (Alabino, Russia) _ A slice of Russian life: a
prince trying to regain his property 30 miles from Moscow reflects
on Russia today. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NAMIBIA-ANGOLA (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ The death toll in
Namibia is mounting as Angola's protracted civil war spills across
its border. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ An adviser to Pakistan's new
military ruler denies Indian charges, saying instead that Indian
intelligence may have staged the hijacking. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DOCKET (Washington) _ The Supreme Court announces, late
in the day, the list of cases it will take. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TERROR (Washington) _ The White House announces its
proposal for new funds to fight cyber-terrorism. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-ADS (Washington) _ With enlistments plummeting, the Army
dismisses its ad agency, Young &AMP; Rubicam, which created ``Be All
That You Can Be,'' and revamps its ad campaign, saying it will tie
new advertising contracts to performance. All branches of the armed
forces are facing a recruiting crisis. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EDUC (Houston) _ A federal court is expected to rule on a
lawsuit claiming bias in Texas's exit exam, which students must
pass in order to graduate from high school. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-DEATH-PENALTY (Tallahassee) _ Debate on death-penalty
related measures continues in the Florida Legislature. By Sara
Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY (Miami) _ Protests continue over the INS decision to
send young Elian Gonzalez back to his father in Cuba. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   MD-SLAIN-GIRL (Silver Spring, Md.) _ More than 13 years after
6-year-old Michele Dorr ran from her house to play in a backyard
pool, police have found her remains. A former neighbor who was
convicted of killing the girl took police to the gravesite on
Thursday. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   ABC-MINORITIES (New York) _ ABC follows NBC in an agreement to
increase minority hiring, but the coalition that pushed for the
deal is starting to splinter. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MCCAIN-TAX (Washington) _ A comparison of the Bush and
Mccain tax proposals, which have become a central issue in their
increasingly competitive campaigns. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP-VENTURE (Brooklyn Park, Minn.) _ Inching closer to a
decision on running for the presidency, Donald Trump comes to this
suburb to raise money for his strongest supporter, Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-DEBATE (Dateline to kum, S.C.) _ A day after their New
Hampshire, the Republicans candidates debate again, this time in
South Carolina. By Alison Mitchel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ U.S. job growth accelerated at the
fastest pace in five months in December as wages also registered
strong gains, bolstering expectations the Fed will raise interest
rates next month. Nonfarm payrolls grew a surprising 315,000 after
a revised 222,000 increase in November. The unemployment rate was
unchanged at 4.1 percent but only because of a change in the
government's method of making seasonal adjustments; without the
changes the rate would have dropped to 4 percent. Average hourly
wages, meanwhile, climbed 6 cents, or 0.4 percent, to $13.46,
slightly higher than expected. Investors, who apparently factored
in a rate increase, sent stocks higher. Bond prices slipped. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Nasdaq stocks recovered some lost ground
after a three-day slump, led by JDS Uniphase and Qualcomm. At 1:10
p.m., the Nasdaq composite index was up 59 points, the Dow Jones
industrial average up 126 points and the S&AMP;P 500 up 14 points.
European markets were also higher: London up 1.21 percent and
Frankfurt 4.55 percent. In Asia, Japan's Nikkei closed up 0.14
percent, and Hong Kong's Hang Seng ended up 1.67 percent. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   DREAMLIFE-INVEST (Undated) _ What do Tom Brokaw, Andre Agassi
and Joseph Flom, a prominent corporate lawyer, have in common? All
three are among a star-studded cast of investors in an tiny
Internet company called Dreamlife, which is more than half-owned by
Anthony Robbins, the motivational guru. And all three men are
preparing to sell their shares to the public. That decision may be
prudent, given that Robbins, whose Dreamlife stake is worth nearly
$400 million, will need all his motivational magic to save
Dreamlife from becoming a nightmare for investors. By Alex
Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   AUDITORS-STOCK (Undated) _ A folo on reports of rule violations
by accounting firm partners in having investments in companies
audited by their firms. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-INTERNET (Sao Paulo) _ A look at the rising concern over
the concentration of power among a handful of large banks and
telecommunications companies in Brazil's Internet industry, Latin
America's largest. An association of Web access providers is
protesting plans by two prominent banks to provide free Internet
access. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   GRANADA-MERGER (London) _ Granada files with British regulators
to make a takeover offer for either Carlton Communications or
United News &AMP; Media, seeking to break up their $6.5 billion merger.
A battle has begun over which company will control Britain's
largest commercial broadcaster, ITV, which was set up as a
commercial rival to the BBC in the form of 15 regional franchises.
By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis' ``Abroad at Home.''
</P>
