<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9472 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-$ADV0     01-07 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR U.S. TAXPAYER, PRICE OF PEACE IN MIDEAST AT $20 BILLION -
AND CLIMBING
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Jan. 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ President Clinton spent last week
shuttling from Washington to this rustic hamlet on the Potomac,
trying to help broker an end to half a century of Israeli-Syrian
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he focused on the diplomacy of ending war, though,
Clinton began the political work of preparing the American people
for the cost of peace.
</P>
<P>
   For if Clinton succeeds in his highest foreign policy ambition _
the cementing of an overall peace accord between Israel and its
Arab foes _ U.S. taxpayers will get hit with a sizeable bill.
</P>
<P>
   The tab could well top $20 billion, analysts say, to help
strengthen Israeli security and resettle Jewish residents from
lands Israel would relinquish under the group of peace accords
Clinton backs.
</P>
<P>
   And that might be the easy part.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military personnel, possibly even troops, could be deployed
to help police the peace, putting Americans at risk in a region
where suicide bombings and other forms of terrorism have become a
tragic part of the culture.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Clinton's challenge, even as he works to bring the
conflicted parties together around the contentious issues dividing
them, is to convince Americans that the price of Mideast peace is a
cost worth bearing.
</P>
<P>
   That became part of the message last week emanating from every
corner of the administration.
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, the point was made by National Security
Adviser Samuel Berger, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
Pentagon spokesman Craig Quigley and even Clinton himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some costs,'' Clinton told reporters in the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start working on that and figuring out what the
specific jobs are that we would be asked to help finance, whether
we could get any others to help, and over how many years it would
have to be done,'' Clinton said. ``Then I'll have to go talk to the
Congress. And I'm just not in a position to say what dollar amount
I would ask our Congress for.''
</P>
<P>
   The costs of peace, in fact, are a central point of negotiation
in any set of peace talks among the United States, Israel and its
Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Israel received $1.2 billion in U.S. military aid as part of the
interim peace agreements Clinton brokered at the Wye River
Plantation in October 1998 between Israel and the Palestinians. The
Palestinians were promised $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   After President Jimmy Carter brokered peace between Israel and
Egypt in the 1978 Camp David accords, the United States paid
hundreds of millions of dollars to, in effect, compensate Israel
for returning to Cairo's control territory on the Sinai Peninsula
that Israeli troops had occupied for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   All of that is in addition to the roughly $3 billion in U.S.
military and economic aid Israel receives each year.
</P>
<P>
   As the ante for the current round of Israeli-Syrian peace talks,
Barak has asked Clinton for $17 billion worth of military and
resettlement aid in connection with the Syrian portion of the talks
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Peace will require Barak to give back to Syria strategic
territory that Israeli troops seized when the two countries fought
a war in 1967. That territory, the Golan Heights, is now inhabited
by an estimated 16,000 Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll want compensation for every one of those people, and
they'll be asking for compensation in the neighborhood of $1
million apiece,'' said Middle East expert Richard Curtiss, a former
U.S. diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis will also seek compensation, Curtiss said, for the far
greater number _ perhaps 160,000 _ of Jewish settlers in the
occupied West Bank territories Israel is handing over to
Palestinian control as part of its peace agreement with Palestinian
Authority President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is also claiming that giving up the Golan Heights and
large parts of the West Bank have the potential of making the
country vulnerable to Arab attack. In return, Israel is seeking
additional U.S. military aid and security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will want some sort of guarantee that they will remain
superior to any combination of Arab forces after this is over,''
said Curtiss, editor of the Washington Report on Middle East
Affairs. ``We'd be talking about more tanks, improved radar of all
kinds, they might even want to have their own surveillance
satellite over the whole area.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak is also seeking U.S. troops to help police the Golan and
take over the operation of spy stations there that now allow Israel
to eavesdrop on Syrian military movements and operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that isn't on the table,'' Quigley told
reporters at the Pentagon last week.
</P>
<P>
   And, while Quigley insisted that the whole subject of increased
U.S. military aid to Israel is ``a work in progress,'' he made
clear that the role would expand as part of any comprehensive peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's in our nation's interest, it's in the region's
interest, it's in the world's interest to have that part of the
world, the Middle East, be a peaceful place,'' said Quigley. ``And
we, the United States, have made a commitment to do that, to be a
very substantive part of that process.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his case to Congress, Clinton will be aided by the
influential pro-Israel lobby, particularly in a year when all
members of the House and one-third of the Senate face elections.
</P>
<P>
   After 50 years of bloodshed and enmity in the oil-rich Middle
East, the argument in favor of investing in peace seems clear
enough to the people who have looked closely at the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing down tensions in a region of the world that has
something like two-thirds of the world's oil reserves is a good
idea,'' said University of California at Santa Cruz professor Alan
Richards, an expert in Middle East economics.
</P>
<P>
   In a region that's holy to three of the world's great religions,
however, there's an argument that transcends dollars and cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the oldest, nastiest conflicts in the world,''
said Richards. ``It's naive to think that it's going to end, but it
certainly would be criminally negligent not to seize any
opportunity to lessen tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
