<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9503 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CYBERTERROR08-COX     01-07 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTERROR08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON MOVES TO DEFEND U.S. CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    360&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to defend America's cyberspace, President
Clinton on Friday sought $2 billion from Congress in his new budget
to safeguard the nation's key computers against terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to protecting critical federal systems, the new
spending would be used to shield privately owned electrical grids,
telecommunications and transportation networks, banking and
financial institutions, water supplies and emergency services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today our critical systems, from power structures to air
traffic control, are connected and run by computers. We must make
those systems more secure so that America can be more secure,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an age when one person sitting at one computer can
come up with an idea, travel through cyberspace, and take humanity
to new heights,'' Clinton said outside the White House. ``Yet
someone can sit at the same computer, hack into a computer system,
and potentially paralyze a company, a city or a government.''
</P>
<P>
   The request to combat both domestic and foreign cyberterrorism
came with the release, eight months behind schedule, of a
comprehensive ``National Plan for Information Systems Protection.''
</P>
<P>
   In acknowledging that such protection is now lacking, the report
sets out a step-by-step 10-point program to fortify vital
infrastructures against deliberate attack by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Key points of the White House program call for enhancing
research and development to detect and deter attacks, training and
hiring a corps of information security specialists, and launching
further outreach efforts ``to make Americans aware of the need for
improved cyber-security.''
</P>
<P>
   Following up on Clinton's remarks, Commerce Secretary William
Daley noted that ``this is the first time in American history that
we in the federal government alone cannot protect our
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only the government is at risk, Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't hire an army or a police force that's large enough to
protect all of America's cell phones or pagers or computer
networks, not when 95 percent of these infrastructures are owned
and operated by the private sector,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The bid for more spending comes after public and private outlays
of an estimated $100 billion since 1997 to correct the so-called
Y2K bug. Since widespread prediction of massive Y2K disruptions
proved unwarranted, White House officials remain eager to emphasize
that major cyberterrorism issues remain unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   For the current fiscal year, which ends next October, Congress
appropriated $1.75 billion for these initiatives, just $2 million
shy of the administration's initial request. In addition, the
lawmakers approved billions of dollars _ the actual figures remain
classified _ to enable the Pentagon to deploy offensive tools to
wage cyberwars.
</P>
<P>
   According to Richard Clarke, who heads counter-terrorism efforts
at the National Security Council, the defensive elements of the
cyber equation cover a wide range of threats ``from the teenage
hacker who sort of joy-rides in cyberspace, up through industrial
espionage, up through fraud and theft, and up at the far end of the
spectrum to another country using information warfare against our
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware now, over the course of the last two years, that
several other nations have developed offensive information warfare
units, organizations, tactics, doctrine and capability,'' Clarke
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean they're going to use them, but it means that
they're developing them, they're getting better all the time,'' he
said. He declined to name any of the countries.
</P>
<P>
   A 33-page summary of the cyberspace protection report can be
downloaded from the White House Internet site (www.whitehouse.gov).
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
