<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN08-CO     01-07 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: When age and driving speed merge
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I'll be 59 this month, and I'm slowing down. In
the process, I'm running the risk of getting run-down.
</P>
<P>
   But that's my New Year's resolution, to drive no faster than 62
mph on the highway, so as not to outpace my aging reflexes.
</P>
<P>
   What I'm finding out, it isn't always easy to stay under the
speed limit. There are limits to what other drivers will stand for.
</P>
<P>
   Easing along at 62 mph on a Texas two-lane blacktop where the
law allows 70 mph, and you'd think I was leading a parade _ all
those cars and trucks backed up behind me.
</P>
<P>
   But they aren't waving and smiling like people in a parade. If
anything, they're shaking their fists.
</P>
<P>
   A speed limit of 70 mph means you can probably push it as high
as 75 mph without getting the attention of the highway patrol. Fact
of the matter, 62 mph was my personal speed limit when the signs
said 55.
</P>
<P>
   All my years, I've driven too fast. Blame it on my upbringing.
In the '50s, when I was a teenager, 80 or 90 mph was considered
cruising speed.
</P>
<P>
   I never will forget one time when I was picking up a date, being
quizzed by her father about my driving habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you're careful on the road,'' he said, sternly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, don't worry, sir,'' I said, honest and forthright young
lad that I was. ``When I have a girl in the car, I never drive over
80.''
</P>
<P>
   The man started sputtering, his face flushed and his neck veins
bulging, and was in the process of getting out of his chair with
what appeared to be the most violent of intentions when his wife
intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, now,'' she said, shushing her husband and shooing us
toward the door. ``I'm sure you're a very responsible young man.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember thinking at the time, ``What's wrong with him?'' But
that's what you get for being honest and forthright, and stupid.
</P>
<P>
   It's taken me a long time time to wise up.
</P>
<P>
   I was at my worst at middle-age and driving a Corvette. That car
was like a wild woman _ she'd do anything you had the nerve to ask
of her.
</P>
<P>
   There was one particular piece of highway, downhill onto a long,
flat stretch where you could see for a mile or more. The Corvette
made it feel like you were coming off a ski jump.
</P>
<P>
   One time I topped 130 mph before chickening out and easing off.
I never did find out exactly how fast that car would go. Whatever
it was, it was too fast for me.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, speed is relative. You go 500 mph in a jetliner and
it's no different from sitting at home in front of the TV. And I
have a friend my age who races motorcycles at 150-plus mph, which
must seem like something akin to warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   But all that's now behind me, along with the line of cars
wanting to pass. No matter. I'll smile and wave even if they won't.
</P>
<P>
   Like the bumper sticker says, honk if you love Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
