<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SOUTHWEST-AIRLINES-HN     01-07 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHWEST-AIRLINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AIRPORT SEES SOUTHWEST ARRIVAL AS HARBINGER OF LOWER FARES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KERI P. MATTOX  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Three months after Southwest Airlines began
serving Bradley International Airport in Hartford, Conn., passenger
traffic has soared 30 percent and fares on other airlines have
dropped by as much as 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The impact was so immediate, Hartford officials dubbed the
results the ``Southwest Effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Now officials at Albany International Airport hope to duplicate
that success when the no-frills, discount carrier begins service in
early May.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of intense negotiations, Southwest added
Albany to its 55-city roster Thursday. An announcement on the
number of daily flights and four destination cities is expected
next week. Based on Albany International's most popular routes, the
cities could include Orlando, Chicago and Baltimore/Washington
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Airport and local officials, who toured the still-unopened $6.2
million terminal expansion into which Southwest will move this
spring, expect that the airline's arrival will mean lower fares,
more jobs and new businesses for the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic impact of this decision is immense,'' said State
Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, one of several key political
leaders who lobbied to land the Dallas-based airline. ``It can
literally change the complexion of a community.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwest began service to Bradley International in Hartford on
Oct. 31. Within a month, the airport topped the 600,000-traveler
mark for the first time. While Southwest flew nearly 60,000
passengers during its first month, other major carriers also saw a
healthy boost in their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines like American, Continental, TWA and United had
passenger numbers almost 50 percent higher than in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although numbers for December are not yet available, Bradley is
on pace to top 6 million passengers in 1999 _ another record.
</P>
<P>
   Fares on all airlines at Bradley have plummeted as carriers try
to compete with Southwest's budget prices. Southwest introduced
with a $65 one-way fare from Hartford to Baltimore/Washington _ 76
percent lower than competitors' fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think once it hits and they realize what this means for
fares, we'll be really busy,'' said Theresa Beverly, owner of
Empress Travel in Latham, N.Y. With fares out of Hartford so low,
Beverly always prices flights for her customers out of both Albany
International and Bradley International. About half of those buying
tickets opt to drive the 108 miles to Hartford, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But that will change once service begins in May, Beverly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have those kind of air fares, people will definitely fly
out of Albany. There will be no reason not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials hope that Southwest, the nation's largest
discount carrier, can bring lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Another discount carrier, Shuttle America, which began service
at Albany International in April, was able to bring down fares when
it moved in, but has since raised its prices and lightened its
flight schedule because of low demand.
</P>
<P>
   Flights to Buffalo started at $49 each way, but are now up to
$79 for the 14-day advance ticket. Ticket prices on other airlines,
however, have fallen to meet the prices offered by the smaller
Shuttle America.
</P>
<P>
   The airport also is expecting the number of travelers to take
off with the anticipated crush of Southwest passengers. Albany
International, like Bradley, was on track to reach record numbers
in 1999 _ almost 1.2 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot wait. All the airlines have dropped their air fares
out of Hartford,'' Beverly said. ``That's the great thing, it's not
just Southwest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1509EST &QL; 
