<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9522 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-PHIL-JACKSON-HNS &LR;      01-07 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHIL-JACKSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAKERS COACH STILL CONNECTS TO HIS DAYS IN THE TRENCHES OF
CONTINENTAL LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK SINGELAIS  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Before Phil Jackson ever worked in the
state-of-the art Staples Center in Los Angeles, he froze in the
drafty Washington Avenue Armory in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   And before he became the intellectual leader of the six-time NBA
champion Chicago Bulls, Jackson tasted a title with the 1984 Albany
Patroons, who reigned atop the Continental Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he still harbors a special place in his heart for
that CBA title, which helped convince him that he made the right
career choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for us, it was important for me,'' Jackson
said recently. ``I was just in the process where I was concerned
whether coaching was going to be something I was going to do or not
do. Or if I was going to be any good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those doubts have long since melted away. When the curtain fell
on the Michael Jordan era in Chicago, Jackson had in his nine
seasons with the Bulls compiled the best regular-season (.731) and
playoff (.730) winning percentages of any coach in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism that Jackson was simply along for the ride as
Jordan and Scottie Pippen carried the Bulls, so far the 54-year-old
coach has duplicated his success with the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have the league's best record at 26-5 (.839) in
Jackson's first year and he was named IBM Coach of the Month for
December. It appears his cerebral approach to the game has unified
a team that was known for clashing personalities (Shaquille O'Neal,
Kobe Bryant) and tuning out coaches (Del Harris, Kurt Rambis).
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had to prove himself to us because he already proved
himself,'' Lakers forward Robert Horry said. ``You had only two
guys on (the Bulls), or three when (Dennis) Rodman was there, that
guys really respected. The rest of those guys, nobody really
respected. But he got all of them to play above and beyond their
potential. Guys always had respect for him. When he first came
here, guys didn't say much to him, but he's a likeable guy. He's
cool, so guys started to warm up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool'' was the same adjective used by Derrick Rowland, who
played for the Patroons during all five of Jackson's seasons there
from 1982-87.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil was just a great guy to play for,'' said Rowland, the
franchise's all-time leading scorer. ``He understands a lot of the
dynamics of the game, the dynamics of people and brings them
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the hardships made it difficult to build a winning
team in Albany. First, there was the frigid atmosphere of the
Armory. While Jackson maintains it was the perfect facility for a
CBA team, it got so cold during practices that players often wore
their sweats and mittens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to talk our commander of the Armory into keeping the
balls in a warm spot in the ticket office so that the guys wouldn't
have to use balls that were 50 degrees, because that was the
temperature in the building,'' Jackson recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we had to always go out and sweep the floor and mop the
court because they used it for everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were also the road trips. Jackson drove the team van to
places like Toronto or Bangor, Maine. And the Patroons only took
nine players on road trips because of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult,'' he said. ``We'd play four games in four
nights on some road trip out West. We fly out to some place, grab a
van and then drive to wherever. You'd get four or five hours of
sleep at night. It was almost impossible to win on the road. But
the players all performed very well. I was impressed by their
cohesiveness, their desire to win. They were motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Jackson felt the egalitarian salary structure of the
Patroons led to success. Married players were paid just $25 more
per week than single players. Nobody was treated above the rest of
the team and players usually didn't grumble about playing time,
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really kind of a taught thing,'' he said. ``We talked
these guys into that. We talked them into sharing time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was former Patroons owner Jim Coyne who gave Jackson his
first head coaching job. It almost never happened. When the
Patroons got off to an 8-15 start in the 1982-83 season, coach Dean
Meminger was fired. Coyne first looked at former UCLA star Henry
Bibby (now the USC coach), but Bibby wasn't available.
</P>
<P>
   Then Coyne called Jackson, who was out of basketball after a
playing career with the New York Knicks and a stint as an assistant
with the New Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Phil how things were going, and I told him I just
wanted him to finish out the year and see if he liked it or not,''
Coyne recalled. ``He told me to call back in an hour, and when I
called back, he said, `I'll be there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Fate is a funny thing,'' Coyne said. ``It's just being in the
right place at the right time. If I didn't make the phone call,
maybe fate would have turned out a different way for Phil and he
might not have gotten back in basketball the way he did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Known as something of a middle-aged hippie, Jackson lived in
Woodstock during his Patroon tenure. He still remembers the one-way
length of his commute _ 47 miles.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a much longer journey to the riches of the NBA. He
recalled making $17,500 in the CBA. The Bulls hired him as an
assistant under Doug Collins in 1987. When Collins was fired two
years later, Jackson ascended to the head position.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson earns $6 million per year with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said motivating players hasn't changed that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still playing for the group, I think,'' he said. ``It's
still playing for your team. It's still a desire to win and play
hard every time you're on the floor. I think it's easier at this
level because of the audience and television that comes with this
game to motivate players, and the fact that their life is so much
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Ron Harper has enjoyed playing for Jackson so much, he
followed him from the Bulls to the Lakers. He's become accustomed
to Jackson traditions such as handing out books to players on road
trips to take their minds off basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who knows the game, who has played in this
league,'' Harper said. ``He's a guy we have fun with. I think he
knows me and I know him. We (the Lakers) have a long way to learn,
that's for sure. Our team is off to a fast start, but we have a
long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   And surely, Jackson has come a long way. It's been 13 years
since his last CBA game, and the Patroons are only a memory, moving
to Hartford, Conn., in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But the days of driving vans, sweeping floors and negotiating
player contracts haven't left Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely who I am,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
