<HEADLINE>
REGAINING DRIVE AFTER THE HOLIDAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With all the holiday hoopla over, it's a little
depressing to be back at work.
</P>
<P>
   That's not at all unusual this time of year, but the malaise
seems to be especially strong this year. All of a sudden, the
parties, the fun and the food celebrating the new century have come
to a screeching halt.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a lot of other excitement looming either. The
University of Wisconsin has won the Rose Bowl, Y2K worries turned
out to be one big bore and warm weather is a long way off. How
excited, after all, can you get about Valentine's Day?
</P>
<P>
   And the new millennium didn't exactly make folks feel like
Masters of their Universe. All the talk about the best of this and
the best of that during the 20th century seemed to remind many of
us that we're just a cog in the wheels of history.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't help that half the country seems to be suffering
from a lingering bronchitis _ in my case, I have developed an
addiction to NyQuil _ or a nasty case of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   During the holidays we tend to refocus on what's important in
our lives, like family and children, said Greg Nakanishi, president
of GN Resources, a human resources consulting firm in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For Nakanishi, who spends a lot of his life working with
charities, the holidays are a time to help others. He recalled the
good feeling he had as he spent Christmas Eve with his family
serving free food to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we come back in January, the old reality hits us,''
he said. ``Then you get back and you have to go to this meeting and
that meeting and you wonder _ does it make a difference?''
</P>
<P>
   So many people were pushing to overcome Y2K problems and
complete their year-end goals that folks feel kind of spent, said
Charlie Rhoads, managing partner of Vandaveer-Rhoads, a consulting
firm in Houston that specializes in helping companies change their
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   He likened the sensation to playing in top form against a superb
basketball team, then playing badly against _ and losing to _ a
weak competitor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ESTABLISHING A GOAL HELPS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So how can you get that jump-start to get going again?
</P>
<P>
   Give yourself a goal to meet, said Rhoads. The day-to-day stuff
is hard to do after doing a big deal like making it through Y2K
problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's human nature to rest on your laurels and slide a little, he
said. It's the time after a big victory _ like a great board
presentation or implementing a new computer system that worked _
that makes someone the most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers get jealous, and that's when they stab the new
golden-haired man or woman in the back or knock the legs out from
under him or her by working hard themselves.
</P>
<P>
   People need to get their momentum going before they're
threatened by someone else, he said. If you have a good victory on
Wednesday, present yourself a big challenge _ with specific
deadlines _ on Friday. That will get your adrenaline going.
</P>
<P>
   A good leader will recognize the human instinct to float and
make sure to set challenges and deadlines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoads said it would be easy to deliver a big project on a
Tuesday, then drift the rest of the week by going to long lunches
and shopping excursions. But if he has another deadline on Friday,
Rhoads said, he knows he'll push to finish the next project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work at a pace at which we think we can get away with,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A CALENDAR IS A GOOD TOOL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting goals is important to getting a jump-start, said
Nakanishi. Focus on just a few things and make an action plan.
</P>
<P>
   It's also helpful to buy a calendar to better plan your time, he
said. And use the slowness of the New Year to reconnect with people
you haven't talked to in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some folks say they're not depressed. In fact, they
report that they are actually thrilled to be back at work.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Jeanneret, an industrial and organizational psychologist
with Jeanneret &AMP; Associates, returned to Houston this week after
spending New Year's Eve on a Caribbean cruise. Jeanneret said he
thought on the ship about how much he was looking forward to coming
back to work. It might be guilt, he said, but he reports not one
speck of sadness, much less malaise.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanneret said he has consulting proposals floating about, and
companies have money to spend on consultants.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great time, he insisted. That may be true, but it will
take many of the rest of us a few more days to feel as chipper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
