<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD OL' DAYS REALLY NOT SO GOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM BARLOW 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gloom and doom. Gloom and doom. People gripe at the news media
for concentrating on them.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason. Things are supposed to go well. We focus on
the unusual _ when they don't. People also like to read, listen and
watch gloom and doom. For proof of that statement, keep an eye on
the bestseller book lists. There's generally at least one book full
of that emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because of that focus we often lose sight of the real
advancements being made. The Cato Institute, a free-market think
tank in Washington, D.C., recently collected an astounding set of
figures about progress. They compared where we are now, with
(mostly) the beginning of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the changes in the past 100 years in the
United States in health and safety trends.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average lifespan increased by 30 years, from 47 to age 77.
</P>
<P>
   _ Infant mortality per 1,000 live births decreased by 93
percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heart disease deaths were cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   _ From 1977, when we first started keeping reliable records,
five major air pollutants have decreased significantly: sulfur
dioxide, 58 percent; nitrogen oxides, 27 percent; ozone, 30
percent; carbon monoxide, 61 percent; lead, 97 percent. Most
problems meeting air pollution standards today don't come from
increasing pollution, but from a tightening of those standards over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Accidental deaths decreased by 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FINANCIAL CONDITIONS IMPROVED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What about how we were financially better off in the good old
days? Not true.
</P>
<P>
   _ The per-person Gross Domestic Product, a measure of the wealth
created, is almost seven times higher today than in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   _ Manufacturing wages, in today's dollars, went from $3.43 per
hour in 1900 to $12.47 now. And that doesn't include the growth in
fringe benefits such as vacation, medical insurance, retirement and
the like.
</P>
<P>
   _ Household assets, everything from the value of our homes to
our personal possessions, are seven times greater.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the beginning of the century, 40 percent to 50 percent of
all Americans had income levels that classified them as poor _
depending upon the measurement used. Today, that's down to between
10 percent and 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Home ownership increased by 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ From 1980, personal computer ownership went up 44 times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Household incomes of blacks increased 10-fold. Although blacks
still earn less than whites, the gap has decreased. In 1900, blacks
earned about 40 percent of whites. It is now 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ The price of wheat, measured by the amount of farmer hours it
takes to produce it, decreased 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Computer speed has jumped 3 million percent since computers
were introduced.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of patents granted each year increased by a factor
of six.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUALITY OF LIFE ALSO BETTER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How about the quality of life in the past 100 years? Here are
the facts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average length of the workweek decreased by 30 percent,
falling from 66 hours to 35 hours. And because of more holidays and
a shorter work week, the average number of hours worked in a year
is half of what it was in the latter part of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   _ The percent of workers on the farm fell by 93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Television ownership went from nothing, of course, to almost
universal. Although I must admit I'm not sure if that's a plus.
</P>
<P>
   _ The percentage of households with electricity went from 10
percent to near-universal. At the same time, the average American
in 1900 had to work six times as many hours to pay his electricity
bill than does a worker today.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of telephone calls per capita per year increased
5,600 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of households with cars increased 90-fold.
</P>
<P>
   _ The percentage of people completing college is four times
higher. Today more people (28 percent) have bachelor's degrees than
the number of Americans who held high school degrees in 1900 (22
percent).
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of women with bachelor's degrees increased by half
with women now earning almost 60 percent of such degrees. Women
with comparable work and work histories comparable to men's earn 98
cents for every dollar men do.
</P>
<P>
   All this doesn't mean we've reached perfection. But the
measurable aspects of life shows lots of improvement, with more
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I'm an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
