<HEADER>
A9552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MUTTER-PHILHARMONIC-N     01-07 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTTER-PHILHARMONIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUTTER SERIES COVERS THE CENTURY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The violin, surrogate of choice for the singing human
voice during the first 200 years of its existence, entered the 20th
century both as friend and enemy. Keepers of the Romantic flame
were grateful for its lyrical qualities. Makers of a new order were
mistrustful. The instrument has endured, indeed prospered, because
the music that Mendelssohn, Mozart, Bach and Tchaikovsky wrote for
it has endured as well. Newer composers deeply suspicious of older
forms of sentiment have explored its rhythmic and percussive
qualities with wary enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Anne-Sophie Mutter is bringing us a brave series that will show
how the violin has fared during the last 100 years: recitals at
Carnegie Hall and three orchestra concerts with the New York
Philharmonic under Kurt Masur, the first of which was played at
Avery Fisher Hall on Thursday night. Offered was a heavy
concentration of Lutoslawski, some Leonard Bernstein and an
orchestral medley of Gershwin's ``Porgy and Bess'' as a tasty
dessert.
</P>
<P>
   The other events next week bring music by Sibelius, Berg and
Wolfgang Rihm. The Lutoslawski pieces _ in fact, a single concerto
made from three separate items _ represent the old ways carried
forward: The Partita in five movements and ``Chain 2,'' the two
bound together by the quiet ``Interlude,'' are expansive personal
statements exploited by a solo instrument engineered for
soul-searching. Depending on your musical politics, the composer
has carried history forward in orderly fashion, or else he has been
a nurse tending an elderly patient on life support.
</P>
<P>
   What this music brings us, and what a lot of 20th-century music
does not, is an intimate passion, an enthusiasm for mystery and an
unashamed intoxication. In matters of harmony and format,
Lutoslawski has moved on. Tonality is often abandoned, though not
rigorously in the manner of Schoenberg. The composer does not
reject the Romantic vocabulary as so many did; he simply adds to
it. Two movements of the Partita expand freedom to the point of
indeterminacy. Elements are allowed to float freely from one
another and to enjoy the chance collision. Radically new in its
20th-century zeal for experimentation this music may well be; but
when one thinks about it, it is also the Romantic impulse carried
to its natural conclusion. For here is freedom supervised; the
voice is allowed its uniqueness, and yet the composer is there in
the background to shelter it from chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Movements of ``Chain 2'' treat the violin with more abruptness,
even brutality. These are traits found also in Bernstein's
``Serenade for Violin, Strings, Harp and Percussion.'' The concept,
a musical version of Plato's ``Symposium,'' is a little stagy, but
the music is fresh, as only his early music was. There is in
Bernstein Lutoslawski's fascination with the violin's gifts of
song, here with a scrubbed-clean quality, but also a willingness to
subject an old instrument to the violences of modern American
exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mutter was a wonder of adaptability. The ability to play
right notes and exact rhythms with correct intonation was taken for
granted. Lutoslawski and Bernstein could not be two more different
spirits, and yet Ms. Mutter took the pulse of each with equal
precision. It is meant as a compliment to say that over a two-hour
stretch one often forgot about the violinist altogether in favor of
what she was playing. Her series is just one more example of
music's sudden rush to celebrate its own time.
</P>
<P>
   Program illustrations for these Fisher Hall concerts are not shy
about exploiting Ms. Mutter's glamour, but if such as this draws
the wary into the concert hall let her be as glamorous as she
chooses. Masur's orchestra, with its equally easy mastery of
several styles, turned at the end to Robert Russell Bennett's
``Symphonic Picture'' of the ``Porgy and Bess'' music. A very
central European conductor wisely conducted as little as possible,
turning the music over to players who have its qualities in their
genes.
</P>
</TEXT>
