<SLUG> BC-NAMIBIA-ANGOLA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 ANGOLA'S DEADLY CIVIL WAR SPILLS INTO NAMIBIA  (ART ADV: A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The death toll in Namibia is
mounting as Angola's protracted civil war spills across its
southern border, resulting in killings, kidnappings and other
violence on Namibian soil.
</P>
<P>
   This week, 10 people were shot to death in the northeastern
corner of Namibia, near the Angolan border, including three French
tourists and seven Angolan rebels. On Saturday, Jan. 1, 20 Namibian
villagers in the region were reportedly abducted from their homes.
And last month, Angolan rebels attacked a Namibian police camp with
mortars and grenades, killing one officer and wounding three
others.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes, which the Namibian government has blamed on Angolan
rebels, follows the government's decision last month to allow
Angola to use Namibia as a staging ground for troops in their
26-year battle against the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, or Unita.
</P>
<P>
   Unita officials promptly vowed to retaliate against Namibia. The
resulting clashes between the rebels and soldiers from Angola and
Namibia have so destabilized the territory between the countries
that the U.S. Embassy in Namibia has warned tourists against travel
in that region.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of the Angolan conflict beyond its borders is yet
another worrisome example of how the bitter conflicts of central
Africa continue to ensnare many peripheral countries.
</P>
<P>
   Namibia, Angola and Zimbabwe are already deeply involved in the
fighting in Congo, where they have provided armed support to
President Laurent Kabila in his struggle against rebels there.
</P>
<P>
   And diplomats and government officials here in South Africa, who
have unsuccessfully lobbied for peace in Congo, are watching the
widening conflict in Angola with growing uneasiness. They are
urging the Angolans to negotiate a settlement that might bring
stability to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to sit around a table and come to terms with their
situation for the sake of peace, not only in Angola, but also in
the region,'' said Daniel Ngwepe, a spokesman for South Africa's
Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But both Angolan and Namibian officials have dismissed the idea
of withdrawing from the conflict. The Angolan army has made
significant gains against Unita in recent months and seems
determined to crush the rebels once and for all. And Namibian
military officials have argued that Unita no longer poses a serious
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care about Unita; we're not scared about Unita,''
said Maj. Gen. Martin Shalli, the chief-of-staff of the Namibian
Defense Force, in a recent telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to give Angola whatever assistance they want,''
Shalli said.``Angola's our ally, our friend. And we as a country
have our own national interest and security interest. We cannot
have this problem on our doorstep, in our backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's shootings of the French tourists seemed to stiffen
the Namibian government's resolve. The family of five was ambushed
on Monday by about 10 gunmen in green uniforms on the Trans-Caprivi
highway about 125 miles east of the Angolan border. The Namibian
government promptly blamed the attack on the Angolan rebels from
Unita, who have denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The parents, Claude and Brigitte Bidoin, were wounded in the
ambush. Their three children _ Cecile, 10, Aurelie, 15, and
Michael, 18 _ were killed.
</P>
<P>
   And as the killings made banner headlines on the front pages of
newspapers in Britain and France, raising fears that Namibia's
tourism industry might be damaged, the Namibian army stepped up its
attacks. On Wednesday, Namibia reported that it had killed seven
Unita fighters and captured four more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to fight until all Unita members are out of
Namibia,'' Shalli told local reporters this week.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts warn that that will not be easy. Despite the
Angolan government's gains, Unita remains a force to be reckoned
with, and many believe the violence is unlikely to stop soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's likely to continue,'' said Richard Cornwell, a
South African analyst at the Institute for Security Studies in
Pretoria, which closely monitors the Angolan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Namibia has been persuaded that Unita is on its last legs, but
we think Unita still has sizeable forces in the field,'' Cornwell
said. ``They've gone back to their guerrilla mode and they're the
finest guerrilla army in Africa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
