way off. How excited, after all, can you get over Valentine's Day?
Charlie Rhoads, managing partner of Vandaveer-Rhoads, a consulting
firm in Houston that specializes in helping companies change their
cultures, believes so many people were pushing to overcome Y2K
problems and complete their year-end goals that workers are
fatigued. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WHIP-RACE (Washington) _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi of California, who
wants to be the next Democratic whip, or third in the party's House
hierarchy, is following a lesson taught by Texas Rep. Tom DeLay,
the Republican whip. As DeLay did in 1994, she is raising money and
so far has quietly doled out nearly $500,000 to her party's
candidates, mostly women, minorities and those in tight House
races. If Democrats grab control of the House, Pelosi hopes to call
in her chits and be elected whip by grateful colleagues. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-STAKES (Washington) _ Following a lackluster
performance during the first part of the 106th Congress,
Republicans are hoping for a better review in this year's session
as they head toward the most important election of their six-year
tenure as the majority party on Capitol Hill. The stakes are high.
The Democrats have to gain only five more seats in the 2000
elections to retake control of the House, which the Republicans
took over in 1994 for the first time in 40 years. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT-AGE (Washington) _ This year marks the dawn of a new
retirement age. Those turning 62 in 2000 who want to retire early
will receive reduced benefits. In 2003 when they become 65, they
won't be able to get full retirement benefits until they are 65 and
two months. The eligibility age gradually moves up to 67 in 2027.
The new retirement age is part of Congress' 1983 effort to shore up
the federal retirement system. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
