<HEADER>
A9562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BUTTERFLY-OPERA-REVIE     01-07 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTTERFLY-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN OPERA REVIVES `MADAMA BUTTERFLY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all its familiarity, Puccini's ``Madama
Butterfly'' is a hard opera to cast. When we meet her in Act One,
Cio-Cio-San, the title character, is a worldly 15-year-old,
overcome with love for Lt. Pinkerton, the hearty American naval
officer who has swept into her life and hastily arranged a
marriage, rescuing her from a humiliating life as a geisha.
</P>
<P>
   To portray her, a soprano must have fragility and tender
lyricism in her singing and demeanor. Yet Cio-Cio-San has had a
hard youth, which is reflected in the music. Whole stretches of the
role require penetrating tone and the stamina to soar. The great
Mirella Freni refused repeated requests to undertake it until
Herbert von Karajan, who had Svengali-like power over sopranos,
persuaded her to at least record the opera with him.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Opera revived Giancarlo del Monaco's
scrupulously realistic 1994 production on Thursday night, and
naturally the focus of attention was the French soprano Sylvie
Valayre, who made her Met debut as Cio-Cio-San. Local operagoers
may remember Ms. Valayre from her intrepid performance last year in
the taxing role of Helene in Verdi's ``Jerusalem'' with the Opera
Orchestra of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Valayre has been all over the soprano terrain in her choice
of roles: Norma, Tosca, Salome, Abigaille in ``Nabucco.'' Her
performance on this occasion suggested that she is essentially a
lyric soprano who has by sheer determination boosted her sound to
sing these heavy roles.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatically, she made a lovely, vulnerable and, as the tragedy
unfolds, impassioned Cio-Cio-San. Her singing was confident and
often striking. She does not have a lustrous sound. A certain
stridency of tone may be the result of her taxing repertory. When
she contained her voice and shaped delicate phrases in her middle
range, her singing had poignancy and beauty. Her high notes came
with effort, but she did not shrink from them. Overall, if this was
not an exceptional Cio-Cio-San, she made the role work on her own
terms. She certainly reached the audience, who rewarded her with a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian tenor Vladimir Galouzine, who sang Pinkerton, made
his Met debut in 1994 singing impressively as Sergei in
Shostakovich's ``Lady Macbeth of Mtsensk,'' and he will return in
that role this season. His Russian voice, with its husky cast and
slightly nasal tone, is not ideal for Puccini. He sings with power
but not much subtlety. On Thursday night, his top notes were
notably shaky. Still, he has the breath control to project long
lines, and there was no lack of energy or ardency in his portrayal.
</P>
<P>
   The mezzo-soprano Jane Bunnell was a vocally strong and
sympathetic Suzuki. The tenor Bernard Fitch was a suitably slick
Goro, and the baritone William Shimell was an elegant Sharpless,
the well-meaning but weak-willed American consul.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss-born conductor Marcello Viotti, recently appointed
principal conductor of the Bavarian Radio Orchestra, made his Met
debut. After a nervous start in which the strings sounded a bit
scrambled, he conducted with a just balance of vigor and pliancy.
With a new cast and conductor, there was a gratifying sense that,
whatever the results, this repertory staple had been approached
afresh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9563 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-HOME-LEARNING-     01-07 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-HOME-LEARNING-$ADV09-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME LEARNING: SEA MONKEYS DO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An intensifying debate going on in our household is whether or
not to get a dog. My 11-year-old son, Roy, has become increasingly
adamant, while my wife for some reason thinks she will be stuck
with all the work. Guy, our 9-year-old, wants a snake. My tentative
step in the direction of pet ownership _ as well as to create
educational adventures at home _ is to send away for sea monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Remember sea monkeys? They have been around as commercial
products for at least 40 years, first as food for tropical fish,
then as pets in their own right, and lately as learning tools. They
are actually brine shrimp, and enjoyed an instant of fame in the
1960s, when John Glenn took a jarful into space to amuse his
children back on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   What is new about the sea monkey enterprise is the way the tiny
crustaceans are packaged. Ours, from Educational Insights ($19.95),
came with food, a little tank, a plastic galleon that glows in the
dark and a tool that shoots air into the water.
</P>
<P>
   We also decided on wrist watches ($9.95 each). A globe on the
watch is filled with water and you can wear a sea monkey on your
wrist. The creatures are recommended for children 6 and up.
</P>
<P>
   On reading the sea monkey instruction book, we learned that we
would witness cryptobiosis, which means ``hidden life.'' Sea
monkeys are like the grains of wheat that sprouted in the sealed
tombs of the Egyptian pharaohs.
</P>
<P>
   We began by putting the water purifier in the tank overnight.
Then came the almost invisible eggs. There was nothing to see, but
the instructions said we had just created ``instant life.'' On the
appointed days, we added a touch of food, then plasma a few days
later. The plasma did something to the water the sea monkeys
apparently liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to fight over the females,'' Roy reported from
the instruction book. He quoted: ``Do not interfere with the fight.
It can only get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   We wait.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   GADGETRY FOR READING
</P>
<P>
   I want my children to be creative, intuitive, deductive students
who genuinely enjoy learning. So, like any other guilt-ridden,
neurotic, anxious parent, I buy them cool educational gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Quicktionary, from Seiko Instruments, looks like a fat pen with
tiny wheels at one end but is in fact a hand-held electronic
scanner geared to adults who need reading help, though children may
benefit from it as well. You roll the device over printed words in
books or magazines, and they are pronounced via optical character
recognition. Definitions _ for 400,000 words, the entire American
Heritage Dictionary _ appear on a narrow screen at the center of
the ``pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Both my boys had trouble at first rolling it absolutely straight
on a line of text, but Roy gradually improved. He now finds
Quicktionary helpful and uses it with his homework. My experience,
too, was smooth and utilitarian.
</P>
<P>
   But Guy, who is not as handy, rejected it. ``The dictionary, I'm
a master at,'' he said, perhaps exaggerating. ``I can find any word
in the dictionary. The scanning thing is harder for me.'' Guy's
coordination might not be developed enough for Quicktionary, which
at $249.95 is no toy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   MORE SEA MONKEYS
</P>
<P>
   About 10 days after we brought the sea monkeys to life, several
grew to more than a quarter-inch long. I arrived home one evening
to find the boys huddled in front of the tank squealing with
delight. ``Hey, Dad, the sea monkeys are mating!'' Guy exclaimed.
``They're staying next to each other and flying around the whole
tank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have hundreds!'' Roy predicted. The next
morning, the two monkeys were still attached. They did not separate
until late evening. The next day, the one we figured as the female
had a large swelling at the base of her tail. Fertilized eggs?
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   GLOBE-TROTTING
</P>
<P>
   Part of a popular series of games focused on geography, the
Geosafari Talking Globe (Educational Insights, $49.95) asks and
answers more than 10,000 questions about countries, capitals,
cities, rivers, landmarks and even national songs, which it plays.
</P>
<P>
   As many as four people can play at once, and both the degree of
difficulty and answering time can be regulated. There are many
flashing lights. (A smaller, hand-held traveling version has 5,000
questions, for $49.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Guy liked the way the voice jingled like a cash register after a
successful answer. ``I just learned that the capital of Poland is
Warsaw,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The game moved along nicely, teaching effortlessly. The medium
levels seemed beyond children of 8, the youngest age for which the
globe is recommended. The upper levels often eluded me. Some
questions were repeated too often, like whether or not the Marshall
Islands are in the Pacific Ocean. But after missing a few in a row,
the game automatically lowered the level of difficulty, at least
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Roy had an idea for a future edition. He suggested the country
in question light up, making it easier to examine.
</P>
<P>
   Geosafari Know It All, also $49.95 and for children 8 and up,
looks like a small laptop computer and asks about 2,000 far-ranging
questions, from geography to weather to sports to astronomy to
punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   Guy thought the state-capital questions were too easy but got
frustrated with the harder ones. I believe it will work out over
time. Roy liked it because, in his view, it finally proved he can
use a dictionary: just like the top of a real dictionary page, the
screen lists the first and last words, then asks players to name
three words whose spellings would fall in between the two words.
Roy scored 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Mom doesn't think I know how to use a dictionary,'' he
said with a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   THINKING-CAPS TIME
</P>
<P>
   The Thinkin' Things series of computer games really do make
children think rather than recite knowledge or, as is often the
case, just play.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent titles are Galactic Brain Benders and Sky Island
Mysteries ($29.95 each from Edmark, ages 8 to 12). Guy was
immediately fascinated with Rebus Isle in the Sky Island game. At
Rebus Isle, you can sharpen your phonics by sounding out clever
combinations of letters and pictures. Guy got his Teddy bear to
push the buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Roy favored Galactic, especially a game called Stocktopus. This
involved trading items, like basketballs, and often required
players to make temporary sacrifices to reach their goals. In
addition to honing mental skills, it suggests the unthinkable to
youngsters: You can't always have what you want when you want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be No. 1 trader,'' he said a few minutes after
beginning. ``I'm not going to stop until I'm No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   I could see him at a Wall Street trading desk until, 45 minutes
later, things turned against him. He glared at the screen and
growled, ``I'm in trouble now.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   STILL MORE SEA MONKEYS
</P>
<P>
   Roy tipped the tank over, and the sea monkeys fell on the floor.
He wailed like a banshee and ran to his room, screaming that he
wanted to die. I managed to save the big, possibly pregnant, one,
but she died by the next morning. A pall settled over our
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Then we threw another pack of eggs into the tank. Like spring
rain, ``instant life'' sprouted again. A couple of our little
friends were soon quite large. The boys chatted eagerly about
buying Cupid's Arrow Mating Powder, one of the many accessories
available to sea monkey owners.
</P>
<P>
   And I tried to remember what was wrong with a dog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
