reported on Friday. Average hourly earnings for the month rose by
0.4 percent, slightly higher than expected. But because workers are
producing more for each hour worked, the growth in wages so far
shows few signs of setting off a surge in inflation. While good
news across the board, the figures substantially increased the
likelihood that the Federal Reserve will act to keep the economy
from overheating by raising interest rates next month. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
