<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLICE SEARCH LANDFILL FOR CLUES TO MISSING GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RYAN KIM  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLEJO, Calif. _ Investigators from Northern California have
been combing a vast landfill along the border of Washington and
Oregon in search of the body of a missing 7-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   Two Vallejo police detectives have been searching since Monday
and have not uncovered any evidence about the missing girl, said
Lt. JoAnn West of the Vallejo police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still there and we're looking,`` West said. ``That's
where all our garbage is dumped, so we're looking through it.``
</P>
<P>
   West said the search of the landfill was routine and not the
result of any tips or outside information.
</P>
<P>
   Xiana Fairchild was reported missing Dec. 9 after her mother's
former boyfriend, Robert Turnbough, told the police he dropped her
off at a bus stop before going to work. He later changed his story
and told the police he last saw her outside the Vallejo apartment
he shared with Xiana's mother, Antoinette Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelt Regional Landfill is perched along the border of
Washington and Oregon about 2 1/2 hours east of Portland, Ore. The
landfill, which covers more than 2,000 acres, has a contract to
take trash from Vallejo and Napa, said landfill general manager
Peter Keller.
</P>
<P>
   Keller said the landfill accepts 180,000 tons of waste from the
two California cities each year.
</P>
<P>
   West said the detectives have been sifting through garbage
delivered since Dec. 9. She said the investigators have narrowed
their focus to a one-third-acre area where the trash from Vallejo
is believed to have been deposited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be there until we have looked through all of
it. We don't know how long it's going to take,`` West said.
</P>
<P>
   The landfill search is the latest twist in an investigation that
has confounded the police. Investigators have been repeatedly
stymied in their attempts to collect accurate information,
especially from Turnbough and Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to changing his story on the last sighting of Xiana,
Turnbough also said the girl was wearing gray sweat pants when he
last saw her. But Robinson said she discovered the sweat pants at
home last weekend. Turnbough has served time for child neglect.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Turnbough, Jim McEntee, said his client is
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also has given conflicting information about when she
discovered Xiana's sweat pants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
