<P>
   FLAT-PANTS (Undated) _ For many years, if you were a guy who
preferred flat-front to pleated pants, you were in trouble. You had
to track them down, like a big-game hunter on the trail of an
endangered species, or else have them made. I did both, until flat
started to come back in the mid-90s. By Rick Marin. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYBOY-PARTIES (Undated) _ Is there no place left where
40-something men can pursue women young enough to be their
daughters, the age difference overcome by the size of their
portfolios? The answer is yes _ at a Ted Field party. Field is the
Hollywood financier who, twice a year, gives a big, splashy,
over-the-top party in St. Barts, Aspen, East Hampton or Paris
during fashion week _ wherever the action is. The guest lists are
drawn up by professional party planners well connected to modeling
agencies, and the ratio of women to men is usually about two to
one. The evenings draw hundreds, sometimes thousands, no matter
what island, yacht or ocean-front mansion is chosen as the setting.
By Monique P. Yazigi. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONES-HEADSETS (New York) _ In New York City, the public
use of cell phone headsets are poised to become the big accessory
for spring _ more useful on the head than a bra strap, and more
attractive. By Penelope Green.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-KATZ (New York) _ Youth and age seemed relative Thursday
night, as did notions of gay and straight, in an evening that
involved Grace Kelly, Eartha Kitt, Noah Wyle and the drag
entertainer Divine. It started at the Walter Reade Theater, where
the producer James C. Katz was introducing his latest work, a
restored version of the 1954 Hitchcock classic movie ``Rear
Window.'' By Linda Lee. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ In the withering heat and
unprecedented dryness of last summer, it was hard to imagine that a
group of untended, unwatered shrubs would decorate my garden with
white flowers and spectacular scarlet, wine-red and lemon-yellow
foliage in the fall. That's what happened, however. I found it
quite wondrous. By Patricia A. Taylor.
</P>
