<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-DAVID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACRE, ADULTERY, INCEST AND BETRAYAL IN AN ELECTION YEAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How are the mighty chosen?
</P>
<P>
   In an election season, the greatest concern might be banality
and boredom. But in the biblical account of the election of King
David, which has just been retold in two powerful new English
translations, here are the dangers: massacre, decapitation,
necromancy, fratricide, adultery, incest, betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us a king!'' the Israelite people demand of their prophet
Samuel, and against his better judgment he does. Divine guidance
seems as fallible as human judgment. The first King, Saul, is a
``fine and goodly young fellow'' who is secretly anointed by Samuel
while aimlessly searching for his father's lost donkeys. Saul is
remarkably clueless, hesitant to act, easily swayed, but when his
power is threatened his manic paranoia is unleashed in ruthless
fury. In revenge for a priest's aiding an enemy, the priest's
entire town is struck down, ``man and woman, infant and suckling,
ox and donkey and sheep.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the 12th century B.C., succession to power is no less
gruesome than the preservation of power. David overturns Saul's
line after a savage civil war. Even David, whose lineage is
prophetically guaranteed, is challenged twice by his own sons in
rebellions that steep the kingdom in blood. David, old and feeble,
finally chooses his heir through what seems a ruse: he is convinced
by one of his wives, Bathsheba (whose first husband David had had
killed), that he once promised the kingdom to her youngest son,
Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   The only suggestion of ordered succession in these tales is the
divine promise that it will take place. But in earthly realms such
promises are meaningless. They come to fruition only by keeping
one's eyes wary and one's back covered. The existence of kings is
hardly a solution. Before a king is named, authority is corrupt,
sons are dissolute, warfare is commonplace and civil strife severe.
After a king is named, authority is corrupt, sons are dissolute,
warfare is commonplace and civil strife severe.
</P>
<P>
   One is reminded not of the legendary David _ whose mastery of
the lyre put Orpheus to shame and whose psalms are the works of a
great visionary _ but of more modern tyrants whose central project
is the preservation of power. Saul, the bloodthirsty, depressive
hick, seems almost Stalinesque.
</P>
<P>
   Both new translations of Samuel I and II also reveal something
else latent in these texts. By forcing close attention to detail,
they show how the repeated power struggles are part of a larger
unfolding drama.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Give Us a King!'' (Schocken) Everett Fox, a professor of
Judaic and biblical studies at Clark University, continues the
project he began with his version of ``The Five Books of Moses.''
Fox does not strive for transparency in recounting these familiar
stories; he wants the text to draw attention to itself. So when the
Hebrew is unsettling and artificial, the English is as well. The
names retain their Hebrew sound. The Ark of the Tabernacle is
called a Coffer.
</P>
<P>
   When David cries out in grief at the death of his traitorous
son, Absalom, instead of declaring his wish to have died instead of
Absalom, his exclamation is stilted, ambiguous and halting: ``Who
would give/my dying, my (own) in your place!'' The unnatural idiom
forces the English reader to ask the same questions the Hebrew
reader would: why are these words used and not others? What are
they trying to tell us?
</P>
<P>
   This sort of inquiry is encouraged also by Robert Alter, a
professor of Hebrew and comparative literature at the University of
California at Berkeley, in ``The David Story'' (W.W. Norton). He
does it not through his translation, which is sober and clear and
fluid, judiciously alluding to King James language while
accumulating fresh nuances. Instead, he creates a provocative
counterpoint to the biblical text: nearly two-thirds of each page
contains masterful commentary. Alter argues that this text offers
``one of the most astounding pieces of narrative'' from ancient
times, deserving a literary place next to the works of Shakespeare
or Stendhal.
</P>
<P>
   Though parts of the text are clearly patched together from
varied sources, Alter suggests that the compiler had a grand,
unified vision: images are repeatedly invoked, phrases echo one
another, no detail is accidental. Alter points out, for example,
that turning points in King David's career are marked by his
responses to death.
</P>
<P>
   In his youth, the charismatic warrior is given to eloquent
elegy; at the height of his power, the elegy is a strategically
worded public proclamation; at the beginning of his decline, the
death of his infant son inspires a humble acknowledgment of his own
mortality; and finally, in old age, David is reduced to a ``sheer
stammer of grief.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the David stories might seem on their surface to be
about divine retribution for the sins of power, they are actually
meticulous accounts of flawed people shaping their own fates. The
prophets who keep appearing are not like their later counterparts,
preaching justice, condemning idolatry and promising punishment;
their proclamations actually seem superfluous. Divine influence is
hardly needed to explain the downfall of Saul or the sorrows of
David. A man's character is his fate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as both translations also show, fate is not solely a
matter of character: the details reveal recurrent narrative
patterns and images, oblique allusions to earlier events and
ominous signs of things yet to come _ evidence of a designer at
work giving shape both to story and to history. But that design is
not apparent to the characters themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The future may be ordained, but it is realized through human
action, which is unavoidably flawed, and through the application of
power, which is unavoidably corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the issue of succession is so central to these
tales. The future in such a world is always in doubt; history's
shape is always in the making, and the relationship between human
actor and divine creator always in flux. With David's death, the
story is just beginning.
</P>
</TEXT>
