A9583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-NY-HNS &LR;      01-07 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-NY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK DISTRICTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN CAMP BLAMES GOVERNOR FOR FAILURE TO GET ON BALLOT IN ALL &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Republican presidential hopeful John McCain has
failed to qualify for the primary ballot in all of New York's
election districts and blamed the setback on his party leadership's
unilateral support for Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a miraculous write-in campaign, McCain has therefore
already lost a third of the GOP delegates New York will send to the
Republican National Convention in August, where the party will
christen its presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   McCain delegates will be on the primary ballot in at least 22 of
New York's 31 congressional election districts, said his state
chairman, Staten Island Borough President Guy Molinari. His camp
collected 30,000 petition signatures statewide.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Bush collected 90,000 signatures and will be on
the ballot on March 7 in all 31 election districts, the state
Republican Party said. The other high-profile GOP candidate,
magazine publisher Steve Forbes, collected ``more than 50,000''
signatures and also qualified for the ballot in all 31 districts,
said his campaign spokesman, Bill Dal Col.
</P>
<P>
   Most of New York's top Republicans _ including Gov. George
Pataki, Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno of Brunswick and Party
Chairman Bill Powers _ support Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The state carries the second-largest number of nominating
delegates in the nation, making its primary a crucial election to
win. Only California has more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of others who wanted to join our ranks, and they
were told, `You'd better not if you want a political future. This
will come back to haunt you,''' Molinari said. ``That was
bothersome but not surprising. A lot of that has been traced back
to the governor's doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon dismissed Molinari's charges.
``If there was broad support, they would be on the ballot in every
district,'' McKeon said of Bush's challengers. ``But since they've
fallen short of that, they've resorted to whining. That's too
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's primary balloting process is widely considered the
most archaic in the nation. To qualify for the ballot statewide,
candidates must collect the number of signatures in each
congressional district that equal half of 1 percent of enrolled
voters there, or 1,000 signatures, whichever is less.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, candidates must collect at least 5,000
signatures statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most onerous process in the country,'' said Dal Col,
who said Forbes' camp spent $750,000 just to get on the ballot.
Still, that's an improvement from Forbes' 1996 primary bid in New
York, during which he spent $1.8 million, Dal Col said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, an Arizona senator, is the only high-profile
presidential candidate _ among Republicans and Democrats alike _
who failed to qualify for a statewide run. On the Democratic side,
both Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley
handily collected enough signatures to get on the ballot in all 31
districts, their camps said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Elections will not have official results for
several days as it wades through the reams and reams of petitions
submitted by the candidates, said agency spokesman Lee Daghlian.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore's state campaign made a big show of wheeling its stacks of
petitions into the elections board office Thursday. The vice
president collected 100,000 signatures _ even more, state Chairman
Eric Eve said, than what Gore and President Clinton collected in
New York during their 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley collected about 46,000 signatures. Like McCain, the
former New York Knicks basketball star also did not have the
backing of most of his party's top officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not the candidate of the Democratic establishment, so
to be the insurgent and to qualify in all 31 congressional
districts is a testament to our strength,'' said Bradley spokesman
Tony Wyche.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore supporters said they were unconcerned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it shows such great strength to lose 2-1 in the
petition count,'' said Rep. Michael McNulty, D-N.Y., who was on
hand to watch Gore's petitions filed. ``I think it's a tremendous
victory for the vice president. He's got twice as many signatures
as his only other opponent. It's not like the opposition is
split.''
</P>
</TEXT>
