<HEADLINE>
SAY IT ISN'T SO, ST. FRANCIS: ASSISI BANS PIGEON FEEDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASSISI, Italy _ The gentleman from Verona reared back guiltily
when asked why a horde of pigeons was pecking around his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do it on purpose; the crumbs just accidentally fell
off,'' Paul Castio, a tourist from Verona, protested, holding up
the remains of a cream pastry. But he expressed dismay over a new
city ordinance that bans the feeding of pigeons in Assisi, the
medieval hill town where St. Francis lived and preached. ``I think
it is unfair,'' he said. ``Even pigeons have to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle between man and pigeon is waged daily in almost every
European city, but it has reached a whole new dimension in Assisi,
where the age-old debate over animal rights and the protection of
historic monuments _ and human health _ is colored by the moral
teachings of St. Francis of Assisi, the humble friar (born in 1182
and died in 1226) who loved animals and preached to the birds.
</P>
<P>
   Assisi, which is still recovering from the 1997 earthquake that
damaged its famous basilica and killed 11 people, is now
traumatized by the crackdown on pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   Some, and especially the mayor, say it is a badly needed measure
to control a growing pigeon population. Others view it as a form of
anthrocentricity that clashes with the town's animal-loving ethos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the mayor's decision, but we do not agree with
it,'' said the Rev. Vincenzo Fortunato, the spokesman for the
Franciscan order of Assisi. ``We believe there are alternatives
that respect animals and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most custodians of churches and historic buildings in
Italy, however, the Franciscan friars have put up thin wiring that
emits an electrical impulse that repels birds along key spots of
their restored basilica to protect the 13th-century building from
pigeon excrement.
</P>
<P>
   Local environmentalists are even more upset. ``St. Francis
called everyone brother and sister, even animals,'' said Silvia
Rapicetta, a director of the Assisi Natural Council, an
environmental and animal rights association. ``This order doesn't
take into consideration the whole problem, it just gives out
prohibitions.''
</P>
<P>
   But even animal rights groups concede that there is no easy
solution to limiting the country's rapidly multiplying urban pigeon
population. Reducing the amount of food available and limiting
nesting sites is a partial solution.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Dinetti, a national coordinator of the Italian League for
the Protection of Birds, said that introducing natural predators
like the falcon or the tawny owl to cities would be ``ecologically
sound and not cruel.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned, ``You have to do food reduction ethically _ you
cannot just take away food overnight and stop people from feeding
the pigeons.''
</P>
<P>
   But Venice, a city where there are almost twice as many pigeons
as people, and where signs ordering tourists not to feed pigeons
are cheerfully ignored, has taken a harsher route. There, since the
end of 1998, about 20,000 pigeons have been captured and gassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could find a falcon that could eat 50,000 pigeons
everyone would applaud, but it doesn't exist,'' said Mario
Scattolin, director of Venice's Environmental Office. ``Nature is
what it is, not what Walt Disney shows us.''
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio Bartolini, the mayor of Assisi, said he would not dream
of introducing extermination measures to his town, and merely
wanted to reduce the pigeon population by cutting back feedings and
closing up windows and holes in abandoned buildings where pigeons
congregate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assisi cannot serve as a welcome center for pigeons,''
Bartolini, warned. ``I am not saying that we have an epidemic on
hand, but their growth rate is alarming, and they damage buildings
and pose a health risk to people.'' Experts disagree on the degree
of risk, but pigeons have been linked to the spread of salmonella,
ticks, and allergies.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor conceded that his order, given just before Christmas
and on the eve of a Holy Year that is expected to bring millions of
additional pilgrims to Assisi, was not widely popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Francis was a saint; I'm just a humble mayor,'' he said.
``I have no interest in becoming a saint. I am trying to apply
common sense and pragmatism.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Assisi, he has some supporters. ``When St. Francis spoke to
the birds, it was before they installed drains,'' grumbled Piero
Coenda, the manager of Cafe Minerva, a cafe across from Santa Maria
Sopra Minerva, a medieval church built over a Roman temple in
Assisi's main piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, locals used to feed pigeons corn on the
piazza when the church bells rang at noon. ``We were infested with
droppings,'' Coenda said. ``We had to change the outdoor
tablecloths every 10 minutes.'' The church now has anti-pigeon
wiring along its roof, and the ritual noon feedings have stopped.
</P>
<P>
   There are other pigeon experts who say people have taken St.
Francis' teachings too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Francis probably never met a pigeon in his entire life,''
said Bernardino Ragni, a zoologist at the University of Perugia who
conducted an experimental pigeon-reduction program in Perugia.
</P>
<P>
   Ragni said he believed that pigeons were introduced a century
after St. Francis' death, brought back from the Holy Land as
dinner. ``They fed pigeons in order to eat them,'' he said. ``Man
is the pigeon's natural predator.''
</P>
<P>
   But other aviary historians disagree. Richard F. Johnston, a
scholar at the Natural History Museum of the University of Kansas,
said pigeons could be found around coastal Europe in 10,000 B.C.
and were domesticated and cooked by Egyptians, and later the
Etruscans and Romans. According to F.R. Cowell's ``Life in Ancient
Rome,'' pigeons were a delicacy served up at the kind of Roman
bacchanals that enrich ``The Satyricon'' of Petronius.
</P>
<P>
   Art in Assisi, moreover, suggests St. Francis not only met
pigeons, but also talked to them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the main art treasures inside the Basilica of St. Francis,
there is a 13th-century fresco attributed to Giotto, which was
covered in dust by the earthquake, and was recently restored. It
shows St. Francis preaching to birds, and some art historians
identify them as sparrows, quails, and also pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   Ragni said he had been unable to persuade Perugia's officials to
adopt an effective anti-pigeon campaign, one that includes
extermination, and doubted whether Assisi's elected officials would
summon the political will to sponsor so unpopular a move.
</P>
<P>
   And even if they did, he said, he feared it would spark
widespread civil disobedience. ``Italians are undisciplined,'' he
said wearily, ``and they are also sentimental about very stupid
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
