u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT     01-07 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Jan. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disturbance that brought rain to parts of southeast Texas on
Friday will weaken as it lifts northeast across the lower
Mississippi and Tennessee valleys. Nonetheless, broken areas of
rain and isolated thundershowers will affect parts of this region.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will increase and thicken over the lower Ohio Valley in
advance of the disturbance, but areas of rain will become more
fragmented and lighter with time, limiting the affects of rain over
the Ohio Valley later Saturday and into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the stage will be set for heavy snow this weekend in
the Cascades as moist Pacific winds are forced to rapidly ascend
the sloping terrain. Snowfalls of two feet are possible in the
Washington and northern Oregon Cascades by late Sunday. Mountain
snows will also affect the Bitterroots of Montana and Idaho, the
Tetons of western Wyoming and parts of the Wasatch in Utah this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Vestiges of Arctic air will shrink from the contiguous states
this weekend as Pacific air continues to gain a foothold on the
nation. By Sunday, nearly the entire region east of the Rockies
will record afternoon temperatures that are above the 30-year
average for the date.
</P>
<P>
   However, much of the northern Middle Atlantic and southern New
England states will be mostly cloudy on Sunday, as moisture from
the Gulf of Mexico associated with weak jet stream disturbances
settles over the region. Patchy light rain, snow or freezing rain
could affect some parts of the region on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: STUNTED SNOWPACKS
</P>
<P>
   Snowpacks in the Sierra Nevada of California contain less than
25 percent of the amount of water that would typically be observed
in early January. Because run-off from melting snow during spring
and summer provides a large share of the water used for agriculture
and human consumption, there is growing concern for the possibility
of rationing during the upcoming warm season. Snowpacks play a more
crucial role in southern California, where there are few reservoirs
to catch run-off from rain. No big snows are in the offing in
southern California in the immediate future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
