<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-0108-CO     01-07 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-0108-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON BRINGS ISRAELI, SYRIAN NEGOTIATORS TOGETHER AGAIN, LAYS
OUT ROAD MAP FOR PEACE ACCORD
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ President Clinton pulled Israeli and
Syrian negotiators together for a brief huddle Friday and presented
them with a U.S. roadmap of the path to peace.
</P>
<P>
   The document, more than a dozen pages of detailed text, was
meant to sidestep an impasse that has bogged down a week of talks
between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   The men were expected to recess the talks for most of the day
Saturday, to mark the Jewish sabbath and a Muslim feast marking the
end of the Islamic holy month, Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks were expected to get back underway Saturday night,
however, amid signs that the leaders were trying to wrap up this
round by Monday without reaching final agreement on the contentious
territorial and security issues that divide them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hosted a half-hour discussion between the two
negotiators on Friday, their second direct meeting since the talks
began Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of face-to-face give-and-take,'' said State
Department spokesman James Rubin. ``This is not warm and fuzzy, but
it is businesslike and professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to nail down and to clarify areas of agreement and
discord, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright put together the
document Clinton presented the leaders with on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The text is meant to be a starting point for what U.S. diplomats
hope will evolve into a formal peace accord ending a half-century
of bloodshed and conflict between the two Mideast neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fair amount of common ground that exists now,''
Rubin told reporters shortly after Clinton hosted the trilateral
meeting between himself, Barak and Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the remaining areas are big differences,'' Rubin said,
``and they are emotional differences and they carry with them
substantial security implications and political implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the week here was spent in what might be called
diplomatic conditioning, efforts to bring Barak and Sharaa to the
point where they would begin seriously negotiating the terms of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   The broad outlines of an agreement are known: Israel would
return the Golan Heights to Syria in exchange for security
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   That land-for-peace formulation has been fundamentally unchanged
since Israel seized the Golan in 1967, after Syria joined Jordan
and Egypt in attacking the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the arrangement, however, are myriad and fraught
with contention.
</P>
<P>
   Real progress this week, for example, has been largely stalled
by a dispute over how to sequence the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Syria and Israel differ, for example, over where the actual
border should be drawn between the two countries following a return
to Syria of the Golan. Sharaa insisted that agreement on that
border should proceed talks on other subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, however, said the talks had to begin with discussion of
security arrangements, not borders.
</P>
<P>
   Over that dispute, talks largely bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   Four working-level committees of subject experts were assembled
to take up security arrangements, overall relations between the two
countries, water rights and border issues.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, though, the latter two committees had not met, while
the others had met only once.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said diplomats remained hopeful that all committees would
meet by Monday. He hinted that this round might wind down by then,
with delegations returning to their respective capitals to try to
assess and digest this week's proceedings, before gathering again
at some point in the future to try to advance their peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
