<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TONY THE TIGER GETS A ROOT CANAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tony the tiger might not have felt
``grrrrrrrrrreat`` Thursday morning after getting a root canal at
the San Francisco Zoo hospital, but he is sure to feel better soon.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how the 7-year-old, 380-pound Siberian tiger
actually broke his lower left canine tooth, said keeper Lori
Komejan, who noticed the snaggletooth about three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   She then found the missing piece _ a conical tip of bone about
the size of her thumbnail _ while draining a water pool in the yard
Tony shares with his twin sister, Emily.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when they knew he had to have a root canal,`` she said,
explaining that the blackened core of the tooth indicated severe
decay.
</P>
<P>
   First thing Thursday, zookeepers used a dart to sedate and
anesthetize Tony, loaded him onto the bed of an orange zoo cart and
drove across the quiet grounds toward the operating room.
</P>
<P>
   Tony looked as harmless as an oversized house kitty, yet it took
five employees to lift Tony's limp body onto a gurney and wheel him
inside.
</P>
<P>
   His gigantic paws _ each one large enough to fill a dinner plate
_ dangled over the side of the table as he was prepared for the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues and caretakers looked on in awe as veterinarians set
up a ventilator, injected an intravenous needle and put a catheter
in place. A cord was knotted on top of his nose to keep the
breathing tube in place and a plastic cylinder was fitted onto the
upper and lower canine teeth on the right side of Tony's mouth to
prop it open. His long tongue extended past his black lips, folded
over on itself like a piece of velvety pink ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   Three dentists dealt with dental concerns while the
veterinarians monitored Tony's vital signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to work on such big teeth,'' said Mehran Fotovatjah,
one of the dentists. And his breath wasn't too offensive, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting a lot worse,`` said Fotovatjah, who had a
paper mask to wear just in case. ``Like that black tiger we did,
oooh, that was bad.``
</P>
<P>
   It was clearly a big event for Tony and his handlers.
</P>
<P>
   The actual work on the tooth lasted only a few minutes, and the
dental crew worked swiftly with shiny silver tools to extract the
dead nerve, which looked like a thin piece of spaghetti burned on
one end.
</P>
<P>
   The real drama came minutes afterward when Tony's temperature
started rising, going from a normal 101.5 degrees to a high of 107
in just a few minutes as a reaction to the anesthetic, said staff
veterinarian John Ochsenreiter. Since anything above 103 is
considered dangerous and could result in shock, organ failure or
brain damage, the crew quickly placed pillowcases filled with
chipped ice between the tiger's legs and draped cool, wet blankets
to reduce Tony's temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The dentists worked quickly to fill the cavity in Tony's tooth
with the same zinc-based paste used for human fillings and filed
the broken edge down to a smooth polish. A small tooth fragment
that split to the bottom was gently pried from the gum line, bring
the only drops of blood shed during the hourlong procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Tony returned to his holding room, he opened his
eyes and growled softly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
