<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIVE SHRUBS: STAR PERFORMERS EVEN IN A DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 9)  
 (bl)  
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the withering heat and unprecedented dryness of last summer,
it was hard to imagine that a group of untended, unwatered shrubs
would decorate my garden with white flowers and spectacular
scarlet, wine-red and lemon-yellow foliage in the fall. That's what
happened, however. I found it quite wondrous, because in earlier
years the same shrubs had sailed through unremitting spring rains.
</P>
<P>
   But the real surprise is that several of these exceptional
native plants are so little known. Most shade gardeners would find
their borders enriched with the easy-care attributes of spicebush
(Lindera benzoin) and fragrant sumac (Rhus aromatica). These shrubs
are also highly recommended by the Garden Club of America in its
book ``Plants That Merit Attention: Shrubs'' (Timber Press, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   In early spring, spicebush's airy, arching branches are dotted
with small yellowish-green flowers, which appear shortly before the
3-to-5-inch-long leaves open. The flowers mature in late summer
into red fruits that nestle as precious gems among lemon-yellow
autumn leaves. If left unpruned, this deciduous shrub will reach 6
to 12 feet. I keep mine trimmed to a more demure 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   One of my spicebushes is paired with a 3-foot-tall fragrant
sumac cultivar known as Gro-Low. Its dark green, glossy leaves are
somewhat similar to Irish shamrocks, with the center leaf 2 inches
long and each flanking leaf 1 inch. The triangular configuration
contrasts nicely with the spicebush's lanceolate leaves. And
Gro-Low's denser habit sets off the more open form of spicebush.
</P>
<P>
   Garden books say Gro-Low's inconspicuous spring catkins mature
into red berrylike fruit, but this has yet to happen on mine. The
fall foliage _ a deep wine red often streaked with scarlet _ is so
handsome, however, that further decoration is really not needed.
</P>
<P>
   Since neither one of these undemanding shrubs is a spring star,
I underplant them with a variety of bulbs like white snowdrops,
pink corydalis, blue muscari and multicolored crocuses. The light
dusting of flowers on the upper branches of the shrubs provides a
gauzy covering for the splashy bulb display below.
</P>
<P>
   While both spicebush and fragrant sumac sparkle in sun, their
location in cooling shade on my property seems to have helped them
to withstand last summer's heat. I let three other underutilized
native shrubs bake in full sun, however, and they didn't mind a
bit. These star performers are groundsel bush (Baccharis
halimifolia), white autumn sage (Salvia greggii Alba) and red
chokeberry (Aronia arbutifolia).
</P>
<P>
   Groundsel bush grows 6 to 12 feet tall and is native to
coastlines from Massachusetts through Texas. Property owners in
these areas plant it because of its salt tolerance. I treasure it
in my inland central New Jersey garden as a privacy screen and as
an unusual fall decoration.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, the slim leaves (1 to 3 inches) of the multistemmed
groundsel bush create a soft gray-green wall. In late September,
multitudes of grayish-white buds start to swell at every branch
tip. Then, in early October, silvery-white seed hairs burst forth
and hold for weeks. The overall effect is that of billowing clouds
crowning the shrub, a picture that is especially dramatic when
flanked by the scarlet foliage of trees like amelanchiers and
stewartias.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, white autumn sage is elusive. It is often
classified as a perennial; its bloom period, despite its popular
name, starts in mid-May, and unknown to many horticulturists, it is
hardy as far north as Zone 5. (The red and pink forms are hardy
only to Zones 7 or 8.)
</P>
<P>
   Once planted, however, this shrub is valued for its continuous
outpouring of creamy white 1 inch tubular flowers. These spray
forth in single blossoms from wiry stems that almost seem to float
above the rich green pungent foliage. While each flower is not
showy in itself, the overall presentation is one of quiet charm. In
its native southern haunts, this shrub is often called Texas sage.
There, it remains evergreen; in my borders, it loses its leaves and
flowers by late November.
</P>
<P>
   Red chokeberry is a beautiful vase-shaped multiseasonal shrub 6
to 10 feet tall. In early May, clusters of white blossoms drift
through slate-gray stems. Throughout summer, dark green leaves 1 to
3 inches long present a handsome backdrop to other plantings.
</P>
<P>
   I have the Brilliantissima cultivar, noted for its abundant
production of red berries and extravagant flame-scarlet fall
foliage. The berries, shunned by birds, remain on leafless branches
throughout much of winter.
</P>
<P>
   From years of growing experience, I know that these five shrubs
not only ignore drought and deluge but are also disease- and
pest-resistant and thrive without fertilizers. All they need is
well-drained, reasonably fertile soil _ and a little more
appreciation from the gardening public.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   All the plants mentioned except white autumn sage are available
from Forestfarm, 990 Tetherow Road, Williams, Ore. 97544; (541)
846-7269; catalog, $4.
</P>
<P>
   Spicebush, groundsel bush and red chokeberry are also offered by
Fairweather Gardens, PO Box 330, Greenwich, N.J. 08323; (856)
451-6261; catalog $3.
</P>
<P>
   White autumn sage is offered by Plant Delights Nursery, 9241
Sauls Road, Raleigh, N.C. 27603; (919) 772-4794; catalog available
if you send 10 stamps of any kind or a box of chocolates.
</P>
</TEXT>
