<HEADER>
A9608 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-SHOWS-ART-     01-07 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-SHOWS-ART-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW PLAYING IN DETROIT, HOPING FOR AN ENCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Having closed its books on a golden year, the auto
industry's movers and shakers gather here this week to congratulate
themselves and to contemplate the possibility, however remote, of
equaling or surpassing their impressive totals for 1999: an
unprecedented 16.9 million cars and trucks sold in the United
States, topping the previous record of 16 million in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that they operate in a business in which everything
comes down to product, product and product, the world's automakers
are using the North American International Auto Show to roll out
the vehicles that will fill showrooms in the months ahead, along
with concept cars that usually provide a sneak preview of the
vehicles that will be on the streets in a year or two. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit show, once a backwater, has in recent years become
one of the world's top automotive venues. It now attracts the top
executives of most of the world's car companies, who want to be on
hand when the drums roll, the lights dim and the sheets are pulled
off their latest and shiniest creations before a 5,000-member press
corps.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, press previews of the Greater Los Angeles Auto Show
offered a warmup for Detroit; mindful of California's importance in
sales numbers and in setting style trends, many manufacturers are
now introducing models there but not in Detroit, or are showing
them in both cities.
</P>
<P>
   These were among the vehicles that made their debuts in Los
Angeles last week: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ACURA 3.2CL This redesigned luxury coupe will go on sale in
March, equipped with the larger V6 and other underpinnings of the
successful Acura 3.2TL sedan. Like the TL, the CL is likely to have
a highly competitive price, probably in the mid-$20,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   SUBARU ST/X Those who remember the Subaru Brat of the 1970s will
not be too surprised by this car-cum-truck concept vehicle. Based
on the Legacy station wagon, the ST/X has four doors plus an
exposed cargo bed. A gate between the pickup box and the cabin
allows long items to be carried partly inside the passenger area.
Nissan has previously shown a truck with a similar design.
</P>
<P>
   BUICK REGAL CIELO Last year in Detroit, Buick displayed a
futuristic car, the Cielo, whose hardtop slid back in sections to
form a convertible. Now the General Motors subsidiary has given a
similar treatment to its midsize Regal sedan; it is unclear whether
the car will be offered to the public.
</P>
<P>
   MERCURY MOUNTAINEER On display in both Los Angeles and Detroit,
this show truck appears to be a thinly veiled version of the next
Mercury sport utility. The Mountaineer has a sharp-edged look in
keeping with the styling of the Mercury Cougar _ and setting the
SUV further apart from its sibling, the Ford Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC AZTEK Shown last year in conceptual form, this
``crossover vehicle'' _ so called because it straddles the
traditional lines between cars, trucks and vans _ returns to
Detroit and Los Angeles in the form it will take when it goes into
production this summer. Based on the Montana minivan, the Aztek has
the exterior style and all-wheel-drive prowess of a sport utility.
It has removable seats, a pull-out cargo tray, removable utility
packs in the doors and a portable cooler that latches between the
front seats like a center console.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, where press previews begin Sunday, the Cobo Center
convention hall is expected to take on the look of GM's
headquarters, which are now just down the street at Renaissance
Center. The company made it clear three months ago that it would no
longer sit on the sidelines in its hometown while Ford and
DaimlerChrysler made headlines with extravagant stage shows and
critically acclaimed concept cars.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, GM has constructed the largest exhibit ever at the
Detroit show. With two decks and 164,456 square feet of floor
space, GM will, for the first time, display in a single location
many past, present and future vehicles from its various divisions
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Aztek, GM will feature another crossover, the
Chevrolet Avalanche, that will also go into production. (Cadillac
is expected to get a version, too.) It has four doors and a roomy
cab for five passengers, along with a pickup bed that can be
expanded by opening a ``midgate'' between the bed and the passenger
cabin. The rear window can be removed, and the sides of the bed
have lockable storage bins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other GM show cars in Detroit that were previously revealed to
the press at the company's virtual-reality center are the Buick
LaCrosse, a luxury sedan with a pickup bed; the Chevrolet SSR,
which looks like a 1950s pickup and has a sporty interior like an
early Corvette's; the GMC Terradyne, an industrial-grade pickup
truck with an extra-large cab and expandable pickup bed; and the
Opel CVC, a compact van outfitted in winter garb, including a
plastic hatch lid that can be used as a toboggan.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler will presumably try to build on Chrysler's
recent history of developing innovative concept and production
vehicles and unveiling them in a highly theatrical style. The
company is expected to show its next-generation minivans, which
will go on sale as 2001 models. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler will also display four concept vehicles. The
Varsity, a five-door ``urban adventure'' Jeep, has the cab-forward
design of Chrysler's cars, with the wheels pushed toward the
corners to create a spacious interior. The Chrysler 300 Hemi C is a
luxury convertible with a powerful V8 engine, suggesting where the
automaker might go if it were to produce an all-American,
rear-drive performance car evocative of the 1957 Chrysler 300C. The
Dodge MAXXcab is a truck that promises comfort and ride on par with
a sedan; the Dodge Viper GTSR is a street-legal coupe inspired by
Le Mans racecars.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ford will unveil highly fuel-efficient vehicle concepts
that stem from joint research efforts of the industry and the
federal government. Both the Ford Prodigy and GM Precept use a
combination of electric motor and small diesel engine to travel up
to 80 miles on a gallon of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to reality, Nissan will unveil its 2000 Sentra, an
efficient and extremely clean car that goes on sale this year. The
Sentra's 1.8-liter engine was certified this fall by the California
Air Resources Board as the cleanest gasoline-burning engine in the
world. Nissan will also introduce a restyled Pathfinder sport
utility in Detroit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Acura will also show in Detroit its MD-X, a slightly disguised
version of the next-generation sport utility that will replace the
SLX, which has been built by Isuzu. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sporty roadsters always draw crowds at auto shows, and there
will be several new ones on hand, including a Jaguar show car; the
production version of the BMW Z8, which has already appeared in a
James Bond film; and two from Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   One, based on the A-Class sold in Europe, is a foot shorter than
the existing SLK and borrows styling cues from the SLR supercoupe
shown at last year's auto shows. The other, larger roadster
actually is a topless version of the SLR. Both evoke Mercedes'
legendary Silver Arrow racers of the 1950s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several vehicles that were shown at the Tokyo Motor Show last
fall will also make their first North America appearances in
Detroit. Ford will show its quirky 021C concept, the first car
designed by Marc Newson, an Australian known for his trendy designs
of kitchen accessories, watches and other consumer products. This
urban vehicle is built around elements of Ford's next-generation
small-car platform.
</P>
<P>
   The Mazda RX-Evolv is a four-seat, four-door sports car with a
new version of Mazda's rotary engine. It may presage the next
edition of the RX sports car.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Toyota's luxury division will show the Lexus Sport
Coupe, which is destined to replace the current two-door Lexus SC
models. The aluminum hardtop on the concept car drops in seconds,
turning the four-seat coupe into a convertible. Lexus will also
show its next-generation flagship sedan, the LS430, which is being
restyled and given a more powerful V8 engine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A rear-drive car called the XVL, which wore a Nissan badge in
Tokyo, will appear in Detroit as an Infiniti concept car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
