<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-KATZ-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH A VINTAGE JAMES C. KATZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LINDA LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Youth and age seemed relative Thursday night, as did
notions of gay and straight, in an evening that involved Grace
Kelly, Eartha Kitt, Noah Wyle and the drag entertainer Divine. It
started at the Walter Reade Theater, where the producer James C.
Katz was introducing his latest work, a restored version of the
1954 Hitchcock classic movie ``Rear Window.'' Katz and his partner
Robert A. Harris _ they also restored ``My Fair Lady'' and
``Vertigo'' _roam the world like detectives searching for bits and
pieces of original film and piecing them together.
</P>
<P>
   It's an odd line of work, part schmoozing Hollywood to raise
cash and part staring at Jimmy Stewart's blue eyes for days.
</P>
<P>
   After years of slogging through piles of old film, this was
Katz's night to let the film shine for film scholars and buffs. The
cocktail party following the screening was no fashion show, with
lots of critics in baggy sweaters and overcoats. Katz, looking at
60 like Daddy Warbucks in his Brooks Brothers chalk-stripe suit,
cut out to hit the town.
</P>
<P>
   His taste in New York like his taste in film is strictly
vintage. With his wife, Marty Wyle, 54, he swept a small entourage
into a waiting car. They would have hit Mortimer's, but it is gone,
and La Goulue is being renovated. So they went to Jo Jo to soak up
a couple of drinks. They are a good match. She drinks her Bombay
martini with olives, he with a twist; she thinks Grace Kelly had
the more luminous skin, he thinks Audrey Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   The Katzes have lived in the Hollywood Hills for decades in a
1922 Mediterranean-style house where they raised six children,
Brady Bunch fashion, three of hers, three of his. One of her sons
is Noah Wyle, the star of the television series ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   His conversation is nostalgic, especially about the Upper East
Side. ``I really enjoy coming back,'' he said. ``But it seems so
big now. You never used to go to Canal Street or SoHo. You know,
I'm not very with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, he said, he would go see Angela Lansbury sing.
``I'm accused of having a gay gene,'' Katz said of his love for
cabaret, old movies and old standards. He met Michael Feinstein,
the lounge singer, when Katz produced ``Scenes From the Class
Struggle in Beverly Hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he produced ``Lust in the Dust'' and befriended
Divine. ``Did you know his parents were nursery school teachers?''
asked Ms. Wyle, a retired nurse, whose experience paid off when her
husband was in charge of the 1983 rerelease of ``Rear Window'' and
Jimmy Stewart was ailing. ``They only let him go to Europe because
I was a nurse,'' she recalled. ``We all shared a two-bedroom hotel
suite.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was time to dash to the Cafe Carlyle, where Eartha
Kitt was about to do her 10:45 show. The Katzes took a table front
and center. More martinis. Ms. Kitt took the stage like a griot of
some ancient animistic cabaret religion. She overcame pepper-mill
bearing waiters, late hours and gravity by sheer force of will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw her in 1952,'' Katz said with excitement. ``My dad took
me to see her 48 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   She announced from the stage that she'd be turning 73 on Jan.
17. ``She's still got the voice, that's a relief,'' Katz said.
``Great body, great dress.'' His appraisal was in keeping with his
passion for all the great old classics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
