u i BC-BRITAIN-DANDO-0108-CO     01-07 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-DANDO-0108-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITISH TV PERSONALITY'S MYSTERIOUS MURDER STILL STUMPS
INVESTIGATORS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Eight months after the mysterious murder of one of
Britain's most beloved television personalities, Scotland Yard
remains short of clear suspects mired in inconclusive leads.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Dando, 37, died instantly April 26 when she was shot once
in the head with a 9mm pistol at the front door of her house in
London's trendy Fulham district. In addition to anchoring the BBC's
Six O'Clock news, Dando also hosted two popular weekly shows _ the
detective series, Crimewatch, and the travel show, Holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The murder and its implications about the cost of fame still
trouble TV personalities here. ``When you are in people's living
rooms, there is always the risk of attracting unwanted attention,''
said Sue Barker, a BBC sportscaster and Dando's friend. ``If you do
a job like mine _ and I love what I do _ you can't live your life
constantly looking over your shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the shooting took place in broad daylight, there
were no witnesses. Neighbors reported seeing more than 20 men who
seemed even a little suspicious _ leads still being followed by
police.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Scotland Yard said it will send investigators to the
United States to consult with FBI ballistic and forensic experts.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Paul Conlan, the longtime Scotland Yard chief, lists the
unsolved case among the major frustrations that will haunt him
after he retires at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the privilege and joy of knowing Jill,'' Conlan told The
Evening Standard. ``If you know the victim the challenge seems that
much greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Conlan is convinced that the killer will not go unpunished.
``This case is solvable _ and it will be solved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't solved, it won't be for a lack of trying. Scotland
Yard has spent more than $60,000 a week investigating what a police
agency spokesman describes as ``thousands of leads.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have yet to establish a clear motive for the killing.
Dando wasn't robbed, and there was no apparent burglary of the
home. Some investigators have speculated that she may have been the
victim of a stalker.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by a lack of progress, detectives met secretly in
mid-December at a London hotel to assess where the investigation
was heading, according to local press reports. The meeting also was
meant to bring in the probe's new chief, Brian Moore, a former
undercover investigator assigned to target police corruption.
</P>
<P>
   These days investigators are focused on records of mobile phone
calls made in the area the day Dando was killed. An estimated
10,000 calls were made in the heavily populated neighborhood that
day, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe that the killer made at least one call soon after
the shooting. Witnesses reported seeing a man talking on a mobile
phone between 10:30 a.m. and 10:40 a.m. outside Dando's home. A
sweating man later was seen talking into a phone as he ran up a
street away from the scene of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Police found six distinctive marks on the cartridge case of the
fatal bullet. Experts believe the round may have been tampered
with, possibly to reduce the amount of powder to deaden the sound
of the blast. Neighbors told police they heard no shot, only a
scream.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland Yard detectives will consult with U.S. ballistic
experts about the type of gun used in the attack and the apparent
modification of the bullet.
</P>
<P>
   However, Conlan denied that the force's decision to seek help in
the United States represents an act of desperation. ``There's a
premier league of police forces around the world,'' he said. ``The
FBI and the (Metropolitan Police) are world players. We work
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took 20 years to catch the Uni-bomber in the United States.
We will keep looking for Jill's killer until he is found.''
</P>
<P>
   Just four months before the shooting, Dando became engaged to
gynecologist Alan
</P>
<P>
   Farthing. They were to be married in September. On the day of
her shooting, she reportedly told Farthing's mother that she
planned to spend the day planning for the big event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've actually got today free, and I'm going to look through
some honeymoon details,'' she is reported to have told Farthing.
</P>
<P>
   But as she returned home in the late morning, she was shot at
close range on her doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden, violent death left all of Britain stunned. Queen
Elizabeth and Prime Minister Tony Blair immediately issued
statements of shock and horror. Within hours, mourners began
visiting the tree-lined avenue where she lived to lay flowers and
notes. It reminded many of the country's response to the death of
Princess Diana, who was killed in a Paris car crash in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jill was a princess among ordinary people,'' Bob Wheaton, her
former BBC producer and onetime boyfriend, said at the time.
``Wherever she went, she left the same impression _ a warm, kind
and gentle person who cared.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
