<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-LUXURY-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOP AMERICAN LUXURY BRAND? (HINT: IT'S GERMAN) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9)  
 (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sales of luxury cars (and luxury trucks) rose again last year,
and most manufacturers reported gains. Conspicuous exceptions were
the two American luxury brands, Cadillac and Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, the American marques lost their place at the top
of the sales chart for the first time ever. Mercedes-Benz moved
into the No.1 spot with sales of 189,437 cars and sport utility
vehicles. Second place went to Lexus _ a brand that celebrated its
10th birthday only last year _ with 185,890 sales.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln, which a year ago passed Cadillac for the first time
since 1939, fell to fourth place as its sales plunged by 10,628.
Cadillac was in third, ahead of Lincoln once again, but its sales
fell, too, by 4,063.
</P>
<P>
   With an increase of more than 22,000, to 153,658, and a hot new
sport utility, the X5, BMW is also within striking distance of the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Other big gainers were Jaguar, up 56 percent; Audi, 39 percent;
Land Rover, 37 percent, and Saab, 29 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
