<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9636 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-FLAT-PANTS-ART-$ADV09     01-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAT-PANTS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE PANTS FRONT: THE WAR OF THE PLEATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 9.)  
(DW) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some things I refuse to wear. Shoes that buckle up on
the side, those brown thatched leather belts that scream ``casual
Friday'' and pleated pants. The first two have been easy enough to
avoid. The pleats have been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, if you were a guy who preferred flat-front to
pleated pants, you were in trouble. You had to track them down,
like a big-game hunter on the trail of an endangered species, or
else have them made. I did both, until flat started to come back in
the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Prada and Gucci led the return to 1960s sleek. Their neo-Rat
Pack silhouette began to elbow out the drapy Armani look, whose
multipleated nadir may have been those white Aladdin-style pants
Don Johnson wore on ``Miami Vice.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Barneys does not even sell pleated pants in its
sportswear department. Donna Karan men's wear is 85 percent
flat-front. There is evidence, too, that in Middle America the
pendulum is swinging back to flat. In November, the men's-wear
trade publication DNR reported the good news on its cover: ``In Age
Old Debate, Flat-Fronts Now Gain on Pleats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For all those who lose sleep at night waiting for a silhouette
change,'' the article announced, ``it's here, with all the
ramifications.'' At Banana Republic, flat chinos were for the first
time narrowly outselling pleats at the 300-plus stores in the
chain, DNR said. Sales of flat-front casual pants at Federated
Department Stores, which owns Bloomingdale's and Macy's _ bastions
of Dockers and Haggar pleats _ are approaching 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wondering where J. Crew, another bellwether of mainstream taste,
is lining up on this ``age-old debate,'' I called Emily Woods, its
chairwoman and co-founder. ``My first inclination is to say flat,
flat, flat,'' Ms. Woods said. ``We have moved from 60 percent
pleats just under two years ago in both styles and sales to just
over 50 percent flat-front.'' She added that J. Crew's first
stone-washed, stone-colored chino, introduced when the company
started in 1983, was flat-front.
</P>
<P>
   We know fashion goes back and forth, and back again. But for
men, trends seem to cycle more slowly than for women. I've been
waiting a long time for pleats to go away. Or maybe it just feels
that way because pleats make me look fat. Or at least a little
fuller in the hip area than I'd like.
</P>
<P>
   Pleats are allegedly more comfortable. But if you're a
relatively young man and you're wearing clothes primarily for
comfort, rather than to look good, you've sort of given up, haven't
you? Perhaps you've also started wearing Rockports instead of
proper dress shoes? Are pleats actually more comfortable? A 34
waist is a 34 waist, whatever kind of accordioning of fabric and
fat is going on underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men have really learned to understand flat-front pants,'' said
Don Witkowski,'' the president of Donna Karan and DKNY men's wear.
``I think they thought pleats hid parts of the man's body, like
overweightness or whatever, because there was more fabric on the
front, which is just a fallacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of stretch fabrics has gone hand in hand with
the flat revival, and stretch will do more on the comfort front
than pleats ever could.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the vanity issue, the slim, clean line of flat-front,
straight pants are part of aretro aesthetic I've had since I used
to borrow my dad's skinny ties in high school. It goes with the
mid-century mod furniture in my apartment and the voices in my head
telling me I was born 30 years too late to buy one of Rob Petrie's
Botany 500 suits or guzzle highballs at El Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Watching ``The Graduate'' (1967) the other night on Turner
Classic Movies, I coveted Dustin Hoffman's wardrobe, his preppy
button-downs and flat-front chinos. Steve McQueen and Sean
Connery's James Bond set off similar pangs of sartorial envy.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a little historical perspective, I asked John Weitz,
the 77-year-old designer, about pleats versus flat-front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it all goes in circles,'' he said. ``The modern-day
circle started after the war, when the men came back wearing what
are now unfortunately known as chinos but were then called suntans,
because they were a tan pant and they were flat.'' Until then,
Weitz continued, ``the only people who wore flat pants were the
upper classes. You saw them in Brooks Brothers and the Ivy League.
The rest of the country wore great big pleated pants in a rather
bad imitation of the Duke of Windsor.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Weitz boils it down, Americans wore flat-fronts until
Europeans, trying to look like Americans in old Hollywood movies,
started doing pleats and convincing Americans to copy them.
Head-spinning, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   He's right about Brooks Brothers, though. Three years ago, I
finally got around to buying a tuxedo and the only place I could
find one with a flat-front pair of pants was at Brooks Brothers.
(J. Press, the other old-money clothier, also stuck with
flat-fronts during the dark ages.) The leg was a little wide, but
it was the best I could do at the time.
</P>
<P>
   I would also argue that flat-front is a more enduring way to go.
Sure, Cary Grant was always dapper in pleats. He was Cary Grant.
But in the '60s, when flat-fronts were standard issue, you didn't
have to be President Kennedy to look sharp in them. They could make
Joey Bishop look hep. Try digging up a picture of yourself in a
pair of billowy triple-pleats, circa 1984. Now burn it and if you
still have them, the pants, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
