<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Saturday, January 8 , 2000,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-MANAGEMENT _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola President Doug Daft, who
is expected to be named chairman in April, reshook a recent shakeup
of top management, naming a new marketing chief and new head of the
soft drink maker's European operations. The selection of current
marketing chief Charlie Frenette as head of the European operations
and the choice of Minute Maid President Stephen Jones to replace
Frenette, was widely praised on Wall Street, which sent Coke's
stock up sharply. E arlier this week, he pursuaded Carl Ware to
head a new global public affairs division. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUILDNET _ BuildNet, the largest software and e-commerce company
in the building industry and headed by a former Home Depot senior
vice president, is attracting a lot of venture capital to expand
its business. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLOORING _ Flooring America Inc., formerly Maxim Group Inc., the
top U.S. carpet retailer, accused 34 suspected employees identified
only by Internet names of misappropriating confidential information
and ``possible'' securities fraud. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DEGREG-SOCOMPANY _ The Southern Co. is kicking off a new $8
million national marketing campaign Tuesday with a fullpage color
ad in The Wall Street Journal that is aimed at opinion-makers that
might be in a position to invest or make big energy buys. The
campaign is Southern's second during the last three years as the
company prepares for eventual deregulation of the electric utility
industry. (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   HUFFY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The investment banker looking at the
possible sale, merger or other strategic choices for Huffy Corp.
has presented the company with some potential alternatives but no
decisions have been made, according to Don R. Graber, Huffy
chairman, president and CEO. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
