<SLUG> BC-WHIP-RACE-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PELOSI DISHES OUT DOLLARS TO PAVE WAY FOR WHIP RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Jan. 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
    c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi is following a formula perfected
by Republican Rep. Tom DeLay as she revs up her campaign for
Democratic whip in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The DeLay formula: Raise campaign funds and share the money with
fellow House candidates in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   If Pelosi's efforts are successful, the Democrats would regain
control of the House and she then would call in her chits to win
election to the majority whip's post, the No. 3 job in the party's
House hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, a Democrat from San Francisco, said last week she thus
far has raised $700,000 and contributed nearly $500,000 to her
party's House candidates, mostly to women and minorities and to
candidates in tight races.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi brushes aside any comparison to DeLay. She says
fundraising is essential for victory and that without aggressive
fundraising, Democrats will ``get overwhelmed by Republican
money.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay clinched the Republican whip's job after his party
captured a majority of House seats in the 1994 election, the first
time in 40 years that the GOP controlled the House.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay gave nearly $2 million to Republican House candidates in
that election. They showed their appreciation by electing him whip
over two rivals in the secret ballot of House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Besides handing out cash, DeLay helped GOP candidates by hiring
a political consultant to provide campaign tips. He also
distributed a video of his own motivational advice for the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said last week that his victory had ``nothing to do with
money.'' Instead, ``It has to do with building relationships,'' he
said, adding that the key to his success was ``analyzing races and
making sure you're involved.''
</P>
<P>
   John Feehery, spokesman for House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, who
managed DeLay's whip campaign, said a lot of members ``owed'' DeLay
because of his hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``DeLay really took it to a new level with the amount of money
he raised,'' Feehery said.
</P>
<P>
   The whip is elected by party members who cast secret ballots for
leadership posts _ usually in December after an election. The whip
is the party's top vote-counter in the House. As the party
disciplinarian, the whip also works to keep members in line on
leadership votes. The job requires organizing coalitions, listening
to members and sometimes twisting their arms.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats seize control of Congress, Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, now the Democratic leader in the House, is expected to be
elected speaker. Rep. David E. Bonior of Michigan, now the party
whip, would become majority leader, leaving open the post of
majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   For Pelosi's scenario to have a chance, the Democrats must first
win control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi created a political action committee, called PAC to the
Future, which she uses to raise funds and contribute to her
selected candidates. Federal law limits her PAC to $5,000
contributions to a candidate in the primary election and $5,000 for
a candidate in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the $700,000 raised by her PAC came from a San Francisco
fund-raiser at the St. Francis Hotel in November with former Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said she has given Democratic candidates and her party
more than $300,000 so far from her PAC and more than $150,000 from
her own campaign coffers, which she says she can afford because her
seat is safe.
</P>
<P>
   She says `'is not trying to break any records'' raising money
but will raise more if candidates need it.
</P>
<P>
   She also plans to hold four fund-raisers in her home in
California for Democratic candidates before the March primary. Her
preferred California candidates are Mike Honda, who is running for
the seat vacated by Rep. Tom Campbell; Susan Davis, who is
challenging Rep. Brian Bilbray; Jane Harman, who is running against
Rep. Steve Kuykendall, and Adam Schiff who is challenging Rep.
James Rogan.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi also says she is ``going one step beyond with helping
women candidates and minority candidates'' even if they aren't in
the most competitive races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to encourage more diversity in Congress,'' Pelosi
said.
</P>
<P>
   She says the 10 percent representation women have in the House
is inadequate, especially when the lawmakers consider such issues
as Social Security, Medicare and women's health.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steny H. Hoyer, D-Md., who would be her chief rival in the
whip's race if Democrats win control of the House in November, says
he is relying on relationships he has established, rather than on
dishing out dollars. Hoyer says he has given less than $100,000 to
Democratic candidates, and has about $225,000 in his political
action committee left to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``If money is the arbiter of who's going to win this race, I
don't expect to win it,'' Hoyer said. He says he has traveled from
Alabama to New York to work for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   As the top Democrat on the House Administration Committee, Hoyer
has another link with his Democratic colleagues. He offers them
advice and counsel on how to manage their offices and finances.
``While members are going to think raising money is important, I
think they'll appreciate my focus on winning the House back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
