 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nietzsche and Math, Together Again
</P>
<P>
   In the latest effort to convert the mathematically squeamish,
Dartmouth College has developed a new program, ``Math Across the
Curriculum,'' that integrates the subject into some very unlikely
places _ art and literature, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Matter of Time'' pairs a comparative literature professor
and a math professor to lead discussions on the fourth dimension.
Readings include ``One Hundred Years of Solitude'' by Gabriel
Garcia Marquez, the Book of Genesis and works by Freud, Nietzsche,
Poe and Borges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pattern'' explores elementary group theory and its
applications to art, ranging from mandalas to Escher to Islamic
tiles. For die-hards, ``Integrated Mathematics and Physical
Sciences'' combines math, science and physics.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which is financed by the National Science
Foundation, ``presents math in the most integrated fashion, using
students' interests as the hook,'' explained Dr. Jane Korey, an
anthropologist and consultant on the project. ``We all learn better
if we can attach ideas to something we already know, so if you're a
strong literature person and the math you use has to do with
literature, you can bootstrap your way up.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``It shows students that math is relevant to their
lives and will be useful to their futures. Math is a whole way of
looking at the world.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ABBY ELLIN
</P>
<P>
   Changing Times at Harvard Law
</P>
<P>
   Image is everything, especially if you are a hallowed
institution trying to alter unflattering public perception. So it
is with Harvard Law School, long synonymous with cut-throat
competition, back-stabbing students and terrorizing professors a la
``Paper Chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Change is indeed afoot. The school's Institutional Life
Committee is exploring ways to diminish the emphasis on grades,
including making the first term pass-fail and reducing the
distinctions from nine letter grades to four categories _ high
honors, honors, pass or fail. The changes could be carried out as
early as next fall, said professor Elizabeth Warren, the committee
chairwoman. The school is also hoping to hire more teachers to
reduce class sizes and offer students more individual attention.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are being considered at the suggestion of McKinsey &AMP;
Co., a New York consulting firm that was hired last year to gauge
the school's mood. The company held dozens of focus groups with
students, faculty members and alumni on everything from the state
of the gymnasium (shabby) to class size (too large) to grading
(fierce) to professor accessibility (limited).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small part of a broad review of the law school's
academic enterprise,'' said Michael Chmura, the law school news
director, explaining the study and proposed changes.
</P>
<P>
   It has nothing to do, he added, with the fact that Harvard Law
has slipped to No. 2 in the U.S. News &AMP; World Report rankings,
behind its archrival, Yale.
</P>
<P>
   _ ABBY ELLIN
</P>
<P>
   No Sex, No Alcohol, Just Government
</P>
<P>
   On 44 acres of secluded land in Virginia, about an hour west of
Washington, the foundation is being laid for an experiment in
higher education _ the nation's first post-secondary institution
designed for home-schooled students and a training ground for
Christian political advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Henry College, to open this fall in Purcellville, aims
to ``help return America to its biblical and constitutional
roots,'' as the literature states. Initially, only bachelor's
degrees in government are being offered, though Michael P. Farris,
the founder and president, is considering an entertainment major _
to nurture a generation of Christian ``storytellers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In very broad terms, I want our students to engage the
culture,'' said Farris, who heads the Home School Legal Defense
Association and was the 1993 Republican nominee for lieutenant
governor of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   For the first year, officials expect to enroll 100 students, 80
to 90 percent of whom would be home-schooled _ a movement fueled,
in part, by parental discontent over the secularization of schools.
All Patrick Henry students must be Christians who can demonstrate
``a personal relationship with Jesus Christ,'' Farris said, and
should engage in Christian social activities.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a gentleman who wishes to court a young lady will
be encouraged to contact her parents, or at the least have her seek
their permission before joining him on group outings. Male and
female dorms will be on opposite sides of the campus, and
premarital sex and alcohol are to be banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a philosophical level, we want to encourage students to
think of relationships as preparing for a lifelong commitment,''
said Bradley P. Jacob, the provost and dean of the college.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators say there are no plans for any dating police.
``The essence of the Christian life is forgiveness,'' Farris said.
``We're not going to ask them what they did. We're going to ask
them what they plan to do.''
</P>
<P>
   _IAN ZACK
</P>
<P>
   Don't Call Them Kelly Girls
</P>
<P>
   The business of hiring substitute teachers _ once a low-key,
word-of-mouth affair and increasingly a frenetic, haphazard
scramble _ has just become a little more crisp. Kelly Services,
whose so-called Kelly girls began pinch-hitting in the office in
1946, now recruits, trains and manages substitute teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly is starting the program in response to a nationwide sub
shortage: 96 percent of roughly 500 school districts that were
surveyed by the Substitute Teaching Institute at Utah State
University said they often came up short. According to Geoffrey G.
Smith, who manages the institute, an educational group that helped
Kelly create its training program, the shortage is fueled by the
lack of available labor in a hot economy and an increase in
professional development sessions, which take teachers away from
the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   A Kelly manual explains the mysteries of school life, like
passes and study halls. The service also trains substitute teachers
to handle situations like what to do when the lesson is over but
the time period is not (beforehand, make a ``super sub pack''
filled with time-consuming activities).
</P>
<P>
   So what gives first-timers the most jitters? ``The first five
seconds,'' said Carl Camden, Kelly's executive vice president.
``You walk into the room, and things are flying in the air and
children are involved in their own conversations. If you speak,
will they listen? How do you get their attention?''
</P>
<P>
   Camden's advice: Speak softly. It's far more effective than
shouting.
</P>
<P>
   _ BRIAN HANSON-HARDING
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Spirits and Spirituals
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible to develop character while living in Animal
House? ``Colleges That Encourage Character Development,'' a new
guide to 400 institutions with programs fostering honesty,
integrity and all-around good character, has made room for the
State University of New York at Albany. Singled out for a peer
counseling program, Albany was also ranked No. 1 party school last
year by another organization, the Princeton Review.
</P>
<P>
   Four colleges on this year's party list, compiled from a survey
of students nationwide, showed enough sobriety and good ethical
form for the guide's publisher, Templeton Foundation Press, which
is part of the foundation financed by Sir John Templeton, the
mutual fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must have completely reversed our character,'' said Vincent
Reda, a spokesman for SUNY Albany, which like other institutions of
higher education denounces the Princeton Review list as a gross
misrepresentation of its campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Schwartz, who edited the new guide, said Albany's feeling
of vindication might be appropriate: A university with a drinking
problem can promote ``spiritual growth'' if it is trying to
discourage bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Other colleges qualifying for both the party and character list
include Michigan State University in East Lansing (for encouraging
community service); Seton Hall University in South Orange, N.J.
(for its volunteer service requirement for freshmen); the
University of Alabama at Tuscaloosa (for a theater group that
addresses social temptations), and Washington State University at
Pullman (for freshmen seminars urging research of social issues).
</P>
<P>
   Selections were gleaned from 2,000 nominations and made by a
panel of educators in conjunction with the Institute on College
Student Values at Florida State University in Tallahassee. That
would be the Florida State University that was ranked No. 1 party
school this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Character is a lifelong process, and college has a unique role
to play,' Schwartz said. ``So many kids were party animals even
before they came to college.''
</P>
<P>
   _ RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD
</P>
<P>
   Live From College, It's ... a Messy Room
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to modern technology, students can broadcast their very
own ``Real World'' from the privacy of their dorm rooms. All they
need is a Webcam and the sense that the minutiae of their everyday
lives _ He eats! He studies! He sleeps! _ are worth sharing 24/7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought college kids are an interesting
demographic,'' said Alex Chriss, 22, who founded WebDorm last
February (www.webdorm.com) when he was a junior at Tufts University
in Medford, Mass. ``It's the only time of your life you're all
together.''
</P>
<P>
   About 25 students from around the country are ``featured Web
dormers'' for one semester. In exchange for software and Webcams,
which beam their images onto the Internet, they must write and post
journals, chat online at least two hours a week, keep cameras
turned on at all times and have a roommate who doesn't mind living
in a fishbowl.
</P>
<P>
   The images, which are updated every 25 seconds, are often
blurry. But they are good enough to decipher what the students are
doing. Sex, drugs and nudity are forbidden, but that's a small
price to pay. After all, being a featured dormer is prestigious:
During a flesh-and-blood meeting in Boston, Chriss said, several
Web dormers were walking through Harvard Square when a group of
Harvard and MIT students stopped them and said, ``You're the Web
dormers, I've seen you online!'' Chriss added, ``They were
attaining this celebrity status.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody Ward, 21, a senior at the University of Florida at
Gainesville, was a Web dormer last spring and still keeps a camera
aimed at himself, posting images on his own site
(www.geocities.com/g8rcody/). ``It just seemed like something fun
to do, just for the thrill of letting my friends and family see
me,'' he said. ``I don't know if it's a purely American phenomenon,
but people like spying on other people and seeing what they're up
to. As long as people want to watch, I don't mind broadcasting my
life.'' People evidently watch; Ward meets five to 10 new people
online each day.
</P>
<P>
   The real-life broadcast was popularized, of course, by ``The
Real World,'' the MTV show that offers a peek into the lives of
Generation X roommates. Jennifer Ringley, who perched a Web camera
in her dorm room at Dickinson College in Carlisle, Pa., in 1996,
was a pioneer of the format online; she can still be found going
about her business at www.jennicam.com. Now there are virtual dorm
sites like www.vdorm. com/thedorm/main.asp, a forum for live-action
chats among students.
</P>
<P>
   So, what is life like with a camera trained on every move?
</P>
<P>
   ``I forget the camera is on,'' Ward said. ``I've had it on for
over a year and only occasionally turn it off. It feels weird
turning it off, I'm so used to being watched.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ABBY ELLIN
</P>
<P>
   BLACKBOARD: TECHNOLOGY: Bedside Classrooms
</P>
<P>
   It's hard enough for children to be hospitalized. Falling behind
in school and losing touch with friends only adds to the trauma. To
combat that isolation, hospitals are incorporating technology into
children's wards to help patients stay connected with their lives
back home.
</P>
<P>
   When Montefiore Medical Center in the Bronx, N.Y., opens a
children's hospital next year, every child's bedside will be
equipped with a computer that has Internet access. Similar plans
are under way for new children's facilities at the Westchester
Medical Center in Valhalla, N.Y., and the Columbia-Presbyterian
Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, children's wards have included classrooms. The
New York City Board of Education runs a program in 40 hospitals for
public and private school students, coordinating lesson plans with
each child's school district. Patients who are well enough attend
morning classes; those who are not ambulatory receive bedside
teaching in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Using computers, students can communicate directly with their
own teachers and tap into hospital databanks to get information
about their illness. And Starbright, a nonprofit computer network
for hospitalized children, puts students in contact with peers who
may be struggling with the same disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child wants to feel like every other child,'' said
Cynthia N. Sparer, the executive director of Babies Hospital at
Columbia-Presbyterian. ``It is particularly important for children
with chronic conditions, like cancer or cystic fibrosis, to keep
up. And that achieves one of our other goals: We do not want them
to focus 100 percent on their medical problems. We want them to
focus on being kids.''
</P>
<P>
   _ KATE STONE LOMBARDI
</P>
</TEXT>
