<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9670 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i BC-RED-ARMY-DISASTER-SLA     01-07 1647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED-ARMY-DISASTER-SLATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MILITARY: NOT MIGHTY, NOT RED, AND BARELY AN ARMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (From Slate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   (David Plotz is Slate's Washington bureau chief.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID PLOTZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, the Soviet army saved the world from Nazism by holding
Stalingrad while the Germans pounded it to rubbe. Today, that
army's delinquent stepchild, the Russian army, is fighting a city
battle of its own.
</P>
