<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f PM-ECON-REPORT-ART-NYT &LR;      01-07 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
JOB GROWTH CONTINUED AT A ROBUST PACE IN DECEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
 PM-ECON-REPORT-ART-NYT  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Employers added jobs at a surprisingly robust rate
in December, propelling the economy into the new year with
considerable momentum, the Labor Department reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The economy created 315,000 new jobs last month, 75,000 more
than economists had predicted and the biggest one-month gain since
July. With more people entering the job market, the unemployment
rate remained at a 30-year low of 4.1 percent, where it has been
for the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Average hourly earnings for the month rose by 0.4 percent,
slightly higher than expected. But because workers are producing
more for each hour worked, the growth in wages so far shows few
signs of setting off a surge in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   While good news across the board, the figures substantially
increased the likelihood that the Federal Reserve will act to keep
the economy from overheating by raising interest rates next month.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, investors acknowledged that a rate increase is
now all but certain, but concluded that inflationary pressures are
so muted that the Fed would limit the increase to a quarter of a
percentage point rather than the half point increase that the
markets had come to fear in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Both blue chip and technology stocks rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough strength in this report to make it a virtual
certainty the Fed will tighten in February,'' said Stuart G.
Hoffman, an economist at PNC Corp. in Pittsburgh. ``But I think a
quarter of a point is all that's likely to come from the Fed, and
appropriately so because this report is not so exceedingly strong
as to force the Fed into a more aggressive increase.''
</P>
<P>
   The report left little doubt that the economy would continue
growing for another month, all but assuring that the current
business expansion will become the nation's longest in February at
8 years and 11 months, breaking a record set in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said the report was further
evidence that their policy of fiscal prudence was helping to create
jobs across the income spectrum. And with the presidential race
heating up, the figures gave Vice President Al Gore a boost in his
effort to cast himself as the best candidate to keep the economy on
a roll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
