<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9677 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-07 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLICE PREPARE FOR SECURITY AT TRIAL OF NEW YORK OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MELISSA GRACE  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Authorities here said they would ban the use of
bullhorns by the thousands of demonstrators expected to come to
protest during the trial of four white New York City police
officers accused of murdering a West African immigrant in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The police are revealing few details about the security plans,
except to say they expect up to 1,000 protesters a day.
</P>
<P>
   Albany Police Chief John C. Nielsen said any demonstrators would
likely be confined to a park across from the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   And if supporters of Amadou Diallo, the 22-year-old victim, or
the officers accused in the racially charged shooting travel from
New York City to demonstrate, local officials will have to guard
against potential clashes between the two groups in the park,
Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen said bullhorns will be banned to keep the noise down and
that if any are used they will be confiscated. He said that
crowd-control measures, including mounted police officers and a
barricade around the perimeter of the courthouse, would be in place
when the trial opens Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of the Bronx officers was moved to Albany last month
after an appeals court ruled that blanket media coverage of the
case had poisoned the New York City jury pool.
</P>
<P>
   The case sparked weeks of demonstrations in New York City, where
more than 1,500 people were arrested in protests in the weeks after
Diallo was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The police chief said that he was in contact with the Rev. Al
Sharpton, the Harlem-based civil rights leader, about the number of
demonstrators he intended to organize. Nielsen declined to give
specifics about the potential number of protesters aside from
saying that up to 1,000 a day could travel to Albany. Sharpton did
not return repeated telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Sharpton supporters, the police say officers from
the New York City force might come to show solidarity for the
accused men _ Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon and
Richard Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, who are white, are accused of gunning down Diallo,
22, outside his Bronx home on Feb. 4, 1999, at about 12:40 a.m.
Diallo, who was black, was unarmed at the time and was struck by 19
of 41 shots fired at him.
</P>
<P>
   Security is an issue both inside and outside the Albany County
courthouse where the trial will be held. But with large protests
over the course of weeks, security is likely to be heightened at
nearby facilities as well, including the state Court of Appeals
building. Beyond the courts is City Hall, and a short distance
beyond it are the state Capitol building and the Empire State
Plaza, where thousands of workers migrate daily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1814EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
