<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      01-07 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Saturday, Jan. 8. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRUST (Phoenix) - More than a tenth of the land in Arizona is
dedicated to making money for schools. But for years, no one paid
much attention to those 8.1 million acres because they didn't bring
in much cash. Now, though, that state trust land is the center of a
hot debate. Some educators want the earnings from trust land to do
more for Arizona's schoolkids. On the other hand, some
enviornmentalists want to preserve some trust land from development
and argue that it would have little financial impact on education.
By KATHLEEN INGLEY.
</P>
<P>
   Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MENDOZA (Phoenix) - David Mendoza, the youngest heart transplant in
Arizona and the first to have two transplants (he eventually had a
third), died last night. A look at David and the history of
Arizona's transplants. By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PIMENTEL-COLUMN (Phoenix) - My mother smoked, and she paid the
price for it. Watching her die was painful. Yes, I know about
personal responsibility, but smokers have such vile accomplices.
Tobacco companies know about finding the weak ones as well. That is
why the young, whose chink is believing they are invulnerable, have
been favorite targets. We've now concluded that tobacco companies
should also be punished, though, because it's now personal with me,
this seems way late and way too little. Helping tobacco's victims
and dissuading future ones seem particularly appropriate uses for
this money. By O. RICARDO PIMENTEL. Column will move in the ``K''
category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
