<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR PATRICK O'BRIAN: CREATED A LITERARY IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In keeping with the mysteries of his life, there was doubt
exactly when Patrick O'Brian, the hugely popular author of the
Aubrey-Maturin historical novels, died in Dublin: either Tuesday or
Sunday. What was known Friday is that he was 85 and that the
recently published ``Blue at the Mizzen,'' No. 20 in the series, is
indeed the last.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other contemporary novelist, Patrick O'Brian
created his own literary identity. More than a pen name, it was a
formal persona both droll and dignified that was at one with the
18th-century world he wrote about. Beginning with ``Master and
Commander,'' the Aubrey-Maturin saga followed the adventures of
Jack Aubrey, the dashing Royal Navy captain, and his physician
friend, Stephen Maturin, through the Napoleonic wars and manifold
related maritime-political affairs of the period.
</P>
<P>
   While thick with enough derring-do and battle scenery to absorb
any schoolboy, the books are distinctive for their elegant syle and
their command of naval practice and technology, medicine, science,
politics, music, philosophy, natural history, and especially
manners. Jack and Stephen, sharply contrasting characters, are
close friends who call one another ``My dear,'' and their
characters are governed by a refined code of propriety amid shot
and shell and bodies falling left and right. Though the action
takes place in the early 19th century, the sensibility is
late-18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was such a good guide to the 18th century,'' said Katherine
A. Powers of Cambridge, Mass., an O'Brian aficionado who writes for
the Sunday Globe book pages. ``He almost seemed to have journeyed
into the 18th from the 20th and come back to us. He had adopted
this literary persona, so much so that it was him. He became an
18th-century man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. O'Brian had written several all-but-unnoticed novels in the
1950s and 1960s, including ``The Golden Ocean'' (1956), a
historical novel. In the late 1960s his American publisher,
Lippincott, suggested he write a series of the same type. The
result was the first Aubrey-Maturin novel, ``Master and Commander''
(1969). It sank in the United States but sold well in England, and
that was the pattern for the four that followed. Lippincott gave up
after ``Desolation Island'' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Starling Lawrence, an editor at W. W. Norton, was urged
by a cousin to read a book by this by-now-unknown Anglo-Irish
novelist. Lawrence was electrified and prevailed on a reluctant
Norton to publish ``The Letter of Marque,'' No. 12 in the series,
in 1990. After a rave review in The New York Times boosted sales,
Norton republished the earlier installments and has issued every
one since.
</P>
<P>
   There are now more than 2 million O'Brian novels in print. For
the faithful, there is also ``The Patrick O'Brian Newsletter,'' a
cookbook (``Lobscouse &AMP; Spotted Dog''), a CD (``Musical Evenings
with the Captain: Music from the Aubrey-Maturin Novels of Patrick
O'Brian''), all found at a popular Web site, ``The Patrick O'Brian
Page'' (at www.wwnorton.com).
</P>
<P>
   Mr. O'Brian's reticence was legendary. Before an interview
during his 1993 American tour, Lawrence firmly warned a Boston
Globe writer not to ask personal questions; when a previous
interviewer had asked, ``Mr. O'Brian, where were you born?'' the
author had angrily ended the interview and fumed later, ``Can you
imagine the impertinence of such a question?'' &UR;  &LR; It was eccentric
but consistent with the manners of his literary world: In one of
the novels, Maturin observes, ``Question and answer is not a
civilized form of conversation.'' Yet he talked wittily and volubly
about literature: His models were Jane Austen, Dr. Johnson, William
Cobbett, and George Borrow.
</P>
<P>
   It was long believed that Mr. O'Brian was born in Ireland in
1914, lived as a small child in Galway, and later with family
friends in England. Because of illness he never went to university,
and he drove an ambulance during the London Blitz, and served in an
intelligence unit in World War II. He spoke or read French,
Spanish, Catalan, Italian, and Irish. He and his wife moved to the
village of Collioure in the south of France in the 1950s, where he
lived for the rest of his life. Besides his fiction, he wrote
biographies of Picasso and the naturalist Joseph Banks, and
translated into English works by Colette and Simone de Beauvoir.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, American journalist Dean King dug into the
O'Brian story and discovered that Mr. O'Brian's real name was
Richard Patrick Russ and that he was born in England. After an
early marriage that produced two children, one of whom still lives,
he changed his name and assumed the Anglo-Irish identity.
</P>
<P>
   Although King praises the novels, his book, ``Patrick O'Brian: A
Life Revealed,'' to be published in April, is censorious, as if Mr.
O'Brian were a fraud for changing his name and a beast for his
apparent estrangement from his siblings and son. Of course his
minor mythmaking annoyed some journalists. It's as if, Lawrence
said in an interview Friday, Mr. O'Brian's change of name ``is
evidence of moral turpitude.''
</P>
<P>
   But the publishing facts are not in doubt. That a formal elderly
writer with an 18th-century style could become a sensation in the
age of ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' demonstrated that there were still
unmet desires in the reading public. In Mr. O'Brian's fiction,
Lawrence said, ``the social and personal relationships restore
something that no longer exists'' in most contemporary literature:
``honor, trust, loyalty, fidelity, open exchange of ideas among
intimate friends, always within the structure of a social contract
that dictates when you should be silent and what subjects shouldn't
come up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
