<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIMENTEL-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY MOTHER SMOKED, AND SHE PAID THE PRICE FOR IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By O. RICARDO PIMENTEL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Watching her die was painful.
</P>
<P>
   In those last months, talking was difficult, the words coming
out in ragged gasps.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted us to know she loved us, that we shouldn't worry,
that she was ready to go because living _ bedridden and drugged _
had become so very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   She'd motion me to come closer. Her hand would flutter down,
across and over in the sign of the cross, a mother's blessing as
she did every night when I was a youngster being put to bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you,'' she'd say. ``Que Dios te bendiga.'' May God
bless you.
</P>
<P>
   The last blessing came on Sept. 30. My mother died on Oct. 1.
Tobacco and emphysema killed her.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know about personal responsibility, but smokers have such
vile accomplices.
</P>
<P>
   She started smoking at 14, a young immigrant girl fresh from a
Zacatecas farm, working in laundries and eager to be grown up and
thinking smoking made it so.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Gaeta Pimentel had few vices, rarely drinking and an
unfinished ``Aye que la . . . (what the . . .)'' being the extent
of her curse-word vocabulary. I often wondered as a kid how ``Aye
que la'' was supposed to end.
</P>
<P>
   But smoking was definitely her demon. We'd plead, cajole and
respectfully request that she quit. The answer was always the same.
``I can't, mijo (my son).''
</P>
<P>
   Even after being diagnosed with emphysema, she'd sneak
cigarettes. Tobacco's grip is that strong, that deadly.
</P>
<P>
   It's just a fact of life. If you've got something bad to sell,
your best customers are the weak ones, the ones with chinks in
their armor. Drug pushers know it. Con artists know it. Society
knows it as well, which is why we punish drug pushers and con
artists when we catch them.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies know about finding the weak ones as well. That
is why the young, whose chink is believing they are invulnerable,
have been favorite targets.
</P>
<P>
   We've now concluded that tobacco companies should also be
punished, though, because it's now personal with me, this seems way
late and way too little. It's funny thinking of $3 billion _
Arizona's share of a national settlement with the tobacco industry
_ as being too little.
</P>
<P>
   Helping tobacco's victims and dissuading future ones seem
particularly appropriate uses for this money.
</P>
<P>
   On this last part, dissuading future victims, I think my mother
would want to do her part. So, I don't think she'd mind if I
described her last days to you if it means even one cigarette going
unsmoked. Or maybe, this is just me wanting her death to not seem
so useless.
</P>
<P>
   She'd lie in her bed laboring to breathe. As a young woman, she
was lively, on the go, enjoying family, particularly enjoying doing
things for family. But here in her bed, trying to find that next
breath, she'd think only, ``How much longer?''
</P>
<P>
   Her advancing illness meant being constantly medicated in the
final years _ things to help her breathe, things to help with the
pain, things to help her deal with the effects of all the other
things she was taking. Diabetes set in. Someone said the steroids
had something to do with that _ I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Where she was once slight, she became heavy and puffy. Her whole
body seemed swollen, as a matter of fact.
</P>
<P>
   She'd lie in bed, waiting for the next dose of whatever. Nights
were scary. Her husband, my father, is hard of hearing, so she
wondered what would happen if one of the bad spells came on again.
So, the family took turns spending the night.
</P>
<P>
   We'd hover and tend to her needs. And this was the most
difficult thing for her.
</P>
<P>
   She had been the one to care for others. Her menudo and tamales
were legend. Her sweetness and caring were, too. But being cared
for made her feel so helpless, so frustrated. She'd get depressed
about that and about the waiting. The tears, in those last days,
flowed easily.
</P>
<P>
   And through it all, there was the constant fight for breath. Her
chest felt like it was being crushed, she'd say.
</P>
<P>
   The priest and the lay ministers visited often. She went quickly
one morning, knowing she was ready. The rest of us couldn't
possibly have been.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she did this to herself, but she did it with tobacco. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Pimentel at ricardo.pimentel(at)ArizonaRepublic.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
