<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CONGRESS-STAKES-$ADV9     01-07 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-STAKES-$ADV9-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAKES HIGH AS REPUBLICANS TRY TO KEEP CONTROL OF CONGRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Jan. 9, 2000) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans head toward the most important election
of their six-year term as the majority party on Capitol Hill and
following a lackluster first run of the 106th Congress, they are
hoping for a better review in the coming session.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. The Democrats must win only five more seats
in the 2000 elections to retake control of the House, which the
Republicans captured in 1994 for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Senate, where the GOP has a 55-45 seat edge, is not
likely to see a Democratic takeover, the chances of the Democrats
re-emerging in the House look better than at anytime in the past
six years.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true most incumbents on both sides of the aisle will
have little trouble winning re-election, the bad news for
Republicans is that they will be defending 19 open seats to only
five for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 19, seven to 10 may be in jeopardy if Democrats field
the right candidate and spend enough money.
</P>
<P>
   Neither recruitment nor money appears a problem this year for
Democrats, who have done better than usual in raising money for
crucial House and Senate campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In fact they've done so well that House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, the GOP's top fund-raiser, has had to work hard and
creatively to keep dollars pouring in to help Republican races.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his own political action committee, known as
Americans for a Republican Majority, DeLay and some of his former
aides have helped create several groups to collect additional money
for the GOP cause. Plans are, said one DeLay associate, ``to spend
it heavily in competitive districts'' where the Democrats have a
good shot at winning.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay normally channels much of the bounty from his fund-raising
efforts to conservative Republicans. But this year, a lot of the
money will end up going to moderate GOP candidates in threatened
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What wealth we have, we plan to share _ wherever it's
needed,'' said the DeLay associate.
</P>
<P>
   As an indication of how close some of the congressional contests
will be, business has stepped up its giving to Democrats this
election cycle as opposed to past years when Republicans usually
got two-thirds more from special interest givers than the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, said one Washington corporate lobbyist whose company
has given more to Republicans in recent years than Democrats, is
because ``2000 is viewed as pretty much a toss-up election year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats have a good shot, and I think that's what a lot
of business givers believe right now,'' the lobbyist said.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take more than money and attractive candidates for
either side to do well next November. The crucial element, both
sides agree, will be ``message.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, many political analysts agree, the Republicans
are struggling with message. A year-end attempt to recast
themselves as the protectors of Social Security instead of tax
cutters must resonate with the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the best efforts of the GOP during the budget
negotiations last fall with President Clinton, polls show that most
Americans still believe that Democrats will do a better job of
protecting Social Security than Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, have been encouraged by recent polls
showing that most Americans are more in tune with their views on
major issues than Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Several year end polls, for example, including a Washington Post
study of major voter concerns, gave Democrats a 6 percent to 7
percent edge over Republicans in this fall's election showdown.
</P>
<P>
   And the top issues identified by those surveyed in the Post and
other studies resemble items that the Democrats tried to get
through the first session of Congress against strong Republican
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   They include managed health care reform known as the ``patients
bill of rights,'' gun control measures, prescription drug benefits
for Medicare patients, a boost in the minimum wage, campaign
finance reform, and improved public education through teacher
hiring and reduced class size.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the spring trying unsuccessfully to convict
Clinton on impeachment charges, the only major legislation
Republicans pushed hard was a $792 billion tax cut bill. But most
Americans turned a deaf ear on GOP attempts to sell it. Clinton
vetoed it without any public backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Republicans are scrambling to find ways to avoid being
labeled a do-nothing Congress as they begin campaigning in earnest
for the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., is talking about reviving
the managed care reform bill, the minimum wage measure, gun control
legislation, and even Social Security and Medicare reform measures.
But most of those issues are still viewed as Democratic agenda
items. So Republican leaders are also talking about breaking out
provisions of their failed tax cut package last year and offering
them as separate pieces of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   They include bills that would eliminate estate taxes, expand
education savings accounts and repeal the marriage penalty. They
may also try to pass another overhaul of welfare laws, a victim's
bill of rights and Internal Revenue Service reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking for is an offensive plan to make (the
Democrats) vote on our issues rather than them forcing us to vote
on theirs,'' said one top Republican aide.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., who heads the National Republican
Campaign Committee, acknowledged recently that the Republican goal
last year was to do ``no harm'' instead of aggressively pushing an
agenda that might conflict with the presidential campaign of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush. Bush has the backing of 160 of 222 GOP members
of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush political strategist Karl Rove told reporters recently that
if the governor wins the nomination he hopes to ``set the tone and
the agenda'' for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expects the leadership of the Republican Congress will be
supportive of that,'' Rove said, adding that a Bush victory in
November could help in tight congressional races that ``will be
decided on the margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the elections are still 11 months away, many
Republicans are banking on being able to ride Bush's coattails to
an increased majority in Congress. But while Bush's favorability
ratings have remained high among likely voters, those for members
of Congress have sunk, indicating that voters may be more than
willing to separate the two when they go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't rely on coattails. They just don't exist anymore,''
said Eric Smith, communications director for the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats learned that lesson in 1996 and 1998 when Clinton won
re-election. Although they picked up seats in each of those
election cycles, Clinton's strong job approval ratings and the
booming economy didn't help at all in the closer races.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Republicans will find the going tough next year when
they try to ``improve their favorability ratings in a year in which
they're going to be competing with their presidential candidate''
for the public's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to try and hustle and redefine themselves. ...
But it's too late. They've really squandered a year,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Although most generic matchup polls indicate that the race for
control of Congress nationwide is a dead heat, analyses of the open
district seats show a slight edge for the Democrats. The most
likely gains for Democrats include seats in California, Washington,
Montana, Oklahoma, Illinois, New Jersey, Ohio, Florida and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   But many surveys of likely voters also suggest there is a huge
number _ 31 percent in a few polls _- of undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate side, seven to 10 Republican seats could be in
danger, compared to only three or four for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent polls showing her trailing New York City Mayor
Rudolf Giuliani to fill the seat of retiring Democrat Patrick
Daniel Moynihan, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is still
considered to have a good chance of winning the New York race.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans seem likely to win the Nevada seat of retiring
Sen. Richard Bryan, and they also have an excellent shot at
Democrat Chuck Robb of Virginia, who is being challenged by former
Gov. George Allen.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, retiring Florida Sen. Connie Mack's seat
may go Democratic. Six other Republican incumbents facing tight
races are William Roth of Delaware, John Ashcroft of Missouri, Rick
Santorum of Pennsylvania, Rod Grams of Minnesota, Lincoln Chaffee
of Rhode Island and Spencer Abraham of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
