A9707 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      01-07 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Jan. 8 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ Employers added jobs at a
surprisingly robust rate in December, propelling the economy into
the new year with considerable momentum, the Labor Department
reported on Friday. Average hourly earnings for the month rose by
0.4 percent, slightly higher than expected. But because workers are
producing more for each hour worked, the growth in wages so far
shows few signs of setting off a surge in inflation. While good
news across the board, the figures substantially increased the
likelihood that the Federal Reserve will act to keep the economy
from overheating by raising interest rates next month. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Mozdok, Russia) _ Frustrated by bad weather and
fierce rebel resistance, the Russian military on Friday suspended
its assault on Grozny, the capital of Chechnya. Maj. Gen. Gennady
Trochev, the deputy commander of the Russian troops in Chechnya,
said the pause was intended to give the thousands of civilians
trapped in the city a chance to escape from the fighting. But the
Russian military appeared to be putting the best face on an
increasingly difficult situation. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   ASSISI-PIGEONS (Assisi, Italy) _ The battle between man and
pigeon is waged daily in almost every European city, but it has
reached a whole new dimension in Assisi, where the age-old debate
over animal rights and the protection of historic monuments _ and
human health _ is colored by the moral teachings of St. Francis of
Assisi, the humble friar (born in 1182 and died in 1226) who loved
animals and preached to the birds. Assisi, still recovering from
the 1997 earthquake that damaged its famous basilica and killed 11
people, is now traumatized by a new city ordinance that bans the
feeding of pigeons. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN (New York) _ A look at Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's campaign finances as he prepares for a U.S. Senate run.
By Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TRUCKS (Undated) _ The Clinton administration has decided
against opening the U.S. border to Mexican trucks in a move that
has angered Mexico, but delighted the powerful Teamsters union at a
time that Vice President Al Gore is vigorously seeking its
endorsement. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-DEATH-PENALTY (Tallahassee, Fla.) _ Florida lawmakers
approve a bill that they say will limit the appeals process so
death row inmates can be executed more quickly. The vote parallels
steps Congress took in 1996 to limit the ability of state inmates
to seek review in federal court, and opponents say the effect of
the two actions together, the congressional and now the state,
would greatly impair the ability of Florida's death row inmates to
assert their constitutional rights. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
</TEXT>
