<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-CHANGES-630&AMP;ADD-     01-07 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-CHANGES-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE EXECUTIVES APPOINTED TO NEW POSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its second round of major changes this week, Coca-Cola
announced Friday that its chief marketing officer, Charles S.
Frenette, would be president of its troubled European operations.
His replacement is a veteran of Coke's business in Japan, long the
biggest single profit source for the soft-drink giant.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Carl H. Ware, the company's highest ranking black
executive who said in November that he would step down later this
year, was named executive vice president for corporate affairs and
government relations. Ware's departure plans, disclosed after a
management shuffle that effectively demoted him, had caused concern
within Atlanta's civil rights community and among some investors,
particularly since the company is facing a racial-discrimination
lawsuit filed by eight of its black employees.
</P>
<P>
   The changing of the guard in the marketing department comes just
days before the company is supposed to announce its new campaign
for Coca-Cola Classic. The campaign, which urges the consumption of
ice-cold Coke in hopes of increasing sales and was developed under
Frenette, will now be supervised by Stephen C. Jones, who has spent
the last five years overseeing Coke's operations in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There Jones worked closely with Douglas N. Daft, Coke's
president and chief operating officer who is expected to become
chairman and chief executive in three months. Jones supervised some
200 brands sold in Japan, where sales were flat in 1998 compared
with 1997 but appear to have been improving lately. He was named
head of the company's Minute Maid juice business in late October;
his successor in that position has not been announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be intriguing to watch,'' said Andrew J. Conway, a
beverage stocks analyst for Morgan Stanley. ``This will be a year
of Steve Jones coming up to speed on the marketing issues in
several important profit centers, not only the U.S., where the
concentrate-price increase means Coke has to be a meaningfully more
efficient marketer, but also in Europe and Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Jones had barely unpacked in Houston, where Minute Maid is
based, the openings created by the retirement of William P. Casey
as president of Coke's European business made him a candidate for
the marketing job. ``The timing allowed Doug Daft to move Steve
into this position without a whole lot of disruption to Minute
Maid,'' said a company spokesman, Ben Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette will replace Casey, 58, who is retiring after 32 years
with Coke, much of that on the bottling side. He was appointed
president of Europe in 1998 by M. Douglas Ivester, Coke's chairman
and chief executive who is retiring in April.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Coke had the biggest product recall in its history in
Belgium, which cost the company an estimated $200 million in
marketing and other costs to alleviate the damage to its image,
which spread beyond Belgium to France, Spain and other parts of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette was named the company's chief marketer just 22 months
ago. He spent a large part of last year in Belgium, supervising the
marketing of Coca-Cola in the wake of the recall, which included
giveaways of Coke that officials ordered stopped after competitors
complained.
</P>
<P>
   In another departure from recent Coca-Cola tradition, Frenette
will be based in London and A.R.C. Allan, who was named head of the
Asian and Middle East operations in October, will be based in Hong
Kong. Jones will be based in Atlanta, although other executives
might soon find their headquarters moved closer to the territory
they oversee as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie's move from Atlanta is the first concrete evidence
we've seen of the decentralization of Coke's top management,'' said
John D. Sicher, editor of Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Daft is likely to make other changes in the company's highest
echelons before the Coke board meets on Jan. 18, Sicher added. Most
analysts expect him to tap Jack Stahl, a senior vice president who
oversees business in the United States and Latin America, as his
president and chief operating officer, and say the announcement
could come early next week. Stahl, a former chief financial officer
at the company who was the second-highest-paid executive in 1998
after Ivester, has long been seen as a candidate for the top jobs
at Coke.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would complement each other very nicely _ Jack the
strength in financial, Doug Daft the strength in operational,''
said Emanuel Goldman, a global consumer-products analyst for
Merrill Lynch. Ivester's refusal to name a second-in-command
worried some on Wall Street and may have been one of the sticking
points between him and the board that led him to resign suddenly
last month, although neither he nor anyone on the board has
publicly said that.
</P>
<P>
   One question that remains is whether James E. Chestnut, the
chief financial officer until last month, will stay on. Chestnut
was given wider responsibilities, including technical services,
corporate affairs and government relations, in the management
shuffle Ivester announced in October. Several of his duties are now
being handled by Ware, and Gary P. Fayard, the new chief financial
officer, may end up reporting to Daft or Stahl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
