<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9709 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-NASA-NAT     01-07 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-NASA-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; More Small Businesses Get A Piece of the R &AMP; D Pie &QL;   &UR; By
Laura Winter &QL;  &QC;  C. 2000 States News Service &QL;  &QC;  WASHINGTON, Jan. 7 -
NASA announced Thursday that it will fund 25 small business
research and development proposals expected to cost the agency $15
million over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from possible congressional budget cuts,
officials for NASA's Small Business Innovation Research program
chose in August 103 proposals from 90 companies for phase II of the
program. The 25 new proposals, submitted from as many companies,
were accepted in addition to the original number, representing an
increase of the program's budget last year, said SBIR Program
Manager Paul Mexcur.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for this phase may give each proposal up to $60,000 to
continue research and development projects. The first two phases
must be funded through the SBIR office inside of NASA's Goddard
Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 companies and NASA can now start negotiating over the
total price of each of their proposal contracts. The small
businesses whose proposals are selected for phase III will work
directly with NASA project scientists and engineers with future
missions in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ResearchSouth, in Huntsville, Ala., made the list of 25 with its
software that simulates hypersonic aerodynamics. The software takes
an aircraft design and simulates the airflow and stress it might
experience travelling at a speed many times that of sound - all
inside a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually used the software to simulate the airflow over
some airplanes with finished designs and the data matched,'' said
Lawrence Spradley, the company's chief scientist. ``We validated
our software. It was such a good comparison that NASA decided to
move us into phase II.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, owned by Spradley's wife of 37 years, has grown to
six employees in seven years. It is just this type of company,
Mexcur said, SBIR is designed for.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a small company and would like to do work with the
federal government and are one the high end of developing
technology, this program provides the best opportunity,'' Mexcur
said.
</P>
<P>
   The SBIR has been financing small business research into
high-risk, high-payoff technologies since Congress created the
program in 1982. Mexcur said NASA's 500 small business contracts
last year were developed through his office.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's 2,000 evaluators nationwide whittled the 2,335 proposals
first received in July 1998 down to 206. Mexcur said he was simply
content that the budget was increased enough to fund 128 total
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have executed a budget at about double of what I
got,'' Mexcur said. ``We fill up the cup until we say we have
bought all that we can.'' A call for submissions for this year's
round of research and development proposals will open in April. All
submissions must be received by mid-July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
