<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-PEACE-TALKS-HNS &LR;      01-07 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACE-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AGAIN MUST INTERVENE IN MIDEAST PEACE TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ In an attempt to focus peace talks,
President Clinton presented a ``working document'' to Syrian and
Israeli leaders Friday summarizing the issues that have kept the
two sides from reaching an accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is difficult stuff,'' Clinton told reporters before
flying here from Washington to intervene for a fourth time in
stalled negotiations between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged there is still hard work ahead as the two
leaders wind down their first round of discussions and prepare to
head home either Sunday or Monday. But the president added that the
two sides are still ``trying to find ways to resolve their
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to imagine the end of the road here,'' Clinton
said. ``It's a difficult, difficult set of negotiations, but we're
working in a steady way and I'm satisfied that everybody is working
in good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's return trip here Friday morning, after staying late
Thursday to meet with the Israelis and Syrians, marked a last-ditch
effort to get the talks moving again and to lay the groundwork for
continued discussions at a later date, either back in Shepherdstown
or at another venue.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said the working
document, which was drafted on orders from Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, ``provides a summary of the issues to be
decided and the differences between the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart described it as a ``procedural tool'' designed to help
motivate the parties rather than a framework for a final
Syrian-Israeli agreement.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin later told reporters that
the document includes new ``creative'' ideas and recommendations
from the president and Albright that could help spur progress
toward a deal between the two long-time enemies, who have been in a
state of war since Israel was established in 1948. But Rubin
stopped short of calling the document an official U.S. proposal for
a final agreement that would return the Golan Heights, which Israel
captured in 1967, to Syria in return for normalized relations.
</P>
<P>
   Albright ordered the document drawn up on Thursday after it
appeared the Syrians might be on the verge of breaking off the
discussions. The Syrians have been complaining since Tuesday that
the Shepherdstown meetings have focused too much attention on
security arrangements for a possible Israeli withdrawal from the
Golan Heights, and not enough on when and how that pull-out will
occur, or where the final border between the two countries will be
drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Syrian concerns had now been addressed, Rubin
said the working document does include a discussion of ``the border
issue'' and every other item of contention standing in the way of
peace. He insisted as well, that one of four technical committees
formed this week to deal with all the disputes would meet before
Monday to hold a thorough airing on the border matter.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S., Israeli and Syrian teams participating in the
negotiations are expected to take a break for religious observances
and begin work again Saturday night and Sunday. But Rubin suggested
that the Shepherdstown round of talks would likely end Sunday night
or early Monday since Barak and al-Sharaa are planning to return
home. He stressed, however, that ``accelerated'' discussions will
continue between the Israelis and Syrians in the coming weeks,
leading to another round of talks involving Barak, al-Sharaa and
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said Barak and al-Sharaa, who also held a
brief face-to-face discussion after their meeting with Clinton and
Albright, plan to study the document presented to them over the
weekend. He said the two told Clinton they regard it ``as a good
way to move the process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks began here on a cautious note Monday, with U.S.
officials saying they did not expect a breakthrough in the first
round of discussions that would lead to what they called ``a core
agreement.'' They reiterated that view Friday, despite Clinton's
presentation of the U.S. document detailing ``where things stand,''
as one official put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very limited expectations of what can be achieved in
one round,'' Rubin said. ``This is a long, long-standing dispute.
It is one that is very emotional and very substantive, and carries
with it enormous security implications. We don't expect in a few
days for those kind of issues to move dramatically forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has pursued a comprehensive Middle East peace settlement
between Israel and all its Arab neighbors since he took office. He
was instrumental early on in helping to strike a tentative deal
between Israel and the Palestinians in 1993, followed by a second
agreement between Israel and Jordan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He has now made the search for an accord between Syrian and
Israel a top priority of his final year in office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
