<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-AGE-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOCIAL SECURITY RETIREMENT AGE IS RISING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Jan. 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Never mind the new millennium. This year marks a
new age of retirement, at least as far as Social Security is
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The official age for full retirement benefits now begins
creeping up from age 65 to age 67 in 2027. The rise, mandated by
Congress in 1983 as part of its effort to preserve Social Security,
affects 150 million working Americans. But it does not touch any of
the 31 million retired workers and dependents already collecting
some $22.3 billion in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Only individuals born in 1938 or afterward must plan on retiring
later than they anticipated if they want full benefits. Those born
in 1938 turn 62 this year, and if they opt for early retirement,
their monthly benefits under the 1983 law will be reduced by 5/9 of
1 percent. By 2003, they will find that they won't be eligible for
full-retirement benefits until they are 65 years and two months
old.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, the age for full-retirement benefits jumps two
months each year between 2004 and 2007 for persons born between
1939 and 1942. For instance, those born in 1939 will reach that age
at 65 years and four months. Those born in 1940 will reach it at 65
years and six months. The full-retirement-benefit age goes to 66
for those born between 1943 and 1954 and 67 for people born in 1960
or later.
</P>
<P>
   Because the 76-million-strong baby-boom generation begins
retiring in massive numbers in 2012, the Social Security system
projects it will run short of money and not be able to pay full
benefits beginning in 2034. However, with the rise in the
retirement age, the Social Security Administration (SSA) estimates
it will save $22.1 billion through 2009.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an important step to assure the financial security of
the system,'' said Social Security Commissioner Kenneth Apfel in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hadn't been made, the long-term problem we face in
Social Security would be 50 percent larger than now.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sweetener, the law provides for a ``delayed retirement
credit'' to workers who stay on the job past the retirement age.
Benefits are increased until age 70. The yearly rate ranges between
5 percent for those born in 1931 and 1932, who turn 70 in 2001 and
2002, and 8 percent for those born in 1943, who start retiring in
2009.
</P>
<P>
   The SSA has made a massive effort to remind current workers of
the rise in the age of eligibility and to tell them what they can
expect from Social Security upon retirement. Last October, the
agency began mailing individualized Social Security statements to
125 million workers over age 25.
</P>
<P>
   The statements list each individual's expected monthly benefit
at age 62, at the age of full retirement and at age 70. The letters
also estimate monthly Social Security disability benefits that will
be paid if the worker becomes disabled and the amount the worker's
family will receive if he or she dies.
</P>
<P>
   Apfel said the statements provide ``not only a projection of
benefits but also good information about when to retire.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Apfel said the hike in the retirement-benefit-eligibility age
rise is justified by rising life-expectancy rates. When the Social
Security system was created in 1935, analysts projected that
65-year-old benefit recipients would live another 12 and 1/2 years.
Now the projection is 17 and  &QC;  years.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the retirement age in 1983 drew a lot of fire, and it
remains controversial. Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the leading
Republican presidential contender, created a mini-firestorm late
last year when he said he would not close the door on yet another
rise if other ways were not found to bail out Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Another GOP candidate, publishing magnate Steve Forbes, called
Bush's position a ``betrayal.'' When Forbes attacked Bush on Social
Security at a debate of Republican contenders on Dec. 2, Bush
struck back. He produced a column that the publisher had written in
Forbes magazine in 1977 advocating an age hike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
