<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKE-CELLS-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STROKE VICTIM STILL HOPEFUL THAT CELL TRANSPLANT WILL PAY OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Jan. 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Four days before Christmas,
occupational therapist Tara Van Buren gave stroke patient Maribeth
Cook the same command she had given numerous times since Cook's
experimental fetal pig brain cell transplant in Brookline, Mass.,
on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open your left hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The response of Cook, 39, to that command had not changed since
the Saratoga Springs woman's stroke in 1994. No matter how much she
willed it to move, Cook's damaged left hand remained paralyzed _
rigid and seemingly as lifeless as a block of wood.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 21, however, Cook experienced what she described as a
breakthrough during a therapy session at the Wesley Health Care
Center here.
</P>
<P>
   ``My left hand opened a little bit for the first time,'' Cook
said. ``It was very slight and nobody would notice it but me and my
therapist. Something's happening. I'm very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some slight flexion for the first time in her left
hand,'' Van Buren said. ``I'm trying to be optimistic, but I also
don't want to give Maribeth any false hope.''
</P>
<P>
   In the four months since Cook became the world's first stroke
patient to receive the unproven and controversial animal-to-human
cell transplant procedure, improvements in the function of Cook's
partially paralyzed left side have been incremental, anecdotal and
inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   What Cook felt she experienced as a breakthrough has not been
confirmed by any irrefutable evidence. ``It's hard to be patient,''
Cook said. ``I really want something major to happen. I want to be
able to wriggle the fingers of my left hand more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, follow-up visits and medical tests at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center _ where 30 million fetal pig brain cells
were injected with a long needle deep into the stroke-damaged
region of Cook's brain _ have not detected new cell growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still too early to tell,'' said Loretta Barron, study
coordinator for Cook's clinical trial. ``Since Maribeth is the
first stroke patient, we don't have anything to measure her
against. We're not unhopeful after four months. We're also not
surprised that we're not seeing any dramatic improvements at this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron said new cell growth has not been detected in the damaged
region of Cook's brain, where the fetal pig cells were injected.
Her brain has been analyzed with magnetic resonance imaging to look
at tissue and brain structure and magnetic resonance angiography to
observe any changes in blood vessels or circulation.
</P>
<P>
   If the xenotransplantation is successful, the fetal pig brain
cells will survive, grow and form tissue that will refill the
``black hole'' of Cook's deadened stroke region. Those cells, in
theory, would then repair her damaged brain circuitry and
eventually restore function on her left side.
</P>
<P>
   Cook currently wears a brace on her left leg, walks with a
pronounced limp, holds her left arm rigid and cannot use her left
hand. A stroke five years ago left her unable to continue working
as a dental hygienist.
</P>
<P>
   According to Barron, Cook's condition has shown some slight
improvements during the four months since the transplant surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough to deem the pig brain cell transplant a
success or to confirm cause and effect. Only an MRI, MRA or similar
test that revealed new cell growth in her deadened brain region
would prove that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed that the MRI didn't show cells growing,''
Cook said. ``I believe they're growing, but just not enough to show
up yet.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, one conclusion that is definitive _ based on the results
of blood samples and other tests _ is that Cook has not shown any
signs of contracting a pig virus. That concern about passing
viruses across species is one of the potential problems cited by
those who oppose xenotransplantation.
</P>
<P>
   Diacrin Inc., the Boston biotechnology company conducting and
paying for Cook's FDA-approved clinical trial, said none of the 25
patients they are tracking after pig cell transplants for diseases
other than stroke have experienced any pig virus infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt great from five minutes after surgery, and I still
do,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   A similar fetal pig brain cell transplant for Parkinson's
disease developed by Diacrin in a joint venture with Genzyme Corp.
has produced dramatic, measurable improvements for some patients.
</P>
<P>
   But it's difficult to know how closely changes over time in Cook
would mirror the track record of Parkinson's transplant patients,
according to Michael Egan, senior vice president at Diacrin.
``Since she (Cook) is the first stroke patient, it's hard to
compare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diacrin's goal is to recruit five additional stroke patients who
meet certain criteria for its clinical trial, but Cook as yet does
not have company in the fetal pig brain cell study.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 60-year-old man who had agreed to undergo the transplant last
month pulled out just before the scheduled operation. ``I'm not
sure what made the man nervous,'' Barron said. She added that a
number of people who wanted the transplant and contacted the
hospital failed certain criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Other female candidates of childbearing age withdrew when they
learned that conceiving children was strongly discouraged after the
transplant because of uncertainties of a pig virus being passed to
a fetus, according to Barron.
</P>
<P>
   Barron and her boss, Dr. Louis Caplan, a neurologist at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center and an internationally recognized
authority on stroke, continue to evaluate potential patients.
They're hopeful that another transplant will be performed later
this month at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Barron and Caplan will continue to evaluate Cook for the next 14
months.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cook's friends and family remain upbeat about
improvements that can't be measured at the hospital. Many have
remarked that Cook's voice now sounds more animated and clear after
the transplant, less slurred and monotone as it had been since the
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I notice a lot more confidence in Maribeth,'' said her mother,
Marie Verdile, of Mechanicville, N.Y. Verdile said she does not
worry as much about her daughter, does not feel compelled to visit
her as often and was not calling all the time during a three-week
vacation as she had done previously.
</P>
<P>
   Cook and her husband, Paul Cook, a sixth-grade math and science
teacher, bought a new minivan that Maribeth drives with much more
confidence than previous vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just doesn't give up and keeps moving forward in positive
directions,'' her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's therapists have observed the same determination. During a
recent session at Wesley Health Care Center, physical therapist
Judy Trier said Cook has gained a total of 28 degrees of ankle
motion in all directions since the Sept. 1 transplant. Trier said
the 28-degree gain is substantial, but she can't say it was a
result of the fetal pig cells. It might instead simply be the
cumulative effect of a renewed commitment to therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She works really hard at her sessions,'' Trier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go ahead and say it. I'm pigheaded,'' Cook said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said she continues to enjoy hearing new pig jokes from
friends after the transplant. ``My favorite one is from my Jewish
friend who said she can't talk to me anymore because she's
kosher,'' Cook said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
