<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9715 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-PLAYBOY-PARTIES-ART-2     01-07 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYBOY-PARTIES-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOST AND HAREM: AT TED FIELDS' PARTIES, THE PLAYBOY PHILOSOPHY
LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill., Alaska)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 9)  
 (bl) MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the Playboy Mansion has been reborn as a hipster
hangout, its parties full of young Hollywood bloods like DiCaprio
and Affleck, what is to become of the scene from the good-old,
bad-old days _ the '70s and '80s, when unfamous, middle-aged men
cavorted with much-younger women in a setting still considered
cheesy, not yet chic?
</P>
<P>
   Is there no place left where 40-something men can pursue women
young enough to be their daughters, the age difference overcome by
the size of their portfolios?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes _ at a Ted Field party.
</P>
<P>
   Field is the Hollywood financier who, twice a year, gives a big,
splashy, over-the-top party in St. Barts, Aspen, East Hampton or
Paris during fashion week _ wherever the action is. The guest lists
are drawn up by professional party planners well connected to
modeling agencies, and the ratio of women to men is usually about
two to one. The evenings draw hundreds, sometimes thousands, no
matter what island, yacht or ocean-front mansion is chosen as the
setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would fly anywhere in the world to go to a Ted
extravaganza,'' said Ivan Wilzig, 44, an heir to a banking fortune,
who has a castle in Water Mill, N.Y. ``It will totally have an
eclectic group of people with different backgrounds, and it's a
guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve in New York, Wilzig brought Mina Otsuko, 21,
whom he calls his ``main squeeze,'' to Studio 54, where Field had
spent over $700,000 to recreate the disco's heyday. They came with
another friend, Robert Hantman, 48, a lawyer who represents models,
and his date, Ina Shapiro, 27, a student (yes, Ina and Mina). At
the stroke of midnight, Ms. Shapiro threw off her top and started
dancing; Ms. Otsuko attempted to peel down her silver bodysuit but
found it too tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud,'' Hantman said later. ``It's a Ted Field party.
You expect a mixture of decadence, sophistication, good cheer and
fellowship.''
</P>
<P>
   Field seems intent on making the world safe for the last
stalwarts of the Playboy philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   The Studio 54 dance floor was full of men in suits and leggy,
wiggling, size 2 women. There was a reproduction of the famous
15-foot gold moon and coke spoon suspended above the crowd. On a
night when many celebrities stayed home or left town, the party
drew a B list of boldfacers, including Harvey Keitel, Grace Jones,
models like Kylie Bax and rappers like Dr. Dre and Eminem.
</P>
<P>
   Field himself did very little mingling. For more than three
hours after corks popped and the champagne sloshed at midnight, he
took over a black leather couch on the perimeter of the dance
floor, where he was surrounded by five women who looked to be 18 to
23. When he got up to dance, two or three women danced with him.
When he sat, the women danced together before him or sat down next
to him. They would stroke his shoulders and knees, and he would
caress their legs. They never disconnected, but they never kissed,
either.
</P>
<P>
   The music, disco chestnuts, was so loud you could feel it in
your ribs. Field would whisper into the ears of his companions, but
they had a hard time hearing, so he would just stroke their
shoulders or necks and prompt them to get up again to dance.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 a.m., he and two young women formed a sandwich, one rubbing
up from behind him and another, in a black halter top, wiggling in
front of him. They were joined by a third woman, and then Field sat
down to watch. He was surrounded by two more women in backless
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice life that guy has,'' said one of four stoic security
guards, who stood behind the couch all night.
</P>
<P>
   Mention Ted Field's name outside Hollywood, and many people
can't place him, not even some of the guests at his parties. ``Ted
gives the hottest, hottest parties,'' said Kristi Horton, 32, an
analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, dressed in a backless
halter t Studio 54. Asked how she knew her host, she
replied, ``I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some party pros are stumped. ``He's a shadowy, mystery
figure of some sort,'' said R. Couri Hay, a society writer who has
attended several of his parties, including the one at Studio 54.
``I don't think I know what Ted Field looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   Field, 47, is a huggy-bear figure who wears round glasses and
keeps his brush mustache well-trimmed. Amid a sea of spangles and
animal prints at Studio 54, he wore a black V-neck sweater that
could have been ordered from L.L. Bean. An heir to the Marshall
Field department-store and newspaper fortune (the family owned The
Chicago Sun-Times until 1983), he embodies a cross between
impeccable, preppy manners and studied contrariness.
</P>
<P>
   After turning his back on his Chicago roots, he founded
Interscope Communications in 1982, which has produced hit movies
like ``Runaway Bride'' and ``Three Men and a Baby.'' The Interscope
record label he began in 1990 has had hit releases by No Doubt and
a string of hard-edged rappers, from Snoop Doggy Dogg to Eminem.
</P>
<P>
   Variety editor in chief Peter Bart recalled that when Field
first came to Hollywood, ``He was originally thought of as the rich
kid who came to town and was exploited by some hungry agents and
producers.'' But that changed. ``He has become a very shrewd and
very successful, respected executive in Hollywood,'' Bart said.
``He has long since shed the image of poor little rich boy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the party-hearty guy that much of the world knows, Bart
said that was not the whole story. Field ``enjoys the good life,''
Bart said, but he added, ``He's a serious guy who reads and
thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Field spent his formative teen-age years in Alaska, where his
mother, Katherine Fanning, had moved following a divorce. (She went
on to become the editor of The Anchorage Daily News and later The
Christian Science Monitor.) When Field was 25, he came into a large
trust fund, which allowed him to continue an infatuation with
Porsches and Lolas, racing the cars around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a first cousin of Field, a man entrenched in the
leisure-class life, acknowledged that he had never met his relative
but said the family lore was that Ted, after growing up cloistered
in Alaska, had gone a bit wild once he came into his inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Field says he is hardly wild; he is a workaholic and says he
doesn't drink or take drugs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He has three ex-wives and six daughters, ages 6 to 21, by four
different women. Currently, he's rekindled an on-again, off-again
relationship with Elizabeth Nottoli, 32, a former model, who is a
partner in a party-planning company, La Bonvie, which lays much of
the groundwork for his parties. The couple met seven years ago,
separated, had babies with other people, then got back together.
They don't live together. Hey, it's Hollywood in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Field saysd he doesn't think he will ever marry again.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Barts over the New Year's holiday two years ago, where he
brought along a dozen beautiful young women to live on his
chartered 190-foot yacht, he could be seen, day after day, in town,
shopping with one or another of them, buying them Italian shoes and
designer dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Is he the playboy he appears to be? Are the women who surround
him a harem?
</P>
<P>
   In an interview (Field rarely gives one), he did not dodge the
question, but he declined to be quoted verbatim, fearful his words
would be lifted out of context by another publication.
</P>
<P>
   He said that because he is in the entertainment business, and
because he is single, it is natural for him to be surrounded by
attractive young women. He doubted they would be around if he sold
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he dates the very young women he is seen dancing
or shopping with, he said yes, sometimes. He says that in the eight
years since his last divorce, he has had eight to 10 steady
girlfriends, all models, whom he met at parties.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Tracy Tweed, is the mother of his youngest
daughter, born out of wedlock. Speaking on the phone from a Los
Angeles hair salon, where she was having her hair highlighted, Ms.
Tweed said, ``Ted has made it possible for me to quit working and
raise our daughter.'' He pays for the 6-year-old's private school
and her own horse and an eight-bedroom mansion in Beverly Hills
with a pool and a tennis court, where mother and daughter live.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a mensch,'' Ms. Tweed added. ``He's true to his word.
Honest to a T.'' She recalled that when she met Field (they were
introduced at a party by Gene Simmons of Kiss), she slouched so as
not to tower above the 5-foot-10 Field. ``Why are you slouching?''
he asked. When she explained, he told her to stand up straight. ``I
can handle 6 foot 2,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nottoli, Field's current girlfriend, maintained that she
doesn't mind all the other women Field surrounds himself with.
``Women are fascinated with him,'' she said. ``He's so intelligent,
he's handsome, he's funny, he's definitely spontaneous. He's very
free-spirited, and he loves life.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention that he is worth $1.2 billion, according to
Forbes magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Norah Lawlor, a publicist who has been to six Ted Field parties
and who gives parties of her own for nightclub and restaurant
clients, said the young women who eagerly attend are often models
or aspiring entertainers who think they will meet a rich and
powerful man.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they are going to be discovered,'' she said. ``They
hear two big shots are going to be at a party, and they think, `Wow
this might be my chance: husband, money, next movie role or
supermodel career.'''
</P>
<P>
   As for the men, their interest is not always the obvious one,
she added. ``There are so many rich men I know that want me to
bring young models to dinner,'' Ms. Lawlor said. ``They don't want
to sleep with them. They just like to have them around. The guys
can relive their youth with women who are not jaded and see the
world from a young eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Ola Solomatina, 22, a six-foot model with short black hair and
blue eyes who was at Studio 54, said that there was an appeal to
being around worldly, older men. She has never been invited to St.
Bart's with Field, but she says that she's available. ``I would
join Ted on his yacht in a minute,'' she said. ``Why not? Whether
it's Ted Field or someone else, it doesn't really matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it more entertaining talking to a 47-year-old man like
Ted than a 20-year-old,'' she said. ``He has interesting people at
his parties. It's very trendy. Like at his Halloween party, I met
Donald Trump. At New Year's Eve, Enrique Iglesias. I like being
around successful people. It's better than hanging around with a
bunch of losers.''
</P>
<P>
   At 4:45 a.m., Field put on his leather jacket by the door,
standing in the middle of a circle of six women. ``Where is he
going?'' a man nearby asked, wondering if there was another party.
</P>
<P>
   No, there was no other party, one of the women in the entourage
said. They were all going back to Field's hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
