<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-DEATH08-COX     01-07 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-DEATH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida GOP rallies to approve limits to Death Row appeals
 &HT;    By S.V. Date and Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Dragging Republicans away from a family
funeral and a wife in childbirth, and aided by a key Democratic
defector, Gov. Jeb Bush salvaged the necessary votes Friday to
radically limit the court appeals of Death Row murderers.
</P>
<P>
   Condemned inmates would have to meet strict deadlines for filing
their claims, would be limited to how many appeals they could file,
and would have to file both their first and second round of appeals
simultaneously _ all with the goal of putting them to death within
five years of conviction, rather than the current 14-year average.
</P>
<P>
   Bush predicted the first execution by lethal injection would be
``a matter of months, not a matter of years.'' He is expected to
sign the legislation within days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without rushing into anything, I tend to sign death warrants
pretty quickly,'' he said and later added, ``It's always longer
than you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Death Row convicts who can afford their own lawyers, however,
are not subject to the limits passed Friday. The new law covers
only those using state-paid lawyers _ one of many questionable
features defense lawyers say could lead the courts to overturn much
of the new legislation and thus add even more delays.
</P>
<P>
   Those criticisms notwithstanding, Florida's all-Republican
triumvirate stood with Democratic Attorney General Bob Butterworth
to praise the new law as something, finally, on behalf of the
families of murder victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here and did what we had to do,'' said House Speaker
John Thrasher, whose miscalculation on how many votes his chamber
needed required an extra day's worth of arm-twisting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims of crimes are the people we should revel for,''
said Senate President Toni Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth _ who originally called for a special session in
November specifically to switch from the embattled electric chair
to the more judicially palatable lethal injection _ hailed both the
lethal injection bill passed Thursday and the appeals measure both
chambers passed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate originally passed its appeals bill 30-7 on Thursday,
only to watch it fail to win the necessary two-thirds majority in
the House. The 75-36 vote there effectively made the bill merely a
recommendation to the Supreme Court to change its rules, rather
than a repeal of existing rules that 80 votes triggered.
</P>
<P>
   Both chambers overwhelmingly passed the lethal injection bill
Thursday: 37-0 in the Senate and 102-5 in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth can now use the new law to ask the U.S. Supreme
Court to drop its review of Florida's electric chair, just as in
past cases it declared moot pending reviews of California's gas
chamber and Washington's gallows when those states switched to
lethal injection amid court reviews.
</P>
<P>
   CALLING THE SICK AND GRIEVING
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Bush had worried that the more independent Senate
might balk at such radical changes to death penalty appeals,
particularly given the risks that the new law might force the
system to a grinding halt if the courts rule it unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the House was where the proposal got snagged.
To reach the two-thirds of the required votes, Thrasher had to find
five votes.hursday night, the calls went out. Four Republican votes popped
up.
</P>
<P>
   Ocala Rep. George Albright climbed inside his red pickup truck
at 7 p.m. for the three-hour drive to Tallahassee, leaving behind
his wife, who is nine months pregnant. ``I felt I had a moral
obligation'' to vote, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Starks of Casselberry, a Delta pilot, rose from the bed
he had slept in for four days while battling the flu to board a
9:35 p.m. commercial plane in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The other two were whisked back to Tallahassee on private planes
solicited by the Florida Republican Party. One carried Rep. Everett
Kelly of Tavares, who was in Alabama for his sister's funeral,
scheduled for Thursday afternoon. ``This is one of the most
important bills I have passed in my tenure in the Florida House. My
sister would understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The other plane retrieved Bradenton Rep. Mark Ogles, who had
been staying with his sick wife in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did was help members get here to do their job,'' said
Florida Republican Party Chairman Al Cardenas, who came to watch
the vote from the public gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, when the House opened for business at 9 a.m.
Friday, Republicans were still one vote short.
</P>
<P>
   The arm twisting intensified.
</P>
<P>
   For three hours, debate began and abruptly ended. Republican
vote-getters, called whips, paced the floor. Thrasher leaned on the
podium, not smiling, but on the phone. Democrats kept tabs on their
own members.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, the mostly Democratic black caucus took a
headcount. Two members were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes they were found _ seated inside the speaker's
office, off the House floor, chatting with Lt. Gov. Frank Brogan,
who sat behind Thrasher's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tallahassee Rep. Al Lawson and Miami Rep. Beryl Roberts
denied Brogan had offered or promised them something to gain their
votes.
</P>
<P>
   But that did little to relieve two of their black caucus
colleagues, Miami senators Daryl Jones and Kendrick Meek, who
stood, bitterly, outside Thrasher's closed office door.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, just after noon, it was time for the vote.
</P>
<P>
   And then it happened: Rep. John Cosgrove of Miami _ the second
highest-ranking House Democrat _ voted yes.
</P>
<P>
   Cosgrove, who in November wants to be elected Florida's next
insurance commissioner, had planned to use a rule that would allow
him not to vote.
</P>
<P>
   But after Thrasher challenged him _ a planned Republican
maneuver _ Cosgrove backed off, ensuring the Republican victory. He
said he did it because he was ``voting the conscience of my
district.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seethed. One called him a ``traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach Rep. Lois Frankel _ who in March will become the
House's top Democrat, stormed over to his desk.Come November, she
said, ``You aren't going to have one Democrat in this state
supporting you.''
</P>
<P>
   PUT OFF UNTIL SPRING
</P>
<P>
   With the new laws to take effect within days, the offices of the
state-paid lawyers who defend Death Row inmates will likely go on a
hiring binge, signing contracts to bring aboard some 100 new
attorneys to file appeals for those inmates already on Death Row by
the Jan. 8, 2001 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators expect to spend an additional $10 million to $15
million a year to pay for the simultaneous filing of the first and
second round of appeals, the so-called ``dual track'' system copied
from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is after we last year gave $1 billion back in taxes,''
Frankel said. ``Why didn't we put more money into the court system
so we could have more judges to speed up this process?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
