<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STERN-GERMANY-ART-2TA     01-07 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STERN-GERMANY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HISTORIAN WHO FLED NAZIS TRIES TO BE PEACEMAKER FOR GERMANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 was sent Jan. 7 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The historian weighs his words. Because his subject is
Germany and the modern history of that nation is a minefield, this
precision is understandable. Yet it is evident that in the crafted
phrases of Fritz Stern, in the sentences that circle a subject like
a hunter closing on his prey, a personality as well as a calling
are revealed. He is a man of nuances; when he defines himself, it
is with a kind of fastidious detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a full-blooded non-Aryan,'' he said, an amused twinkle in
his small eyes, hands so mobile they appear to be plucking each
shade of thought from the air. ``That is a definition I like. Of
course, I am completely of Jewish descent. But my stumbling block
with the description of myself as a Jewish historian is that it was
Hitler that decided I was a Jew. My grandparents converted to
Christianity; my parents were baptized at birth; I, too, was
baptized. It took Hitler's racial laws to turn me into a Jew, and
that provokes a certain _ let me put it like this _ a certain
hesitation in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1926 in the German town of Breslau (now Wroclaw in
Poland), later a child-escapee from Hitler, now a U.S. citizen,
Stern is a natural builder of bridges. For without such connections
_ between Germany and the United States, between Jews and Germans,
between Berlin and Warsaw, between the horror of then and the hope
of now _ what chance would he have to make himself whole?
</P>
<P>
   His historical writing amounts to a quest to go beyond the
fragments offered by memory. ``Memory may be mighty,'' Stern said
in Frankfurt, ``yet it can also be inaccurate. It keeps us on our
toes, but it brings us only to the threshold of historical
understanding.'' At a time of intellectual turmoil in Germany, this
quest for understanding has earned Stern, a professor at Columbia
University, a special role in the country of his birth. He has
emerged as a sort of moral arbiter.
</P>
<P>
   For the last year, Germany has been seeking a new 21st-century
identity. It has manifested impatience with the stigma of the Nazi
past, a thirst for normality, a new readiness to talk openly of
German power, and a hankering for some acceptable German
patriotism. Many Germans feel the ``constitutional patriotism'' of
philosopher Jurgen Habermas _ the neutered national identity that
substituted values like democratic government for the treacherous
emotions of anthem and flag _ is no longer enough. In short,
Germans are unbuttoning themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But as Germany searches for its new self, Germans are still a
little unsure, giddy with the new vocabulary of interests, great
European power and influence where once the talk was only of Europe
and detente. They tremble at their boldness in moving beyond the
self-imposed constraints of the postwar years. In this shifting
environment, symbolized by the move of the capital from small-town
Bonn to brash Berlin, Stern has emerged as perhaps the closest
thing to a trusted external judge of the country's bitter internal
debates.
</P>
<P>
   Germans often turn to Americans when problems of memory are
particularly intense. It is not for nothing that an American,
Michael Blumenthal, runs the new Jewish Museum, whose architect,
Daniel Liebeskind, is also an American, or that the planned
Holocaust Memorial was designed by Peter Eisenman, another
American. The basic difficulty behind these choices is an old one:
how should the perpetrator commemorate or simply remember the
crime?
</P>
<P>
   Stern, the author of several books on Germany, including ``The
Politics of Cultural Despair,'' is a victim. His world began to
fall apart in 1933; the family fled to New York in 1938, when young
Fritz was 12. But as a historian he has been little interested in
victimhood. This flight from emotion to reason reassures Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Stern has been interested in trying to recreate the time
in which his father, a prominent doctor named Rudolf Stern, long
thrived, in order to understand the political, cultural and
economic forces that ultimately destroyed the fecund German-Jewish
world of the late 19th and early 20th centuries. His affection for
the pre-Nazi Germany of his parents is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Ulmer, the president of the German Booksellers' and
Publishers' Association, said: ``The skill of Fritz Stern's
depictions and his integrity have generated an atmosphere that
provides the descendants of the victims and the descendants of the
perpetrators with the building blocks from which to fashion a
shared memory of a time when German-Jewish patriotism was
thinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he is seen as a conciliator at a difficult time.
Ulmer led the jury that in 1999 awarded Stern the Peace Prize of
the German Book Trade, the country's highest literary honor. In
effect, a Jewish American professor was asked to step into another
storm over the Nazi past and calm it. For the recipient of the
prize a year earlier was the German author Martin Walser, who chose
to speak aloud what many Germans silently feel.
</P>
<P>
   Auschwitz, Walser declared in late 1998, should not become ``a
routine threat, a tool of intimidation that can be used at any
time, or a moral cudgel.'' Apparently speaking of claims for
compensation that have led to a 10-billion-mark settlement for
forced and slave laborers put to work by the Nazis, he deplored the
``exploitation of our shame for present purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   A storm duly erupted. Ignatz Bubis, the late Jewish leader in
Germany, called Walser a ``mental arsonist.'' Abruptly all the
unhealed wounds of Germany's trauma were suppurating once more.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise that, a year later, Stern should be chosen
to apply some balm. He duly obliged. His response, in a speech
delivered in October, was typically measured, balanced, shaped at
some level by the hesitation of a man who has done something
essentially perverse: grown close to the country that murdered his
uncle and aunt and hounded his parents from their home.
</P>
<P>
   Stern declared that ``any instrumentalization or trivialization
of the Holocaust, consigning the millions of other victims to
oblivion, is a crime against the victims themselves.'' He noted
that the ``first victims of National Socialism and the revival of
torture were so-called Aryans,'' including pastors in Breslau. He
recalled ``how greatly attached my parents were to their home
country, how naturally _ up until 1933 _ they saw themselves as
Germans.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   is was certain to provide some comfort to a German
audience. But Stern was also stringent in his admonitions. He
deplored the government's adoption of the phrase Berlin Republic,
saying ``the result is simply to underline undesirable
discontinuity.'' He warned that what he has called Germany's second
chance could be undone if understanding did not overcome suspicion
between Germans and from the west and the east. Above all, he
suggested that the enormity of the Holocaust was such that ``every
attempt to escape into `normality' is vain.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was marked by a favorite word: context. It was the
absence of context, as he saw it, that led Stern to a sharp
condemnation of the most controversial recent work on Germany,
Daniel Goldhagen's best-selling ``Hitler's Willing Executioners.''
In an essay reprinted last year in ``Einstein's German World,''
Stern's latest work, he charges Goldhagen with ``the indictment of
a people.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldhagen, a social scientist at Harvard, retorted that Stern's
was the ``reaction of the old guard, and one of striking
intellectual bankruptcy.'' He continued, ``I was accused by him of
defaming the German national character, but all I said was Germans
believed certain things at a certain time, just as it is clear that
in the 1860s most whites in the American South were racist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goldhagen book was troubling to Stern because he has been
concerned with steering a repentant postwar Germany toward the
stable democracy with strong trans-Atlantic bonds that it is today.
For Stern, the Goldhagen work _ with its thesis of a deeply rooted,
widespread and peculiarly German anti-Semitism as the basis of the
Holocaust _ was shallow and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   For him, it underplayed the role that the national humiliation
of Versailles had in igniting anti-Semitism; it ignored the
participation or complicity of other European nations in the
annihilation of European Jews; it might only reignite ``latent
anti-German sentiment among Americans, especially Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument simmers on. Goldhagen makes a powerful case that
anti-Semitism was part of the ``cultural cognitive model'' of the
German society that produced Hitler; Stern says that ``is an
incredibly simplistic view.'' His reality is another: the ambiguity
of German sentiment toward the Jews and the Jews' painful German
patriotism, which together made up the unquiet world of his
forebears. Anti-Semitism was not the whole story as the Sterns
lived it in Breslau.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, unlike some Germans, has no illusions that the world of
interwoven German and Jewish culture into which he was born can be
restored. The Jews arriving from Russia, drawn by financial
enticements, will not recreate what Hitler destroyed. Germany must
help bring Central European states like Poland firmly into the
Western fold. For in illusions about the past lies the danger of
another departure down some shimmering, unique and volatile German
path, which Stern has always feared and always fought.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest book, Stern quotes Einstein on the Germans: ``A
country of mass murderers.'' He also quotes another brilliant
scientist and German Jew, Fritz Haber: ``The nation is bourgeois to
its very depths.'' Germany, of course, has been both those things.
Therein lies its fascination. Einstein never converted; Haber was
baptized at the age of 24. Both veered between love and despair at
their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   These are the intellectual struggles between attraction and
repulsion that intrigue Stern; in some measure they are his own.
``In retrospect,'' he says, ``I can understand what motivated my
paternal grandparents to convert, as I think a historian must
understand things in the context of when they occurred. I am not
necessarily happy about it, because I do not like the idea of
changing religion for national advantage, but I can certainly
comprehend.''
</P>
<P>
   This baptized German Jewish family was not simply persecuted,
for it first advanced thrillingly in the politically unstable,
fast-growing, inventive and finally humiliated German world of the
first third of this century. Germans, ever torn between the light
and dark of their natures, ever harboring secrets, are drawn to
Stern because he has sought to portray all these shadings of the
German tragedy. At another moment of uncertain change, he helps
them believe in themselves _ with wariness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
