<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NUMISMATIC-SOCIETY-AR     01-07 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUMISMATIC-SOCIETY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COIN SOCIETY'S PLANS UPSET SOME MEMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since 12 Victorian gentlemen gathered for its first
meeting on April 6, 1858, in the New York home of Augustus B. Sage,
the American Numismatic Society has grown into a research
institution with one of the finest collections in the world,
holding nearly a million Greek, Roman, Islamic, Asian and medieval
coins.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, thanks in part to its low profile and, some
say, its distant site in upper Manhattan, the society has largely
been forgotten by the public. Now a plan to reduce the society's
annual deficit of nearly $1 million by offering buyouts to its five
curators while at the same time spending most of its endowment on a
new home downtown has sparked a rebellion among a group of its
devoted members.
</P>
<P>
   A special meeting of the society's 16-member board, which it
calls the council, will be held Saturday, Jan. 15, to discuss the
changes. The protesters plan to appeal to the society's leaders to
freeze the buyouts for a year and to reconsider its decision to
spend $16 million to move the society downtown from the
neo-Classical villa on 155th Street and Broadway that has been its
home for 93 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unique as a cultural institution,'' said Dr. James H.
Schwartz, a professor of neurology and psychiatry at Columbia
University's College of Physicians and Surgeons, who is leading the
revolt. He accused the council of acting without properly
consulting the society's 2,000 members and said its actions
threaten the organization's strongest asset: its international
reputation for scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   But Ute Wartenberg, the society's executive director, says that
she is simply following through on the council's directive to cut
the annual deficit by $400,000. In addition to offering to buy out
the curators, the senior staff took a 7.5 percent salary cut, six
guards and maintenance workers were laid off Dec. 31 and the
society is now closed to the public on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we want to get rid of the curators,'' said Ms.
Wartenberg, who has a doctorate in papyrology and is an expert on
ancient Greek coins. ``We are trying to cut the deficit to half a
million dollars and hope that the move downtown will allow us to
raise money and build the organization back up.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems facing the Numismatic Society are similar to those
that confront many museums as government support has waned in
recent years and the competition for private philanthropy has grown
more fierce. But the adjustment has been particularly difficult at
the society, which is also having an identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had the question of: Who are we?'' said Arthur A.
Houghton III, who stepped down as president of the society in
October. ``Are we a learned society or are we a museum?''
</P>
<P>
   The society houses what is widely acknowledged to be the best
numismatic library in the world. Both the librarians and the five
curators are recognized by other scholars around the globe for
their expertise. (Several scholars have sent letters of protest to
the council since word of the proposed cuts has spread.) The
society's graduate summer seminar is famous as a training ground
for budding archaeologists and historians.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The society's deficit has been growing for more than a decade. A
campaign raised $3.6 million in the late 1980s but that was not
sufficient to cover annual losses. In 1998, the American
Association of Museums revoked the society's accreditation. It said
the society's public community and education programs were too
weak, and criticized the society for raiding its endowment, which
it said was inflated by the booming stock market, to pay for its
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years many members of the council also came to the
conclusion that the society would not survive unless it moved from
its historic location at Audubon Terrace on 155th Street, which is
also home to the Hispanic Society of America and the American
Academy of Arts and Letters. (The Museum of the American Indian and
the American Geographical Society were once located there as well.)
</P>
<P>
   They say that it is too difficult to get people to visit the
society and that wealthy benefactors do not feel comfortable with
the location. ``Where we are now we can't raise funds,'' said
Donald G. Partrick, a Long Island real estate developer who is the
society's new president.
</P>
<P>
   After an exhaustive search in which the society contemplated
moving to San Francisco, Philadelphia and a site on Central Park
West, it bought a building at 140 William St. in the financial
district for $7.8 million. Proponents of the move say that a museum
devoted to the history of money, located in the heart of Wall
Street, will draw wide interest.
</P>
<P>
   To buy the building, which formerly housed a bank, the society
borrowed $4.2 million from its $16 million endowment. It plans to
spend $6 million to create a library, vault and office space in the
first phase of a renovation and $4 million to create exhibition and
lecture space in a second phase that won't be completed for at
least five years.
</P>
<P>
   Partrick said the society had already paid back $1.2 million to
the endowment and has pledges of $5.2 million toward the cost of
the renovations.
</P>
<P>
   But Schwartz, the chief critic, said that the move amounts to a
Faustian bargain. He says he does not believe the society can be
turned into a museum that will mount blockbuster exhibitions. The
decision to move should be reconsidered, he added, if it means
having to eliminate the society's curatorial staff. ``If they can
drum up $10 or $15 million for the building, why can't they drum up
half a million a year for curatorial salaries?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Partrick countered that one has nothing to do with the other.
``Pledges have been made for the new location,'' he said. ``They
are not available to fund our deficit. Nobody wants to support a
sinking ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Though all five curators have been offered the severance
package, which includes up to 18 months' pay and a year of health
insurance, it is not clear how many positions will be cut. Schwartz
wants the council wait a year before eliminating any positions so
that he and other society members can mount a major fund-raising
campaign. He freely admits that the society's bylaws give the
fellows no power over the council.
</P>
<P>
   Partrick does not sound like he will be moved. ``These people
suggest that we may be able to raise funds to save the curators,''
he said. ``I hope they are right, and I will try as hard as I can
to help them. But I have to be realistic. I honestly don't think it
is going to happen. We need an angel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
