<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BROADCAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SEEKS 100 PERCENT CANADIAN CONTENT ON CBC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Quebecer Celine Dion may sing the theme song, but
Canadian broadcast regulators want to scuttle ``Titanic.'' And they
want movie spy Austin Powers to keep his shagging self south of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the stage for a Canadian clash over American culture,
government regulators this week told the Canadian Broadcasting
Corporation to stop showing blockbuster Hollywood movies in favor
of loftier Canadian-produced fare.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Radio-Television and Communications Commission,
which regulates the country's airwaves, also wants the
government-funded CBC to cut back on highly popular showings of NHL
games and concentrate on home-grown drama, dance, documentaries,
and ``amateur athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a surprising show of defiance, the CBC's boss has vowed
to resist nationalist meddling, saying it would economically
endanger the venerable network by driving away viewers and
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to transform CBC into the PBS of the north,
with nothing but elitist programming,'' said CBC President Robert
Rabinovitch, referring to America's highbrow Public Broadcasting
System.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need those American shows to generate revenue,'' he said at
a news conference. ``There is no way CBC can implement these
decisions, period.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission flatly instructed CBC to stop showing ``big box
office, non-Canadian'' movies _ read, American _ within three years
or risk losing its license. Although it seems doubtful the
regulatory body has authority to shut down the national
broadcaster, it can certainly turn the debate over programming from
the United States into a hot political issue, and perhaps force
Parliament to resolve what could turn into an ugly controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The CBC is a national institution created in 1936 as a radio
counterweight to the deluge of broadcasts from the giant neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   CBC Radio offers commercial-free programming that is nearly 100
percent Canadian in content. But CBC TV, which airs commercials, is
a curious melange of Canadian ``public interest'' programming,
including newscasts and documentaries, coupled with entertainment
that includes Canadian-produced dramas and sitcoms but also
Hollywood films. The movies attract big audiences and big
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   CBC TV competes against two smaller Canadian commercial
networks, both of which have complained that ``Mother Corp,'' as
the CBC is sometimes called, receives $515 million a year in
government subsidies, or about three-quarters of its budget. The
private networks serve mainly as profitable platforms for American
TV. Nearly every Canadian can tune in US channels via cable or
satellite, or because they live close enough to American cities.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the Radio-Television Commission was taking aim at
a perceived onslaught of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CBC is a critical pillar of Canada,'' said Elizabeth
McDonald, president of the Canadian Film and Television Production
Association. ``The fact that the CRTC sees this is good news.''
</P>
<P>
   But many ordinary Canadians turn to nightly TV for a good flick
or rousing sports match, not caring too much about its national
origin. There are extremely popular Canadian shows, such as the
comedy ``This Hour has 30 Minutes,'' but also lots of stultifying
programming subsidized by this or that provincial film board. It's
a standard complaint among Canadians that they are force-fed too
much ``this is good for you'' programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privatize the CBC, and let the public decide what they want to
see and hear in a mandarin-free environment,'' urged viewer Robert
Wilson in a letter to the Toronto-based National Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Still, polls show that most Canadians see CBC as an important
guardian of national culture and values. Rabinovitch noted that CBC
is Canada's biggest producer of home-grown television, but it needs
some American fare to survive in an era of government budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new conditions are fiscally irresponsible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ban on Hollywood movies, the commission
instructed CBC to make a 20 percent cut in professional sports
programming (including NHL games, which are very popular), dedicate
more prime time to ``dramas, music, dance, and variety shows''
produced in smaller provinces, and emphasize ``cross-cultural
French-English'' programming.
</P>
<P>
   The CBC has been the subject of fierce debate in Canada for five
years, ever since the government of Prime Minister Jean Chretien
cut public funding by $250 million, which resulted in more
commercial programming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
