u i BC-ISRAEL-VISITS-NYT &LR;      01-07 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-VISITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN WOULD STRENGTHEN TIES BETWEEN ISRAEL AND YOUNG JEWS ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.C., N.Y., Pa.)  (mk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As loudspeakers blared a welcome at Ben-Gurion
Airport, Michael Sherman stepped off a jumbo jet one recent morning
with more than 400 other American Jewish college students.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the group, Sherman, 21, had never been to Israel
and had only tenuous links to Jewish life back home, in Orlando,
Fla. Standing on the sun-drenched tarmac, he seemed expectant that
his 10-day visit would reconnect him to his Jewish identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this will spark something inside me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman's group was the first planeload of students brought here
as part of Birthright Israel, an ambitious effort to stem erosion
of Jewish communities abroad by bringing young Jews on free
educational visits to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to reach the Jewishly uninvolved, strengthening their
ties to Israel and Judaism, thus bolstering Jewish communities that
have been hard hit by intermarriage and a drifting away of their
younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been nothing quite like this in Israel,'' said
Shimshon Shoshani, the chief executive officer of Birthright. ``We
will lose the Jewish people if we don't do something.''
</P>
<P>
   But the vast scope of the project, the first of its kind funded
by the Israeli government, in partnership with Jewish
philanthropists and communities abroad, has generated heated debate
about the allocation of Jewish resources. The ultimate goal is to
draw 50,000 young Jews a year to Israel, both high school and
college students.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that Birthright's long-term impact is impossible to
assess, and that it would be better to spend the money on Jewish
day schools and social services in Israel than on giving free tours
to people who could well pay. The critics ask whether the students
are just coming for a free ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providing vast sums of money to youngsters, including many
from affluent homes, for 10-day junkets without requiring any form
of commitment is demeaning to Israel,'' Isi Leibler, the chairman
of the board of the World Jewish Congress, wrote recently in The
Jerusalem Post. ``It is inconceivable that a 10-day trip can be the
jump-off point for creating newly committed Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers reply that they are seeking the uncommitted, and that
reaching them could transform the relationship between Israel and
the Jewish diaspora. They argue that Jewish communities could be
energized by the vastly increased numbers of young Jews who would
experience Israel and return home with a heightened awareness of
their Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   In the first wave of visitors expected through February, 6,000
college students are supposed to arrive from a dozen countries,
mostly the United States. The visitors typically heard about the
program on their campuses, and competed in a lottery for spots.
Many more high school students come in as first-time visitors.
``This would change the Jewish world,'' said Michael H. Steinhardt,
a former Wall Street financier and philanthropist from New York. He
initiated the project with Charles R. Bronfman, co-chairman of
Seagram Co. and a prominent contributor to Jewish causes.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by an idea first proposed several years ago by Yossi
Beilin, now the justice minister, Steinhardt said that his ideal
would be to provide ``every young Jew on the planet a free
educational trip to Israel as a birthright.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The non-Orthodox diaspora is in crisis, and we've reached the
point where the decline in numbers is critical,'' Steinhardt said.
``None of the efforts Jewish communities are making are reaching a
substantial portion of the young people, who are uninvolved and
remote from the community. We have to reinvent this connection.''
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle is a visit to Israel. According to current
estimates, more than 80 percent of the 1.2 million Jews who are 15
to 26 years old and living outside Israel have not visited the
country, and 65 percent of American Jews have not been to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Students visiting under the program go to some of Israel's most
evocative sites like the Western Wall, the ancient Jewish fortress
of Massada and the Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial, and have meetings
with Israeli students and discussions about Jewish identity.
</P>
<P>
   The experiences touched Gabriel Stern, 19, a Duke University
student from Long Island, N.Y., who described himself as an
atheist.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents always impressed upon me that I'm Jewish, but I
never really bought into it,'' he said. ``But after going to
Massada, seeing that my people were there 2,000 years ago, touching
the stone, it hits home. There's a passion here. People my age are
walking around with guns, defending their country, all with a
purpose. In Long Island, the biggest problem is what I'm going to
wear the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Other students said they were struck by the secular character of
a country they had always thought of in religious terms, and some
said they were intrigued enough to consider a return trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here and seeing the diversity of opinions raises more
questions,'' said Sari Altschuler, 20, of New York City, a student
at Swarthmore College. ``In Israel, you see hundreds of different
viewpoints of what it means to be Jewish. Does it mean religion,
ethnicity, or a culture?''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the students have begun criss-crossing Israel, key
elements of Birthright have yet to fall into place, raising doubts
about its future.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish communities in the United States are still hesitant to
contribute money, worried that the project will draw funds and
people away from their own programs, including youth trips to
Israel for which participants pay.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 14 philanthropists that are supposed to help finance
the effort has yet to be completely assembled. And the Israeli
government, though it agreed to provide $70 million over five
years, has allocated only $8 million in its current budget,
according to Rabbi Michael Melchior, the Israeli minister of
diaspora affairs, who is a strong advocate of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Blumenthal, a member of the opposition Likud party, who
chairs the Israeli Parliament's committee on immigration and
diaspora affairs, said the government was throwing money at the
wrong people for the wrong purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that huge sums are being spent to bring young
people here for free, while children in poor Israeli towns can't
afford a class trip,'' Mrs. Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main goal of the project is not immigration to Israel but
strengthening Jewish communities abroad. That's not the thrust of
the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoshani, of Birthright, noted that many public buildings in
struggling Israeli towns were built with contributions from Jews
abroad, and he argued that a vibrant diaspora was a critical
support for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the strategic assets of the state of Israel,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1917EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
