<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9740 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS &LR;      01-07 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH TALK FROM BOTH SIDES MARKS ISRAELI-SYRIAN TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying the Israeli-Syrian peace talks were ``hard
stuff,'' President Clinton presented leaders of both sides a
working document Friday to help them bridge their differences.
</P>
<P>
   While Syrian and Israeli sources called the document helpful,
they compared five days of talks so far in a conference center in
the Shepherdstown, W. Va., hills to two foes peering at a
chessboard, neither side moving key pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Syria wants Israel to declare first that it will retreat from
the Golan Heights, restoring the border to where it was on June 4,
1967, before Israel seized the high plateau. And Israel wants Syria
to say first what Israel will get in return, both in terms of
peaceful relations and security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Among all the pairs of Middle East peace negotiators, there is
no dynamic as cool and calculating as the Israeli-Syrian one, where
developing personal relations has almost no importance.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin spoke Friday of an
improving ``chemistry'' between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa after their second
meeting alone with President Clinton, but he quickly added, ``This
is not warm and fuzzy.''
</P>
<P>
   After his fourth visit to West Virginia in five days, Clinton
would only say the teams were ``working along, working along.''
Rubin suggested that Barak and Sharaa might return to their
respective homes early next week, leaving technical teams behind to
work on details. Clinton, he said, might return over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Early difficulties for Syria and Israel do not mean they cannot
strike a deal, but the opening round shows the going will be tough
and business-like.
</P>
<P>
   That's how one man wants it. He is Syrian President Hafez Assad
in Damascus, who gave Sharaa enough direction to consummate the
final steps of a deal, as long as it includes all of the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not a Syrian bluff,'' said Murhaf Jouejati, a Syrian
foreign policy analyst. ``There have been a series of crises in
West Virginia that are all related to the same point: the Syrians
insist on hearing a commitment from the Israelis that in the end
they will withdraw to the June 4 lines. And we want to make damn
sure that the Americans are witness to this, so it's not some
exercise in futility.''
</P>
<P>
   The tenor of the discussions provides a glimpse into the future
difficulties of establishing a relationship after more than three
decades of war, regardless of whether Israel opens an embassy in
Damascus or Syria installs one in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is one of the world's most diplomatically isolated
countries, and Assad is one of the world's most isolated leaders,
having never traveled to the United States and rarely going abroad,
with the exception of Egypt. Since the early 1970s, he has
controlled a vast bureaucracy, and along the way he has shrunk the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs to its skeletal state.
</P>
<P>
   The post of ambassador is vacant at about 40 Syrian embassies
around the world; Assad's apparent disdain for diplomacy is so
great that he even pulled out his longtime US ambassador, Walid
Moualim, on Dec. 22, just 11 days before the peace talks with
Israel began anew.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sharaa stopped recently in Cairo to talk with Eygptian
officials, a sign that he is looking elsewhere in the Arab world
for support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Syria has learned something from Egypt and the
Palestinians . . . to hold back more, so they didn't have to come
forward too much in these talks,'' said Mohammed Wahby, a former
diplomat and now a columnist at the Egyptian newspaper Al-Mussawar.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts on Syria, including Richard W. Murphy, the longtime
American diplomat who served as US ambassador to Syria from 1974 to
1977, believe that Assad gave one clear order to his negotiators:
</P>
<P>
   ``The border is where it was June 4, 1967,'' Murphy said. ``It
doesn't take too much creativity to say, `June 4, 1967, do you
understand me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   After earlier Israeli-Syrian talks, from late 1995 to March 1996
in eastern Maryland, all parties said the outlines of a deal were
either two-thirds or three-quarters complete. In 1995, secretary of
state Warren Christopher told Assad that Israel would withdraw to
the June 4 lines, but Israeli leaders later said that was only a
hypothetical position, contingent upon other parts of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Uri Savir, who was then head of the Israeli delegation, cited
progress in eight broad fields. Moualim, the just-recalled Syrian
ambassador who headed the Syrian side, generally agreed with Savir,
telling Helena Cobban, an author, that the two sides had completed
arrangements on a two-stage Israeli withdrawal from the Golan;
early-warning systems monitored by airplane and satellite; zones of
demilitarization and limited forces _ in all, nine of 15
``elements'' on the table for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``The Process: 1,100 Days That Changed the Middle
East,'' Savir said shifting from talking with the Palestinians to
negotiating with the Syrians took much adjustment for the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our standpoint, the negotiations were a more difficult
intellectual challenge than the talks with the Palestinians,
because we had to adjust to dealing with a mindset radically
different from our own,'' Savir wrote. ``. . .If the negotiations
with the Palestinians turned with time into a dance in which each
side tried to outdo his partner, . . . the negotiations with Syria
were like a complex, multilayered chess game in which the players
had to finish in a satisfactory draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Singer, the Israeli legal adviser to the Syrian talks and
now a Washington lawyer, also described it as a chess game. ``You
are calculating,'' he said in an interview. ``You can smile if it
fits your purposes, but it's not a spontaneous smile. With the
Syrians, either none are smiling, or all are smiling, depending on
their instructions. It's all part of the rules of the game that are
provided to them from home.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Friday night during the 1996 Israel-Syria talks, a Syrian
official flew to Damascus to brief Assad in person because the
Syrians did not trust the security of telephone lines, Cobban said.
At the beginning of each week, the official returned with new
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian and Israeli teams in West Virginia are largely made
up of the 1996 players, with the exception of Sharaa and Barak.
While Barak's presence ensures fast decision-making on the Israeli
side, there is still doubt about Sharaa's leeway, although it would
be greater than Moualim's in 1996, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian side includes three generals who sit on committees
dealing with security arrangements and borders; two former
ambassadors to the United States, Moualim and Rafiq Jouejati; four
water experts; and Assad's translator, Bouthaina Shaban, a
professor of literature who has written about feminism in the Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
   Singer, the former Israeli legal adviser, said that regardless
of the personalities involved, ``the negotiations will be conducted
in a pressure cooker,'' and the Israelis shouldn't expect as much
as a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Palestinians, I was shocked when I first met with a
PLO representative in Oslo and he kissed me,'' Singer said.
``Generally, I'm not used to this man-kissing-man thing, and
specifically I'm not used to when it comes from a member of a
former terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``But does this mean negotiations are easier with the
Palestinians than with the Syrians who will not shake hands with
Barak? Not necessarily. To get a deal you need to talk and talk and
talk. That's what it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
