</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-GHOSTS$ADV9-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GHOSTLY SIGHTINGS LEAVE PRISONERS, GUARDS ON EDGE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Jan. 9, 2000) 
 
By JIM HENDERSON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Sam Houston was new to the Walls Unit in
1985 and to the cell block known as the Old East Wing, but he had
heard stories about the strange assortment of convicts that faded
in and out of the place. Not long after his arrival, he met one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just come in from work about 11 that morning,'' he says.
``I was in my cell layin' down and a guy came by wearing a coat ...
a white coat like the inmates wear. But it was warm, too warm for a
coat. I thought it was Sam Hoover, the guy in the cell next to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I yelled, `Hoover, what are you doing, having the chills?'
Then I thought, `Hoover don't walk that way.' I went over to the
door and looked through the bars and this guy was walking past
Hoover's cell and just disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, a 66-year-old lifer with a famous name and a string of
auto theft convictions, had no doubt he had seen a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people laughed at me, but I know I seen what I seen,''
says Houston, a trusty who was moved to the Walls Unit 15 years ago
to cook for the warden. He was so unnerved by the experience that
he arranged to be moved to another cell block.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone laughed. Similar sightings have been reported in
the prison for generations by inmates and guards alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some guards who won't come back here,'' says prison
spokesman Larry Fitzgerald, standing deep in the abandoned cell
block, near the solitary confinement box where outlaw John Wesley
Hardin once spent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The East Wing, built in 1848, was the original Texas prison and
was changed little over the years. Plaster eventually covered the
brick walls and a larger structure was built around it; otherwise,
it retained the grim texture of a frontier lockup, adjacent to the
present-day execution chamber.
</P>
<P>
   It was closed to inmate occupancy in 1990 and the 120 cells have
since been used for storage while the building awaits conversion to
a museum or is preserved for some other use.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of history and a lot of sadness here,''
Fitzgerald says.
</P>
<P>
   Suicides were common during the nearly 140 years that the East
Wing was occupied. The most storied was that of Santana, a
marauding Kiowa chief, who flung himself off the third-story
catwalk rather than live behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the apparitions are believed by the inmates to be the
ghosts of convicts who died in the cell block.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one called Ax Man,'' Houston says of a spirit thought
to be that of a convicted murderer who decapitated his victim. ``A
lot of people have seen him. He walks around carrying a head in his
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners also tell stories of ghosts that hovered or walked
through walls as they move from nowhere to no place, of barber
chairs that spun mysteriously when no one was near them, of
footsteps on the stairs when all the inmates were locked down, of
moaning and wailing coming from empty corners and ashen men seen
sitting in cells that had been vacant for years.
</P>
<P>
   Houston never saw any ghosts there after the 1985 incident, but
as recently as four months ago he felt their presence. He went to
the cell block, escorted by a captain, to look for a mattress. The
captain waited at the entrance, while Houston went to the second
floor, where mattresses were stored in abandoned cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't go up there with me,'' Houston says of the
captain. ``I don't blame him. I'd never go in there if I didn't
have to.''
</P>
<P>
   On the second level, Houston reached through the bars of a cell
door that was closed and padlocked and inspected the mattresses.
Not finding a suitable one, he moved on to the next cell and then
returned to the first one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stepped back over there and that door was open,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ghost stories have persisted for so long that it is
difficult to dismiss them as the delusional babbling of stir-crazy
convicts. The guards tell similar tales.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Rod Kukua was introduced to the ghostly inhabitants shortly
after he began working at the Walls Unit 15 years ago. All the
inmates had been locked in their cells and Kukua was walking the
corridors counting heads, making certain that every prisoner was in
place.
</P>
<P>
   After counting rows on the first floor, he went up to the second
level and saw an inmate standing outside a cell, looking into it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `` &LR; I was going to ask him what he was doing out there, so I
counted my way toward him. When I got to where he had been
standing, nobody was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kukua went to the back of the cell block and circled back to
where he had started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't find him,'' he says. ``All the doors were locked,
so it couldn't have been one of our inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Bill Holmes, a 14-year veteran of the Walls Unit, was
working the graveyard shift in the East Wing several years ago.
Looking up from a table where he was doing paperwork, he saw
something, or someone, come out of the exterior wall and enter the
last cell at the far end of the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hairs on my neck raised up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He walked to the cell and asked the inmate if he had seen
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir, Mr. Holmes,'' the inmate said, ``he comes through
here every once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes requested, and was granted, a transfer to another area of
the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father had worked here and he told me a lot of stories
about this place,'' he said. ``In the early stages, I didn't want
to go in there.''
</P>
<P>
   One story his father had told him was about a night when he was
stationed in the guard tower at one end of the East Wing. The steel
trap door into the tower began jumping up and down, as though
someone were pounding it from below.
</P>
<P>
   ``There couldn't have been anyone there,'' Holmes says. ``For
anyone to get onto the stairs to the tower, my father would have
had to lower the key to them on a string. He had the only key and
he hadn't lowered it to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't bother him that there are skeptics who scoff at such
tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a believer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
