<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OFFENSIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN BOMBARDMENT OF GROZNY HALTED AMID ARMY SHAKEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In an apparent sign that Russia's campaign against
separatist rebels in Chechnya may be running into trouble, military
officials Friday announced a shakeup of its top combat generals and
called a temporary halt to the bombardment of Grozny, the breakaway
republic's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements were the first sign of concern in Moscow about
the three-month-old military operation in Russia's restive Caucasus
region. For months, Kremlin and military officials have been
claiming that the war was going smoothly, and that Chechnya would
soon be under their control.
</P>
<P>
   The changes came as Russian forces remained bogged down on the
outskirts of Grozny, as they have been for weeks. Moscow had hoped
to capture the capital by New Year's, but its forces appear to have
been frustrated by the mobile and determined, albeit outnumbered,
Chechen fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Ministry said Lieutenant General Gennady Troshev,
commander of Russia's forces in eastern Chechnya, and Major General
Vladimir Shamanov, who heads federal troops on the western front,
were being replaced. Troshev was replaced by his deputy, Major
General Sergei Makarov, and Shamanov was succeeded by Major General
Alexei Verbitsky.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials insisted that such command reshuffles are
common and that the changes were not related to the performance of
the Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The command changes were ``not the result of any professional
errors of the commanders, who are simply returning to their former
positions,'' said a Defense Ministry statement read on television
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders also said they were scaling back air and
artillery strikes on Grozny, although details were sketchy and
statements on the matter contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grozny has today been officially declared a risk area, an
ecological danger zone. That chiefly affects civilians and
children,'' Troshev told NTV television from the Russian military
headquarters in Mozdok, outside Chechnya. ``Therefore the military
command decided to suspend operations _ suspend does not mean
discontinuing military actions. Military actions are being carried
out round the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   In other televised comments, Troshev said the assault on Grozny
would continue ``in areas where there are no civilians.'' The
Russian state news agency Itar-Tass said Troshev's comments
referred only to air and artillery bombardment of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Russia claims that some 20,000 civilians remain trapped in
Grozny and are being used as human shields by the rebels. The
separatist fighters, however, say 40,000 civilians remain in the
capital and are unable to leave due to constant Russian
bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Moscow also said the rebels have been blowing up
containers of toxic chemicals in Grozny. The Chechen fighters
denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, Russian forces launched artillery attacks on the
town of Vedeno, a rebel stronghold in the mountains of southern
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin launched its military assault on Chechnya in late
September after a series of apartment bombings that killed hundreds
of people in Moscow and other Russian cities. Russian authorities
blamed Chechen rebels for the bombings, although the Chechens deny
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
