<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ARMY-ADS-ART-470&AMP;ADD-     01-07 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-ADS-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY IS CHANGING ITS ADVERTISING AGENCY AND PROBABLY ITS SLOGAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ill.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With recruiters struggling to fill its ranks and
public perceptions of its role apparently blurring, the Army plans
to overhaul its advertising and marketing campaign, ending its
contract with the advertising agency Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. after 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate and perceptible impact of the changes, which
the Army announced Friday, may be the demise of ``Be all that you
can be,'' the Army's slogan for two decades, but one that officials
said may no longer attract the prospective enlistees the Army
desperately needs.
</P>
<P>
   ```Be all you can be' is a great slogan,'' P.T. Henry, the
assistant secretary of the Army for Manpower and Reserve Affairs,
said Friday. ``It is the trademark of the Army, known around the
world, and it has served the Army well. The question is, is it the
right slogan today to recruit young men and women for the Army of
the 21st Century?''
</P>
<P>
   The Army's announcement underscored the nagging difficulties
that all of the nation's armed services are having signing up new
recruits at a time when the economy is booming and more young
people than ever are finding college an attainable goal. Despite
higher bonuses and grants for tuition, the services' harried
recruiters have been scrambling, often unsuccessfully, in recent
years to meet their recruiting goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year that ended last September, the Army fell
short of its goal of 74,500 recruits by 6,291, an 8 percent
shortfall, while the Air Force missed its goal 32,673 by 1,727, or
5 percent. A year before, the Navy fell short by 7,000 recruits or
12 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this fiscal year, the Air Force has
again fallen short. While the Army has reached its monthly
recruiting goals, officials worry that the service could fail to
reach the more ambitious annual goal of 80,000 new enlistees it
needs to maintain its current force of 480,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do anything,'' Henry said of the Army, ``we're not
going to make the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army did not formally dismiss Young &AMP; Rubicam, which took
over the service's advertising campaign in 1987. But in an unusual
move, the secretary of the army, Louis Caldera, decided to exercise
the Army's option not to renew the agency's contract when it
expires on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The current contract, worth about $14 million a year, was
negotiated in 1997 and included four one-year options, renewable
each year. Had the Army continued its renewals, the contract would
have continued through 2002.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its announcement, which The Wall Street Journal first wrote
about on Friday, the Army said it would invite major advertising
agencies to bid for a new contract that would link payment to
measurable results in increasing enlistments. The Army hired a
consulting firm, Jones-Lundin Associates Inc. from Chicago, to help
in the search.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Army said it hoped Young &AMP; Rubicam would
compete for the new campaign, but officials at the agency sounded
irked by the Army's handling of the contract and its decision to
exercise its option seven months early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not made a decision yet as to whether we'll take part
as the Army recompetes the contract,'' said Bill Kelly, managing
partner for the agency's U.S. Army Group, overseeing general
advertising, direct marketing and public affairs. ``We're not
balking at recompeting. That's a fact of life for a government
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``We have real issues with the process and the
timing.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Army has taken the most drastic step, all of the armed
services have begun to rethink their advertising and marketing
strategies in the wake of several years of recruiting difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, no longer content with public service television
announcements, the Air Force began paying for television
advertising for the first time, and so far has spent $29 million
this year to put them on the air, though officials say it is too
early to tell if those ads have helped boost enlistments. Last
fall, the Navy took the unusual step of mailing letters to 65,000
retired sailors and officers, asking them to consider rejoining.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's changes grew in part from a critical study completed
last fall for Secretary of Defense William Cohen by two prominent
political consultants, Carter D. Eskew, a Democrat, and Michael R.
Murphy, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In it, they criticized the services for failing to articulate
their mission and for spending advertising dollars inefficiently,
by broadcasting ads during national sports events, for example,
rather than targeting niche markets on syndicated or cable
programs. The consultants also recommended that the services
conduct better research into young people today in order to target
advertising to different audiences.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the Army announced it was creating a marketing
division to do just that. It also plans to hire market-research
firms to devise ways to learn more about attitudes and tastes of
young people so that the Army's advertising budget, which has risen
from $85 million two years ago to $115 million today, is better
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said that officials now believed that people enlist for a
variety of reasons _ patriotism, college tuition, adventure _ while
the Army had a broad, blunt message.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make the case the Army has not maintained a
communication link with America,'' he said. ``We used to do that,
but we're not making the case as well as we used to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1924EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
