<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9745 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-HEATING-OIL-BOS &LR;      01-07 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HEATING-OIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS EXPECTED, HEATING OIL PRICES SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What a difference a year has made for Massachusetts
householders who heat with oil.
</P>
<P>
   Last January's rock-bottom average heating-oil prices, between
75 and 80 cents a gallon, are but a memory. The state office that
monitors prices this week said the prices being charged by
full-service dealers across Massachusetts ranged from 94 cents to
$1.30 per gallon, averaging $1.12.
</P>
<P>
   That's up 30 to 35 percent on average, and perhaps as much as 50
percent if you were buying cheap in 1998-99 but got caught at the
high end of the scale this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Runups like these were predicted last fall in a federal agency
report that cited production quotas imposed by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries as the reason, and recalled that
warmer-than-average weather last year reduce the need for heating
oil and helped keep prices down.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many consumers apparently were numbed by the smaller
bills they paid last winter and and spring and even as recently as
last October, and caught off guard by the upturn that crossed the
$1-dollar-a-gallon mark in November and kept on climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find some of my automatic-delivery customers aren't filling
up their tanks,'' Diane Silvia, manager at the Top Fuel Co. in
Woburn, said. ``They say, `Give me a hundred gallons,' hoping it is
going to go down. I say to them, `It's like going to Las Vegas.
It's a gamble.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Also, more of Silvia's customers are asking to pay with credit
cards this year. ``I do feel sorry for the elderly and for the
young kids,'' she said. Her cash-on-delivery customers this week
were paying 99.9 cents a gallon; those on automatic delivery plans
and those who get monthly bills were charged a dime more.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Condon, who manages the family-owned G. W. Condon Inc. oil
dealership in Randolph, says he's not getting complaints. He said
his $1.16-per-gallon price included a set operating margin that
doesn't vary no matter what wholesale prices are.
</P>
<P>
   But this price also reflected a nickel-a-gallon boost Condon and
other dealers saw from suppliers between Christmas and New Year's
Day. ``It was just before the millennium kicked in,'' said Pat
Murphy, manager at D.J. Cutter Oil in Dorchester. The price hike
apparently was based on expectations that consumers would demand
tank fill-ups in case Y2K computer failures stalled deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale price fell back when no problems occurred. But
Condon said it was no surprise that many dealers tried to make up
for last year's low revenues. ``It's been very mild for the last
few winters and you've got to make hay during hay season,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While dealers took abuse from customers, the underlying reason
they are charging more remained unchanged. OPEC, whose members
produce half the world's oil supply, agreed last March that it had
to tighten supplies to raise prices that fell during economic
downturns in Asia, Latin America, and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with those regions recovering from their 1997 and 1998
troubles, ``demand is up and production is down, and as a
consequence, predictably, prices go up,'' said David O'Connor,
commissioner of the Massachusetts Division of Energy Resources.
</P>
<P>
   The price shock was made more severe because it was hidden from
view during the summer, when demand for heating oil is almost nil.
Gasoline prices meanwhile were rising steadily, to a Massachusetts
average of $1.36 a gallon for unleaded regular at self-service
dealers in December, up 34 cents from February.
</P>
<P>
   According to US Energy Information Administration data, the
price of heating oil last winter was the lowest since 1979. The
agency, using a different statistical method than the state, said
Massachusetts consumers paid an average of 75.3 cents per gallon
last January.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said that because last winter's low demand forced
distributors to carry over stocks until fall, this season's first
deliveries cost less than they might have, averaging 95 cents a
gallon in two state surveys made in October.
</P>
<P>
   The state survey is limited to 20 dealers, and excludes dealers
who give discounts for cash payment on delivery. It also excludes
consumer buying groups. One such group, the Boston Oil Consumers
Alliance, said its prices Friday were 94.5 cents per gallon for
cash on delivery and 98.9 cents per gallon for customers who wanted
30 days to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for oil on the New York Mercantile Exchange and other
spot markets fell somewhat Wednesday and Friday on forecasts that
US and European weather may remain warm through January and reports
that some OPEC members increased production in December.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald B. Gold, a vice president at the Petroleum Industry
Research Foundation in New York, said there is no sign of OPEC
members or other exporting nations that went along with the quotas,
including Mexico, are about to break ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warmer weather has taken the edge off things, but it also has
taken the pressure off OPEC to open the taps a little bit wider,''
Gold said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
