<P>
   GRIDLOCK-EMERGENCY (Los Angeles) -- Frustrated by delays in
improvements to the 101-405 freeway interchange, California
Assemblyman Tom McClintock said he will push to declare a state of
emergency becaus the level of congestion has hit 3,000 hours of
delay a day. McClintock, R-Granada Hills, said his will propose
legislation that would empower Gov. Gray Davis to speed work on the
interchange to solve ``emergency gridlock.'' McClintock, director
of policy for the Assembly Republicans and vice chairman of the
transportation committee, said problems at the 101-405 interchange
could be solved as quickly as were those along the Santa Monica
Freeway after the Northridge Earthquake. McClintock also said that
California has $4.7 billion in transportation money that is unused
and could be directed immediately to the junction. By Steve Carney
(Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   GANG-SPIKE (Los Angeles) -- Federal agents have been called in
by the LAPD to help reverse a spike in gang violence, as reflected
by the recent gang-related shooting in San Fernando. The rise
continues a disturbing trend that began with the dissolution of the
gang truce in 1999. Violent gang crimes are on the increase
citywide and valleywide -- with a 3.3 percent increase in 1999 over
1998 citywide and 25 percent valleywide. In an attempt to avoid
more serious crimes, the city of San Fernando will devote an
officer to the schools. And the LAPD is revamping its approach to
gangs in the Valley, with better communication amongst divisions
and doing more undercover operations with federal task forces. By
Lisa Van Proyen (Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   BIG-COMPANIES (Los Angeles) -- The recent volatility on Wall
Street has caused a momentous shift among the largest companies in
Southern California. (Will move on the ``n'' California, ``a''
national and ``f'' financial news wires.)
</P>
<P>
