<HEADER>
A9749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUDITORS-STOCK-NYT &LR;      01-07 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDITORS-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: RULES PUT ACCOUNTING FIRMS ON THE DEFENSIVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1931, the American Institute of Accountants heard a plea from
its immediate past president that it adopt a rule to require that
auditors not be officers or directors of the companies whose books
they were certifying. It was needed, he said, to preserve public
confidence in the integrity of financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal did not get a warm reception. ``We have too many
rules already,'' one accountant complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with the spirit of the resolution, but I think it is
far too broad and sweeping,'' another said. ``It is dangerous
because it would prevent, or tend to prevent, a perfectly proper
relationship that might come under it ethically.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the proposal was shelved. ``The profession,'' wrote
John L. Carey, in his book, ``The Rise of the Accounting
Profession,'' ``had missed a chance to take a forward step
voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the first rules on that question were imposed in
1933 by the Federal Trade Commission, which administered the first
federal securities law until the Securities and Exchange Commission
was created in 1934. That rule barred auditors from investing in
companies that they audited, as well as barring them from being
officers or directors of those companies.
</P>
<P>
   Those rules have continued in force for nearly seven decades,
required by both the SEC and the American Institute of Certified
Public Accountants, the successor to the American Institute of
Accountants. Details have been added, but the principle has never
changed.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that many in the accounting profession have agreed
with the 1931 accountant who thought there were ``too many rules
already.'' While some have pushed for rules changes, others seem to
have concluded that the existing rules were more in the way of
suggestions than requirements. The regulators made the rules, and
the accountants promised to obey them, but no one seems to have
checked to be sure that was happening.
</P>
<P>
   At the world's largest accounting firm, PricewaterhouseCoopers,
a report released by the SEC on Thursday concluded that the vast
majority of partners had violated the rules. Partners pleaded that
the rules were too complicated and said they had not understood
them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the SEC and the Public Oversight Board gear up to
inspect other accounting firms _ with the expectation that the
results are likely to be similar _ the accounting profession is on
the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SEC has a right to expect the profession to adhere to the
rules,'' said Barry Melancon, the president of the accountants'
institute. But, he added, ``the profession has a right to expect
the regulatory environment to remain modern.''
</P>
<P>
   To some in the profession, the old rules are a handicap because
they have failed to keep up with changes in two areas _ the
expansion of the accounting firms and the growth of two-earner
families.
</P>
<P>
   The current rules say that partners in the firms _ whether they
are audit partners, or tax partners, or management consulting
partners _ are covered by rules barring them from having most types
of financial interests in companies that are being audited. A
management consulting partner based in San Diego may have nothing
at all to do with the audit of a company based in Bangor, Me., but
it is a violation if she, her husband or her minor children have a
stake in that company.
</P>
<P>
   The mutual fund rules also seem to have led to many violations.
It is acceptable to own shares in a mutual fund, even if that fund
owns shares in an audit client, but it is not acceptable for a
partner to own shares in a mutual fund if the accounting firm is
the auditor for that fund or for its investment adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts are under way to modify some of those rules. The
Independence Standards Board, an organization that monitors auditor
independence and has the authority to make changes in the rules,
subject to SEC approval, has proposed new rules on mutual fund
investments _ opening them up to all but people directly involved
in the audits of the fund companies _ and is seeking opinions on
changes regarding the way rules affect the employment of spouses.
Melancon of the institute is a member of that board, as is James J.
Schiro, the chief executive of PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a rapid growth in the services, most notably
management consulting, that are provided by accounting firms. As an
accounting firm does more and more business with a company, is
there a risk that an auditor, faced with a tough decision on an
accounting issue, will be influenced by the chance the firm will
lose the other business?
</P>
<P>
   The most important issue for the accounting profession,
particularly the Big Five that audit most large public companies,
should be the preservation of a reputation that investors are
willing to rely on.
</P>
<P>
   That reputation is coming under attack again, particularly with
the disclosure that most of the senior executives of
PricewaterhouseCoopers had violated the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-interest has replaced much of the profession's fidelity
to the public trust,'' wrote Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., in a
letter to the SEC on Friday, inquiring what the SEC was doing to
``clean up this mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Few investors seem to share Dingell's suspicions. But that could
change. The establishment of accounting independence rules in the
1930s came after the stock market had collapsed, when many
investors were looking for someone to blame for their losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
