<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW STOCK MARKET?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's a new millennium. Is it also a new stock market?
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the first week of trading, 2000 looks little like
the last half of 1999. The biggest about-face came in the NASDAQ
composite index, which rose 39 percent in the last two months of
last year. The composite ended the week down 4.59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One week's trading does not make a trend, of course, and the
NASDAQ paddled furiously upstream on Friday. But several of last
week's developments, taken together, may presage a market shift.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what happened to shares in Lucent Technologies when the
company announced flat sales and a profit decline in its first
quarter. Investors who had been happy to pay 65 times trailing
earnings for the company couldn't sell fast enough. By the end of
the week, the shares were down 25.7 percent, wiping out some $59
billion in investor wealth. Lucent closed at $53.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the news that the Securities and Exchange
Commission had sued the Internet's best-known stock guru, accusing
him of fraud. The SEC said Yun Soo Oh Park, aka Tokyo Joe, enriched
himself at the expense of his subscribers. When he urged his nearly
4,000 disciples to buy certain stocks, he was often selling shares
in the same stocks at a tidy profit for himself, according to the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Activities of Tokyo Joe may seem unrelated to the future
performance of the market over all. But his actions and those of
other Web stockjockeys have been responsible for some of the wilder
rides in NASDAQ stocks of late. If the SEC's suit has a chilling
effect in the Internet chat rooms _ which seems likely _ that could
reduce some of the volatility in the NASDAQ stocks that Web traders
like to duck in and out of.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Olstein, manager of the Olstein Financial Alert mutual
fund and an investor who likes to take a sharp pencil to company
financial statements, believes that the market is indeed at a
turning point. He thinks that investors, burned by companies whose
shares plunge a la Lucent, will start to exit sexy stocks with
excessive valuations _ and rediscover undervalued shares of
companies with venerable, if boring, businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of great companies in the nifty 50,'' he said.
``But the valuations are going to be looked at in a different
light.''
</P>
<P>
   If investors are at an inflection point, the new world may take
some getting used to. Stocks with no earnings will no longer
outperform those with solid earnings. Investors who buy stocks
based on gossip will no longer run circles around those who study
financial statements and invest based on sound business trends. The
something-for-nothing stock market will go the way of all good
things.
</P>
<P>
   Olstein may be a bit early in his call of a market sea change.
He was also early when he warned last April that Lucent was not
growing as fast as its earnings seemed to indicate. Most of the
growth in Lucent's earnings, he maintained, had come from
accounting cleverness rather than from an improving business; at
the time, the stock was trading at around $64.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent lovers scoffed. They are not scoffing now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
