<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RAMADAN08-COX     01-07 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMADAN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mosque's leader chants entire Koran from memory
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Before Imam Dr. Zafar Ali Anjum was a
Muslim cleric or a Ph.D. in Arabic literature or the leader of the
largest mosque in Palm Beach County _ before, in fact, he was even
an adult _ he was just Zafar, a 7-year-old son faced with a
daunting task: Memorize the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   Anjum was as prepared as any boy that age could be. Growing up
near New Delhi, India, the son of one of the area's most renowned
Islamic scholars, he had studied Arabic _ along with his native
language of Urdu _ since he was 4. But still, the task was
daunting. His older brother had not been able to memorize the whole
sacred book of Islam, nor had anyone else he knew.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason: The Koran is enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Between the words ``All praises are due to Allah'' and ``We
always seek refuge in Allah'' are about 1,000 pages of text and
more than 6,000 footnotes. Within those lines are everything a
Muslim man or woman needs to know to live a well-informed and holy
life, according to tradition. There is the story of creation, the
history of Noah, David, Solomon, Ishmael, Isaac, Joseph and Jesus.
There is criminal and civil law, morals, manners and philosophy, as
well as instructions for the proper way to worship, dress and eat.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Koran tells a Muslim how long a child should be
breast-fed (two years) and how and where to hit an enemy in a fight
(mightily, and in the neck). It contains the four types of liquids
the rivers in heaven run with (water, milk, honey and wine that
doesn't cause hangovers) and the maximum number of times a man can
divorce and remarry the same woman (twice).
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning I memorized two or three lines a day,'' Anjum
said this week at the mosque he now leads on Purdy Lane in West
Palm Beach. ``It's very hard because the mind isn't used to it, but
as I did it more and more I started to take half a page a day and
then a page a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, when he was 10 years old, he finished. And
this month that Herculean feat was put to the test for the 19th
year in a row as Anjum chanted the entire Koran from memory over
the course of the 30 nights of Ramadan, the Muslim holy month. Each
recitation lasted about an hour and fifteen minutes and took place
in front of about 300 Muslims. Congregants stood shoulder to
shoulder, kneeling and bowing in unison and listening to Anjum
chant in a haunting, melodic rhythm that has been handed down,
Muslims believe, since Allah spoke to his prophet Mohammed 1400
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   According to Muslim belief, the Koran was dictated to Mohammed
by Allah over the course of several years. Because Mohammed
couldn't write, he memorized the words Allah spoke to him and then
recited them to followers who wrote them down.
</P>
<P>
   The reason imams memorize the Koran today is as a kind of
insurance, Anjum said. In case there is ever an uprising against
Muslims and every Koran in the world is destroyed, the word of
Allah will be preserved in memory. Every Muslim boy _ and some
Muslim girls _ are asked to memorize at least a portion of the
Koran. Anjum estimated that perhaps one in 10,000 successfully
memorizes the entire book. And though imams are not required to
memorize it, most have.
</P>
<P>
   To keep his memory sharp, Anjum said he studies the Koran for
about a half-hour a day throughout the year and two to three hours
a day during the month of Ramadan, which, depending on the moon,
will likely end this evening.
</P>
<P>
   When Anjum was a boy and he finished the memorization, his
grandfather threw a party to celebrate the achievement and invited
500 people. The imam, now 34, remembers the lamb curry and sugar
pudding and his grandfather's praise. He never doubted he would
become an imam after that day.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishment was not only his, it was also his family's:
It is written that the parents of a child who memorizes the Koran
will be treated especially well in heaven. So Anjum is keeping a
watchful eye on his son, Sabeeh, now 11 months old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try my best to start with him as soon as possible,''
Anjum said. ``As soon as I see that his mind is developing he will
begin to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
