A9762 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-ROCKER08-COX     01-07 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consensus in mental health field: Rocker not mentally ill
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Do making racist remarks and tossing around bigoted
opinions like wild pitches mean Braves reliever John Rocker is off
his rocker?
</P>
<P>
   Whether racism is a mental disorder had been pondered by experts
long before people began scratching their heads about Major League
Baseball's order that Rocker undergo psychological evaluation for
his slurs against blacks, gays, foreigners and women in the Dec. 27
issue of Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Braves president Stan Kasten said Friday that what baseball
commissioner Bud Selig mandated for Rocker on Thursday ``isn't
exactly'' a mental-health check. ``The medical professionals
involved may be psychologists,'' Kasten said, ``but they're really
there to sit down and evaluate and suggest what the next step
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the commissioner's order has been widely interpreted as a
attempt to find out whether Rocker's behavior is rooted in a
psychological problem. The consensus in the mental health field is
that racism is not a mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Keith Woods, a psychologist and director of the mental
health center at Atlanta's Grady Memorial Hospital, says there are
so many variations of prejudice among people that finding a
psychological label to fit them all might be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many forms of racism and sexism and other `isms'
that typically aren't defined as mental disorders,'' Woods said.
``They are defined as issues we all have that we try to deal with.
But it's like gambling or other things. When it becomes excessive,
it becomes a disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Some mental disorders have symptoms that might cause people to
say racist things, Woods said _ such as Tourette's Syndrome, which
can cause sufferers to utter profanities and racial slurs
involuntarily. ``These are disorders,'' Woods said, ``where people
say things without the editing that most of us go through.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that he does not think Rocker is so afflicted.
``My assumption,'' Woods said, ``is that (the evaluation) is buying
time. They just want to put off having to do something about his
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sabina Widner, a clinical psychologist who teaches at
Augusta State University, sees something much more sinister in
what's being done to Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear these types of things, I think about Russia,'' she
said, ``where people who are dissidents, people who don't hold
majority views, are subjected to psychiatric treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alvin Poussaint, a clinical professor of psychiatry at
Harvard Medical School, is one of the few voices advocating that
racism be declared a mental illness. But he would limit the
diagnosis to ``extreme'' or ``delusional racism.''
</P>
<P>
   What Rocker has done doesn't fit that definition, but it's
``right on the edge,'' Poussaint said. ``Now, if he were to walk
into the clubhouse and punch a black teammate simply because he was
black, then I'd say he has a mental disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
