<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9763 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-FORBES-HNS &LR;      01-07 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FORBES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TRIES TO CLARIFY VOW ON TAXES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.H. _ As Republican front-runner George W. Bush
equivocated Friday on whether he had pledged not to raise taxes if
elected president, rival Steve Forbes launched a new television
commercial in New Hampshire accusing Bush of breaking an anti-tax
pledge as Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, speaking at a Rochester, N.H., news conference, described
the new ad as a ``negative'' attack by a candidate who knows the
``political clock is ticking.'' The first-in-the-nation New
Hampshire primary is Feb. 1, and Forbes is trailing in public
opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's other problem Friday was his effort to convince
reporters they had heard what he said but not what he meant during
a debate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stunned many observers during a GOP debate Thursday when he
made a pledge that sounded like his father's ill-fated 1988
presidential campaign promise of no new taxes. But Bush Friday said
that is not what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. I made a vow to cut the taxes,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters then read Bush his exact statement: ``This is not
only, `No new taxes' _ this is `Tax cuts, so help me God.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush then tried to clarify his statement, apparently to limit it
to the $483 billion tax-cut plan he has already proposed, using
money from the federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made a new announcement. It's just that I've
reconfirmed my commitment to get done that which I have done as
governor,'' noting he signed $1 billion in Texas tax cuts in 1997
and another $2.8 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was in the course of a debate, and I meant what I said,''
Bush said. ``When I say something, I mean to get it done. I've got
a record of getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, at the Republican National Convention in 1988,
pledged: ``Read my lips: No new taxes.'' But after he was elected
president, he was compelled to raise taxes in 1990, and many
believe that broken promise led to his re-election defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The new Forbes commercial, running in New Hampshire and nearby
Boston, features Houston taxpayer watchdog Mary C. Williams saying
Bush's tax record in Texas is a ``record of broken promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, head of Taxpayers for Accountability, says Bush signed
a pledge for her group during his first gubernatorial campaign in
1994, promising to oppose increases in sales or business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The pledge that bears Bush's signature is a promise to oppose a
state personal income tax or an increase in the sales tax, but it
says nothing about business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial, Williams says that Bush broke the pledge in
1997 when he asked the Texas Legislature to enact a new business
tax and raise the sales tax. But Williams doesn't say in the ad
that the governor's proposed tax increases were part of a package
of tax tradeoffs that would have cut school property taxes by $3
billion and produced an overall net reduction in state and local
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature rejected Bush's proposal and, in the end, simply
increased the homestead exemption on school property taxes from
$5,000 to $15,000. That resulted in many, but not all, Texas
homeowners receiving tax cuts of as much as $140 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which Bush supported, was the first of the ``two
largest tax cuts in Texas history,'' for which the Texas governor
has repeatedly claimed credit during his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Forbes ad does say is as a part of my plan I was
cutting taxes on the taxpayers and did. Go back and look at the
history of the tax package. It was a tax cut from day one and it
ended up being a tax cut on the final day,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The base line of our budget would have been $1 billion larger
had I not stood up and said, `We're going to cut taxes by $1
billion.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would not demand that Forbes remove the ad, but
said New Hampshire voters will know all the truth before they vote.
But he likened the commercial to ones Forbes ran against Republican
front-runner Bob Dole in 1996, ads that many Republicans believe
crippled Dole's general election campaign against President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he ought to have withdrawn the ads he ran against
Bob Dole in 1996. But he's an independent-minded person, and we'll
just have to deal with it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said commercials like Forbes' are bad for the
political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's good for the process for candidates, when
their political clock is ticking, not to lay out all of the
facts,'' Bush said. ``There's always a tendency in politics when
things aren't going well on the positive side to resort to the
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, whose campaign is struggling, has made reform of the
federal tax system a major priority.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes' ad carries a disclaimer that Williams' group doesn't
endorse candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Friday that the Forbes campaign asked her to
appear in the ad.
</P>
<P>
   She said she initially refused, but changed her mind after
deciding that voters have a ``right to know the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the Bush campaign now
believes Bush's signature on the 1994 anti-tax pledge was written
by an automatic signature pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if he used an auto-pen,'' Williams said. ``Who's
going to believe (Bush's denials)?''
</P>
<P>
   Williams admitted that Bush, despite what she says in Forbes'
commercial, didn't promise to oppose an increase in business taxes.
But she said an ill-fated proposal to expand the corporate
franchise tax to business partnerships and sole proprietorships,
which Bush also supported in 1997, could have been construed as a
personal income tax, which the governor did vow to oppose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are now witnessing is the dissembly of Mr. Bush's
campaign into its own version of Clinton denial,'' Forbes spokesman
Keith Appell said.
</P>
<P>
   Appell said the Forbes campaign also may run the TV spot in Iowa
and South Carolina, two other key early nominating states.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
