r a BC-EMBRYOS08-COX     01-07 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRYOS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Couple may destroy embryos
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The fight to give life to six embryos,
frozen for more than a decade, may soon be over. Their parents,
frustrated for two years after doctors repeatedly steered potential
couples toward ``fresher'' embryos, are considering letting them
thaw into oblivion _ even though they believe them to be living
babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may resort to some sort of memorial service and put them
to rest because it's been so frustrating,'' said Charlotte Danciu,
a Boca Raton lawyer who specializes in adoptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just wanted to give them a chance to have life,'' Danciu
said Friday. ``For them, it's been very emotional because they do
value these lives. It's not just something they want to discard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron, a 45-year-old production manager, and Donna, a 43-year-old
homemaker _ the western Broward County couple doesn't want to be
identified for fear of harassment _ had tried for 15 years to
conceive. In 1989, doctors fertilized 15 eggs and implanted four of
the resulting embryos. One took: Young Ronnie was born in May 1990.
But the pregnancy was difficult and Donna almost died. The couple
decided not to try again, but procrastinated on the fate of the
other nine embryos. After Donna later learned a vial containing
three embryos had broken and that the clinic planned to begin
charging $600 a year for storage, the couple announced in December
1997 they wanted to give the embryos away.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Danciu said, her office has received about 70
responses. Seven times, Danciu said, couples have met Ron's and
Donna's standards _ mostly that they be ``good people and
Christians'' _ but each time the effort has fallen through, most
recently within the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hurdle has been doctors' concern that freezing
techniques weren't as good a decade ago as now and that the embryos
have been frozen so long they wouldn't survive the thaw just before
implantation. Because the procedure is expensive and requires the
potential mother to take many drugs, both orally and through
injections, doctors have suggested potential parents seek other
donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we get up to the end, some doctor or fertility
center says, 'You've got a 5 percent chance of it working and
you're going to be spending $10,000 and we can get you some fresher
stuff.' That's how the doctors, unfortunately, look at them _ very
clinically. They (the couple) look at it like these are their
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth Drury, director of the In-Vitro Fertilization
Laboratory at the University of Florida, said frozen embryos have
only a 50 percent chance of surviving a thaw, but that doesn't
change over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they've been looked after, there's an almost unlimited time
span,'' Drury said from Gainesville. ``People have talked about a
thousand years.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple did not respond to a request for comment made through
Danciu. Anne DeLong, spokeswoman for the Catholic-based Human Life
International, said the embryos are live humans and it would be
wrong to destroy them. But she could offer no solution because, she
said, the couple should never have artificially created them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad when a man and woman are married and are unable
to conceive, but there comes a time when they simply must accept
that that must be part of God's plan for their lives,'' DeLong
said.
</P>
<P>
   The medical industry is wrestling with the ethics of
infertility, which affects 5.3 million Americans _ about one in 10
of reproductive age _ and has generated a $2 billion-a-year
business. While selling embryos for profit violates medical ethics
and is illegal in Florida and other states, some clinics around the
country reportedly sell eggs left by patients and fertilized by
donor sperm to desperate couples. Ethicists have said the practice
could lead to ``designer babies.'' And it's been estimated that,
across America, 100,000 human embryos sit in cold storage.
</P>
<P>
   eliotkleinberg(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
