<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Jan. 9, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-INTERNET-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Internet was supposed to be
a global medium and a stateless realm, a kind of cyber-Pangaea. But
its innovations have flourished primarily in the United States. The
generally-cited reasons include America's entrepreneurial climate _
venture capital financing, close ties between business and
universities, flexible labor markets, a deregulated business
environment, and a culture that celebrates risk-taking, ambition
and getting rich. By Steve Lohr. (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS-REVIEW (Jerusalem) _ In some ways, comparison
between the 1978 Camp David talks and the current talks in
Shepherdstown is unfair. Camp David _ 12 excruciatingly long days
in which Jimmy Carter, Menachem Begin and Anwar Sadat hammered out
a framework of peace _ was the climax of a process. Shepherdstown,
where bilateral contact has been limited to clipped utterances, is
an opening scene. But the comparisons and contrasts are inevitable,
because parallels are so explicit. By Deborah Sontag. (Moving in
`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   ROCKER-RACISM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Is making racist or xenophobic
remarks a sign of mental illness? Major League Baseball seemed to
suggest it was last week when it demanded that John Rocker undergo
psychological testing following his rantings about immigrants and
blacks. But the consensus among psychiatrists and psychologists is
that racism in and of itself is not a mental illness, unless
combined with a host of other problems. If it were, then a huge
swath of society would be considered mentally ill. By James C.
McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL-COACHES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The history of the rising
power and prestige of football coaches. In football's early years,
coaches were not venerated figures; in fact, players sometimes
ejected them from the field by when they became too dictatorial.
Today, a top coach like Bill Parcells _ who turned three losing
franchises into winners _ had achieved the superstar free-agent
status that team owners succeeded in denying the players. By Allan
Barra. (Also moving in `s' category)
</P>
<P>
   ATTICA-REVIEW (Undated) _ Why rehash the bloody Attica prison
uprising of 1971 almost 29 years later? Because its demons have
never been exorcised. Memories of them may have faded, but their
shadows are felt just the same. They were back last week when a
federal judge announced a settlement that may at last bring
finality to Attica's painful aftermath. By Clyde Haberman.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATES-MEDICAL-REVIEW (Undated) _ No law forces candidates
to bare their medical histories. But the news media and political
rivals press for revelations, hinting that those who decline may
have something to hide. Some people maintain that the public
interest demands that the usual right to confidentiality be waived.
Others question whether the public needs, wants or has the right to
such information and whether it serves a legitimate purpose. By
Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   TRAFFICS-SUVS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Once the province of city
councils and mayors, suburban traffic problems have grown
sufficiently pervasive that they are drawing attention from
presidential candidates like Al Gore. Little noticed is an
intriguing new debate among civil engineers over whether traffic is
made worse by changes in the vehicles that Americans drive. The
question is whether increasingly popular sport utility vehicles,
pickup trucks and minivans clog intersections and slow traffic. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-PENALTY-REVIEW (Houston) _ The thought of Texas as a
national role model for capital punishment is enough to make death
penalty opponents shudder, but at least a few places regard the
state worth emulating. Yet whether this suggests a growing national
appetite for more executions, carried out more quickly with fewer
appeals, is unclear. A national review of capital punishment last
year reveals several conflicting signals. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   BRAND-NAMES-REVIEW (Undated) _ In today's cluttered and
confounding marketplace, brand identification has never been more
important. The topic is ultra-hip, both in the realms of style and
business. But ``branding'' is easier said than done. By Douglas
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   BRAND-CLAIMS-REVIEW (Undated) _ What if Dominos or Chevrolet had
to prove that their advertising slogans are true? Pizza Hut was
recently awarded damages from Papa Johns for the latter's claim
that its pizza was ``better.'' By Jayson Blair.
</P>
<P>
   DYLAN-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ British poet laureate Andrew
Motion recently created a stir when he proclaimed Bob Dylan's
``Visions of Johanna'' the best song lyric ever written. A look at
some of the discussions outlining a peculiarly British fascination
with a peculiarly American performer.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY-CHRONO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Elian Gonzalez timeline: a
chronology of the child custody dispute that has roiled U.S.-Cuban
relations.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-ISLAM-REVIEW (Gusau, Nigeria) _ A look at the way Islam
must bend in Nigeria and other sub-Saharan African countries, where
it exists alongside Christianity and indigenous traditional
beliefs. In recent years, Sudan's Islamic rulers have grabbed the
West's attention in this region, as Khartoum became a harbor for
anti-American terrorists and a long-running civil war against a
mostly Christian and animist south killed 2 million people. But it
would be wrong to think that Sudan represents the attitude taken by
Muslims elsewhere in Africa. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY-SWEDEN-REVIEW (Oslo) _ Norway and Sweden are both
prosperous, blue-eyed and reserved. On the world stage, they hand
out peace prizes and preach global cooperation while saving their
aggressions, if any, for the ski slope. However, in the privacy of
their snowbound peninsula, Sweden and Norway have lately been
slugging it out. By Walter Gibbs.
</P>
