<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON INTERVENES IN MIDEAST PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ President Clinton on Friday intervened in
the peace negotiations between Israel and Syria by presenting
leaders of both countries a seven-page ``working paper'' defining
their differences over a deal that would return the Golan Heights
to Syrian control.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's action on Friday, during his fourth trip to
Shepherdstown this week, marked his first effort to define the
terms of a ``core agreement'' that could lead to a far more
detailed peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   It came after five days of wheel-spinning during the talks in
this small town 70 miles from Washington, and was presented only
after U.S. officials concluded that both Prime Minister Ehud Barak
of Israel and Syria's foreign minister, Farouk al-Sharaa, had
sufficiently demonstrated to their domestic constituencies that
they were holding out on the emotional questions of new borders and
security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was certainly part of the thinking,'' a diplomat involved
in the talks said Friday, when asked why Clinton had waited until
his fourth trip here to make the U.S. draft paper the centerpiece
of the talks. ``We had to give everyone time to vent, and they did
so pretty thoroughly.''
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat described the document as containing a proposed
text for an agreement, with points of dispute contained in
brackets, the standard method of hashing out textual differences in
diplomatic and trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials familiar with the talks said on Friday that
there was virtually no chance that the ``core'' text would be
agreed to before Barak and al-Sharaa return to the Middle East,
probably on Sunday or Monday. But a second round of talks is
expected to reconvene in the next few weeks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A similar technique _ allowing both sides to vent and then
interceding with a U.S. proposal _ was used by President Carter in
1978 on the sixth day of the Camp David meetings, which ultimately
resulted in the peace agreement between Egypt and Israel the next
year. But the United States had to go through 22 more drafts before
the deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton presented the U.S. working paper to Barak and al-Sharaa
on Friday morning, as they were seated around a fireplace in the
Clarion Hotel and conference center here, where both the Israeli
and Syrian delegations have been confined all week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wore a sweater and looked more like he was ready for
skiing than presiding over peace talks. Al-Sharaa showed up in a
suit and tie.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, whose team here drafted
the paper, and Sandy Berger, the national security adviser, also
attended the session.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, abiding by the news blackout that has surrounded
the entire week of talks, said little about the contents of the
paper. But James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said on
Friday that in defining the differences of position, the U.S. paper
would pave the way for ``some new ideas for bridging'' differences.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the paper had been constantly revised during the week
to reflect Clinton's and Albright's private conversations with both
sides. He described the talks as ``not warm and fuzzy, but
businesslike and professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides suspended the talks late Friday afternoon for 24
hours of religious observances.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to present the paper was clearly motivated by
frustration at the slow pace of the first substantive negotiations
between the two countries since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides argued all week over what issues will be
negotiated first. The Syrians were intent on establishing for their
domestic audience that Jerusalem was committed to giving back the
Golan Heights, which Israel seized during the 1967 Arab-Israeli
war, before the subject turned to the kind of security guarantees
that Barak would get in return.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis wanted just the opposite: a discussion of security
first, to make the case in Israel that they have obtained
concessions more valuable than the Golan Heights buffer zone, which
has been their main deterrent to Syrian attack for a quarter of a
century.
</P>
<P>
   If a treaty is reached, Barak has promised to hold a national
referendum before signing it. And it is far from clear that Israeli
citizens, who have been told for years that the Golan is the key to
national survival, will be persuaded to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-page document covers all the major areas of dispute,
starting with whether the border would go back to the 1967 line _
whose exact location is also in dispute _ or the 1923 line that
runs along the shore of the Sea of Galilee. That is closely related
to the question of water rights: Israel fears that if Syria can tap
the sea, Israelis will lose some of their most vital water
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue is what U.S. officials call ``normal peaceful
relations,'' the issue of whether Syria would allow Israel to open
an embassy in Damascus and, ultimately, open the border to tourism
and commerce. Syria has opposed any symbols of Israeli presence.
None of these issues are new; all have been exhaustively discussed
in past negotiations, reaching back to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the U.S. effort to get the talks started by
creating committees of Israelis, Syrians and Americans to take up
each subject broke down by mid-week. No one could agree on what
would be discussed first. Two of the committees _ one on borders,
one on water _ have yet to meet.
</P>
<P>
   The procedural argument, however, may have been largely for
show. For while they argue over the details, both sides are aware
of the changing strategic landscape.
</P>
<P>
   For the Syrians, the cost of continuing isolation, the U.S.
economic sanctions applied against a terrorist state and a
fast-declining economy have all put pressure on an ailing President
Hafez Assad to reach an accord.
</P>
<P>
   And for the Israelis, the security gains of the Golan have been
offset by better defense technology, although the Israeli right
wing argues that no amount of weaponry could replace the security
of holding on to the Golan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
