</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-MORALE-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY FINDS MILITARY MORALE, READINESS SINKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     For release Monday, Jan. 10)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Morale and overall preparedness of U.S. troops are
sinking because the stepped-up pace of peacekeeping missions over
the last decade has taxed a shrinking and underfunded American
force, a new study being released Monday concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted over the last two years by the nonpartisan
Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) here, found
that ``morale and readiness are suffering from force reductions,
high operational tempo and resource constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   Many service members, the study said, ``have deep concerns about
the state of training and readiness in their units'' and military
``leaders at all levels are frustrated by the signs of declining
readiness in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the study's authors wrote, officials at the Army's
premier training facility _ the National Training Center at Ft.
Irwin, Calif. _ said they have observed ``a marked decrease in the
proficiency'' of the service's frontline units.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little doubt in the minds of the study participants
that conditions within the armed forces are far less favorable than
they were a decade ago,'' said the 200-plus page report. It was
based on 99-question surveys of 12,000 U.S. service members in the
United States, Korea, Europe and Hawaii. The surveys were
supplemented by interviews of 125 ``focus groups'' of service
members.
</P>
<P>
   The study was headed by Edwin Dorn, a former undersecretary of
defense for personnel and readiness during much of the Clinton
administration, and Howard Graves, a retired Army lieutenant
general and former head of the U.S. Military Academy at West Point.
A major problem, according to the report, is the rapid growth of
peacekeeping, or humanitarian, missions that the military has
conducted since the George Bush administration, coupled with
shrinking budgets and a significant reduction in the size of
military forces.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pentagon figures, the rate of overseas deployments
of Army units has increased 300 percent and the number of deployed
Navy ships has increased by 52 percent since the fall of the Berlin
Wall in 1989, Bush's first year in office.
</P>
<P>
   But during the same period, the size of the Army has fallen 38
percent, the number of Navy ships, 30 percent and Air Force
personnel, 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the U.S. military has dropped from a force of 2.1
million men and women in 1989 to 1.4. million today. In constant
dollars, defense budgets have dropped 31 percent during that
period.
</P>
<P>
   The reduced budgets, low pay and far-flung peacekeeping
operations to such places as Somalia, Haiti, Bosnia and Kosovo have
contributed to ``a profound stress on the armed forces,'' the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, the leadership of the armed forces has not yet
adjusted to the reality that there are insufficient operating
resources and personnel to match missions,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Collins, a senior fellow at CSIS who helped conduct the
surveys, said in an interview with the Hearst Newspapers that
understaffing and equipment shortages are a ``major problem very
intimately connected with morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to get these words out of my mouth as an old
soldier but there is a significant morale problem,'' said Collins.
</P>
<P>
   He added that troops in all services made such comments as
``people in my unit are stressed out,'' ``my unit is continuously
being surprised with new missions,'' and ``it's impossible in my
service to have a balance between work and family life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon offered no comment on the report. But in the last
six months, military leaders have begun to acknowledge that
readiness is slipping.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Army Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, testified that while the readiness of so-called
`first-to-fight units'' was satisfactory, weaknesses in other areas
threatened the overarching U.S. strategy of being able to fight two
major foreign wars at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take longer to respond to hostilities which, in turn,
means territory lost and an increased potential for casualties,''
he said, citing problems in maintaining equipment and difficulties
in recruiting and retaining personnel.
</P>
<P>
   That same month, two Army divisions fell to the military's
lowest level of combat readiness, and the Pentagon acknowledged
that recruiters were struggling to meet their quotas for new
soldiers. To combat readiness problems, the Pentagon is asking
Congress to increase military budgets by $112 billion over the next
five years. The current annual budget is $267 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The increase will be used in part to improve the quality of life
for the troops and to modernize weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's budget, President gave the military a 4.8 percent
pay raise, the largest since 1981. Congress also gave a one-time
boost to many pay scales so that about 75 percent of all service
members will receive extra raises on July 1. In addition, the
administration recently announced hikes in housing allowances for
military members who live off base.
</P>
<P>
   In other conclusions the CSIS said race relations in the armed
forces generally are better than in the society at large. The study
found that 71 percent of all respondents said their units didn't
have racial discrimination problems, although 36 percent of
minority respondents disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   The CSIS also reported that that 28 percent of female
respondents and 13 percent of males said sexual harassment or
gender discrimination was a problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
