<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGANSTANLEY-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY WINS RIGHT TO INTERNET DOMAIN NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time around, David had a Web site but Goliath prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., the big securities firm, won
its legal fight to take possession of an Internet domain name that
purportedly was registered for a teen-ager's Web site dedicated to
mountain biking.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley plans to use the domain name, www.msdwonline.com,
as the World Wide Web address for its new online trading service,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Online.
</P>
<P>
   When Morgan Stanley introduced the service in November, it was
stuck with a cumbersome address, www.online.msdw.com, because the
address it preferred had been registered by a California family
using the name Smart Ideas. Sau Wong, a resident of Hillsborough,
Calif., claimed that his son Ivan, a 17-year-old high school
student, wanted the domain name for a mountain-biking Web site
called Mud Sweat's Downhill World.
</P>
<P>
   After the Wongs rejected Morgan Stanley's offer of $10,000 and
demanded $75,000 for the domain name, Morgan Stanley filed suit in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan. The defendants asked the court to
dismiss the suit because they did not live or do business in New
York, but Judge Alvin K. Hellerstein rejected that motion three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very purpose of the defendant's act, it is alleged, is to
attack Morgan Stanley and extort money from Morgan Stanley because
of a confusingly similar domain name that was created for no
legitimate purpose,'' Hellerstein said during a Dec. 15 hearing on
that motion.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in the case said they thought the judge's statements in
the hearing over jurisdiction indicated that he would favor Morgan
Stanley if the case continued. At that hearing, Hellerstein said
the court had jurisdiction because the Wong family's offer to give
up the name for $75,000 _ ``outrageous terms'' in the words of the
judge _ meant they were attempting to do business with a New
York-based company. ``That's business. It may not be nice business,
but it's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Wongs agreed to turn over to Morgan Stanley that
domain name and another they had registered,
morganstanleydirect.com, at no cost to the firm. Those domain names
were among dozens the Wongs had registered that contained
well-known brands and the names of Wall Street firms, like
goldmansachsdirect.com and jpmorganonline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's lawyers pointed to the long list of corporate
and brand names the Wongs had registered as evidence that they were
``cybersquatters'' seeking to profit by selling domain names to
companies that had a business purpose for them. They also pointed
out in their complaint that the Wongs did not create the
mountain-biking site until after Morgan Stanley sued them.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed legislation late last year that was aimed at
preventing cybersquatting by making it punishable with damage
awards of up to $100,000. Steven Lincoln, a lawyer in San Jose,
Calif., who represents Wong, said the new law spurred his client to
consider giving up the domain names based on corporations and brand
names.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is that Smart Ideas does not retain
registration of any domain names that are similar to or contain any
corporate names,'' Lincoln said.
</P>
<P>
   After that law passed, Morgan Stanley wrote a letter to the
judge stating that the firm believed the Wongs would be liable for
damages. The Wongs quickly shut down the Web site, replacing the
pictures of downhill bike racers with the message: ``This site will
be inactive until further notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Wong's lawyers said his clients have registered another domain
name, www.msdhw.com, that will be the new home of Mud Sweat's
Downhill World, which they described as a Web site ``devoted to
promoting the sport of mountain-biking over the Internet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
