<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN LEFTHANDER LEE JOINS RED SOX BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If the Eck was lefthanded and Korean, and dyed his hair
a shade this side of orange, he might look something like Sang-Hoon
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   And if Lee throws his fastball and slider anything like the Eck,
then the Red Sox might have themselves a surprisingly effective
addition to their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, on the day he was presented a Red Sox cap and
jersey by a sore-thumbed Dan Duquette, who has been pursuing Lee
for years, only this much is certain: Lee, whose gaudy statistics
on the far side of the international dateline led the Sox to give
him a two-year, $3.35 million contract (with a club option for
2002), has the makings of a genuine character.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: When the 28-year-old Korean went to the mound to pose
for pictures Friday, he pantomimed a pitcher watching a long drive
disappear overhead. After another ghostly delivery, he clutched his
left shoulder in mock pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a Korean, he is very unique,'' said Michael Min, a
journalist for the Chosin Sports Daily, one of several Korean
papers that dispatched reporters to Fenway Park for Lee's formal
introduction by the Sox. ``He's a very different guy.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows it, too. Two years ago, when the Red Sox thought they
had a deal for Lee only to have it scotched by Major League
Baseball, Boston Globe reporter Kevin Paul Dupont interviewed Lee
in Korea and mentioned another notable Sox pitcher of the same
surname.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Lee was crazy?'' Lee repeated. ``So am I.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee not only has a rock star's tresses, but likes to sing and
play the guitar, too. He has had not one nickname, but at least
three. When still in college, according to another Korean
journalist, he was known as Papillon, after the Steve
McQueen-Dustin Hoffman prison thriller, for his repeated (and
successful) attempts to escape dorm life. The long hair inspired
another handle, Samson, and during his time with the LG Twins, his
Korean team, he was also known as the Wild Horse, back when
Duquette swears his shoulder-length hair was jet black and not the
Tang-colored look he now sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like to go to barbershops,'' he said Friday. ``And
now it has become my trademark.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lee was asked what he knew about Red Sox history, he
revealed that rumors of the Curse apparently have circulated in his
native Seoul, too. With his words translated by his Korea-based
agent, Jung hon Lee, who works for Cleveland-based IMG, Lee said;
``I know that Babe Ruth was here and was traded (sic) to the
Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Korea, Lee is big news. He has a chance to become the
first player from his country to pitch professionally in Korea,
Japan, and the United States. When his deal with the Sox was
nullified two years ago by MLB, which temporarily quashed all
signings of Asian players until a protocol could be worked out, Lee
wound up spending the last two seasons in Japan, with far more
modest results than he had in Korea, where he won 20 games as a
starter in 1995 then two years later led the league in saves with
37.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, of course, have tried these cross-cultural experiments
before. You might recall the $3 million investment they made in the
Dominican mystery man, Robinson Checo, who came to the Sox via
Japan and in two years won one game in a Sox uniform before going
to the Tigers and then the Dodgers, who recently designated him for
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Checo, however, had had some elbow problems in the past, and
hurt his elbow again when he overdid it in his first workout with
the Sox. Lee has not had any arm problems, except for an injury to
his right (nonthrowing) shoulder, according to one of his Korean
chroniclers, that made him exempt from the military service
compulsory for all Korean males.
</P>
<P>
   Though he started 11 games last season in Japan, where he was
6-5 in 36 appearances for the Chunichi Dragons, the plan is to use
Lee exclusively in relief, according to Duquette, who expects Lee
to join Rheal Cormier as the Sox' lefthanded setup men.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said that Lee, like Korean imports Jin Ho Cho and Sunny
Kim before him, will undergo an orientation program here to make
the transition easier. He did not say whether catcher Jason
Varitek, who is facing the prospect of handling a pitching staff
that also includes Dominicans (Pedro and Ramon Martinez, Juan
Pena), a French-Canadian (Cormier), a Japanese rookie (Tomo Ohka)
and a native New Englander (Brian Rose), will be enrolling soon in
Berlitz courses.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who is married and has two daughters, plans to return to
Korea before reporting to Fort Myers Feb. 1 to begin informal
workouts with the club. According to agent Lee, the Sox gave him a
$1.05 million signing bonus and a contract that calls for him to be
paid $850,000 in 2000 and $1.45 million in 2001. Duquette, who on
Monday underwent surgery for a torn ligament in his left thumb, an
injury he sustained last week in a skiing accident, was unfazed by
the price tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great premium for lefthanded pitchers throughout
baseball,'' said Duquette, who noted Lee throws three pitches _ a
fastball, slider, and split-fingered fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The $850,000 reportedly matches the money he was paid in Japan
last season. Chunichi wanted him back and told him he could be a
closer, but Lee has had his sights set here for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With his long flowing hair,'' Duquette said, ``he'll be a good
complement to Rod Beck. He's a colorful player. We're looking
forward to having him here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
