<SLUG> BC-TITANS-BILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS-BILLS SEEN AS LIKELY SUPER BOWL MATCHUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ It goes by the name of a wild-card game, but this
could be good enough for a Super Bowl matchup in this season of
parity and surprise. Both Buffalo (11-5) and Tennessee (13-3) are
playing that well.
</P>
<P>
   NFL rules require that the two most-mediocre AFC teams in the
playoffs _ Miami and Seattle _ play. (The division-winning Seahawks
draw the team with the worst record.) The result is that the Bills
and Titans, either of whom could win the Super Bowl, are paired on
what usually is a lost weekend of football.
</P>
<P>
   All varieties of subplots abound. The Titans will be playing
their first postseason game Saturday (12:30 p.m.) in the noisy and
hot cauldron that is Adelphia Coliseum. Tennessee running back
Eddie George, like so many of his mates, will be making his first
playoff appearance ``and I'm sure I'll be nervous; I'm going to
have to calm myself down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills and the Titans will be meeting for the first time
since one of the most memorable playoff games in NFL history, when
the Houston Oilers _ the Titans' former nom de plume _ jumped out
to a 35-3 lead Jan. 3, 1993, as Warren Moon directed the Oilers'
run-and-shoot offense with ease and precision. But, with 13:15 left
in the third quarter, Buffalo backup quarterback Frank Reich began
the greatest comeback in NFL playoff history, capped when the
Bills' Steve Christie kicked a winning 32-yard field goal in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I remember the pain of that game,'' said Titans guard and
old warrior Bruce Matthews, ``I would never play football again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills, of course, are coached by Wade Phillips, who just
happens to be the son of Bum Phillips, the most storied coach the
Oilers ever had. But the son has taken a huge gamble that his
risk-taking father never took _ changing quarterbacks on the eve of
a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on playing a great game,'' said new starter Rob
Johnson, who was inserted by Phillips _ although some in Buffalo
believe owner Ralph Wilson might have taken a part in the move _ to
replace Doug Flutie. Johnson's status rose after playing very well
last Sunday against the Colts, as he threw quickly and with
confidence. The knock against Johnson in the past was that he held
the ball too long and was not quick in his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Indianapolis defense is the weakest in
the AFC East and the Colts, according to some in the Bills
organization, were not playing with their usual gusto. Johnson's
performance, therefore, should have an asterisk next to it.
</P>
<P>
   Still in all, he looked sharp and efficient in his only start of
the season, and Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher said Johnson put on
``one of the best performances'' of any quarterback this season.
Fisher's quarterback, Steve McNair, is similar to Johnson in that
he, too, will be making his first playoff start.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills have other problems. Veteran wide receiver Andre Reed
chose this week to announce that he is done in Buffalo and no
longer wants to play with the Bills. Reed, who has been known to
sulk in the past, also took some shots at Flutie. ``At this point,
I just want to go where I'm appreciated and respected,'' said Reed,
``and I haven't had that here.'' Flutie and Reed spoke Friday,
however, and cleared the air.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the status of Buffalo offensive tackles John Fina and
Robert Hicks remains uncertain for the game. Fina did not practice
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The game will feature two of the best lead blockers in the NFL _
the Bills' Sam Gash and Tennessee's Lorenzo Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Plots abound, but so will some excellent football between two of
the NFL's best teams, each forced into a wild-card matchup that is
good enough for an AFC title game . . . or even a Super Bowl, if
quality of the teams is all that mattered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
