</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUEWEST08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revamped magazine keeps tales from the Old West aliveBy Michele
Chan Santos
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The headline reads like an old-style movie
trailer in melodramatic boldface: ``Fringe Benefits of a
Prospector: He lives on the fringe of society, borders on the
fringe of starvation, skirts the fringe of paranoia _ and
undoubtedly is the luckiest man in the world!''
</P>
<P>
   It's the true story of ``Seldom Seen Slim,'' a prospector from
Sierra Nevada _ and it was typical of the tales of prospectors and
mountain men, lumberjacks and gunfighters, outlaws and cowboys that
have filled the pages of True West magazine since its inception in
the 1950s. Five decades later, though, the venerable publication
was hovering close to extinction _ until 1999, when two lifelong
fans decided to rescue it by investing their money and bringing
ownership of the magazine back to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   True West was founded in Austin in 1953 by Joe Small, and its
editors included ``Old Yeller'' author Fred Gipson, former Texas
state historian Walter Prescott Webb and renowned Austin folklorist
and author J. Frank Dobie.
</P>
<P>
   With a colorful cover and adventure-driven copy, it was the kind
of magazine boys in the 1950s and '60s adored, full of tales of
murder, train robberies and lost treasure taken from the pages of
history. It was ``All True _ All Fact _ Stories of the Real West,''
as its masthead trumpeted, but never let the fact that its stories
were true get in the way of their bravado and suspense. You can
practically hear the guitar picks behind song verses quoted in
early issues of the magazine: ``Young Billie Grounds, he was wild
and free/He was still in his teens, just a kid you see. /Young
Billie Grounds, reckless, brave and bold./ He lost his life and
caused much grief/ All for the sake of gold.''
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, in the 1960s when Western-themed TV shows like
``Gunsmoke'' and ``Bonanza'' were popular, True West had a
circulation of more than 500,000. But over the years, the
magazine's ownership drifted and its circulation began to drop. Its
headquarters moved away from Austin, first to Michigan, then to
Oklahoma. Its readers were mostly older men, and the publication
was struggling, its circulation dropping to a paltry 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then, like a sheriff and his posse riding in to save a frontier
town, two die-hard fans of True West magazine stepped in to save
it. Robert McCubbin, the recently retired vice president of
operations of El Paso Natural Gas Co., and Richard Baish, who just
retired as president of El Paso Natural Gas, began reading ``True
West'' when they were in their teens. Both have made a love of the
Old West part of their lives. McCubbin has a large collection of
Western artifacts, photographs and rare books. Baish owns a
17,000-acre cattle ranch in New Mexico and a lot of Western
memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Along with historian and author Bob Boze Bell, Baish and
McCubbin bought True West last fall. This month's issue is their
first, and these El Pasoans say they are proud to bring ownership
of the magazine back to Texas. The new publishers have already
begun renewing and improving the magazine, overseeing a redesign,
adding new columns, adding color inside and improving the quality
of the paper, hoping eventually to go to glossy pages inside. Baish
and McCubbin say they plan to add more stories about Texas Rangers
and Texas history. Although they both live in El Paso, they
temporarily moved the headquarters of the magazine to Cave Creek,
Ariz., where Bell oversaw the redesign. Most of the writers
featured in True West are free-lance contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The stories in their first issue bear the colorful flavor that's
such a trademark of True West: the adventures of John Horton
Slaughter, Texas Ranger; the story behind a mysterious highwayman
who roamed northern California in the winter of 1889; an interview
with ``Lonesome Dove'' author Larry McMurtry about his Crazy Horse
biography.
</P>
<P>
   In the February issue, one story begins ``Deep along the
unforgiving pines, their search for gold ends in a pitched light
and sudden death.'' It's not quite as kitschy as '70s-era stories
like ``He Killed A Cagey Outlaw,'' but the romantic devotion to the
Old West remains.
</P>
<P>
   One feature they're adding is a column called ``Wild Wild Sex,''
about brothels in Montana in the Old West. It's about the lives of
the women who worked there, and is an attempt to broaden the
magazine's appeal, McCubbin says. (The first line in the February
installment of the column: ``Whores have always been a hardy
breed.'') McCubbin would also like to see the publication read by
younger people and is working on ways to appeal to them.
</P>
<P>
   For Baish, taking over ownership of True West means preserving
something that was integral to his youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a business deal for us,'' says the retired
businessman, who has degrees from Southwest Texas State University
and the University of Texas. ``It's worth preserving as part of the
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, Baish says, is to see if he and his friends can
make True West adapt and evolve, so that it not only survives but
grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to go in and find something that maybe other people
thought should be written off and turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
