<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9774 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-1STLD-WRI     01-07 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB GROWTH CONTINUED AT A ROBUST PACE IN DECEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: expands on earlier PM version) 
(ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Employers added jobs at a surprisingly robust rate
in December, propelling the economy into the new year with
considerable momentum, the Labor Department reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The economy created 315,000 new nonfarm jobs last month, 75,000
more than economists had predicted and the biggest one-month gain
since July. With more people entering the work force, the
unemployment rate remained at a 30-year low of 4.1 percent, where
it has been for the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Average hourly earnings for the month rose by 0.4 percent,
slightly more than expected. But because workers are producing more
for each hour worked, the growth in wages so far shows few signs of
setting off a surge in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   While good news across the board, the figures substantially
increased the likelihood that the Federal Reserve will act to keep
the economy from overheating by raising interest rates next month.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, investors acknowledged that a rate increase is
now all but certain, but concluded that inflationary pressures are
so muted that the Fed would limit the increase to a quarter of a
percentage point rather than the half point increase that the
markets had come to fear in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Both blue chip and technology stocks surged. The Dow Jones
industrial average was up 269.30 points, to 11,522.56, a record.
The Nasdaq composite index reversed three days of sharp declines,
rising 155.49 points, to 3,882.62. Bond prices also rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough strength in this report to make it a virtual
certainty the Fed will tighten in February,'' said Stuart G.
Hoffman, an economist at the PNC Corp. in Pittsburgh. ``But I think
a quarter of a point is all that's likely to come from the Fed, and
appropriately so because this report is not so exceedingly strong
as to force the Fed into a more aggressive increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Job gains were particularly strong in retailing and construction
last month, while a prolonged decline in manufacturing jobs slowed
as exports showed signs of picking up.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed that unemployment for all of 1999 averaged 4.2
percent, down from 4.5 percent in 1998 and the lowest rate since
1969, when it was 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among black workers, the rate for the full year fell to 8
percent from 8.9 percent a year earlier, the lowest since the Labor
Department started keeping separate records by race in 1972. Among
Hispanic workers, the rate fell to 6.4 percent in 1999 from 7.2
percent a year earlier, the lowest since the department began
breaking out statistics on Hispanic employment in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The report also left little doubt that the economy would
continue growing for another month, all but assuring that the
current business expansion will become the nation's longest in
February at 8 years and 11 months, breaking a record set in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential campaign heating up, the figures suggested
that the economy will only be a political issue during the primary
season to the degree that Vice President Al Gore can claim credit
for its strength or to the degree that the other candidates in both
parties can convince voters that they have the prescription for
keeping the good times rolling.
</P>
<P>
   But the economy's resilience presents a tricky challenge for the
Fed, whose chairman, Alan Greenspan, was nominated to a fourth
four-year term this week by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has been increasingly blunt in warning over the last
few months that the economy is running out of workers, and that
even the substantial gains in productivity growth generated by huge
investments in technology are not sufficient to eliminate the risk
of spiraling wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed raised its benchmark Federal funds target rate three
times last year in quarter-point increments, to 5.50 percent. The
central bank's policy-setting committee meets again on Feb. 1 and
2, and analysts are almost unanimous in expecting another
quarter-point increase then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers suggest that economic activity continues to be
strong, and undoubtedly stronger than the Fed believes is
consistent with holding down inflation,'' said Paul L. Kasriel, an
economist at Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   So far there is little hard evidence that inflation pressures
are taking root. Although wage growth is running slightly higher
now than it was last summer _ average hourly earnings were up 3.7
percent last month over the same month a year earlier, compared
with 3.4 percent in August _ the average increase in the fourth
quarter was actually lower than in the first half of 1999.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hoffman said Friday's numbers provided some clues that
productivity growth continued to be strong at the end of the year,
allowing employers to absorb higher wage costs without having to
raise prices or sacrifice profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been tentative signs that higher interest rates
are beginning to slow the housing market, a possible precursor of a
more generalized economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   But Kasriel cited two statistics watched closely by Greenspan
that suggest a potential for trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   One is a broad definition of the number of available workers _
people who are officially unemployed, plus those not actively
looking for a job but interested in working. By that measure,
joblessness fell last month to its lowest level during this
business cycle, 4.5 percent, down from 4.6 percent a month earlier
and 4.8 percent a year earlier, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other is the ``quit rate,'' or the number of people who have
left their jobs voluntarily as a percentage of total unemployed
workers. That rate rose to 14.4 percent from 14.3 percent last
month, also a high for this business cycle, indicating that workers
are increasingly confident of their ability to find a new and
better paying job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implication is that you're going to have to pay more to
retain your staff,'' Kasriel said.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists say the Fed is likely to have to raise rates a
number of times this year to slow the economy to a noninflationary
pace. Economists at Salomon Smith Barney forecast Friday that the
Fed would raise rates at least three quarters of a point, and
perhaps a full percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan has proven to be a gradualist when it comes to
adjusting monetary policy, raising and lowering rates a quarter of
a point at a time and reassessing the economy every few weeks or
months. He has not raised rates by half a percentage point since
1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
