<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DREAMLIFE-INVEST-ART-     01-07 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMLIFE-INVEST-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD MOTIVATIONAL SPEAKER'S WEB SITE MOTIVATE INVESTORS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, Dreamlife appears to be just another Internet
company with high hopes and hazy prospects.
</P>
<P>
   But it is majority owned by Anthony Robbins, the motivational
speaker and star of TV infomercials. And it has a roster of
big-name investors, including NBC anchorman Tom Brokaw, tennis
player Andre Agassi and securities lawyer Joseph Flom, who bought
their shares months ago at lower prices than were available to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   This week, those minority investors filed with regulators for
the flexibility to sell their shares _ even before Dreamlife's web
site gets going.
</P>
<P>
   A close look at the company's own filings shows some reason for
caution beyond the usual Internet uncertainties. The company says
it will need to raise more money by September, so Brokaw and his
fellow investors may simply be being prudent. After all, as Robbins
explains on wealthmastery.com, ``Your decisions, not your
conditions, determine your financial destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, who created Dreamlife last spring and whose stake is
now worth $370 million, specializes in helping the successful
become more successful. At his day-long seminars, which regularly
draw audiences of 10,000 or more, he encourages people to take
control of their lives and make more money by overcoming fear and
unleashing the passions that drive them. In addition to the
seminars, he hosts smaller, pricier retreats, including a week-long
``Date with Destiny'' at his private island in Fiji for $12,000. He
has also sold millions of tapes and books.
</P>
<P>
   Though Robbins did not return calls last week, Dreamlife
president Beth Polish said her company would become the online side
of Robbins' burgeoning empire. ``His online presence with content
or communities will be through Dreamlife,'' she said. ``And that
obviously is a tremendous benefit to Dreamlife.''
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is Dreamlife? It is described as a network of
Internet sites focused on personal and professional improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is build a place where people will go
and assess their life,'' Ms. Polish said. ``Then, after they've
assessed their life, define their dreams or their goals, and after
they've defined their dreams or their goals have the opportunity to
pursue their dreams or their goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be able to learn how to write a screenplay, how to find
a new job, how to have better communications skills, because it's
really the whole person that we're interested in,'' Ms. Polish
said. ``We really view ourselves as a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreamlife began its life as a publicly traded company last year
through a complex and unusual deal. In what is known as a reverse
merger, Robbins struck an agreement in April to turn a little-known
developer of high-tech cancer treatments called GHS into his
Internet venture. In exchange for his participation, Robbins and
other investors received 30 million new shares in GHS, which at the
time had just 7 million shares. With 23 million shares himself,
Robbins took control of the company. GHS then spun off its old
assets into a new company called U.S. NeuroSurgical, and changed
its name to Dreamlife in November.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction had the effect of putting Dreamlife shares in
public hands while bypassing the traditional scrutiny of a stock
offering in filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Dreamlife worked with Allen &AMP; Co., a boutique
investment bank known for its media company clients, to sell $15
million of stock to a small group of wealthy investors at a 40
percent discount to the price then being paid by the public. The
shares, which were issued as preferred but converted to common
stock in September, were sold at the equivalent of $9 a common
share, when the public price was $16.625.
</P>
<P>
   The discount reflected the restrictions on trading the shares,
Ms. Polish said. ``They were locked up for over six months,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The private placement was needed to raise capital in lieu of a
traditional public offering of stock. Most private companies go
public by finding a securities firm to sell shares directly to
investors, a practice that raises capital for operations or other
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because a reverse merger does not really raise money from
outside investors, the technique is rarely used by well-known
companies, said Richard Peterson, market strategist for Thomson
Financial Securities Data, which tracks initial public offerings.
``It's something I would not perceive as a boon,'' he said. Perhaps
the best known example in recent years was Muriel Siebert's move to
become a public company by acquiring a furniture company and then
selling those assets.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Jan. 4, the investors in the Dreamlife private
placement filed a statement with the SEC registering their shares
for sale to the public. Along with Brokaw, Agassi and Flom, the
list of nearly three dozen prospective sellers includes Wayne
Huizenga, the billionaire owner of the Miami Dolphins, NBC
president Robert Wright and CBS talk show personality Bryant
Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   The registration statement does not compel the investors to
sell, and at least one said last week that he had no plans to do so
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   And Agassi, at least, is a fan of Robbins, whose well-known
clients include the New Jersey Nets and President Clinton. But
skeptics say Robbins' true genius is self promotion. In 1995,
Robbins agreed to pay more than $220,000 to settle a complaint by
the Federal Trade Commission that he and his company, Robbins
Research International, had overstated the earnings potential of
his franchisees, which sold his tapes and organized seminars.
Robbins did not admit or deny any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Even by the standards of Internet companies, Dreamlife is
unusual. The company has no sales, much less profits. In the three
months ended Sept. 30, Dreamlife lost $3.2 million on revenues of
$155,000, all from interest on its bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the small matter of Dreamlife's Web site. While
Robbins has his own well-developed website, which will eventually
be linked closely with Dreamlife, Dreamlife's site consists of
nothing more than one page for people to submit e-mail and a notice
that ``We'll be launching soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's ever perfect _ it's hard to build a business,
whether you're public or you're private,'' Ms. Polish said. ``We
are a public company, we opted that route, but not everybody who's
a public company from day one is actually launched.'' She said the
Dreamlife web site would be running by mid-February and its first
offerings would include some type of self-improvement classes.
</P>
<P>
   Web users, though, have shown great reluctance to pay for
content, making advertising space and product sales the major
source of revenue for most online companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obstacles, investors are valuing Dreamlife at $650
million. That's more than bigger and better known Internet content
companies such as financial news provider Marketwatch.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made an investment in it because I think it's an interesting
content area, and it piqued my interest,'' said Dr. Samuel Waksal,
chief executive officer of ImClone Systems, who bought 66,660
shares in the May placement. Though he has registered to sell, he
said he has no plans to do so. Allen &AMP; Co., he said, handled the
filing for all the investors.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Gumbel, who owns 15,000 shares, and Brokaw, who
owns 22,220, said they had no comment on Dreamlife. A spokesperson
for Huizenga, who owns 222,220 shares, called the investment
``typical'' for Huizenga. One of the biggest investors in the
private placement, Huizenga now has more than $1.6 million in
profits on paper for his $2 million investment. Flom, a top
fund-raiser for Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley, did
not return calls for comment. He owns 5,550 shares. Calls to other
investors were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   While the investors who bought in the private placement have
seen gains of more than 80 percent in seven months, public
shareholders have not fared as well. Dreamlife's shares closed
Friday at $16.50, down about 1 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   If all the registered sellers follow through, it would put
nearly 50 percent more shares in public circulation, almost
certainly putting downward pressure on the stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
