<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AILING-HMO-BOS &LR;      01-07 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AILING-HMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLUTION TO HARVARD PILGRIM WOES WILL TAKE MORE THAN A MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Warning there may be more financial bombshells buried
deep in Harvard Pilgrim Health Care's books, state officials say it
will take them more than 30 days to put together a plan to save the
ailing health insurer.
</P>
<P>
   When the state took over management of the $2.8 billion-a-year
health plan on Tuesday, it promised the Supreme Judicial Court a
rescue plan within a month. But officials Friday backpedaled on
that promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically what we'll be able to do in 30 days is to report
back to the court as to what our status is,'' said Dean Richland,
who is Atty. General Thomas Reilly's first deputy. ``We're not in a
position to say we'll have a plan in 30 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Time is a critical factor in the efforts to save New England's
largest health maintenance organization, because pressure is
building from the HMO's creditors, who want their money, and from
its customers, especially large employer groups which must decide
in the next few months whether to stay with Harvard Pilgrim or jump
ship.
</P>
<P>
   Richland said the task of coming up with a rehabilitation plan
for the HMO ``is complicated by the fact that we don't know what
the real financial condition of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care is
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Any new financial surprises could well affect the structure and
feasibility of any plan to rehabilitate Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping we know the worst, but I don't think we know the
worst yet,'' Richland said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Only last weekend, according to Harvard Pilgrim officials,
accountants discovered an additional $58.5 million in financial
losses for 1999, on top of $118.5 million in projected losses.
Faced with that revelation, state officials asked the state's high
court to put the health maintenance organization into state
receivership to block creditors from demanding payment _ a scenario
that would have led to the HMO's total collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Officials don't even know how much Harvard Pilgrim owes
hospitals, doctors, suppliers and other creditors. ``We're told by
Harvard Pilgrim they owe something like $300 million, but they
don't know how much of that is real, since billing practices in the
health care industry aren't the greatest,'' Richland said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the $300 million figure dates from last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated wrangling over Harvard Pilgrim indebtedness is
reflected by the Massachusetts Hospital Association's claim this
week that Harvard Pilgrim owes $300 million to hospitals alone. It
is not certain what the hospitals included in their aggregate
total.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the state Division of Insurance, Chris
Goetchius, indicated the daunting task that faces insurance
commissioner Linda Ruthardt, the court-appointed receiver who is
charged with coming up with a rescue plan.
</P>
<P>
   Goetchius said Ruthardt's staff and two outside auditing firms _
Price WaterhouseCoopers for Harvard Pilgrim and KPMG Peat Marwick
retained by the insurance division _ are expected to work through
the weekend to reexamine the health plan's tangled accounting
records, digging as far back as 1997 for more hidden debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got a very big surprise on Jan. 3rd, and obviously,
we'd like to know if there are any more,'' Goetchius said. ``We'd
also like to get a more exact accounting of what they owe and what
kinds of things are outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she was confident that there aren't further unpleasant
surprises lurking in those books, Ruthardt replied: ``To be honest,
I'm not. If I felt confident I wouldn't have gone into
receivership. I'm hoping to know before the first week in February,
when I make my next report to the court.''
</P>
<P>
   While state officials begin their financial archeology, Harvard
Plan executives scrambled to assure their customers that they can
deliver services and survive over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been thousands of phone calls and e-mails,'' said
Harvard Pilgrim spokesman Alan Raymond. ``We're sending letters to
all our providers and employers who use the plan, anybody we feel
would benefit from communication from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried Harvard Pilgrim patients and health care providers have
also been calling state agencies to ask about the Harvard Pilgrim
crisis. The attorney general's office has received about 1,500
telephone calls since Wednesday, and traffic on its website has
been twice the normal volume.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general is inviting Harvard Pilgrim subscribers and
providers to register questions and complaints through a hotline,
1-888-830-MASS.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers may have valid complaints about denial of care.
For instance, one woman said a pediatrician in the HMO's network
said she was no longer accepting Harvard Pilgrim patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would violate the court injunction, which requires that
all provides in the network continue to provide services to all
Harvard Pilgrim members,'' Richland said.
</P>
<P>
   Some doubts began to surface Friday about whether Harvard
Pilgrim could survive without a tax-funded bailout of some sort _
whether an outright grant or perhaps a loan, similar to the federal
government's loan in the Chrysler Corporation case.
</P>
<P>
   Two planned bond issues that would have yielded Harvard Pilgrim
up to $237 million were cancelled on Tuesday when the additional
1999 debts were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   With the bond deal at least temporarily on the rocks, some
industry leaders said Harvard Pilgrim is unlikely to find an
alternative way of raising enough money to get back on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody sees how they can do it on their own,'' said an
executive at another major health plan who asked not to be
identified. ``That looks very grim. The only way I see them
surviving is a state bailout.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office will assess the ability of other
Massachusetts HMOs to absorb Harvard Pilgrim's million-plus
subscribers if the health plan does fail. But Richland said such
speculation is premature.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts Health Plan, the state's second-largest HMO, Friday
challenged a published report that its financial reserves sank to
only 16 days of cash on hand last summer, compared with Harvard
Pilgrim's 34 days.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-day figure didn't take into account $147 million in stock
investments, Tufts officials said. Including that money, the health
plan had 47 days of available cash. Though Tufts is expected to
post losses of $45 million for 1999, its condition has improved
through the year, said chief financial officer Richard Hallworth.
</P>
<P>
   In Rhode Island, where Harvard Pilgrim's subsidiary declared
bankruptcy last fall, Secretary of State Jim Langevin proposed
borrowing $7 million from the state's rainy day fund to help former
Harvard Pilgrim doctors build new practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't only about helping doctors, but providing an
adequate pool of doctors for our patients,'' Langevin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 1959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-VALUE-AMERICA-ART     01-07 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-VALUE-AMERICA-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TURMOIL BEHIND THE BROWSER AT VALUE AMERICA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of stock is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nagging question lingers as one new Internet company after
another bursts into public view, offering glittering Web sites,
charismatic founders, innovative business models, surging sales and
soaring stocks. What, exactly, is going on behind the screen?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, at least in the case of Value America, the once
highflying Internet department store based in Charlottesville, Va.,
is not pretty. It is also most likely not unique to the company,
though a war among board members that broke out in recent months
has focused considerable public attention on the company.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Craig Winn, a co-founder and the chairman, and his
handpicked chief executive, Tom Morgan, have left the company. And
the new chief, Glenda Dorchak, has put forward a turnaround plan
that repudiates much of what Winn did.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the discord, each faction is in remarkable agreement about
many elements of the Value America saga:
</P>
<P>
   They agree the company has been mismanaged. They accept that
entrepreneurial founders of companies are often not the best
executives to run them as they grow. And they say that things have
gone so far off track for Value America that it would probably be
better off if it were bought, at least in part, by a larger
company.
</P>
<P>
   As to what the management errors were and who made them,
however, there is no shortage of debate.
</P>
<P>
   Such recriminations, about tactics, people and plans, are likely
to reverberate around many companies in the next year as the wings
melt off many an Internet Icarus. Some companies are realizing that
the rising tide of e-commerce did not in fact raise their ships.
And some investors are beginning to see the downside of backing
companies that put growth over discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Value America's board ultimately came to accept the view of Ms.
Dorchak, who had been president, that the company had expanded too
fast, selling a sprawling jumble of goods from barbecue grills to
breakfast cereal, when most of its business was in computers and
office products.
</P>
<P>
   William D. Savoy, a board member, said Value America stumbled,
as much as anything, because it lost the confidence of Wall Street.
``They got themselves in a box by creating different expectations
than what the company's core competencies were,'' said Savoy, who
represents the interests of the Microsoft co-founder Paul G. Allen,
a Value America backer.
</P>
<P>
   Winn defends the broad selection and grand pronouncements to
investors. And he contends that Morgan and Ms. Dorchak mishandled
the company's marketing and botched a computer upgrade. ``There
will be no slow-growing e-tailing companies,'' Winn said. ``I
believe that entrepreneurs should eventually phase themselves out,
and I handed an aggressive and well-managed company over to Tom in
March. In retrospect, the company needed the entrepreneurial spirit
and leadership for another year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dorchak declined to be interviewed. Morgan said Winn did not
criticize his leadership while he was chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Outside analysts and competitors raise a more fundamental
question about the business model developed by Winn, who
established Value America as the most virtual of companies. It
holds no inventory, simply passing the telephone and Internet
orders it receives to manufacturers, which send goods directly to
the buyers.
</P>
<P>
   But in many cases, manufacturers have been so lackadaisical
about shipping that customers have suffered unusual delays.
</P>
<P>
   The current scene at Value America could not be more different
than on April 8, 1999, the day after its initial public offering.
The stock hit $55 a share, giving the company a market valuation of
$3.2 billion and making Winn, who owns 35 percent of the company, a
paper billionaire for 24 hours. The shares have been on a steady
slide since, closing on Friday at $5, for a market value of $224
million.
</P>
<P>
   With the luxury of hindsight, investors might have seen some
warning signs. The company's initial prospectus disclosed that its
auditors found significant gaps in its inventory tracking system,
although the issue was cleared up before the offering. And Dynasty
Classics, the lighting company that Winn founded and ran from 1986
to 1993, wound up in Chapter 11.
</P>
<P>
   None of this kept investors from flocking to the offering. And
who could blame them, in a market where everybody is making it up
as they go along?
</P>
<P>
   Winn's energetic persuasion attracted a star-studded list of
investors, including Allen; the FDX Corp., parent of Federal
Express; and Frederick W. Smith, its chairman. He also persuaded
some of the world's biggest manufacturers, including IBM and
General Electric, to sell their products through Value America.
</P>
<P>
   After the offering, revenues grew even faster than projected.
But so did expenses, and Value America's underwriters, Robertson
Stephens, downgraded the company several times, out of fear that it
was not getting the leverage from its huge expenditures on
newspaper and television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Winn reacted to the falling stock price alternately by telling
investors that they were applying flawed analysis and by making
ever bolder promises about the company's future plans. That was a
particular frustration to the company's management and board
because Morgan, who became chief executive in March, was supposed
to be the one dealing with Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   By November, Morgan, angry that Winn was meddling in management
affairs, handed in his resignation. Winn convinced him to stay, but
they continued to spar. Two weeks later, Morgan resigned again;
this time, Winn accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves started a monthlong battle for the soul of the
company. The board appointed Ms. Dorchak as chief and Wolfgang R.
Schmitt, former chief of Rubbermaid, as chairman. They contended
that the company should pare its product line and focus on serving
business and government customers rather than consumers. Winn, then
still a board member, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the board decided to back Ms. Dorchak's plan to
switch gears and dismiss nearly half the company's 600 employees.
Winn and his co-founder, Rex Scatena, who owns 15 percent of the
company, left the board.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been running through its cash, now $100 million,
at a rate of $10 million a month. Smith of FDX has been put at the
helm of a committee charged with considering a sale of all or part
of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Board members say Value America's technology would be of great
value to a traditional retail company looking to catch up with the
Internet leaders. But with Value America's founders gone and its
strategies repudiated, buyers will have to think long and hard
about what is left behind the screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
