<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9781 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-AR     01-07 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY ENGINES LIFT FIVE PORFOLIOS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most mutual fund investors closed 1999 with fireworks,
rebounding smartly from third-quarter losses in a stock market led
by technology and smaller issues.
</P>
<P>
   The market revival brought plenty of cheer to investors with
diversified portfolios, including the five professional money
managers who have built hypothetical retirement portfolios for The
New York Times. All five earned double-digit returns in the fourth
quarter, and four of the five beat the average return of 19.6
percent for diversified domestic equity funds as tracked by Lipper
Inc. All five outperformed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index,
which posted a 14.5 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the managers expects those heady returns to
continue. ``I believe we are in a bubble that has the potential to
end badly,'' said Sheldon Jacobs, who edits The No-Load Fund
Investor in Irvington, N.Y. ``The market is overvalued by a number
of measures, and the advance this year has been narrow, focusing on
technology stocks. I would look to see whether the market broadens
out in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs was the leader for the quarter, with a portfolio gain of
27.68 percent. He rode the strength of the technology sector with
stakes in Janus Olympus, Marsico Focus and T. Rowe Price Science
and Technology.
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter of 2000, he is consolidating most of his
15 percent holding in the Vanguard 500 Index fund, which mimics the
S&AMP;P 500, into an existing 35 percent position in the Vanguard Total
Stock Market fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Total Stock Market is 80 percent invested in the S&AMP;P
500,'' Jacobs said, ``the remaining 20 percent is in mid- and
small-cap stocks, which I think will do relatively better in
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   He is increasing his international exposure by taking 5 percent
of the portfolio's assets out of his index-fund position and
redirecting them to Asia and Europe in equal measure. Strong Asia
Pacific and Scudder Greater Europe will each get one-tenth of the
portfolio; the Scudder fund replaces T. Rowe Price European Stock,
which has performed less strongly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs retains the lead among the five managers with a gain of
212.31 percent since the contest began in July 1993. In that time,
the five portfolios have grown by an average of 174.71 percent,
compared with a 277.92 percent return for the Vanguard 500 Index
fund.
</P>
<P>
   The hypothetical portfolios' performances are tracked each
quarter by Lipper, the research firm in Summit, N.J. They exclude
sales charges and transaction costs, and because most retirement
money is held in tax-deferred accounts, the effects of taxes are
excluded. The five managers can choose from among all funds open to
new investors and can shift money quarterly. The portfolios are
meant to grow until July 2013, some 20 years after the competition
began.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also gave a big boost to Eric M. Kobren,
president of Kobren Insight Group and editor of Fidelity Insight in
Wellesley, Mass. His all-Fidelity portfolio rose 25.49 percent in
the quarter, the second best of the five.
</P>
<P>
   Going forward, Kobren is dropping Fidelity International Value
and Fidelity Capital Appreciation, beefing up Fidelity Aggressive
Growth and adding Fidelity Europe Capital Appreciation. ``I think
Europe could surprise everyone in how rapidly it will incorporate
technology into the workplace and garner productivity improvements,
focus on improving shareholder value, accelerate cross-border
acquisitions and show improved economic growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While he is sanguine about the American economy, he is worried
about investors' seeming greed. ``The percent of household assets
in equities is at historically high levels,'' he said. ``My advice
to investors is to control their expectations and not become
complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack A. Brill, who has joined Natural Investment Services in San
Diego as vice president, created a ``socially responsible'' fund
portfolio that took third place for the quarter with a gain of
20.73 percent, buoyed by technology issues in IPS Millennium and
Citizens Emerging Growth.
</P>
<P>
   Following his view that broad portfolio diversification will be
more important than ever in the coming year, Brill is moving 6
percent of his portfolio's assets into Calvert New Visions, a
small-cap fund that blends growth and value stocks, while trimming
positions in Ariel Appreciation and MMA Praxis International.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the coming year will be very volatile,'' Brill said.
``I am optimistic that the market will rise, but less than in 1999.
Technology stocks will continue to dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Evensky, an investment adviser in Coral Gables, Fla.,
plans no changes in his broadly diversified portfolio in the first
quarter, despite placing fourth in the most recent period with a
19.98 percent gain. His market outlook is cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the large-cap domestic market going straight up,
nor do I see it achieving `riskless' returns remotely comparable to
those of the '90s,'' he said, adding that investors might
reasonably expect returns in the range of 9 percent to 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Dziubinski, until recently editor of Morningstar Fund
Investor, was in fifth place for the quarter with a gain of 17.68
percent. Ms. Dziubinski is handing over the reins to Russel Kinnel,
director of the Morningstar.com Web site, who is replacing all the
holdings for the new quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Large chunks will go into the Vanguard 500 Index as a low-cost
diversified anchor, and into MAS Mid-Cap Growth Institutional for
inexpensive but superior performance, he said. T. Rowe Price Small
Cap has the potential for above-average returns with lower risk,
Kinnell said.
</P>
<P>
   For overseas exposure, Kinnel will place 18 percent of the
portfolio's assets in Fidelity Diversified International, a
quantitatively run fund, and 8 percent in Harbor International
Growth, whose 30 stocks are selected with a growth slant, he said.
A concentrated fund, Oakmark Select, and MSDW Institutional U.S.
Real Estate round out the new portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether technology stocks continue to deliver good growth has
a lot to do with where the market goes,'' he said, adding that 2000
can't possibly be as good 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
