r e BC-DIGITAL-LA-COLUMN-LAD     01-07 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE LITTLE DVD EXTRAS HELP PRESERVE THE PAST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: replace (AT) with that squiggly computer `at' symbol for the
e-mail address at the bottom). 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of my favorite things about the DVD explosion is that so
many of the discs, and certainly the ones I highlight in this
column, come loaded with extras designed to appeal to movie fans.
Those extras are almost never included on video releases, and often
are otherwise just plain unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   But they're great fun for movie buffs, and in many cases,
important tools in helping fans understand a film's historical
import and what prodigious effort was needed to create it.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly so with the documentaries that are commonly
included on DVDs of most major releases. The productions have even
created a dream job for one West Hollywood-based Frenchman, Laurent
Bouzereau, who has now done 24 of them, first for laser disc
releases and now for the burgeoning DVD market, for some of the
biggest films by some of the biggest directors ever, from Alfred
Hitchcock to Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up outside of Paris, Bouzereau said, he was a little
different from many of the kids he knew. Not only was he a big
movie fan, as many French are, he particularly loved big,
mainstream American movies, which many of his countrymen disdain as
too commercial.
</P>
<P>
   He particularly loved the work of directors such as Brian
DePalma, George Lucas and Martin Scorsese, so much so that at 19,
he came to Hollywood with few skills and no money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did all kinds of jobs in the film business: I was a
publicist, a journalist, did feature development for Bette
Midler,'' Bouzereau said. ``I had all kinds of experiences.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote six books, including one, when he was 25, about
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, (laser disc maker) Criterion contacted me to do a
commentary on (DePalma's) `Carrie' for laser disc,'' Bouzereau
said. ``That's when I discovered that whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   He subsequently was asked to direct the documentary for
Spielberg's modest comedy, ``1941.'' That led to a series of other
laser disc projects, with his last in that now-fading medium in
late 1998, for the release of Spielberg's ``Close Encounters of the
Third Kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's mostly been doing projects for DVD release,
including three about-to-be-released Hitchcock films: ``Rear
Window,'' ``The Birds'' and ``Marnie.''
</P>
<P>
   Other recent projects include both the original and remake of
``Cape Fear,'' along with ``The Last Picture Show,'' and the ``Back
to the Future'' trilogy. And in a new venture, Bouzereau shot a
``making of'' documentary during the production of ``Snow Falling
on Cedars'' that will be used to help promote the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing that's going to be sad is that a lot of
classics are going to be forgotten or left behind,'' Bouzereau
said. ``The only way for them to survive or not be forgotten is to
reinvent them for another medium and that's DVD. Documenting the
history of those movies is my own small contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating documentaries about older films can be especially
difficult, because studios once routinely tossed or lost most
archival materials, outtakes and other odds and ends that could be
used to flesh out a documentary. Thankfully, Bouzereau said,
studios now realize the value of that material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios are very careful about saving stuff now,''
Bouzereau said. ``Before, stuff was trashed or not catalogued
properly, or lost and never heard from again.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he does find archival material, there are other
challenges with older films.
</P>
<P>
   ``With `Rear Window,' everybody that's a recognizable name is
gone,'' Bouzereau said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more frustrating, of course, is that star Jimmy Stewart was
still alive just a few years ago and could have talked about the
film's making, had someone thought to do it then.
</P>
<P>
   Bereft of big names, Bouzereau tracked down one of the actresses
Stewart's character spies on in the film, to provide viwers a sense
of what it was like during shooting. And to give viewers a critical
understanding of the film, he also interviewed a prominent
Hitchcock scholar and Oscar-winning writer-director Curtis Hanson,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   Bouzereau, who started his work with little training as a
director, said he tries to create a different tone when he is
interviewing his subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's a difficult process for them to talk about an
old movie they made,'' Bouzereau said. ``I try to make it
technically very simple and use a very small crew, so the talent is
not intimidated. There's a real sense of something kind of warm.
We're just chatting about the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The digital explosion has created a whole new field for film
freaks like Bouzereau, both as creators and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weird business,'' Bouzereau said, marveling at his own
good fortune. ``I never thought I'd be able to put to good use that
kind of passion that I had for movies. If you have kids and aren't
sure why they're passionate about something, it's important to
encourage that, because you don't know what it will lead to. It
didn't pay off for me for years. Now my parents say, `Hey, you've
found the perfect job for you.''' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POKE-MOMENTUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think (wish?) Pokemon fever is abating here or in Japan? Nah.
Nintendo says it sold 1 million units of Pokemon Yellow when that
Game Boy title hit U.S. shores ... in a two-week span. That would
make it the fastest-selling videogame here ever, Nintendo claimed.
</P>
<P>
   And in Japan, the company finally released Pokemon Gold and
Silver, the game's latest iteration, and sold 1.8 million units in
just one !ital!day!off!. Another 600,000 units had been sold by
Dec. 1, the company said. For 8-year-olds, it's a Pokemad, mad,
mad, mad world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------ &QL;
</P>
