<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEREG-SOCOMPANY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Co. plans ad effort
 &HT;    to bolster image
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Southern Co. launches an $8 million yearlong national
advertising campaign next week to promote the company as a
dependable source of energy as the nation's $250 billion utility
industry is changing.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the industry is ``full of uncertainty'' with the
transition to deregulation, the newspaper and magazine ads tout
Southern as a ``constant, dependable source of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the strength to fulfill our commitments when other
companies scramble for resources. In fact, we've honored all of our
energy contracts,'' says one of the new ads.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spencer, Southern's director of external affairs, said
the new ads are aimed at three audiences: Wall Street, Washington
policy-makers and potential customers for Southern's growing
national wholesale energy business. ``We want people to buy our
stock and know we're a good value, come to us for advice in the
policy arena and to sell to large customers,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign begins Tuesday with a full-page ad in The Wall
Street Journal that says Southern generates more electricity than
any of its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   It's Southern's third major national marketing effort in three
years. Southern became the first utility to launch a national ad
campaign in 1997 with a $14 million campaign aimed at building
brand awareness with a broader range of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Southern has also incorporated its Southeastern utilities, such
as Georgia Power Co., into its ``branding'' effort to shore up its
image at home. The parent company's logo has been hoisted to the
top of Georgia Power's downtown Atlanta headquarters. The company
spent $22 million for advertising in 1998 and 1999. The new
campaign is less expensive because it is aimed at targeted
audiences and includes no TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   As national momentum toward deregulation has slowed, Southern
has adopted a strategy that targets five high-growth regions around
the country for wholesale electricity and natural gas sales.
Spencer said the new campaign reflects that shift.
</P>
<P>
   Southern now hopes to influence potential investors in Southern
and inside-the-Beltway elected officials and regulators who will
have a say in deregulation and other legislation that could affect
the company. Southern also wants to reach executives at a growing
number of utilities and large companies that already have the
ability to shop for electricity among competing suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign will be focused on print publications that
circulate in those audiences. These include Bloomberg Magazine,
Barron's, Institutional Investor, The Washington Post, The New York
Times and the Capitol Hill publications Roll Call, Congressional
Quarterly and The Hill. Energy trade publications that reach energy
decision-makers and Internet ads are also anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
