u f BC-HUFFY08-COX     01-07 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUFFY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Credit boost helps Huffy
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMISBURG, Ohio _ The investment banker looking at the possible
sale, merger or other strategic alternative for Huffy Corp. has
presented the company with some proposals but no decisions have
been made, according to Don R. Graber, Huffy chairman, president
and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing they've brought back that we agree, `This is a
wonderful idea,''' Graber said.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came Friday, the day after Huffy Corp. announced
that seven lenders had agreed to extend a $175 million line of
credit to the company. The pact requires that Huffy meet financial
and performance goals set mutually by the company and lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Graber said those lenders have been in contact with PaineWebber
Inc., the investment banker Huffy hired in November after
defaulting on loans, bouncing checks and failing to honor dividend
checks.
</P>
<P>
   He said lenders are not mandating that Huffy accept
PaineWebber's proposals for strategic alternatives, which could
include a sale, merger, joint venture or partnership for some or
all of the company as it struggles to put the bicycle division on
sound footing. Graber has emphasized that a viable alternative for
Huffy Corp. includes remaining independent.
</P>
<P>
   There are changes afoot internally, however, with a new top
financial officer charged with improving lender relationships and
devising a better financial structure.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Lafferty replaces former chief financial officer Tom
Frederick, who becomes vice president of corporate strategy.
Lafferty, who also will hold the titles treasurer and vice
president of finance, comes from Gencor Industries Inc., a Florida
manufacturer of food processing equipment. He served as senior vice
president and chief financial officer at Gencor. Prior to that he
had financial positions with Hoechst Marion Roussel and Dow
Chemical.
</P>
<P>
   Where Frederick's financial expertise is primarily on the
operational side, Lafferty brings extensive experience in working
with banks and structuring arrangements like Huffy's new line of
credit, Graber said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to pay a lot more attention to our lender
communications and relations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company has more to do in the cash management area
and needs to better organize and strengthen its financial
structure. While the lenders reporting demands are ``disciplined,''
they are not ``onerous'' and the targets are in line with Huffy's
own projections, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lafferty said he took the job because it looked interesting and
he sees strength in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked at the basic business, I thought this was
something that could be turned around, righted,'' Lafferty said.
</P>
<P>
   Graber said the company's sporting goods, assembly and inventory
services divisions are strong, so the challenge for 2000 is to put
the bicycle division on the same footing. The restructuring of the
division is complete _ the remaining two American plants closed in
early December and a supplier network is in place in Asia and
Mexico. The company will save $20 million annually in operational
costs by pulling out of the bicycle manufacturing business, a
decision Graber called painful but necessary.
</P>
<P>
   This year Huffy will introduce a line of bicycles, capitalizing
on the extreme sports market, and is diving head-first into
Internet sales of high-end Airborne bicycles, Graber said.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring has strengthened Huffy's hand and the new line
of credit brings flexibility to make operational and strategic
improvements, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst David Leibowitz said analysts had expected Huffy to
negotiate a new line of credit, but investors are likely waiting to
see what else happens before interest in Huffy stock drives the
price back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities are there,'' said Leibowitz, managing
director for Burnham Securities in New York. ``It's a question of
how quickly we can see some top line growth, which would permit the
company to benefit from the efficiencies that have been put into
place.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Huffy stock (NYSE:HUF) closed at 6 3/16, up 1/16, but
still far from its 52-week high of 16 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Graber said he believes investors are waiting until the line of
credit paperwork is finalized in a couple of weeks, which also is
when the company will honor dividend checks it could not pay during
the November cash crunch.
</P>
<P>
   The need to improve shareholder value has been a constant
concern during Graber's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we don't deserve long-term to be at six dollars and
change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
