<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-VENTURA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURA AND TRUMP STIR THE POLITICAL POT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN PARK, Minn. _ It was politics as theater, and the
matinee attractions Friday were ex-wrestler Jesse Ventura and
mogul-playboy Donald Trump.
</P>
<P>
   That Ventura is now governor of Minnesota and Trump is pondering
a bid for the Reform Party's presidential nomination bears witness
to the varied tapestry that public life in America can sometimes
weave.
</P>
<P>
   That Ventura and Trump may join forces alerts the body politic
to keep the smelling salts handy.
</P>
<P>
   That on the other side of the Reform Party chasm, spoiling for a
fight, are Ross Perot, Pat Buchanan and similarly colorful
characters from the political fringe has put spring in the wintry
step of late-night television monologue writers and talk-show hosts
of all stripe.
</P>
<P>
   That all this is being taken seriously _ and watched nervously,
especially by Republicans _ points to what could be another
fractious election season in which the two major parties must again
defend their domination of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, the billionaire developer, flew to the Twin Cities area
aboard his customized Boeing 747 to confer with Ventura, the senior
Reform Party officer holder in the nation, and stir the party's
presidential pot.
</P>
<P>
   It was a love feast, but stopped short of Ventura endorsing
Trump's possible campaign. The governor explained that if he
stepped out now and Trump didn't run, he would appear foolish, and
``I don't like looking stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump did not commit to running but dismissed talk that he was
on the political circuit just to boost sales of his fourth book, a
volume on public policy titled, ``The America We Deserve.'' Trump
conceded it was probably easier to peddle his earlier three titles,
all best-sellers, on how to make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am looking very, very seriously as to whether or not it can
be won,'' Trump said of a presidential race. ``If I can win, I
think I can do a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump had been less equivocal in an interview with The
Associated Press earlier Friday when he said only one thing would
keep him out of the race: ``Death.''
</P>
<P>
   But Trump told a larger group of reporters that perceptions of
his status are a problem for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people think that I'm running, we'll do great,'' he said.
``A lot of people say, `Aw, he's maybe not going to run, he's just
having lots of fun.' That's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosaic point of Trump's trip was to speak to a luncheon
meeting of some suburban chambers of commerce in this Minneapolis
suburb, where Ventura got his political start by winning the
nonpartisan mayor's job in 1990, and to star at a fund-raising
reception for Ventura's political committee. In between, they held
a joint news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Money is the main issue in the fight for the Reform nomination,
attractive since Perot drew almost 20 percent of the national
popular vote on the third-party line in 1992, said Phil Madsen,
founding chairman of the Minnesota Reform Party. Money's needed for
petition drives to get on state ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trump has it, Buchanan doesn't,'' Madsen said. Buchanan gave
up his campaign for the Republican nomination last year and was
welcomed to the Reform race by the faction of the party loyal to
Perot, its founder and major funder.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform nominee will be decided by a vote of party members _
by mail, e-mail, phone _ that will precede a national convention
scheduled for early August. The Perot faction has announced the
meeting will be in Long Beach, Calif., but Ventura's backers want
it moved to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Once selected, the Reform Party nominee will be entitled to
$12.5 million in general-election campaign funds from the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Trump and Ventura joined to lambaste the decision of the
commission on presidential debates to prohibit any presidential
candidate without 15 percent popular support in a group of polls to
participate in the fall debates, a decisive element in the national
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a clear case of them fearing there could be
another Jesse Ventura and that they're going to stop it any way
they possibly can,'' the governor said. Ventura recalled that he
was polling only 10 percent as the 1998 general-election campaign
began in Minnesota. ``It shows great fear on their part'' that a
lesser-ranked candidate can be included in debates ``and can turn
around in a mere six weeks and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura and Trump said the commission is dominated by lobbyists
aligned with Democrats or Republicans, ``and they don't make money
off us.''
</P>
<P>
   Others aspersions were cast freely.
</P>
<P>
   Trump made clear he had little use for the current crowd of
presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are these people stiffs or what?'' Trump asked the luncheon
audience, referring to the candidate debates he'd seen on
television this week. Ninety percent of the folks in the Northland
Hotel ballroom were ``more capable,'' he assured listeners.
</P>
<P>
   As for Buchanan, Trump said: ``I don't think about him very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Clinton administration foreign policy, Trump said it
was being run by ``a bunch of weak sisters'' who on international
trade issues acted as ``a whipping post.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have too much tact and diplomacy'' in dealing with supposed
friends and enemies alike overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trump said that because of his international business dealings
he knows some foreign leaders ``better than the so-called
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly set straight a questioner who wondered whether it
was really the time for a rich guy to run the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't come from great wealth. I built a lot of great
wealth,'' Trump said, contrasting himself to other current
candidates whom he said were from the ``lucky sperm club'' and born
into great financial or political families.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few of them around,'' Trump said later. He refused
to point the finger at contenders such as Republicans Steve Forbes,
the multimillionaire publisher; or Gov. George Bush of Texas, the
multimillionaire son of a former president and grandson of a
senator; or Democrat Al Gore, the vice president, whose father was
also in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Trump also said he preferred a wealthy candidate over ``losers''
who brag about being from a poor family for generations untold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who the hell wants to have a person like this for president?''
Trump demanded.
</P>
<P>
   But Trump also recalled he'd bounced back from being $9.2
billion down in the early 1990s. ``The world was coming to an
end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
