<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-7     01-07 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-700&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA CALLS TEMPORARY HALT TO ASSAULT ON GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ Confronted with fierce rebel resistance, rising
casualties and bad weather, the Russian military announced Friday
that it was suspending its assault on the Chechen capital, Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Gennady Troshev, the deputy commander of the Russian
troops fighting in the separatist region of Chechnya, said the
pause was intended to allow the thousands of civilians still
trapped in Grozny to escape. He did not say how long it would last.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military appeared to be putting the best face on an
increasingly difficult situation. The command also announced a
shakeup of its top leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Though the orders were issued locally, they were likely
coordinated with Vladimir Putin, Russia's acting president. Popular
support in Russia for the campaign in Chechnya has been a central
factor in Putin's rapid rise from an obscure prime minister to
acting president and front-runner in Russia's presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   There was no sign that this support is waning, but there has
been widespread speculation that rising casualties or continued
setbacks could start to erode it.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension marks an abrupt change for Russia's generals, who
had vowed to make short work of the militants. Just last week, Col.
Gen. Valery Manilov, deputy chief of the general staff, predicted
that Grozny would be seized in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   But with Chechnya covered by a dense fog, the Russians have not
been able to use artillery and air power, which are vital to their
operation, to seize Grozny. Russian commanders have also been
surprised by the stubborn rebel resistance and may have been
compelled to rethink their tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will also use this as a short break for our personnel,''
Troshev said. ``We will regroup, and when we feel that the
civilians have left Grozny we will inflict a resolute and final
blow against the militants who sit in Grozny.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement, the army said that Maj. Gen.
Vladimir Shamanov, a swaggering and contentious commander, was
removed from his post as the leader of the Western Group of Russian
forces, which is fighting in the southern foothills of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Shamanov declared last year that there would be mass
resignations and possibly even civil war if the Kremlin sought to
halt the military campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Though such hawkish views on Chechnya are shared by many
civilians, his open challenge to Russia's political leaders was
unusual for a nation in which the military has generally stayed out
of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates have also charged that Shamanov's troops
looted homes in the Chechen town of Alkhan-Yurt and executed
civilians who tried to stop them. Russian prosecutors are
investigating the episode, which has become an international
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There had been reports that Shamanov might be forced to retire.
Instead, he was among the Russian commanders in Chechnya who were
decorated with the country's highest military award, Hero of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Now,r, he appears to have been sidelined and will return
to his duties as commander of the 58th Army, which is deployed in
Vladikavkaz, west of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``His political activity went beyond the role outlined in the
constitution for the army, and Alkhan-Yurt was the last straw,''
said Yevgeny Krutikov, a correspondent for the Russian newspaper
Izvestiya.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Shamanov was replaced as commander of the Western Group by his
deputy, Major Gen. Aleksei Verbitsky.
</P>
<P>
   Troshev, who announced the suspension, also said he would
himself be replaced as commander of the Eastern Group of Russian
Forces in Chechnya, which is fighting in the Chechen highlands. He
said that his former deputy, Maj. Gen. Sergei Makarov, would take
the position and concentrate on duties as deputy commander of the
forces in the North Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops began the war three months ago by sweeping
through the northern plains and then steadily advancing in the
lowlands. The street fighting in the Chechen capital, however, has
proved more difficult.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Russian forces began their assault on Grozny on Dec. 26,
they planned to surround the rebels in the city and pound them with
artillery to weaken their resistance. Russian Interior Ministry
troops and commandos were then to move through Grozny
house-by-house to ensure that the city was free of rebels. But the
plan quickly ran into problems. The artillery destroyed many of
Grozny's buildings but not the cellars in which the rebels hid.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has generally shied away from carrying out
more powerful air strikes, fearing they would kill many of the tens
of thousands of civilians believed trapped in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Russian soldiers have also been vulnerable to ambushes and
snipers, and their casualty rate is climbing. A thick fog has also
rolled in and prevented the Russians from launching bombing
missions or making effective use of their artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of occupying the city's center, Russian forces have been
battling groups of rebels on its outskirts as the rebels try to
break out of the Russian encirclement.
</P>
<P>
   The dour mood was summed up by a report issued here Friday by
the Russian command, which bluntly stated that the situation in
Chechnya ``continues to remain complicated and tense.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the suspension of the bombardment of Grozny,
Troshev insisted that the evacuation of the city's civilians was
urgent, charging that the militants had blown up several tanks of
chlorine to poison the air and thwart the Russian attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an enemy is encircled they will resort to anything,'' he
said. ``All they want to do is inflict greater casualties on us
without thinking about the future of Grozny and Chechnya. Grozny
has officially been declared today a zone of ecological danger.''
</P>
<P>
   New tactics for taking Grozny seemed to be emerging. Troshev
implied that the civilians needed to leave to provide the Russian
forces with an even freer hand in launching punishing artillery and
air strikes against the city.
</P>
<P>
   The general said that leaflets were being dropped to encourage
the frightened population of Grozny to evacuate the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has scored some successes. Commanders say,
for example, that they have surrounded the town of Vedeno, the
hometown of Shamil Basayev, one of the main rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Troshev said most of the rebel fighters are in the mountains,
with Basayev; Kattab, a rebel fighter who was born in the Middle
East; and Aslan Maskhadov, the Chechen president. Only 500 to 1,000
militants are still in Grozny, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With winter and one of the densest fogs in years settling in,
however, the Russian military is afraid of becoming mired in
fighting in Grozny and the highlands. It also faces possible
guerrilla attacks behind its lines.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the difficulty of the military's mission, Troshev
began his news conference Friday by saying he would not discuss
Russian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me about losses,'' he cautioned. ``Every loss is a
tragedy. Let the analysts talk about this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
