<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9798 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-FORBES-BOS &LR;      01-07 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FORBES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES DROPS CAMPAIGN CIVILITY IN AD ATTACKING BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN AND JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican Steve Forbes Friday unveiled the first attack ad
aimed by one candidate at another in the current presidential
campaign, in a spot that features an anti-tax activist accusing
Texas Gov. George W. Bush of breaking promises to his home-state
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   The ad raised immediate concerns in the Bush campaign,
especially, that Forbes, lagging in the polls, may be poised to
repeat his strategy of 1996, when his harsh TV campaign undermined
the candidacy of the eventual nominee, Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The star of the new spot is Mary C. Williams, who described
herself in an interview as the ``housewife-in-charge'' of the
Houston-based Taxpayers for Accountability. Williams says in the ad
that Bush, in 1994, signed a pledge not to support sales or
business tax increases and ``in 1997, unfortunately, he broke this
pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush wants people to examine his record to see how he
will perform as president,'' Williams says, ``and his record as far
as taxes are concerned is a record of broken promises.''
</P>
<P>
   In Portsmouth, N.H. Friday, Bush told reporters that Forbes' ad
_ aired less than a day after Bush promised that as president he
would cut taxes ``so help me God'' _ is a disservice to the
political process, launched by a failing candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``His political clock is ticking down, winding down,'' Bush
said. ``And he's now reacting in the year 2000 the way he did in
1996. He must be feeling that sense of gloom that affects
candidates who cannot sell his message in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are and the truth is, every plan I proposed was a
tax cut,'' said Bush. ``As a result of my leadership I signed the
two largest tax cuts in my state's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush reluctantly acknowledged that he did sign the Taxpayers for
Accountability pledge promising not to support sales or business
tax increases. ``Yeah I guess so,'' he said, when asked if he had
signed the oath in 1994. ``It was an auto-pen signature, but it was
a signature.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes ad comes amid other indications that what has been a
comparatively civil campaign in both parties, thus far, may be
taking a turn to the negative as New Hampshire's
first-in-the-nation Feb. 1 primary nears:
</P>
<P>
   _ Former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley Friday launched a new,
30-second ad in New Hampshire implicitly criticizing Vice President
Al Gore for ``doing nothing'' on gun control, child poverty and
health care. In fact, both Gore and Bradley have offered ideas on
gun violence, child poverty and health insurance, but the two
Democrats disagree on how best to combat those problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Sierra Club environmental organization Wednesday began
airing an attack on Bush's environmental record, charging that
Texas leads the nation in releasing hazardous chemicals to the air
and water and that Bush nevertheless advocated weakening the Clean
Air Act. It's true that Federal regulators have been pressing Texas
to improve toughen environmental regulations, and that Houston this
year displaced Los Angeles as the urban area with the worst air
pollution problems in the nation. But Bush aides claim there have
been major improvements in air and water quality in Texas during
Bush's administration.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andy Martin, a fringe Republican candidate, said Friday he
expects to have ready for showing next week an ad attacking Arizona
Senator John McCain for alleged improprieties in dealing with the
Federal Communications Commission. Martin already is airing a
commercial on New Hampshire television accusing Bush of cocaine and
alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes press secretary Juleanna Glover Weiss denied that the
commercial is an attack ad, but strategists for other candidates
said it was a classic of the genre because of its apparently
selective presentation of the facts. In the storm stirred by its
release, Forbes' aides and Williams neither accepted nor disputed
Bush's claim to have cut taxes; they said the issue in the ad was
not the total tax burden, it was that Bush broke his word.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the Forbes camp initially contacted her before
Christmas to do the ad' she said she initially did not want to
``but after thinking it over, I thought this story needed to be
told....
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the Bush people want the story to be tax cuts _ we call
'em the phantom cuts,'' Williams said. ``The story is that he broke
his pledge, his own pledge, then he began to spin it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark MacKinnon, Bush's chief media strategist, said he and other
campaign officials are discussing whether to respond to Forbes on
television. He said the campaign, anticipating just such an attack,
already has prepared several possible responses.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after Gore aides lashed out at Bradley for his new
ad, the vice president's camp announced a new commercial of its own
which takes an implicit shot at Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The announcer says that for 70 million Americans, Medicare and
Medicaid are a lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore: the only Democratic candidate who saves Medicare by
setting aside 15 percent of the surplus to keep Medicare solvent,''
he says. ``The only Demcratic candidate who preserves Medicaid
instead of replacing it with a $150 a month voucher. Al Gore: The
only Democratic candidate who reforms health care in a way that
protects seniors and working families.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad, which Gore aides said would be shown beginning this
weekend, suggests that Bradley would do the opposite of Gore and
hurt Medicare. The two have been battling over Medicare, Medicaid
and their respective health plans for months. Bradley has strongly
criticized Gore for suggesting he would not protect Medicare or
safeguard services for those on Medicaid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TEDJANE08-COX     01-07 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEDJANE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fonda seeking a more spiritual path in life
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the many questions swirling around her separation
this week from media mogul Ted Turner, it's increasingly clear that
spirituality is playing an increasing part in Jane Fonda's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that as she approached her 60th birthday, she began to
search for more meaning,'' said the Rev. Gerald Durley, pastor of
Providence Missionary Baptist Church and the former president of
Concerned Black Clergy. ``I am extremely impressed with the
genuineness and sincerity in her search for spirituality and
wholeness.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't known whether that's responsible for the 62-year-old
actress' separation from Turner mere days after they marked their
eighth wedding anniversary. But citing unnamed sources, the
conservative online magazine WorldNetDaily.com reported this week
that the split was partially prompted by Fonda's ``embrace of
`born-again' evangelical Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   It said Fonda, whose husband once derided Christianity as
``religion for losers,'' now attended Bible study, but didn't
specify where.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda was unavailable for comment, representatives of Turner
Broadcasting said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Durley, who speaks to Fonda ``fairly regularly,'' would not
comment on Turner or the couple's marriage. As a board member of
Fonda's Georgia Campaign for Adolescent Pregnancy Prevention, or
G-CAPP, he said he is ``around her quite a bit'' and said he
doesn't think that she regularly attends Bible study. But that
doesn't mean she's not spiritual, Durley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's found a certain sense of peace among people
who've found peace with Christianity,'' said Durley, adding that
Fonda has been to Providence Missionary ``a couple of times,''
primarily due to their G-CAPP connection. Durley said Fonda helped
Providence found the Fathers Resource Center, which educates young
males on the emotional and social responsibilities of fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Just before celebrating her 60th birthday in December 1997,
Fonda said she had asked herself, ``Where do I want to go with the
last third of my life?'' Clearly, part of the answer was to
continue her work in the area of teen pregnancy, which may have
brought her even more in touch with issues of spirituality and
religion. In that same 1997 interview, Fonda said teen pregnancy
prevention was largely about self-esteem and self-image.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it begins,'' said Durley, who had early
conversations with Fonda about approaching the religious community
in the Bible Belt about the potentially touchy subject of teen
pregnancy. ``You start talking about self-esteem and something
greater than yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda's apparent spiritual quest is bound to surprise many
people who still remember her as the outspoken Vietnam War
protester once married to Chicago Seven member Tom Hayden. Nor does
it jibe with the standard image of Turner.
</P>
<P>
   At a banquet where he was named Humanist of the Year in April
1990, Turner said he started to lose his faith when his sister died
after a lengthy illness, despite his prayers. He said the further
from his faith he strayed, ``the better I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   The humanists applauded loudly. A few weeks later, he publicly
apologized for his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the bottom of my heart, I apologize for the things I said
about Christians,'' he told members of the First Baptist Church in
Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Turner appears to have publicly hinted at a clash
of spiritual values. Turner confirmed last year that he and Fonda
were seeing a marriage counselor. ``Jane wants me to become a
saint,'' the Jan. 17 People magazine said he groused at a
California awards dinner. ``But I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   The report that religion is at the root of Turner and Fonda's
problems is from a source whose objectivity has been questioned and
that has taken issue with Fonda in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The story was written by WorldNetDaily editor and CEO Joseph
Farah, the one-time editor of the now-defunct Sacramento Union.
After becoming editor in 1990, Farah attracted attention for
editing a description of the National Organization for Women as a
``radical feminist group'' into one story, for banning the use of
the word ``gays'' to describe homosexuals and for describing the
Union as ``a pro-life paper.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1991 Los Angeles Times story, the Union's owner said the
paper had a ``Christian philosophy'' and that a prayer committee of
local residents had been established ``... to lift up the Union to
God.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times story said an editor quit when Farah criticized her
for running a favorable review of a book about Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   Farah told the Times he objected to the review because ``it was
a defense of Jane Fonda and Jane Fonda's politics. ... We've got a
readership that's totally at odds with that point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Also quoting unnamed sources, People is reporting in its Jan. 17
issue that Fonda has told friends recently that a sticking point
with Turner was her desire to spend more time in Atlanta with her
daughter, Vanessa, and new grandchild, Malcolm, who live in Grant
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors say Fonda indeed has been spending time at her
daughter's Grant Park home. ``She's been seen there two days in a
row,'' Grant Park resident Carol Fisk said late last week. ``She's
definitely helping her daughter out. She was seen raking leaves.''
_ Staff writer Gayle White contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
