<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-TRUMP-VENTURA-NYT &LR;      01-07 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-VENTURA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONALD TRUMP LETS MINNESOTA SEE A REAL WINNER _ HIMSELF  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN PARK, Minn. _ Taking potshots at Ed Koch, all the
Republicans running for president, North Korea, Fidel Castro,
Japan, Russia and candidates of humble background, Donald Trump on
Friday brought his presidential exploratory campaign to Minnesota,
where he outlined his vision of a Trump administration and helped
raise money for his Reform Party ally, Gov. Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, who called himself ``the biggest developer in the hottest
city in the world'' _ that would be New York _ spoke at a Chamber
of Commerce lunch and later at a dinner where more than 200 people
paid $100 a ticket to attend. Aides to Ventura, the Reform Party's
highest-ranking elected official, said the money would be used to
spread the party's gospel around the state.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, however, Trump seemed no closer to announcing
whether he would compete for the Reform Party's presidential
nomination than when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am looking very, very seriously at whether or not it can be
won,'' he said at a news conference with Ventura, sandwiched
between his scheduled events. ``Instinctively, I want to know if I
have a good chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   For Trump, the visit was a chance to share with appreciative
audiences his views of just about everything. He said New York
City's inability to fix the Wollman skating rink in Central Park,
which Trump repaired for the city at cost in 1986, showed that Koch
was a bad mayor. Trump said he watched the Republican candidates
debate on Thursday night and concluded: ``Are these people stiffs,
or what? It was pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   He described North Korea as the United States' greatest foreign
threat, a country ``run by some very bad people.'' He called
himself ``a big, big fan'' of the economic embargo against Cuba,
whose president, Castro, is ``a bad guy.'' He said that Japan had
been ``ripping us off for 25 years,'' and that Russia was ``totally
mixed up, and they have missiles run by people nobody ever even
heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   He struck a blow for rich people as national leaders, chiding
candidates who express pride in their humble backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're losers,'' Trump said. ``Who the hell wants to have a
person like this for president?''
</P>
<P>
   Without criticizing anyone, he reviewed his proposal to
eliminate the national debt with a one-time tax on the nation's
wealthiest people and said he would put forth his ideas on health
care and overhauling the welfare system within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Trump said he came to Minnesota as a favor to Ventura, not to
get his endorsement. But the governor made it clear that Trump
would get it if he decided to run. Otherwise, Ventura said, he
would endorse someone else, anyone but Pat Buchanan, the
Republican-turned-Reform candidate who is seeking the party
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Because of policy differences with Buchanan, the governor said,
``It would be very difficult for me to support him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV09-B     01-07 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING DEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 9, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the talk about a ``new economy,'' good old technical
economics gives many signs of being in remarkably good shape as it
enters the 21st century. Among the portents has been a certain
amount of stock-taking recently in the technical journals.
</P>
<P>
   The Quarterly Journal of Economics, for example, has a special
issue coming next month on the topic ``What Have We Learned Since
Marshall? '' The answer seems to be: some. (Alfred Marshall's text
``Principles of Economics,'' dominated the teaching of economics in
1900.) The editors of the Journal of Economic Perspectives
organized their Winter 2000 issue around a series of ``Reflections
on Economics at the Turn of the Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best evidence of the robust health of the discipline
was to be found in the annual meetings of the American Economic
Association and its affiliates, which ended Sunday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 economists, most of them professors in research
universities or colleges, many of them deeply involved in the
affairs of the world, attended more than a hundred different
sessions at which new work was reported and discussed. There were,
as usual, only two plenary events: a grand lecture, given this year
by Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers on the subject of financial
crises; and a presidential address, delivered this year by outgoing
president D. Gale Johnson of the University of Chicago, an
agricultural economist who spoke on the future of food. The
convention was organized and presided over, at least in some
distant way, by Dale Jorgenson of Harvard University, who as
president-elect organized the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The serene collegiality with which the AEA presidency passed
from one leader to the next is another of those signs of a
discipline in firm control of its destiny. However much the AEA
remains dedicated to scientific opennesss and social democracy _
many different organizations gather beneath its big tent and its
commitment to gender and racial equality is pronounced _ the
organization remains a strict scientific meritocracy at its
uppermost reaches. However much economics remains divided into
differing camps _ and it does to some extent _ it has little
difficulty deciding who among its rivalrous leaders have earned
nearly universal admiration.
</P>
<P>
   Each spring, a nominating committee recommends a short list of
possibilities, and the executive committee then slates a single
distinguished economist to run for the presidency of the
association. (The other seven offices are contested.) What's the
basis for selection? It's not easy to say, beyond a lifetime's
leadership in the field, intellectual and professional, public and
behind-the-scenes. Whatever arguments take place behind closed
doors, the Association seem to know how to achieve consensus. It
has been decades since the last controversial choice.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of those who held the position over the last thirty
years discloses an unsurprising drift from liberal to conservative.
Because the last act of a president is to head the nominating
committee five years after he or she steps down, birds of a feather
tend to follow one another in office, but only for a a year or two
at a time. Surprises crop up occasionally. The deeper rhythym of
developents in the field obiously has something to do with it as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the 1970s saw men such as James Tobin, John Kenneth
Galbraith, Kenneth Arrow, Walter Heller, Robert A. Gordon, Franco
Modigliani, Lawrence Klein and Robert Solow serve as president,
while in the 1980s, economists as various as Moses Abramowitz,
William Baumol, W. Arthur Lewis, Charles Schultze, Charles P.
Kindleberger, Alice Rivlin, Gary Becker, Robert Eisner and Joseph
Pechman served.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, presidents have included Gerard Debreu, Thomas
Schelling, William Vickrey, Zvi Griliches, Amartya Sen, Victor
Fuchs, Anne Krueger, Arnold Harberger, Robert Fogel, D. Gale
Johnson. Jorgenson _ who won distinction as an econometrician
devising new tools for the measurement of capital _ and Sherwin
Rosen, the University of Chicago labor economist who earlier this
fall was was elected to succeed him, will lead the economists into
the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The president serves for a few years in a high saddle between
the peaks of what has been described as the Reward System and the
Authority Structure of science (in an illumninating article,
``Inside Science,'' in the current issue of The American Scholar.)
David Goodstein and James Woodward, the authors, are professors at
the Califorian Institute of Technology respectively of physics and
philosophy. Both have served in executive capacities as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pinnacle of the Reward System is scientific glory,'' they
write. ``The goals of those in the Authority Structure are power
and influence.'' Those who leave science for adminstration seldom
are permitted to return. ``The university president is a kingpin of
the Authority Structure, but a dropout from the scientific Reward
System,'' they write.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the AEA _ any association president _ becomes a
key figure in the Authority Structure in the act of organizing
meetings and deciding who will be on the program and who will not.
(``Even if you manage to finance and publish your work, it will be
little noticed unless you also manage to get invited to speak at
national meetings organized by your professional society,'' write
Goodstein and Woodward in American Scholar.) Jorgenson organized
his meetings in a relatively decentralized way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enlisted the eight officers, and named eight additional
people to the program committee. I asked each member to review
massive sets of proposals. I also asked each one to award _ to
arrange _ a section of their own. (Such seesions are automatically
published in the AEA proceedings.) Some people have had themes for
their meetings. My feeling was, let the voices speak.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Jorgenson's list of the most interesting sessions this year
consisted mainly of his lieutenants' efforts. These can fairly be
described as reporting work that is digging deeper into
well-established concerns: a session on new approaches to taxing
the rich, for instance (``everybody likes to tax the rich,'' says
Jorgenson;) another on inflation targeting, a fashionable new
approach to monetary policy; a third on the macroeconomics of
emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Other featured panels examined new issues in immigration; the
division of labor between men and women and welfare of children in
developing countries; the National Bureau of Economic
Research-Sloan Foundation project to visit various factories and
carefully examine the issues that they raise; the empirical testing
of trade theories; unresolved issues in personnel policy.
</P>
<P>
   Still other marquee sessions considered the quality of private
and public financial planning; the restructuriing the financial
system; the effects of welfare reform on family structure and
fertility; the political side of economic developoment; the crucial
relations among preferences, behavior and welfare; new
understandings of executive compensation; and what Jorgenson
described as ``Myron Scholes tells all'' _ a star-studded panel on
the near-crash of 1998, featuring one of the Nobel laureates who
was among the partners when the Long term Capital Management
trading firm went broke then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big surprise to me was how far interests in microeconomics
have moved toward health and environmental issues,'' Jorgenson
concluded. ``Both of these areas seem to bed thriving. On the macro
side, the big issuies are inflation targeting in monetary policy,
and the Long Term Capital debacle and its implications.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
