<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE FINE DAY, DON MARTIN PICKED UP A PEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM WHITING  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Don Martin Dept. is closed.
</P>
<P>
   That means a final ``fwak!'' for the long-faced, hinge-footed
buffoon who walked innocently into calamity for 30 years of
one-page comics in Mad magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who died Thursday at age 68, was crowned ``Mad's maddest
cartoonist'' for the strip he drew from 1956 until the mid-'80s.
The gags were just sick and cynical enough to set up a generation
of Baby Boomers for what was to come. In those primitive years
before cable, kids got their laughs from ``Spy vs. Spy,'' ``The
Lighter Side of ...'' and ``The Don Martin Dept.,'' a strip
scattered throughout each issue.
</P>
<P>
   The classic Don Martin episode carried an innocuous title such
as ``One Fine Day at ...'' There could be men, women, babies,
lovers, but they all had a variation on the same homely face, as if
there was an entire society of Don Martins somewhere. The
protagonist would be going about his business oblivious to the trap
he was about to enter. When he got there, a gruesome scene would
usually occur, punctuated by words like ``thort'' or ``spladap,''
which Martin made up.
</P>
<P>
   The characters were never named, but it was assumed that Don
Martin the artist was also Don Martin the hard-luck character.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and clumsy, Martin was the first cool adult geek of the
comics. His hair stuck out the side of his head. His attempts at
modern fashion failed. His jaw dropped to reveal horse teeth. His
feet bent at odd angles and always preceded the body around the
corner and into danger. Though he usually came to a bad end, he was
always optimistic. He could be mutilated four different ways in an
issue, and after each he'd rise with that foolish grin, less
worried than Mad's ``What Me Worry'' cover boy Alfred E. Neuman.
</P>
<P>
   In the early comic books, artists did not own their work, so
Martin quit ``Mad'' and in 1987 went to work for the imitator
``Cracked.'' His audience did not follow. The Don Martin Dept.
belonged in Mad then and forever after.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
