<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-07 2023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACHES LOOK AT THE NFL PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Jim Fassel, head coach of the New York
Football Giants, and Dick Vermeil, head coach of the St. Louis
Rams, were talking on the phone (no, not about Bill Belichick)
about what they consider The Natural Order of Progession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed that it has disappeared,'' said Fassel, ``and what
we see is something new developing. In the old days, there was a
natural order. As a team moved, it moved slowly. One year you might
be 10-6. You make a few moves, and go up to 11-5. Or you you start
to slip, and go 9-7. But things moved slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it changes fast. The dissent is rapid. Last year, Denver,
Atlanta, and the Jets were in the final four. All of them were set
back by injury, or free agency, and had dramatic drops compared to
a year ago. This season, Indianapolis, St. Louis, Tennessee, none
of them playoff teams a year ago, come out of nowhere and to the
top.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil said he studied what happened and it seems as though
three or four player moves changed the balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams that have had big years, (Fassel's) team, Indy,
others that moved up fast, picked up a few guys that made them
better and stayed away from injury,'' Vermeil said. ``The teams
that dropped down lost guys in free agency, didn't replace them,
got hit by injury, and couldn't respond.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing are the long-term affects of free agency,''
said Fassel. ``The talent is so thinned out that three or four
players, here or there, getting them or losing them, can change how
good a team is in a hurry. It didn't used to be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   To follow his New Order theory a little closer, let's take an
informed look at the NFL's postseason tourney, which begins
Saturday with two wild-card games, with comments from coaches who
have played both teams this season.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo at Tennessee, Saturday at 12:30, analysis by Oakland
coach Jon Gruden: ``The big thing will be to see how Rob Johnson
taking over at quarterback is going to change things for Buffalo.
Tennessee is a very tough place to play. The noise factor in that
stadium is very important. It is loud. The Tennessee defense uses
that noise to its advantage. They really come after the passer
hard. They'll be after Johnson. They blitz a lot and keep the
pressure on. How he handles it will be important to the Buffalo
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo's defense should be a tough matchup for the Tennessee
offense. Eddie George is a terrific runner for Tennessee, and they
primarily are a running team. But Buffalo has a great front seven
on defense and is one of the best in the league against the run. If
they stop George, then it will fall on (QB Steve) McNair, and this
is when Bruce Smith can be a big factor in the game, getting off
the ball and getting a good pass rush on McNair. I think it's going
to be a fun game. I see both teams trying to spread out a little
bit and try to make some big plays downfield. I think it will be
the best game of the bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit at Washington, Saturday at 4 p.m., analysis by Chicago
coach Dick Jauron: ``Detroit beat them in Detroit during the
season, but I think Washington will have the edge at home in this
one. The Washington offense against the Detroit defense is a good
matchup. Washington has a lot of talent on that offense. (Redskins
quarterback) Brad Johnson had a big year throwing the ball, and
they can run it. Detroit is very good up front on defense, and
(defensive end) Robert Porcher is outstanding. Washington has to
block him in pass-rush situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Detroit's linebackers as well, they are very active.
But the Lions' defensive backs are not that big. Washington's wide
receivers, (Michael) Westbrook and (Albert) Connell, are a tough
matchup. (Quarterback Gus) Frerotte is getting the start for
Detroit. He played for Washington, so they know what he can do.
He's a guy that can get hot if you let him. He gets rid of the ball
fast and has a history of being a better quick thrower, a guy who
is more effective short than deep. On grass, at home, I think
Washington will be tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas at Minnesota, Sunday at 12:30 p.m., analysis by Fassel:
``We played these teams the final two games of the season. The key
to the game is the way these two teams play in the red zone (inside
the opposing 20-yard line). This is where the Dallas defense is
really tough. I think they are second- or third-best in the league
in this area. You can move the ball on them, but then they make you
take a field goal instead of a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dallas strength is on defense. They are very fast in the
secondary and at linebacker. They use their good speed to cut down
on the number of big plays. Their linebackers, (Dexter) Coakley and
(Randall) Godfrey are very good in coverage. As a group they tackle
very well in the open field. Minnesota is big on the outside, with
(Randy) Moss, (Cris) Carter, and (Jake) Reed for receivers. I don't
think Dallas can match up with all of those guys. Dallas does not
have it going on offense. They don't have the ability to make the
big play. Minnesota will force them to drive the ball, and it's
difficult to score a lot of points when you are playing on a long
field all afternoon. Toward the end of the season Minnesota was
playing the better football, and I think they should have the edge
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami at Seattle, Sunday at 4 p.m., analysis by Jets linebacker
coach Al Groh: ``We played Seattle last week and they just seemed
to want to throw the ball. They are very hard to defend. They use a
lot of different formations and cause a lot of problems for
defenses. They ran the ball only 12 times against us. Ricky Watters
was supposed to be hurt, but he played. They went away from him.
Miami's difficulty will be handling (wide receiver) Joey Galloway
on the outside. He has blazing speed. Seattle will try to have
(quarterback) Jon Kitna get rid of the ball fast, to cut down on
Miami pressure on the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Seattle coach) Mike Holmgren likes those quick slants, and
they might be the best screen (pass) team in the league. Seattle
likes to get the ball to its receivers going up field, so if you
don't tackle well, they can be gone. Miami will have to tackle well
in the secondary. When we played Miami (in the penultimate game of
season), they changed what they had done in the past. They didn't
even put up the pretense of trying to run. They came out in passing
formations on first down and just went after it. Miami better not
get in many third-and-longs. Seattle has two guys coming off the
corner on the pass rush, Chad Brown and Michael Sinclair, that can
really bring it. And with Cortez Kennedy inside, Seattle can fold
the pocket. I think Seattle, playing at home, on the faster track,
has the edge. But to me, the team that wins the game is the one
going into the game with the better attitude. Both played poorly in
the second half of the season, compared to the first. The team that
thinks it still has a chance to do something in the playoffs, is
the one that will win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quiz question of the day: The last time Miami played in Seattle,
the Seahawks won with their quarterback throwing three touchdown
passes of more than 50 yards. Who was the Seattle QB? Answer below.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What happened to our Doug? Well, it seems the Buffalo coaching
staff thinks Flutie can't throw the ball deep with success, and the
opposing teams are jumping on the shorter Buffalo pass patterns,
making it difficult to generate any offense. The Bills replaced him
with Rob Johnson, who has a much stronger arm, but has another
problem: He's made of paper-mache. It's not that Johnson isn't
tough enough, he's just injury-prone. He's had just nine starts in
the NFL and has been injured four times. He started one game his
final year in Jacksonville, played a great game, and never returned
because of an ankle injury. His first start for Buffalo in San
Diego in 1998, he got a slight concussion and left the game. He
returned the next week to start again, but four weeks later,
suffered a rib injury, and Flutie took his job. This season, when
the Bills had a big lead in Philadelphia, they brought Johnson in
in the second half, and he got KO'd again with another concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Johnson has the better arm, and may be able to throw
the deep ball better, I think it's Russian roulette playing an
injury-prone guy against Tennessee, one of the league's best
pass-rushing teams. If Johnson holds onto the ball long enough to
throw deep, he might get decked again. When he can stay on his
feet, Johnson is good. In his last four starts, two in mopup games
the final week of the last two seasons, the team averaged 32 points
a game. But all of us around here know that something will happen
to get Flutie in the game to win it at the end for the Bills.
Flutie is 26-13 as a starter with the Bills, the best record in the
NFL the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are hurting just as much in attendance as they are
on the floor. This reporter went to the game vs. Cleveland at the
FleetCenter Monday night. It was announced that 18,624 tickets were
sold, 14,115 people in house, which adds up to 4,509 no-shows. No
way. The no-show number is bogus. The actual count was fewer than
12,000 in house, which is the lowest number since 1980, or since
Larry Bird came to town. It isn't good when some 6,000 people buy
tickets to a game and don't bother to show. And it doesn't help
Jerry Jacobs pay the mortgage on the FleetCenter. The per capita on
concessions and merchandise sales for a Celtic game runs around
$12, so multiplied by 6,000, and the building took a hit for more
than $70,000. The Celtics have been playing to more empty seats
this season than they have in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heard that Harry Sinden went ballistic in the Bruins' locker
room after they handed over a game in Ottawa in overtime Dec. 30.
The Bruins had a 4-2 lead going into the third period and just kept
icing the puck, trying to sit on the lead, and it backfired. Sinden
ripped into the team and the coaches for such an inept performance.
Hopefully, the discussion will have the team trying to score goals,
even when it has the lead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll will not be the next defensive coordinator in
Seattle as reported. Ditto for Green Bay. From what I've seen of
some of the candidates the Patriots have brought in here, or talked
with, about being their next coach, Steve Sidwell would be the best
of the bunch. Why haven't they interviewed Patriots defensive line
coach Ray Hamilton, a hard-nosed, intelligent guy who would get the
players back to thinking more about what they were going to do on
Sunday afternoon rather than what they were going to do Monday and
Tuesday nights at the Foxy Lady?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a misconception that commissioner Paul Tagliabue can
unilaterally decide on a settlement that would bring Bill Belichick
to Foxborough as the next coach and general manager of the
Patriots. The Jets are the only ones who can decide if what the
Patriots will offer is good enough to let Belichick move on. Not
Tagliabue. Three years ago, in the Bill Parcells move to the Jets,
both sides agreed to let Tagliabue decide the settlement. The Jets
don't plan to do that and won't name a new head coach until the
next owner is selected, which is expected to come next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tell me how Belichick's agent, Neil Cornrich, is going to get
around this one when he meets Tagliabue Monday to argue that
Belichick never had a contract to coach the Jets. When Belichick
decided to resign Tuesday, he wrote his own resignation letter and
signed it, as the coach of the Jets. Not a very smart thing to do
when your agent is telling the world you were never coach of the
Jets. Somehow Belichick must have thought he was.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quiz answer: Patriots backup quarterback John Friesz.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
