<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9809 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-MANAGEMENT08-COX     01-07 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MANAGEMENT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daft molding his Coca-Cola team
 &HT;    By Henry Unger and Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola President Douglas Daft continued to put his
stamp on the company Friday by naming a new marketing chief and
head of European operations.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Charlie Frenette, 47, to head Coke's business
in Europe and Minute Maid President Stephen Jones, 44, to replace
Frenette as chief marketing officer, was received well on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's stock rose 6 percent Friday in heavy trading on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Daft's moves also further upset a management restructuring
launched last October by Chairman M. Douglas Ivester, who plans to
retire in the spring after a tumultuous two years at the helm of
the world's largest soft drink company. Daft is slated to succeed
him.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the 49-nation Greater Europe Group, Frenette will
oversee operations in Coca-Cola's third-largest market after the
United States and Latin America. But it's also a region where the
company has faced obstacle after obstacle in reaching 866 million
potential consumers of its products.
</P>
<P>
   Those troubles last year included Coca-Cola's inability to seal
acquisitions because of government concerns of market dominance and
a summer health scare that involved contamination of its core soft
drink brands. The latter sent youths to hospitals and resulted in
the largest product recall in Coke's history.
</P>
<P>
   The health scare, and the perceived slow response by Coke
management to contain and explain it, cost the company millions in
lost sales and ignited a firestorm of government criticism.
</P>
<P>
   It was Frenette's job to oversee the intense marketing effort to
rebuild consumer confidence and to get the company's products back
on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie's experience in directing our marketing efforts in
Europe during the past year make him the ideal leader for our
business there,'' Daft said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Dixon, a portfolio manager at Arnhold &AMP; S. Bleichroeder
Inc., said one of Frenette's objectives should be to ``change the
environment in Europe to one of cooperation rather than
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   John Sicher, editor at Beverage Digest, said Daft ``could not
have picked a better executive'' to head the company's European
operations. He cited Frenette's leadership in southern Africa,
where he once headed Coke's operations under the supervision of
Carl Ware, president of the Africa Group. Earlier this week, Daft
named Ware to head a new global public affairs division.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette replaces William Casey, 58, who has been with the
Coca-Cola system for 32 years. Casey, who has been president of the
Greater Europe Group since 1998, will become a consultant to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Robert Baskin said the troubles in Europe had
nothing to do with Casey's departure. ``This seemed like a good
time to do it, what with Doug Daft organizing for the future and
putting his own team in place,'' Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one analyst, however, Skip Carpenter of Donald, Lufkin
&AMP; Jenrette, said it's ``somewhat surprising that Casey is retiring,
given his age and he was still directly reporting to the CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW MARKETING CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   Frenette's reassignment comes days before Coca-Cola launches a
new ad and marketing effort for Coke Classic that replaces the
``Always'' campaign with a new ``Enjoy'' theme. The new campaign is
designed to pump more excitement into stagnant consumer demand for
the flagship brand.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola describes Stephen Jones, Frenette's replacement, as a
veteran marketing and operations executive with 13 years of
experience in the United States, Canada, the United Kingdom and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Jones' knowledge and skills in developing and managing a
large portfolio of brands to meet the range of local consumer needs
has global applications for our company,'' Daft said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Ivester named him to head Minute Maid last November,
Jones was deputy division president for Coca-Cola in Japan, where
he was instrumental in managing a portfolio of about 200 products.
They included soft drinks, coffees, teas and water.
</P>
<P>
   EXCITEMENT ON WALL STREET
</P>
<P>
   Daft's quick management reshuffling this week came as a welcome
surprise on Wall Street. The stock closed up $3.62 1/2 Friday at
$60.62 1/2. It remains well off its 52-week high of $70.87 1/2,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daft wants to be seen as taking charge,'' said Dixon at
Arnhold &AMP; S. Bleichroeder Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to move more senior executives away from Coke's
North Avenue headquarters and into the markets they oversee.
Frenette, for example, will be based in London, while Sandy Allan,
who now heads Middle East and Far East operations, will be based in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Daft himself has seen his career bolt at the company just in the
past several weeks. In a management restructuring in October,
Ivester named the native Australian to head the company's
operations in Asia, the Mideast and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Then in December, when Ivester announced his planned retirement,
Daft was promoted to president and chief operating officer, and the
company's board indicated he would be named chairman and chief
executive officer in April.
</P>
<P>
   Among other top appointments, Daft still must appoint someone to
head Minute Maid and Coca-Cola's operations in Africa. Daft is also
expected to name a new president and chief operating officer after
he himself is elevated. Wall Street expects Jack Stahl, head of the
company's North America and Latin America operations, to be named
to the posts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-GERMWARFARE-AR     01-07 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GERMWARFARE-ART-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH U.S. AID, RUSSIAN LAB'S RESEARCH SHIFTS FROM GERM WARFARE TO
HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a bitter cold afternoon last fall, a handful of Russian
scientists gathered at a cemetery in Siberia for an impromptu
ceremony to mark the 25th anniversary of the founding of what was
once the Soviet Union's largest laboratory for developing germ
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lev Sandakhchiev, the director of the lab, known as Vector,
situated in the town of Koltsovo, raised a plastic cup of vodka to
the memory of Dr. Nikolai Ustinov, a scientist who died in the
spring of 1988 after accidentally infecting himself with the
Marburg virus, a hemorrhagic killer that he and his colleagues were
trying to perfect as a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside Ustinov's widow, Yevgenia, at the foot of her
husband's still-contaminated grave, Sandakhchiev, toasted their
fallen colleague and friend, who documented the progress of the
disease as it ravaged him, in a diary stained in his own blood.
``Thank God it is over,'' Sandakhchiev said, as tears streamed down
his face.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly a decade since the fall of the Soviet Union,
Sandakhchiev, quietly aided by the United States, says he has been
steering Vector, or the State Research Center of Virology and
Biotechnology, away from its past and toward peaceful research.
Rather than using germs to kill people, he says, Vector is now
trying to save people, and itself in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. intelligence analysts and congressional staff members
remain wary of Vector's research and fearful that Russia may still
be conducting secret germ warfare work at closed military sites and
institutes. But administration officials and scientists who have
toured the lab _ once the crown jewel of the Soviet germ warfare
empire _ say the administration's investment to transform Vector
seems to be paying off.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the World Health Organization endorsed a proposal
backed by President Clinton to conduct research into smallpox
vaccines and anti-viral drugs at both the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta and at Vector, a decision that
helped cement Vector's status as a legitimate player in
international science.
</P>
<P>
   Given such developments, U.S. officials and germ warfare experts
say, Vector has quietly been removed from the administration's
``threat'' list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mention of Vector used to send shivers down the spines of
intelligence analysts,'' said Amy Smithson, a germ and chemical
warfare specialist at the Henry L. Stimson Center in Washington,
and the author of a new study of the administration's programs to
reduce the threat of the former Soviet Union's germ warfare
institutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with all of Sandakhchiev's changes and the frequent
visitor traffic in and out of there, Vector hardly rates as a
concern,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, once part of a closed Soviet city, Vector has
increasingly welcomed foreign scientists. In September, the center
played host to more than 50 American and foreign scientists at a
conference financed in part by the United States. It also gave a
reporter an unprecedented tour of laboratories where the most
sensitive germ research was once conducted and allowed Vector's
scientists to discuss their previous smallpox research and other
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists and officials say Vector scientists are now joining
forces with American and European scientists in various commercial
and nonprofit research ventures: making diagnostic kits for markets
in the former Soviet Union, enriched milk for children, interferon
and antibodies, even cosmetics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In one project, Vector scientists and two American biotech
companies are developing a powerful new anti-viral drug that was
tested last year at Vector and that they hope will help neutralize
Ebola and other hemorrhagic viruses, thus reducing the threat of
bioterrorism, or will augment other drugs to which bacteria and
viruses have grown increasing resistant.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of transformation has been neither smooth nor easy.
Enmeshed in Soviet-style secrecy and nationalism, hardliners in
Russia have resisted scientific exchanges and Vector's growing ties
to the West, U.S. officials and Russian scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, skeptics in Congress and national security
circles also initially opposed the administration's attempts to
finance the center's transformation, warning that Russia might use
U.S. aid to continue offensive germ research at other, still-closed
labs.
</P>
<P>
   But several key critics of the program were surprised when the
administration quietly informed Congress earlier last year that
Vector had rebuffed potentially lucrative offers from Iran to buy
products, technology and scientific expertise. Detailed audits of
Vector's grants show that the millions of dollars invested by
Washington _ which now account for about half of Vector's annual
budget _ have been spent as Congress intended.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Congress substantially increased the Pentagon's
request to finance programs to open Russia's germ labs, bringing
the total to $14 million. While the State Department has yet to
decide how to allocate the money, its biological programs could get
as much as $48 million, more than three times last year's level.
</P>
<P>
   Daily life at the isolated installation remains difficult,
however. Vector, deprived of most Russian government funds, now
struggles to get by with about 2,200 scientists _ less than half
the number who worked at the lab during its heyday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Ken Alibek, a defector who was a top official
in Moscow's germ warfare program, smallpox had long been the Soviet
Union's strategic biological weapon of choice. ``Moscow,'' he wrote
in ``BioHazard,'' a book published last year by Random House, ``had
stored up to 20 tons of the virus at other facilities to ensure
that Moscow would never be caught short.'' Those stocks have since
been destroyed, say Alibek and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Even as his country had promised to end its germ weapons
program, the last Soviet leader, Mikhail Gorbachev, financed the
construction of dozens of installations at Vector for the smallpox
weapon project in the 1980s, soon after the World Health
Organization had unwittingly declared the ancient scourge
eradicated.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of those installations are empty, unfinished or
deteriorating through neglect. A giant viral reactor built then has
been dismantled, and Vector has lacked money even to buy monkeys
for tests since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what was planned for this facility, we were lucky that
communism ended when it did,'' said an administration official who
follows biological issues closely.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A key part of the administration's conversion strategy has
involved the World Health Organization, some of whose scientists
have been suspicious of Vector ever since they learned that the lab
once carried out secret germ research in violation of a 1972 treaty
banning germ weapons, which the Soviet Union had signed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Russia quietly moved to Vector its collection of
smallpox strains from the Ivanovsky Institute of Virology in
Moscow, although the WHO had designated Ivanovsky as the only
official storage site in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The WHO quickly visited Vector and designated it as the official
site, but the move raised suspicions. Sandakhchiev asserted in an
interview that the strains had been moved merely because Russia
faced a terrorist threat from war in Chechnya and Vector provided a
more secure site for Russia's 120 different smallpox isolates _ the
world's largest collection, twice the size of America's.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about smallpox intensified this year after Alibek and
others warned that strains of the deadly virus had found their way
to Iraq, North Korea and other countries and that therefore the
supposedly eradicated disease still posed a threat to a now
unvaccinated world.
</P>
<P>
   Based on such reports, Clinton reversed his earlier support for
the WHO's decision to destroy the virus at the two declared storage
sites in Atlanta and at Vector. In Geneva in May, Washington led a
successful campaign within the WHO to defer destroying the virus
and to endorse research on the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dr. Sergei Shchelkunov, a leading smallpox
expert at Vector, said more work was now needed to understand the
virulence and peculiarities of all the strains, which should help
to develop new vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1991, Dr. Alexander Guskev, a Vector scientist,
led a team more than 2,400 miles across Siberia to the tiny town of
Chersky, north of the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   There the scientists unearthed in the deep permafrost the
still-frozen bodies of people wrapped in deer skin shrouds and
buried in pits who were thought to have died of smallpox nearly 145
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Guskev insisted that his goal was not to find more smallpox
strains, which were plentiful at Vector. The mission's goal, he
insisted, showing visitors videos of the expedition, was to
disinfect the cemetery of what might be a dangerous living virus.
</P>
<P>
   Initial biopsies of bone and skin fragments from the bodies
found no trace of the virus, he said. But the team returned the
following July and August and hit scientific pay-dirt _ frozen
bodies so well preserved that pox marks were still visible. ``But
when we returned to Vector, we found that we couldn't isolate or
revive the virus-like particles,'' Guskev said.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to return to another permafrost area next summer to
further his studies, although he now lacks funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such research is a luxury that Vector cannot afford and whose
medical application is debatable,'' an American military scientist
said. ``Until the past is truly dead and buried, I doubt that
anyone will fund it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandakhchiev, whom even Alibek praised for his ``determination
to protect his employees,'' seems eager to bury the past. ``All
labs like ours have a responsibility to be open and to share
information,'' he said in an interview. ``To fight disease and
inspire mutual trust, we must communicate with each other. That is
our future. There is no alternative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
