<SLUG> BC-BUILDNET08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BuildNet's infusion worth $104.7 million
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Heavy-hitting investors appear confident in BuildNet's
strategy to streamline the way houses are built.
</P>
<P>
   The Durham, N.C.-based Internet firm, run by a former Home Depot
executive, landed one of the nation's largest venture capital deals
ever. BuildNet said it raised $104.7 million this week from
builders and suppliers such as Pulte Home Corp., Beazer Homes and
Owens Corning. Venture investors included BancBoston Ventures, J.W.
Seligman &AMP; Co. and others.
</P>
<P>
   BuildNet aims to revamp the supply chain of the home
construction industry by linking suppliers and builders through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a contractor is running behind schedule,
BuildNet would automatically contact suppliers and tell them to
hold off on deliveries. BuildNet would then take a commission from
each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to launch its Internet site in U.S. cities
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is mapping all the industry information to a
uniform, standard language,'' said Nathan Morton, chief executive
of BuildNet. Morton is the former senior vice president of
operations for Home Depot and former chairman and CEO of computer
retailer CompUSA.
</P>
<P>
   This week's deal marks the second time that BuildNet made a
record venture capital deal. In May, the company secured $35.7
million in capital, which was then the largest single venture
capital round ever in North Carolina's Research Triangle Park.
</P>
<P>
   BuildNet employs about 300 people in offices in Durham, Atlanta,
San Francisco, Redmond, Wash., and Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
