</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EKITCHEN-WHIRLPOOL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-kitchen on front burner
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Whirlpool Corp.'s Dayton Technology Center will
likely begin working on kitchen ovens and other cooking devices
that are linked to the Internet, a company official said.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool is teaming with Sun Microsystems and Cisco Systems to
develop home appliances that have broadband Internet technologies.
Whirlpool displayed prototypes of an Internet-connected
refrigerator and oven at the Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fanning, Whirlpool's director of home solutions, said the
Dayton Technology Center will likely further develop the oven
prototype. The idea is to bring such products to appliance stores
and consumers' kitchens in the next 12 months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fanning said Whirlpool, and many other big companies, are
focusing on kitchen technologies since families cook, eat and
gather in their kitchens. But who needs an oven or fridge linked to
the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Fanning said home chefs could follow instructions from a cooking
show via the Internet or families could keep electronic shopping
lists on their fridge and someday order groceries electronically.
Using broadband technology, the Internet connection would be on
constantly, eliminating the need to boot up a computer and dial
into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And will this catch on with Americans who still have trouble
programming their VCRs?
</P>
<P>
   ``This cannot be as complicated as a computer operating system.
It can't be something you have to fish through 20 pages of
documentation. It's got to be very screen driven ... and easy to
walk through,'' Fanning said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
