<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-BILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE AND TITANS ON THE INSIDE LOOKING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the end of the previous three seasons, Eddie George and his
Tennessee Titans teammates would talk in the locker room about
plans for the off-season. Travel and families and social events
would be discussed. So would the reasons that George and the bunch
finished with an 8-8 record in each of those years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago around this time, I was sitting at home watching
the playoffs on TV,'' George said, ``and couldn't wait for it all
to end so that I could get to Hawaii and to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to talk to some guys there and see what was the
difference with their teams. What could I do differently to get
into the playoffs? It was so frustrating being on the outside
looking in. Now, in our locker room, there is a totally different
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   A different atmosphere. A tingling buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Because Tennessee is in the playoffs. The Titans finished with a
13-3 record and twice beat the Jacksonville Jaguars, the team that
owns the home-field advantage throughout the American Football
Conference playoffs. Tennessee was 8-0 at home in its brand-new
Adelphia Coliseum. It has won four straight games, and the offense
averaged 39.3 points in the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday the Titans tackle Buffalo (11-5) at Adelphia Coliseum
in a wild-card playoff game that features teams with the most
combined victories (24) ever in a wild-card matchup. Buffalo has
playoff experience, Tennessee does not. Buffalo's Rob Johnson will
make a surprise start at quarterback, replacing Doug Flutie, and
George will have his wish _ a chance to excel in the postseason and
for all the Titans to enjoy the playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved from Houston and Memphis to Nashville and did not
have stability in the last three years,'' George said. ``We didn't
have the greatest facilities. We wondered how many fans would show
up to our games, and if they did how many would be cheering for us.
No matter how you try to put these kinds of things out of your
mind, they are distractions. Now we have stability plus some new
blood like Jevon Kearse that has helped our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done this year is make sure we were invited to the
party. In the AFC, it's like there are six teams in a room and
there is a prize. It does not matter how you come out of that room,
you want the prize. We don't care that we have a good record and
have to play in the wild-card game. We want the prize, no matter
the road.''
</P>
<P>
   George has produced his best season to help the Titans
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He rushed 320 times for 1,304 yards, averaged 4.1 yards a carry
and scored nine rushing touchdowns. His teammates call him The
Beast, because he can speed around the end and also punish up the
middle with his strong 6-foot-3-inch, 240-pound frame.
</P>
<P>
   This season George added pass receiving as a strong component of
his game. He caught 47 passes. In his first pro season he caught
23, the next year seven and last year 37. This season George also
turned catches into big gains _ he averaged 9.7 yards a catch and
caught four passes for touchdowns, including a 54-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Barry Sanders, Eric Dickerson and Earl Campbell as the
only backs to gain at least 1,200 rushing yards in each of their
first four pro seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been my best season as far as what they have asked me
to do, especially coming out of the backfield as a receiver,''
George said. ``I study defenses more and understand what they are
trying to do. But my real breakout year _ I don't think that's
happened yet.''
</P>
<P>
   George knows he will see a nasty defense from Buffalo, one that
attacks with speed and power and that is anchored by the venerable
end, Bruce Smith. George preaches patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may run and get 1, 2, 3 or 4 yards,'' he said. ``Our
longest run may be for 10 yards. But we have to stick with the run
and believe in it. We can't take for granted that what we've done
at home this season, with the great and loud fans we've had, will
all fall in place. We have to put ourselves in position to give the
fans something to be excited about and not let Buffalo jump on us
and take them out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that George and the Titans are finally in the playoffs, they
plan to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very realistic that we can go deep into the playoffs,''
George said. ``We're in it, first of all. We are among that small
elite. This is the time to take advantage, because we know from
experience how hard it is to get here and that next year is not
guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The Bills have not been shy about voicing their concerns this
week. Doug Flutie said he was unhappy about being benched in favor
of Rob Johnson at quarterback for the wild-card game. Now, Andre
Reed, the veteran wide receiver, has complained about his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious I'm not in their future plans, and I can't
subject my family or myself to that anymore,'' Reed wrote on his
Internet site. ``It's time for me to move on. I'll be happier. I
was not a happy player this year; it was miserable going to work
every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
