A9831 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-STUDENT-HARASSED-BOS &LR;      01-07 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-HARASSED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT ACCUSED IN ALLEGED COMPUTER HARASSMENT OF WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Web-Stalker)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Beng Ky asked a UMass-Boston classmate out on a
date last fall, the 20-year-old woman told him she just wasn't
interested.
</P>
<P>
   But Ky persisted, investigators say. He called her repeatedly at
home. He followed her around campus, from building to building,
class to class. When she signed out a video at the Language
Library, Ky was right behind her, allegedly stealing her student ID
number _ which also was her Social Security number _ in order to
harass her in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the 24-year-old computer science major stood in
Dorchester District Court, charged with using the woman's Social
Security number, taken from the lab sign-up sheet, to break into
her campus computer account, order credit cards in her name, and
open an Internet account in the name of her nephew.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest in a wave of new-age computer crimes, a
burgeoning criminal frontier that has sparked calls for tighter
controls and spawned a national commission on ``cyberstalking.''
Just Wednesday, a Swansea, Mass. man was charged with making
Internet death threats against Mayor Thomas M. Menino and two other
city officials.
</P>
<P>
   The misdemeanor charges of computer trespassing and identity
theft lodged against Ky were the first brought against a
UMass-Boston student _ and among the first local cases of alleged
cyber-harassment resulting in criminal charges. The case has forced
U-Mass to rethink its policy of using students' Social Security
numbers as their student ID numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this particular case will be the impetus to look at
some of our policies and procedures and how students should provide
information,'' said UMass-Boston spokeswoman Annemarie
Lewis-Kerwin. ``We have zero tolerance for Internet fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ky had no criminal record, Suffolk Assistant District
Attorney Nancy Hathaway asked District Court Judge Margaret A.
Zaleski to set bail at $5,000 cash. Zaleski agreed, ordering Ky not
to contact the victim.
</P>
<P>
   With the assent of Ky's court-appointed attorney, Daniel E.
Dilorati, Zaleski included additional conditions: Ky must stay off
the Internet and give his computer hard drive to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Dilorati told reporters that $5,000 cash was ``excessive'' and
stressed that Ky has not been charged with the felony of stalking.
He also said that Ky ended his attempts to contact the woman last
November after the school warned him his actions were unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a harassing case,'' DiLorati insisted. ``This is
not a stalking case.''
</P>
<P>
   The university has suspended Ky, a sophomore, who was arrested
Friday by UMass-Boston police. They began investigating when the
woman, whom authorities declined to identify, first complained
about unwelcome attention from Ky last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was frightened,'' said Detective Kathleen Potter, who
investigated with Sergeant Detective Stanley Stewart. ``She just
wanted him to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Potter said Ky was not charged with stalking because he never
made any threats, as required for prosecution under the stalking
law. The woman continued to attend classes last semester as Ky
continued to shadow her and authorities looked into his activities.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement he allegedly gave police after his arrest, Ky
said he was upset that his advances had been rejected but that he
did not view his actions as harmful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad at her,'' Ky wrote, according to the office of
Suffolk District Attorney Ralph C. Martin II. ``I didn't really
want to hurt'' her ``at all. It was just for the fun of it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Potter and Hathaway, Ky used the woman's Social
Security number, which doubled as her identification number, along
with a Personal Identification Number, to access her internal
UMass-Boston computer account.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was still unclear how Ky obtained the PIN,
which is randomly selected by a computer and then mailed to the
student at home. Without the PIN, Ky would not have been able to
swap the woman's address with his own, as he is charged with doing.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Ky also allegedly used the woman's Social Security
number and the name of her 3-year-old nephew to set up an Internet
account with Digital Broadband Communications of Waltham, according
to court records.
</P>
<P>
   He also allegedly used her Social Security number to apply for
credit cards, which he apparently never used. According to
Hathaway, the woman's father is a mail carrier in and a co-worker
alerted him to mail addressed to his daughter at Ky's home, which
turned out to contain the credit cards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
