<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES A FEDERAL CYBER SERVICE TO PROTECT COMPUTERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Friday proposed new measures
to combat unauthorized intrusions into the nation's key computer
networks, including a monitoring program for government computers
that was scaled back amid criticism and a subsidized training
program for cybersleuths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an age when one person sitting at one computer can
come up with an idea, travel through cyberspace, and take humanity
to new heights,'' Clinton said. ``Yet someone can sit at the same
computer, hack into a computer system, and potentially paralyze a
company, a city or a government.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that, as part of the budget for the 2001
fiscal year that he will propose on Feb. 7, he would request $91
million to develop programs to protect computer security. That sum
would be part of a $2-billion package _ up from $1.7 billion in the
current fiscal year _ for existing computer security efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The president's plan would create an institute that would gather
``the finest computer scientists and engineers'' from universities,
research organizations and private enterprise to advance computer
technology and security. College scholarships would be offered to
students who study computer security and agree to join a ``Federal
Cyber Service'' that would help the government combat computer
attacks, a model similar to the ROTC program used to train military
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The president's plan would include a sophisticated software
system to monitor government computer activities in search of
intrusions and other illegal actions. The Federal Intrusion
Detection Network, or Fidnet, has raised concerns among civil
liberties groups.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides reworked the proposal to address privacy concerns
by restricting monitoring to government computers, not those in key
private industries, and by making clear that the program would be
run by the General Services Administration, not the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   If the monitors picked up illegal activity, information would be
sent to the FBI, an administration official with knowledge of the
plan said. But the FBI would not have routine access to the
program, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his chief counter-terrorism adviser, Richard
A. Clarke, of the National Security Council, said threats to
government and private computer networks run the gamut from
teen-age hackers to industrial spies to international terrorists.
Several countries have embarked on computer-terrorism programs to
created havoc in rival states, said Clarke, who refused to name
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in American history that we in the
federal government, alone, cannot protect our infrastructure,''
Commerce Secretary William Daley told reporters. ``We can't hire an
army or a police force that's large enough to protect all of
America's cell phones or pagers or computer networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials say that thousands of unauthorized computer invasions
are attempted across the country every day. The targets are
governments, utilities and businesses, and the invaders' intentions
range from playing pranks to stealing passwords to planting
damaging computer viruses. A study by the General Accounting Office
issued in October said that security shortcomings in government
computers could jeopardize national defense, law enforcement, air
traffic control and other key operations.
</P>
<P>
   Several government Web sites have fallen victim to hackers in
recent months, including those at the White House, the FBI and the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking the hackers will take a more coordinated government
response, a partnership with private companies and a corps of
trained specialists, the president said. The initiatives grew out
of a study that Clinton ordered in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Thomas, an information security expert at AverStar Inc.
who previously oversaw the Pentagon's response to computer attacks,
said keeping up with hackers will require a spirited government
response together with the commitment of private industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hackers don't have the bureaucracy we have to deal with in the
corporate world or in government,'' Thomas said. ``They're much
quicker and some of them are geniuses. The good news is we're
arresting more and more people. The bad news is it's a smaller and
smaller percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said heightened computer security should not tread
on the privacy rights of businesses and citizens. ``It is essential
that we do not undermine liberty in the name of liberty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some computer activists remained concerned about a
government offensive in the unstructured world of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is making some appropriate and even laudable
proposals but the monitoring of government computer systems _ I
call it a surveillance program _ could still violate the privacy of
legitimate computer users,'' said James X. Dempsey, staff counsel
for the Center for Democracy and Technology, a civil liberties
group in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
