<SLUG> BC-FED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
19 STATES PAID BILLIONS MORE IN FEDERAL TAXES THAN THEY GOT BACK IN
SERVICES 

</HEADLINE>
 SPENDING-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nineteen states paid billions more dollars in federal taxes in
fiscal 1998 than they got back in federal services, according to a
recent Harvard study, but Texans came pretty close to breaking
even.
</P>
<P>
   Texas collects less per capita than the national average in such
areas as Social Security and Medicare payments, but nearly makes up
the difference in federal defense spending in the state. Texans
collect about $250 per capita less in federal services annually
than they pay out in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Though defense spending is a much smaller percentage of the
federal budget than the social service and assistance programs, the
concentration of defense dollars in a smaller number of states,
where defense contractors and bases are located, is a big factor in
determining winners and losers in federal funds distribution.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report from Harvard University's JFK School of
Government concludes that in general terms, the rich states give to
the poor. On average, states whose residents have higher per capita
incomes receive less per capita federal spending than lower income
states.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest growing elements of the federal budget _ Social
Security, Medicare, retirement and disability programs _ have
always been oriented toward lower income states, the report states.
And defense spending has declined significantly in a small number
of high income states, such as California, Colorado and
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a large number of states find themselves paying
taxes toward defense facilities located in a small number of
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing about defense is it tends to be highly
variable across states, very idiosyncratic,'' says report author
Herman B. ``Dutch'' Leonard, professor of public finance at the JFK
School. ``What does the success in this process have to do with how
long your congressional delegation has been in office? The answer
is probably a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard adds, however, that the states actually have a pretty
big hand in determining how much federal money they get.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state chooses to fund in a relatively low level in some
of these domains, like welfare, the federal government pays
relatively low as well,'' Leonard said. ``Therefore the total is
reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas, for example, has a relatively high poverty rate but
chooses to fund many of its social service programs at a rate about
10 percent lower than the national average. That means the amount
of federal matching funds returned to the state are proportionately
lower, too.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, for example, is at the bottom of the list of states
in terms of federal funds received vs. taxes sent to Washington, a
deficit of $2,400 per resident. But Connecticut residents have the
highest per capita incomes in the nation, about 45 percent higher
than the national average, and therefore don't qualify for much
federal poverty assistance funding.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico is at the top of the list, collecting $3,600 more in
federal funding per resident than what it sends to Washington in
tax dollars. But the key to New Mexico's success in the federal
dollars game is that the small state population is reaping the
benefits of expensive defense and energy facilities located in Los
Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   Southern states tended to collect more than they paid out in
federal taxes, while states in the Northeast and around the Great
Lakes did not.
</P>
<P>
   The first analysis of federal dollars collected vs. federal
dollars spent in the states was commissioned by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan in 1977, mainly to counter criticism that New York was an
unfair recipient of federal largesse.
</P>
<P>
   The report eventually began to examine all 50 states, and
Harvard scholars took over the project in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the federal government's role were to be neutral, if they
were to give back exactly what their citizens pay in, I would raise
the question: Why would we need the federal government?'' asks Ray
Scheppach, executive director of the National Governor's
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most economists would argue that at least for elderly and
disabled populations, to the extent that they are low-income
populations, there is a federal role to re-distribute.''
</P>
<P>
   The report ranked the states where the federal government
collected more tax dollars than it spent from highest to lowest.
Those states are New Mexico, Virginia, West Virginia, North Dakota,
Montana, Mississippi, Arkansas, Maryland, Kentucky, Hawaii,
Alabama, South Dakota, Oklahoma, Maine, Arkansas, Louisiana,
Missouri, South Carolina, Tennessee, Idaho, Rhode Island, Iowa,
Arizona, Wyoming, Pennsylvania, Kansas, Vermont, Florida, Nebraska,
North Carolina, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   These states had deficits in federal funds: Georgia, Texas,
Washington, Ohio, Indiana, Oregon, Colorado, California,
Massachusetts, New York, Wisconsin, Delaware, Minnesota, Illinois,
New Hampshire, Minnesota, Nevada, New Jersey and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
