<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9838 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      01-07 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS _ WITH AN EYE ON BELICHICK _ CONTINUE INTERVIEWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If life was fair, the new coach of Patriots
would be a man who has earned his stripes through years of loyalty
and excellence, one who has seen and dealt with every situation,
one who has been successful with different teams and adapted his
philosophy of the game to the talent he has on the field.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be someone who tells it like it is, no lip service.
</P>
<P>
   Those qualities define Patriots defensive coordinator Steve
Sidwell, 55, who formally interviewed with the team Friday and will
interview in Green Bay unless the Packers make a quick decision on
Butch Davis or are able to extract Jon Gruden from Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots feel Bill Belichick is a bigger fish, and the
one they want swimming in their humble Foxborough pond. It appears
only a matter of days before Belichick will be announced as the
team's head coach and general manager and the team reassigns vice
president of player personnel Bobby Grier, who will be a
transitional consultant, if he so chooses.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is what will Belichick's coaching staff look
like if he can't take the Jets' assistants with him? One
possibility might be to elevate Jets running back coach Maurice
Carthon to offensive coordinator or hire Chicago offensive
coordinator Gary Crowton and give him an assistant head coach tag.
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell met with Grier and Andy Wasynczuk Friday. Robert Kraft
was present for Sidwell's interview and available when Baltimore
Ravens defensive coordinator Marvin Lewis, 41, met with the
hierarchy in Boston and Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed the process,'' said Sidwell. ``I'm happy that I was
able to talk to them about my football philosophy. I hope I made a
good impression. I would love to be the head coach of the New
England Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell is also a potential candidate in New Orleans, where
owner Tom Benson is a big supporter of his. But the Saints will
hire a GM first and he'll hire the coach. New Orleans GM candidate
Charley Casserly was in Houston Friday meeting with owner Bob
McNair about taking over that expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have now interviewed Oakland Raiders defensive
coordinator Willie Shaw, Crowton, Sidwell, and Lewis. There are
more to come, but the information in Foxborough is not being
released in great doses in what is a very private process.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will take the weekend to review the candidates they
have interviewed. St. Louis offensive coordinator Mike Martz, who
is now being considered for a position in New Orleans, may be a
future candidate. There appears a slight chance Marty
Schottenheimer could be talked out of retirement, but that is still
a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   But all of it appears to be window dressing _ killing time until
Belichick arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Until commissioner Paul Tagliabue actually rules on the
grievance Belichick filed Thursday, there will be other issues to
speak about.
</P>
<P>
   One of the charges you always hear during these contractual
squabbles between rival teams is tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Newsday reported that Jets officials feel
there was evidence of tampering by the Patriots with Belichick. The
charge was that the Patriots made it clear to Belichick they wanted
him long before Bill Parcells resigned (while Belichick was still
an assistant coach), which the Jets would have had to honor. But
the Jets have claimed Belichick's head coaching deal kicked in the
moment Parcells tendered his resignation last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Tampering was brought up three years ago when the Patriots felt
the Jets had pre-arranged a deal with Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Though the league has specific tampering rules, they are rarely
enforced or proven because there are so many ways for Team A to
communicate with a player or a coach on another team.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, for example, Belichick's agent is Neil Cornrich,
who represents several Patriots (Andy Katzenmoyer, Adam Vinatieri,
and Tony Simmons) and Jets (former Patriots punter Tom Tupa,
defensive end Anthony Pleasant). The NFL has not cracked down on
agents representing both players and coaches like Major League
Baseball has in recent years. It leaves the door wide open for
tampering.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had a similar situation with Pete Carroll, who was
represented by Gary Uberstine's California firm, which also
represents Troy Brown, Shawn Jefferson, Chad Eaton, Steve Israel
and Willie McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is represented by Ray Anderson, who also represented
Willie Shaw, the Oakland Raiders' defensive coordinator who
interviewed Wednesday. Anderson also represents Patriots strong
safety Lawyer Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said on Wednesday that he didn't know of any evidence
that the Patriots had tampered.
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriots GM Patrick Sullivan recalls when owner Victor
Kiam tried to press tampering charges against the Jets when the
late Dick Steinberg left the Patriots to go head the Jets. Kiam
tried to get compensation, but Sullivan informed Kiam that he
likely didn't have a case because he told Steinberg he was free to
go. When Kiam brought the case to Tagliabue, very early in his job
as commissioner, Tagliabue threw the case out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember Leon Hess sitting there, shaking his head,''
said Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan is certainly intrigued by the current Patriots-Jets
drama. He's been on an ownership team about to sell a franchise,
and he understands what the Jets are going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``There a lot of conversations going on in an effort to get
stability,'' said Sullivan. ``You go through the entire process and
due diligence concerning the value of the franchise on a set of
circumstances that now do not exist. The value of the Jets is
pretty much fixed. They know what their stadium deal is, their
merchandising deals, the local rights deals. The variables, what
are the players worth and who's your coach? It puts a real monkey
wrench into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally wouldn't be surprised to see Parcells back in
there. The new owners have to take a crack at enticing him back. If
I were in their shoes, that's what I would want to do. If he's not
the best coach, he's in the top two or three in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said that for the most part, the Jets' sale in fairly
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Until now) there's not been an enormous amount of publicity
about it,'' he said. ``It's been quiet. It's not like the Redskins,
where John Cooke wanted to keep the team. John Hess doesn't want to
keep the team. I think it's been a stable sale situation. (Jets
president) Steve Gutman is a very sharp guy. Very capable guy. He
said he'll run that thing until there is an owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said whether there are tampering issues or simply an
issue of the validity of Belichick's contract, ``It's ultimately
going to be decided by compensation.'' While the Jets will pursue a
similar package to the one the Patriots received for Parcells,
Sullivan doesn't believe the package will be comparable. ``It's
tough to get that because you're not dealing with a coach in this
case with the same track record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan believes that the Patriots have handled everything the
right way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``They asked permission to speak to
Belichick and did that on the up and up. There's no mistaking this
guy is a good coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan doesn't buy a scenario in which Belichick doesn't
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not gonig to walk away from that type of contract,'' said
Sullivan. ``He's either going to another team or he's going back to
the Jets. He's not going to sit out the prime three years of his
coaching career. Coaches are very practical people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
