<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARCH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gay coalition working for unity
 &HT;    By Kavita Kumar
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ They spent almost half an hour deliberating over
verbs and prepositions. They knew one word could mean the
difference between solidarity and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Should their banner read ``Sharing in his dream'' or ``Working
for his dream''?
</P>
<P>
   Gay-rights activists wanted to make sure they appeared to be
supporting and not appropriating Martin Luther King Jr.'s dream.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether they should include the coalition's name on the
banner or just carry rainbow flags, well, that was a whole other
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they unanimously agreed on ``Working for his dream''
in large letters with the group's full name _ The Miami Valley Gay,
Lesbian, Bisexual, Transgender and Supportive Community Coalition _
in smaller letters at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The recently formed umbrella organization will carry this banner
at Dayton's Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Day march and rally Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The group voted on the banner and the action Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Its decision came weeks after several area ministers, many of
them black, lobbied members of the Dayton City Commission to block
Commissioner Mary Wiseman's proposal to add homosexuals, the poor
and Appalachians to the city's anti-discrimination ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The activists saw the King parade as an opportunity for members
of the gay community to express their solidarity with blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're realizing that while we're not anywhere close to being
the same, that the struggle for GLBT people for civil rights has
many parallels with the black community,'' said Lee Strausberg,
founder and director of the coalition. ``And while we do not want
to steal from them, we do want to stand up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   March organizers say the coalition is welcome to march _ as is
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not about to be discriminating against any person who
is marching for the dream and legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr.,'' said Raleigh Trammell, president of the Dayton chapter of
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. King's dream and
legacy ``is that we ought to love one another and come together in
peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The GLBT Community Coalition, formed early last fall, now has an
e-mail list of more than 120 members.
</P>
<P>
   The recent dispute over changes to the city ordinance has
galvanized the group and brought more people to its meetings.
</P>
<P>
   While the organization has a specific focus, coalition members
emphasize that, like its banner says, they are working towards
equality for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to focus on getting rights for everyone because we
understand we can't do it alone,'' Strausberg said. ``If we want
the community to support us, then we want to support the community.
After all, we are a community made up of all the other
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
