A9847 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RELIGION-GAYS08-COX     01-07 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-GAYS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who speaks for Jesus?
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As a gay man, it is no surprise that the Rev.
Mike Castle supported a recent failed effort to extend Dayton's
anti-discrimination ordinance to include homosexuals and poor
people.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, he invited the author of that proposal, City
Commissioner Mary Wiseman, to speak to his congregation at Cross
Creek Community Church. The congregation, about half of whom are
gay, gave Wiseman a warm welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus showed up at city hall, and all hell broke loose!''
proclaimed Castle.
</P>
<P>
   Those who successfully opposed the amendment would agree that,
indeed, Jesus showed up at city hall. But he was on their side.
It's difficult to deny that both the Old and New Testaments speak
with a strong voice that homosexuality is a sin. Wiseman's
opponents would argue that sinful behavior should not be protected
by law.
</P>
<P>
   In a Christian-based society, it's a question that comes up in
any attempt to legislate morality: Who gets to speak for Jesus?
</P>
<P>
   Don McMurry believes the truth can be found in 1 Corinthians
6.9: ``Or do you not know that the unrighteous shall not inherit
the kingdom of God? Do not be deceived; neither fornicators, nor
idolaters, nor adulterers, nor effeminate, nor homosexuals, nor
thieves, nor the covetous, nor drunkards, nor revilers, nor
swindlers, shall inherit the kingdom of God.''
</P>
<P>
   McMurry, associational missionary for the Greater Dayton
Association of Baptists, helped lead the charge that defeated
Wiseman's amendment. The organization sent out faxes and e-mail to
its 30,000 members, and many of them, both lay and clergy, showed
up at two City Commission meetings to speak against the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that they spoke for the Christian
community,'' he says, pointing out that they came from Assembly of
God, Pentecostal and other denominations.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't speak for the Rev. John Paddock. Paddock, rector
at Christ Episcopal Church, was one of a dozen clergy who signed a
letter of support for the ordinance that was sent to the Dayton
Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Paddock acknowledges that there are several biblical passages
that condemn homosexuality. ``But every one of them is
problematic.'' Two thousand years ago, he says, people did not
understand that homosexuality is an orientation, not a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he adds, ``Jesus never said anything against
homosexuality. He was constantly welcoming (outcast) people _
prostitutes and tax collectors _ and was constantly criticized by
church leaders for hanging out with them.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that Jesus condoned a sinful lifestyle,
according to the Rev. Randy Chesnut. Chesnut, of North Dayton
Baptist Church, is troubled by the notion that ``love is
permissive. That if you really love someone, you don't speak
against their sin.'' It was Christ, he points out, who said, ``Go
and sin no more.'' He emphasizes that he opposes any form of
violence, persecution or harassment. ``Homosexuality doesn't
deserve greater condemnation than any other sin.'' But forgiveness
is only part of the package that is Christian salvation, he
explains. The other part is transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Castle admits that the Bible doesn't mince words about
homosexuality. Leviticus 18:22 says, ``You shall not lie with a
male as one lies with a female; it is an abomination.'' But Castle
observes it isn't fair to pick and choose with Leviticus, which
also condemns the eating of pork and the wearing of clothing woven
from different types of fibers. ``I don't know many Southern
Baptists who want to give up their barbecued pork,'' laughs Castle,
who was himself an ordained Southern Baptist minister until he
could no longer reconcile his homosexuality with his denomination's
position on homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Castle, who is now ordained with the United Church of Christ,
approaches Scriptural interpretation using the criteria set forth
by John Wesley, founder of the Methodist Church. Scripture, Wesley
said, should be informed by reason, church tradition, experience
and discipleship.
</P>
<P>
   Wiseman, who was raised United Methodist, wasn't surprised that
biblical Scripture was used to oppose the amendment. That's what
has happened in cities across the country, where there have been
attempts to pass such an ordinance. ``But I was surprised that it
got such a strong foothold here,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the voices of the opponents were louder than those
who supported the anti-discrimination amendment. Did they speak for
the majority of Dayton's Christian community? The Rev. Karen
MacDonald of Northminster Presbyterian Church isn't sure. ``I still
think a fair number of folks aren't sure about it. They'll still
trying to sort it out. They're the ones who are not speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   And they are the ones whose voices will need to be heard, as
mainline churches enter the 21st century. Methodists, Presbyterians
and Episcopalians have grappled with issues of the ordination of
gay clergy and the blessing of gay unions in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mainline church has to open its doors wider than ever
before,'' says the Rev. Steven Camp of Faith United Church of
Christ. His church took out an ad in Impact Weekly in support of
the amendment. If churches don't become more welcoming, he says,
``a lot of gifts that people bring will not be present. A lot of
churches will close.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiseman describes herself as ``a perpetual church-hopper,'' in
search of a spiritual home. She believes that faith and politics
can _ and should _ mix. ``To be a good public servant, you have to
remain true to your own core values. For many of us, that is
remaining true to our religion. The line you draw is when you say,
'This is my personal faith, and this is the way the rest of the
world ought to be.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
