u p BC-BUSH-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      01-07 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BOOK CHALLENGES IMAGE; OBFUSCATING ON OBFUSCATE; GETTING THE
SONG WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also REPUBS-DEBATES) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ Voters who attended speeches by Gov. George
W. Bush this week in New Hampshire and Iowa got more than just a
handshake, a promise and a heady brush with political celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   They got a bound, paperback copy of his collected works.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Fresh Start for America: Policy Addresses of George W.
Bush'' brings together Bush's entire canon: his November
reflections on foreign policy (``A Distinctly American
Internationalism''), his October musings on education (``A Culture
of Achievement''), his July comments on the role of religious
organizations in social work (``The Duty of Hope'').
</P>
<P>
   The latter was particularly compelling, at least according to
the journalist Clarence Page, who wrote a column in The Chicago
Tribune that raved, ``If it were a movie, it would deserve an
Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   The reader of ``A Fresh Start for America'' knows this because
the book is rife with blurbs, and not only on the matte back cover
of the 208-page book, but also in between every chapter, one per
big speech.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that some of them were carefully selected from longer
articles or television commentaries that included less flattering
observations. The Bush campaign has learned how to use ellipses and
learned how to use them well.
</P>
<P>
   None of these addresses was previously kept under wraps. Each
time Bush gave one, his aides provided journalists with a title, a
transcript, a synopsis, short biographies of the academic and
political luminaries who influenced it and even their telephone
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Fresh Start for America,'' which came out this week,
revisits the hits, in a portable volume that allows the more
discerning, attentive types of people who vote in state primaries
to take measure of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The book accurately conveys what the Bush campaign intends it
to: that despite his opponents' characterizations of him as vague
and weightless, he has clearly stated his views on an array of
issues and has put forward several concrete proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Fresh Start for America'' is also a near-perfect emblem
of the style, methods and gestalt of the Bush campaign, which is
amazingly thorough, astonishingly organized, opulently packaged and
a bit overemphatic in its response to any insinuation that Bush
lacks the gravitas to govern a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had already produced an election-season autobiography, ``A
Charge to Keep,'' written primarily by his communications director,
Karen P. Hughes, and financed and distributed by Random House.
</P>
<P>
   So ``A Fresh Start for America'' is a bonus, published by the
campaign itself, at a cost of nearly $1 per copy. Aides said that
50,000 copies have already been printed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush held one aloft at an appearance in Salem, N.H., on Thursday
morning. ``For people having trouble sleeping at night,'' he said,
``I suggest Chapter Three.''
</P>
<P>
   A Trip of the Tongue and Memories of His Father
</P>
<P>
   Away from the printed page, Bush was having a little trouble
with eloquence _ or at least pronunciation _ this week.
</P>
<P>
   Television viewers who watched the Republican debate on Thursday
night probably noticed this when Bush, wearing an expression of
apparent satisfaction with the big word he was about to unleash,
promised that he would never ``obsfucate'' as president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   That is a good thing, because the verb is ``obfuscate,'' and
this was the third time in two days that Bush seemed to mangle it.
</P>
<P>
   On each occasion, he paused slightly either before or after, the
oratorical equivalent of a drum roll or cymbal crash. And on each
occasion, it never sounded quite right.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, it was clear why. He had the consonants mixed
up, the letter ``s'' in the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, at an appearance in Rochester, N.H., he was
neither obsfucating or obfuscating, but he was conflating the words
tariff and barriers into terriers, which he promised to knock down
in the name of trade. Would retrievers and spaniels be next?
</P>
<P>
   Bush quickly caught himself, which he did not do when, during
two previous appearances in New Hampshire this week, he referred
twice to ``a post-cold world,'' strangely bypassing the war. Or
maybe he was just referring to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   And Speaking of Father: Let Him Speak for Himself
</P>
<P>
   These verbal tics _ the exception with Bush, not the norm _
brought to mind his father, who was renowned for the grammatical
and syntactical chaos he made of the English language.
</P>
<P>
   But former President Bush was hovering over the week's events in
other _ and sometimes stranger _ ways.
</P>
<P>
   His son was reminded repeatedly of his father's famous broken
pledge not to raise taxes (``Read my lips'').
</P>
<P>
   And it put Bush in an odd bind. He could not say his father's
actions were laudable because that would make his own stated
passion for tax cutting seem suspect. But he could not say his
father's actions were deplorable because that would make him seem
like a cad.
</P>
<P>
   So he bunted, saying his father and his father's record could
speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But what was being said by another record: a rendition of the
song ``Cat's in the Cradle,'' which describes a son who vows to
grow up to be just like his father?
</P>
<P>
   It was part of a soundtrack that was put together by the Bush
advance team in New Hampshire and blared over speakers at several
events. And it seemed to represent the rare occasion when the
campaign's attention to detail flagged.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the song is that the father, too busy with his own
ambitions to pay any attention to his son, makes a similarly
insensitive man out of him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
