<HEADER>
A9851 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-ANNUITIES-2TA     01-07 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-ANNUITIES-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REINVENTING THE VARIABLE ANNUITY, WITH MORE BELLS AND WHISTLES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  (af) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Jones is holding forth in a small conference room in the
John Hancock tower in downtown Boston, talking about new features
of a product that receives a lot of negative comment from experts _
variable annuities. Among other benefits, the annuities may now
offer guaranteed returns, even in market downturns, and money for
nursing home care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked at answering objections to the product,'' said
Jones, who is in charge of variable annuities, a combination of
mutual funds and insurance, at the John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co., ``and we've added features to address things that
consumers worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   But the things that many financial planners worry about most are
fees, which for variable annuities are averaging 50 percent more
than those for comparable mutual funds. And there is only so much
that John Hancock and the other big variable-annuity companies say
they can do to pare those costs. Adding more features generally
adds more in fees, which can be a big drag on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to buy one of these things you ought to buy
the simplest version at the lowest cost,'' said Judith Martindale,
a fee-only financial planner in San Luis Obispo, Calif., who rarely
recommends variable annuities. ``Some of these features may not
actually be worth much. And for things like nursing home needs,
you'd probably be better off shopping for the coverage separately.
You usually can't get everything at the best price at one stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, big variable-annuity companies like Nationwide and
American Skandia are convinced that customers want more, not less,
in their annuities. So they are offering a cafeteria of choices,
letting customers pick what they like and pay accordingly. That can
make a complicated investment even more so.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Eisenbach, in charge of variable annuities at Nationwide,
calls the new approach ``customization or modularization _ as
opposed to one size fits all.''
</P>
<P>
   With competition heating up, the companies are also offering
cash bonuses to attract business, the way banks once offered
toasters and blenders. Many companies are adding at least 3 percent
to the value of the initial investments _ meaning that a new
$100,000 account, for example, is credited as $103,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another kind of bonus helps customers use the strategy of
dollar-cost averaging _ the investing of fixed amounts at fixed
intervals. A company puts an investor's cash into a sort of holding
area, paying interest of 10 percent or 12 percent, significantly
above money market rates, as it is disbursed into mutual funds over
six months. (The company may offer lower, but still above-market,
rates for six additional months.)
</P>
<P>
   Such bonuses reduce the companies' profit but are a calculated
trade-off. ``It may be a long-term solution to get customers in and
collect insurance and management fees for 15 or 20 years and maybe
get some other business out of the same customer,'' said Patrick
Reinkemeyer, who monitors variable annuities for Morningstar, the
financial researcher in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The variable annuity has long been a way to take a run at the
stock market with the assurance that if the investor dies, the
heirs will receive at least the original amount invested. Now
companies will increase the amount that an investor's heirs receive
so that it equals at least 5 percent compounded annually, or the
high-water mark reached by the investment, whichever is higher. The
cost for this guarantee is often one-quarter of a percentage point
of the account's value annually.
</P>
<P>
   American Skandia offers the highest guaranteed return of this
type _ 7.2 percent compounded annually, which means that a $100,000
investment will at least double in 10 years. The cost is half a
percentage point a year, or $500 on a $100,000 investment.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are offering an even better guarantee _ a promise
that the money available to the investor, rather than his or her
heirs, will increase at a steady rate. That guarantee gives a
variable annuity, which fluctuates with the market, some of the
safety of a fixed annuity.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the market does, the investment will grow by a
guaranteed percentage _ often 5 percent. But you have to pay for
that guarantee, typically 0.3 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial experts say such guarantees are usually a waste
of money, because stock investments have historically enjoyed
average annual returns of more than 10 percent _ and there have
been few periods of even five years in which stock investors have
lost money.
</P>
<P>
   ``These benefits are much more psychologically valuable than
economically valuable,'' Reinkemeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   To provide for nursing home care, Nationwide intertwines nursing
home coverage with a variable annuity, while John Hancock promises
to pay a set amount for three years to cover any expenses that may
arise from infirmities of age.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Nationwide package, to be introduced in most states later
this year, a 55-year-old woman, for example, would make a single,
up-front payment of, say, about $60,000. Of that total, 40 percent,
or $24,000, would go into mutual funds. The balance would pay for
nursing care indefinitely at a rate of $100 a day. The amount would
rise 5 percent annually so that in 30 years the daily benefit would
be $432.
</P>
<P>
   Because women tend to live longer than men, a 55-year-old man
could get the same minimum daily benefit for a single payment of
$33,500, with 60 percent of the money, or $20,100, going into the
mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The annual cost for the mutual funds in this package is 1.40
percent of assets, or about the same as for many variable annuities
without the nursing care, plus the usual average of about
0.9percent charged to manage the funds.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nationwide package, the benefit of the health care
allocation can be claimed only if the investor qualifies for
nursing home services or their equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   The plan addresses customers' concerns about their ability to
pay for such care _ and offers a convenient way to get coverage.
Although financial planners and consumer advocates say a consumer
might find a better deal by shopping for nursing home coverage
separately, Tom Houle, who is in charge of new products at
Nationwide, said customers could generally expect premiums on
separate nursing home care to rise over the years.
</P>
<P>
   For the Nationwide nursing home care, there are no charges after
the initial payment. Moreover, he said, the customer's heirs would
receive at least the amounts originally invested into the funds and
the health care component.
</P>
<P>
   The John Hancock plan pays 1 percent of an initial investment _
say, $1,000 on $100,000 _ every month for three years from the time
an investor can no longer take care of himself. It costs
35-hundredths of a percentage point. The benefit is paid directly
to the investor rather than to a nursing home and can be used for
any purpose.
</P>
<P>
   One big caveat, however, is that the benefit cannot be received
until the eighth year of the investment. That is just past the
seven-year period in which Hancock, like most other companies, is
recouping the up-front commissions it pays to sales
representatives. During that time, companies impose big cash
penalties on withdrawals, known as surrender charges _ as high as
8.5 percent of the initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   Surrender charges have prompted many investor complaints; they
apply even if the account holder goes into a nursing home or
becomes disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some companies will waive the surrender charges under such
circumstances _ but again, at a cost. Scudder Kemper Investments, a
unit of the Zurich Financial Services Group, lets investors
eliminate the penalty should they go into a nursing home by paying
an additional five-hundredths of a percentage point annually.
</P>
<P>
   The exception for other disabilities costs another
five-hundredths of a point. While a customer younger than 59{ would
still have to pay a 10 percent penalty to the Internal Revenue
Service, the company's penalty would at least be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, some companies have been permitting withdrawals
of up to 10 percent of the amount invested in the annuity without
penalty. Now, at no extra charge, some companies are increasing
that ceiling to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All these features are meant to encourage the timid investor to
forswear certificates of deposit and venture into the often more
rewarding, but riskier, world of stock investing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, variable annuities may be more expensive than mutual
funds,'' said Jones of John Hancock. ``But many people would not be
in the equities market if we did not have these features.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a price to pay for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9855 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GAMESHOWS07-COX     01-07 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMESHOWS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's in the money? Everybody, if the latest slate of big-cash
game shows is any sign
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, as TV personality Fred Allen said nearly 50 years ago,
``Imitation is the sincerest form of television,'' then this
weekend will find TV at its most sincere. ABC juggernaut ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' returns; NBC and CBS debut their own
game shows, trying to jump-start the same kind of pop-culture
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who isn't admitting to being a copycat is a liar,''
admits Leslie Moonves, president of CBS Television, with unusual
candor for a TV exec.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's running to copy (`Millionaire'), and we are,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Television and the game show are made for each other,'' says
Robert Thompson, director of Syracuse University's Center for the
Study of Popular Television. ``The miracle is it didn't happen a
long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit _ or blame _ ``Millionaire,'' the fuse that set off the
explosion. When it debuted in August, it was seen as a cheap summer
substitute program. By its second run in November sweeps, it was a
national obsession, seen by more than half the country at least
once, averaging 24 million viewers and knocking off Top 10
stalwarts such as ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``America didn't fall in love with the game show,'' says
Thompson. ``It fell in love with this particular game show.''
</P>
<P>
   Four game shows in prime time will be the most since the early
'60s. Although the quiz show scandals of 1958-'59 wiped out most of
them, panel shows such as ``What's My Line?'' and ``I've Got a
Secret'' remained popular.
</P>
<P>
   Now, networks see game shows as quick fixes for their scheduling
problems. And like newsmagazines, which proliferated in recent
years (and now are mostly seeing their audience drop away), game
shows are much cheaper to produce than sitcoms or dramas, even with
the money they give away.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's convergence is just part of the story, though.
This summer, CBS will run ``Survivor,'' in which 16 regular folks
will be stranded on a desert island in the South Pacific, then vote
to eliminate each other one by one, with the winner at the end
getting $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeopardy!'' and ``Wheel of Fortune'' continue to rank as the
most popular syndicated shows, and ``Win Ben Stein's Money'' on
Comedy Central has the best categories (``Keep Your Hands Off My
Falkland Islands,'' ``50 Ways to Leave Your Louvre'').
</P>
<P>
   Even Game Show Network, a small cable channel with limited
distribution in metro Atlanta, is building a cult following with
its ``Inquizition,'' a laughably cheap ($500 for first place) but
fast-moving and addictive show in which a mysterious host, whose
face is never seen, fires rapid questions at a panel of citizens
and mocks them as they are eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone loves the trend. ``Game shows are just white noise
in life,'' says Harry Knowles, Web master of the entertainment site
Ain't It Cool News. ``They create the desire to get rich quick. By
making the game easy and the prize value high, (they) create a
feeling of success and self-esteem in the viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, audiences and advertisers love them, says Allen
Ginsberg, executive vice president of media for the Atlanta-based
ad agency BBDO South. Even though he predicts that ``the majority,
if not all, of the imitators will stumble or fail,'' he admits he
could be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had put Regis (Philbin) in front of me six months
ago,'' Ginsberg says, ``I wouldn't have thought that was going to
be a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, of the Center for the Study of Popular Television,
agrees that the mania may quickly fizzle, including, possibly,
``Millionaire.'' ABC executives have agonized over how to best use
their unexpected hit, fearing that audiences would burn out on it
quickly as a regular series. But that's what ``Millionaire''
becomes later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger of game shows is that once you're tired of them,
there's nothing the network can do to bring you back,'' says
Thompson. ``With a drama like `ER,' it can be fixed or beefed up if
it starts to lag. With a game show, it is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC may have won the November sweeps with ``Millionaire,'' but
it didn't use the show to launch a single new series, and in fact
pre-empted shows such as ``Sports Night'' that are having trouble
building an audience. Such herky-jerky scheduling angers viewers _
why should they commit to a show if the network won't? _ even if
those viewers are flocking temporarily to game shows.
</P>
<P>
   The backbone of the big networks _ their reason for being _ is
still entertainment series, the dramas and comedies that run for
years. Viewers are amazingly loyal to these TV families. In the
long run, the craze for game shows may hurt the very networks that
are rushing them on.
</P>
<P>
   A quick scorecard of the new wave of game-shows:
</P>
<P>
   'TWENTY ONE'
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Maury Povich
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NBC's ``Twenty One,'' a remake of the '50s show that was at
the center of the quiz show scandals (and the 1994 movie ``Quiz
Show''), debuts at 8 p.m. Sunday and has three more one-hour
specials (Jan. 16, 19 and 26). Maury Povich hosts the show, which
will once again stick competitors in soundproof isolation booths so
they don't know the score as they try to reach 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   'WINNING LINES'
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Dick Clark
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CBS' ``Winning Lines'' premieres at 8 p.m. Saturday for a
six-episode run. Hosted by Dick Clark, ``Lines'' is a knockoff of a
British show (as is ``Millionaire'') that starts with 49
competitors but quickly narrows it down to two people vying for $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   '. . .MILLIONAIRE'
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Regis Philbin
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' the show that started
it all, returns at 8 p.m. Sunday for a run of eight straight
nights, then settles into a thrice-weekly schedule on Sundays,
Tuesdays and Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   'GREED'
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Chuck Woolery
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fox's ``Greed,'' the first of the ``Millionaire'' rip-offs,
</P>
<P>
   settles into a permanent (for now) time at 9 Friday. It has yet
to award its $2 million top prize.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
