</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GAYS-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY VIE FOR GAY VOTE IN NEW YORK AND CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley are fighting tooth and nail for votes in New Hampshire and
Iowa, but they are also looking ahead to the two biggest prizes in
the Democratic primary, New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   This goes a long way toward explaining Gore's statement
Wednesday night that he would apply a litmus test to the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, appointing only those who would agree to implement
his proposal to allow gays to serve openly in the military. While
Bradley was not so explicit, he said he would expect the military
to follow his orders as commander in chief to allow gays to serve
openly.
</P>
<P>
   California and New York are home to significant numbers of gay
voters, and for the first time in presidential politics, those
voters are now part of a calculated strategy to win the Democratic
nomination. Homosexuals figure as prominently in Gore's plans to
stop Bradley as do African-Americans and organized labor, while
Bradley is counting on them to help transform his insurgent
candidacy into the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time there's been a competition in any
presidential primary for the gay and lesbian vote,'' said Jeff
Trammell, Gore's adviser on gay issues. ``It's part of the coming
of age politically for gay and lesbian Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   What is different in this election is not only the competition
for the gay vote but that the gay vote is now perceived to be
significant enough to form part of Gore's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking inside the Gore camp goes like this: Gore is poised
to win the Iowa caucuses Jan. 24 but is neck and neck with Bradley
in New Hampshire, whose primary is Feb. 1. If New Hampshire
legitimizes Bradley, New York, which votes March 7 and is already
extremely receptive to Bradley, could follow suit. In that case,
California, which also votes March 7, becomes all the more critical
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore is counting on organized labor and minorities to help
him in New York, he is also relying on voters who are gay to stop
any Bradley momentum in California, advisers said. Turnout among
gays could be higher than usual in California this year because of
a state initiative on the ballot to ban same-sex marriage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Homosexuals have increasingly found strength at the ballot box.
People who identify themselves as gay make up between 8 percent and
9 percent of the primary electorate nationwide and a bit more in
New York and California, according to surveys of voters in previous
elections. In general elections, they account for about 5 percent
of the national total.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have openly gay delegates to the Democratic
National Convention. Both candidates have conducted numerous events
with gay leaders, and both have given lengthy interviews to The
Advocate, the gay magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Some Gore advisers believe that Bradley has gained ground among
gays for two reasons. One is that Gore suffers by association with
President Clinton. Although Clinton was the first presidential
candidate to openly seek support from gays, many were disenchanted
with his compromise on gays in the military, settling for a ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy that now even Clinton has called
unworkable.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason is that some Gore supporters think Bradley has
out-foxed Gore in the race for gay votes. ``Gore has a stronger
record over a longer period of time of being a leader on these
issues,'' said Richard Socarides, until recently the Clinton
administration official who oversaw gay and lesbian issues. ``But
it's frustrating because he's been out-maneuvered on tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, while Gore has long argued privately within the
administration to allow gays to serve openly in the military, it
was Bradley who first said in this campaign that he favored such a
policy. Gore did not publicly declare his position until after
Hillary Clinton and then the president both criticized the current
policy. This played into the damaging perception that Gore is a
politician who waits for political cover before taking a bold
position.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Gore has been looking for ways to distinguish
himself on matters of interest to homosexuals. In a first for a
presidential aspirant and a sitting vice president, Gore is
planning to answer questions online at a gay Web site
(www.gay.com), which has more than 2.3 million visitors per month.
</P>
<P>
   In December, he met with 300 gay and lesbian leaders here. On
Monday, after a speech at the United Nations in which he will
highlight global problems like AIDS, Gore plans to meet with a
number of gay and lesbian leaders in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers said that the sharper comments at Wednesday night's
debate stemmed from Gore's long-held belief that gays should serve
openly but also from his need to reassert himself over Bradley with
gay voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would insist before appointing anybody to the Joint Chiefs
of Staff that that individual support my policy, and yes, I would
make that a requirement,'' Gore said in response to a question at
the debate. Bradley stopped short of saying he would apply a litmus
test.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore's comments have raised the ire of many in the
military, they were defended here Friday by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
, D-Mass., who is campaigning for Gore. He noted that military
commanders never made an issue of a soldier's sexuality when they
needed people to fight a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the fewest kinds of court martials on this issue during
the Tet offensive and during the heaviest fighting,'' Kennedy told
reporters in Dubuque, Iowa. ``This was never an issue when the
bullets were flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers said that the vice president's comments reflected
a growing consensus that supporting gay rights is not as
politically perilous as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup Poll in December found that 70 percent of Americans
support allowing gays in the military (although 76 percent of those
in senior military ranks are opposed).
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore and Bradley are sensing a change in public opinion,''
said Aaron Belkin, an assistant professor of political science at
the University of California at Santa Barbara and a director of a
center that studies gays in the military. ``The issue has become
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And, they really want the gay votes in California,'' Belkin
said. ``Both are coming from exactly the same position, they're
just trying to outflank each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
