<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9860 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DIRECTOR-JEWISON09-CO     01-07 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTOR-JEWISON09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director Jewison storms back with `Hurricane'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Norman Jewison flings open the curtains of his Four
Seasons Hotel suite, stands in the glorious light of a fiery
setting sun and does what he likes to do best: marvel at the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that!'' the celebrated movie director says, Atlanta's
downtown skyline arching before him, golden sunlight streaking
across the rising buildings. ``It's such a stunning city and very
famous with the Olympics and, you know, the engine of Ted Turner,
the engine of CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, he's heading for the phone. He's got to locate
Denzel Washington, who on this day is still in metro Atlanta,
filming Disney's high school football film ``Remember the Titans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to find out where he's staying,'' Jewison, 73, says
by phone to an assistant in Los Angeles. He'd like to catch up with
Washington, whom Jewison first directed in 1984 in the actor's
breakout film, ``A Soldier's Story,'' and chat about their latest
movie, ``The Hurricane.'' It's Jewison's 24th film and the one that
could land Washington, an Oscar winner for ``Glory,'' another
Academy Award nomination. ``Hurricane,'' the film biography of
boxer Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, wrongly imprisoned for nearly 20
years for murders he did not commit, opened Friday in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Jewison's critically acclaimed film is up for three Golden Globe
awards, including best drama, actor (Washington) and director
(Jewison).
</P>
<P>
   While not exactly a household name, Jewison has been a fixture
in movies for roughly 40 years. Moviegoers who don't exactly know
of him likely have seen several of his films from the '60s to the
'80s, including ``The Russians Are Coming! The Russians Are
Coming!,'' ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' ``Fiddler on the Roof,''
``Jesus Christ Superstar,'' ``... And Justice for All,'' ``A
Soldier's Story,'' ``Agnes of God,'' ``Moonstruck'' and ``In
Country.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Oscars honored him with the Irving Thalberg
Award, and his most honored film _ ``In the Heat of the Night''
(1967) with Rod Steiger and Sidney Poitier _ won best picture.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Heat,'' Jewison's ``Hurricane'' reflects the director's
longtime interest in racial issues. A half-century ago, he left his
native Canada and hitchhiked across the South. ``I couldn't believe
what I saw,'' he says. ``It was apartheid.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on two books, Sam Chaiton and Terry Swinton's ``Lazarus
and the Hurricane'' and the boxer's own, ``The 16th Round,'' the
movie details how Carter was wrongly convicted in 1967 along with
fan John Artis in the murder of three people at a New Jersey bar.
It includes Bob Dylan's spirited 1975 anthem ``Hurricane,'' based
on the boxer's plight, and the efforts of a young African-American
and his trio of social worker friends who banded together and
sparked a campaign to free Carter from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Jewison, visiting Atlanta recently to promote ``Hurricane'' and
film some spots for Turner Classic Movies, talked about making the
movie, working with Washington and his disdain for corporate
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you get involved in this project?
</P>
<P>
   A: About eight or 10 years ago, (producer) David Picker came to
Toronto to meet with Rubin Carter, who lives there. He brought with
him the Sports Illustrated article that told the whole story of him
and this kid reading a book _ ``The 16th Round.'' That whole thing.
I was absolutely fascinated. I had remembered the incident when I
was shooting ``In the Heat of the Night.'' I remembered a little
bit of the press and I remembered the Bob Dylan song, but I had no
idea Rubin Carter was living in Toronto. I had no idea what had
happened and the connection with the Canadians and the kid. That's
what the picture is about _ him and the kid. But anyway, so what
happened is I read the book and was just totally mesmerized. I just
thought it was eloquent and passionate and moving. It was just a
plea for help. It was kind of biblical.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And did you have trouble getting Hollywood interested?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nobody wanted to make it. It's a black story. The studios are
very reluctant to get involved with a story like that. They think
the public doesn't want to see them. I went through it with ``A
Soldier's Story.'' I went through it with ``In the Heat of the
Night.'' So it wasn't commercial enough, I guess. And I don't think
it ever would have been made by a studio. Even now it's been made
by Beacon (Communications), which went out and raised the money.
All that's been done by Universal is getting the prints and ads and
releasing it. They weren't dying to make this film. But no, of
course, they'll try to take all the credit for it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Denzel Washington's performance is intense. What did you do
to help spur him on?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I think it was through fear. I said, ``Denzel, you are
over 40, you've got to play a 28-, 29-year old fighter. I can't
help you. You're going to be alone in the center of the ring in a
pair of shorts and boxing shoes and gloves. You're naked. And
you've got to think about that. Are you right for this role? Do you
have the rage?'' I challenged him a little bit. He lost 44 pounds.
He went into training for six months. He boxed two hours every day,
five days a week, sometimes six. By the time we started that
picture he was unbelievable. And I got him together with Rubin. And
then things started to happen. It was just exciting stuff. He had
it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: All the boxing sequences are in black and white. And the
extras surrounding the ring had such classic '60s faces. How did
you manage such detail?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ohhh, yeah. That was all shot in, believe it or not, Toronto.
I got all these actors. Talked to a lot of actors and got them to
play the people around the ring right where you can really see all
their faces. I tried to get some really interesting actors to play
roles and then I'd say, ``All right, you're the radio announcer.''
And then I thank Roger Deakins (the cinematographer for ``Fargo''
and ``Kundun''). He's just brilliant. This guy operates every shot.
So he's not only lighting, he's operating, which is really
difficult. But he gets it. You feel like you're joined at the hip.
It was great. I hope he gets a nomination. He deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The scene where Denzel spends 90 days in solitary confinement
should have been pretty challenging. He's hallucinating and seeing
and talking with several parts of himself.
</P>
<P>
   A: That was the most difficult and challenging artistic thing.
We were trying to literally conceive it where you've got a guy
talking to himself and then you see the person he's talking about.
You have to see the alter ego. And then he sees himself as a child.
And these obviously are voices in his head. I didn't want to do
``The Snake Pit,'' which is just voices. That's kind of boring. I
was trying to use the camera to establish that he thought someone
else was there and then the next time you cut he's that other
character talking and now he's talking back here. I think we caught
that kind of mental anguish.
</P>
<P>
   I went and sat in a cell in solitary and I'll tell you
something. I wouldn't last one night. I don't know how anyone could
do 90 days without totally freaking out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Years ago you left North America and went to live in Europe
for a while. What went wrong here?
</P>
<P>
   A: I remember marching and getting my head beat up and those
things in the '60s. I left the country in 1970 totally
disillusioned about America. I had been here 10 years making movies
in Hollywood and television in New York. And I left. God, Nixon was
president, Reagan was governor, the war in Vietnam. Forget it. You
know, Martin Luther King's funeral. I was working on Bobby
Kennedy's campaign. I was working with Melina Mercouri, and we were
supposed to meet him. ... I was so disillusioned, I was so empty
and I was so defeated. I had lost my faith in the American dream, I
guess. So I went to Europe for the next 10 years. I made
``Fiddler,'' ``Jesus Christ Superstar,'' ``Rollerball,'' all those
pictures I made in Europe and lived in Europe and took my family.
And then I got over it. Because when you start to lose your sense
of humor you're in big trouble. It wasn't the American people I was
angry at, it was the times and the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
