<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9862 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GAMESHOWS-TIMELINE07-     01-07 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMESHOWS-TIMELINE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The rise, fall and rise of a celebrated tv genre
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  June 20, 1946: The Dumont Network debuts ``Cash and Carry,''
the first TV game show series.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Feb. 2, 1950: ``What's My Line?'' debuts on CBS, running in
prime time until 1967.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 26, 1956: ``The Price Is Right'' debuts on CBS. Through
several time, network and host
</P>
<P>
   switches, it's still on the air.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 28, 1956: Charles Van Doren makes his first appearance in
the isolation booth on NBC's ``Twenty-One.'' He is later at the
center of the quiz-show scandal and is publicly humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1958: The game show is the most popular genre in television;
23 of them air in prime time, and during one week, eight of the Top
10 programs are quizzes. Allegations that some shows are fixed lead
to congressional hearings. Eventually, most game shows are canceled
in the backlash.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 30, 1963: ``Let's Make a Deal'' debuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  March 30, 1964: ``Jeopardy!'' debuts as an NBC daytime quiz
show, with Art Fleming as host, Don Pardo as announcer. The first
``Final Jeopardy'' ever: (Famous Quotes) ```Good night, sweet
prince' was said to him.'' (Who is Hamlet?) The daytime version
runs through 1975.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 17, 1966: ``Hollywood Squares'' debuts, with Peter
Marshall as host. Paul Lynde does not become a regular until 1968.
The original version ends in 1981, but in 1997, a new syndicated
version debuts with Whoopi Goldberg in the center square.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jan. 6, 1975: ``Wheel of Fortune'' debuts with host Chuck
Woolery and hostess Susan Stafford. Pat Sajak becomes host in 1981,
Vanna White replaces Stafford in 1982, and by the '90s, numerous
international versions make it one of the most popular shows in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 14, 1976: ``The Gong Show'' debuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  September 1984: The new syndicated version of ``Jeopardy!''
debuts, with host Alex Trebek.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aug. 16, 1999: ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' debuts in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  January 2000: Sparked by the success of ``Millionaire,'' a
second age of game shows begins, with four in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   _Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
