r e BC-KING-CONCERT09-COX     01-07 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-CONCERT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King legacy resonates with musical tribute
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Symphony Orchestra's annual concert in
honor of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday is ``the
biggest thing we do every year,'' said Mark Mobley, producer for
National Public Radio's ``Performance Today.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the eighth year that the King tribute concert has been
broadcast live by NPR, according to the ASO. With the support of
the Robert W. Woodruff Foundation, the ASO and regular guests such
as the Morehouse College Glee Club and Wendell P. Whalum Community
Chorus are heard across the country.
</P>
<P>
   NPR's participation also helps draw notable guest artists. This
year, actress S. Epatha Merkerson (``Law &AMP; Order'') will narrate
Aaron Copland's ``Lincoln Portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   All the works on the program, which will be conducted by Andre
Raphel Smith of the Philadelphia Orchestra, ``have a resonance and
a meaning to the legacy'' of King, Mobley said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Lincoln Portrait,'' for instance, has multiple
significance. The year 2000 is the centennial of the birth of
composer Copland, to whom tributes are being paid by musical
organizations across the country. A passionate advocate of civil
rights, Copland conducted a performance of the ``Lincoln Portrait''
with Coretta Scott King as narrator. Mrs. King plans to attend
Friday's concert in the Martin Luther King Jr. International Chapel
at Morehouse College.
</P>
<P>
   Because the concert coincides with the first anniversary of
Robert Shaw's death, it will open with Brahms' ``Tragic Overture,''
which Shaw led at one of the first King tribute concerts. And the
program includes several of Shaw and Alice Parker's arrangements of
spirituals, including ``I Got Shoes'' and ``My God Is a Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the Morehouse College Glee Club goes back to
Shaw's first years in Atlanta, when he heard this group led by
Whalum. The glee club and the Wendell P. Whalum Community Chorus
are now led by David Morrow, while Spelman's glee club is directed
by Kevin Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The program includes the ``Negro Folk Symphony'' of the
African-American composer William Dawson, who was born in Atlanta,
and two spirituals, ``Ain't That Good News?'' and ``I Want to Be
Ready,'' arranged by Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   African-American composer James P. Johnson, whose work was
spotlighted by the ASO under guest conductor Marin Alsop last
summer, also appears on the program: ``Drums,'' which begins with a
timpani solo for the ASO's Mark Yancich.
</P>
<P>
   The concert ends with the traditional singing of the ``Negro
national anthem,'' ``Lift Ev'ry Voice and Sing,'' also by Johnson
and arranged by Nathan Carter of Morgan State University in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   A King Celebration Concert
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, Andre Raphel Smith, conductor, with
Morehouse and Spelman
</P>
<P>
   College glee clubs and Wendell P. Whalum Community Chorus. S.
Epatha Merkerson, narrator.
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Thursday-Friday. $20, $5 seniors/students. Martin Luther
King Jr. International Chapel, Morehouse College, 830 Westview
Drive S.W. 404-733-5000.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
