<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MILLER09-COX     01-07 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arthur Miller: A dramatist for the ages
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the many pleasures in tonight's Showtime presentation of
``Death of a Salesman,'' there is an unexpected one. It's simply a
glimpse of the playwright, Arthur Miller, sitting in the audience
of Broadway's Eugene O'Neill Theatre. He looks as sturdy and
craggy-handsome as ever at 84, gazing toward the stage as the house
lights dim and the hubbub is hushed, waiting for his masterpiece to
once again hold 1,000 breathing witnesses in its thrall.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's a presence, all right, this greatest of living
playwrights. Unlike O'Neill, who died when appreciation for his
work was at low ebb, or Tennessee Williams, whose struggle to
retrieve past glories were as sad as his own characters, Miller
weathered shifting winds of fashion. He emerged on the other side
as a dramatist for the ages. The 1990s have seen a fine film of
``The Crucible,'' his 1953 classic about the Salem, Mass., witch
trials; a powerful New York revival of ``A View From the Bridge'';
and successful London productions of newer plays not well-received
in his home country. Miller's ``The Price,'' one of the better
American dramas of the 1960s, is being revived on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's 50th anniversary Broadway production of the Pulitzer
Prize-winning ``Salesman'' was doubly joyous (if that term can
apply to a tale so shatteringly sad) because the playwright was
interviewed, honored, so thoroughly there.
</P>
<P>
   Dustin Hoffman, who played Willy Loman on Broadway in 1984, once
said that Miller ``looks like a California redwood and talks like a
New York taxi driver.'' Miller talked from his Connecticut home
recently, with that image and sound in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At the Broadway revival, I heard people sobbing. There's no
question that ``Salesman'' has lost none of its power. But do
people react to it differently today than they did 50 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: I keep hearing how people are surprised at how contemporary
the play is. I'm very pleased about that. Now, the Robert Falls
production stays true to the original period of the '40s, so there
must be something inside these relationships, between the lines,
that speaks to today. Shakespeare, when he's done well, is the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In 1949, communism was the hot-button topic, so ``Salesman''
was seen as a critique of capitalism gone wrong. Perhaps today
those issues are more in the background, and it's the family
relationships _ father and sons, wife and husband _ that grab
people by the throat?
</P>
<P>
   A: My plays are always involved with society, but I'm writing
about people, too, and it's clear over the years that audiences
understand them and care about them. The political landscape
changes, the issues change, but the people are still there. People
don't really change that much.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We see Willy Loman being crushed under a system, or his
delusions about it. And yet I talked to the daughter of a
successful developer who was shattered by the play because, she
said, ``That's my father up there.''
</P>
<P>
   A: I get that all the time _ it's amazing to me. Or maybe I
shouldn't be amazed because as I said, there are qualities and
dreams that all people share. It hardly matters what level of
society you're at to find some part of yourself in the Loman
family.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You wrote once about how your Uncle Manny walked up to you,
during the original run of ``Salesman,'' and picked up exactly
where he left off bragging about his son, years before, just like
Willy does to the neighbor boy, Bernard. Do you think he knew he
was the model for Willy?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Laughing.) No, not for a minute. But then, Willy came from
so many places, I don't think people in my family recognized him as
my uncle, either.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've had an incredible range of great actors play Willy,
haven't you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it's not a question of who's better but how each gave
his distinctive stamp. George Scott is so different from Hoffman,
for example. (Brian) Dennehy has a heroic quality that I like,
similar to Lee Cobb. When those guys go down, it's a very big tree.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And for once the praise for the Linda Loman _ Elizabeth Franz
_ is as high as it is for the Willy.
</P>
<P>
   A: Elizabeth attacked the role quite differently _ with a
wonderful outrage _ than other Lindas, some of whom were seen as
timid. I never intended that. Linda is the only thing holding the
family together. She must have great strength.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you could see any of your other plays have a first-class
revival in New York, which would it be?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it was done beautifully in London not long ago, but I'd
have to say, ``After the Fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think some of the harsh reviews it got when it opened
had to do with the recent death of Marilyn Monroe (Miller's second
wife, 1956-61), so clearly the model for Maggie?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think everyone would have a clearer view of what the play's
really about, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You wrote in your 1987 autobiography, ``Timebends,'' that ``A
Streetcar Named Desire'' gave playwrights ``the courage to cry at
full throat.'' You began ``Salesman'' soon after. Here we are 17
years after Tennessee Williams' death, and you're still writing.
What's the secret to your stability?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it helps to have a great wife! (Inge Morath, his third,
since 1965). There's a lot of land out here for me to take care of,
so I can't afford to sit around. But you know, I've had dry spells
of three or five years when no good writing would come. Luckily,
I'm not a big drinker. Alcohol has done terrible damage, especially
to some of our greatest writers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
