<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9865 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SALESMAN09-COX     01-07 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALESMAN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tony winner comes alive on TV
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Showtime presentation of Arthur Miller's ``Death of a
Salesman'' is as close as you can get to the real-time thrill of
sitting in a Broadway theater, watching the 1999 production that
plunged into the drama's molten, fiery core.
</P>
<P>
   Know, too, that even the best tape of a live stage performance
may sabotage itself: For instance, when the camera zooms in to
capture ``innermost feelings'' that the actor is trying to project
to the back row. For seamless television, see the 1985 Dustin
Hoffman production that was rethought in a studio for CBS. But for
the unique excitement of being there at the creation, as it were,
see this Showtime thunderbolt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salesman'' unfolds in the life and splintered mind of Willy
Loman (Tony winner Brian Dennehy), a pusher of some unnamed gadget
but really a man who sells himself. No one's buying anymore. At 63,
his brag and bluster and gags worn thin, he's a used-up cog.
Crumbling around him is the Brooklyn household ``where we never
told the truth for 10 minutes,'' in the words of grown, raging son
Biff (Ron Eldard, replacing Broadway's superbly seething Kevin
Anderson). Biff is waking up, too, from useless training as a
braggart jock.
</P>
<P>
   We're riveted by Willy's preordained doom, if for no other
reason than to discover the terrible secret that came between
father and son years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The dreamlike sweep of director Robert Falls' turntable staging
_ dizzily gliding us in and out of the past, in and out of Willy's
head _ doesn't always translate through Kirk Browning's TV
production, and we miss the real, rafter-rattling presence of
Dennehy. Thanks to close-ups, though, we follow the story in his
eyes: darting and trembling like a child's, then opaque with
terror. When he shouts, ``The woods are burning, boys!'' you expect
to see the flames.
</P>
<P>
   Even stronger than she was onstage, if possible, is Elizabeth
Franz, in her portrayal of Willy's wife, Linda. (She, Falls and the
show also won Tonys.)
</P>
<P>
   For all its fireworks, what sets the Falls production above all
others (even the 1949 Lee J. Cobb/Mildred Dunnock original, judging
from a videotape) is the humor and immense thwarted tenderness
beneath the despair. The protective tenderness of Linda for Willy,
Willy for Biff _ indeed everyone in the family, including clueless
son Happy (Ted Koch), for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's genius is elevating these characters to American
archetypes while keeping them so plainly, movingly human.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting cast is also splendid. It may be no coincidence
that Richard Thompson as Bernard, the nerdy neighbor boy, looks
startlingly like the young Miller. In the real-life story behind
``Salesman,'' Miller was indeed the gawky visitor who studied hard,
mocked by his Uncle Manny and his two like-minded sons for lacking
the muscle and charm to capture the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   When the astonished Willy meets the grown Bernard, now handsome
and successful, those false tickets to the dream turn to ashes in
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Death of Salesman''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight (Sunday) on Showtime .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
