A9866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-AUBURN08-COX     01-07 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-AUBURN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auburn getting its act together
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Ah, how expectations have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn, which opens its Southeastern Conference season against
Georgia at 1 p.m. today, comes in with a 12-1 record and No. 4
national ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the most commonly heard question on the Plains is, ``What's
wrong with the Tigers?''
</P>
<P>
   After Auburn's amazing run last season, nothing but winning _
and winning big _ is going to do this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers lost one starter from last year's 29-4 team that lost
in the second round of the NCAA Tournament to Final Four
participant Ohio State. And while Auburn has been winning this
season, it hasn't done so in the dominating fashion of a season
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's average margin of victory during the early, mostly
nonconference slate last year was nearly 30 points a game, with its
closest game being a 12-point victory over Florida. This season,
the Tigers already have struggled in four games, losing to Stanford
67-58 in the John Wooden Classic and squeaking by Florida State
(55-54), Penn (77-70), Southern Miss (56-50) and Virginia Tech
(73-63).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about it,'' coach Cliff Ellis said, referring to
the Tigers' victory margin. ``I guess everybody has different
opinions about it; I can't get caught up in all that. I don't even
know how many points we're averaging. I don't know how much we
averaged last year. That's for (the media) to keep up with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers have been indicating, however, that they are about to
get it going again. Several factors contributed to their
less-than-stellar performance in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   First has been the play of senior forward Chris Porter. A
preseason national player-of-the-year selection, Porter spent the
early part of the season trying to develop his outside shot.
</P>
<P>
   Many predicted the 6-7 forward would make the jump to the NBA
after last year's All-America season. But the knock on him was his
lack of range. Porter evidently set out to prove them wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Porter came out of the gate shooting 3-pointers, and he wasn't
making many of them. He came out of December with a .153 3-point
percentage (2 of 13). Included during that early stretch were some
un-Porter-like line scores: four points and four rebounds against
Penn, nine points and five rebounds against FSU and nine points and
seven rebounds against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early going, Chris probably stepped out there too
much,'' Ellis said. ``His game is from 12 to 15 feet, and he's done
better since he's come back in there. I'm sure he'd like to be a
great outside shooter, and it might make him a lottery pick. But
having him 18 to 25 feet from the basic is not the answer for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Since persuading Porter to come back into the lane, Porter's
average has risen from 12.2 to 13.5 and he's been the Tigers' top
scorer the past four games.
</P>
<P>
   Porter's perimeter experimentation briefly caused tension within
the team. Sophomore David Hamilton, who backs up Porter at power
forward, said after the Penn game, ``We don't need any more
7-for-20 shooting performances. Our inside guys need to play
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's return to the court has proved to be a settling
force. The 6-9 sophomore missed the first five games because of
academic suspension. Since returning, the Tigers are undefeated,
raised their shooting percentage from .369 to .470 and are
averaging 80.4 points per game, as opposed to 68.6. Most notably,
Porter's minutes dropped from 32 to 25 a game. Hamilton has
averaged 7.1 points and 4.6 rebounds during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn also has played a more challenging schedule this year,
although it lags well behind the ones played by Kentucky or even
Georgia. And opponents are much more focused on beating the Tigers,
given their lofty ranking and reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in as good of shape as we could be right now,''
said guard Scott Pohlman, a junior from Roswell. ``Teams are coming
in a lot more focused on us. We're not coming out and surprising
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia would be challenged enough against Auburn without its
depth problems. The Bulldogs found out Thursday they will be
without freshman guard Ezra Willliams, who was ruled ineligible.
Reserve forward Badi Oliver remains sidelined with a stress
fracture in his left foot, and junior center Robb Dryden, while
available, is limited by his injured left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Tigers will counter with a balanced group. No
Auburn player averages more than 28 minutes, 10 players average at
least 5.2 points a game, and its top five scorers are separated by
four points, with Porter high at 13.0 and Pohlman low at 9.0
</P>
<P>
   ``They're one of the best teams in our league,'' Georgia coach
Jim Harrick said. ``I'm interested in playing them and seeing how
we play. They've had back-to-back great years, and it could mean a
lot to our team to know we can play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
