<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9867 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CAVEMAN-REVIEW08-COX     01-07 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAVEMAN-REVIEW08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Caveman' a funny look at differences in genders
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You should see ``Defending the Caveman'' with someone you love.
After you get home, you can lock yourself in the bathroom to escape
that very person and get a little peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Becker's ``Caveman'' was the longest-running solo show in
Broadway history (more than 700 performances) when it closed in
1998 and went on the road. Becker's genial comparison of the
genders, besides being very, very funny, is so acutely observed
that he has performed for national conventions of marriage and
family therapists. He's a lot easier to take than ``Men Are From
Mars, Women Are From Venus'' and all the rest of those
war-between-the-sexes self-help tomes.
</P>
<P>
   Becker's thesis is that our dominant traits go back to
prehistoric times: Men are hunters, women are gatherers. ``We have
different customs,'' he explains, and goes through a long list of
behaviors to prove it. For instance: Man, the hunter, focuses on
one object, to the exclusion of all else, until he hunts it down
and kills it. Woman, by contrast, accumulates information, enjoying
multiple sensations, colors, tastes, smells, as she gathers up
diverse materials and puts them in her basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words: shopping!'' Becker says, beaming. Man, by
contrast, shops by zeroing in on the one thing he needs (in this
case, a shirt), symbolically kills it and takes it home in a bag,
relieved to get the whole shopping thing out of the way until the
next time he needs a shirt.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with conversation. Women gather information and
dispense it with equal delight; men keep their interchanges simple
and direct. Where a woman might greet a friend she hasn't seen for
a long time by hugging her and telling her how good she looks and
describe from top to toe what things are the same and what are
different about her and wonder why it's been so long since they've
gotten together, a man will accomplish the same thing by eyeing his
buddy's car and saying: ``Still driving that piece of junk?''
</P>
<P>
   Since going on the road, Becker has gussied up the show with a
video prologue: unnecessary but inoffensive. He's also performed it
enough that his diction has gotten sludgy and his timing
perfunctory. Some of the lines are frankly unintelligible. Of
course, the venue is no help. This small-scale show was not
designed for the cavernous Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But his large, galumphing persona is still endearing and his
insights right on the money. Across the aisle from me were a
typical couple. The man guffawed and slapped his knees when Becker
described men and hugged his significant other at the descriptions
of women. So did she, except vice versa. That's how ``Defending the
Caveman'' strikes all us Fred and Wilma Flintstones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defending the Caveman''
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Becker. 4 and 8 p.m. today; 3 and 7 p.m. Sunday.
$30.50-$38.50. Fox Theatre, 660 Peachtree St. N.E., Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   404-817-8700.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Men are men, women are women, and Rob Becker knows
why.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
