<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9868 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CHARLOTTE-ARTS09-COX     01-07 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLOTTE-ARTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A savvy corporate partnership has the North Carolina city
banking on cultural investment to bring even more vitality to an
urban core on the mend
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlotte _ Less than 10 years ago, North Tryon Street, a
stretch of the main downtown artery in North Carolina's largest
city, was a drag. Vacant buildings and parking lots testified to
the sorry state of America's center cities. It was, recalls
Asheville gallery owner John Cram, ``the perfect example of
sterility.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, North Tryon is home to monumental new office towers.
Fancy lobbies and chic restaurants beckon from wide promenades.
There's little retail yet, but with almost 8,000 people living in
the vicinity, the stage is set.
</P>
<P>
   An example of the nationwide resurgence of downtowns? Yes, but
with a twist. Through the leadership of Charlotte's corporate
community, art is blooming on this 11-block stretch, right along
with commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of eight months, two new major arts institutions
have taken root ``Uptown'' (as Charlotte calls it) and preserved
some of the city's architectural history in the process.
</P>
<P>
   An old department store now houses the Mint Museum of Craft +
Design, one of a select few institutions in the country devoted to
those subjects.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks down the street is the Tryon Center for Visual Art,
a fire-damaged Gothic Revival stone church transformed into an
artists' community. It provides studios for visiting and local
artists as well as a public gallery.
</P>
<P>
   While these unusual facilities give Charlotte a higher profile
on the national scene, their contribution to their neighborhood is,
in a way, more far-reaching. The pair adds critical mass to
Charlotte's designated arts and culture district. It draws
visitors, making the area more attractive to commercial and
residential development.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more arts development as well: The Mint Museum
proper, now located in a residential suburb, and the Light Factory,
a nonprofit exhibition space for photography, film and video, are
considering moving intown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so turned around, it's flabbergasting,'' says Cram, who
owns three galleries in Asheville. ``And it's thanks to Hugh McColl
(chief executive officer of Bank of America). He single-handedly
had a vision and backed it up with the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   McColl has been involved in Charlotte's urban planning team
efforts since the '60s. His personal interest in art, his
understanding of the role art can play in community development and
his company's stake in the health of its home base has shaped
Charlotte's city center.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the company headquarters, designed by Cesar Pelli with
a monumental lobby fresco by local arist Ben Long, opened at North
Tryon and Trade streets. When, in 1998, the bank built a parking
deck a few blocks away, it made it a destination by putting retail
on the ground floor and turning the building into an interactive
sound and light artwork.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, McColl offered the old Montaldo's department store,
which his bank owned, to the Mint Museum to persuade them to come
downtown. The bank funded the renovation of the store to house the
Mint Museum of Craft + Design, the Bank of America gallery and
space for expansion, which is now leased. McColl and a business
associate raised $11 million to endow both downtown institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of his efforts, the American Craft Council gave
McColl its Aileen Osborn Webb Award in November. (Webb founded and
underwrote the council.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood out in the field for doing something for crafts,''
says ACC director Jeffrey Larris.
</P>
<P>
   It was McColl's idea to turn the 1.1-acre Associate Reformed
Presbyterian Church property, which the bank had purchased in 1995,
into an artists' colony. The bank underwrote the $7 million
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The artists' colony will be a unique addition to our growing
arts community,'' McColl said when the Tryon Center plan was
announced in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlotte will position itself as a leader of arts in the
Southeast. It will raise the quality of art we have access to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America employees are actively involved in the workings
of these and other arts institutions. Jim Palermo, executive vice
president, management services, chairs the Arts and Science
Council, which funnels city, county and corporate money to
Charlotte's nonprofit institutions. Senior vice president Barbara
Spradling is Tryon Center's board chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the arts organizations and the bank are pretty tight.
Some find the relationship a little close for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about centralized power and decision-making,'' says
Paul Sires, an artist who opened a pioneer gallery on North
Davidson Street, what he calls the ``unfunded'' part of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would a board member stand up to his corporation if there was
a disagreement?''
</P>
<P>
   Gallery owner Dot Hodges raises the issue of corporate
propriety, which tends to smooth the healthily rough edges of art
into a safe blandness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that, in trying to please everyone, you don't
necessarily get the strongest art,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even if corporate patrons exert no pressure, there is the
potential for self-censorship to avoid offense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the active corporate support has served the arts, and
downtown Charlotte, extraordinarily well. When it comes to
assessing the impact of McColl and the Bank of America, Hodges
says, ``Basically, most people are grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Arts by the numbers
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Metro population: 1,383,080.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Art museums: Mint Museum of Art, Mint Museum of Craft +
Design.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Art spaces: 16 commercial galleries and nonprofit venues
Uptown (Charlotte's downtown) and in NoDa (the area around North
Davidson Street), and others spread throughout town, including the
Light Factory, a nonprofit devoted to photography, film and video.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other museums: Discovery Place, an interactive science and
technology museum; Museum of the New South, a history museum.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Marketing inspiration: The first 90 minutes of parking are
free at the Seventh Street Station deck in the arts and culture
district.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the horizon: Next up for the district is a children's
theater and library.
</P>
<P>
   _Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
