r l BC-MLK-SUMMIT08-COX     01-07 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-SUMMIT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Serving others is essence of King Holiday'
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dante Hudson's life was changed by a service project.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Hudson was a senior at Morehouse College, trying
to decide whether he should go to law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really wanted to do was work with inner-city
children,'' says Hudson, 23, a resident of Austell.
</P>
<P>
   By chance, Hudson received a pamphlet in the mail, addressed to
someone else, advertising the Martin Luther King Jr. Service
Summit, an annual day of service sponsored by Hands on Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, he attended a program held in conjunction with the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   At the workshop, Hudson recalls a principal in the Atlanta
Public Schools system saying that many of her students were
ill-equipped to enter the work force, that they wouldn't even have
the skills to work at a fast-food restaurant. ``That threw me for a
loop and fueled my passion for service,'' Hudson says.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the next day _ the King Holiday _ working on a service
project and found the experience so rewarding that he joined Hands
on Atlanta's Americorps program. He spent the next nine months as a
volunteer at Thomasville Heights Elementary School, working with
tutoring and enrichment programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exactly what I wanted to do,'' Hudson says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he later joined the professional staff of Hands on
Atlanta as a community projects coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's annual MLK Service Summit _ it's called
``Remember! Celebrate! Act!'' _ Hudson will coordinate a drive to
collect blankets for homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serving others is the essence of the King Holiday,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As in past years, the seventh annual summit spans two days, with
a day of lectures and workshops followed by a day of service. The
event is co-sponsored by the King Center.
</P>
<P>
   The workshops, held Jan. 16 from 1 to 8:30 p.m. at the Georgia
State University Student Center (Gilmer Street and Piedmont
Avenue), will explore King's teachings of nonviolent social change
and how they can enable citizens to strengthen their communities.
Topics include reflections on King's ``I Have a Dream'' speech from
firsthand observers, women in the civil rights movement, and
volunteerism as a bridge toward diversity. Coretta Scott King is
expected to give a brief address at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 17 day of service will include about 30 projects across
metro Atlanta, such as feeding the homeless, tutoring kids, working
with refugee children, renovating homes and maintaining the grounds
at the MLK Jr. National Historic Site. About 1,000 volunteers are
expected to participate.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year, Regina Dobson of Stone Mountain will
coordinate a project painting and repairing houses of senior
citizens in Atlanta's Dixie Homes community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. King stood for bringing people of all races and
backgrounds together for the common good, and on this project
people of all backgrounds will work together shoulder to
shoulder,'' says Dobson.
</P>
<P>
   She adds that the project is in answer to a question once asked
by King _ ``a persistent and urgent question,'' King said. ``What
are you doing for others?''
</P>
<P>
   KING SERVICE SUMMIT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cost: Admission to the King Service Summit is $15 plus a
canned good. The cash helps defray costs of presenting the summit,
while the canned goods benefit the Atlanta Community Food Bank's
efforts to feed the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Registration: Begins Jan. 16 at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: To find a complete list of activities, log onto
the Web site handsonatlanta.org/mlk or call 404-872-2252, Ext.
2035. Derrick Henry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
