<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PRINCE-ART-NYT     01-07 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRINCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN FAMILY ASSERTS ITS RIGHTS IN RUINS OF AN ANCESTRAL ESTATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 was sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALABINO, Russia _ The prince was at the kitchen table, teaching
his daughter Katya, 13, how to roll out dough for a Christmas pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep it round,'' Prince Yevgeny Meshchersky barked as he
swiveled over to the wood-burning stove to check potatoes on boil.
``Press hard, harder.''
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Lyudmila, away at work on Russia's Christmas
holiday, Meshchersky, 49, was in charge of preparing the
traditional meal at his ancestral home _ a badly battered
18th-century gatehouse that stands by the ruins of a palace, on the
edge of an overgrown park. All are part of a 64-acre estate where,
for three years now, he has been squatting in a campaign to reclaim
it as his own.
</P>
<P>
   The inside of his house looks much like the outside, battered by
a century that has been exceptionally cruel to the Meshcherskys,
like so many other aristocratic families that remained in Russia
after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution. The floorboards tilt
dangerously; the ceiling is full of holes. The windows are covered
in plastic to keep in warmth provided by the stove and a fireplace
that the prince himself pried loose from a wall of Soviet-era
bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, on the Christmas holiday celebrated by the Russian
Orthodox Church according to the Julian calendar, the family was
getting ready to receive guests with family names and titles like
theirs, which go far back in Russian history but which, until
recently, were hushed up and played down in a proletarian state.
</P>
<P>
   For the occasion, the shabby kitchen-living room had acquired a
faint holiday glow: a scrawny tree propped on the grand piano,
cheap gold-colored garlands hanging from the gaps in the ceiling,
and a cardboard Father Frost, made by one of Meshchersky's four
children, propped up against a windowpane.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly the stuff of a 19th-century Russian novel. But in some
ways, the story of Meshchersky and his Sisyphus-like attempt to
reclaim his heritage is a tale that fits this turn-of-the-century
Russia, where many people are wondering now _ as others did 100
years ago _ which way the country is heading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to make the Russian state live according to the
law,'' said Meshchersky, an unassuming man with wire-rim glasses
and a graying goatee. ``Maybe it is a small step, but I want it to
be a precedent, because once Russia, as a state, starts abiding by
its laws, then it will no longer be a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Meshchersky, an engineer, returned to Russia from Ukraine in
1996, looking to settle on his family's former estate in this
village, 35 miles south of Moscow. The family palace, built in
1775, had been blown up by the Communists to provide rubble for a
nearby road and was a hollow shell, a gigantic folly of broken
columns and crumbling bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the revolution, the Meshchersky palace was looted of
a priceless art collection, which included paintings by Botticelli
and Velazquez. In the 1930s, it was turned into a holding camp for
political prisoners arrested by Stalin's secret police. After World
War II, the estate was abandoned. The ruins were declared a
national monument in 1964, but nothing was done to stop the
continuing decay or looting of the buildings that remained.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the returning prince, emboldened by Russia's democratic
changes and by a new constitution that for the first time
guaranteed the right to own and inherit property. Although his
wife, according to several reports, was less than enthusiastic, he
moved his family into one of four gatehouses that stand at the
corners of the ruined palace, with no water, no plumbing, no
electricity and no heat.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has hooked up the electricity and installed a
plumbing system. For water, he still goes to a nearby spring, and
heat still comes from firewood culled from the forest at the back
of the house. But Meshchersky has a dream, for which he is willing,
as some Russian commentators have noted, to make his family live
like refugees.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the authorities have made no effort to evict the
Meshcherskys. But they have also done nothing to give the prince
the estate or a mansion in St. Petersburg that he also claims.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, unlike post-communist countries in Central Europe, has
no law providing for the restitution of property seized by the
state, but that has not deterred Meshchersky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need a law on restitution,'' he said. ``I have Article
35 of the Russian Constitution, which guarantees my right to own
and inherit property.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Russian courts have turned a deaf ear to Meshchersky's
quest, and he is now pursuing his case in the European Court of
Human Rights in Strasbourg, France. At stake, he says, are two
principles: property and law. ``Why should I give up the property
of my ancestors?'' he asked. ``Why should I give everything up to
bandits and thieves, which is what Russia's new rich are, people
who stole everything they have? This was my family's property; we
didn't steal it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Meshchersky family's return to Alabino _ now formally
controlled by the state Committee of Culture _ has been tolerated
by the Russian government and local authorities. Meshchersky said
the administration of former President Boris Yeltsin had given de
facto recognition of his right to ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But without judicial recognition, the Meshcherskys are not
owners but squatters. And although his neighbors say they have good
relations with the prince, Meshchersky says he feels hostility from
local Communist officials and from neighbors who resent him for
stopping a thriving business: the looting of materials from the
ruins on the estate.
</P>
<P>
   His story has been told in the Russian news media, and was
recently made into a documentary film, ``Prince,'' by the noted
filmmaker Marina Goldovskaya. But so far, the publicity has not
given him the legal recognition he seeks nor the money he needs to
turn his estate into what he calls a historical preserve, where
tourists would be able to see for themselves the ravages that
communism brought upon Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
