u a BC-ABC-MINORITIES-NYT &LR;      01-07 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABC-MINORITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING NBC'S LEAD, ABC OUTLINES MINORITY HIRING PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two days after NBC announced an agreement with the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People intended
to increase minority hiring, ABC Friday announced its own
``statement of understanding'' with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   But while NAACP president Kweisi Mfume appeared to be making
progress with the networks, he was also moving to assuage a
coalition of minorities that said he was not fulfilling his promise
to represent their interests.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume and ABC president Pat Fili-Krushel released a statement
that outlined steps similar to those NBC announced Wednesday. NBC
said it would provide internships and scholarship programs and
promised to increase its purchases from minority-owned suppliers
and to pay for a minority writer to be added to the staff of every
new network show that went into a second year of production.
</P>
<P>
   ABC said it intended ``to increase opportunities for qualified
people of color in the network television industry'' both in front
of and behind the camera, and underscored its existing diversity
plans, including mentoring programs and programs to encourage
minority writers. Each division of the network will be required to
interview minority candidates for open jobs and to offer at least
one for-credit minority internship per year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, all ABC employees will be required to take part in
a diversity training program.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fili-Krushel said at a news conference Friday that the
statement represented ``ABC's diversity objectives and the NAACP's
endorsement of those objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   An ABC executive said Ms. Fili-Krushel was careful not to imply
that the other members of the coalition had endorsed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of those other groups criticized Mfume on Friday,
saying he had neglected their specific concerns in negotiating the
agreement with NBC. Esteban Torres, the spokesman for the National
Hispanic Media Coalition and a former Democratic congressman from
California, said that agreement did not address issues specific to
Hispanics. Torres said he had not yet seen the ABC statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the points didn't exactly speak to the West Coast
initiative that we and Japanese-American groups had been seeking,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Torres pointed out that the agreement with NBC did not provide
for the appointment of a vice president for diversity who would
report directly to Bob Wright, the network's president, although
``that was one of our specific demands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbeknownst to us,'' Torres said, `` Mfume went to a press
conference with NBC to address the issues, and we were not invited.
We thought we were working as a coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Skyhawk, the president of American Indians in Film and
Television, and Norman Mineta, the director of the Asian Pacific
American Coalition, also criticized Mfume.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume tried to soothe feelings Friday evening by speaking with
the members of the coalition in a conference call.
</P>
<P>
   ``These agreements are first steps in a very long and sometimes
difficult process to create real and meaningful opportunities for
men and women of color in network television,'' he said. ``But they
should only be seen as first steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Mfume said the leaders of the coalition had set up guidelines to
prevent future misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that each quarter of the coalition is
working toward the same goal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Wright of NBC will fly to California to meet with
the coalition's leaders. At that time, Mfume said, the coalition
will make a joint statement ``to underscore our solidarity and our
commitment to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreements come six months after Mfume criticized the
networks, calling their programming ``a virtual whitewash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
