<HEADER>
A9875 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-MALCOLM08-COX     01-07 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MALCOLM08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dysfunctional family at home in `Malcolm'
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's something you haven't seen lately: a Fox comedy good
enough not to be animated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm in the Middle'' is a sweetly outrageous sitcom that
plays like a live-action mutation of ``The Simpsons,'' which it
follows at 8:30 Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowed (loosely, we hope) from the childhood of creator
Linwood Boomer, it centers on a middle-class family with four boys,
including third son Malcolm (Frankie Muniz), a boy genius who just
wants to be normal.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm's wide, young-man's head, balancing like a candy apple
atop his narrow, 11-year-old shoulders, suggests a wry wisdom
beyond his years. It's through his eyes and raspy asides (which
sound a lot like young Kevin's in ``The Wonder Years'') that we
observe the rest of this perfectly functioning dysfunctional
family.
</P>
<P>
   There's oldest brother Francis (Christopher Kennedy), who's teen
antics have landed him in military school; next oldest brother
Reese (Justin Berfield), who loves to pick on the picked-upon; and
youngest brother Dewey (Erik Per Sullivan), a sour-smelling
first-grader who sometimes finds himself tied up by his brothers
and hung from a bedroom door.
</P>
<P>
   The brood is shepherded as best it can be by a pair of
pre-self-esteem parents: bawdy, no-nonsense Lois (Jane Kaczmarek)
and yeah-whatever Hal (Bryan Cranston), whose self-involved
befuddlement is an echo of the late Phil Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   Each family member seems so wrong for the other that it all adds
up to ... family. On the surface, life unfolds like outtakes of
what couldn't be shown on ``Leave It to Beaver.'' It's a dead-on
caricature of the chaos that lurks inside every full house: No room
is ever picked up, the front lawn is never tended. And there is
never time to take anything too personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make me so mad sometimes I just want to break your neck!''
Lois shouts over the phone to Francis, who's up to no good at
school, a thousand miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Two beats later, Lois adds before hanging up, ``Did you get the
cookies I sent you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Francis says, warming at the memory. ``They were
great.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how unbundled family life gets, it's always saved by
the warmth the show captures of a clan that loves as hard as it
fights.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's pilot might be an unfortunate introduction for some. It
overdoes the Fox tendency to shock viewers to attention: It opens
with Lois in the kitchen shaving the body of a naked,
newspaper-reading Hal, and later signals its anything's-game
approach with a series of ``cripple'' jokes.
</P>
<P>
   It overplays a hand it doesn't have to. But stick with it. By
the next two episodes, without being one inch less outrageous,
``Malcolm in the Middle'' becomes this midseason's one real delight
_ a welcome, even welcoming, winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm in the Middle''
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m. Sunday on Fox (7199).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: News services
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
