<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES IN FAVOR OF TEXAS PUBLIC SCHOOL TEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a victory for state education leaders, a
federal judge in San Antonio ruled Friday that the test all Texas
public school students must take to graduate ``is not perfect,''
but also does not violate the rights of minority students.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Edward Prado's ruling in favor of the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills acknowledged the high numbers of
minority students who have failed to pass the test. But the judge
said the state had demonstrated the need for such a test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Prado has given this state and its children a great
victory today,'' said Texas Education Commissioner Jim Nelson in
Austin. ``This ruling vindicates the Texas testing program, which
is considered to be one of the model testing programs in the
nation.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The case is considered to be the most significant challenge to
high-stakes standardized testing to reach the federal courts in the
past two decades. The outcome was being watched by education
leaders in 20 other states with high school exit exams.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also has particular significance for Gov. George W.
Bush, who has made education reform a cornerstone of his
administration and, in his GOP presidential bid, has promised to
link federal education funding to student testing. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I'm very pleased,'' Bush said while campaigning in South
Carolina. ``The federal court made the right decision in confirming
our strong accountability system. I've always advocated that strong
accountability is good for all children, and the court ruled that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The case _ presented in five weeks of testimony last fall _ also
bolsters a Bush initiative to crack down on social promotion,
Nelson said. Last year, the Legislature approved a plan that
requires TAAS scores in lower grades to be a major factor in
determining whether students are promoted to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   The political implications of the ruling apparently were not
lost on Prado, who said on the closing day of testimony last fall
that the case is ``probably the most challenging decision I've had
to make'' in 15 years on the bench. Prado, a Republican and a
Hispanic, was appointed to the bench in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to the TAAS test was filed in 1997 by the Mexican
American Legal Defense and Educational Fund on behalf of two
Hispanic rights groups and several minority students who were
denied diplomas after failing repeated attempts to pass the test.
</P>
<P>
   MALDEF claimed that civil rights and due process rights of
African-American, Hispanic and other minority students were
violated because they fail the test in disproportionately high
numbers. The organization sought to bar the test as a graduation
requirement and to retroactively award diplomas to an estimated
45,000 students denied diplomas only because they failed to pass
the exam.
</P>
<P>
   MALDEF lawyer Al Kauffman said the organization is ``profoundly
disappointed'' with Prado's decision and will consider whether to
appeal to the U.S. 5th Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minority students are the ones left holding the bag after this
opinion,'' Kauffman said. ``The judge agreed with the plaintiffs
that the test has a significant adverse impact on minority
students, yet he accepted the state's assurances that the test is
for the good of the educational system.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Prado ruled that the remedial programs offered to
students who fail the exit test and the eight chances they are
given to pass the test during high school were the saving grace for
the testing program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence that one of the goals of the test is to help
identify and eradicate educational disparities,'' Prado wrote in
his 33-page opinion. Getting an education that does not meet some
minimal standards, he added, is ``an adverse impact just as surely
as failure to receive a diploma.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge noted that while there is a significant gap in the
passing rates of minorities and whites, that gap is shrinking, and
``the lot of Texas' minority students, at least as demonstrated by
academic achievement, while far from perfect, is better than that
of minority students in other parts of the country and appears to
be getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   In conclusion, the judge wrote, ``It is not for this court to
determine whether Texas has chosen the best of all possible means
for achieving these goals. The system is not perfect, but the court
cannot say that it is unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston schools Superintendent Rod Paige, who testified during
the trial on behalf of the state, called it ``a great day for young
people in Texas. Our students can pass this examination, they are
passing this examination, and this is something that is going to
stabilize that and move us forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also was praised by Madison High School Principal
Walter Ervin. Last year at Madison, a Houston school that is 68
percent black and 30 percent Hispanic, not one senior was denied a
diploma for failing the TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we are going to try to prepare our youngsters to be able
to go out and do the things they are supposed to do in society,''
Ervin said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas began administering the TAAS exit exam as a high school
graduation requirement in 1990. Students must score 70 or higher on
each of three sections _ math, reading and writing _ to pass the
exit exam. Beginning in their sophomore years, they are given eight
chances to pass the test. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
