<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORTHODOX-LEADERS-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLY DAY FOR ORTHODOXY'S FLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2, NYT3 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ In a parade of patriarchs and presidents,
of mitered metropolitans and gray-suited prime ministers, religious
and civil leaders from throughout the Eastern Orthodox world filled
the fourth-century Church of the Nativity Friday for a Christmas
service that may have been the most inclusive Orthodox Christian
gathering of modern times.
</P>
<P>
   The service, in a church built over the cavern where Christian
tradition holds that Jesus was born, was the centerpiece of Eastern
Orthodox celebrations marking the 2,000th anniversary of Jesus'
birth. Orthodox Christians here observe Christmas on Jan. 7,
following the old Julian calendar also used by the churches of
Russia, Georgia and Serbia; most other Orthodox branches now
celebrate on Dec. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The service was as striking for its Byzantine glitter as for the
fact that it would have been impossible only 10 years ago. The
guests included political and church leaders from Russia and
Eastern European countries whose former Communist regimes were
ardent foes of religion.
</P>
<P>
   They included Boris Yeltsin, who came as the representative of
Russia despite his abrupt resignation one week ago. After cheerily
blowing kisses to the crowds outside as he entered the church,
Yeltsin left early, looking pale and perspiring. Persevering for
the three-hour service were leaders of Belarus, Moldova, Ukraine,
Georgia and Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Equally significant for the Orthodox faithful was the presence
in one church _ for the first time in centuries _ of the hierarchs
who head 15 major Eastern Christian churches. ``This is a rare,
historic event,'' said Archbishop Christodoulos of Greece.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 200 million followers worldwide, the Orthodox
churches have been divided along national, ethnic and sometimes
even liturgical lines. Two of the major powers of the Orthodox
Christian world _ Bartholomew I, the ecumenical patriarch of
Constantinople, and Aleksy II, the patriarch of Russia _ had never
both participated in a formal Orthodox assembly until a closed-door
synod of the 15 churches on Wednesday in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The somewhat unlikely host for the historic celebration was
Yasser Arafat, the Muslim head of the Palestinian Authority, which
governs Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   For Arafat, who has assiduously courted European Catholic
leaders, Friday's Orthodox service was yet another Christmas coup.
On Dec. 24, flanked by the prime ministers of Italy and Spain, the
Palestinian leader attended an internationally televised Roman
Catholic midnight mass here, furthering his efforts to present the
Palestinian Authority as a tolerant and responsible caretaker of
the many Christian holy sites in its domain. He is also ever
mindful of the small but affluent Palestinian Christian exile
communities in Europe and the Americas, which are potentially
important sources of investment and international political
support.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There has been some Islamic grumbling about Arafat's tactical
embrace of Christianity, a faith practiced by barely 2 percent of
the local Palestinian population. Some of the European leaders at
Friday's service are associated with what Muslims perceive as the
persecution of their co-religionists in Chechnya, Kosovo and
Bosnia-Herzegovina. But any such misgivings were deftly submerged
Thursday, when Arafat treated the visiting clerics and politicians
to the traditional ``iftar'' sundown meal of Ramadan, when
practicing Muslims break the daylight fast maintained during the
holy month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very pleased that Arafat is our host,'' said Milorad
Dodik, the prime minister of the Serbian enclave in Bosnia. ``This
is part of the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orthodox conclaves here and in Jerusalem this week were an
equally significant diplomatic achievement for the Greek patriarch
of Jerusalem, Diodoros I, who is accused by local churchgoers of
maintaining a deliberate distance from his Palestinian flock.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is profound anxiety and unhappiness about the lack of
attention of the patriarchate to their pastoral, religious and
human needs,'' said the Rev. Leonid Kishkovsky of the Orthodox
Church in America, an authority on inter-Orthodox matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican, by contrast, with its centralized structure and
well-financed religious orders, is viewed by the local Orthodox
laity ``with admiration and frustration,'' he said. ``Rome is
organized, whereas the Orthodox world is fragmented.''
</P>
<P>
   By most estimates, about half of the Palestinian Christian
community belongs to the Greek Orthodox church, down from perhaps
two-thirds a century ago. Roman Catholics remain the second-largest
local Christian group, now numbering about 30 percent, but have a
much larger relative presence in schools, hospitals and social
welfare services.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is still a strong historical attachment among Orthodox
Arabs to the patriarchate of Jerusalem, which has been a fixture of
the local religious landscape since the very beginning of organized
Christianity. ``It is the remaining presence on the ground of
Byzantium,'' Kishkovsky said.
</P>
<P>
   That ancient connection was proudly reinforced in Friday's
service, as local Greek clerics escorted the visiting patriarchs
past their church's surviving patches of Byzantine mosaics and the
subterranean chamber said to be the cave where Jesus was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in history that all the denominations are
together, respecting each others' traditions, and celebrating
Christmas together,'' said Torkom Manoogian, the Armenian Orthodox
Patriarch of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Armenian Christians, few in number but deeply rooted here,
have for theological and ethnic reasons never been part of the
wider Eastern Orthodox community. Yet their participation in
Friday's services _ and their welcoming embrace of the visiting
Orthodox bishops _ was seen as evidence of a new ecumenical spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would like to see as a Christian is a reconciliation
between the Greek Orthodox hierarchy and local Orthodox laity,''
said Bernard Sabellah, a Bethlehem University sociologist and a
practicing Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Palestinian Christians in the Holy Land, we do not want
divisions and exclusivity,'' Sabellah said. ``We want to be part of
the whole picture, of the whole mosaic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
