<HEADLINE>
KERREY MAY LEAVE SENATE FOR UNIVERSITY POST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Bob Kerrey, an influential Nebraska Democrat
and one of the party's brightest stars, is considering leaving the
Senate to become president of the New School University in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, 56, an unsuccessful candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 1992, decided just over a year ago not
to run for president this fall so he could focus on winning a third
six-year term in November. But the possibility of replacing
Jonathan F. Fanton, who headed the university in Greenwich Village
for 17 years before stepping down last fall, has captured the
senator's fancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy doing what I'm doing, but this offer
unexpectedly came my way,'' Kerrey told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   A university spokeswoman, Carmen Ashhurst, said: ``We have
several candidates. We have not discussed who the candidates are.''
</P>
<P>
   It is expected that Kerrey would decide before Nebraska's Feb.
18 deadline for incumbents to file for re-election.
</P>
</TEXT>
