<HEADER>
A9888 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FLA-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT     01-07 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA PASSES BILL TO SPEED PACE OF EXECUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SARA RIMER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida lawmakers made sweeping changes in
the way the death penalty is carried out, approving a bill on
Friday that they say will speed the appeals process so that death
row inmates can be executed more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The law parallels steps Congress took in 1996 to limit the
ability of state inmates to seek review in federal court, and is
patterned after a 1995 Texas law that greatly speeded the pace of
executions in that state.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush, who proposed and aggressively pushed for the
Florida bill, as his brother George W. Bush did in Texas as
governor of that state, said revising the appeals process is
intended to shorten the length between sentencing and execution to
five years, from an average of 14 years. His goals would be
achieved by tightening filing deadlines and limiting the number of
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an historic piece of legislation that will be much
more respectful of family members and victims of these heinous
crimes,'' the Florida governor said after the vote Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The law, he said, ``brings a semblance of justice to this very
complicated issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the death penalty said the Florida law,
combined with the federal action, would greatly impair the ability
of Florida's 366 death row inmates to assert their constitutional
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made one of the most precious rights in our system
habeas corpus, the ability to come back into court and say, `My
constitutional rights have been violated,''' said Elizabeth Semel,
director of the American Bar Association's Death Penalty
Representation Project in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's action in Tallahassee, she said, deepens concerns that
when it comes to habeas corpus for the state's death row inmates,
``We have made it so inaccessible that we risk losing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said of Florida's death row inmates, ``No one's rights are
being taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents complained that lawmakers were pressured into hastily
overhauling one of the most complicated and important pieces of the
criminal justice system in a two-and-a-half-day special legislative
session. Les Miller, the House Democratic leader, called the change
in the appeals process ``a reckless, rushed and risky piece of
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts around the country predicted that the changes
would be challenged on constitutional grounds, and that they could
ultimately result in more delays and a slower pace of executions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system has been tried out in Texas and has been shown to
be a colossal failure,'' said George Kendall, a staff lawyer with
the NAACP Legal Defense Fund in New York. ``in Texas, they haven't
been able to provide adequate legal representation. There isn't
serious review in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Spalding, legislative staff counsel for the American Civil
Liberties Union of Florida, said the lawmakers' action Friday
represented a sort of victory for Bush as well as for the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get to say they're tough on crime,'' Spalding said,
referring to Bush and the Legislature, ''and capital defense
lawyers have just been given lots of ammunition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an in-your-face challenge to the court,'' Spalding
added, referring to the Florida Supreme Court, which reviews all
capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would pattern the appeals process in Florida after
the one in Texas, where more people have been executed than in any
other state since the Supreme Court allowed the death penalty to
resume in 1976. As governor, George W. Bush has presided over the
executions of 111 men and one woman.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jeb Bush took office last January, one inmate has been
executed. The inmate, Allen Lee Davis, bled profusely when he was
electrocuted in July.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of his corpse posted on the Internet by the Florida
Supreme Court, showing Davis with a contorted face and a
blood-soaked shirt, contributed to a public outcry over Florida's
use of the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' was the latest in a series of botched executions that led
the U.S. Supreme Court to announce that it would review Florida's
use of the electric chair. Advised by legal experts that Florida's
death penalty was in jeopardy, Bush convened the special
legislative session. But he linked it to his plan to restrict
appeals, and that proposal was the dominating theme of the session.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Legislature voted overwhelmingly on Thursday to
make lethal injection the state's primary method of execution.
</P>
<P>
   The reform bill imposes what is known as a ``dual track''
system, which requires inmates to file their post-conviction
motions _ or habeas corpus review _ within six months of the day
they file their direct appeal. In many states, these motions are
not filed until the direct appeal is concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The post-conviction motion is the only legal means by which
evidence that was not presented at trial can be introduced in a
court. Legal experts who oppose the dual track system say that
having both reviews proceed simultaneously and quickly makes it
less likely that crucial evidence will be uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Florida Supreme Court accepts this, this is not a great
day for fairness and justice,'' said Kendall of the NAACP Legal
Defense Fund. ``This is going to guarantee the execution of the
innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters his proposal was fair. ``I want justice not
to be delayed unnecessarily,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Bob Butterworth, a Democrat, supported
the proposal. ``Working together we have struck a balance to carry
Florida's criminal justice system boldly into the next century,''
he told reporters after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973, 87 people on death row in America have been found to
be wrongly convicted, and released. The average time those inmates
spent on death row was seven-and-a-half years, Ms. Semel said.
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark case in Florida, Freddie Pitts and Wilbert Lee,
who were sentenced to death for the 1963 murder of two gas station
attendants in Florida's Panhandle, spent 12 years in prison _ more
than nine of them on death row _ before they were released and
given full, unconditional pardons by Gov. Reubin Askew after
another man confessed to the murders.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts, 55, who is now a contractor living in Miami, took the
floor here on the first day of the session to tell lawmakers he
would have been dead if the shortening of the appeals process had
been in effect years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida just voted themselves out of the twentieth century,''
he said Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
