<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS TEXAS EXAM DOES NOT DISCRIMINATE AGAINST MINORITY
STUDENTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A federal judge in San Antonio Friday rejected a
lawsuit that claimed an exam that Texas students must pass to
graduate from high school discriminated against minority students.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a blow to opponents of so-called high-stakes
standardized tests and a victory for Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential front-runner, who has hailed the improved
scores on the test during his tenure as evidence of his commitment
to education.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, Judge Edward C. Prado of U.S. District Court
ruled that while minority students had failed the exam at
disproportionately higher rates than whites, the test still met
constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   Prado said that the test, the Texas Assessment of Academic
Skills, known as TAAS, did not single out minority students, and
that the state administered it fairly, allowing students to take it
eight times, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Prado agreed with the plaintiffs that ``Texas minority students
have been, and to some extent continue to be, the victims of
educational inequality.'' But he said the plaintiffs could not
prove that minority students ``do not have a reasonable opportunity
to learn the material covered on the TAAS.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the plaintiffs did not prove that the negative
aspects of the test outweighed the positive, or suggest a better
alternative. ``The system is not perfect, but the court cannot say
that it is unconstitutional,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called the decision ``a victory for high standards and
strong accountability.'' He also noted that scores by minority
students, while lagging behind, had improved in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed by the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Educational Fund, which argued that test was discriminatory and
placed minority students at a disadvantage because they were more
likely to attend schools with fewer resources and where learning
was more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs said that since the tests began, minority dropout
rates had risen to 50 percent from 40 percent. The state has
challenged those figures and noted that the passing rate for
minority students on the exam had improved to 65 percent in 1999
from 40 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was any sort of endorsement of the test or
the way they use the test,'' the lead lawyer for the plaintiffs, Al
Kauffman, said of the decision. ``He said there were problems with
the test but that they were not so great as to make it
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of standardized graduation exams, often called
high-stakes tests, expressed disappointment with the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Linda McNeil, a Rice University education professor and a critic
of the test, called the ruling ``a very sad blow for equity and
civil rights in our state.''
</P>
<P>
   Monty Neill, executive director of FairTest, a testing reform
advocacy organization in Cambridge, Mass., contended that students
in states that did not use such tests actually performed better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it's bad news for advocates against the use of
high-stakes tests for individuals,'' Neill said of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   One of 19 states that requires a graduation test, Texas
initiated the test in 1990. Students begin taking the TAAS test in
the third grade. In the 10th grade, students are offered the ``exit
level'' TAAS test, which is divided into sections on reading, math
and writing. If a student fails the test, he or she may take it
seven more times to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for Bush, said the passing rate for
all grade levels of the test had improved to 78 percent in 1999
from 53 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Susana Navarro, executive director of the El Paso Cooperative
for Academic Excellence, a group that works with many poor,
Hispanic students, said her students had shown great improvement in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about holding everyone in the system accountable for
achievement on the part of all students,'' Ms. Navarro said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nelson, Texas' commissioner of education, said in a
statement that the ruling had ``given this state and its children a
great victory today.'' Nelson credited the standards established by
the test for the recent improvements made by students in national
assessment exams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
