<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-TEENDRIVING08-COX     01-07 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-TEENDRIVING08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia governor supports raising driving age to 17
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sixteen-year-olds looking to keep their driving
privileges won't get much comfort from Gov. Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   But legislators hoping to boost the driving age in Georgia to 17
may have found an ally.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the number of serious driving accidents involving
teen-agers, Barnes this week said he favors raising Georgia's
minimum driving age by one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic has increased so much and the dangers have increased
so much, there should be, in my view, some increase in the age of
driving,'' Barnes said. ``Seventeen is a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Mark Taylor also says he's ``very open'' to the
possibility of raising the driving age.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to do just that is awaiting Georgia lawmakers.
Lawmakers convene Monday, but Sen. Phil Gingrey (R-Marietta) has
prefiled a bill to raise the driving age to 17. It also would
require parents to sign sworn statements that they've given their
child 50 hours of driving instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is delivering babies,'' said Gingrey, an obstetrician.
``I don't want to see them die so young.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen driving restrictions adopted in Georgia have cut the number
of crashes since 1997, but national and state statistics show that
auto accidents are the leading cause of death among 15- to
20-year-olds and that one in five teen drivers in the metro area
had an accident in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If supporters of a higher driving age prevail, Georgia would
become the only state besides New Jersey to make 17 the minimum
driving age, according to the Insurance Institute for Highway
Safety. Teen restrictions approved in 1997 that prohibit late-night
driving, raise penalties for excessive speeding and limit the
number of passengers would kick in at 17 rather than 16, under
Gingrey's proposal. Full driving privileges would still be granted
at 18, and learner's permits would still be available at 15.
</P>
<P>
   But major changes are not a forgone conclusion. Some House
Democratic leaders have resisted efforts to restrict teen driving.
And if Barnes uses his office to push the issue _ something he's
not yet agreed to do _ he could be on an ideological collision
course with some of his staunchest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people look forward to getting their license at 16,''
said House Majority Leader Larry Walker (D-Perry). ``It's been 16 a
long time. There are already restrictions on it. I wouldn't favor
that (age increase).''
</P>
<P>
   The issue isn't expected to be a major flashpoint between Barnes
and other legislators this year. Barnes' already-packed agenda
gives little time for him to take on another issue, said Michael
Binford, a Georgia State University political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   But a popular governor such as Barnes voicing even general
support for a higher driving age is enough to significantly
increase its credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would give other legislators a little bit of cover,''
Binford said. ``If he's out front, they wouldn't have to take as
much flak.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia voters may be receptive to the idea. A recent survey by
Democratic pollsters Cooper &AMP; Secrest found that 67 percent of
Georgia voters favor raising the driving age to 17. But those
findings probably underestimate the strength of opposition from
parents and teens who've waited a lifetime for the independence of
driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents talk about driver safety, but a lot of these parents
will be very grateful that these children get to a point where
(parents) ... don't have to be soccer moms anymore,'' said Rep.
Alan Powell (D-Hartwell).
</P>
<P>
   Delaying the driving age only means that it will be
inexperienced 17-year-olds instead of inexperienced 16-year-olds
behind the wheel, Powell and others say. More driver training is a
better solution, critics argue. Republicans are pushing for
mandatory driver's education in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
