<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NY     01-07 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JETS' DEBACLE IS NOT ABOVE SUSPICION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are some in the National Football League who
stare at the Jets' coaching debacle and see nothing but
conspiracies. They are educated people, with advanced degrees, who
do not believe in little green men or the grassy knoll theory. But
when it comes to Bill Parcells, who is about as trusted by the
league office as a shark in a pool of bluefish, or even Bill
Belichick trying to escape his ironclad contract as if he's Harry
Houdini, all logic goes flying out the window.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase one official, something about this Jets situation
stinks like week-old Muenster cheese on a hot day.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest theory bouncing off the walls and burning up
the telephone lines, according to team and league officials who
have been part of the bouncing process. When Parcells left the New
England Patriots in 1997 to join the Jets as a ``consultant,'' it
was Belichick who was named head coach of the Jets for just short
of a week. Then Parcells and the Patriots, with the help of the
league office, brokered an agreement allowing Parcells to get out
of his contract with New England in exchange for the Jets sending
draft picks to the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The belief among some executives is that Parcells is repaying
Belichick for playing the role of puppet three years ago. How? All
along, the conspirators think, Parcells intended to retire, then
change his mind and coach again for one more year. He would then
hire Belichick back as defensive coordinator, but without the
contractual provision that Belichick must replace Parcells as
coach. That way, there would be no hindrances to prevent Belichick
from taking a head coaching position elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The two men can help each other. The new owner of the Jets would
talk Parcells back into coaching and give him a large bump in
salary. This is what the conspirator theorists feel Parcells has
wanted out of this situation all along _ more money. Belichick is
helped because he can become free to join the Patriots as general
manager and coach, which is what he really wants.
</P>
<P>
   Before laughing this theory off as Oliver Stone's latest movie _
call it ``Any Given Contract'' _ the point needs to be made that
Parcells has a questionable track record with the league. That is
where the suspicion is rooted.
</P>
<P>
   So when Belichick did an about-face this week and resigned as
head coach of the Jets, this actually should not have come as a
surprise, because when it comes to pulling a fast one, Belichick
learned from the master.
</P>
<P>
   Item: Post-1986 season. Parcells had his agent, Robert Fraley,
contact the Atlanta Falcons about Parcells' becoming director of
operations and head coach, despite the fact that Parcells had one
more year left on his Giants contract. Commissioner Pete Rozelle
ruled that Parcells could take only the director of operations
portion of the job, not the coaching part, because he was already
coach of the Giants. Parcells stayed with New York.
</P>
<P>
   Item: Dec. 29, 1991. Hugh Culverhouse, then the Tampa Bay owner,
accused Parcells of backing out of a contract he had agreed to for
five years worth $6.5 million. ``He said we were all set; we will
execute the contract,'' Culverhouse said at the time. ``It was
executed by Tampa Bay. We now feel like we have been jilted at the
altar.''
</P>
<P>
   Only several days before Culverhouse basically called Parcells a
liar, Frank Litsky of The New York Times asked Parcells if there
was any truth to the Tampa Bay rumors. Said Parcells: ``There's no
truth to anything you've heard. Write it.''
</P>
<P>
   Item: January 1997. In the days before Super Bowl XXXI, there
was a report in The Boston Globe that said Parcells would leave the
Patriots for the Jets. Parcells responded: ``Nothing has changed.
Just because there's another report out doesn't make it
different.''
</P>
<P>
   But something was different. After Parcells' Patriots reached
the title game, Dave Anderson, the Times columnist, quoted a friend
of Parcells' who maintained that Parcells, referring to his
nickname, had said, ``The price of Tuna has just gone up.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks later, Parcells resigned as coach of the
Patriots, despite days of denials that he would do so. Soon after
that, he was general manager and coach of the Jets, but only after
a lengthy and painful process that involved Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue playing the role of Henry Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   So forgive some in the NFL if they see a few dark shadows when
it comes to Parcells, and now Belichick. They've been down this
road before.
</P>
<P>
   If the league really wants to know what is going on inside the
head of the two men, it should hire a mind reader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
