<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-SUSPECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANGER SAYS DRIFTER HAS ADMITTED TO 10 HOMICIDES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A violent, rail-riding drifter charged with capital murder in a
New Year's Eve knife attack on two girls in Del Rio, Texas, has
admitted to 10 homicides in at least five states, according to a
Texas Ranger involved in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lynn Sells, 35, has provided Val Verde County sheriff's
officials and Texas Rangers with details of the slayings of men and
women around the country, Texas Ranger John Allen said late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just admitted to lots of homicides throughout the country
_ in Arkansas, several homicides in California, Arizona and the one
in Kentucky,'' Allen said, referring to the rape and knife slaying
of a 13-year-old girl last May in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're in the process of trying to get some (of the
slayings) verified right now.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the information Sells has given has proved reliable, the
Ranger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've yet to prove that he's lied to us about anything. It may
take us a while to get police agencies to verify the homicides.
Some of the homicides appear to go back as far as 20 years,'' Allen
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ranger said Sells, a bearded man with a shock of thick hair,
has shown ``only a tiny bit of remorse. It doesn't seem to bother
him.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sells can't explain why he kills, the Ranger added.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's asked me that several times. He hasn't asked why he
killed, but he's asked me `Where do you think I went wrong?' ''
Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sells was arrested in Del Rio on New Year's Day after the murder
of Kaylene Harris, 13, and the attempted murder of her friend,
Krystal Surles, 10, in the Harris family mobile home outside Del
Rio.
</P>
<P>
   By pretending to be dead, Krystal survived a throat-slashing
that severed her vocal cords. She climbed through a window and
walked a quarter mile to a neighbor's home to seek help. Unable to
talk, Krystal was able to write down a description of her attacker
that a Texas Department of Public Safety sketch artist used to make
a composite drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified Sells using the sketch and a description of a
man seen walking in downtown Del Rio provided by the boyfriend of
Krystal's mother. Sells was arrested at his mobile home in the
Amistad Campgrounds on New Year's Day, and has been charged with
capital murder in Kaylene's death and attempted capital murder in
the attack on Krystal.
</P>
<P>
   He remains in the Val Verde County jail in lieu of $800,000
bond, and has been cooperating with the investigation into the New
Year's Eve attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's basically a transient,'' the Ranger said of the suspect.
``He came to Del Rio approximately two years ago with a carnival
and ended up marrying a local girl in Del Rio.''
</P>
<P>
   Sells married the woman 14 months ago. She was ``a teeny bit
upset'' when she learned of his activities, Allen said. ``It does
not appear she was aware of his lifestyle, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   The murder suspect has no family in Texas, the Ranger said, and
was working in Del Rio as a used car salesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was born in Oakland, Calif., raised in St. Louis and went
to school through the 8th grade. He left home when he was 13 and
has been on the streets ever since,'' the Ranger said, adding that
he has an extensive criminal record and has done time in prisons in
Wyoming and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said Sells has a history of alcohol abuse, and has spent
much of his life riding freight trains. ``That's how he did most of
his traveling _ that and in stolen cars and hitch-hiking,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sells has provided details of killing people who picked him up
as he hitch-hiked around the country. Other victims were fellow
transients with whom he had argued, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like some of the homicides may be sexually related,
coming after a sexual attack or rape,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the homicides were planned, and others were random,
Allen said. ``He used everything from pistols, strangulation,
knives. He had no particular weapon of choice,'' the Ranger added.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky police officials have been to Del Rio and interviewed
Sells about the May slaying of 13-year-old Haley McHone, whose body
_ with her throat slashed _ was found along the railroad tracks in
Lexington. He faces rape, kidnapping and capital murder charges in
that case, Kentucky officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Kentucky police believed that another suspected
multiple murderer, Angel Maturino Resendiz, was involved in
McHone's slaying. The body of a Lexington college student whom
Resendiz is charged with killing was found on the same tracks, only
yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Allen described Sells as soft-spoken and polite.
</P>
<P>
   ``As weird as it may sound, he's polite, he's well-mannered, but
everything we can gather so far is he can become extremely
agitated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
