<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-MARINO08-COX     01-07 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARINO08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marino faces age-old question and every QB's toughest call
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ And so after nearly 17 seasons, it has
come to this: Dan Marino, the most productive passer in NFL
history, being mentioned in the same breath as Johnny Unitas, Joe
Namath, Y.A. Tittle.
</P>
<P>
   Only these days, the 38-year-old Marino is conjuring up images
of a sorry sort: A 40-year-old Unitas getting sacked on his final
play. A battered Broadway Joe hobbling off the field in a Rams
uniform. Tittle, on his knees, blood dripping from his face.
</P>
<P>
   They are Hall of Fame players who stuck around too long. Is
Marino doing the same? He has struggled this season with injuries,
inconsistent performances and clashes with coach Jimmy Johnson. But
will he retire? Can he just walk away? Should he walk away? ``Oh,
it's hard to walk away from it,'' said Phil Simms, who won two
Super Bowls with the New York Giants before retiring against his
wishes after the 1993 season, his 15th in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me three years to get it out of my system. I didn't
miss it because of the money. I just missed it because I liked my
lifestyle. I liked the work and the system.''
</P>
<P>
   And he liked to win. Simms left football at age 39 with a couple
of championship rings. He had just finished his best season in five
years, after recovering from shoulder surgery, when the Giants let
him go. ``They made it clear it wasn't about my play,'' Simms says.
``I was getting ready to go in and ask for a pay increase. They
said, 'No, you just had surgery, you're getting old. It's time for
someone new.'''
</P>
<P>
   Simms pondered playing for the Browns before deciding to spend
more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   For Marino, the emotional stakes are higher. He reached the
Super Bowl early in his career, when the Dolphins lost to the 49ers
in 1985. Fourteen years later, he desperately wants to return one
last time, even though a bulging disk and cervical bone spur have
sapped the power from his arm.
</P>
<P>
   His demise has been painful to watch. Dolphins fans can blame
Marino's pursuit of a title on at least one man _ John Elway, who
entered the league with Marino in 1983 and retired last spring
after winning his second straight Super Bowl with Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that that is an issue,'' sports
psychologist Jim Loehr said. ``(Marino) saw John, and he wanted to
make a final run and go out just like (Elway) did, and it's
backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quarterbacks, to be good, have to have an unbelievable level
of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And when their skills diminish, Loehr said, ``it's very
difficult to look at themselves and say it can't be done anymore.
You still have this tremendous feeling of confidence, and it's hard
to switch that off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hebert, another product of the storied quarterback Class
of '83, never achieved greatness in his 11 seasons but led the
Saints and Falcons to playoff appearances. He did recognize the
end, when his passes no longer packed a pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm wasn't the same,'' said Hebert, a USFL refugee who
retired after the 1996 season. ``Mentally, I was as sharp as ever,
but it was really frustrating (to realize) you are not able to make
the plays you made when you were younger.''
</P>
<P>
   After nine concussions and a career played mostly on artificial
turf, Hebert hung it up _ and with few regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still thought at the end of my career, `If I could play once
or twice more ... ' Then I remember the last year I played. You
wake up every (Monday) morning and you feel like you've been in a
bad car wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hebert knows it can't be easy for Marino to come to terms
with the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like he doesn't move around as well,'' he said. ``But
that's just wear and tear on the joints. He's never been the most
mobile guy, but he's always had that quick release and could avoid
sacks. He's always had that confidence in his arm. Maybe as you get
older you have to face the music that you can't do the same
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe age doesn't mean a thing when it comes to an athlete's
ability to perform at the top of his game. Elway showed that,
though he did admit upon his retirement that physically he no
longer could perform to his standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a different physiology,'' said Dr. Jeffrey
Minkoff, an assistant orthopedist for the Namath-era Jets who now
is team physician for the NHL's Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``30 years is considered old in the professional
athletic world,'' Minkoff said that doesn't mean the 30-year-old
athlete's body automatically starts to break down. Look at George
Blanda, who played 26 seasons before retiring with the Oakland
Raiders in 1976, one month shy of his 49th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Says Minkoff, ``There's nothing that takes the place of good
genetics.''
</P>
<P>
   Or a talented team. In Elway's last two, Super Bowl title
seasons, he wasn't asked to carry the team because Denver had a
strong runner in Terrell Davis and a tough defense. The Dolphins
still are trying to develop a running game and even their reliable
defense has faltered late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Elway ``was a big part of it maybe half the time,'' says Simms,
a CBS analyst. ``He didn't have to go out there every week and
physically carry the team. Dan Marino? Dan is not getting a free
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are he will not ride off with a championship, as Elway
did at Pro Player Stadium last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the 31 teams, not even 50 percent (of quarterbacks) are
legitimate starters,'' Hebert says. ``There are maybe 12 or 13 guys
who can get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Marino among them? ``Marino might be,'' Hebert says. ``If he
is willing to move, he would have the opportunity to play somewhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   That might not be a bad option, Simms says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about playing quarterback is that knowledge is
a great thing,'' Simms said. ``As long as you don't have the
physical liabilities, you can still take that knowledge and be a
very capable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen both sides of Dan Marino this year, the best and
some of the worst. The question I have is, can he go out there
every week and physically have the chance to be at the top of his
game? It doesn't look like he can.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Simms thinks Marino should retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of those (who say), `Oh, he should retire. His
skills have faded.' You quit when you want to quit. If your skills
erode and you're the worst damn thing in the world and some (team)
wants you, you play. You dreamed about it your whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
