<SLUG> BC-SCI-FLU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLU VICTIMS OVERWHELM EMERGENCY ROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Mont., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's wave of influenza has become widespread across the
nation, overwhelming emergency rooms in cities from Boston to Los
Angeles, filling hospital beds and forcing postponements of
operations as staff members turn to treating the rising number of
flu patients. And many patients are simply forgoing treatment
rather than face the increasingly long waits in overcrowded
emergency rooms, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta said this year's
outbreak has arrived much earlier than usual and has increased
death rates from pneumonia and flu-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the third bad year in a row for the flu,'' said
Lynnette Brammer, flu-surveillance coordinator at the CDC.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brammer said the disease had ``exceeded the epidemic
threshold'' _ meaning the deaths it has caused have somewhat
exceeded the normal number of deaths during a flu season. But, she
said, this occurs frequently during heavy flu seasons, and, though
the attacks are severe and widespread, the 1999-2000 season is
still far from the the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brammer added that it was impossible at this stage to
predict how long the increase in cases would last.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Vacanti, an anesthesiologist at the University of
Massachusetts Memorial Medical Center in Worcester, said that
almost all hospital beds in central Massachusetts were filled with
flu patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elective surgery is being postponed and hospitals are trying
to transfer other surgical patients elsewhere because hospital beds
and services are taken up by patients with the flu,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Pearlmutter, the chief of emergency medicine for St.
Elizabeth's Medical Center in Brighton, Mass., said that ``the
intensity seems to be more acute than it has.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just sicker,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Staci Freeman, 32, of Brighton, seeking treatment for the flu
Friday at St. Elizabeth's, said she had not felt so sick ``since
the time I had pneumonia when I was 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal Flomenbaum, emergency physician in chief at New York
Presbyterian Hospital's Weill Cornell Center, said doctors were
overworked over the New Year's weekend, and then came in Monday to
find rooms filled with patients with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used two to three times the normal complement of doctors
and nurses over the New Year's weekend only to come in Monday
morning and face a true flu epidemic,'' Flomenbaum said. ``And
people have been working nonstop ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   At many overcrowded emergency rooms, people simply are leaving
without being treated, he said. That is especially dangerous for
elderly patients or those with other medical conditions, Flomenbaum
said.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, health officials said, was that the strain of
virus circulating in the country, called Sydney influenza A, was
not an unusual one, and the vaccines recommended for use this year
were effective against it. These officials also said that the new
medications Relenza, made by Glaxo Wellcome, and Tamiflu, made by
Roche Laboratories, both of which were made available last fall,
were found to be highly effective if taken promptly after symptoms
appear.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts said these new prescription drugs, for people who
have been tested and found to have the flu virus, must be taken
within 48 hours after symptoms appear.
</P>
<P>
   But people were said to be generally slow to react to coughing
or other signs of the flu like an aching body, fever and nausea,
trying to tough it out and get through the illness with
over-the-counter medicines. By the time these flu victims become
thoroughly miserable and need help, it is too late for the
prescription medications to work, the health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   IMS Health, a market research company, said 50,000 Relenza
prescriptions were written the week before Christmas, four times
the previous week. Nearly 45,000 prescriptions were written for
Tamiflu.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Ossi, vice president and director of
infectious-disease clinical research at Glaxo Wellcome Corp., said
drugs work ``by inhibiting a protein on the surface of the flu
virus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That enzyme is necessary for the virus to spread through the
respiratory system,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Medical Center in Missoula, Mont., was another
place with more flu patients than beds to put them or places to
keep them from infecting other patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw over 60 people in seven hours, almost all with flu
symptoms,'' said Jennifer Krueger, a physician's assistant at the
center. ``We've had people in here who will usually ride out a
cold, and they want help. People weren't expecting this, and it's
hitting like a ton of bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, emergency room physicians at Cedars-Sinai
Medical Center have seen twice the number of patients they saw last
year, said Dee Dee Klute, the administrative director of the
emergency department.
</P>
<P>
   One 77-year-old man's lungs were so impaired by his flu symptoms
Thursday that doctors had to give respiratory assistance at once,
Ms. Klute said. And a 31-year-old woman was so dehydrated that it
took five liters of saline solution to bring her back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the middle of it, that's for sure,'' Ms. Klute said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
