<HEADER>
A9912 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-FRANCE-INVEST-ART-2TA     01-07 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-INVEST-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FRENCH ARE RESISTING AMERICAN FUNDS AND INVESTORS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of foreign stock investment, GDP, unemployment,
stock market in France is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Elf Aquitaine, France's largest oil company, surrendered
last summer to a hostile takeover from a domestic rival, Elf's
departing chief was rewarded with stock options worth $38 million.
Not long thereafter, Michelin, the highly profitable French tire
maker, announced that it would eliminate 7,500 jobs across Europe.
And earlier in the year, the government's support for a three-way
merger of big banks was thwarted when investors balked.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, that kind of corporate news might be seen
as routine. But in France and across Europe, it is providing grist
for a volatile debate about the role of big foreign investors,
including American pension funds, in European business. The pension
funds are portrayed as demanding unreasonably high profits at the
expense of jobs, as promoting outlandish rewards for executives and
as a general threat to established ways of life.
</P>
<P>
   In October, when William D. Crist, board president of the
California Public Employees' Retirement System, the largest
American public pension fund, arrived in Paris for a routine visit,
Le Monde, the Paris daily, published an article titled ``The
Pension Funds That Drive Fear Into the French.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're called Calpers, Templeton and TIAA-CREF,'' the article
said, ``and for the French, who are discovering with a certain
anguish the globalization of their economy, these pension funds
from abroad are the masters of this new world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, pension funds have been long-term
investors in business for decades. They are an accepted, even
welcomed, part of the financial landscape, seen as protectors of
the savings of millions of working individuals and as more
conservative and reliable than many other investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   But in Europe, where retirees have long relied on pay-as-you-go
public pension systems and many industries have been financed by
government or through cozy relationships with local banks, the
mounting influence of such outside and outsized institutional
investors is creating serious tensions.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the government recently assailed a hostile takeover
bid by Vodafone AirTouch of Britain for Mannesmann, the German
telecommunications conglomerate, as tantamount to an attack on
German sovereignty. The bid had been favored by several
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, the government has expressed unease at the free flow
of investment, declaring the former national telecommunications
company, Telecom Italia, off limits to foreign hostile takeover
bids and putting the brakes on banking deals.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere have pension funds and other foreign investment
firms set off more fury than in France. As French industry
restructures to improve its global competitiveness, it has
attracted billions of dollars in investment capital, much of it
from American and British pension funds. Now, the funds' role in
the French economy is spawning the latest in a series of fierce
conflicts that pit French cultural values against the demands of
international finance.
</P>
<P>
   Even the president of France, Jacques Chirac, complained
publicly that French workers were being asked to sacrifice simply
to ``safeguard the investment benefits of Scottish widows and
California pensioners.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Trichet, governor of the Bank of France, the central
bank, tried to explain what he called ``a French paradox.'' While
France has emerged lately as the strongest locomotive of Europe's
economy, he said in an interview, ``the image that is displayed
might be misleading, since the rear-guard part of the economy is
more eloquent than the successful part.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue weighs on French-American relations, already burdened
by various squabbles. They include an American ban on French luxury
foods, to protest French unwillingness to import hormone-treated
American beef, and a refusal by France to buy genetically modified
American crops.
</P>
<P>
   But the investment debate also complicates life for the
government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, of the Socialist Party.
Tensions erupted in his administration last month after the
Communists, a junior partner in the coalition, called for laws
banning layoffs by profitable corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The financial trend is clear. In the first eight months of 1999,
foreign investment in French stocks and bonds totaled 457 billion
francs, or $70.3 billion, more than in all of 1998, when the inflow
of 400 billion francs was 50 percent higher than the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The windfall, Trichet said, partly explains recent French
economic gains. Growth in 2000 is expected to reach 3 percent, up
from 2.8 percent in 1999. Unemployment, the chief blemish on an
improving record, should drop below 10 percent for the first time
in years. Much of the investment driving the French revival has
come from institutional investors: among the top 40 companies on
the Paris stock exchange, an average stake of 35 percent is now
held by American and British institutional investors and pension
funds.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than cheering their success, many French are wringing
their hands. When Crist of Calpers paid a visit, the leftist daily
Liberation outlined the immense size and power of the pension fund,
but felt obliged to reassure its readers that Crist was ``no Darth
Vader'' _ especially since the newspaper ran a photograph that made
him (italics)look(end italics) like Darth Vader.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have the jibes been restricted to the left. Jean-Louis
Beffa, the chairman and chief executive of Compagnie de
Saint-Gobain, the glass and building materials group, accused
foreign pension funds of forcing on French corporations ``a
quickness of change that imposes considerable human problems.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I'm not sure they're best adapted to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the French government has been gradually selling off
control of more than a score of huge enterprises like banks,
insurance companies, industrial companies and even the national
flag carrier, Air France. Since his election in 1997, Jospin, who
had campaigned with a pledge to end privatizations, has sold a
further chunk of assets worth roughly $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   To sweeten the auction of nationalized property for the
Socialists and their allies in the Communist Party, Jospin promoted
the idea of employee shareholding. Now, roughly three-fourths of
all the employees in privatized companies are shareholders in their
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, 15 percent of the French population owns stock, far
below the 50 percent level for the United States. But the increase
has been profound, from 1 percent a decade ago, and at times is
crucial in corporate decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The power shifts were seen last year in an unusual takeover
battle within the French banking industry. Last March, two big
French banks, Societe Generale and Paribas, announced plans to
merge, only to see their plans upset days later by a third domestic
rival, Banque Nationale de Paris, which started a $37 billion
hostile bid for both its rivals together.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of the French authorities was typical of an older,
cozier tradition of business-government linkage.
</P>
<P>
   Trichet, the central bank governor, convened the banks'
directors and urged them to agree to a three-way alliance. That, he
argued, would create a strong French banking champion.
</P>
<P>
   But Paris did not get its way. Banque Nationale won the backing
of investors to gain control of Paribas, but not of Societe
Generale, illustrating two lessons to the French. One was the power
of institutional investors, not only pension funds but also hedge
funds and arbitrageurs, to thwart government wishes. The other was
the increasing financial influence of workers, who, thanks to their
employee stock ownership plan, held roughly 8 percent of the stock
in Societe Generale. Employees, the biggest single bloc, voted
overwhelmingly against the Banque Nationale takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, said Sophie L'Helias, a French lawyer who
represents American funds, ``shareholders were always the ones
writing the checks so management and stakeholders could play
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Toulisse, national secretary of the CFDT labor union,
acknowledged that French labor-management relations, once a
you-scratch-my-back-and-I'll-scratch-yours arrangement, produced
frequent strikes but also high productivity and comfortable
employee benefits. Now, with the rise of employee shareholders, he
said, labor relations has ``pushed from a game of two to a game of
three.
</P>
<P>
   The union seeks to tread a middle path, Toulisse said, deeming
employee shareholding neither the ``alpha and omega'' nor
``something diabolical.'' It wants to avoid a division between
employees who own shares in their companies and those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   Pension fund managers reject accusations that they wield undue
power and destroy jobs to benefit distant shareholders.
``Nonsense,'' said Crist, whose fund has roughly $2 billion in
French stocks, making it probably the largest single investor on
the Paris Bourse. He said that France would gradually move away
from total reliance on a pay-as-you-go public pension system, but
that ``this is not going to be a quick or easy transition.''
</P>
<P>
   The activist policies of Calpers, meanwhile, are aimed at
promoting respect for minority shareholders' rights, independent
boards of directors and greater openness in setting executive pay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter C. Clapman, chief investment counsel of TIAA-CREF, the
teachers pension fund, has regularly visited France to sow the
seeds of shareholder activism. In 1997, the fund helped to lead a
successful minority shareholder revolt at Eramet SA, a mining
company in which the French Treasury held a stake, after the
government tried to appease the independence movement in a South
Pacific territory by swapping a nickel mine owned by Eramet for a
less profitable one owned by local separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Now shareholder activism is catching on, and the government is
trying to help. Legislation is being considered to compel the
release of details about executive compensation and to require
shareholder approval if the jobs of chairman and chief executive
are combined, to curb the omnipotence of French executives.
</P>
<P>
   And this month, Trichet, the central banker, and H. Carl McCall,
the New York state comptroller and pension trustee, plan to conduct
a public forum here on the role of pension funds in a modern
economy. Felix G. Rohatyn, the American ambassador in Paris and a
former investment banker, arranged McCall's visit _ to show the
French, he explained, that there was ``no contradiction between the
fiduciary responsibility of a pension fund manager and the social
responsibility of a public official.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9915 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-AFCLEDE08-COX     01-07 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFCLEDE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titan-ic start bypasses Flutie
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville, Tenn. _ Last season, Flutie Magic swept over Buffalo
like a late-autumn blizzard.
</P>
<P>
   Bills quarterback Doug Flutie, the 1984 Heisman Trophy winner
and six-time Canadian League MVP, led Buffalo to a 10-6 record and
the playoffs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie played in the Pro Bowl and grocery stores couldn't keep
``Flutie Flakes'' on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Now, grocers might be demanding a frosted version of the cereal.
</P>
<P>
   After leading the Bills to a 10-5 record this season, Flutie was
benched by Buffalo coach Wade Phillips. Rob Johnson, who has
started all of eight games in his five-year pro career, will start
today's AFC wild-card game at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   And Flutie isn't happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that frustrates me more than anything is I've been
waiting 10 years for this opportunity,'' Flutie said. ``We've got a
great football team. We've got the best defense in the league.
We've got a real chance. And this is the reason I came back _ and
then all of a sudden you turn it over.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an all-too-familiar feeling for Flutie, who was benched 11
years ago by New England coach Raymond Berry. In the Patriots'
final game of the 1988 season, Berry started Tony Eason, who was
still hurt and unable to throw well. The Broncos won that game and
knocked New England out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exactly what happened with the Patriots,'' Flutie said.
``What bothers me about this is that I felt the decision back then
was made because Tony was a first-rounder, Tony was making $1.2
million and I was making $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went into that offseason as a free agent and a starter,
they were going to have to pay me what Tony made. So they had to
make a decision then and do it. And I feel like I got caught in the
middle of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie might be caught in the middle of cap-o-nomics again. The
Bills are paying Johnson, a former backup with the Jaguars, about
$5 million a year; Flutie earned about $4.4 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   Having two high-priced passers might not be an option for the
Bills, who are projected to be about $5 million over the salary cap
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, here's a situation where they've given up a
first-rounder for Rob, he signed for a lot of money, and he hasn't
done anything yet,'' Flutie said. ``It all had that same feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The move is a daring one by Phillips. Not since Jets coach Joe
Walton replaced Ken O'Brien with Pat Ryan in 1986 has a coach
benched a quarterback on the eve of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough decision certainly,'' Phillips said. ``I studied
the film. It wasn't a haphazard thing. I talked to our coaches, and
I think it gives us the best opportunity to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips might be right. Although Flutie is 17-9 as an NFL
starter, his passer rating of 75.1 this season is ranked only 23rd
in the league. Flutie has thrown 19 touchdowns and 16 interceptions
and averages only 6.63 yards per pass attempt. In his last five
games, the Bills scored only 85 points.
</P>
<P>
   Teams learned how to defend him this season.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents stacked the line of scrimmage and daredFlutie to beat
them with his arm. Teams also rushed him from the outside to
prevent him from leaving the pocket, where he is most dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, an All-American at Southern California, threw for 287
yards and two touchdowns in last week's 31-6 romp of the Colts. He
engineered four 80-yard touchdown drives against Indianapolis,
after the Bills had only five in their first 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is confident in me right now,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he thinks that Johnson can be more accurate
throwing the deep ball. That could be a key against the Titans, who
might be without injured free safety Marcus Robertson, who suffered
several facial lacerations in a motorcycle accident.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie says he'll be ready if Johnson falters. If Buffalo loses,
it might be Flutie's last game in a Bills uniform. His relationship
with Phillips seems irreparable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should talk to my wife,'' Flutie said. ``Basically, she
said, `I told you so,' and can't wait for me to come home. I don't
think my role with this team is through. We'll see how it plays
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
