<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GRANADA-TV-MERGER-(TR     01-07 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANADA-TV-MERGER-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S GRANADA GROUP CONSIDERS BIDS FOR TV RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A battle to rule Britain's commercial television
industry began on Friday when the Granada Group said it intended to
spoil the recently planned $6.6-billion merger between Carlton
Communications and United News &AMP; Media by trying to buy one of the
media companies.
</P>
<P>
   Granada, a leading British operator of television networks,
hotels and restaurants, said it would request permission from
regulatory authorities to bid for either company, though executives
at Granada declined to identify which one.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Carlton and United News announced that they would
merge, a deal that would create the largest commercial television
concern in Britain, reaching more than 65 percent of the nation's
homes.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is control of Britain's Independent Television Network,
or ITV, the principal nationwide commercial television network that
is broadcast conventionally rather than via a cable or satellite
provider. Seven companies currently own ITV, including Granada,
Carlton and United News.
</P>
<P>
   If the Carlton-United merger were approved and Granada were not
allowed to bid for one of the two companies, Granada would be left
with very little opportunity to acquire another company that could
give it the size and muscle to compete effectively with the
combined Carlton and United.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of Carlton and United has yet to be approved by
regulators, and Britain's Office of Fair Trading is expected to
refer the deal to the Competition Commission for a full review. The
Broadcasting Act forbids media companies to control more than 15
percent of the audience and 25 percent of advertising revenue.
Carlton and United said their merger would give them a 14.9 percent
share of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Granada chief executive Charles Allen suggested that regulators
should block a merger between Carlton and United. ``We believe that
further ITV consolidation raises a number of competition and public
policy issues that should be referred to the Competition
Commission,'' Allen was quoted by Reuters. ``Obviously, it makes
sense for shareholders in Carlton and United to wait before taking
any action.'' Shareholders of both companies are expected to vote
on the merger later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Both Carlton and United issued a statement saying that the
companies' boards were committed to the merger and continued to
recommend it unanimously to their shareholders. The companies said
that Granada's move should be ignored, in part, because it
contained no specific proposals.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Granada has made no secret of its desire to expand in the media
industry through acquisitions and has said it may split up into
media and hospitality divisions. It is one of Britain's largest
hotel and restaurant operators. The company's media enterprises
include a number of popular television productions like
``Masterpiece Theater'' and film documentaries like ``42 Up,'' a
series that chronicles the lives of several individuals. It also
has an agreement with The New York Times to create television
documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that if Granada were granted permission to make an
offer for either Carlton or United, such a deal would most likely
face even more regulatory hurdles than the Carlton-United merger
because it would be larger.
</P>
<P>
   ITV has historically competed for viewers only with the British
Broadcasting Corp.'s channels, which do not carry advertisements.
But the media companies that have stakes in ITV have become
convinced that they must consolidate to compete effectively for
advertising with commercial channels carried over Britain's cable
and satellite networks.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Granada rose 4 pence, to 585.5 pence, or $9.66. Shares
of Carlton rose 16 pence, to 573 pence, or $9.45. Shares of United
fell 5.5 pence, to 792.5 pence, or $13.08.
</P>
</TEXT>
