speaks to reporters while sitting in front of a map of the province
on Friday. Troshev said a temporary halt in its intensive air and
artillery bombardment of the capital of rebel Chechnya had been
called, but that fighting in Grozny persisted on the ground. (James
Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BETHLEHEM -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ORTHODOX-LEADERS-2 --
Orthodox Patriarch Diodoros I of Jerusalem, in a wooden wheelchair,
is greeted by orthodox patriarchs during a procession which was
part of services observing Orthodox Christmas, Friday in Bethlehem.
Patriarchs and politicians from all the major Eastern Orthodox
churches and nations filed into the fourth-century Church of the
Nativity for a Christmas service that was one of the most inclusive
gatherings of Orthodox Christian leaders in modern times. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BETHLEHEM -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ORTHODOX-LEADERS -- Former
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, left, speaks with Suha Arafat as
her husband Yasser Arafat looks on Friday during a Mass celebrated
for Orthodox Christmas. The three-day Holy Land pilgrimage that
ended Friday was Yeltsin's first major public appearance since his
abrupt resignation that shook the world just hours before it
entered the new millennium. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
