<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9922 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-NFCLEDE08-COX     01-07 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCLEDE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History haunts Lions
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Detroit Lions quarterback Gus Frerotte should
feel right at home in this afternoon's playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Give him credit, too, for trying to brainwash his teammates into
feeling just as cozy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're playing the same Redskins team we played (in
Detroit on Dec. 5),'' Frerotte said. He played his first five NFL
seasons for the Redskins and still maintains a home in nearby
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice if the Lions could believe him, but probably
more on their minds is their 0-19 all-time record against the
Redskins in Washington and Maryland since they moved from Boston
before the 1937 season.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Lions are not the same team that began the season 6-2,
then 8-4, including a 33-17 win over the Redskins last month.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (8-8) hasn't won since, losing four in a row, while the
Redskins (10-6) won three of four and the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware of the history,'' Lions center Mike Compton said.
``Everybody keeps mentioning it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all of the bad history.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit has won one playoff game in 42 years, 38-6 at home
against Dallas in 1991. The next week, they got drilled in the NFC
Championship game, 41-10 at Washington. The Lions also have lost
their last seven road playoff games, dating back to 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Frerotte was 2-4 this season while starting in place of Charlie
Batch, who re-fractured his right thumb in last Sunday's 24-17 loss
at Minnesota and might not even be able to play today in an
emergency. But Frerotte was good against his former team last
month. He passed for 280 yards, one touchdown and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   And he swears he will feel at home in FedEx Field, trying to
beat the team that made a scapegoat of him after last season by
cutting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like RFK,'' the Redskins' old stadium, he said.
``There won't be any bleachers rocking. The fans are farther from
the field. But it will be loud. It's kind of like going back to my
old home. I can't wait to run out of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins have had problems of their own this season.
</P>
<P>
   New owner Daniel Snyder has become a modern NFL version of what
Yankees owner George Steinbrenner was like in the 1970s and early
'80s, meddling almost daily in team affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive guru Bill Arnsparger was hired to advise embattled
coordinator Mike Nolan near midseason, and the Washington defense
has improved, although it still ranks second-worst in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In the first eight games, the Redskins allowed 27.8 points,
402.3 total yards and 127.4 rushing yards per game. In eight games
since, they have allowed 19.4 points, 310.9 total yards and 119.3
rushing yards. The offense, triggered by former Vikings quarterback
Brad Johnson, ranks No. 2 in the NFL and expects to get running
back Stephen Davis back. Davis, who led the NFC with 1,405 rushing
yards, missed last week's game with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's running game dealt well with the retirement of Barry
Sanders, but when his replacement, Ron Rivers, broke an ankle in
November, it suffered. Startling left tackle Ray Roberts was lost
for the season Dec. 19, and the Lions have averaged 47 rushing
yards over their past five games.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Cory Schlesinger is expected to get most of the
carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start to lose a little bit ... there's a confidence
factor that you have to regain,'' Detroit coach Bobby Ross said.
``And I think that's what we're working on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   More problems for Detroit: Pro Bowl defensive tackle Luther
Elliss has a badly sprained ankle, and the other starting defensive
tackle, James Jones, isn't certain to play. His wife, Son-Ja,
earlier this week underwent a kidney and pancreas transplant.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Lions beat the Redskins last month, it ended
another amazing Lions streak _ 16 consecutive regular-season losses
to the Redskins, home or away.
</P>
<P>
   Can Detroit snap another streak?
</P>
<P>
   Redskins veteran return man Brian Mitchell said, ``History can
fool you sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
