<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9923 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TVCROSSING-REVIEW-LAD     01-07 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVCROSSING-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars By ROB LOWMAN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may not know that George Washington was something of a role
model for Ho Chi Minh, the Vietnamese revolutionary leader.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the Virginia plantation owner and the communist
leader share much political ideology, but Ho recognized that
Washington's tactics during the American Revolution were the best
way for an underfunded, undermanned insurgency to fight against
superior forces.
</P>
<P>
   As history shows, Ho chose a successful path, but then he had
history to guide him. Washington, on the other hand, was something
of a madman, not that we like to question the sanity of the Father
of Our Country. But that is exactly what many of his aides did when
he marshaled his underarmed Continental Army for a surprise attack
as darkness fell on Christmas Day in 1776 against a highly trained
army of Hessian mercenaries in Trenton, N.J. The story of this
pivotal moment in our history is told Monday night in ``The
Crossing'' on A&AMP;E. Starring Jeff Daniels as a stoic Washington,
this adaption by Howard Fast of his own novel gives us a
straightforward and intelligent _ if somewhat passionless _ account
of the event without shedding much light on it.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly history and partly the enigma that is Washington.
Our image of Washington crossing the Delaware is probably taken
from Emanuel Leutzel's 1851 painting, where the general is standing
in the prow of a boat, rather foolhardy. In ``The Crossing,''
Washington sensibly sits in the middle of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly romantic, but Washington was, on one hand, a pragmatist.
It was the undertaking itself that was considered foolhardy. By
December 1776, Washington's army had been beaten badly in battle
after battle by the British and had shrunk from 20,000 men to less
than 2,000 in six months. In Washington's mind, a victory was
mandatory to even have a revolution. (He was, no doubt, right,
since only about a third in the American colonies even supported
the war.)
</P>
<P>
   To ``The Crossing's'' credit, all the political implications and
logistics of the attack are quite clearly laid out. As a history
lesson _ especially a TV history lesson _ the film is well done.
(One you wouldn't mind seeing used in classrooms.)
</P>
<P>
   The acting is uniformly solid, although the roles, especially
that of Washington, are more archetype than characters. So while we
see the brilliance of Washington's strategy, we never really grasp
the fire in his belly or understand what made him take such a risky
gambit. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``The Crossing.'' &QL; 
What: Retelling of George Washington's famous Christmas Day
attack. &QL; 
The stars:!off! Jeff Daniels, Roger Rees, Sebastian Roche, Stephen
McCarthy. &QL; 
Where: A&AMP;E. &QL; 
When: 7 and 9 p.m. Monday. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
