<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9924 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-     01-07 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI CAMPAIGN COLLECTS FUNDS FROM 2 LOOSELY-REGULATED GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In preparing a run for U.S. Senate, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has paid for much of his political operation by collecting
money through two little-known political committees that are
subject to looser fund-raising restrictions than an official Senate
campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   The two committees have taken in and spent nearly $1 million for
the mayor's political operation since March 1998, according to
disclosure records. The mayor collected much of the money from a
loyal corps of donors, many of whom have also given the legal limit
to Giuliani's separate Senate campaign committee. Often, the donors
contributed to all three accounts on the same day, the records
show.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates are generally required to finance their races through
official campaign committees, but in recent years many have
increasingly sought to use other vehicles to raise and spend money,
which has to some extent rendered the limits on donations to the
official campaign committees almost moot. This trend has spurred
calls for changes in the campaign finance laws that would seek to
limit the influence of such outside spending, markedly decreasing
the size of many donations.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Giuliani has chastised his likely Democratic
rival, Hillary Rodham Clinton, for collecting more than $350,000
through a special Democratic Party national committee that can
legally accept donations in unlimited amounts. Some of that
so-called soft money appears to have been spent on television
advertising promoting Mrs. Clinton's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides said his use of the two other committees was
entirely proper and was not an attempt to get around the limits.
They said they had received no objections from the Federal Election
Commission over the way that the Giuliani political operation was
financed.
</P>
<P>
   The official Giuliani campaign committee can accept a maximum of
$2,000 from each donor. Of the two other Giuliani committees, one,
Solutions America, which was set up under federal rules, has a
limit of $5,000 annually per donor. Under the rules, this type of
committee, known as a leadership account, is not supposed to be
used for campaign expenses, but rather to promote the candidate's
political philosophy and to contribute money to other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's other fund-raising committee, Giuliani for New York,
was established under even more lax New York rules and can collect
up to roughly $45,000 per donor. It is not supposed to be used for
federal campaigns, but for election to state offices like governor.
</P>
<P>
   By taking advantage of the different limits, the Giuliani
operation has been able to raise roughly $800,000 more from donors
who would otherwise have reached the $2,000 limit for contributing
to a Senate campaign, an analysis of campaign finance records
shows.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on the same day in March 1998, a Wall Street
financier Dave H. Williams donated $1,000 to the Senate committee,
$5,000 to Solutions America and $20,000 to Giuliani for New York.
</P>
<P>
   The records also show that for 1998 and the first half of 1999,
the mayor's three committees shared costs of at least one major
fund-raising event, as well as rent, salaries and other
administrative items for the Giuliani political operation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On April 15, 1999, the mayor's top political aide, Bruce
Teitelbaum, who the mayor this week said would be his campaign
manager, was paid $1,133.73 by the Senate campaign, $1,421.07 by
Solutions America and $1,133.73 by Giuliani for New York. For
several months, he was paid from the three different accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani aides said that in the second half of 1999, they had
used the two other committees mostly to finance advertisements to
build support for a referendum in November 1999 pushed by Giuliani
to change the city charter. The voters ultimately rejected the
Giuliani proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said that under the rules, the mayor was free to spend
from all three committees until he formally notified the Federal
Election Commission that he was considering running for Senate.
They said he did so in April 1999, and after that point, he had
largely stopped raising and spending money through the two
committees, with the exception of the Charter advertisements. They
acknowledged that the committees are not defunct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until late April we could raise and we could spend money
without it being viewed as promoting a Senate campaign because in
fact the mayor was undecided,'' said John Gross, the mayor's
campaign treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was widely expected that Giuliani would run for
Senate after Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan announced in November
1998 that he would not seek another term, Gross maintained that the
mayor had not begun focusing on the Senate until April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gross added that the Giuliani political operation has not used
either of the two committees to pay for television advertising for
the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Some election lawyers disputed the legal interpretation given by
Giuliani's aides.
</P>
<P>
   While the lawyers emphasized that they did not know whether any
election rules were violated, they said the issue did not rest on
when the mayor notified the Federal Election Commission that he was
considering running for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the lawyers said, adherence to the rules required that
the Solutions America account and the state account could not spend
money at any time on Giuliani's Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really depends on what these people did with the money,''
said Jan Witold Baran, a prominent election lawyer in Washington
who represents Republicans. ``It is dependent on how the money was
spent and whether or not it promoted the Senate election in a very
specific way.''
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Congress have set up federal leadership
accounts, and other lawyers noted that the Federal Election
Commission has adopted criteria to ensure that the accounts are
separate from campaign committees and not used to circumvent the
donation limits.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the rules say that if two committees have the same
staff members and similar patterns of contributions, that could
indicate that they are affiliated. If so, donations from an
individual would be subject to the Senate committee's limit. In
Giuliani's case, the lawyers said, donors would be able to give a
maximum of only $2,000 to all three committees combined.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the rules regarding the financing of campaigns, the
issues are murky and there is not much enforcement. Still, a few
politicians, including Bob Dole, have run afoul of the rules
regarding leadership accounts. Dole was penalized by the FEC for
using his leadership account, Campaign America, to help his 1988
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates of tightening the campaign finance system said
that whatever the rules intended to keep the committees separate,
the leadership accounts themselves were troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``These leadership PACs have been used by members of Congress as
the equivalent of political slush funds to pick up various costs,
ranging from legitimate political expenses to costs that wind up
being personal expenses,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of
Democracy 21, an advocacy group in Washington. ``They are very
questionable from a campaign finance standpoint, but they are used
by many members of Congress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
