<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-INTERNET-600&AMP;A     01-07 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-INTERNET-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL GROUP PROTESTS 2 BANKS' FREE WEB ACCESS PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Spain)  (js) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Drawing attention to the growing
concentration of power among large companies in Brazil's Internet
industry, a group representing several hundred of the country's
Internet access providers protested on Friday over plans by two
prominent banks to offer free access to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian Association of Internet Providers said that the
entry of the banks, Banco Bradesco SA and Uniao de Bancos
Brasileiros SA, into the access business could inhibit competition
since the financial institutions' ability to draw on existing
client bases is so huge.
</P>
<P>
   The banks' forays have thrown the Brazilian Internet industry,
Latin America's largest, into a frenzy with many companies
redrawing strategies to compete under new conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're witnessing an attempt to conquer the Brazilian Internet
by institutions who have never given anyone anything free during
their existence,'' said Antonio Tavares, president of the Internet
providers association. ``Their rhetoric is of democratizing access,
but this is the kind of democracy recognizable only in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many people in the Internet business in Brazil think
that the service providers' complaints will not amount to much
unless these small companies find viable ways to compete with
larger companies, their protest has shed light on the competition
and consolidation that are advancing at a rapid pace.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the growing strength of corporate titans illustrates
how the spread of the Web in Latin America's largest country has
raised competitive pressures since the Internet was introduced on a
commercial basis in Brazil five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign concerns like America Online and PSInet Corp. are
seeking to win new customers and take market share from Universo
Online, the leading domestic service provider. Other companies,
like Telefonica SA of Spain, have made large acquisitions of
existing companies, while Microsoft Corp. is teaming up with Globo,
Brazil's largest media group, to offer high-speed access over a
network of pay-television cables.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an amazingly competitive market,'' said Bruno
Fiorentini, the managing director of Yahoo's Brazilian operations.
``You have 10 large portals competing for advertising money and now
you have the big banks. The small providers will have to find other
ways to survive or they will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Internet service providers already have reduced the
monthly fees they charge because of competitive pressure. But they
still charge anywhere from 19 to 40 reais a month, or roughly
$10.40 to $22.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the fast-consolidating market, it is no surprise
that Brazil's largest banks moved to offer free Internet service.
Taking advantage of their large client bases, which in the case of
Bradesco and Unibanco amounts to a combined 11.4 million people,
the institutions are seeking to expand revenue from their offering
of financial services and to attract new clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to lunch in any nice restaurant in Sao Paulo and you
overhear talk of Internet this and Internet that,'' said Plinio
Patrao, the superintendent of Internet operations at Unibanco,
Brazil's third-largest bank not under control of the government.
``We realized we had to be a part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the announcements of Bradesco and Unibanco
sent shares in both banks soaring on the Sao Paulo stock exchange,
other institutions have said that they are studying similar plans.
These banks include Banco Itau SA and Banco Bilbao Vizcaya of
Spain, which has a substantial Brazilian operation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While financial institutions stake out claims on Brazil's online
map, their offerings of free dial-up service to the Web have
generated lively discussion over the pricing of Internet access.
With the advent of greater competition among Internet and telephone
companies, Brazil could be headed toward a model similar to that of
some European countries where free Internet access is common.
</P>
<P>
   The deregulation of the telecommunications industry is largely
fueling this speculation. During the next several weeks, a number
of new companies are expected to start operations in competition
with existing concerns that provide conventional fixed-line
telephone service. The advent of competition in the fixed-line
business is part of a wide-reaching deregulation program that began
with the privatization of the state telecommunications monopoly in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone customers are charged by the minute for local calls in
Brazil, so it may be in these new companies' interests to work out
deals with local Internet service providers to have charges for
access to the Web imbedded in customers' phone bills instead of
charged separately. And in a newly competitive marketplace,
offering Internet access in conjunction with a given service
provider could attract new clients.
</P>
<P>
   While such a model does not appeal much to service providers
that depend on subscriptions for most of their revenues, it does
appeal to a number of other companies, like online retailers or
auctioneers, that benefit from increased customer access to the Web
in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great wonders will be done for our business with a greater
number of people on the Internet so I'm all for free access, which
I think is largely inevitable,'' said Antonio Bonchristiano, the
president of Submarino, one of Latin America's largest electronic
commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate over free access continues, the Internet service
providers association said it was considering taking legal action
with government antitrust authorities against the banks. And the
group said it was asking the government to limit the reach of the
Brazilian subsidiary of Telefonica.
</P>
</TEXT>
