<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 01/07/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- RUSSIA-GERMWARFARE --
Yevgenia Ustinov at the grave of her husband and fellow scientist
Nikolai, who died after accidentally infecting himself with the
Marburg virus, a hemorrhagic killer that he and his colleagues were
trying to perfect as a weapon. In nearly a decade since the fall of
the Soviet Union, Vector, or the State Research Center of Virology
and Biotechnology, has moved away from its past and toward peaceful
research. (Judith Miller/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- OBIT-ROSSI-B&AMP;W -- Dr. Harald
Hermann Rossi, a biophysicist who improved the ability to measure
minute amounts of ionizing radiation and their effects on living
things, died Jan. 1 at his home in Upper Nyack, N.Y. He was 82.
While he was active professionally until his death, he had been
suffering from heart disease, his family said. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- OBIT-THOMAS-B&AMP;W -- Robert
McG. Thomas Jr., a reporter for The New York Times who extended the
possibilities of the conventional obituary form, shaking the dust
from one of the most neglected areas of daily journalism, died
Thursday at his family's summer home in Rehoboth Beach, Del. He was
60 and also had a home in Manhattan. The cause was abdominal
cancer, said his wife, Joan. Jr. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- NY-DRAG-QUEENS-2 -- Ben
Sander, aka Brini Maxwell, on stage at the Glammy Awards in
Manhattan. Brini and three other drag queens - Cookie, Hedda
Lettuce and Cherry Jubilee - were all nominated in the ``Best TV
Performer'' category. The Glammys are awarded by the drag queen
community at an annual ceremony for shows telecast the previous
year. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- NY-DRAG-QUEENS-1 -- Brini
Maxwell, the svelte and stylish creation of Ben Sander, tapes a
show for his weekly cable access television program from his small
apartment in Manhattan. Maxwwell is a drag queen's answer to Martha
Stewart. Dressed in a meticulously coiffured blond wig, patent
leather pumps and an array of vintage dresses, she gushes over
obscure household tips, etiquette and recipes on her weekly show.
``Brini is a terribly good cook and hostess,'' says Sander of his
alter ego. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- COKE-CHANGES-B&AMP;W -- In its
second round of major changes this week, Coca-Cola announced Friday
that its chief marketing officer, Charles S. Frenette, seen in this
undated photo, would become president of its troubled European
operations. Frenette spent a large part of last year in Belgium,
supervising the marketing of Coca-Cola in the wake of a recall
which cost the company an estimated $200 million. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BOSTON -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- BBA-RED-SOX-LEE -- Sang Lee,
the onetime MVP from South Korea's top baseball league, during a
news conference on Friday. Earlier, Lee, the Red Sox new relief
pitcher, toured Fenway Park for the first time after the team
signed him away from Japan's Chunichi Dragons for $3.35 million
over two years. When he begins playing in the Spring, Lee will be
the first person to play in the pro leagues of Japan, Korea and the
United States. (Barry Chin/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- NUMISMATIC-SOCIETY-2 -- Ute
Wartenberg, head of the numismatic society, at its new building. A
plan to reduce the society's annual deficit of nearly $1 million by
offering buyouts to its five curators while at the same time
spending most of its endowment on this new downtown home has
sparked a rebellion among a group of its devoted members. (Ruby
Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- NUMISMATIC-SOCIETY-1 -- Dr.
James H. Schwartz at the American Numismatic Society's old
building. ``This is unique as a cultural institution,'' he says.
Since 12 Victorian gentlemen gathered for its first meeting on
April 6, 1858, in the New York home of Augustus B. Sage, the
American Numismatic Society has grown into a research institution
with one of the finest collections in the world, holding nearly a
million Greek, Roman, Islamic, Asian and medieval coins. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) FOXBORO, Mass. -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- FBN-BILLS-FLUTIE-BOS
-- Buffalo Bills quarterback Doug Flutie is pulled down by his
shirt for a sack by a New England Patriots linebacker Chris Slade
during a Dec. 26 game at Foxboro Stadium. Flutie can't remember
what he said when Wade Phillips told him he was being benched
before the Bills' 31-6 win over the Indianapolis Colts on Jan. 2.
But Flutie remembers the same thing happening with the Patriots 11
years ago. (Matthew J. Lee/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- COPYRIGHT-LAW-B&AMP;W -- The Walt
Disney copyright on Mickey Mouse hasn't kept him from evolving over
the decades. In 1989, Americans took out 95,537 patents; in 1998
the number reached 147,521 and 72,395 more were issued to
foreigners. (Walt Disney Productions/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9 --
ABOUT-CARS-SHOW-2 -- From top: The Buick Regal Cielo, the Ford 021C
and the Mercury Mountaineer. The world's automakers are using the
North American International Auto Show to roll out the vehicles
that will fill showrooms in the months ahead, along with concept
cars that usually provide a sneak preview of the vehicles that will
be on the streets in a year or two. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9 --
ABOUT-CARS-SHOW-1 -- From top: The Acura MD-X, the Mazda RX-Evolv
and the Mercedes-Benz roadster. The world's automakers are using
the North American International Auto Show to roll out the vehicles
that will fill showrooms in the months ahead, along with concept
cars that usually provide a sneak preview of the vehicles that will
be on the streets in a year or two. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9 --
PLAYBOY-PARTIES -- Party-goers of all ages enjoying Studio 54's New
Year's Eve bash, hosted by Ted Field - the Hollywood financier who
throws big, splashy, over-the-top events wherever the action is.
The guest lists are drawn up by professional party planners well
connected to modeling agencies, and the ratio of women to men is
usually about two to one. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9 --
NIGHTOUT-KATZ -- The producer James C. Katz and his wife, Marty
Wyle hoisting a few martinis at the Carlyle Cafe. Katz's new
project: a fully restored version of the 1954 Hitchcock classic
movie ``Rear Window.'' (Miles Ladin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9 --
FLAT-PANTS -- For many years, if you were a guy who preferred
flat-front to pleated pants, you were in trouble. You had to track
them down, like a big-game hunter on the trail of an endangered
species, or else have them made - until flat started to come back
in the mid-'90s. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- BUTTERFLY-OPERA-REVIEW --
Sylvie Valayre as Cio-Cio-San and Vladimir Galouzine as Pinkerton
in Puccini's ``Madame Butterfly'' at The Metropolitan Opera House.
Dramatically, Ms. Valayre makes a lovely, vulnerable and, as the
tragedy unfolds, impassioned Cio-Cio-San. Her singing is confident
and often striking. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- STERN-GERMANY -- Fritz Stern
is a Columbia University historian who has become a trusted
external judge of Germany's bitter internal debates on its history
and its new role in the world. ``I am a full-blooded non-Aryan,''
he says. ``Of course, I am completely of Jewish descent. But my
stumbling block with the description of myself as a Jewish
historian is that it was Hitler that decided I was a Jew.''
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9 --
BIZ-VALUE-AMERICA -- Glenda Dorchak, chief executive of Value
America, the online retailer, believes it grew too quickly and has
put forward turnaround plans. But its best hope may lie in being
acquired. (CNBC/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ARMY-ADS -- Staff Sgt.
Joseph Mitchell mans a recruitment table at the Potomac Gardens
housing project. With enlistments plummeting, the Army dismissed
its ad agency, Young &AMP; Rubicam, which created ``Be All That You Can
Be,'' and revamped its ad campaign, saying it will tie new
advertising contracts to performance. All branches of the armed
forces are facing a recruiting crisis. (Justin Lane/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ALABINO, Russia, -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- RUSSIA-PRINCE --
Prince Yevgeni A. Meshchersky prepares a Christmas pie with the
help of his son Dima, 6, and daughter Kataya, 13. The story of
Prince Meshchersky and his attempt to reclaim his heritage is a
tale that fits this turn-of-the-century in Russia, where many
people are wondering now, as they did 100 years ago, which way this
country is heading. (Jaqueline Mia Foster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- MUSLIM-HOLIDAY -- Celebrating
the Muslim holiday Eid Al-Fitr, commemorating the end of Ramadan,
Medhat Abdalla, 42, an Egyptian living in Manhattan, prays at the
Islamic Cultural Center on the Upper Eastside, Friday. (Librado
Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- NY-LOTTERY-WINNER -- Johnnie
Ely, who won the New York Lottery $100 Million ``Millennium
Millions'' jackpot, holds a facsimile of one of several future
checks during a news conference on Friday. Ely, 66, a former
short-order cook at a New York city restaurant, said he resigned
from his job shortly after he won. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MOZKOK, Russia, Jan. 7, 2000 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA -- Lt.
Gen. Gennady Troshev, the deputy Russian commander in Chechnya,
speaks to reporters while sitting in front of a map of the province
on Friday. Troshev said a temporary halt in its intensive air and
artillery bombardment of the capital of rebel Chechnya had been
called, but that fighting in Grozny persisted on the ground. (James
Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BETHLEHEM -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ORTHODOX-LEADERS-2 --
Orthodox Patriarch Diodoros I of Jerusalem, in a wooden wheelchair,
is greeted by orthodox patriarchs during a procession which was
part of services observing Orthodox Christmas, Friday in Bethlehem.
Patriarchs and politicians from all the major Eastern Orthodox
churches and nations filed into the fourth-century Church of the
Nativity for a Christmas service that was one of the most inclusive
gatherings of Orthodox Christian leaders in modern times. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BETHLEHEM -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- ORTHODOX-LEADERS -- Former
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, left, speaks with Suha Arafat as
her husband Yasser Arafat looks on Friday during a Mass celebrated
for Orthodox Christmas. The three-day Holy Land pilgrimage that
ended Friday was Yeltsin's first major public appearance since his
abrupt resignation that shook the world just hours before it
entered the new millennium. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) GRACANICA, Yugoslavia -- Jan. 7, 2000 -- KOSOVO-ORTHODOX
-- Kosovar Serbs with candles on Friday during an Orthodox
Christmas Eve service in a monastary south of Pristina. Many of the
Serbs who gathered Friday were hoping their festive season to
herald a prolonged period of peace after a year of violence and
turmoil. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
