</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TRUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING SAFETY, U.S. DELAYS OPENING BORDER TO TRUCKS FROM MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, citing safety concerns, has decided
to delay opening all 50 states to Mexican trucks and buses this
month, as is called for by the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials denounced the decision as a violation of the
1993 pact, which calls for letting Mexican trucks and buses travel
anywhere north of the border beginning on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insist that NAFTA allows them to delay
or suspend certain provisions when they have safety or health
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to a two-month-old inspector general's report,
which found that when 21,000 Mexican trucks were inspected at the
border, before transferring goods to American trucks, 41 percent of
the Mexican vehicles failed to meet American safety requirements.
The report found numerous serious violations, including defective
brakes, badly worn tires and nonfunctioning lights.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which was first reported by The Los Angeles Times on
Friday, delighted the powerful Teamsters union at a time when Vice
President Al Gore is vigorously seeking its endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters has long campaigned
against opening the border, pointing to the safety concerns and
fears that a large influx of low-paid Mexican truckers would cost
the jobs of thousands of American truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a sharp debate between administration
officials who did not want to anger the labor movement by opening
the border and some in the State Department and the U.S. trade
representative's office who feared that not opening the border
would strain relations with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Antonio Zabalgoitia, a spokesman for the Mexican Embassy in
Washington, said, ``The United States is in violation of the
treaty. Mexico has been insisting that the U.S. should comply with
NAFTA. The treaty is very clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between Mexico and the United States has heated up
since Mexico decided last month to move ahead with its trade suit,
in which it is seeking millions of dollars in compensation from
Washington for what it insists is wrongful closure of the border.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Clinton administration has initiated its own
trade case against Mexico, asserting that Mexico's closing of its
borders to American trucks for the last four years has constituted
improper unilateral retaliation, which the administration asserts
is illegal under NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials would not comment on how long they
thought it would take to resolve this dispute, but several industry
officials said Friday that they thought the administration would
delay any border openings until after the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party officials and some trucking executives said
that the White House decision not to open the border was intended
to help line up labor support for Gore in his battle against former
Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Collins, a spokesman for the Republican National Committee,
said, ``With the Clinton administration, you always have to suspect
that politics played a big role in any decision. But the fact is
there are legitimate safety questions here, which several of our
own candidates have made note of.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials insisted that the decision to keep the
border closed was motivated by safety concerns and not politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important factor here is the safety concern for American
motorists,'' said Jim Kennedy, a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the administration has blocked a
NAFTA provision. In December 1995, Clinton decided not to allow
Mexican trucks to travel beyond a narrow border zone and into all
of California, Texas, Arizona and New Mexico _ as was called for by
NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials had voiced optimism in recent months that the
Clinton administration, in facing a new NAFTA deadline, would make
some significant move toward opening the border to Mexican trucks
and buses on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   With trucks carrying 90 percent of the goods traded between
Mexico and the United States, the border-opening provision has long
been looked to as a major step toward removing trade barriers
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Hoffa, the Teamsters' president, hailed the
administration's decision. ``Working families throughout the United
States appreciate this bold step taken by the Clinton
administration,'' Hoffa said in a statement. ``No longer will
companies be allowed to use NAFTA to take our jobs and endanger our
health and safety.''
</P>
<P>
   In fighting any move to open the border, Teamster leaders have
over the last year organized protest rallies, made stem-winding
speeches, issued scathing reports and lined up support from nearly
half the members of Congress. The union's leaders repeatedly
asserted that opening the border would endanger the jobs and living
standards of many Teamsters because Mexican truck drivers often
earn just $2 an hour, compared with the $18 an hour earned by many
American drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes just weeks before a Jan. 26 meeting at which the
board of the 1.4-million-member Teamsters union is expected to
decide whether to endorse Gore or Bradley. The Teamsters and the
United Auto Workers union were the only two major unions to oppose
the AFL-CIO's decision last October to endorse Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Teamster officials have privately said that it
would be highly doubtful that the union would endorse Gore if the
administration opened the border to Mexican trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first indicated that he was leaning against opening the
border when he appeared in October at a New York City dinner
honoring Hoffa, where the president vigorously criticized Mexican
trucks for being unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, said Friday,
``As the president has said, we are not going to open our border
until we are sure that our legitimate safety concerns have been
addressed. Under the NAFTA, countries can take reasonable measures
as to health and safety issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speeches to the Teamsters board last fall, Bradley and Gore
opposed opening the border because of safety problems with Mexico's
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has often emphasized the need for
safer trucks, both American and Mexican, saying that he favored
tougher enforcement over continued closing of the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
