<SLUG> BC-TIMES-TELEGRAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES CO. COMPLETES PURCHASE OF WORCESTER TELEGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New York Times Co. said its acquisition of the
Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette, the third-largest daily newspaper in
Massachusetts, was completed Friday, with the previously announced
purchase price of about $295 million unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which also owns The Boston Globe, named Globe
publisher Richard H. Gilman as president of the Worcester Telegram
&AMP; Gazette Corp. A spokeswoman said financial results for both
papers will be combined for reporting purposes under a single
division of Times Co., New England Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce S. Bennett continues as the publisher of the Telegram &AMP;
Gazette, reporting to Gilman.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo to Telegram &AMP; Gazette employees, Times Co. chairman
and publisher Arthur S. Sulzberger Jr. and president and chief
operating officer Russell T. Lewis pledged ``to ensure the
editorial independence'' of the paper while seeking new revenue
opportunities and operating efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ownership of The Boston Globe and the Telegram &AMP; Gazette
will enable us to better serve readers and advertisers in the
eastern half of Massachusetts,'' Lewis said in a news release
announcing completion of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said changes in administration and procedure are
underway, including a previously disclosed plan to cut 30 jobs from
a staff of about 500. He said all employees who are 57 or older
have been offered voluntary separation packages.
</P>
<P>
   The Telegram &AMP; Gazette, with a history of morning and evening
editions dating back to 1866, had been owned by Chronicle
Publishing Co. of San Francisco since 1986, following more than
half a century of ownership by Worcester-area families. The morning
Telegram and evening Gazette were merged in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The paper's daily circulation is about 107,000 weekdays and
about 134,000 on Sundays, mostly in Worcester and Middlesex
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Times Co. also owns 22 other daily and weekly regional
newspapers, mostly in the South and West. It publishes three
magazines and operates eight television stations and two New York
City radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Another business unit, Times Company Digital, operates nearly 50
Internet Web sites, including Boston.com, eWorcester.com,
nytimes.com, and winetoday.com.
</P>
<P>
   Times Co. reported sales in 1998 at $2.9 billion, and posted
revenues of $2.25 billion for the first nine months of 1999. Shares
closed Friday on the New York Stock Exchange at 45 3/4, up 1 1/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
