<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-US-RUDDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLEGAL RUDDER MAY DOCK STARS &AMP; STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The high-flying Team Dennis Conner, with
its threadbare budget and a bunch of wise old grey heads calling
shots from the cockpit of Stars &AMP; Stripes, may have outsmarted
themselves this time. Or merely blundered.
</P>
<P>
   Having amassed the only undefeated record (3-0) after three
races in the challenger semifinals here, Stars &AMP; Stripes may get
tossed out of the regatta for breaching protocol, which is a nice
way of saying cheating.
</P>
<P>
   An international arbitration panel will decide Saturday whether
to dock Stars &AMP; Stripes one or more points. Or the panel could
remove the San Diego entry altogether. The crime is violating a
protocol requiring a boat's appendages (keels, rudders, wings,
etc.) be manufactured either in the competitor's country of origin
(in this case, the United States) or in New Zealand. The Stars &AMP;
Stripes beat Nippon in the series opener using a rudder
manufactured in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, while Team Dennis Conner was sitting on its 3-0
lead, it was notified that Nippon had issued a protest.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a race jury found Nippon's charge to be true: ``The
raw materials used to manufacture the rudder were sourced from the
USA and shipped to Australia where they were then formed, shaped,
and moulded and assembled into a rudder by the Australian
manufacturer,'' read the jury decision. ``The completed unit was
then shipped to Stars &AMP; Stripes in New Zealand.''
</P>
<P>
   The rudder was only used in the first race before it was
replaced. Stars &AMP; Stripes believed the rudder was in compliance
with what in called a ``very complicated rule.''
</P>
<P>
   If the two international panels rule Stars &AMP; Stripes has
violated the protocol, they could assess a lesser penalty, such as
the deduction of a point.
</P>
<P>
   But that still leaves a potential problem should Stars &AMP; Stripes
win the semifinals (and the Louis Vuitton Cup) to earn the right to
challenge New Zealand for the America's Cup next month.
</P>
<P>
   Under Article 8 of the Cup Protocol, the winning challenger must
be able to declare that it has ``complied with all aspects of the
conditions of Race, the Protocol, the Deed of Gift, the
Interpretive Resolutions, and the decisions of the America's Cup
Arbitration Panel.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, should Stars &AMP; Stripes win the semifinals and then be
ruled ineligible, the second-place boat _ the loser of the Vuitton
two-boat finals _ would get to race New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   As unlikely as this scenario may be, any ruling against Stars &AMP;
Stripes would make them vunerable to the eligibility issue.
</P>
<P>
   The nationality issue was most hotly contested in 1983 when
Australia II beat Conner's Liberty in Newport, R.I. The Australian
boat was fitted with a revolutionary winged keel that the New York
Yacht Club charged was designed in part by Dutch engineers in
Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout that contentious summer, New York tried to prove the
Australian-Dutch connection. Just days before the match, the NYYC
race committee considered withdrawing from the match. After a close
vote, the match went on, and Australia won the Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2141EST &QL; 
