A9945 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      01-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' FOUNDATION HAS CRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ After the Bruins' appalling loss to the
Carolina Hurricanes Thursday night, right wing Joe Murphy walked
through the locker room, stopped momentarily, and rolled his eyes
in a manner that conveyed a perfect blend of exasperation,
embarrassment, and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are in disarray and they continue to get worse, not
better. They host the New York Islanders Saturday night to start
the second half of the season, and with only one win in their last
nine games and three victories in their last 18, the second 41
games had better be a whole lot better than the first.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns has been trying to get the newest members of his
club to play the system that has made it successful the last two
seasons. That endeavor has been met with mixed results. Some
players follow it, others haven't mastered it, and others have
simply ignored it. Getting everyone on the same page has been a
significant challenge for Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a certain amount of guys pulling one way and a certain
amount of guys pulling the other way,'' said Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Jacques Laperriere had a parallel view of
things. He said there were three kinds of hockey players _ those
who made things happen, those who watched what happened, and those
who wondered what happened. On Thursday night, there were far too
many of the latter, not to mention the arena full of fans who were
tearing their hair out.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Burns spray-painted the defensive zone at the Ristuccia
Center, dividing it into four parts. The point? A back-to-basics
look at defensive responsibility. No running around, no leaving
your coverage area unless you're the designated support man, no
massive chaos as witnessed recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our zone play has been a problem,'' said Burns. ``In years
past, we took pride in not caring who scored a goal. All we cared
about was winning the game and keeping the goals-against down and
being in every game, fighting hard every game. There's a certain
way this team plays and a certain way we've had success. What we
have to do is get the individuals who weren't here into that
program. Some players have played on different teams with different
styles but they can't bring that into here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't change the way a team plays overnight and feel that
`Well, this is an easier way.' Right now, players are finding a way
not to work. We're (trying to find) an easier way to do it and
there's not really an easier way. There is a work ethic that still
has to be there no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns is also concerned that some players have more pressing
issues on their minds than the team's success. There's the issue of
individual bonuses, which tend to be divisive. There's the issue of
ice time, and some players thinking they should get more. There are
some players who would prefer to play more wide open. The coach
said he's determined to start from Square One and get his club to
focus on what's important _ winning. If they do that, he contends,
all the other stuff will take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to at least pledge allegiance to the jersey and to
the fans,'' said Burns. ``You have to at least do that no matter
what system you play, who you're playing for, and whether you like
it or not. That's what we have to get back on board now. I'd
certainly hate to see a player leave a hockey game and feel good
about himself because they scored one goal yet we lost, 7-3. I
certainly have a problem with that. That's a domino effect. We're
playing with guys who can't get down low and do their jobs. Jason
Allison can't get down low and be the defensive guy he can because
of his wrist, so we have (Anson) Carter having to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Joe (Thornton) is creating a problem, too, that he won't
go down there and do it now because he feels like maybe he's saving
energy out there. When you have 11 returning players (not including
the goalies) in the game and the other guys have no clue what went
on here before, it's a bit different. We have to get these guys on
board. It's going to be for the good of the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
