u a BC-MD-SLAIN-GIRL-NYT &LR;      01-07 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-SLAIN-GIRL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY OF GIRL WHO DISAPPEARED IN 1986 IS FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SILVER SPRING, Md. _ The mystery of Michele Dorr's disappearance
from her father's back yard in 1986 finally yielded to persistent
police work Thursday night when detectives unearthed the 6-year-old
girl's skeleton near a playground beside a highway here.
</P>
<P>
   Police would not say who led them to the grave, but people who
have followed the case assume it was Haddon Irving Clark, the
43-year-old handyman and drifter who was convicted of second-degree
murder in the girl's death.
</P>
<P>
   Medical examiners in Baltimore confirmed late Friday that the
bones were Michele's. The pink ruffled bathing suit with white
polka dots she was wearing when she disappeared _ a detail repeated
over the years of unrelenting local coverage of the case _ was
found with the bones. The towel she was carrying when her father,
Carl Dorr, last saw her skip out the door on her way to a backyard
wading pool was not found, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Edward Tarney, who had worked on the case from the
beginning, could only shake his head in relief Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all lived with this case,'' Tarney said Friday
afternoon. ``We all have kids, and it's just something you live
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorr could not be reached Friday, but late Thursday night he
came out of his modest home in Kensington to tell reporters that
the news had come as a relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have the chance to bury Michele and have a
funeral for her, which we haven't been able to do for so long,''
Dorr said. ``I still miss Michele to this day and I will continue
to miss her, but at least I'll have somewhere to say good-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Michelle disappeared on May 31, 1986, the case
gripped the Washington area _ not only because a little girl had
been stolen from the presumed safety of her home, but also because
of the bizarre and often heartbreaking detours the investigation
took.
</P>
<P>
   Michele's parents were going through a harsh divorce proceeding
at the time. Dorr was an early suspect, particularly when his
estranged wife, upon hearing that her daughter had disappeared
while visiting Dorr, had blurted out, ``Carl did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the pressure of the divorce and of his daughter's
disappearance, Dorr at one point confessed to her murder, but later
recanted. At another point he declared he was Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1993 murder of Laura Houghteling, 23, produced a break
in the case. Clark, who had done work around the house for Ms.
Houghteling's mother, confessed to the murder, and eventually led
police to Ms. Houghteling's grave near Interstate 270, north of
Washington. He was sentenced to 30 years in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   After the police had Clark in custody for the Houghteling
murder, they learned that he had lived two doors down from Dorr at
the time of Michele's disappearance, and he was charged in that
murder as well. The trial in the Dorr case turned on extensive
physical and circumstantial evidence, including testimony from a
cellmate that Clark had confessed to the killing. Clark was
convicted and sentenced to 30 years in prison last October. The
police believe he stabbed Michele to death.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, residents of the Paint Branch development took awkward
strolls to the forested playground along the northbound lane of
Route 29 where Michele's body was unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' said Andy Blanc, 15, who lives nearby. ``I've
been living here for three years and we play basketball down here _
I've been stepping on her grave all this time, and it's just scary
to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clark was the one who led police to Michele's body, it is not
known why he waited so long to do it. Clark is appealing his
conviction in the Dorr murder and the police have speculated that
he may have hoped for a break by cooperating with investigators.
Clark also says he has found religion in state prison in
Hagerstown, and he has been seen on television newscasts singing
hymns.
</P>
<P>
   Dorr, who said he never doubted that Clark was his daughter's
killer, reacted caustically to the idea that prison might have
changed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that he has developed some kind of conscience,'' Dorr
said in a television interview Friday. ``It is very difficult for
me to see him on video singing Sunday school rhymes about Jesus
making him the man that he could be.''
</P>
<P>
   For Tarney, the final chapter in the murder of Michele Dorr will
mean a little more time at home and a little less time working the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all spent a lot of time away from home while this was
going on,'' he said, ``but that's why we're here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
