<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-GEORGIA08-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: Clarifies location information in 1st graf.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Keeping close tabs on the flu
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The flu has pummeled more than a dozen Northeast and
Western states, but it has made a timid entry into Georgia so far,
according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Although metro Atlanta doctors have fielded many patient
complaints of cold- and flulike symptoms, CDC officials say this
season's flu bug has not been more severe or widespread than in
past years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Influenza activity is picking up across the country, but this
is nothing unusual for this time of year,'' said Thomas W. Skinner,
the federal agency's spokesman. ``Some areas might have been hit
harder than others, but that, too, is not unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen states reported the flu was widespread, and 22 states
reported it was a regional problem, meaning doctors are seeing more
than just a few, sporadic cases in certain areas. In other states,
flu cases are sporadic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really been in the flu season for only about two
weeks,'' said Dr. Kathryn Arnold, a state public health official.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, about 50 physicians in the state's 19 health
districts report their flu case loads each week. When a physician
in the survey reports that more than 3 percent of patients have
flulike symptoms, public health workers assume the flu is a
``regional'' problem in the state. When more than 50 percent of the
physicians report the same information, the flu is considered to be
``widespread,'' Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   In the states hardest hit, patients have been forced to wait in
halls and on gurneys in backed-up emergency departments. In some
cases, hospitals diverted patients while they struggled to add
extra staff. Those states include Colorado, Illinois, Indiana,
Iowa, Minnesota, Montana, New York, Pennsylvania, South Dakota,
Texas, Utah, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Actual numbers of flu cases are not available, state and federal
officials said. And although some hospital emergency rooms
experienced a spike in visits over the New Year's weekend _ when
doctors' offices were closed _ the crush of patients eased when
doctors reopened offices this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're experiencing a heavier load'' of patients than on a
typical day, said Dr. Stanley Mogelnicki Jr., an internist with
WellStar Towne Lake Medical Center in Woodstock, Ga., ``but that's
not out of the ordinary for this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   He said about 10 percent of his patients have come in with
flulike symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC reported that 6 percent of overall patient doctor visits
in the nation were attributed to flulike symptoms, ranging from 4
percent of cases in the New England and Mid-Atlantic regions and 15
percent in the West South Central region.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts note flu shots, which take about two weeks to be
effective, could still protect residents from the height of flu
season, expected to arrive here within three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And despite some media reports that claimed the flu shot was
ineffective against this year's strains, the CDC said that the
vaccine does offer protection. Patients also have a choice of new
anti-viral medications, including Tamiflu and Relenza released last
year, that can lessen symptoms if taken within 48 hours of the
flu's onset. Annually, up to 40 million Americans get the flu, with
about 300,000 hospitalized. Between 20,000 and 40,000 die from flu
and its complications.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Diane Stepp and the Associated Press contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT INFLUENZA
</P>
<P>
   _ This year's dominant flu virus originated in 1997 and has
caused flu for three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ It has been 25 years since a virus of this type returned for
even a second year.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CAUSES IT
</P>
<P>
   - Influenza, commonly called flu, is caused by viruses that
infect the respiratory tract.
</P>
<P>
   FLU SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Three times as many people got flu shots this year as did so
10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ The vaccine normally would be effective against a returning
virus, but flu deaths have increased this winter.
</P>
<P>
   WORST CASES
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1918, the Spanish flu caused the highest known
influenza-related mortality: Approximately 500,000 deaths occurred
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
