<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS SIT IN LIMBO, BUT THOUGHTS FLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The unsettling situation revolving around the Jets _
a team currently without an owner or a head coach _ moved into its
fourth day Friday with no resolution in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was one more bit of potentially disheartening
news for Jets fans. Mo Carthon, the team's running backs coach,
will be interviewed by the Cleveland Browns for the offensive
coordinator's post.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier it was learned that Romeo Crennel, the Jets'
defensive line coach, would be traveling to Cleveland to interview
for the defensive coordinator's job.
</P>
<P>
   Both Crennel and Carthon are part of a cohesive group of
assistants loyal to Bill Parcells, and the danger that they could
fragment during the current void has to be at least a little
worrisome to the Jets' organization.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who still remains the Jets' director of football
operations after resigning as coach on Monday, stated this week
that he would not start the search for another coach until a new
owner stepped in. But that could happen early next week. And if it
does, there will most likely be a brief period before Parcells
names the man to succeed him _ unless, of course, he is persuaded
to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of this is a short period of limbo,'' Charlie
Weis, the Jets' offensive coordinator, said Friday. ``This will get
settled. Bill will straighten this out right away.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems clear at this point is this: The most seamless move
Parcells can make is to promote an assistant coach or take over the
team himself. If Parcells taps an assistant, it appears the
front-runner for the head coach's post may now be Al Groh, the
linebackers coach who was also Parcells' defensive coordinator for
four years in New England.
</P>
<P>
   While Dan Henning, the quarterbacks coach, is the only current
Jet assistant with experience as an NFL head coach and is a
respected teacher of signal callers, his losing record as the head
coach of the Atlanta Falcons and the San Diego Chargers might make
it difficult for Parcells to sell him to the new owner, or to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   If Parcells picks from within, his chances of keeping his
assistants relatively intact will obviously improve. But at the
same time, the coaching staff is not the only matter of concern for
the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The team is about $10 million over the salary cap and obviously
has some serious restructuring to do. At least one starter,
cornerback Marcus Coleman, who is a free agent, said that with the
unsettled situation he will now wait for the free-agency period to
begin rather than re-sign immediately. The Jets have offered him a
three-year deal worth about $4 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' other heralded free agent, linebacker Mo Lewis, has
listened to his team's offer, which includes a $6 million signing
bonus. But two agents contacted Friday said they believed Lewis
would probably be moving on to another team.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets may get one break this year. Free agency is scheduled
to begin in mid-February, but the league is negotiating with the
players association to push it back to early March. If that
happens, as appears likely, then Parcells, in his role as
operations chief, will have that much more time to assess his own
players as well as those he may attempt to bring in.
</P>
<P>
   But over all, it remains an iffy time for the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one well-known agent, Brian Levy, who represents four
Jets, said the free-agency market for the team has changed because
of all the unknown factors.
</P>
<P>
   As for players re-signing with the Jets, Levy said, ``Obviously,
any type of uncertainty when you're trying to sell a team to a free
agent causes players to wonder about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy said he had not spoken with the Jets about one of his
players, Bobby Hamilton, the defensive end who will be a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if that isn't an aftereffect of what's going on,''
Levy said. ``I think that other teams will snipe at their free
agents before the situation is settled. If you don't know who the
coach is, do you want to play for them?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parcells is almost certain to have a head coach in place
by the time free agency really heats up.
   Bill Belichick _ the man who stepped down as the Jets' new coach
on Tuesday after only one day on the job and set off much of the
week's mayhem _ continued to keep a low profile Friday.
</P>
<P>
   An old friend of Belichick's, Rob Ingraham, acting as his
spokesman, said Friday that Belichick would not be making any
statement on his attorney's advice, since a grievance against the
league has now been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tagliabue, the NFL commissioner, received the grievance on
Thursday. It asked that Belichick _ who had been the Jets'
defensive coordinator before being promoted to coach to succeed
Parcells _ be freed from his Jets' contract ``so that he can make a
living in the NFL.'' The league said Friday that there had been no
further communication regarding the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets will have to respond to the letter by Monday. The
New England Patriots, who had requested permission to speak to
Belichick about becoming their coach and general manager, have not
had further dealings with the league.
</P>
<P>
   But it would not surprise anyone in football if the matter was
quickly dealt with, and that ultimately Belichick would become the
man in charge of the Patriots in exchange for one or more draft
choices yielded to the Jets by New England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
