<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9956 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-OVERVIEW-ART-     01-07 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-OVERVIEW-ART-3TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 LEADING FIRMS' FUNDS LAGGED BEHIND PEERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Md., N.Y., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The telephone rings. Your broker is on the line. He has a
suggestion: Move some of the extra cash in your account into a
mutual fund managed by his firm.
</P>
<P>
   Before you do, consider this:
</P>
<P>
   Through last November, the big five retail brokerage firms _
PaineWebber, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Salomon Smith Barney,
Prudential and Merrill Lynch _ posted three-year cumulative returns
for their diversified domestic stock funds that were 7.3 percent to
26.3 percent lower than the industry average. One-year returns also
lagged behind, by 1.8 percent to 7.9 percent, according to Kanon
Bloch Carre, a Boston consulting firm that compiled its rankings
through asset-weighting _ giving large funds more weight than
smaller ones.
</P>
<P>
   For all international funds, the relative performances of the
same five brokerage firms were even poorer. Weighted by assets, the
cumulative returns of their international offerings trailed the
industry average by more than 20 percent over the three years,
Kanon Bloch found, and by 2.5 percent to 21 percent over the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The big brokerage firms have ``fumbled the  mutual
funds,'' said John Rekenthaler, research director at Morningstar
Inc., the financial publisher in Chicago. ``They took their
position for granted,'' he added, ``and they lacked the hunger that
a lot of other mutual fund companies have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are some flowers amid the weeds. The Merrill
Lynch Pacific fund, for example, has been the top fund in its
category over the last decade, according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, brokerage firms' funds have not been known for
standout performance. And since the bull market shifted into
overdrive in the mid-1990s, the relative overall record of the
brokerage funds has been downright dismal. Many investors who
bought in-house funds have paid a steep price in lost
opportunities, as many other broker-sold funds _ including those of
Alliance Capital, MFS Investments and AIM _ have outpaced their
investments.
</P>
<P>
   But investors seem to be waking up. Or perhaps some brokers are
splashing some cool water on their clients' faces. Whatever the
case, investors are yanking assets out of brokerage-managed funds.
The top five retail brokerage firms, which started 1999 with a
combined $240 billion in long-term assets in their funds, had
combined estimated outflows of more than $13 billion through
November, according to the Financial Research Corp., an industry
researcher in Boston. In the previous decade, combined flows had
never been negative, and as recently as 1993 the five firms enjoyed
$30 billion in inflows.
</P>
<P>
   The outflows, poor performance and new competition from index
funds and others have had a big effect on market share: Brokerage
firms now have 10 percent of all mutual fund assets, down from 19
percent a decade ago, according to Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The poor performance has been humiliating for some large firms
at a time when the fortunes of so many fund groups have soared.
</P>
<P>
   In-house funds are ``almost a trademark or signature product
within a company,'' said Raymond A. Mason, known as Chip, chief
executive of Legg Mason, a regional brokerage firm in Baltimore
whose largest fund, Legg Mason Value Trust, has beaten the S&AMP;P 500
stock index for nine consecutive years. ``It often ends up a
reflection of the firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some big brokerage firms _ which look to money
management as a more stable and reliable source of profits than
investment banking or stock-trading commissions _ are scrambling to
revamp their ailing fund businesses and to improve their funds'
performance.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen whether those efforts will pay off, or
whether investors shouldn't continue to be skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who buy through a broker or other intermediary
generally pay a load of 4 percent to 6 percent of the purchase
price, which compensates the broker for time and expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Although many investors now invest only in no-load funds, more
rely on brokers for advice and hand-holding and thus still own load
funds. But how does a broker decide what to recommend to a client?
Apparently, that depends on where the broker works, as some
brokerage firms have had far greater success than others in selling
in-house funds.
</P>
<P>
   Cerulli Associates, a research group in Boston, estimates that
80 percent of the money invested in funds by Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter's customers goes into the firm's own funds. That compares
with 45 percent at Merrill; 35 percent at Salomon Smith Barney, a
unit of Citigroup; 25 percent at Prudential; and 10 percent at
PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Selling such funds raises the potential for a conflict between a
broker's desire to make money for the firm and his duty to steer
clients into the most suitable investments.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, has discouraged brokerage firms from using higher
payouts or other incentives to push proprietary funds over outside
funds. A panel he appointed, led by Daniel P. Tully, the former
chairman of Merrill Lynch, reported in 1995 that some firms still
paid brokers more for selling proprietary products, and it urged
the firms to stop the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say such differentiated payouts have stopped
at almost all _ if not all _ large firms, and the regulatory unit
of the National Association of Securities Dealers is weighing a
rule prohibiting higher payouts for proprietary sales.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say, however, that incentives to sell in-house
funds have vanished. Some industry executives say in-house fund
sales at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter lead to higher compensation for
branch managers at the firm _ giving brokers who want to win favor
with the boss an incentive to push proprietary funds.
</P>
<P>
   A Morgan Stanley executive declined to say whether branch
manager compensation was affected by the level of proprietary fund
sales. Officials at Merrill Lynch and Salomon Smith Barney said
their compensation of branch managers was not affected by
proprietary sales. PaineWebber and Prudential officials declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions about the performance of Merrill
Lynch's funds, a spokeswoman, Christine Walton, said that ``changes
in Merrill Lynch's asset management group in the past year have
sharpened our focus'' on earning high returns. Results are already
apparent, she said, noting that the Merrill Lynch Growth fund fell
by 24 percent in 1998 but returned 26 percent last year, following
a manager change.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney officials, in response tame
questions, said their stock funds took in close to $1 billion in
new money this year, although investor withdrawals from bond funds
meant that overall flows were slightly negative. But they disputed
Financial Research's methodology in calculating the firm's flows.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Morgan Stanley said they had positive cash flows
in each of the last few years, which they attributed to what they
called their funds' solid and steady performance. They said many of
their funds received four or five stars _ the two highest rankings
_ from Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential is expected to introduce funds this year that will
bring a broader range of styles and market capitalizations to its
lineup. ``During the past year, Prudential has integrated all of
its asset management expertise into one group,'' said Timothy
Biggs, a spokesman. ``We are now bringing the strength of that
organization to bear on our mutual fund offerings.''
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber executives declined to discuss their funds'
investment performance or cash flows.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, of course, means that your broker is doing
anything wrong if he recommends investing in in-house funds. Some
of those funds have strong records. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's
Small Cap Growth fund B shares, for example, soared 41.1 percent,
annualized, over the five years through Dec. 31, putting it near
the very top of its peer group, according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   But the discrepancy between the performance of such standouts
and most other broker-managed funds is eye-opening. According to
Kanon Bloch, the diversified domestic equity funds managed by the
five large brokerage firms had cumulative asset-weighted returns
for the three years ended in November of 51.3 percent to 70.3
percent _ all below the industry average of 77.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For international funds _ including stock and bond funds _ the
five returned 24.4 percent to 39.9 percent over the three years,
not even close to the industry average of 60.7 percent, according
to Kanon Bloch.
</P>
<P>
   In its calculations, Kanon Bloch used Merrill Lynch's ``B''
class of fund shares _ which have the most assets but also higher
expense ratios than other classes, thus reducing returns somewhat.
Calculations for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter do not include results
from two fund families it acquired _ Miller Anderson &AMP; Sherrerd,
whose funds go by the name MAS, acquired in 1995, and Van Kampen
Investments, added in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Including those results, the firm's diversified domestic equity
funds had a 77.3 percent cumulative three-year return, just under
the industry average, and its international funds returned 38.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   So what accounts for big firms' overall lackluster returns? A
good deal of it stems from the brokerage funds' conservative bent
and their emphasis on the value style of investing during a period
in which large-cap growth stocks and highflying technology shares
have dominated the market.
</P>
<P>
   But the particular _ some would say peculiar _ nature of the
brokerage firm fund business has clearly added to the problems,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, fund performance was not crucial to the success of
an asset management unit. ``The idea was to let the outside funds
be spectacular, because when they go up, they attract money, and
when they go down, that gives a chance for the representative to
move the money out'' into one of the firm's own funds, said A.
Michael Lipper, chairman of Lipper Inc., the research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Because the firms' mutual fund units have what the industry
calls ``captive'' shareholders for their funds, drumming up
enthusiasm in the sales force has been more important than
performance in attracting assets. For years, a number of securities
firms even paid brokers extra-large commissions for selling
in-house funds.
</P>
<P>
   But as pressure from regulators _ in the wake of what became
known as the Tully Report _ led firms to quit favoring in-house
funds, and as investors have gotten easier access to performance
data, brokers and investors alike have become quicker to sell
shares of any underperformer.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, every brokerage firm's fund family is just a part of a
larger financial-services company, where most of the attention
traditionally has been on retail brokerage, investment banking or
trading. Those activities are the usual routes to the top positions
at such firms; asset management is not.
</P>
<P>
   Such firms are ``typically very, very political operations, and
there is a great rivalry between the capital markets, retail and
investment banking people,'' said Burton Greenwald, a consultant in
Philadelphia. ``You don't have that in a typical mutual fund
management company.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Given that, it makes sense that many people who want to make
stock-picking their life's work go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Some performance factors are easier to quantify. Many of the
larger funds managed by the big brokerage firms have annual
operating expenses that are higher than the industry average, even
though such expenses should decline as assets rise because the fund
is spreading fixed costs over a larger base.
</P>
<P>
   Even big index funds are not immune: Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
according to Morningstar, has almost $2 billion in an S&AMP;P 500 Index
fund that charges a 1.5 percent expense ratio. (The T. Rowe Price
Equity Index 500 fund, by contrast, charges just 0.40 percent
annually.)
</P>
<P>
   Such disparities can make a huge difference over time: $10,000
invested in a fund that returns 15 percent a year for a decade will
grow to $40,500; the same amount compounding at 14 percent a year,
because its expense ratio is a point higher, will grow to just
$37,100.
</P>
<P>
   HigH fees might be forgivable if brokerage firms used the money
to pay for star managers. But their pay packages generally do not
approach those for managers at firms like American Funds, Fidelity
Investments, Putnam Investments and Janus, industry compensation
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage firms ``tend to spend as much money marketing the
product as they do on investment technology or investment talent to
manage the funds,'' said William Dougherty, president of Kanon
Bloch. ``They're marketing companies, and they tend to sell their
funds regardless of the performance.''
</P>
<P>
   With fund flows tepid, the firms are trying to turn their funds'
performance around. Salomon Smith Barney has been moving toward a
more consistent and rigorous investment approach that will adhere
more closely to capitalization and style classifications like value
and growth, industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The change reflects the backgrounds of the two co-chairmen of
SSB Citi Asset Management Group, which includes the firm's mutual
fund unit: Peter Carman, former head of equities at Putnam, and
Thomas W. Jones, former chief operating officer of TIAA-CREF, the
huge pension fund for educators.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, PaineWebber hired Brian M. Storms away from
Prudential Investments to become president of its Mitchell Hutchins
Asset Management arm. In December, the firm bought an index-fund
boutique, DSI International Management, and it plans to roll out
several enhanced index funds this year. (Last month, it also showed
that its brokers can still pitch a fund, raising $2.1 billion for
one that invests in stocks recommended by Edward M. Kerschner, a
respected PaineWebber strategist.)
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, created when Morgan Stanley merged
with Dean Witter, Discover in 1997, has been integrating its fund
units. That has led to some cross-pollination, with managers from
the different fund groups serving as subadvisers for funds in other
families.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest changes may be at Merrill Lynch. Jeffrey M.
Peek, appointed head of Merrill Lynch Asset Management two years
ago, brought in Robert C. Doll Jr., Oppenheimer Funds' chief
investment officer, to run its fund unit and led a shake-up of the
business last year.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill has also been moving to promote new growth-fund
offerings and has hired a new index-fund team from Deutsche Bank.
And it has added respected portfolio managers like James McCall,
formerly of Pilgrim Baxter &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are no guarantees in the fund business. That is why
Edward Jones, the nation's seventh-largest brokerage firm, has long
had a policy of not selling its own brand of funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never want our name on any mutual fund, because from time
to time, the performance is going to disappoint,'' said John
Bachmann, managing principal of the firm, ``and we certainly don't
want our customers blaming us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
