<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MIAMI-CLUB-MAFIA-680&AMP;     01-07 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-CLUB-MAFIA-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAMOROUS WELL-WISHERS MEET IN COURT FOR A CLUB FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The glamorous world of Miami Beach celebrity culture
collided Friday with the gritty workings of what prosecutors called
a Brooklyn Mafia crew, as a South Florida nightclub impresario
charged with murder was ordered released from custody on $15
million bail.
</P>
<P>
   As a white stretch limousine waited at the curb outside U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn, two fixtures of South Beach nightlife,
Ingrid Casares, a restaurateur, and Sofia Vergara, a model and
Spanish-language television personality, milled in the hallways
with their publicist, Lizzie Grubman, waiting to offer the
nightclub owner, Chris Paciello, support.
</P>
<P>
   Paciello, 28, whose real name is Christian Ludwigsen, moved from
Staten Island to Miami in 1993 and quickly opened a string of
glittering restaurants and dance clubs, including Liquid and the
Bar Room, that attracted the likes of Madonna and the actress
Gwyneth Paltrow. But in November, just as he was planning to open
another club, he was accused in a federal indictment of being a
member of a robbery squad connected to the Bonanno organized crime
family. He turned himself in to the authorities in Florida on Dec.
1.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Brooklyn contend that on Feb. 18, 1993, Paciello
drove the getaway car during a botched robbery in which a Staten
Island woman, Judith Shemtov, 46, was fatally shot. He has also
been charged with robbing a Chemical Bank branch at the Staten
Island Mall on Dec. 14, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Paciello has denied the charges, and his lawyer, Roy Black, said
Friday that the government's accusations were a result of his
client's fame, not any ties to organized crime. ``Unfortunately,
the way our society works,'' Black said, ``when someone becomes a
successful or high-profile person, they also become a target.''
</P>
<P>
   Paciello walked into the courtroom for his bail hearing on
Friday smiling at Ms. Casares, his business partner, and Ms.
Vergara, the co-host of a television show on the Univision network,
who described herself as Paciello's former girlfriend. The two
women stood in court beside members of Paciello's family, including
his grandfather, Louis. In turn, each agreed to secure a share of
the $15-million bail with cash, securities and their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of bail surprised even prosecutors, who said it was
one of the highest they had ever seen. By comparison, John A.
Gotti, the acting boss of the Gambino crime family, was required to
put up $10 million when he was released from federal custody in
October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions of Paciello's bail agreement were as severe as
its cost, prompting the presiding judge, Magistrate Joan M. Azrack,
to announce to the court, ``There are more conditions on this bond
than I think I've ever seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Paciello will be required to live at his
mother's home in Staten Island for almost three months. He will be
subjected to round-the-clock video surveillance and random
unannounced visits, and he is barred from owning a cellular phone
or pager. On April 1, he will be allowed to move to his home in
Florida, Ms. Azrack said, with similar restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   As the hearing drew to a close, Paciello blew a kiss to his
supporters and was led from the courtroom. His release could take
two to three weeks, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   After the bail hearing, Paciello was taken to a separate
courtroom where he joined the eight other defendants named in the
racketeering indictment. The other defendants, mostly men in their
20s from Brooklyn, are known in court papers as the Bath Avenue
Crew because they grew up near Bath Avenue in Bensonhurst. Anthony
Spero, whom prosecutors described as the former acting boss of the
Bonanno family, is also one of the defendants in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges the men with six murders and with trying
to commit four more while working with the Bonanno family between
1991 and 1995. They are also accused of a dozen other charges,
including arson, extortion and selling marijuana and crack cocaine.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jim Walden, an assistant U.S. attorney, said in court Friday
that the government was close to working out a plea deal with one
of the defendants, whom he would not identify. As Walden and a team
of defense lawyers, including Gerald L. Shargel, who has
represented both Gotti and his father, John J. Gotti, addressed
Judge Edward R. Korman, Paciello mouthed endearments to his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Maryann Reynolds, the mother of one defendant,
Thomas Reynolds, said she was tired of being in court because,
``Nothing gets done, nothing gets solved.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Ms. Casares came out of the courthouse, Ms. Reynolds,
who lives on Staten Island, acceded to the glow of celebrity,
telling reporters: ``Ingrid's here. Everyone can leave me now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
