<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS AND STRIPES CAUGHT UP IN DISPUTE OVER RUDDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ It was a vintage America's Cup news
cycle: accusations and revelations off the water; high intensity
and close-quarter racing on the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's what all the sailors live for,'' said Paul
Cayard, the skipper of America One, after his crew and new boat had
beaten Nippon Challenge by 23 seconds on Friday. ``Those kinds of
races where the boats are not the factor, and where the crews are
tacking and grinding, and getting the sails up and down makes all
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   This contentious competition is seldom so straightforward,
however, and on Friday night the regatta's international jury
convened to consider a protest against Team Dennis Conner's Stars
and Stripes. The jury's deliberations could complicate matters
considerably for Stars and Stripes, which leads the challenger
semifinals with a 3-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon, which lost to Stars and Stripes on the first day of the
six-team semifinals, had protested that Conner's team used an
illegal rudder in the race. The rudder was, Nippon claimed, in
breach of Article 19 of the America's Cup protocol because it was
not made in the United States or in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the rudder was designed by American designers
but manufactured in Australia with materials shipped from the
United States. The rudder was installed for the semifinals and then
quickly removed after the opening victory over Nippon and replaced
by a rudder of wholly American origin.
</P>
<P>
   Why was it replaced so hastily? Conner was not saying. ``It's a
little bit like Monica Lewinsky talking about her case while it's
still going on. It's not really appropriate,'' Conner said
Saturday, shortly before Stars and Stripes raced America One. ``But
we're quite confident that we'll be fine and we haven't violated
any rules and that we'll be totally vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   The other syndicates believe the rudder was replaced because
America True, the team headed by Dawn Riley, had asked the
arbitration panel for a clarification of Article 19: a request that
the panel still has not answered formally.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Stars and Stripes is indeed in breach of
the rules. The arbitration panel opened deliberations Saturday and
has asked each of the semifinalists to provide its interpretations
of Article 19. It will then reconsider the issue on Sunday morning,
make a formal interpretation and refer the matter back to the jury
for action if required.
</P>
<P>
   Article 19 reads: ``Providing a Challenger's yacht arrives in
New Zealand with appendages (including foils, bulbs, canards, etc.)
designed by a national and manufactured in the country of the
Challenger, further appendages may be constructed in New Zealand
for that yacht provided they have been designed by a national of
the country of the Challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Nippon certainly thinks it understands its meaning. In a news
release issued Saturday, it said, ``The protocol is loud and clear
even when it is translated in Japanese, French, Italian or any
other language.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Marcus Hutchinson, a spokesman for the Louis
Vuitton Cup, as the challenger series is known, possible penalties
could include forcing Stars and Stripes to re-race Nippon; granting
a point to the Japanese and stripping a point from the Americans,
or even expelling Stars and Stripes on the grounds that it would no
longer be eligible to compete in the America's Cup finals against
New Zealand should it win the Challenger series.
</P>
<P>
   Conner has spent much of his career navigating amid America's
Cup controversy. ``There's nothing in the rules that says the
rudder can't be made in Australia,'' he said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's hearing, Stars and Stripes was represented by Peter
Isler, Peter Holmberg and Tom Whidden. According to a witness, they
said Stars and Stripes did not believe the nationality rules
applied to underwater appendages like rudders and argued that the
nationality issue had been diluted in the modern America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Stars and Stripes has not raced since Wednesday, when it damaged
its stern scoop in a collision with Le Defi Francais. Stars and
Stripes, which seems to perform better in higher wind conditions,
was to return to action against America One in light to moderate
winds. The race matched the two leaders in the series _ America One
is now 3-1 with six races remaining in this round, which will cut
the challengers from six to two. Prada and Nippon are 2-2. America
True is 1-2 and Le Defi Francais is 0-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
