<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; CES  &LR; _ As Bay Area commuters know all too well, getting stuck in
traffic is a grand waste of time. But at the Consumer Electronics
Show this week, big companies such as Motorola and Sony joined with
startups like Command Audio to unveil new computer-controlled,
voice-activated, Web-attached automobile gizmos designed to fill
those wasted commute hours with productivity, not to mention
distractions. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; XILINX  &LR; _ Keeping up with the Joneses may soon get a bit easier, at
least when it comes to making sure your cell phone, TV and other
consumer electronics devices can do all the latest tricks _ without
making you trade up for a new model. That's the promise of a new
family of ``future-proof'' chips thatsemiconductor vendor Xilinx
plans to unveil on Monday. The chips, which will cost as little as
$10 apiece in volume, will allow manufacturers of next-generation
digital devices to add new features, as well as fix bugs, simply by
offering software updates for users to download over the Internet.
By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; VISA _ &LR;  Anybody who has surfed stock message boards on Internet
sites such as Yahoo or Silicon Investor has seen them _ anonymous,
sometimes scurrilous postings that dis a company, its management
and its products.
</P>
<P>
   ZixIt, a Dallas designer of Internet commerce software, noticed
a raft of such missives on the company's Yahoo message board last
year, placed by posters identified only as ``twenex,''
``stockerama'' or similar aliases.
</P>
<P>
   ZixIt's Web transaction-authorization system had ``no chance of
success,'' its stock was ``a sure way to financial ruin'' and its
CEO was ``busy smoking a big fat cigar and laughing his ass off,''
messages warned. Typical Internet fare. Except, it turned out, more
than 400 such messages were posted by Paul Guthrie, vice president
of technology research at Foster City's Visa International, which
sells a system that competes directly against ZixIt's e-commerce
software. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
</TEXT>
