r f BC-VISA-VISA_SFCHRON &LR;      01-07 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-VISA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Stock Message Board Brouhaha Flares  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Anybody who has surfed stock message boards on Internet sites such
as Yahoo or Silicon Investor has seen them _ anonymous, sometimes
scurrilous postings that dis a company, its management and its
products.
<P>
   ZixIt, a Dallas designer of Internet commerce software, noticed
a raft of such missives on the company's Yahoo message board last
year, placed by posters identified only as ``twenex,''
``stockerama'' or similar aliases.
</P>
<P>
   ZixIt's Web transaction-authorization system had ``no chance of
success,'' its stock was ``a sure way to financial ruin'' and its
CEO was ``busy smoking a big fat cigar and laughing his ass off,''
messages warned.
</P>
<P>
   Typical Internet fare. Except, it turned out, more than 400 such
messages were posted by Paul Guthrie, vice president of technology
research at Foster City's Visa International, which sells a system
that competes directly against ZixIt's e-commerce software.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of December, ZixIt sued Visa in a Texas court,
charging the giant credit card association with libel. Guthrie's
Yahoo postings were ``malicious, highly arrogant, and filled with
false statements,'' ZixIt's complaint charged.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the complaint said, they were part of a larger ``plan
to destroy ZixIt through various means, including improper
intimidation, anonymous fronts, and business and personal
disparagement.'' The company demanded a jury trial and unspecified
monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   Visa admits that Guthrie posted the messages and may have done
so while on the job. But it insists he was acting on his own.
``There was no knowledge or approval by anyone at Visa,'' said
spokesman Michael Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   Visa said Guthrie is still an employee but wouldn't comment on
whether he has been disciplined. Guthrie, who supervises Visa
technology initiatives including the e-commerce software, didn't
return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the episode is a classic David versus Goliath
story: Was mighty Visa, with 21,000 bank members and 5,000
employees worldwide, trying to crush tiny ZixIt, which is still in
the development stage with no revenue and just 78 employees?
</P>
<P>
   From another angle, though, the ZixIt /Visa spat shows how the
Internet speeds up and intensifies all kinds of communication. And
that presents a new array of challenges to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like this have been happening in the real world for
centuries,'' said Henry Dinger, a Boston e-commerce lawyer with the
firm Goodwin, Procter &AMP; Hoar, citing anonymous slander campaigns
and phony letters to the editor. ``The Internet is exacerbating the
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say it's not clear what responsibility Visa has to
control the Internet behavior of its employees, given the rapid
development of technology and law.
</P>
<P>
   Visa and other organizations have issued rules regulating
Internet use and notified employees that their Web activity could
be monitored, in part because of legal concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was ZixIt, not Visa, that fingered Guthrie. ZixIt
declined to say how it identified the Visa executive. It may have
had outside help. In recent years, investigative agencies have
sprung up nationwide that track down Internet posters.
</P>
<P>
   That Guthrie was exposed proves one thing. On the Internet, said
Dinger, ``people are not as anonymous as they think they are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
