<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, JAN. 8
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-HUNGARY-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 2,
about Hungary and the Sacred Crown of St. Stephen referred
incorrectly to the Hungarian Truth and Life Party; it is not a
member of the governing coalition. The article also misspelled the
name of the site where St. Stephen is entombed; it is
Szekesfehervar, not Szekesfehervom.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incorrectly to the language group that
includes Hungarian. It includes Estonian and some languages used by
indigenous peoples in northern Russia, not just Finnish.
</P>
<P>
   BC-REPUBS-DEBATES-NYT (moved on Thursday, Jan. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Jan. 6,
about the previous night's debate among Republican presidential
candidates misattributed a comment. After Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas said, ``I would take an expression into the Oval Office of
`Dear God _ help me!''' it was Gary L. Bauer, not Alan Keyes, who
replied, ``So would we, Governor.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-GEOGHEGAN (moved on Wednesday, Dec. 29)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of John J. Geoghegan, sent by the New York Times
News Service on Wednesday, Dec. 29, omitted a surviving son. He is
John J. Geoghegan III of San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
