r f BC-CES-FINBUDGET_SFCHRON     01-07 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CES-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 A Trunkful of Car Gadgets  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
As Bay Area commuters know all too well, getting stuck in traffic
is a grand waste of time.
<P>
   But at the Consumer Electronics Show this week, big companies
such as Motorola and Sony joined with startups like Command Audio
to unveil new computer-controlled, voice-activated, Web-attached
automobile gizmos designed to fill those wasted commute hours with
productivity, not to mention distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers soon will be able to download spoken versions of their
e-mail, the latest stock quotes or stories from the Wall Street
Journal while they're waiting to get past the morning mess at the
Bay Bridge toll plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can use the time to record their favorite music from
their CD collections or MP3-formatted songs downloaded off the
Internet while negotiating Hospital Curve. And mom and dad can
sidetrack their kids from bickering in the back seats by flicking
on a video (or DVD) of ``The Matrix'' on the new theater systems
designed for cars.
</P>
<P>
   Car stereos are no longer just car stereos.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first car didn't even have a radio,'' said James Armstrong
of Point  &LR;   &LR; Roberts, Wash., as he checked out a special GMC Yukon
sport utility vehicle decked out with about $2,500 worth of JVC
audio and video electronics. The gear included a DVD player,
computer navigation system, two independent video screens for the
rear seats, two headphones for the passengers and booming 12-inch
subwoofers for the driver and anyone else standing within earshot
of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   To judge by some of the exhibits at the annual electronics
extravaganza in Las Vegas, auto dealers may soon start using more
megahertz instead of more horsepower to sell cars.
</P>
<P>
   Computer chips are already in use throughout even the average
sedan in everything from engine controls to stereo systems. But
now, electronics companies are bringing the Web to cars.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, Clarion Corp. and Ford Motor Co. unit Visteon
Automotive Systems all unveiled new in-dash or dash-mounted car
computers that they hope to start shipping later this year. Each
offers a wider range of services than the standard AM-FM cassette
deck, to put it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Motorola's iRadio, with models costing between $500
and $1,000, combines digital cellular phone service, satellite
links and the Internet to allow drivers to download traffic reports
on demand, instead of having to wait until an on-the-air radio
station broadcasts them.
</P>
<P>
   A driver also can get e-mail, updated stock quotes, tune in 100
different radio stations delivered by satellites, download
MP3-formatted digital music and find the nearest McDonald's or dry
cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Motorola announced a partnership with Redwood City
startup Command Audio Inc., which is trying to sell a subscription
service for drivers to download audio versions of written news,
sports and information from sources like Time magazine and the Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Command Audio, which also markets a handheld receiver made by
RCA, initiated the service last month in Denver and Phoenix,
although it may not reach its own home market until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But chief executive Don Bogue believes interest in the
$15-per-month Command Audio subscriptions will accelerate because
both motorists and mass transit riders want to make better use of
their travel time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there's a great opportunity in addressing the market
for mobile consumers,'' Bogue said. ``For all consumers, there is
just an explosive amount of media, but just less and less time to
consume it. They don't have time to read a daily newspaper
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the iRadio, Visteon's ICES, which stands for Information,
Communication, Entertainment and Security, is linked to a Web site
so a driver can personalize a selection of entertainment and data.
The voice-activated ICES may be out in the second quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Markatos, Visteon's multimedia and electronic systems
supervisor, conceded the initial $3,200 cost of a ``fully
installed'' ICES will initially turn off the average car buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price point has got to come down to $500, but it can in
time with (sales) volume,'' Markatos said. That may happen by 2003,
especially as more car computer systems are sold overall, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarion Corp., showed off the ``concept'' of its
second-generation AutoPC, which can play MP3 music and run two
video screens for rear-seat passengers to view DVD movies and video
games.
</P>
<P>
   Jukka Rissanen, a Clarion marketing specialist, said the company
hasn't released the sales numbers for its first-generation AutoPC,
which went on the market last year. But he said the newer model
might be ready for sale in the fall at about the same price,
$1,600.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of MP3, the popular audio format used to compress songs
downloaded from the Internet, Atlanta's i2go.com introduced its eGo
player. The $270 device not only plays MP3 music through a car
stereo, but can compress e-mail messages into an MP3 format and
read back the text in a synthesized human voice.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer electronics giant Sony Corp. is also trying to fill
drive time, in particular, the commute hours of trendy digital-age
GenerationY youth.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Electronics Inc. unleashed several new car products under
its year-old Xplod brand, including an AM-FM stereo that can record
songs onto a MiniDisc.
</P>
<P>
   The MD Record, due to hit the U.S. market in March at a retail
price of $699, allows drivers to record tracks from their CDs,
using an optional CD changer, or from the radio.
</P>
<P>
   It has a 10-second memory so users can record songs or programs
off the radio even after they started. An included timer can record
up to 80 minutes worth of a programming after the driver leaves the
car.
</P>
<P>
   Even people too busy to record their favorite songs at home,
``have some time in the car,'' said Romeo Hakusui, a senior vice
president for Sony's mobile communications division.
</P>
<P>
   The era of the drive-in theater may be dead, but electronics
manufacturers are trying to create a new drive-on theater
phenomenon. At CES, there were a slew of products to turn that car
or SUV into a rolling entertainment unit, including new car DVD
video players from Sony and Panasonic.
</P>
<P>
   There were also kits like the $700 Back Seat Theater from TMI
Products Inc. of Corona (Riverside County).
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone is worried about all that expensive equipment
luring thieves, Clifford Electronics of Southern California offered
a new car security system that can be controlled remotely through
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of these smart car devices said their ease of use and
often hands-free operation should make them safe to operate while
driving. Yet there is already a national debate about whether the
use of cell phones in cars is safe, although attempts to ban their
use have failed except in one Midwest town. A New England Journal
of Medicine study showed drivers using cell phone were 34 percent
more likely to have an accident than drivers without cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Harrington, communications director with the nonprofit
National Safety Council, was concerned the new car devices
introduced in Las Vegas also will take drivers' eyes and minds off
the roads if not used with proper precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if it's hands-free,'' said Harrington. ``If
you bought technology stocks on Monday, you wouldn't be feeling
good about it today, so as you're making your expletive-deleted
comments, you have to be aware that does add to the risks that
you're going to hit something.''
</P>
<P>
   And he noted motor vehicle accidents are the leading cause of
death for people age 25 and under. ``They're targeting a market
that needs to pay attention to driving the most,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
