<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unemployment Rate Stayed At 4.1 Percent in December
</P>
<P>
   Employers created 315,000 new nonfarm jobs in December, 75,000
more than economists had predicted and the biggest one-month gain
since July. With more people entering the work force, the
unemployment rate remained at a 30-year low of 4.1 percent, where
it has been for the last three months. The report showed that
unemployment for all of 1999 averaged 4.2 percent, down from 4.5
percent in 1998 and the lowest rate since 1969, when it was 3.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Average hourly earnings for the month rose by 0.4 percent,
slightly more than expected. But because workers are producing more
for each hour worked, the growth in wages so far shows few signs of
setting off a surge in inflation. The figures increased the
likelihood that the Federal Reserve will increase interest rates
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Granada Group Plans to Buy a Rival
</P>
<P>
   Granada Group, a leading British operator of television
networks, hotels and restaurants, said it plans to buy either
Carlton Communications or United News and Media in an effort to
block the $6.6 billion merger of the two companies and win control
of Britain's commercial television industry.
</P>
<P>
   Army Set to Change Its Advertising
</P>
<P>
   With recruiters struggling to fill its ranks, the Army plans to
overhaul its advertising and marketing campaign. It will end its
contract with Young &AMP; Rubicam advertising agency after 12 years and
plans to stop using its slogan, ``Be all that you can be.''
Officials have had a difficult time putting their finger on what it
is about the slogan, or its intended audience, that makes for a fit
that is not quite comfortable. They simply have a general sense
that the motto does not seize today's young people, and that the
service could also do a better job of marketing its mission to
older people.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Internet Providers Protest
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian Association of Internet Providers protested plans
by two prominent banks to provide free access to the World Wide
Web. The association said the move may inhibit competition because
its members _ small providers of Internet access _ may be forced
out of business by the big competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Wins Name Spat
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter won a fight to take possession of an
Internet domain name for its new online trading site. The name was
given up by a California teen-ager who had registered the names of
dozens of well-known brands and Wall Street brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch Reimburses a Client
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch said it reimbursed millions of dollars to the Arab
International Bank and was pursuing prosecution of a former
Egyptian employee who may have misappropriated the funds.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and NAACP in a Job Pact
</P>
<P>
   Two days after NBC announced an agreement with the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, ABC said it
reached its own deal with Kweisi Mfume, the president of the NAACP.
ABC said it intended ``to increase opportunities for qualified
people of color in the network television industry'' both in front
of and behind the camera, and underscored its existing diversity
plans, such as formal mentoring plans and programs to encourage
minority writers.
</P>
<P>
   McLeodUSA to Acquire Splitrock
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications company McLeodUSA said that it would buy
the data communications provider Splitrock Services for about $1.75
billion in stock to widen its service offerings beyond voice
telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Central Banker Nominated
</P>
<P>
   Israel's prime minister nominated a senior central bank
economist, David Klein, as the bank's next governor, signaling a
continuing hard line against inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
