<HEADER>
A9974 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-DISABLED-SURVIVAL-$AD     01-07 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-SURVIVAL-$ADV09-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING HARD CHOICES AS THE DISABLED AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Md., Ariz. )(ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 9)  
(DW) 
 By BRUCE FELTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Margaret Moran's parents died within six weeks of each
other in 1975, her first concern was for her brother, Jimmy,
developmentally disabled since birth. Ms. Moran was 30 and working
in Boston as a book editor. Jimmy, four years older, was living in
a group residence in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our parents gone, I knew there was nothing to do but step
in and take responsibility for him,'' she said. ``I didn't want to.
But someone had to make sure he was well taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Morans had left $140,000 to cover their son's financial
needs. The money, which was invested in money market funds, had
dwindled to $269 by last July. While Philadelphia County has since
picked up most of the $93-a-day residence bill, the balance comes
out of Jimmy's $680 monthly Social Security check, leaving Ms.
Moran with $271 to pay for medical care, clothing and other
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't go very far,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Had he been born a generation earlier, Jimmy Moran would
probably have died before his inheritance ran out; a developmental
disability often meant a shortened life expectancy. But now,
``people with disabilities are living longer, just like the general
population,'' said Stanley Klein, a Brookline, Mass., psychologist
and consultant on disability-related concerns. ``It used to be
unusual to see elderly parents caring for adult children. Now it's
becoming common.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 480,000 adults with mental retardation live with
parents who are 60 or older, according to Rick Berkobien, a
spokesman for the Arc, formerly the Association for Retarded
Citizens; some research, he added, suggests that ``there may be as
many families in those circumstances who are unknown to either the
aging or mental retardation services systems.''
</P>
<P>
   At 58, Jimmy Moran has a developmental age of 7 and a passion
for taking apart flashlights. ``But, like many middle-aged
people,'' his sister said, ``he has aches and pains and tends to
doze off in front of the TV.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, the medical advances that have extended human
longevity have proved a mixed blessing as more and more people
begin to outlive their savings. Moreover, through most of the last
century, ``children with disabilities were routinely
institutionalized by their families and cared for at public
expense,'' Klein noted.
</P>
<P>
   It could be grossly substandard care, as anyone familiar with
names like Willowbrook and Pennhurst may know. But the closing of
these and other facilities in the 1970s and '80s, together with
shrinking Medicaid and Medicare allotments and soaring health care
costs, has shifted the financial burden to families. Many are
buckling under the weight.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when she realized that her brother's inheritance
would soon run out, Ms. Moran began putting aside some money on her
own. She said she had managed to save only ``a few thousand''
dollars to date; even so, she is light years ahead of the vast
majority of families in similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1997 Census report, about nine million Americans,
not counting those in institutions, ``have disabilities so severe
that they require personal assistance to carry out everyday
activities.'' In most cases, experts say, their families have taken
no steps to secure their financial future.
</P>
<P>
   Those steps include making sure that there is enough money set
aside to cover housing, food, health care, day-to-day nurturing and
other necessities after the parents die, and that there will be a
responsible adult to protect the child's interests. Such
considerations are common to all estate planning. The difference is
that healthy children eventually outgrow their need for financial
support; those with disabilities are always dependent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are any number of reasons why these families don't plan
ahead,'' said Christopher D. Sullivan, who heads a new Merrill
Lynch service billed as the first financial planning program
intended expressly for families of children with disabilities.
``They may think it's unnecessary on the assumption the child will
die first. Or they simply can't imagine someone else taking over
their parental duties.''
</P>
<P>
   For many parents, just getting through the day leaves little
time and energy to plan for the future _ especially for ``sandwich
generation'' families caring for their own aging parents as well as
for a child with special needs.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when cognitive deficits, as well as mental
illness, autism and traumatic brain injury, were associated with
shortened life spans. In the 1920s, for example, the average age at
death of children with Down syndrome was 9, according to Senate
testimony by David Braddock, head of the department of disability
and human development at the University of Illinois. It rose to
30.5 in the 1960s and to 55.8 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood of older persons with developmental
disabilities living into their own retirement and outliving their
family caregivers has increased substantially in recent years,''
Braddock said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who is deaf, runs Merrill Lynch's investment service
for deaf and hearing-impaired clients; he founded the service a
decade ago. In 1997, Exceptional Parent magazine commended the firm
for pioneering efforts to reach out to disabled clients _ and, at
the same time, took it to task for not doing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we'd done quite a lot in the area,'' Sullivan said.
``What I wasn't aware of was the wide gap between the long-term
needs and preparedness of families.''
</P>
<P>
   The gap became grimly real to him several months later, when the
parents of his wife's cousin, an adult with profound mental
retardation, were killed in a Thanksgiving weekend car accident.
``They had always taken complete responsibility for their
daughter's care and never involved their other children,'' he said.
``Now there was no one to step in and make sure she was happy and
comfortable. It was a terrible situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of the Merrill Lynch program is a detailed
planning exercise in which a family assesses all aspects of its
current and projected financial situation. Working with a financial
consultant, families review expenses that they are paying on their
own _ including those for housing, medical care, clothing,
recreation, vacations and personal needs _ and then figure out a
realistic way to make sure those expenses continue to be met after
they die. The firm then prepares a ``financial foundation report''
that can serve as the basis of a comprehensive financial strategy.
The cost of the report is about $250.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most compelling objectives of the Merrill Lynch
program is the preservation of eligibility for various federal
benefits. Probably the most fragile of those is Supplemental
Security Income, generally available to people who are 65 or older
or disabled, provided that they own no more than $2,000 in assets
(excluding a house, car and burial plot, among other items). The
monthly payment for an individual can be up to $512 nationally, but
most states kick in some money of their own; in New York, the
add-on is $86. In addition, eligibility for SSI is often a
prerequisite for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   It is a benefit definitely worth protecting, regardless of the
income level of the family, but it is also easy to lose. ``The
problem is that many families don't understand the full
implications of the $2,000 ceiling on assets,'' said Barton
Stevens, a special-needs estate planner in Scottsdale, Ariz. ``If a
grandparent dies and leaves money to the child, the SSI benefits
will be terminated, plus Medicaid can claim reimbursement for every
dollar it has spent.'' Only when the assets have been spent down to
$2,000 can a new application for SSI be approved.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The standard way around such traps is to place the assets in a
special-needs trust, administered by a trustee appointed by the
family. Approved by Congress in 1993, such a trust lets the family
save and invest money for a child without jeopardizing government
entitlements. But it must be set up with obsessive attention to the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a problem with your heart, you wouldn't consult an
eye doctor,'' said Douglas Moore, senior counsel of estate and
trust services for Salomon Smith Barney. ``By the same token, don't
have a real estate lawyer set up your special-needs trust. They can
be tricky, so it's essential to use a specialist.''
</P>
<P>
   Errors and omissions can not only put SSI benefits at risk, but
they can also set off costly gift and income tax consequences, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who are not specialists may err, for example, by
including instructions that the funds be spent on necessities like
food and housing. ``There's a reason these are also known as
supplemental needs trusts,'' Moore said. ``They're expressly
intended to pay for things that enhance the beneficiary's quality
of life, like vacations and hobbies. If the income is earmarked for
basics, the trust will be disqualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Williams, a special-needs lawyer in Glendale, Calif.,
said she often found herself ``fixing trusts done by other lawyers
who don't fully understand the underpinnings and how they work _ or
they try to get creative, and run afoul of the rules.'' Her advice:
``Ask your lawyer how many special-needs trusts he or she has done.
If they say that yours is their first, but that a trust is a trust,
go elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the trust is written, it is a good idea to send a copy to
the Social Security Administration for review, Stevens suggested,
``and request a letter confirming that the trust is in
compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Because special-needs trusts must be irrevocable, older parents
with limited resources sometimes shy away from them. ``They're
uncomfortable tying up their money knowing that they may have
long-term savings or health care issues of their own,'' said James
Cotto, a Merrill Lynch financial consultant in Mount Kisco, N.Y.
But you can have a trust ``without funding it, and draft your will
so that your assets go into the trust when you die.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Ann McDonnell's three adult daughters suffer from a
variety of physical, mental and developmental disabilities. Ms.
McDonnell, who is divorced, established trusts that will receive
the proceeds of a separate life insurance trust when she dies.
``Their older sister will slip easily into my role,'' said Ms.
McDonnell, who is 61 and lives in Mount Kisco. ``She'll be the one
to make decisions affecting them, but she won't have to worry about
finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Some families sidestep the issue of trusts and government
entitlements altogether by handing all their assets to their
offspring who are not disabled _ along with the burdens of
long-term care. That, Stevens said, can be a bad move. For one
thing, there is nothing, other than good faith, to prevent those
children from using the money to make a down payment on a home or
pay off debts.
</P>
<P>
   Venality is not the only risk. He told of a California couple,
parents of a grown son with Down syndrome, who willed all their
assets to their two married daughters. ``The daughters love their
brother and aren't likely to misuse the funds,'' he said. ``But the
money is in their name, and that exposes it to creditors and
litigation. If they die, the money goes to their husbands. And, if
they get divorced, their husbands get half, since California is a
community property state.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, it is no wiser to leave all the money to the
disabled child, on the grounds that his need is greater than that
of his siblings. That may breed only enmity and jealousy. ``When
more than one child is involved, special-needs estate planning is
an inherently touchy situation,'' said William Testa, chief
executive of the Morris County, N.J., chapter of the Arc. ``It can
create a chasm in a family just when the support of siblings is
most important.'' All family members _ brothers and sisters as well
as parents _ should have a voice in the planning process, added
Sullivan of Merrill. ``Saving for your disabled child shouldn't
preclude setting up a college fund for your other children.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie and Mike Golden's 18-year-old son, Joshua, was born with
Angelman syndrome, a genetic impairment that causes seizures,
mental retardation and a range of physical limitations. Their
daughter, Jessica, who is 21 and works as a cosmetologist, ``has
grown up with the idea that someday her brother may be her
responsibility,'' Ms. Golden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's important to us,'' she added, ``to make sure that he
doesn't take over her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, the Goldens established a special-needs trust
for Joshua two years ago, to be financed by the proceeds of a life
insurance policy they recently bought. They have also set in place
a far-reaching circle of friends and family in and around their
Baltimore neighborhood, including teachers, nurses, and physicians'
assistants, as well as neighborhood youngsters who visit Joshua for
play dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have told us to call them in any emergency, day or night.
Others can give only limited time and resources, but they have
something to offer, too,'' Ms. Golden said. ``The important thing
is that the burden of caring for Joshua won't fall entirely on
Jessica. And our son will continue to live at home, surrounded by
people who love him. That's very reassuring.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from setting their child's financial house in order,
families should also prepare a letter of intent _ a biographical
profile that describes the precise nature of the child's
disability, medical history, capabilities and limitations, likes
and dislikes, daily routine and relevant behavioral quirks and
nuances. If the child has a favorite TV show or breakfast cereal,
or an aversion to broccoli, it should be duly noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen letters of intent that say things like, `If our son
has an episode and gets upset, you can calm him down by putting on
a Scooby-Doo video,''' said Cotto, the financial consultant in
Mount Kisco. ``That can be very helpful to future caregivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a letter of intent is not legally binding, ``in many
ways it's the most important document of all,'' Stevens added.
``It's the voice of mom and dad instructing what they want for
their child and how to meet his or her needs after they're no
longer around.'' The letter should be updated regularly as the
child grows and changes, ``and shared with any family members and
friends, so they can ask questions while mom and dad are around.''
If the child lives in a residential facility or otherwise spends
time away from home, ideas from staff members can be enlightening,
``since kids tend to behave differently when their parents aren't
around,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' he added, ``it's not a bad idea to observe the
child in that setting, and record what you see in the document.''
</P>
<P>
   Letter of intent can be especially important in the case of
individuals who cannot communicate their needs in an understandable
way. Ms. Williams recalled meeting with a married couple and the
wife's 46-year-old brother, who had suffered an oxygen deficit at
birth, leaving him at the cognitive level of an 18-month-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, he started rocking back and forth and smiling,
saying `bubba, bubba,''' Ms. Williams said. ``His sister told me he
was saying `bubbles,' which meant Pepsi-Cola. He wanted a drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless those who cared for him knew that, she said, ``he would
become increasingly frustrated, and after a week he'd stop
communicating with the outside world. That's the kind of tragic
outcome that can be averted with a letter of intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Few families caring for children with disabilities take the time
to map out a formal financial plan, much less a letter of intent.
``I'm forever amazed at how so many people lack any awareness of
basic estate planning issues, or have even drafted a will,'' said
Moore of Salomon Smith Barney, who works primarily with affluent
families that do not have disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estate planning involves confronting your own mortality,'' he
noted. ``A lot of people, regardless of their circumstances, are
just uncomfortable with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
