<HEADLINE>
N.H. NEWSPAPER FAULTS RUSSERT'S HANDLING OF DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ The Union Leader, a sponsor of the debate
among Republican presidential candidates on Thursday night,
apologized Friday because, it said, the moderator, Tim Russert,
paid so much attention to the two front-runners at the expense of
the other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Union Leader, the largest newspaper in the state, has an
aggressively conservative viewpoint and has often been successful
in using its weight in New Hampshire politics. This year the paper
has endorsed Steve Forbes for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in a signed editorial on the front page, the publisher,
Joseph W. McQuaid, wrote that Russert had apparently decided to
make the debate ``his own two-man show with candidates George Bush
and John McCain, virtually ignoring the four others for much of the
questioning.''
</P>
<P>
   If readers and viewers are upset, McQuaid declared, they are
``no more so than this newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Russert, of NBC News, said that an analysis of the tape showed
that the time allotted each of the candidates was ``remarkably
comparable,'' and that he had been complimented on his handling of
the debate not only by Bush and McCain but also by two other
candidates: Gary L. Bauer and Sen. Orrin Hatch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
