<HEADER>
A9979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-SC-GOPDEBATE08-COX     01-07 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-GOPDEBATE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tax cut issue dominates GOP debate
 &HT;    By Jena Heath and Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ In a debate dominated more by a raucous South
Carolina crowd than any of the candidates, the two Republican
presidential front-runners sparred for the second time in two
nights on taxes and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the few substantive exchanges in the debate _ disjointed
by a hodgepodge of questioning formats, applause and boos from the
crowd _ were between Texas Gov. George W. Bush and his closest
rival, Arizona Sen. John McCain. The gentlemanly tone that
prevailed between the two early on has begun to evaporate as the
Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary approaches. South Carolina hosts its
primary Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know your people are running around saying your tax cut is
bigger than mine,'' McCain said of Bush's $483 billion tax-cut
proposal, which he called ``fiscally irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, we ought to pay down the national debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Replied Bush: ``There is enough money to take care of Social
Security, there's enough money to meet the basic needs of our
government, and there's enough money to give people a substantial
tax cut, and that's what I intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Things got more heated a few minutes later when Bush asked Utah
Sen. Orrin Hatch why so few Republican senators voted for McCain's
campaign finance reform bill, which the Arizona senator has made
the centerpiece of his campaign but that Bush says would hurt the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I or any other Republican be for a bill that's
unconstitutional?'' said Hatch, referring to the bill's
restrictions on campaign contributions. ``John is starting to sound
like the accordion player who only knows one tune: `Lady of
Spain.'''
</P>
<P>
   McCain demanded a chance to respond to Bush and Hatch,
proclaiming that ``I've always thought that what's best for the
country is best for the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are defending an illegal system,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   After appearing stiff in earlier debates, Bush for the second
night in row seemed relaxed, often employing the wry humor that he
has displayed in the Texas Governor's Mansion. When a reporter
asked each of the candidates to name the biggest mistake of his
adult life, Bush said his occurred when he was managing general
partner of the Texas Rangers baseball club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed off on that wonderful transaction: Sammy Sosa for
Harold Baines,'' Bush said of the trade that sent Sosa, one of the
greatest home-run hitters in the game, away from the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday marked the fifth debate for Bush, McCain, magazine
publisher Steve Forbes, Hatch, Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes. They will
meet again Monday in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Republicans traditionally back the establishment
candidate and this year is no exception. In recent weeks, McCain
has gained on Bush here, but still isn't close to erasing Bush's
large lead. The picture is different in New Hampshire, where Bush
and McCain are in a dead heat and where McCain's blunt, outspoken
style has played well with the state's fiercely independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
