<HEADLINE>
MENDING KINGS CATCH A BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Although Christmas has passed and the All-Star
weekend is a month away, the Los Angeles Kings find themselves with
a bit of a break after recording a victory and a tie against two of
the league's better teams.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday night's 4-2 win over the Florida Panthers, the
Kings don't play again until Tuesday against Ottawa. After a
physical practice Friday, the team has today off before
participating in the NHL Skills Competition on Sunday at the
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings aren't looking at the break as lost momentum, rather a
chance to get injured players healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone feels pretty good that we have started playing well
again,'' said third-line center Ian Laperriere, who practiced with
the team Friday for the first time since bruising his left knee 10
days ago against Edmonton. ``We are going to be coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (18-15-7) play five of their next six games at home
and all are against teams that made the playoffs last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Laperriere, who was thought to be lost for several weeks,
could be back for Ottawa. First-line center Jozef Stumpel, also
sidelined with knee problems, hopes to play against the Senators,
but that is less likely. Stumpel underwent an MRI on Thursday and a
second on Friday to check for structural damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still sore but it's better,'' Stumpel said. ``A couple of
days can make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel would have been a likely candidate to participate in the
skill competition, which will be held for season ticket holders
only on Sunday. Among the activities: fastest skater, hardest shot,
most accurate shot, stick handling and goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   Each team in the NHL has its own skills competition, with the
winners to face off the day before the Feb. 6 All-Star Game in
Toronto. It is sponsored by the NHL Players Association with
proceeds to benefit the pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel is considered one of the league's finest stick handlers
but has missed all but three games in the past two months with
injuries. Ziggy Palffy, perhaps the Kings most-skilled offensive
player, also will not participate in the Skills Competition.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, the team's leading scorer with 35 points, has been
bothered by a strained lower back the past month. His availability
has been a game-time decision the past few games, but he did play
Thursday and recorded an assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ziggy was in practice today and said he was fine, but we let
him out a little early as a precaution,'' coach Andy Murray said.
``For the next few weeks we probably won't know until game time if
he is going to play. That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy's uncertainty created some interesting lines Thursday.
Luc Robitaille, who played with the second unit of Bryan Smolinski
and Glen Murray on Tuesday when Palffy was out, was back on the
first line Thursday. Donald Audette, benched for several games,
returned to the second line.
</P>
<P>
   Len Barrie, who scored two goals Thursday as the first-line
center, also popped up on the third and fourth lines against the
Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings haven't had much good news about goaltender Jamie
Storr, who has had trouble recovering from a concussion suffered
Dec. 11 in Montreal. But Storr has been skating lightly the past
two days after doctors cleared him to step up his workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said he could do more than the exercise bike, so we let him
go out there and shoot around some pucks. But he is still a long
ways off.''
</P>
<P>
   Since coaches don't participate in the skills competition,
Murray is spending the next few days in Minnesota with his family
before returning Monday for practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
