<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CANDIDATES REDIRECT THEIR FIRE TOWARD DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With REPUBS-DEBATE-TEXT) 
(js) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. _ A day after an aggressive and sometimes
vitriolic encounter in New Hampshire, the Republicans went easier
on each other in debate Friday night, this time turning much of
their fire on President Clinton and the Democratic candidates for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain took several shots at the Democrats, mocking
Gore's 1997 comment that there had been ``no controlling legal
authority'' barring him from making fund-raising calls from his
office. And McCain called it ``disgraceful'' that Gore had said at
a recent debate that senior appointees to military posts would be
judged on whether they would support allowing homosexuals to serve
in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a total destruction of the entire concept of the
military, and we as Americans should reject such a thing,'' said
the Arizona senator who endorsed the current ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Friday night Gore backed away from his statement, saying
he had not meant to imply ``that there should ever be a personal
inquiry into the political views'' of military appointees, putting
him closer to his opponent Bill Bradley, the former senator, who
also favors allowing openly gay people into the military.
</P>
<P>
   The charge against the Democrats was begun by the publisher
Steve Forbes, who accused Gore's campaign manager, Donna Brazile,
of making ``racist remarks'' and said she should be fired for her
suggestion that Republicans had no interest in helping black
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve, you're absolutely right,'' Gary L. Bauer replied with
zest. ``Let me just say to the good people in this audience, You
have watched for 10 years while the Democratic Party has tried to
smear our party with charges about racism, with charges about not
caring about the poor, with all kinds of scare tactics.'' Bauer
added, ``Al Gore's campaign manager ought to be ashamed of herself
and she ought to resign tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate, sponsored by the South Carolina Republican Party,
featured a crazy-quilt format, which included e-mail inquiries,
questions from the audience and rapid responses limited at some
points to two sentences. The audience of 3,000 often booed and
cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, whose performance in some earlier
debates was criticized as lackluster, seemed almost totally at
ease, even when questioners tried to pin him down on the incendiary
issue here of whether the Confederate flag should be flown over the
Capitol. The very question posed by the MSNBC moderator, Brian
Williams, drew loud boos from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said repeatedly that he believes that South Carolinians
should be left to decide the fate of that flag and that a candidate
for president should not meddle. But Williams asked him if he was
personally offended by the banner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're trying to get me do is express the will of the
people of South Carolina,'' he said. ``I believe the people of
South Carolina can figure out what to do with this flag issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams tried a different tack: Did Bush have a visceral
reaction, as an American citizen, to seeing the flag?
</P>
<P>
   ``As an American citizen,'' Bush said, ``I trust the people of
South Carolina to make the decision for South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second night in a row, McCain was put on the defensive
over reports that he had intervened before the Federal
Communications Commission on behalf of companies whose executives
are donors to his campaign. He was asked about an Associated Press
report that two weeks after Ameritech's chairman held a fund-raiser
for him, he sent a stinging letter to federal regulators accusing
them of being unfair toward the phone company's proposed merger
with another Bell company.
</P>
<P>
   Once again McCain said that his role as chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee was to ``oversight bureaucracies. ``I will
continue to do that job,'' he said. He added that ``I believe that
people like me should weigh in, particularly when it is my
responsibility as chairman of the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not the only one whom the panel of questioners sought to
put on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, whose opposition to abortion is a cornerstone of his
campaign, was asked what he would say to his daughter if she were
raped and wanted to end the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would comfort her, I would pray with her, I would explain
that she couldn't make right the terrible thing that had happened
to her by taking the life of an innocent, unborn child,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was the second between the Republican candidates in
two days, reflecting the accelerating pace of the 2000 campaign.
And it capped a week of intensified competition between Bush and
his chief challenger, McCain, in which the two men have sparred
over tax cuts, Social Security and the overhaul of the campaign
finance law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the most revealing segments of the evening came when each
candidate was asked to name the biggest mistake he had made as an
adult and what he had learned from it.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes, the radio commentator, railed at the question,
saying it was invasive and intrusive and more fittingly discussed
in confession with a priest.
</P>
<P>
   McCain started off with humor, saying that he had thought his
biggest mistake may have come during his years in the Navy when he
raised his hand after a disastrous fire on his aircraft carrier to
volunteer to serve on another carrier. He was later shot down and
held as a prisoner of war in Vietnam for five-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
   But then he became serious and said his biggest error was
meeting with federal regulators years ago on behalf of Charles H.
Keating Jr., a corrupt savings and loan association operator.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stuck with comedy for his own answer, in the process
bringing up his mother, who is highly popular in South Carolina.
Referring to reports of his raucus past, he said: ``Well, as you
know, I've had a perfect background. After all, I was raised by
Barbara Bush.'' The crowd cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Then he mentioned his former position as managing general
partner of the Texas Rangers baseball team. ``I signed off on that
wonderful transaction, Sammy Sosa for Harold Baines.'' Sosa has
since become one of the most prolific homerun hitters in the game.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's primary comes less than three weeks after New
Hampshire's. It is the first of the Southern primaries and has
often been pivotal in the fight for the Republican presidential
nomination. McCain, who is running ahead of Bush in New Hampshire
but well behind him nationally, considers the state critical to any
chance he has of pulling off an upset. He is trying to mobilize the
state's large numbers of veterans and active duty military
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike New Hampshire, however, South Carolina does not have a
history of propelling mavericks forward. It has been more likely to
restore the fortunes of front-runners who stumbled in New Hampshire
or Iowa. Four years ago, for example, it was where Bob Dole
effectively put an end to the campaign of Patrick J. Buchanan, who
had won New Hampshire with his appeal to conservatives and the
economically downtrodden. And this time much of the state's
political establishment has rallied around Bush.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Republicans are also considered more conservative
than those in New Hampshire, with the candidates vying for the
support of the Christian right who make up a large portion of the
electorate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
