<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Jan. 9,
2000.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HANK-GREENBERG-FILM (Undated) _ ``The Life and Times of Hank
Greenberg,'' a new documentary by Aviva Kempner, of the great
Detroit Tigers slugger. Aviva Kempner and her brother, Jonathan,
knew of Greenberg from their father, Harold, who left Lithuania for
Pittsburgh in 1925 and settled in Detroit. To Harold Kempner,
baseball was a ritual of American assimilation and Greenberg a
symbol. By Richard Sandomir. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LUCIE-AUBRAC-VIDEO (Undated) _ In 1943 in Lyon, France, at the
height of the Nazi occupation, a man jailed for buying sugar and
noodles on the black market gets a note from his wife. ``A third
night without you in a big, hopelessly cold bed,'' it reads.
Nothing like a little Gallic news from home to rally a man.
Unfortunately, Raymond (Daniel Auteuil) is suspected by the state
attorney of belonging to the Resistance, which means he won't be
curling up with Lucie (Carole Bouquet) for quite a while, if ever.
It is at this point that we begin to appreciate the differences
between a thriller from the French director Claude Berri, a student
of the intensely personal in ``Jean de Florette'' and ``Manon of
the Spring,'' and the standard commotion on American screens. By
Peter M. Nichols. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL-THEATER-PROJECT (New York) _ Hallie Flanagan
(1890-1969), who headed the Federal Theater Project in its brave
and troubled existence, deserves better. The movie ``Cradle Will
Rock,'' treats her deservedly as a heroine of America's one effort
to create what she envisioned as a free, adult, uncensored theater.
But in trying to reproduce the commotions of the 1930s, the film
director, Tim Robbins, captured by nostalgia for the left,
diminishes her accomplishment. By Walter Goodman. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WRONG-MOUNTAIN-THEATER (New York) _ David Hirson's second play,
``Wrong Mountain,'' will open on Thursday at Eugene O'Neill
Theater. His first play ``La Bete,'' set in 17th-century France,
opened at the same theater on Feb. 10, 1991, and very shortly
became one of the most famous flops in Broadway history. ``Wrong
Mountain,'' directed by Richard Jones, who also directed ``La
Bete,'' makes demands on the audience to see in the lives of
artists, reflections of their own existential problems. This time
Hirson's play has a contemporary setting, and it is written in
nonrhyming prose, the story of Henry Dennett, 60, an embittered,
unappreciated poet who, infuriated by the presumption of his
ex-wife's new boyfriend, a popular playwright named Guy Halperin,
makes a bet that he can write a play and have it produced. By Bruce
Weber. (Moved). Photo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARILYN-HORNE-MUSIC (New York) _ Marilyn Horne has been worried
about the song recital for some time. As an art form the song
recital has been languishing, she says, which is why seven years
ago she set up a foundation to do something about it. Ms. Horne
speaks of the problem with considerable authority. Besides being
one of the great operatic mezzo-sopranos in history, she has been
an devoted recitalist. She lost count of total number of recitals
she has given when the tally topped 1,300 a few years back. By
Anthony Tommasini. (Moved). Photo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTRIDGE-MUSIC (Undated) _ Not since Peter Pears faded from the
spotlight in the 1970s has an English tenor garnered more attention
than Ian Bostridge. Suddenly, this redoubtable 35-year-old seems
everywhere on CD, capturing the interest of music lovers throughout
Europe and America. And though some mavens have demurred, the hype
has been buttressed by albums remarkable for both artistic quality
and repertorial variety. By David Mermelstein. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   20TH-CENTURY-MUSIC (Undated) _ The 20th century was, in musical
terms, a noisy one. I don't mean loud or even discordant, the
customary complaints of audiences encountering new music, whether
Igor Stravinsky's ``Rite of Spring,'' John Coltrane's ``Ascension''
or Jimi Hendrix's Woodstock rendition of the national anthem. I'm
referring, rather, to the way that 20th-century composers have
embraced sounds _ environmental, industrial, often random _ and
thereby laid siege to inherited notions of musical order. If last
century's avant-garde taught us anything, it is that such
disturbances can be the stuff of art. By Adam Shatz. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENSOR-ART(Brussels, Belguim) _ By the time James Ensor
celebrated his 30th birthday, in 1890, he was already an
exceptional painter. Equally comfortable with portraits, still
lifes, domestic interiors and seascapes, he had learned what he
wanted from his French Impressionist contemporaries and was now
going his own way. Yet, when he died in 1949, aged 89, he was a
relatively marginal figure, regarded as something of an eccentric
by his fellow Belgians and known abroad principally for the
sinister masked figures and skeletons that peopled many of his
paintings, drawings and etchings. But talented he was, above all in
his early years, as quickly becomes apparent in a major
retrospective of his work, organized by the Royal Museums of Fine
Arts of Belgium and on display at the Museum of Ancient Art in
Brussels through Feb. 13. By Alan Riding. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCCLEERY-BIRDS-ART (Undated) _ Dr. James M. McCleery, a
collector of stamps and coins since childhood, redirected his focus
in 1963 to buying decorative bird carvings and, later, to acquiring
vintage American decoys. His carved birds will be auctioned at
Sotheby's in New York. The 450 lots of decoys and 180 lots of
duck-calling instruments, traps, shell boxes, prints and baskets
will be auctioned on Jan. 22 and 23. The sale is expected to total
$5 million to $6 million. By Rita Reif. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   METROPOLITAN-MUSEUM (New York) _ If asked to say what you love
about the Metropolitan Museum of Art, you might think of mummies or
shining armor or old-master paintings in curly gold frames. You
might even think of the grand central staircase, which, when you
descend it, makes you feel like an affluent if doomed character in
a turn-of-the-last-century Edith Wharton novel. But you probably
wouldn't think of contemporary art. Virtually since it opened in
1870, the Met has been accused of snubbing the art of the present.
By Deborah Solomon. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-ELEANOR-ROOSEVELT (Undated) _ Monday at 9 p.m., PBS
inaugurates the 12th season of the ``American Experience'' series
with ``Eleanor Roosevelt,'' a two-and-a-half hour documentary about
the woman who was widely considered among the finest politicians of
the 20th century. By Kathryn Shattuck. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
