<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON GETTING HIS CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This could be the day Rob Johnson becomes a great
USC quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, time out, Trojans fans are saying. It's been five years
since Johnson peeled off the cardinal and gold. The annals of the
school's great quarterbacks are closed at least until Carson Palmer
throws his next touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's technically too late for Johnson, who ended his USC
career in 1994 distinguished as the leader of the first four-year
class that never defeated UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   But I also know how it works on campuses everywhere: It doesn't
matter how insignificant or even despised you were when you were
there, as long as you bring glory to the old school in your
professional life.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a girl who's too shy to raise her hand in typing class
blossoms into an Oscar winner, and the high school that ``made
her'' names the library for her.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, an athlete who's better known to the campus police chief
than to his coach matures into an all-pro, and his college boasts
about its latest star ``product.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there's hope for Rob Johnson if he can quarterback the
11-5 Buffalo Bills to an upset of the 13-3 Tennessee Titans today
in the strongest game of the NFL's wild-card playoff weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, playing for his second NFL team, he's finally getting
another shot at winning the big one that eluded him in college.
</P>
<P>
   In upstate New York this week, there have been enough tears shed
for Doug Flutie, the quarterback Johnson replaces, to make Lake
Erie overflow.
</P>
<P>
   After leading the Bills to the playoffs, Flutie has been pushed
aside by head coach Wade Phillips after Johnson has one winning
performance inan anything-but-pivotal regular-season finale against
the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strange move, benching a veteran with a reputation for
miracles, inserting a guy with a grand total of eight NFL starts.
</P>
<P>
   But look at it from Johnson's end, and they're feeling sorry for
the wrong man.
</P>
<P>
   How'd you like to go through life remembered for letting down
half a city, always a heartbeat away from a chance to prove
yourself, never quite getting the chance?
</P>
<P>
   That's been Rob Johnson the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   He was, in fact, a great quarterback by every measure except the
one by which Trojans are ultimately measured _ number of victories
over UCLA and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   After three years as the starter he was USC's all-time leading
quarterback, first in completions (678), percentage (.646), yards
(8,472) and touchdown passes (58). He still holds those records.
</P>
<P>
   But he was 0-5-1 (the tie with Notre Dame in 1994 in Johnson's
final game at the Coliseum) against USC's two rivals. And although
it wasn't all his fault there wasn't much of a running game to
support him fans can't excuse his interception in the end zone at
the end of the 1993 loss to UCLA that cost the Trojans a Rose Bowl
berth or his painfully similar error the following year in the same
game.
</P>
<P>
   A Newport Beach native, son of a football coach (Bob), brother
of a CFL quarterback (Bret), cousin of a major-league pitcher
(Bart), 6-foot-4 and built to throw the deep routes, Johnson was
one of those guys for whom everything seemed to come easy.
</P>
<P>
   It was just as easy for his critics to question his footwork,
his decisiveness and his judgment with big games in the balance.
They saw a perfectionist who didn't know when throwing a pass away
_ instead of taking a sack or risking an interception _ was the
better part of valor.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why, having once been labeled a Heisman Trophy
candidate and likely top quarterback in the 1995 NFL draft, he
dropped all the way to the fourth round before the Jacksonville
Jaguars took him. Among the six quarterbacks to go before Johnson
was Steve McNair, his opponent today in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   If they had a Hall of Fame for exhibition-game quarterbacks,
they'd waive the five-year waiting period for Johnson. But in his
first three regular seasons he threw just 35 passes while backing
up Mark Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a trade to Buffalo and a five-year, $25 million
contract but, so far, more frustration. He began 1998 as the Bills
starter, got hurt, watched Flutie work his magic. He was back on
the bench for the first 15 games of 1999 ...
</P>
<P>
   And now a chance, the biggest game of his pro career. Johnson is
only one NFL quarterback with something to prove in these playoffs.
Seven of the 12 scheduled starters will be making their playoff
debuts. Only Jacksonville's Brunell, Dallas' Troy Aikman and
Miami's Dan Marino _ who also has something to prove after 16 great
seasons without a championship _ have ever won a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bills lose, Johnson might be in for more abuse. A Toronto
columnist has predicted Flutie will have to bail them out ``when
Johnson can't hack it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Bills win, the impact might be felt in Los Angeles. Maybe
all those big-game losses at USC weren't his fault after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
