<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WOULD USE FORCE TO TAKE BACK PANAMA CANAL IF EVER CLOSED TO
FREE COMMERCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Confederate flags, the Clinton administration
and personal shortcomings were issues of contention for six
Republican presidential candidates debating for the second night in
a row Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush engaged in major saber-rattling for
the conservatives and military presence in South Carolina by
declaring that he would use force to take back the Panama Canal if
it is ever closed to free commerce. The canal was officially turned
over to Panama on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do whatever it takes to keep the canal open. It is in
our national strategic interest to have a peaceful hemisphere,''
Bush said. ``I'll liberate the canal if I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, meanwhile, found himself again
explaining another letter he wrote, as chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee, to the Federal Communications Commission on
behalf of a campaign contributor.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, McCain was questioned about a letter he wrote
to the FCC on behalf of Paxson Communications, run by a contributor
whose jet he leases, when it wanted to buy a television station.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was questioned Friday about a letter to regulators at the
FCC last April in which he said he was ``extremely troubled'' by
delays in their handling of the merger of Ameritech with SBC
Communications. The letter was written less than two weeks after an
Ameritech executive hosted a political fund-raiser for McCain in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a constituent of mine, a person of this country, can't
get an answer from a bureaucracy that's being paid for with their
tax dollars, I believe that people like me should weigh in,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was sponsored by the South Carolina Republican Party
as part of its Silver Elephant Dinner honoring Sen. Strom Thurmond.
Other GOP contenders who participated included conservative
activists Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes, publisher Steve Forbes and
Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is a battleground state for McCain and Bush, with
both advertising heavily here. McCain wants to win New Hampshire on
Feb. 1, South Carolina on Feb. 19 and Arizona and Michigan on Feb.
22 to gain the momentum to catch up with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the most recent poll here, conducted Dec. 6-19 by KPC
Research for local news media, showed Bush leading in South
Carolina 54 percent to McCain's 21 percent. All other candidates
were in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked his personal reaction to the Confederate flag, a
seemingly straightforward question but a contentious local issue
because South Carolinians are debating whether a depiction of the
rebel colors should be removed from state flag. The NAACP has
called for a tourism boycott of the state until the state flag is
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dodged the question, saying he was not going to be drawn
into a local battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of South Carolina can figure out what to do with
the flag issue,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to a question of what was the greatest mistake of
their adult lives, most of the candidates used the occasion to
criticize President Clinton while avoiding answers too personally
revealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made my share of personal mistakes. Fortunately, none of
us here put together tonight will match what has been done in the
White House in the last 7 1/2 years,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain said the biggest mistake of his life was meeting with
federal banking regulators, along with four other senators, on
behalf of Arizona savings and loan executive Charles Keating. When
Keating's financial empire collapsed as part of the savings and
loan crisis of the late 1980s, the federal government was stuck
picking up the $2.6 billion tab. McCain has always maintained he
did nothing wrong, but that he regrets his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something that will always be a mark on my record and
something that people will judge me for for the rest of my life,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who previously has said he was once ``young and
irresponsible,'' was almost flippant in his response.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, I've had a perfect background. After all, I was
raised by Barbara Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his biggest mistake was, when he was managing partner
of the Texas Rangers baseball club, he traded away Sammy Sosa for
Harold Baines of the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who later become a member of the Chicago Cubs, went on to
become one of the leading home run hitters of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
