u a BC-NY-BRICK-SUSPECT-NYT &LR;      01-07 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEA OF NOT GUILTY IN BRICK ATTACK ON WOMAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (rk) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The man charged with attacking a woman with a brick
in Midtown Manhattan in November pleaded not guilty Friday and said
he was in his girlfriend's apartment in the Bronx at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Paris Drake, 32, is charged with attempted murder,
attempted robbery, assault and weapons possession in the attack on
Nicole Barrett, 27, a native of Texas. She was hit with a six-pound
paving stone on the afternoon of Nov. 16, and needed two brain
operations as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the incident, it was thought that the attacker
was homeless and mentally ill. The attack prompted a crackdown by
the Giuliani administration on homeless people who sleep on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   But from details presented Friday during the hearing in State
Supreme Court in Manhattan, it appeared that Drake was neither
homeless nor mentally ill. He had no history of psychiatric
problems and had lived at least temporarily with his girlfriend on
the Grand Concourse. A woman sat with his lawyers in the courtroom
Friday, holding an infant, but the lawyers would not identify her.
</P>
<P>
   And Drake is being represented by a lawyer, who has offices on
Park Avenue, who was hired by his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the attacker, and he's not the panhandler the press
has painted him,'' said the lawyer, Louis A. Zayas. ``Quite
frankly, I think they've got the wrong person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got family members that care a great deal about him,''
Zayas said.
</P>
<P>
   In a police statement made public Friday, Drake said he was
unemployed and could not remember the last time he had worked. He
routinely spent his days on Eighth Avenue, between 34th and 41st
streets, where he bought almonds, crushed them and sold the powder,
pretending it was crack, the statement said. With the profits, he
took the subway to 146th Street, bought crack and got high,
according to the statement. He repeated the trip two or three times
a day, depending on how much money he made, he told the police.
</P>
<P>
   Drake was arrested after an inmate at Rikers Island told the
police that he had bragged about the crime after his Nov. 23 arrest
on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Drake first told the police he spent Monday, Nov. 15, going in
and out of the apartment on the Grand Concourse, buying crack and
food. But when asked how he spent Nov. 16, he said he had stayed in
the apartment both Monday and Tuesday, resting from the previous
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts have said they thought prosecutors were
relying on too little evidence in charging Drake and that they
might have a difficult time convicting him. Officials have said
there are no fingerprints or other physical evidence to link him to
the crime.
</P>
<P>
   One of six witnesses who viewed a lineup identified Drake as the
suspect. But papers from the district attorney's office show that
another witness identified a photograph of a different person as
the attacker and had earlier identified a third person in a lineup
as the person who hit Ms. Barrett. The other witnesses failed to
pick Drake out of a lineup.
</P>
<P>
   After the arraignment, Zayas said the police had found the wrong
person to charge in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire New York Police Department's detective bureau was
mobilized to find someone who was responsible for this,'' Zayas
said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution offered no new evidence against Drake Friday. If
convicted of all the offenses, he could be sentenced to 72 years in
prison. He is scheduled to appear in court again on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett, who has returned to her family in Texas, is
recovering faster than expected, but doctors have said she may have
permanent brain damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
