<HEADLINE>
TIMOTHY ELLIOTT, 51, ADVERTISING EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Britain)   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Timothy Charles Venn Elliott, a Manhattan advertising
executive, died Dec. 30 at his home on the Upper East Side. He was
51.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pancreatic cancer, his associates said.
</P>
<P>
   At his death Elliott, a native of England, was the managing
director of the flagship office in New York of FCB Worldwide. He
had previously led Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding's San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Dorset, Elliott was educated at Harrow School and
graduated from Cambridge University, earning a B.A. in 1969 and an
M.A. in 1974. In a 30-year-career in advertising, he worked for a
number of agencies, including Benton &AMP; Bowles in London and, for 15
years, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather in South Africa, Canada and eventually New
York, where he managed international accounts for companies like
American Express and Trans World Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   He joined FCB Worldwide in New York in 1997 to handle its
Citibank business worldwide and moved to San Francisco to direct
its office there in 1998. He returned to New York last January to
take charge of that office.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott is survived by his wife, Daryl Elliott, executive vice
president of Young &AMP; Rubicam in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
