<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-GRIZZLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIZZLIES OUTREBOUND NETS IN 101-91 VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The prospect of witnessing history
apparently did not excite the sports market of Northern New Jersey
on Friday night. A crowd generously announced as 14,246 came to
Continental Arena to see the Nets try for a franchise record of 10
consecutive home victories when they played the Vancouver
Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies are one of the worst teams in the National
Basketball Association, but they led the Nets most of the way and
left with a 101-91 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dickerson led Vancouver with 28 points and Mike Bibby
had 20, including 4-of-6 shooting from 3-point range. Othella
Harrington, a Grizzlies forward, had 12 rebounds and Vancouver
finished with a 51-32 rebounding edge.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles led the Nets with 21 points, and Stephon Marbury
had 19 to go with 11 assists. Keith Van Horn also had 19 points,
including three field goals from outside the arc as the Nets'
second-half comeback fell short.
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies made all 21 of their free throws; the Nets were 12
of 16 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   Nets Coach Don Casey said the free-throw totals of both teams
gave a hint of the final outcome. The two Vancouver forwards,
Shareef Abdur-Rahim and Harrington, were a combined 17 for 17 from
the line. Of Casey's two starting forwards, Kendall Gill was 5 for
6 and Van Horn was 0 for 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your front line is not getting any foul shots, you have
to guess what was is going on,'' Casey said. ``Our offensive end
was like an adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, referring to his assists, said, ``I was doing my job. I
was getting people the ball where I was supposed to.'' When asked
about the Nets taking so many jump shots from the outside, Marbury
said, ``They packed it in and made us shoot jump shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim McIlvaine, the Nets' center, left the game after being poked
in his left eye early in the second half when he and Kittles went
up for a rebound. It was bloodshot after the game. But McIlvaine
said that he could have returned and that the injury was not as
serious as one earlier this season in the right eye that caused him
to have double vision for about a month.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles started well for the Nets (12-20), scoring 12 points in
a first quarter that ended with Vancouver leading, 28-27. But
Kittles went scoreless in the second quarter as the Grizzlies ran
out to a 53-45 halftime lead. The Nets were outrebounded by 30-15
in the first two quarters. Harrington and Bibby each had seven
rebounds for the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury led the Nets with only 4 points at the half. Dickerson
led all scorers with 18 points, on 8 of 14 from the field including
2 of 3 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine had three personal fouls and played only 13 minutes in
the half, with no points, two rebounds and one turnover to go with
three blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' next game could be difficult. They travel to Miami to
play the Heat on Saturday night, the first meeting of the season
between the two Atlantic Division rivals. The Heat leads the
division with a record of 21-10 and is tied for fourth over all in
the 29-team National Basketball Association. Last season, the Nets
were 1-3 against the Heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2304EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
