<HEADER>
A0070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-FORBES-AD-BOX-NYT &LR;      01-07 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-AD-BOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: FORBES TAKES THE OFFENSIVE IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several months of ``will he or won't he'' questions about
whether Steve Forbes would unleash negative advertisements against
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas ended Friday when the Forbes campaign
begin using a 30-second spot in New Hampshire attacking Bush's
stand on taxes. The commercial comes just a day after Bush pledged
to cut taxes ``so help me God,'' and the Forbes spot accuses him of
breaking a no-new-tax pledge he made in Texas in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER William Eisner &AMP; Associates, Hales Corners, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The advertisement opens with a black-and-white
sign reading ``Mary C. Williams, Taxpayers for Accountability,
Houston.'' It dissolves to a close-up head shot of Ms. Williams
talking earnestly into the camera. It also features tight views of
her hands holding up a copy of a pledge Bush signed with her group
in 1994 saying he opposed enacting a state income tax or increasing
the Texas sales tax. The advertisement alternates between close-ups
of Ms. Williams and shots of Bush's signature on the group's
pledge.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``There's something you need to know about George W.
Bush. In 1994, he signed a pledge with my organization that he
would not support sales tax or business tax increases. In 1997,
unfortunately, he broke this pledge. He proposed an increase in the
business tax and sales taxes. Governor Bush wants people to examine
his record to see how he will perform as president. And his record,
as far as taxes are concerned, is a record of broken promises.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: In January 1997, Bush proposed a sweeping
restructuring of the Texas tax system, which he called the
centerpiece of his legislative agenda. The plan called for a $3
billion-a-year cut in local property taxes, which would be paid, in
large part, by a half-cent increase in state sales taxes and new
taxes on businesses, including the first-ever taxes on lawyers,
accountants, doctors and other professional partnerships. The
purpose of the tax plan was to end a 25-year court battle over
inequities in public school financing and would have, over all,
lowered taxes. The plan was defeated by the state Legislature the
following May in what was seen as a stinging defeat to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bush was sharply criticized for breaking his 1994
campaign pledge to oppose sales tax increases, and many political
observers suggested that this episode could haunt him if he made a
similar pledge in his 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: The tax issue is tricky for Bush, especially after
his father's famous ``read my lips'' pledge not to raise taxes,
which was later broken. Forbes has made tax reduction the
centerpiece of his campaign, but until now has refrained from
attacking Bush directly in television commercials, as he did in
attack advertisements against Bob Dole in 1996, leaving Dole
wounded and Forbes' reputation tarnished. With Forbes trailing
badly in the polls in New Hampshire, he has now pulled off the
gloves. The Forbes campaign has long said it could turn out attack
ads within 24 hours, if necessary. This advertisement, coming just
a day after Bush's ``so help me God'' pledge, proves their point.
It is expected that this commercial, now being shown on New
Hampshire and Boston television stations, will be followed by other
negative advertisements from Forbes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2305EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
