<HEADLINE>
ROCKER AGREES TO TESTING IMMEDIATELY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Md.)  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Rocker traveled to Baltimore Friday to begin the
psychological testing that was ordered by Major League Baseball a
day earlier following the disparaging comments that he made last
month about gays and minority-group members.
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking baseball executive said Rocker immediately agreed
to start the testing, and the Atlanta Braves pitcher was scheduled
to meet with Dr. Joel Solomon and Dr. Robert Millman, consultants
to baseball who have been mutually approved by the Major League
Baseball Players Association and the Player Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker had the right to refuse to submit to the testing but had
he done so, said a baseball official with knowledge of the
negotiations between Bud Selig, the baseball commissioner, and the
players association, Selig would have then issued immediate
disciplinary measures against Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The union agreed that Rocker should be tested, which delayed
Selig's dispensing any punishment and also gave Rocker the chance
to prove that, despite the inflammatory remarks he made to Sports
Illustrated, he is a rational person.
</P>
<P>
   If and when Rocker is disciplined, it is still conceivable that
the union will file a grievance on his behalf. But baseball would
invoke Paragraph 3(a) of the Basic Agreement to explain why Rocker
violated his major league contract.
</P>
<P>
   That part of the agreement pertains to loyalty and states: ``The
player agrees to perform his services hereunder diligently and
faithfully, to keep himself in first-class condition and to obey
the club's training rules, and pledges himself to the American
Public and to the club to conform to high standards of personal
conduct, fair play and good sportsmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   When Selig was contacted at his office in Milwaukee on Friday,
he refused to answer questions about Rocker and explained that he
must be cautious because he was the judge in this case. Selig
declined to say if he thought that Rocker had failed ``to conform
to high standards of personal conduct'' and would not specify what
he would do after Rocker completed the psychological tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to do what I think is right in the best interests of
baseball in every way,'' Selig said. ``How I think it impacts the
best interests of baseball is the only thing that will influence my
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear why Rocker, who is from Macon, Ga., was asked to
meet the doctors in Baltimore. Millman represents baseball, while
Solomon represents the union in certain cases involving players who
require medical attention. They have worked together on several
substance-abuse cases with major leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where John is,'' Stan Kasten, the Braves'
president, said. ``The reason I don't know is these things are
always done in a confidential manner. I've heard that his father
said he's in Baltimore.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten said that Rocker planned to ``get whatever help he
needed,'' which Rocker has shown by submitting to the testing a day
after Selig's order. While Rocker has been criticized for calling
an African-American teammate ``a fat monkey'' and for making racial
and homophobic slurs about New Yorkers, there have also been
questions about his rights.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said that the Braves and baseball had the license
to punish Rocker because the First Amendment's right of free speech
was applicable only in government action, not in the private
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   While free speech exists in the workplace, Siegel said, there
are certain limitations on it when those words have an adverse
impact on a person's job or create a hostile work environment.
Since Rocker is undergoing testing, which Siegel said could be
construed as adversely affecting his job, and since some teammates
have expressed disdain over his comments, Siegel noted that that
could be construed as fostering a hostile work environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the context of the private workplace, major league baseball
and the Atlanta Braves have concerns and interests there about
their business,'' Siegel said. ``So his rights arery strong.
In fact, they're pretty weak at best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
