<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SIGN SANTANGELO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Continuing their offseason plan of acquiring
players with strong clubhouse character, the Los Angeles Dodgers
gained a measure of versatility by signing free agent F.P.
Santangelo to a two-year, $1.6 million contract Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A switch-hitter, Santangelo plays all three outfield positions
and anywhere in the infield. He adds depth to the bench and gives
manager Davey Johnson a late-inning double-switch candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those quality, versatility guys,'' Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone said. ``He's one of those guys you can start a
week at second base, a few days at shortstop, a week at third and
he won't hurt you. He can play center field for a month. He gives
Davey so much more versatility and flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo, 32, played predominantly at center (49 games) and
left (26) with the San Francisco Giants last season, but he also
played right (9), second base (11), third base (3) and shortstop
(1). He also has a good swing, hitting .260 in 113 games last
season with a .406 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo will be paid $750,000 during the 2000 season and
$850,000 in 2001. Performance-based incentives could earn him an
additional $1.3 million during the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my value to a team is being able to play a lot of
positions and being able to play every day,'' Santangelo said.
``I'm just thrilled to be part of the Dodgers. Regardless of what
they say of my role, things always change so you can't worry about
that. I want to go in and earn a spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo spent the first four years of his career with
Montreal. He broke into the major leagues when Malone was the
Expos' general manager. He can also partially fill the leadoff
role.
</P>
<P>
   With the Giants, Santangelo usually batted first and second. He
hit .262 with a .392 on-base percentage from the first spot. He
also has a strong reputation of being a solid clubhouse guy, which
fits into the Dodgers' offseason free agent acquisitions. Both Orel
Hershiser and Gregg Olson have similar characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my career, at all levels, I've been on a lot of winning
teams, and those teams ... it's a bunch of guys pulling for each
other and wanting to win,'' Santangelo said. ``It's not guys
worried about their ERA or how many hits they had. If you can get
that kind of attitude ... that's what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   The Santangelo signing wasn't the only news the Dodgers made.
They avoided salary arbitration with pitcher Darren Dreifort,
inking the right-hander to a one-year, $3.7 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, 27, was 13-13 with a 4.79 ERA in 1999 before missing
the last few weeks of the season with arm problems. The Dodgers
wanted to sign Dreifort to a multi-year deal, but he's eligible for
free agency after the season and he's expected to enter the market.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Scott Boras, the agent for Dodgers third baseman Adrian
Beltre, said he doesn't expect a decision on the grievance filed by
the players association on Monday until next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to imagine it's going to be some time in February,''
Boras said. ``I hope it's early in the month instead of later.''
</P>
<P>
   After signing at the age of 15, Beltre is seeking free agency.
Major League Baseball already declined that request.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be heard by arbitrator Shyam Das. He's expected to
take an additional 10 days to two weeks after the hearing before
making a decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
