<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS IN DIALLO TRIAL WANT EXPERTS TO TESTIFY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The four police officers accused of murder in the
shooting death of Amadou Diallo plan to call two police firearm and
training experts and a Columbia University psychology professor as
expert witnesses at their trial next month, according to court
papers filed in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion submitted Friday to the State Supreme Court in
Albany, the Bronx district attorney's office asked Judge Joseph
Teresi to review whether the defense witnesses _ James Fyfe, a
Temple University criminologist; Jon Cerar, a former commander of
the New York Police firearms and tactics division; and Lynn A.
Cooper, a Columbia professor and psychologist who specializes in
human perception _ should be allowed to testify at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors said they questioned whether the expert
testimony would be relevant. If the witnesses are allowed to
testify, the prosecutors have asked Teresi to preclude them from
discussing the core issue of the case, namely whether the officers'
conduct was justified, because to do so, the prosecutors argued,
would pre-empt the jury's role as the ultimate finders of fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``These experts, if permitted to testify at all,'' the motion
said, ``should be limited to matters of expertise that do not
invade the province of the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The motion said Fyfe would testify about, among other things,
how long it takes to fire a semiautomatic pistol 16 times, as two
of the officers involved in the shooting did. The papers did not
specify the nature of Cerar's testimony, but as a police commander,
Cerar supervised the tactical training under which officers learn
the circumstances in which it is permissible to fire their guns.
Ms. Cooper, the papers said, is preparing a report for the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, who fired 41 times at Diallo last February as he
stood in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment building, have said
they mistakenly believed he was reaching for a gun. He was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Worth, a lawyer for one of the officers, Edward
McMellon, said the defense would challenge the prosecution motion.
``The jury needs to be educated as to proper police training to see
that these officers followed it,'' Worth said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The defense also filed a motion Friday, under seal, that asked
Teresi to review prosecution witness statements to see whether
additional evidence must be turned over to the defense before
trial, defense lawyers said. Under the law, defendants in criminal
cases are entitled to review material collected by the authorities
that would help bolster their defense.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers said they had provided the judge with a
rationale for their belief that certain outstanding material is
favorable to the officers. But they asked that their papers be
sealed because they did not want prosecutors to gain a tactical
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not file it to keep it from the eyes of the public,
just the prosecutors,'' said Bennett M. Epstein, a lawyer for
Officer Sean Carroll. ``We do not want the prosecutors to get
tipped off to what our theory of the defense might be prior to
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight news organizations, including The New York Times, the
Daily News, Newsday and the Associated Press, have objected to the
use of sealed motions in the case. Earlier this week, the
organizations filed their own motion asking the judge to rule that
all motions and proceedings in the case be public. Teresi told
prosecutors and defense lawyers Friday that they must respond to
that motion by Jan. 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
