<SLUG> BC-IOWAWRESTLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA'S WRESTLING PROGRAM IS KEEPING ITS WINNING WAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   T.J. Williams knew the Iowa wrestling team hadn't done its job _
not by Iowa standards _ in simply winning the 1998 Midlands
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes may have won the team title at the event, a
prestigious annual meet held at Northwestern University, but Iowa
hadn't displayed total dominance. Williams was the only Hawkeyes
wrestler to win his weight class.
</P>
<P>
   Williams figured Iowa's performance wasn't good enough to
satisfy coach Jim Zalesky, and he was right. The morning after the
team arrived back home in Iowa City, Iowa, the wrestlers found
themselves doing hourlong sessions of sprint laps at Carver-Hawkeye
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would get done \Rwith one session\S and were all exhausted,
and we knew that they were going to make us do more,'' Williams
said. ``And then it hit me _ this is what it's all about right
here. Nobody else is doing this. This is what wins championships.''
</P>
<P>
   At Iowa, which has won the past five NCAA crowns, nothing less
than championships are expected. Expectations haven't changed,
despite the major changes the Iowa program has undergone in the
past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes, the No. 1-ranked team in the latest National
Wrestling Coaches Association's NCAA poll, continue to work.
</P>
<P>
   Zalesky said he wants to see improvement from the Hawkeyes.
Although Iowa is 5-0 in duals and has been extremely strong in the
lower weight classes, athletes in the upper weight classes have
proven vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the guys they've gotta be prepared. We have a standard
at Iowa, and we have to keep that standard,'' Zalesky said. ``If
you're getting your butt kicked, you run back to the center of the
mat.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Zalesky became familiar with the Iowa standard,
set by legendary coach Dan Gable, long ago. Zalesky won three
individual NCAA titles from 1982to 1984 while wrestling for Gable,
then served as an assistant at Iowa before getting the nod as head
coach when Gable retired after the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   Any new coach would have his work cut out for him. Gable had
taken the Iowa wrestling program to legendary status and in 21
years had guided the Hawkeyes to 21 Big Ten and 15 NCAA team
titles, including a string of nine in a row that tied the record
for consecutive NCAA titles by any school in any sport. Hawkeyes
athletes also achieved All-America status 152 times, and won 45
individual NCAA titles.
</P>
<P>
   Entering his third season, Zalesky has already felt the pressure
his position can bring. Although the Hawkeyes won the 1998 Big Ten
and NCAA titles, Iowa had four returning NCAA champions to do it
with, and many observers gave credit for the season to Gable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's pressure anywhere at the top. To me it's good
pressure,'' Zalesky said. ``I've got a great administration, a
great fan base. To me, there are more positives than negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Zalesky has proven that he can spur the team when he needs to.
After Iowa lost the Big Ten title last year for the first time in
26 seasons, finishing second behind Minnesota, the Hawkeyes came
back to win the NCAA title by two points over the Golden Gophers.
Sophomores Williams and Doug Schwab won individual crowns, and
sophomore Eric Juergens took third.
</P>
<P>
   Gable, who still holds an office at Iowa as ``assistant to the
director'' and is co-head coach of the 2000 U.S. Olympic freestyle
team, said he thinks Zalesky has adjusted to his new job well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both years have been hard on him, but we haven't
dropped from the national title ranks,'' said Gable, who will
attend the Lone Star Duals as a broadcaster for Iowa Public
Television. ``His communication has picked up a lot, and his ways
of translating information away from the mat have been key in the
last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, who holds a 13-1 record this season at 141 pounds, said
he came to Iowa knowing that he would probably be wrestling for
someone other than Gable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at who else was around, and I knew the program was
still going to be top-notch,'' he said. ``The attitude hasn't
changed one bit. We still preach the same thing. We still outwork
everybody.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
