<SLUG> BC-CT-PURPLE-HEARTS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN'S MUSEUM PROJECT GOING NOWHERE SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENFIELD, Conn. _ Ever since the day in 1983 when residents
broached the idea of building a National Purple Heart Museum here,
the museum has remained just that: an idea _ whose time came, went
and kept on going, for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an advisory panel that includes Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf
and the actor James Garner, more than $1.2 million in state grants
and the support of Gov. John Rowland, the military museum today is
little more than an aging set of computer-enhanced blueprints and
an unfulfilled flight of fancy for an unknown town seeking a
tourist lodestone.
</P>
<P>
   A report this week by the Connecticut attorney general's office
offers a detailed explanation. According to the report, the
12-member board charged with planning, financing and building the
$18.75 million museum was so incompetent that it spent more than
$500,000 in public and private funds and allowed the museum's
former executive director to mishandle tens of thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management was inept and shoddy, and record keeping was
completely inadequate; accounting was essentially incompetent,''
the attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, said by telephone. ``We
believe the blame lies with the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum was conceived as a one-of-a-kind shrine of history
and memorabilia dedicated to the hundreds of thousands of Americans
who have received the Purple Heart medal, which is awarded to
members of the military wounded in battle. The museum was to be
situated in this middle-class town of shopping malls on the
Massachusetts border because, according to local lore, this is
where Gen. George Washington in 1774 enlisted one of the first
soldiers to receive the medal.
</P>
<P>
   State officials were so enthusiastic about the museum that the
powerful state Bond Commission, headed by the governor, voted in
1998 to grant $1 million to make it a reality. Town officials
envisioned streams of tourist dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the glitter and high hopes, Blumenthal says, could
offset the gross financial ineptitude of the museum's directors.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the board has spent more than $500,000, mostly in state
grants, for about $33,000 worth of architectural plans, Blumenthal
said. Shoddy bookkeeping and a lack of fundamental accounting
measures make it unclear what happened to the rest of the money, he
said. Although he added that despite their bad judgment, board
members had only the best intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the financial problems were tied to the dealings of the
museum's former executive director, Joseph Donohue, who according
to the state report was hired in 1997 without a contract, used
state grant money to pay his personal health insurance premiums and
federal tax bills, and often filtered private donations through his
own bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be much stronger oversight so as to assure
competent management,'' Blumenthal said. He added that he had
referred his findings about Donohue, who resigned as executive
director of the museum in April, to Connecticut's chief state's
attorney, John Bailey, for possible criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, who now works in Washington, could not be reached for
comment Friday. But his successor, and the museum board's current
executive director, Charles Alfano, called Blumenthal's report
``flawed'' and said it gave the false impression that hundreds of
thousands of dollars had been wasted. In fact, Alfano said, the
cost of mismanagement by the board, which he said had been
corrected, added up to less than $20,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Blumenthal said he began investigating the Purple Heart Museum
project about three months ago, after complaints from contributors
and volunteers began filtering into his office. Since then, the
state Department of Economic and Community Development has stopped
the disbursement of the remaining state grant money.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wednesday, when the attorney general's report was made
public, Alfano has been meeting with state and town officials to
coax them into releasing the money. Once that begins, he said, the
museum will send out 125,000 direct-mail solicitations for
donations and begin mapping out a fund-raising strategy with a
California public relations firm that has agreed to work at no
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to kick off our national campaign in early
spring,'' Alfano said. But he added, ``We can't move forward unless
we get the remainder of the state grant.'' The earliest the museum
may be ready for visitors is in late 2002, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the land reserved for the museum remains an expanse of
scrub stuck bordered by a nursing home, a cemetery and Interstate
91.
</P>
<P>
   How much of the $18.75 million cost the museum board has on hand
even Alfano did not know Friday. But, he said, ``We probably could
get by with $15 million.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
