A0122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOPDEBATE-BAXTER08-CO     01-07 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPDEBATE-BAXTER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Past plays powerful role in S.C. debate
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ On the weekend that South Carolina's
Republicans gathered to hear their presidential candidates talk
about the future, the past reared its insistent head to demonstrate
that it still packs a powerful political charge.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome South, candidates of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of any other questions they faced at Friday night's
televised forum here, the candidates had to negotiate the tricky
issue of whether the Confederate flag should fly over state
buildings, the burning question of the hour in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The past has a way of creeping back unobstrusively here. After
honoring their nonagenarian senator, Strom Thurmond, the party
faithful dined listening to the soundtrack of Ken Burns ``Civil
War'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever relevance it has for the presidential election, the
flag question wasn't long in coming in the debate, and it seemed to
work entirely to the benefit of the front-runner, Texas Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bryan, I believe the people of South Carolina can figure out
what to do with this flag issue,'' Bush told questioner Bryan
Williams, when asked if the flag offended him personally.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that he got a big round of
applause.
</P>
<P>
   But, did he have ``a visceral reaction to seeing the Confederate
flag?'' he was asked in possibly the most fruitless follow-up in a
debate so far this campaign. More applause _ although later, when
he pointed out that the same self-determinist approach should apply
to whether South Carolina should have a lottery _ a Democratic
proposal _ the response was more tepid.
</P>
<P>
   Bush picked up another easy clap line when all the candidates
were asked the worst mistake they'd made as adults. Trading Sammy
Sosa, the Texas Rangers co-owner said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, who has made this state and New
Hampshire the battlegrounds where he hopes to unseat Bush, did not
have as easy a ride.
</P>
<P>
   His first question dealt with his intercession on behalf of
Ameritech, a regional telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second such report to crop up in the past few days,
clouding his support for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the hourlong format never gave the challenger much
opportunity to draw the kind of sharp distinctions he needs to cut
into Bush's substantial lead here.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been riding high, butw year has brought some
choppy waters for the former Navy pilot. Not only his constituent
services but his taste in rock bands have been called to question.
(He defended his Senate activities but backed off an endorsement of
Nine Inch Nails at a New Hampshire debate Thursday night when
challenged by former Ambassador Alan Keyes.)
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty he will have expanding his New Hampshire success
into South Carolina is also becoming more apparent as the
substantial political machine that has been supporting George
Bushes, father and son, in this state since the 1970s swings into
action.
</P>
<P>
   Former S.C. Gov. Carroll Campbell spoke at a Bush pep rally
before the debate, and former aides are showing up in the Bush
campaign at an increasing rate.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the flag a moment. Considering that it really is a state
issue and presidential candidates can do little other than pander
or get themselves in trouble with it, it was a dumb question to
ask.
</P>
<P>
   But does the fact that we're asking so many dumb questions about
the past reveal that we don't know many smart questions to ask
about the future?
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
