<SLUG> BC-NJ-AUTO-INSPECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF PLANNED FOR N.J. DRIVERS STUCK IN LONG INSPECTION LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey drivers may have shorter and warmer waits while their
cars are inspected: Federal regulators have authorized use of a
speedier emissions test, and the testing company agreed Friday to
install heated waiting areas at inspection stations.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists criticized the decision to revert to the
faster test, which is less stringent, and accused Gov. Christie
Whitman and other officials of putting political expedience ahead
of clean air. The change still needs legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line of her proposal is, do less to protect the
health of New Jersey residents,'' said Curtis Fisher of New Jersey
Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers have endured long waits _ up to five hours in places _
since stricter emissions testing began on Dec. 13 to bring the
state into compliance with the Federal Clean Air Act. Drivers must
wait outside their cars during the test, which can take more than
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, whose administration awarded a $463 million contract to
a private company, Parsons Infrastructure and Technology Group, to
install and run the new testing system, expressed outrage this week
at the company's performance. She demanded Thursday that Parsons
install heated waiting areas, which the company said it would begin
building on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also asked the federal Environmental Protection Agency
to allow the former, faster test to be used when waits exceed 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the agency wrote to Whitman's transportation
commissioner, James Weinstein, authorizing use of the less
stringent test until June 30. But the agency also told Weinstein
that it expected to meet with him in April for a report on the
company's progress in permanently reducing waits.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, legislators are to vote on a bill introduced by the
state Senate president, Donald T. DiFrancesco, to amend New
Jersey's emissions testing law to allow the speedier test, said Rae
Hutton, a spokesman for DiFrancesco.
</P>
<P>
   The DiFrancesco bill would also call for other measures to
reduce waiting times, including exempting cars five years old or
less from testing, temporarily suspending safety inspections, and
directing Parsons to give drivers vouchers so they can have the
inspections done at private licensed service stations.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Sullivan, a spokesman for the state Division of Motor
Vehicles, said those options are being examined.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hutton said that DiFrancesco, a Republican, was considering
holding hearings on the award of the testing contract to Parsons,
the sole bidder, in 1998. Democrats have been the loudest critics
of the contract award, pointing out that Parsons contributed
$62,000 to New Jersey Republicans in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Friday that waiting times at inspection
stations are already falling, thanks to basic moves to improve
workers' efficiency. Carl Golden, a spokesman for Parsons, said the
average waiting time at inspection stations statewide was down to
16 minutes Friday from 24 minutes on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
