<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENDOZA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART RECIPIENT'S DEATH A TRAGIC 1ST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - At a time when most 13-year-old boys were playing
video games, David Mendoza became Arizona's youngest heart
transplant recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the East Phoenix area teen became the first
Arizonan to undergo a second heart transplant, and eventually, he
received a third.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, Mendoza, 31, became the state's first heart
transplant recipient to earn a tragic distinction _ he died of
complications from chicken pox.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a risk of so-called opportunistic organisms
affecting these patients,'' said Dr. Jack Copeland, who performed
two of Mendoza's transplants at University Medical Center in
Tucson. ``But we've never lost a patient due to chicken pox.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza's death caught Copeland and his team by surprise.
Although Mendoza initially had a fever of 103, he seemed to be
recovering after his mysterious exposure to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all sort of underestimated the risk, David included,''
Copeland said. ``I saw him at 11:30 Tuesday night, Jan. 4, and he
was joking around. He felt pretty good, he looked pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mendoza took a turn for the worse and died late Wednesday,
Jan. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Born with a heart defect that left him with just two chambers
instead of four, Mendoza received his first transplant in 1981. At
the time, heart transplants were a nascent medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   University Medical Center performed its first heart transplant
in 1979. Since then, it has done more than 500.
</P>
<P>
   After his first heart transplant, Mendoza developed graft
arteriosclerosis, a form of chronic rejection. The condition
required that he receive another transplant in 1984 and a third in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   His plight caught the public's attention, prompting Jack
Weckesser of Glendale to raise $3,000 for Mendoza through a Grand
Canyon hike fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland said Mendoza's death was a blow to him and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody really loved David,'' the surgeon said. ``We felt
like he was our adopted child or something. When he was growing up,
it was was fun to see him take on responsibility and earn a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza worked as a counselor for the state.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, who live in Scottsdale, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his medically troubled life, Mendoza maintained a
quick wit and a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Once, after being sedated for a transplant surgery, Mendoza
awoke to realize his chest bore no fresh incision because a donor
heart turned out to be unsuitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, Copeland's a miracle worker; he did it without an
incision,'' Mendoza quipped to the medical staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept us laughing all the time,'' Copeland said. ``He was
just a great kid.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at kerry.fehr-snyder(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8975. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-07-00 2346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
