<DOCNO> NYT20000107.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0133 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TRUST-AZR &LR;      01-07 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS SHORTCHANGED, EDUCATORS CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Arizona's piggybank for education is getting fatter,
approaching $1 billion, thanks to sales of state trust land. Yet,
the schools aren't getting any richer.
</P>
<P>
   Many educators argue that the system is set up to benefit
taxpayers, not kids. And they want trust land to give an extra
boost to schools. More computers, perhaps. Or a longer school year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Legislature pours money from trust land into the
regular school budget, offsetting the amount coming from taxes. If
trust income goes up, the taxpayers get a break, but there's no
additional money for education.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Bob Burns, chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, maintains that the formula is a fair and effective way
to divvy up funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the debate as to whether there's enough
money,'' the Glendale Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   But others want to earmark trust money for extras, such as the
all-day kindergarten class at Andalucia Primary School in the
Alhambra Elementary School District in west Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen 6-year-olds worked on their journals on Friday, Jan.
7, drawing pictures and trying to write sentences. Then, they
turned to ``5'': holding up the right number of fingers and
objects, watching teacher Linda Cerracchio demonstrate how to write
it.
</P>
<P>
   When the school year started, 20 of the children spoke virtually
no English, but ``you can't tell it now,'' Cerracchio said. Coming
from impoverished households, many didn't know colors or recognize
their written names.
</P>
<P>
   Without all-day kindergarten, Alhambra Superintendent Carol Peck
said, ``they are at a disadvantage that takes years to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Alhambra pays for extended kindergarten through a budget
override, but Peck worries whether voters will approve it again in
March. She wishes there were funds for giving help even earlier, by
expanding the district's preschool program.
</P>
<P>
   For years, no one would have thought much about tapping state
trust land for such projects. It just didn't generate much cash.
</P>
<P>
   Trust land, now 9.3 million acres, was given to Arizona at
statehood as a way to raise money for public institutions, mostly
schools.
</P>
<P>
   `LOOK TO THE FUTURE' &QL; 
Profits from selling or mining trust land go into a permanent fund,
with the interest distributed each year. The permanent fund is
approaching $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a billion isn't enough, just look to the future,'' said
Keith Meyer, a spokesman for the State Land Department, which
oversees trust land.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, voters allowed the fund to make stock investments,
which should pump up returns.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the trust includes lucrative urban land. A $40 million
parcel along Interstate 17 was sold to USAA, a military insurer, in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what the interest from that one sale could do, said
Chuck Essigs, an assistant superintendent in the Mesa Unified
School District: It could pay for 70 new teachers. It could buy
2,500 computers.
</P>
<P>
   FREEZE SUGGESTED &QL; 
Essigs suggests freezing the amount of money that the trust
contributes to the overall education budget. Although it accounts
for just 3 percent of the state's $2.4 billion contribution to
education, Essigs figures that legislators would be loath to hunt
for the money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Ann Day, R-Tucson, proposes phasing trust money out
of the education budget over several years. Then, she would
dedicate it to something special, such as reducing class size.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees that the system needs fixing.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with using trust land to foot part of the total
bill for education? wondered state Sen. Randall Gnant,
R-Scottsdale, who heds the Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Graham Keegan, state superintendent of public instruction,
hasn't decided whether to support earmarking the money for specific
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear that goes along with it is that you'll see a
reduction in the overall education budget,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Land Department, Meyer calculates that losing trust
money from the education budget would cost each taxpayer nearly $50
more.
</P>
<P>
   There's one more twist in the issue: the move to dedicate trust
money to special projects is backed by environmentalists who hope
to preserve some of the trust land from development.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of school organizations are leery about how such
conservation would work, especially if it meant giving up land
without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Robey of the Arizona School Boards Association says one
intriguing idea is that adjacent trust land might be more valuable
if some was left undeveloped.
</P>
<P>
   Income from trust land makes up just 2 percent of total local
and state spending on schools, according to a study by the
non-profit Sonoran Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake to rush land to the market without really
understanding the net income of selling properties,'' said Luther
Propst, executive director of the Tucson-based institute.
</P>
<P>
   And he adds that educators shouldn't overlook one special cost:
When trust land is sold for subdivisions, the schools get a flood
of new students. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kathleen.Ingley(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or at (602) 444-8171. &QL; 
Republic writer Kelly Pearce contributed to this article. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
